<HEADLINE>
SKINNER DENTS POINTS STANDINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKINGHAM, N.C. _Mike Skinner's goal heading into North
Carolina Speedway this weekend was to leave ``The Rock'' with all
fenders intact on his Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner exited the 1.017-mile oval not only with straight sheet
metal but also as points-leader of the NASCAR Winston Cup Series
for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner finished sixth in the Dura-Lube/Big Kmart 400 yesterday,
a week after he ran fourth in the season-opening Daytona 500. His
combined results _ and Jeff Gordon's uncharacteristic 39th-place
result here via a blown engine _ vaulted Skinner to the top of the
points heap after two of 34 races.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner has a 29-point lead over Rusty Wallace, the 1989 Cup
champion. They are the only drivers to begin the season with two
top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as we struggled here at Rockingham, this is like a win
for this team,'' said Skinner, driver of the No. 31 Lowe's Chevy
Monte Carlo owned by Richard Childress. ``This was pretty awesome.
If we're leading the points headed into the last race of the
season, then I'll think we've got a shot to win it \Rthe
championship\S. We're still the hunter. We're still hunting our
first win.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner is winless in 78 career Cup starts as teammate to
seven-time Cup champion Dale Earnhardt. But Skinner knows how to
win. He captured the first race of NASCAR's Craftsman Truck Series
in 1995 and its first championship. Skinner's crew chief is Larry
McReynolds, one of Winston Cup's top strategists and a veteran of
points races at Robert Yates Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The points-leader situation is certainly something to be proud
of, but we just got going,'' McReynolds said. ``It's like saying we
led the first 10 laps of a 500-mile race. It's nice to do, but
you've still got a long way to go.'' EARNHARDT HAS CHASSIS PROBLEMS
While Skinner moved into NASCAR's high-rent district, teammate
Earnhardt was saddled with a 41st-place finish after brushing a
wall after 275 laps.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who finished second at Daytona and was second in
points overall, said he missed the setup here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really off on the chassis,'' said Earnhardt, driver of
the No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus Chevy. ``We were off after 15
or 20 laps. I probably should have gone softer on the back and
softer on the front, too. Me and \Rcrew chief\S Kevin Hamlin worked
awful hard to come up with it. But I was fighting it the whole
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt is 17th in points, 105 behind his front-running
teammate. FAST LAPS Second-place Dale Jarrett remains winless in 24
races at North Carolina Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Third-place Bobby Labonte scored his second top-five in 13 races
at Rockingham.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-place Jeremy Mayfield, Wallace's teammate, posted his
first top-10 finish in 10 races at Rockingham.
</P>
<P>
   Race-winner Mark Martin, fourth-place Jeff Burton and Jarrett
made the points moves of the race, each gaining 23 positions in the
Cup standings. Martin moved from 31st to eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart's 12th-place result was the highest among series
rookies for the second consecutive race. LAST WORDS ``I love these
Chevys. That's all I needed. We're going to win some races.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Geoffrey Bodine after finishing eighth yesterday at ``The
Rock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
