<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-CHARTER-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI'S POSSIBLE RUN PROMPTS TALK OF CHANGING NYC CHARTER ON
SUCCESSION  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Knowing full well that the election of Sen. Rudolph
Giuliani would mean the appointment of Mayor Mark J. Green, some
Democratic officials are quietly looking into tinkering with the
city charter to deny Green, the city's public advocate, the right
to automatically succeed the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The officials _ particularly the city comptroller, Alan G.
Hevesi _ are testing the feasibility of altering the charter to
require a special election to fill out Mayor Giuliani's term should
he resign to run for U.S. Senate before his second term ends in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions in the corridors of City Hall and in the
Legislature in Albany reveal much about the intensity of the
competition among Democratic politicians over who will ultimately
succeed Giuliani, who is barred from running for a third term.
Hevesi is considered a leading contender, and has been raising
money toward a possible run.
</P>
<P>
   The charter places Green, a Democrat who has also been raising
money for a possible mayoral campaign, first in line to succeed
Giuliani. His appointment would make him the incumbent in 2001, to
the considerable disadvantage of other mayoral aspirants.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Hevesi said he had made no formal
proposals on the topic of succession. But aides say he has
discussed changing the charter to require a special election with
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver; the City Council speaker, Peter F.
Vallone, and other elected officials in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't taken an official position in the sense of having
thought through all the alternative ways to legally deal with
succession,'' Hevesi said. ``But I am tending toward the notion
that you go to the voters. I believe in elections. If you forget
who is helped and who is hurt, if you can separate the politics,
the issue seems clear. Should the voters decide or not? I think
they should.''
</P>
<P>
   But separating the politics has proven to be difficult. Green
recommends that the charter be left alone and suggests that
Hevesi's suggestions are politically motivated. ``It's so
politically inspired to now change the city's constitution in order
to stop a particular official from succession that it doesn't pass
the smell test,'' Green said recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't burn down the house to roast a pig,'' Green said.
``And you don't alter a 167-year constitutional precedent to stop
the public advocate from being the next-in-line successor to the
mayor for an undeniably political purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Green said, it would be more valuable for Hevesi
and others interested in changing the charter ``to help the best
Democrat possible win the Senate seat in 2000 _ so that the issue
of mayoral succession never arises.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So far, not many public officials seem to favor such a change.
``I recognize that the current system can confer a political
advantage,'' said Fernando Ferrer, the Bronx borough president, who
is also raising money for a potential mayoral campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you don't like the way things are, run against that
person. To change as important a document as the charter because
you are motivated by personal convenience is not a sufficiently
good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the issue has contributed to the growing
tension between Green and Hevesi, aides to the two men suggest.
When the two Democrats ran together on a ticket with David N.
Dinkins on the top in 1993, they developed a close relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, however, their names surfaced as potential rivals for
the Democratic mayoral nomination in 2001. And in 1997, Hevesi
endorsed the short-lived candidacy of one of Green's opponents for
the public advocate seat, Assemblyman Roger L. Green, a Brooklyn
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has not said whether he will run for the Senate seat
now held by Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who plans to retire at the end
of next year. The mayor has repeatedly made it clear that he
harbors no affection for Mark Green.
</P>
<P>
   In his ``state of the city'' message in January, Giuliani said
he was interested in revising the charter, but on other matters.
Colleen Roche, the mayor's press secretary, said recently that
Giuliani had taken no position on any revision of the charter to
affect mayoral succession.
</P>
<P>
   But any plan to revise the charter on the topic of mayoral
succession is likely to become a cumbersome, politically thorny
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Green and others opposed to changing the charter cite a
1952 New York state law that states that a mayoral vacancy must be
filled by an official elected citywide at the same time the mayor
was, so a new state law would be required.
</P>
<P>
   While Hevesi has discussed the matter with Silver, the assembly
speaker is said by officials in Albany to be highly uncomfortable
with the idea of seeing any such legislation pass.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some politicians contend that a change in mayoral
succession could be achieved through a referendum, which could be
initiated by the mayor, the City Council or the petitioning of at
least 50,000 New York City residents. Meanwhile, Hevesi said he
believed that revising the charter remained a viable idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Green has argued that voters have spoken by adopting a
charter,'' Hevesi said. ``But the same charter recognizes that
there are anomalies in the charter. The same charter provides that
the voters can change the charter by referendum. If the public
wants to change the charter, it can do so. It's not a revolutionary
idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
