<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYST-RATINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS' REPORTS ON STOCK LACK ANY STANDARDIZED GRADING SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Doublespeak, thy name is Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   As if financial concepts aren't hard enough to understand,
analyst ratings that are supposed to make it easier for investors
to buy, hold or sell stocks end up doing just the opposite:
confusing folks who need help.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because there are no standardized ratings. Each brokerage
or research firm has its own way of ranking stocks. Collectively,
that can be as clear as mud.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, ratings by Goldman Sachs in descending order are
Trading Buy, Market Outperform, Market Perform and Market
Underperform. The word ``sell'' is not seen at all, although
investors might assume that the lowest rating is a recommendation
to dump the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Everen has only three ratings: Outperformer, Marketperformer and
Underperformer. No buy or sell in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch uses the words ``buy'' and ``sell'' in its
recommendations, but also uses ``accumulate,'' ``neutral'' and
``reduce.'' What's the difference between ``buy'' and
``accumulate''? Apparently it's the added word ``particularly.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the Merrill Lynch definition: A stock is a buy if it is
``considered to have a particularly attractive potential for
appreciation.'' It's an accumulate if it has an ``attractive
potential for appreciation.''
</P>
<P>
   This linguistic alphabet soup seems just plain silly to David
Forrest, analyst for The Motley Fool, an Alexandria, Va.-based
online investment forum.
</P>
<P>
   His advice to investors: ``Just ignore it. We generally tell
people to pay no attention to that nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Forrest has seen an analyst from a brokerage firm change a
stock's rating from ``short-term outperform'' to ``long-term
neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they saying in the long-term it's no good but in the
short-term it's going to do well?'' asked Forrest, a former broker.
``It's an incredibly confusing system.''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks one reason the ratings are obtuse is to make investors
more dependent on their brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Another may be a brokerage firm's reluctance to give bad ratings
to a stock, especially if it has an investment banking relationship
with that company. After all, ``market underperform'' sounds better
than ``sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Wall Street, the investment banking department of a
brokerage firm handles a company's public offering while analysts
in another department of the same firm are grading the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be a fire wall between the two,'' he said, but
that doesn't always stop influence from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   While the two departments should not influence each other,
there's often implied pressure on analysts not to trash a client's
stock, said Hal Lenhart, a chartered financial analyst at the
College for Financial Planning, a Denver-based organization that
educates investment professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Chip Review in Portland, Ore. calls itself unbiased in
its analysis because it's primarily a research firm. It doesn't
have investment bankers, brokers or a trading desk. It makes money
by charging subscription fees to its customer base, most of whom
are individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not after an investment banking deal,'' said Louis
Feldman, an analyst at Red Chip. ``We don't make a market on any of
these stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean its rating system is flawless. While Red
Chip uses a relatively easy-to-understand ``A'' to ``D'' rating,
based on the strength of the company, there's one confusing
ranking: the ``NA.''
</P>
<P>
   It's used on a stock for which it cannot ``justify any valuation
based on the information available.'' But it's not clear how ``NA''
is distinct from ``D.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just the nature of the business, said Margaret Draper,
spokeswoman for the Securities Industry Association in New York, a
trade association for brokerage firms and mutual fund companies.
Investors who aren't sure what the ratings mean should consult
their financial advisers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   If used properly, the ratings have value, many advisers say.
</P>
<P>
   Lenhart and others recommend that investors compare several
analysts' recommendations to see if there's agreement. Do many of
them recommend a buy or are their ratings all over the board?
</P>
<P>
   And most advisers say investors should look at analyst ratings
only as one part of the research made into a company. It shouldn't
be the only factor in an investment.
</P>
<P>
   But if many analysts agree that a stock deserves their highest
ranking -- whether it's called ``buy,'' ``accumulate'' or ``get
lots of'' -- and that affirms other research done on the company,
then the ratings strengthen any investment decision.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
