</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TCU-IMAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU HOPES CONFERENCE DREAMS CAN MATCH REALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ If people at TCU wanted to, they could drive
themselves crazy with the ifs and maybes.
</P>
<P>
   If TCU had funneled additional funds into athletics 10 years ago
instead of now, maybe TCU would be talking of keeping up instead of
catching up. If TCU had done that, maybe Horned Frogs fans would be
discussing remaining a player in big-time Division I athletics
instead of trying to become one.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, TCU procrastinated, and two conferences later finds
itself in a tug of war between the image of where it wants to be in
the larger scheme of college athletics and the reality of where it
can actually go.
</P>
<P>
   That battle has taken on a certain immediacy with the breakup of
Conference No. 2, the Western Athletic Conference, looming in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the big hope is to be in one of the major
basketball- and football-playing conferences,'' said Jack
Hesselbrock, TCU associate athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   TCU has invested almost $10 million in athletic facilities and
$1 million in coaching salary increases in hopes of being on par
with nationally prominent athletic programs such as Texas and Texas
A&AMP;M when, and if, conference realignment happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't making this kind of financial commitment to
improve relationships with Tulsa, UT-El Paso and San Jose,'' said
Fred Jacoby, former Southwest Conference commissioner. ``I think
what they are doing is positioning themselves that if something
fragments in the Big 12 Conference they'll be able to jump in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby had a ringside seat for TCU's wake-up call when Texas,
Texas A&AMP;M, Texas Tech and Baylor bolted from the Southwest
Conference for the Big 12 after the 1995-96 season. TCU, along with
SMU, Rice and Houston, was left behind to wonder what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years of standing pat had caught up with the Frogs, and
they've been scrambling to catch up since.
</P>
<P>
   Now with Notre Dame turning down a chance to join the Big Ten,
the question has become what school will step in to that
conference. When that domino falls, another round of conference
musical chairs will likely begin, and TCU will get a chance to see
how far they've come.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time we're better prepared,'' Hesselbrock said. ``We were
going along for so long thinking: `This is good enough.' It
wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby looks at TCU and finds two problems lingering from the
old SWC days that can't be solved by throwing money at them _
ticket sales and TV attractiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Simple numbers explain that gap.
</P>
<P>
   TCU averaged 27,181 fans a football game in 1998. Texas A&AMP;M's
lowest turnout of the season was 54,506, on Nov. 6 against Oklahoma
for a game played in a driving rain.
</P>
<P>
   TCU, a small private university, draws from a student body of
7,240 and an alumni base of about 50,000, while Texas A&AMP;M has a
student body of 42,572 and an alumni base of about 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is whether the school has a marquee reputation
and national appeal, not size,'' said Mike Aresco, vice president
of programming at CBS Sports. ``TCU would not have it as much, but
would not be unknown either. ... TCU is certainly in that middle
level of teams that people know a little about but doesn't have the
same marquee name as say a Florida State or an Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   Aresco said TCU showed potential in a Sun Bowl upset of Southern
Cal that was televised nationally by CBS.
</P>
<P>
   TCU drew a 6.2 rating and a 16 share in a Fort Worth-Dallas
market, meaning 6 percent of all television sets and 16 percent of
those that were turned on were tuned in to the game. In comparison,
Texas A&AMP;M and Kansas State's Big 12 Championship game Dec. 5, 1998,
drew a 13.9 with a 28 share.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can say `Can TCU make that step up like
Texas or Texas A&AMP;M?' '' Horned Frogs men's basketball coach Billy
Tubbs said. ``I think it's better to say `Can TCU make that step up
like a Duke or a Miami of Florida or a USC?' I'm talking more or
less about the private institutions that are a factor on the
national level.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke, Miami and USC play in strong, national conferences. TCU
does not.
</P>
<P>
   TCU thought it would be when it joined the 16-team Western
Athletic Conference for the 1996-97 school year. The conference
didn't last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little tougher sledding because there were not as
many regional rivalries and marquee names,'' Aresco said.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, at this time, there will be fewer. The WAC will be an
eight-team league.
</P>
<P>
   Half its members announced in May plans to leave and form a
rival conference. Come July, the Mountain West Conference will
begin and the WAC will attempt to begin again.
</P>
<P>
   The WAC is without a television deal and an NCAA automatic bid
for basketball. TCU is left to ponder whether the WAC is where it
needs to be if it's going to be a player instead of merely a
spectator in big-time college athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's possible we could \Rbe a player\S if we stay in
the WAC,'' TCU football coach Dennis Franchione said. ``And I think
it's possible that we could have to make a move. But we won't be
able to make a move without doing the things we're doing and then
being good in the WAC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we have to do is not talk about other
conferences but talk about being good in this conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Too late.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of other conferences is common at TCU nowadays. The Big 12
Conference and Conference USA are the most frequent topics of
conversation. Horned Frogs alumni and fans dream of basketball
games with Louisville and Cincinnati in Conference USA and football
games with Texas and Texas A&AMP;M in the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   That Conference USA says expansion isn't a priority doesn't
really seem to matter. Speculation continues because everybody
knows that something needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
   One TCU assistant coach was on the road recruiting recently and
had a player tell him that an opposing coach said TCU and SMU would
be playing in a conference that basically amounted to the Southland
II next year.
</P>
<P>
   So the question remains: What is realistic for TCU? Is it a
triumphant return to national prominence in a league with Texas and
Texas A&AMP;M or is it a conference with Tulsa and SMU and a future as
a midmajor more likely?
</P>
<P>
   ``On a scale of 1 to 10,'' Jacoby said, handicapping TCU's
chances of achieving the former instead of the latter, ``no more
than a five, at best a six and at worst a three.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
