r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONFUSA-FUTURE-TEX     02-22 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFUSA-FUTURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE USA IS ONE OF THE NATION'S MORE DIVERSE CONFERENCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Its logo doesn't include an image of the Statue of Liberty. But
for universities looking to better themselves by emigrating,
Conference USA is a beacon of hope.
</P>
<P>
   TCU and SMU are just two of the schools connected in rumors
regarding C-USA, a four-year-old league born during the conference
shuffling earlier this decade. And while C-USA presidents met
earlier this month to discuss strategic planning, expansion is
hardly a hot topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidents talked about expansion more as a concept,''
C-USA commissioner Mike Slive said. ``Right now, we're in the
fourth year of our initial five-year plan and we're in the process
of developing our plan for the next five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Conference USA had six football-playing schools in 1996, but
will have nine in 1999. That rapid growth has caused scheduling
problems, but is not indicative of expansion wanderlust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinking about getting to 12 in order to play a football
championship game would be for two or three reasons,'' Slive said.
``Would it strengthen the league? Do we want a championship game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that going to 12 strengthens our league. Now is
the first time we've thought about that as a part of a strategic
plan. We will not add schools in order to get to 12. We'll only add
if it makes us stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   And, with 12 basketball-playing schools, there is little desire
among member schools to go beyond that number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a very solid and stable league,'' said
Louisville athletic director Tom Jurich, who formerly was the
athletic director at Colorado State. ``I know \Rcommissioner Mike\S
Slive fields calls from all over the country from schools that want
to be in this league. This is a league that's working very smoothly
as it's currently set up.''
</P>
<P>
   Conference USA, like many other conferences, is waiting to see
if the Big Ten Conference decides to expand from 11 to 12. Slive
believes that even if the Big Ten initiates another round of
musical chairs there is no guarantee that C-USA will be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Conference USA's four goals during its first five years were:
(1), develop football at the national championship level; (2),
maintain men's basketball at the national championship level; (3),
maximize opportunities in men's and women's sports; (4), ensure the
league has a voice in NCAA legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Slive believes that C-USA is 4-for-4. However in football, it's
a ``glass is half full, glass is half empty'' argument.
</P>
<P>
   This past season, C-USA member Tulane finished 12-0, but was an
also-ran in the football Bowl Championship Series. The Green Wave
played BYU in the Liberty Bowl, which has a deal with the league to
take its champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that hurt us. I think it helped because
everybody was talking about it,'' Jurich said of Tulane not being a
championship contender.
</P>
<P>
   Slive points out that C-USA placed three teams in bowl games
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in a short period of time we've established ourselves
as a pretty good football conference,'' Slive said. ``We expect our
basketball to be good, but there's a lot of life and vibrancy in
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Conference USA could also be called the Diversity Conference.
Membership ranges from public schools like Cincinnati and South
Florida (each with an enrollment of approximately 36,000) to
private schools like Saint Louis (enrollment, 12,100) and Marquette
(10,000).
</P>
<P>
   And geographically, C-USA ranges from West Point, N.Y., south to
Tampa, west to Houston and north to Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The conference has 12 member schools. Five _ DePaul, Marquette,
Saint Louis and South Florida _ don't play Division I-A football.
And even though that makes for an odd mixture of conference
schools, there is little sentiment for dumping the non-football
schools in order to bring in more football schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The football schools and the non-football schools have a great
relationship,'' said Marquette's Bill Cords, who is chair of
C-USA's athletic directors. ``We don't view ourselves as simply a
basketball school in a I-A football conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Conference USA also would have a difficult time justifying
ridding itself of major markets such as Chicago (DePaul), Milwaukee
(Marquette), Tampa, Fla., (South Florida), St. Louis and Charlotte,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``This league married football and basketball in a way that made
sense to both groups,'' Slive said. ``It was a compatible marriage,
and we don't have football vs. basketball issues. We would be very
wary of walking away from those markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference has two football-only members _ Army and East
Carolina. Next season, Alabama-Birmingham's football program will
start playing in C-USA, giving the league nine football teams.
</P>
<P>
   And South Florida, after two football seasons at Division I-AA,
is hoping to move up to I-A status soon. That could give C-USA a
10th football team in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looked upon now as a total conference,'' Jurich said.
``Obviously, we've got some marquee basketball programs, but
there's a huge commitment to football. It's a very young league,
but it's already achieved a ton. I think this is one of the premier
conferences going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
