<HEADLINE>
`BLOWED UP' GORDON FALLS FROM LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKINGHAM, N.C. _ Jeff Gordon's remarkable run of NASCAR
consistency came to an abrupt halt yesterday when, in Winston Cup
garage parlance, he `blowed up.'
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the engine in Gordon's Chevrolet expired after he
had completed 310 of the 393 laps that made up the Dura-Lube/Big
Kmart 400 at the North Carolina Speedway. Gordon was running fifth
when his car slowed. A week after starting the season with a
victory worth $2.1 million in the Daytona 500, Gordon coasted
around to pit road and immediately turned left into the garage
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unfortunate,'' said Gordon, who won both races at ``The
Rock'' last year and was working on a streak of three consecutive
series victories dating to the end of last season. ``We led at
times. I think we were going to be a big factor at the end. These
guys \Rat Hendrick Motorsports\S don't let me down very often,
especially with the engine department. Today it just blew up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the three-time and reigning series champion, was
credited with a 39th-place finish. Gordon's last DNF _ Did Not
Finish _ occurred at Richmond International Raceway last June. The
last time Gordon failed to finish a Cup race because of an engine
failure was in March 1997 at Atlanta Motor Speedway, where he
placed 42nd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew they \Rhis crew\S were human,'' said Gordon,
driver of the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Refinishes Monte Carlo.
``Maybe everybody else didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome dropped Gordon from first at the start of the day _
10 points ahead of Dale Earnhardt _ to 11th in the Cup points chase
after two of 34 events. Gordon's DNF cleared the way for Mike
Skinner, who finished sixth, to assume the points lead for the
first time in his series career.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon came into the event having finished in the top 10 _ and
on the lead lap _ in 21 consecutive races. In a word, he had become
practically bulletproof.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are bound to happen eventually,'' said Gordon,
who led the race seven times for 90 laps. ``Today pretty much shows
that it doesn't matter what you do in Daytona. You've got to do it
every weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett, who finished third in the No. 88 Quality Care
Service/Ford Credit Taurus, said he was too busy trying to keep
pace with eventual winner Mark Martin and Roush Racing teammate
Jeff Burton to notice what had become of Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't looking for him,'' Jarrett deadpanned, ``but we
appreciate him waiting on us.''
</P>
<P>
   As consolation, Gordon was voted winner of the Goody's Headache
Powder Award by the media for suffering the day's worst luck. The
award pays $3,600.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 0004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
