<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ROCKINGHAM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOOTH CREW HELPS MARTIN CAPTURE CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKINGHAM, N.C. _ Nearly 10 years have passed since Mark Martin
and Jack Roush celebrated their first NASCAR Winston Cup victory at
the North Carolina Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Driver and car-owner were relative series neophytes when Martin,
making his 113th career Cup start, won the fall race here on Oct.
22, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Mark was dying to win a race at that time,'' Roush
said yesterday at the same Sandhills racetrack. ``We were probably
lucky that day. I do not remember how we won that race. We were
probably lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Martin admittedly was not as good as teammate Jeff
Burton around the abrasive 1.017-mile oval. But Martin and his pit
crew were better than everybody along pit road, which is where they
combined to win the Dura-Lube/Big Kmart 400.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was running second to Burton when debris on the
backstretch brought out the day's fourth caution flag on Lap 357 of
the scheduled 393. Martin entered the pits second but exited first,
courtesy of crew chief Jimmy Fennig and a team that changed four
tires, refueled the No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus and put the veteran
driver into a lead he would hold for the remaining 35 laps.
</P>
<P>
   Martin remained at the point despite two additional late-race
cautions and restarts, pulling away from Dale Jarrett to record his
30th career Cup victory. It was Martin's initial visit to Victory
Lane in 1999 and first return visit at ``The Rock'' since that
October race nearly a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was another example of what a great race team I work
with,'' said Martin, whose crew adjusted the car to the end.
``They've been awesome and they've worked at it and they deserve
it. Their hard work has paid off and we'll see if we can keep that
going and make it even better.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after he trailed Burton home in a 1-2 Roush sweep during
the Alltel 200 NASCAR Busch Grand National Series race here, Martin
came to grips with a track that traditionally has given him
handling fits. It is a track, Martin said, on which Burton excels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, Jeff Burton is the master here,'' said Martin,
after his teammate had led eight times for a race-high 227 laps.
``And he is the master at Darlington and he may be the master at
Martinsville and he's awfully good at Richmond, too. These are all
places where you can spin the tires, and I'm not good at those
places. I like to be able to slam it to the floor. I know how to go
fast and give it gas and when you can't, I can't stand it. And I
give it the gas anyway and peel the rear tires off.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin kept enough Goodyear Eagle rubber intact to finish 1.397
seconds ahead of Jarrett, who like Martin, was swept up in a 12-car
wreck in the season-opening Daytona 500 on Feb. 14. Martin finished
31st and Jarrett 37th in that race won by Gordon, who saw how the
other half lives yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The defending race champion, Gordon's quest for a fourth
consecutive victory over two seasons was ended when the engine in
the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Refinishes Chevrolet blew after he
completed 310 laps. Gordon, who was running fifth when his engine
quit, was relegated to a 39th-place finish and dropped from first
to 11th in Cup points.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's exit paved the way for the first Ford victory in the
first unrestricted engine race this year. Martin and Jarrett were
followed home by Bobby Labonte's Pontiac Grand Prix, and the Fords
of Burton and Jeremy Mayfield completed the top five.
</P>
<P>
   The race was run in temperatures that only reached the low 40s,
and before a rare non-sellout crowd estimated at 45,000 in an arena
that seats approximately 67,000.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who scored a career-high seven victories last year while
finishing second to Gordon in the points chase, successfully held
the lead on restarts on Lap 376 and Lap 385. Jarrett was second on
both occasions but could not reel Martin in. Jarrett now has
finished second in six of the last seven races at Rockingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made at least two adjustments on every pit stop,'' said
Jarrett, who failed to lead a lap in the No. 88 Quality Care
Service/Ford Credit Taurus. ``The \Rlast\S restart was pretty good,
but once we got down into Turn 2 he got away. Mark's car was just
better at getting in the throttle. That was gonna be my one shot,
if I could do something on the restart.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin led five times for 50 laps. But given his unstable
history on this slick racetrack, he said every restart was
nerve-wracking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's all kinds of things that go wrong on restarts,'' said
Martin, who averaged 120.750 mph in a race that took 3 hours, 18
minutes and 36 seconds. ``I never count them until I can get to
where I can coast to the start-finish line. Then I start
hollering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
