<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS STILL HAVE OPTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ There are at least two good things about the
Rangers losing the Roger Clemens derby:
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Curt Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   One is staying, and the other? ... Well, tune in in August, if
I'm reading the Philadelphia Phillies' odd mind-set correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Infatuated with the pinstripes and, perhaps, the drive home
through the South Bronx after night games, Clemens became a New
York Yankee last week.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Rangers fan, you sighed. You shook your head. You
called him Benedict Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I had always thought Rockhead Roger would sign with
the Houston Astros. Silly me. I thought the Toronto Blue Jays might
have something to do with where Clemens played these next two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had what the Rangers didn't _ an array of
major-league bodies _ to throw at Blue Jays general manager Gord
Ash, who thinks his team can finish in second place. But the Astros
clung tightly to the two young players that Toronto reportedly
valued most, pitcher Scott Elarton and outfielder Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   It says something about the Rangers' earnestness that they were
willing to part with ``their'' Hidalgo, young Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   But was there ever a chance?
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto papers have reported that Ash's grocery list for the
off-season included a left-handed starting pitcher, a second
baseman and help for the bullpen. The Yankees filled that list on
all three counts.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the Rangers could have come was last July, when
lefty starter Darren Oliver was still with the team (the Royce
Clayton-Todd Stottlemyre deal) and second-base prospect Warren
Morris was still with the organization. Morris was traded to
Pittsburgh in the deal that brought Esteban Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   The meter never stops running, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockhead wanted to be a Yankee. The rich got richer. Let it
be a lesson to Melvin and owner Tom Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, though, let it strengthen their resolve to trump
the Yankees' move in the months ahead. Clemens isn't the only No. 1
starter that will be available.
</P>
<P>
   In the Phillies' Florida camp on the day after the Clemens
trade, pitcher Schilling was quoted as saying, ``I want to be here
and contend on this club. But if that's not going to happen in the
immediate future, and they can move me to a club that's contending,
then I would be willing to see if we can work something out.''
</P>
<P>
   Note to Schilling: The Atlanta Braves are in your division. The
New York Mets, who spent a queen's ransom on new contracts, are in
the Phillies' division. The Giants, Cubs, Cardinals, Padres _
wild-card candidates all _ have better playoff chances than the
Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling is younger than Clemens. He throws, for all practical
purposes, just as hard as Clemens. He has better control than
Clemens. And he is every bit the prime-time competitor that Clemens
is.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound, Schilling could do everything for the Rangers that
Clemens could. If it makes a difference, he could learn the words
to The Eyes of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Phillies general manager Ed Wade is down in spring
training, talking as if his team is going to provoke more than a
shrug from the Braves. I don't see it, not with Rico Brogna at
first, Ron Gant in left, and Wade trying to pull four rabbits of
the hat for a rotation behind Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told people we're not moving him,'' Wade told the
Associated Press on Friday. ``For the whole season? I can't answer
that. But our desire is to build around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Hicks, did you hear that?
</P>
<P>
   In February, everybody is a keeper. Every team is a contender.
</P>
<P>
   OK, every team except the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wants to hold on to their designated franchise bedrock,
their Junior Griffey, their Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   But in the heat of July, reality casts a broad shadow.
</P>
<P>
   There was never a chance for Rockhead Roger, as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   But Owner Hicks _ don't you have six pence for a Schilling?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 0005EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
