<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3904 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TOURNAMENT-PREVIE     02-22 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TOURNAMENT-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIME FOR MADNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider it another annual rite of spring passage. With less
than two weeks to Selection Sunday, the NCAA men's tournament
committee again is faced with the problem of too many teams for too
few spots.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into last weekend, there were nearly 100 teams with 16
victories. And while a few dozen of those teams are from smaller
conferences and have padded their victory totals against schedules
too weak to earn serious consideration, nevertheless the at-large
pool is Olympic sized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every year we're getting more teams that are on
the bubble, and there are just a lot of teams that look alike,''
said Kentucky athletic director C.M. Newton, chair of the
tournament committee. ``It's difficult to evaluate those teams in
terms of selecting them as at-large teams and as far as seeding
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting March 5, the nine-member committee will meet in Kansas
City, Mo. Over three days, they'll select 34 at-large teams to go
along with 30 teams that qualified by winning their conferences'
automatic bids. The committee also will seed and place the teams in
the 64-team bracket.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of which teams are in and where they're going
will be made on Sunday, March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first order of business is selecting the right teams, and
then we worry about seeding them,'' Newton said.
</P>
<P>
   It appears the top four seeds are set: Duke, Connecticut, Auburn
and Michigan State. The questions remain, though, where those teams
will be assigned.
</P>
<P>
   Duke is atop the polls and published power rankings. However,
Connecticut, which spent nearly two months ranked No. 1, is also an
Eastern team. Which team gets to be the No. 1 seed in the East
Region?
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils, probably. If assigned to the East, Duke likely
would start play in Charlotte, N.C. If it wins its two games there,
it would advance to the East Region in East Rutherford, N.J., where
the Blue Devils have qualified for the Final Four on four different
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   With Michigan State probably set as the top seed in the Midwest,
the committee must decide whether to ship Connecticut to the West
or South. If the Huskies go West, then Auburn would remain in its
natural region, the South.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, there are two interesting story lines:
</P>
<P>
   TCU, which last year made the field as a No. 5 seed, is sweating
its selection as an at-large team. Tonight's game at Nevada-Las
Vegas, another team on the at-large bubble, will carry significant
weight.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, which started 2-7, has rallied to build a 17-10 record.
The Longhorns' strong finish should catch the committee's
attention. Also, if Texas wins the Big 12 Conference's
regular-season title, that could be important.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we always consider is the regular season and
regular-season conference champions,'' Newton said. ``We want to
make sure we don't overlook any conference champion on that
at-large board.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12 is an example of the jumble of teams the committee
must sort through. The Big 12 has seven teams with at least 17
victories, but none had fewer than six losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, when we got down to the last eight to 10 teams for
the last few spots, it got really, really difficult,'' Newton said.
``At that point, we look at every piece of information we have.''
Projected top 4 seeds ``Star-Telegram'' college basketball writer
Wendell Barnhouse projects the top four seeds in each of the four
NCAA Tournament regions: No. East South Midwest West 1. Duke Auburn
Michigan State Connecticut 2. Kentucky Maryland Cincinnati Stanford
3. St. John's Miami (Fla.) Arizona Utah 4. UCLA Wisconsin North
Carolina Ohio State Projecting the field
</P>
<P>
   The following conferences should place more than one team in the
NCAA Tournament bracket: Atlantic Coast Conference
</P>
<P>
   Locks: Duke, Maryland, North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: The last time the ACC had less than four teams was 1979
when it sent just two to the NCAA Tournament _ when it was a
40-team event. Wake Forest is making a small late run, but none of
the other also-rans _ North Carolina State, Georgia Tech, and
Florida State _ are showing signs of a late-season charge. Atlantic
10
</P>
<P>
   Lock: Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Xavier and George Washington are probable selections,
and Rhode Island, which started slowly, is still in the hunt. Big
East
</P>
<P>
   Locks: Connecticut, Miami (Fla.), St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Figure Syracuse, Villanova and Rutgers in the mix. At
least two and perhaps all three will make it. None can afford a
late-season slump, however. Big Ten
</P>
<P>
   Locks: Michigan State, Ohio State, Wisconsin, Indiana, Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Two weeks ago, there was talk the Big Ten would set an
NCAA Tournament record with eight teams. Now, it looks like maybe
just six. Northwestern has played its way out. Iowa and Minnesota
are in danger of doing the same. Big 12
</P>
<P>
   Locks: Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: The Longhorns have two things in their favor _ a strong
finish and a likely regular-season title. Both are major factors
for at-large teams. The Sooners have been impressive on the road,
another important factor. Oklahoma State is making a late run.
Conference USA
</P>
<P>
   Lock: Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: The Bearcats probably lost a No. 1-seed during a recent
three-game losing streak. Louisville and North Carolina-Charlotte
are likely to get bids. Alabama-Birmingham and DePaul are also in
the picture. Pacific-10
</P>
<P>
   Locks: Stanford, Arizona, UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Washington probably will give this league a fourth
entrant. California probably played itself into the NIT with losses
at Washington State and Washington last week. Southeastern
</P>
<P>
   Locks: Auburn, Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Florida, Arkansas and Tennessee have bids in sight. The
Razorbacks' victory over Kentucky on Saturday was huge. Western
Athletic
</P>
<P>
   Lock: Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: TCU's loss at Air Force might cost the Frogs a bid.
Likewise, UNLV's tourney hopes were hurt by its loss to SMU. The
loser of tonight's TCU-UNLV game can probably start making plans
for the NIT. New Mexico has 20 victories, but the Lobos' anemic
power rating has them sweating. Mid-American
</P>
<P>
   Lock: Conference tournament winner.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Miami (Ohio) could wind up with an at-large bid. Toledo
and Kent are also still in the picture. Missouri Valley
</P>
<P>
   Lock: Conference tournament winner.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Southwest Missouri State has a chance if another team
wins the conference tourney. West Coast
</P>
<P>
   Lock: Conference tournament winner.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: If it doesn't win the WCC tournament, Gonzaga will have
a good shot at an at-large bid. One and only one The following
conferences are projected to get only one team, the winner of its
automatic bid (projected winners are listed): Conference Projected
America East Drexel Colonial George Mason Big Sky Northern Arizona
Big South Winthrop Big West Boise State Ivy Penn Metro Atlantic
Siena Mid-Eastern Athletic South Carolina State Midwestern
Collegiate Detroit Mercy Mid-Continent Oral Roberts Northeast
Maryland-Baltimore County Ohio Valley Murray State Patriot
Lafayette Southern College of Charleston Southland Texas-San
Antonio Southwestern Athletic Alcorn State Sun Belt Louisiana Tech
Trans-America Samford
</P>
