OATES HINTS AT WHO MIGHT BAT THIRD FOR RANGERS (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ It remains to be seen whether left
fielder Rusty Greer will continue to hit third in the Rangers'
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates hinted this winter that Greer would, but
remains noncommittal. First baseman Rafael Palmeiro, whom the
Rangers signed as a free agent Dec. 1, made it known of his desire
to hit third in front of right fielder Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to hit wherever they want me to hit, but I feel like
I can hit third,'' said Greer, who arrived in camp early and
participated during yesterday's workout. ``I feel comfortable
there, but I'll do whatever is good for this ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer likely will hit third this season and be followed in the
order by Gonzalez, Palmeiro and catcher Ivan Rodriguez. MORE MONEY,
SAME SELE Right-hander Aaron Sele appeared astonished yesterday
after learning he became the highest-paid starting pitcher in
Rangers' history earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Sele and the Rangers avoided an arbitration hearing and reached
an agreement on a one-year contract worth $5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what it is,'' said Sele, who went 19-11 with a 4.23
earned-run average during 33 starts for the Rangers. ``You know me.
I'm going to go out there and work hard and have the same approach
I've always had. I would never change who I am.'' PATTERSON'S
PROGRESS Right-hander Danny Patterson entered camp a year ago
rehabilitating his right shoulder after undergoing arthroscopic
surgery to repair partial tears of his labrum and rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   It showed in his performance.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson missed the first 17 days of the 1998 season and
finished it with a 2-5 record and 4.45 ERA, recording only 33
strikeouts during 60 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth/Dallas chapter of the Baseball Writers
Association of America selected Patterson as the Rangers' Rookie of
the Year after the 1997 season. Patterson went 10-6 with a 3.42 ERA
and recorded 69 strikeouts during 71 innings that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patterson is so far ahead _ not only physically, but mentally
_ of where he was a year ago,'' Oates said. ``He's not even the
same person.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson agrees, and his changeup proves it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was working about 75-80 percent of the time today,''
Patterson said. ``That's better than the 20 percent it was last
year.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Cesar King, who will begin this season at either
Double-A Tulsa or Triple-A Oklahoma, will be sidelined 2-4 weeks
after sustaining a fracture to a bone in his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Tony Fossas sustained a bruise to his right hand
after being hit with a ball during yesterday's workout. He should
be able to participate in today's workout.
</P>
</TEXT>
