<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-PROSPECTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' STAR SEARCH CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ His name is Joaquin Benoit. Remember it.
The Rangers hope one day he'll be as familiar to people in Texas as
Kevin Brown, Bobby Witt and Kenny Rogers once were.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more so.
</P>
<P>
   He is 20, a right-handed pitcher from the Dominican Republic who
can throw hard. His minor-league record is 13-11 with a 2.71
earned-run average with 167 strikeouts in 209 innings and 52 walks.
</P>
<P>
   He is only a blip on the Rangers' minor-league screen. He's not
in major-league camp and his name has yet to be mentioned in
magazine lists of baseball's top prospects. He hasn't pitched above
Class A.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers know who he is. So do other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``His name has been brought up in trade talks,'' Rangers general
manager Doug Melvin said. ``He's got a great arm.''
</P>
<P>
   They've said that, though, about so many through the years, but
the Rangers still await the eye-popping player who can shake up
their camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' farm system once turned out pretty good front-line
pitchers, including Brown, Witt, Rogers, Darren Oliver, Roger
Pavlik and Robb Nen. But Rick Helling in 1994 is the last rookie to
make the starting rotation out of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen any Kerry Woods in our camp lately,'' manager
Johnny Oates said. ``But there are probably 24 other major-league
managers saying the same thing. Guys like that don't come down the
pike very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates would love to see one. He was watching his team work out
yesterday when he was startled by a loud pop on a minor-league
field. He turned to see a 6-foot-4 pitcher pummeling the catcher's
glove with an impressive fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Oates strolled over to watch 19-year-old Justin Backsmeyer, the
organization's 10th-round draft pick out of Missouri who pitched
eight innings last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told Doug, I like 6-4 right-handers or left-handers,''
Oates said. ``That's what I've been looking for. You never know if
you're looking at a 19-year-old Roger Clemens.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is one, he's not in the Rangers' big-league camp.
</P>
<P>
   There are ``good arms'' here that are a year or more away from
being ready. Ryan Glynn, 9-6 with a 3.44 ERA at Double-A Tulsa last
season, and Corey Lee, 10-9 with a 4.51 ERA at Tulsa, are likely
headed for Triple-A Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Johnson, the Rangers' No. 1 pick in 1995, will likely
be there for a third consecutive season. So too will Matt Perisho,
who got hit hard last June, then ended up having shoulder surgery,
and Eric Moody.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde King, a former Yankees pitching coach who is considered a
shrewd judge of arms, once told Melvin: ``Take your top five
pitching prospects. You'll be lucky if just one of them ever makes
it big and real lucky if two of them have success in the big
leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers like two younger pitchers in camp. Doug Davis, a
left-hander from City College of San Francisco, led the Class-A
Florida State League with 173 strikeouts in 1551/3 innings.
Right-hander Derrick Cook was 13-7 with a 3.66 ERA in the Florida
State League. Both will start at Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   There are others not in big-league camp who are still to come.
</P>
<P>
   R.A. Dickey, the 1996 No. 1 draft pick without an ulnar ligament
in his right elbow, is trying to make it as a reliever after
recording 38 saves in Class A last season. Sam Marsonek, the other
first-round pick in 1996, pitched 11 innings last season because of
a bad elbow, but he's only 20 and is pitching pain-free in the
minor-league camp.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Dittfurth, last year's No. 5 pick, impressed Rangers
officials with a 1.34 ERA in the Gulf Coast League. Oates would be
impressed with him as well. He's 6-6 and 19.
</P>
<P>
   But he's still a blip on the radar screen. The long-awaited stud
simply isn't here yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
