<HEADLINE>
TCU TOURNEY HOPES ON THE ROPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. _ His smile vanished, exchanged for a
furrowed brow and a lowered gaze.
</P>
<P>
   TCU guard Ryan Carroll had been asked what results were needed
from a two-game swing through Air Force and Nevada-Las Vegas to
assure an NCAA Tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``A sweep,'' Carroll said finally, his smile returning. ``We
need a sweep, and I think we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   His words provided a painful reminder as he and his teammates
quietly filed onto a bus after an 81-78 loss to hapless Air Force
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A sweep had become impossible, getting swept a sudden
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   So when TCU finishes this two-game swing against Mountain
Division-leading UNLV at 11 tonight at Thomas &AMP; Mack Center, it is
no longer to assure an NCAA berth but to prevent itself from being
knocked from consideration altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Horned Frogs coach Billy Tubbs responded
curtly when asked what the loss did to his team's chances for an
NCAA Tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   It probably means that the Frogs must win the Western Athletic
Conference tournament in Las Vegas to get in. It definitely means
that the Frogs need to get to the WAC tournament.
</P>
<P>
   That trip isn't guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   TCU (17-8, 5-6 WAC) dropped to sixth place in the WAC's Mountain
Division with three games remaining. Only the top six teams in each
division make the tournament. The Frogs are in a battle with
Wyoming, which lost 80-75 to Colorado State on Saturday night, for
the sixth and final spot.
</P>
<P>
   A victory against UNLV (15-9, 8-3) will go a long way toward
getting the Frogs in both tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   But Tubbs said he realizes that the Frogs need to play much
better than they did against Air Force to stand a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we were ready to play like we have to play,''
Tubbs said of the Air Force game. ``I just don't think we were
combat ready, to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a couple of weeks ago, Lee Nailon and Prince Fowler called
a players-only meeting to try to try to address a somewhat
lackadaisical attitude that pervaded the team.
</P>
<P>
   The problems had begun with a 95-88 overtime loss to UNLV on
Jan. 23. Nailon was ejected for fighting less than 60 seconds into
that game. It began a four-game losing streak for the Frogs, with
Nailon missing two games and being a nonfactor in the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Victories against Wyoming and Colorado State followed the
meeting, and the Frogs appeared to have the problem addressed. This
trip was supposed to be TCU's take-a-look-at-us,
you-can't-possibly-leave-us-out-of-the-NCAA-tournament tour.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to culminate with a big finale in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs would get the victory, Nailon would get a little
redemption and Dick Vitale would be there to lay on superlatives
for the ESPN audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody realizes what's at stake,'' Carroll said before TCU
left on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes remain high for the Horned Frogs, although it's no
longer about assurances but survival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
