<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS-AVALANCHE CLASH ENDS IN TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Consider yesterday's game between the Stars and
Colorado Avalanche a television miniseries of sorts. Mark it: ``To
be continued.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Western Conference's top teams settled nothing at
Reunion Arena in a 1-1 matinee tie which, ironically enough, leaves
their season series at 1-1-1.
</P>
<P>
   And while there were plenty of highlights, big plays and
breakdowns, the general feeling afterward for both sides was: We'll
see you later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, anytime you play a team like Colorado, it's going
to be a bigger game,'' veteran winger Dave Reid said. ``But the
bottom line is I think both teams came out of it with a healthy
respect for the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars move their unbeaten streak to six games (5-0-1) and
their league-best record to 35-10-9. The Avalanche (29-21-7)
stretches its winless streak to five games (0-2-3), but gave the
Stars plenty to think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it felt very much like a playoff game,'' Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock said. `It was a well-played hockey game with a
tremendous amount of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The only negative aspect was a knee injury to Stars defenseman
Darryl Sydor, who is listed as day-to-day pending a re-evaluation
today by team doctor Dan Cooper. Hitchcock said he doesn't expect
Sydor to be out more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Stars' power play struggled mightily without Sydor,
who leads the team in man-advantage scoring at 30 points (seven
goals, 23 assists). Sydor, in fact, ranks fifth in the NHL in
power-play points.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars missed his presence at the left point, especially
after Sydor set up Brett Hull perfectly for a power-play goal at
the 7:58 mark of the first period. After Mike Modano did a gritty
job of digging the puck in the left corner, Sydor one-timed a pass
to Hull, who made an amazing redirection into the net from 25 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, Sydor then bruised his left knee in a
knee-to-knee collision with Colorado winger Stephan Yelle and had
to leave the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars went 0-for-6 on the power play the rest of the day and
looked disjointed as Shawn Chambers, Derian Hatcher and Mike Modano
all tried to fill the role of Sydor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be easy. When you lose a guy who's so
important to your power play and offensively to your team,'' Ludwig
said. ``You don't expect something like that, so we haven't really
been using other players out there. The chemistry was off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars failed to take advantage of six power-play chances in
the first two periods, and the Avalanche bounced back to tie the
game on a hard-working play by winger Adam Deadmarsh, which led to
a goal by rookie Chris Drury at the 11:30 mark of the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   Deadmarsh brought the puck up the right wing and took so much of
the attention of the Stars' defense that he was able to pass back
into the left circle to feed a wide-open Drury. It was the only
goal Ed Belfour would allow against 18 shots.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the rink, Colorado's Patrick Roy was equal
to the task. After shutting out the Stars two weeks ago on 27
shots, he turned away 23 shots yesterday, including two in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought both goalies were very good,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock also was pleased with a strong team effort, which
included a 30:30 performance from Hatcher, a 29:34 day from Sergei
Zubov and a 26:56 effort from Modano, who also added an assist.
</P>
<P>
   In all, it was the perfect set up to the next meeting between
the Stars and the Avalanche, the final game of the regular season
on Sunday, April 18 in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season is the season, we learned that in the past,'' Roy
said. ``And the playoffs are the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
