<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BELFOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, BELFOUR'S NO SLOUCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL KRUGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In his well-documented, ``worst game in recent memory''
two weeks ago, Ed Belfour let three of 12 Colorado shots get under,
around and through him.
</P>
<P>
   That's .333 of all the shots he faced in a 3-0 loss against the
Avalanche. Not a bad batting average, but not a memorable day
minding the net.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to yesterday, when the tough-minded and
tough-to-beat Ed Belfour returned to Reunion Arena. He seemed so
focused on not letting anything get past him, when Avalanche winger
Valeri Kamensky tumbled toward the goal in the second period,
Belfour kick-saved him aside.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour might have said there was no redemption on the line
yesterday, but in stopping 17 of 18 shots, his play seemed to
indicate otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely didn't have my best game the last time they were
here,'' Belfour confirmed after the Stars' 1-1 tie with Colorado
yesterday. ``So, you try to make up for it in the next game you
play against them.''
</P>
<P>
   As Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy noted, Belfour looked ``sharp''
from the outset. A minute into the game, Avalanche right winger
Milan Hejduk slapped a shot that echoed through the arena after
bouncing off Belfour's pads.
</P>
<P>
   Though 18 shots isn't exactly working overtime, Colorado coach
Bob Hartley said Belfour ``made the big saves when he had to.''
Three of those came with the Avalanche pressing on a 4-on-3 power
play when Belfour stopped defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh twice from the
slot then snuffed a rebound by sharp-shooting center Peter
Forsberg.
</P>
<P>
   On the one shot Colorado did get past Belfour _ a one-timer from
the doorstep by Chris Drury off a pass through the goal mouth by
Adam Deadmarsh _ Drury said, ``I was lucky to get it in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   And this seemed to be one of those Belfour performances in which
the opponent needed some luck to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't really view it as a bounce-back game, he viewed it
as a challenge,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said of Belfour. ``The
thing I liked about him was he was really strong positionally. He
outwaited people, especially when we really needed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Belfour might as well have been playing the waiting
game for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime one of our guys has a bad game, we want to make up for
it,'' Belfour said. ``You don't like feeling that you let your team
down. That's the case for me, too.'' /
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 0007EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
