r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     02-22 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ IN A FOUL MOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Shaquille O'Neal's shot faltered Sunday, his usually
automatic two-footers clanging like hail off aluminum siding, but
while the Seattle SuperSonics momentarily silenced his game,
nothing could quell his postgame rant.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq's shooting percentage plummeted in a 92-89 loss to the
Sonics, but he more than compensated by shooting his mouth off
afterward. O'Neal missed an uncharacteristic 9 of 14 shots in the
first half _ and didn't make a single trip to the foul line _ while
the Sonics took a lead they would never relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of thing that puts a 7-foot-1, 320-pound
Superman in a bad mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make these B.S. rules up, then they don't enforce them,''
he said, and he was referring to Rule 12B, Section 1, Parts A
through K _ personal fouls.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal, in a mood to get fined, was only getting started. In
his semiannual address on the issue, O'Neal claimed to be the
victim of constant hacking, rarely whistled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game, seven years, for every game,'' he said. ``All
those guys say they want to hack-a-Shaq. It's in all the papers,
it's on TV, I still don't get the calls. That's cool. I know what I
gotta do. I'm gonna have to start acting crazy to get something in
this sorry league. . . . I gotta start acting like a wild man.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least he didn't threaten to break anyone's nose. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   Olden Polynice would have been high on the list of candidates,
though. Polynice, signed by the Sonics in January, proved an
effective answer to O'Neal in the paint, an answer Seattle never
had when Jim McIlvaine was the center.
</P>
<P>
   Though O'Neal eventually got 27 points, he scored only two
points in the second quarter, while the Sonics built a nine-point
halftime lead. He finished 11 of 24 for the game, a far cry from
his usual 57-percent shooting. And Polynice grabbed a season-high
17 rebounds to go with 15 points and a lot of purposeful
fist-pumping to incite the KeyArena crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It figured. Polynice worked out with the Lakers after the
lockout, openly lobbied for a job with them and has been a general
irritant to them ever since.
</P>
<P>
   He derided $49 million backup center Elden Campbell as ``the
albatross.'' And once Polynice signed with Seattle, he created a
national stir by divulging that O'Neal and Kobe Bryant had once
fought in practice, intimating some kind of power struggle that was
more media-spun fantasy than reality.
</P>
<P>
   So here was Polynice, again getting under the Lakers' skin,
accomplishing the mission Seattle had in mind when it signed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they brought me in here,'' he said of neutralizing
O'Neal. ``I'm not intimidated by anyone. I respect people's games,
but I'm not intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice did the job long enough to let the Sonics' main weapons
do their job _ Gary Payton scoring 26 points and Vin Baker 19.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers watched their winning streak end with a whimper
at three games as they shot 41 percent and rarely threatened the
Sonics' lead.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant had 23 points and 13 rebounds but shot 8 for 20 and
committed four turnovers. Eddie Jones got the Lakers back in the
game with an outstanding third quarter and finished with 17 points
but along with his teammates came up short in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The three-point final deficit was deceptive. The Lakers hit 8 of
22 shots in the fourth and were down eight points with 28.9 seconds
to go. And they would have lost by six if not for a buzzer-beating
3-pointer by Derek Harper to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   They had long ago been done in by a sluggish first half in which
Bryant and O'Neal combined to go 10 for 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, I thought we were trying to do too much on
our own,'' coach Del Harris said. ``All the shots were taken by
Kobe or Shaq, the ball movement just wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant admitted as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq and I saw so many gaps . . . we were like licking our
chops, not knowing which way to go. So oftentimes it kind of got
confused,'' he said. ``That's all right, chalk it up to experience.
We won't make the same mistake again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
