<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CAN'T COMPLETELY KILL RANGERS' SPIRITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The sun illuminated the Florida sky. The
isolated clouds above moved slowly across the blue background with
assistance from the cool, gentle breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Tony Fossas described yesterday as ``the perfect
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, despite not having right-hander Roger Clemens on hand
at the Charlotte County Stadium complex, Rangers manager Johnny
Oates continued to supervise his pitchers, catchers and the few
position players who reported early.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some pronouncements that the Yankees _ by virtue of
their trade for Clemens on Thursday _ have secured the American
League pennant before a game has been played, the other 13 AL teams
did not cancel camp and the season.
</P>
<P>
   The National League teams, however, are ready for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll need Roger when they play us in the fall classic in
October,'' Los Angeles Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone told
reporters. ``It'll be fun. It will be nice to see Kevin Brown and
Roger Clemens matched up in October.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Rangers players would be better served using this time
and weather improving their handicaps at nearby Riverwood Golf
Course or a leisurely afternoon along the Gulf Coast's sandy
beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already asked for four tickets in Los Angeles and New
York,'' Oates said, ``but I know I can get rid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers continued preparations to defend their AL West
title and, despite Malone's bold proclamation, perhaps challenge
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not chopped liver, and there's not anyone in here who's
scared of them,'' designated hitter Lee Stevens said. ``We didn't
do it in '96 or '98, but there's too much competitive juice in here
to be in awe of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, don't misunderstand Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the team to beat every year until someone knocks them
off,'' he said. ``They're the most dominating team in the American
League. They could be the Chicago Bulls of major-league baseball if
their team stays intact and wins a couple more World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, though, must prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're wasting our time,'' said left fielder
Rusty Greer, who reported early to camp yesterday. ``Obviously,
they were a great team before they got Clemens. He's only going to
add to their firepower, but we believe we can go out and play with
anybody. I imagine that's the way everyone in baseball feels right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not everyone shares Greer's optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might as well pack up and go home,'' Boston Red Sox
right-hander Tim Wakefield told reporters after learning of the
Yankees' acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, though, ``by no means are a lock to win the World
Series again,'' Rangers right-hander Rick Helling said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone realizes how close we were last year,''
the 20-game winner said. ``Nobody else even sniffed them during the
playoffs. We had a chance to beat them in all three games, but
that's why they were who they were last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling referred to the Yankees' three-game sweep of the Rangers
in the 1998 Division Series despite scoring only nine runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're better than we were last year,'' Helling said,
``and hopefully we'll find ways to win those games.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, though, lacks faith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
