<SLUG> BC-SKOREA-DISSIDENTS-RELEASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREA AMNESTY WILL FREE DISSIDENT JAILED FOR 41 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ South Korea said on Monday that it would release the
last long-term political prisoners held in its jails, including the
world's longest-serving prisoner of conscience, to commemorate the
first anniversary of the inauguration of President Kim Dae Jung,
himself a former political prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the government will offer amnesty to some 8,800
prisoners, most of whom have been convicted of minor offenses like
inciting labor unrest but are not serving prison terms, a
government spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Among 17 long-term prisoners scheduled to be released on
Thursday is Woo Yong Gak, the longest-serving detainee, who was
captured 41 years ago as a member of a North Korean military
reconnaissance team whose boat was seized when it entered South
Korean waters, a government spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Woo and the other prisoners were to have been let go last August
on the 50th anniversary of the end of the Japanese occupation of
Korea. But they refused to renounce their commitment to North
Korea's radical Stalinist doctrine and agree to abide by South
Korea's National Security Law. The law can be so broadly construed
that it has ensnared labor leaders and even those caught listening
to North Korean radio broadcasts and distributing pamphlets about
Communism.
</P>
<P>
   When the amnesty of last year was announced, advocates said the
requirement to abide by the South Korea law effectively undercut
the government's decision to abandon its demand that prisoners
renounce their ideological beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for that reason, the amnesty failed to empty South
Korea's prisons of political prisoners like Woo, who has
steadfastly refused to abandon his principles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
