</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING LOST IN RIVIERA'S CORRIDOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Augusta National Golf Club has Amen Corner.
Riviera Country Club has Eucalyptus Corridor, and as Ernie Els will
attest, it is one sticky stretch of scenery. Els gummed up the
11th, 12th and 13th holes but good Saturday at the Nissan Open and
it cost him the 54-hole lead.
</P>
<P>
   He needed 16 strokes _ 3 over par _ to navigate the 1,394 yards
during the third round, which is why he was chasing Ted Tryba. The
three tight holes tucked like a military fold into the left corner
of the 6,946-yard Pacific Palisades layout were pivotal again on
Sunday. The difference was that this time both the gusts and the
putts broke Els' way.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied all three holes in that sinewy stretch, trimming six
strokes off his previous day's score. That reduction loomed large
in Els' two-stroke victory over Tryba, Tiger Woods and Davis Love
III.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of a tournament-record 56,723 fans was the finishing
hole and the failure of Tryba and Woods to manufacture the birdies
they needed to force a playoff with Els. But neither Woods nor
Tryba likely would have found themselves in such an unenviable
position _ with a wicked wind in their faces and the weight of the
tournament on their shoulders _ had either been able to cut
Eucalyptus Corridor down to size as did the 29-year-old Els.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really nice to play that stretch well,'' Els said.
``That was a key to my win.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Eucalyptus Corridor was where the aptly named Tryba
(pronounced TREE-buh) branched out from the faceless clump on the
tour in which he long has been bunched. He went eagle-birdie-birdie
to sustain the charge that culminated in a course-record
10-under-par 61.
</P>
<P>
   The wind and the pressure picked up on Sunday and try as he
might, Tryba couldn't come close to his previous day's feats. He
birdied No.11, gave the stroke right back with a bogey on 12 and
parred 13.
</P>
<P>
   His playing partner, Woods, also covered the stretch in a
pedestrian 1 over par. With his prodigious length, you would expect
Woods to leave skid marks on the par-5 11th, not spin his wheels as
he did in parring it three of the four days.
</P>
<P>
   Among Els' closest challengers, only Love, who played the three
holes in 1 under par, gained any momentum heading into the wind
tunnel that was the rest of the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winds started switching and swirling on 10 and 11 and it
made it very difficult,'' said Tryba after his closing 72. ``You'd
hit a perfect shot and it would fly the green. When you hit a good
shot, you like to get the most out of it. We weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11th, 12th and 13th fairways are as slender as fingernails
anyway. When the winds started gusting, they became harder and
harder for shots to graze. Too, the greens grew as hard as the
hearts of the PGA officials who settled on Sunday's pin placements.
</P>
<P>
   Els loves playing Riviera, but he can be forgiven for not having
a soft spot for Eucalyptus Corridor. The three holes are grooved
for the golfer who draws the ball and Els plays a fade.
</P>
<P>
   It's a small wonder he hasn't been tempted to take some of those
eucalyptus leaves off the trees lining the three fairways and chew
on them between shots. For all the trouble he's found on the holes
in his three visits here, Els could play the ``medicinal purposes''
card without anyone batting an eyelash.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared no relief was in sight when Els pulled his drive
into the left rough on No.11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've come close to hitting that fairway,'' Els
lamented.
</P>
<P>
   An adequate 8-iron and a satisfactory 7-iron left him with a
30-foot birdie putt, which he sank. That lifted his spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a real big turnaround,'' said Els, who thought he was
staring hard at a 5 or, gulp, even a 6.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the par-4 12th was a snap: driver, sand wedge to 8
feet, birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Then came No.13, which was very unlucky for Els on Saturday. You
don't soon forget hitting your drive out of bounds and slinking off
with a double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you let it, it can get to you a little bit,'' said Els, who
managed to block out the events of the previous day and rebound as
resolutely as a certain power forward the Lakers might or might not
finally welcome into the fold today.
</P>
<P>
   Els hit a 4-wood off the tee, drilled an 8-iron to 5 feet and
drained the birdie putt to exact a measure of revenge on the hole.
</P>
<P>
   All that remained was for Els to collect some compensation for
his final-round collapse here during the 1995 PGA Championships.
Which he did as dusk approached when he accepted the winner's
trophy and a check for $504,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played the back nine the way I should have today,'' Els said
and it effectively started at Eucalyptus Corridor. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
