<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, BLUES MAY BE VULNERABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Outcome aside, Kings coach Larry Robinson said
Sunday he didn't have much to complain about when he looked back on
his team's start to its season-long six-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (21-31-5) blew a 2-0 lead and settled for a 2-2 tie
Saturday night in Calgary, then flew to St. Louis on Sunday for
tonight's game against the Blues (22-23-10) at the Kiel Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at our film,'' Robinson said Sunday afternoon. ``We
had a couple of guys who I didn't think played well, but overall,
we had good scoring chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, probably with Stephane Fiset in goal, the Kings will
try to beat a team they've struggled against in recent seasons,
most memorably when they were swept out of the first round of last
season's playoffs by the Blues. In their past six visits to St.
Louis, including a 5-2 loss earlier this season and two losses in
last year's playoffs, the Kings are 0-6-1.
</P>
<P>
   But St. Louis has been struggling recently, and for one of the
few times this season, the Kings _ who did not practice Sunday _
will be facing a team with more injuries than they have.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' top four players are defenseman Rob Blake, left wing
Luc Robitaille, right wing Glen Murray and center Jozef Stumpel,
and Saturday's game marked just the eighth time this season that
all four have been in the lineup and healthy. In those games, the
Kings have a 6-1-1 record. All four were in the lineup for nine
games early in the season, but Stumpel was playing hurt at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   When the Blues' injury woes were mentioned to him, Robinson was
unmoved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to get any sympathy from this side,'' he
said. ``When it comes to injuries, that's been our season.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray's return: Murray played Saturday for the first time since
injuring his right knee seven weeks earlier, bringing to the lineup
his speed, willingness to go to the net and talents on the power
play and on the penalty-killing unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first game,'' Murray said. ``I felt a little behind
the play and thinking too much. But it's a fast game, especially
when you miss 19 games. For most of it, though, I felt all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray came close to winning the game with consecutive
one-timers from the slot about 12 minutes into the third period,
but was stopped both times by Calgary goalie Fred Brathwaite. He
played 23 minutes, 51 seconds, fourth-most on the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think his timing is completely there,'' Robinson said,
``but I think once he got going, it got better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
