<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS DRAW THE WRATH OF SHAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Emergency alert for Denver tonight and Vancouver
tomorrow: Prepare the shelters, stock up on batteries and water,
and put extra rotations in the hospital ERs.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq Diesel is coming, and jeez, is he mad.
</P>
<P>
   The next two stops on the Los Angeles Lakers' road trip will
feel the wrath of Shaquille O'Neal's Sunday afternoon in Seattle,
where Olden Polynice, Vin Baker and the rest of the green meanies
wailed on his pitiful 7-foot-1, 315-pound self. They were abetted
by an officiating crew he called ``cheating bastards.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal vowed afterwards, in his usual quiet voice, to seek
vengeance upon the hapless hordes wherever they lurk.
</P>
<P>
   In enunciating his own personal jihad, it wasn't quite as
eloquent as, say, ``My sword shall run with the blood of the
infidels,'' but the point was no less unmistakable after Sunday's
92-89 defeat in which the Lakers never led:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going,'' he said, ``to break people up.''
</P>
<P>
   Well. So much for the new, fan-friendly NBA. Imagine paying $650
for a courtside seat only to have one's Armani soiled with the
entrails of the hometown heroes.
</P>
<P>
   If it happens, send the dry-cleaning bill to Polynice. It was
his fault, after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glad I got away with it,'' said Polynice, a faint nee-ner,
neener somewhere in the back of his voice. Then he changed to a
more conciliatory posture, knowing that there are further crossings
of elbows to come with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please tell Shaq: `I love you still.' I'm sorry he feels that
way. I love him as a person, and consider him a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Now he says it. Where was this compassion on KeyArena's
low blocks Sunday? How can Polynice not appreciate his rival's
persecution? Where's his empathy for travail of the giant?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, he's like the big kid in the park,'' Polynice said.
``He's too big for any of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein rubs the rub.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and the Lakers are convinced that, as coach Del Harris
put it, ``Shaq gets more (uncalled) fouls on him than anybody in
the league.'' Harris went on to say that referees have told him
that if O'Neal were a smaller guy, he would probably draw more
fouls. But the conventional NBA wisdom is that for opponents to
have a chance against His Largeness, they must be allowed heavier
ordnance.
</P>
<P>
   To which O'Neal said: ``It's been this way every game for seven
years. It's written down: Hack-a-Shaq. I'm not going to take it any
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to act crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. I thought that's why the Lakers were trying to sign Dennis
Rodman. How many cartoon characters is a single NBA team allowed to
have?
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that O'Neal's threat of lightning from his
terrible, swift sword may be a set-up for Rodman's entrance, which
could be announced this morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers currently are a flawed team less formidable than when
they wasted the Sonics 4-1 in the second round of last spring's
playoffs. Sunday they were missing from the '98 team forward Robert
Horry (heart problems) and guard Nick Van Exel (gone to Denver),
two players whose advantages in quickness were difference-makers in
the Seattle series.
</P>
<P>
   Their replacements in the starting lineup are slow-footed
forward Travis Knight and ancient guard Derek Harper, believed to
have once teamed with Bob Cousy in the same backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Troubles were compounded by the fact that wunderkind forward
Kobe Bryant is still packing way too much mustard for his hot dog
of a game, as well as the Laker bench supplying just 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was O'Neal, with his lower lip stuck so far out it
was like a sixth defender for the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   This team could definitely use Rodman, if for no other reason
than one glaring statistic from the game: O'Neal didn't get a
single rebound in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine His Largeness blaming the officials for
that one. Rebounding is chiefly a matter of positioning and effort.
If he wants to use the excuse that the Sonics held him, too, that
whopper deserves a place alongside the presidential assurance that
he never had sex with that woman.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that the current Lakers nearly have been caught by
the Sonics in one area that separated them last May: Interior size
and toughness. Polynice's 15 points and 17 rebounds were almost 15
points and 17 rebounds more than the Sonics obtained from Jim
McIlvaine and Sam Perkins against L.A.
</P>
<P>
   While it's not likely that Polynice can maintain those numbers,
it's also unlikely that the rest of the Sonics will continue to be
as wretched on offense. The best 3-point shooting team in the NBA
last year missed 15 of 17 triplets Sunday, suggesting that if just
one guy finally heats up, the Sonics will border on the
respectable.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the Lakers are the worry of other teams. The Sonics
don't have to play the them again until March 5, which is enough
time for O'Neal to be subdued by the National Guard, Power Rangers,
Jackie Chan or the Wide Warrior himself, Commissioner David Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, O'Neal will remember that however agonizing the
persecution, however vile the conspiracy, Polynice still loves him.
A tough love, true, with two hands pushing in the back; but love
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
