<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
` BOTTLE' EDGES OUT `PAYBACK' AT BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Romance won out over revenge as ``Message in a
Bottle'' edged ``Payback'' in a steady performance at the nation's
multiplexes with an estimated $10.3 million at 2,545 theaters
during the Friday-Sunday period, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The second weekend of Warner Bros.' love story, starring Kevin
Costner and Robin Wright Penn, led by about 1 percent over
Paramount's third weekend of ``Payback'' with $10.2 million at
2,768 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   But the positions could be reversed today when final figures are
released if there are slight shifts in Sunday's totals.
</P>
<P>
   Holdovers took the first five slots as a trio of new entries
failed to generate much excitement among customers. Analysts noted
that the weekend following the Presidents' Day holiday is
traditionally slow, leading studios to hold back top-tier titles
for periods with more potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is usually a pretty dead weekend,'' said movie analyst
Arthur Rockwell. ``I'm a little surprised that `Message in a
Bottle' held up so well, but part of that is due to there not being
any heavy-duty new films.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting
service, said ``Message'' benefited from being the only major movie
in the market for adult audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Message,'' which has received mixed reviews, has seen its
cumulative gross top $32 &UR;  &LR; million while Mel Gibson's ``Payback''
has gone past $57 &UR;  &LR; million to become the top grosser for 1999 films
so far. Rockwell said its success is due to Gibson's ongoing box
office appeal, adding, `` &UR;  &LR; `Payback' is a strong film with an
incredibly strong star.''
</P>
<P>
   Comedies took the next three slots, led by Disney's second
weekend of ``My Favorite Martian'' in third with $6.7 &UR;  &LR; million at
2,312 locations, followed by New Line's second weekend of ``Blast
From the Past'' with $6.1 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,544 sites and Miramax's
11th weekend of ``Shakespeare in Love'' with $5.7 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,030
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare,'' which received an impressive 13 Academy Award
nominations on Feb. 9, has topped $54 &UR;  &LR; million overall and should
continue to perform well, Bucksbaum said. ``There is a lot of buzz
right now for `Shakespeare in Love,' &UR;  &LR; '' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's opening of ``October Sky,'' a family drama set in a
coal-mining town at the dawn of the space age, performed moderately
with $5.5 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,495 theaters. Bucksbaum said ``Sky,'' which
has received generally positive reviews, could benefit from strong
word-of-mouth among moviegoers but will face a tough marketplace
with studios usually opening four new films each weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really isn't a lot of room for all these films,''
Bucksbaum said, adding that next weekend's strongest entries appear
to be Disney's family drama ``The Other Sister'' and Sony's
thriller ``8mm'' with Nicolas Cage.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's fourth weekend of ``She's All That'' continued to draw
respectably with $5.4 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,639 theaters to top
$49 &UR;  &LR; million overall, followed by 20th Century Fox's opening of
corporate comedy ``Office Space'' with a barely adequate
$4.1 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,740 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's fourth weekend of ``Rushmore'' finished ninth with
$2.7 &UR;  &LR; million at 764 screens, followed by DreamWorks' 31st weekend
of ``Saving Private Ryan'' with 2.4 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,139 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan,'' which has 11 Oscar nominations, has topped
$203 &UR;  &LR; million overall and passed ``Armageddon'' for 24th spot on
the all-time domestic chart.
</P>
<P>
   Tied for 11th at $2.3 &UR;  &LR; million each were Universal's ninth
weekend of ``Patch Adams'' and Miramax's 18th weekend of ``Life Is
Beautiful.'' The former has about $130 &UR;  &LR; million overall; the
latter, with seven Oscar nods, is near $24 &UR;  &LR; million and already has
the highest gross in U.S. theaters for a foreign language movie.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's other major opening saw moviegoers mostly ignore
Sony's teen-horror comedy ``Jawbreakers'' with $1.6 &UR;  &LR; million at 801
sites. Also finishing well below the top 10 was Fox's ninth weekend
of ``The Thin Red Line'' with about $900,000 at 900 theaters as the
studio and exhibitors continue to pull the war drama from screens
despite its Best Picture Academy Award nomination. The studio made
its major push for ``Line'' in early January, and its grosses have
totaled a somewhat disappointing $34 &UR;  &LR; million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of shocked that a Best Picture candidate is losing
screens like this,'' Bucksbaum said, noting that the number of
screens was above 1,600 two weeks ago. ``Usually, business would be
improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney reported strong response for sneak screenings Saturday at
1,030 theaters for ``The Other Sister,'' starring Juliette Lewis as
a mentally challenged woman finding romance. Warner Bros. also
showed sneaks of ``Analyze This,'' a Billy Crystal comedy due March
5.
</P>
<P>
   Overall business totaled about $77 million, down from the same
weekend last year when ``Titanic'' topped the slate for the 10th
straight time. Year-to-date totals are down about 12 percent due
largely to ``Titanic,'' which went on to gross more than $600
million domestically.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ``8mm'' and ``The Other Sister,'' two other films will
open this Friday _ MGM's romance-drama ``Just the Ticket'' and
Paramount's ensemble comedy ``200 Cigarettes.''
</P>
