<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3925 &Cx1f; tth-z
r S &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      02-22 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE SLUGGER IN FOR A LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Goodwill isn't the only reason the greatest
player in Japanese baseball is coming to the Peoria Sports Complex
on Monday. Mutual curiosity is bringing Ichiro Suzuki and the
Mariners together.
</P>
<P>
   It's only a coincidence that Suzuki is the first player to wear
No. 51 for the M's since the Randy Johnson trade. But there's no
doubt he's a star.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki has his own clothing line and endorsement deals for
Japanese car, soft drink and food companies. He wears his first
name, not his last, on the back of his uniform. On Dec. 16 _ just
two days after Kevin Brown became this country's first $100 million
player _ he signed a contract making him the first Japanese player
to earn 500 million yen in a season.
</P>
<P>
   That's roughly $4.15 million in U.S. dollars, and the Orix Blue
Wave has every reason to make Suzuki happy. A lifetime .350 hitter,
he's won the batting title and a Gold Glove in each of the past
five years, three times adding a Most Valuable Player award.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 25-year-old wants to take his act to the American major
leagues _ and seems to favor Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He personally has told me one of his dreams is to play in the
same outfield as Ken Griffey Jr.,'' said Mariners president Chuck
Armstrong, who saw Suzuki twice last offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked every day,'' said Jamie Moyer, who visited Japan
with a team of major league stars in November. ``His biggest
question was always, `Can I play in the U.S.?' I said, `I don't
know, I've only seen you play two or three games, but you've got a
lot of ability. ... '
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's trying to make the club; I have no idea
of that perspective. But I do know it seemed in Japan that he
wanted to play for the Mariners.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki is one of three Blue Wave players who arrive in spring
training Monday and stay through March 7. He and pitchers Nobuyuki
Hoshino and Nobuyuki Ebisu will be eligible to play in the
Mariners' first four spring training games. The M's are expected to
reciprocate by sending players to Japan in the future.
</P>
<P>
   If Suzuki impresses _ and the Mariners will be watching closely
_ it could increase the likelihood of him playing for the Mariners
one day. In Japanese baseball, a player is bound to his club for
nine years before becoming a free agent. Few in Japan expect Suzuki
to stay four more years, but he has conceded that could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the first player to show what Japanese batters
can do in the major leagues,'' Suzuki said in November. `` ... Of
course I would like to try to play in America, but it basically
depends on my bosses letting me. What is important to me is
choosing a city where I am able to relax away from baseball, like
Seattle or Los Angeles (or) San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Jongewaard, the Mariners' vice president for scouting and
player development, gives Suzuki a ``plus'' rating in four of the
five position-player categories: hitting, arm strength, fielding
and speed. Suzuki's power is below average, but it's not for lack
of trying. Seeking to boost his home run total, Suzuki reportedly
began patterning his swing after Griffey's last year. (The
experiment resulted in just 13 homers.)
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki's arm strength, Moyer said, is equal to or better than
anyone's in the majors. But what the M's like most is Suzuki's
speed. He has stolen as many as 49 bases in a season, and Moyer
said he's the kind of player who could bunt for a single and be on
third base two pitches later. Suzuki could get 20 to 30 infield
hits a year if he puts the ball in play regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's faster than anybody over here, from what I saw of
him,'' Moyer said. ``Every lead he takes, he's got both feet on the
carpet. He's got great instincts on the basepaths, and from that
standpoint, he would give us some great team speed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners failed in their efforts to land a speedster this
winter, and it's tantalizing to think of Suzuki batting just before
Alex Rodriguez and Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be a leadoff hitter or a No. 2 hitter and get a
couple hundred hits for us, steal some bases,'' Jongewaard said.
``He'd be perfect in our lineup. We're looking for speed, someone
to get on base in front of Alex and Junior.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki had 210 hits in 130 games for Orix in 1994, a feat that
enthralled Japanese sports fans. Hide Sueyoshi, a former Blue Wave
staffer who now works in the Mariners scouting department, said
that performance was significant for Japanese baseball, which had
been losing fans to an upstart soccer league that started in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many fans came back to the ballpark,'' Sueyoshi said. ``He's
kind of the phenom of Japanese baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that, Armstrong, Sueyoshi and Jongewaard stressed
the team would follow protocol if it wanted to pursue Suzuki. With
Nintendo owning 60 percent of the franchise, the Mariners are
conscious of their image in Japan. If Suzuki's visit comes off as
goodwill, and not an audition, the M's will look better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously very important to us that we have a presence in
Japan, and that it be a favorable impression,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Armstrong has been assured that the M's will play
regular-season games in Japan as soon as baseball finalizes the
plans. Also, the M's have had a working agreement with the Blue
Wave since last February.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Wave, which plays in Seattle's sister city of Kobe,
exchanges player information and cross-markets with the Mariners.
The Mariner Moose has visited Japan, the Blue Wave's mascot has
frolicked in the Kingdome and the clubs sell each others'
merchandise at home games.
</P>
<P>
   Preserving that agreement is important, Jongewaard said. If
Suzuki does become free, the Mariners think their history of good
relations with Orix could give them an edge in signing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the working agreement with the Blue Wave, obviously
we're not trying to steal him away or do anything under the
table,'' Jongewaard said. ``But we'd hope with our relationship
with them, it might be something we could work out down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: The Mariners' full squad reports today, with all players
expected to arrive. ... New outfielder Butch Huskey has been placed
on an advanced workout program in hopes that he'll quickly shed 10
pounds. ... Manager Lou Piniella made a quick exit Sunday for a
golf date with Armstrong, M's CEO John Ellis, and vice president of
baseball operations Woody Woodward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
