<HEADER>
A3928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-OILERS-NY     02-22 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-OILERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL EYES ON GRETZKY BUT LACROIX WINS IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ Midway through Sunday night's game between
the Rangers and the Oilers, defenseman Marty McSorley of Edmonton
checked Wayne Gretzky of New York and held him along the boards
with a tight grip that stretched Gretzky's blue jersey. Perhaps
McSorley, in addition to covering his man, was trying to get a
claim on a souvenir shirt from what could have been an historic
game.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been Gretzky's last appearance in Edmonton in a
magnificent hockey career. And there was still a chance that it
could have been the night Gretzky added another line to his large
page in hockey's history book. Alas, Gretzky did not score, but
Marc Savard did, and so did Eric Lacroix, who joined the Rangers
this month and is playing for his third team this season. Savard's
goal tied the score late in the third period, and Lacroix's goal
gave the Rangers a 2-1 victory in the first minute of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Rangers a 3-1 record in their last four
games and moved them into 11th place in the Eastern Conference, 4
points behind the Florida Panthers, who hold the eighth and final
playoff berth in that bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Savard's goal on a breakaway at 11 minutes 31 seconds of the
third period came after a turnover near the Oilers blue line by
Boris Mironov. His pass hit John MacLean of the Rangers. Savard
took the puck, waited until Kevin Stevens cleared the zone and got
on side, then moved in on the goalie. Taking his time to make a
couple fakes, Savard dropped the goalie to the ice and then put the
puck into the net with a forehand shot.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous game, a 6-1 victory over Pittsburgh Friday night
at Madison Square Garden, Savard had three assists.
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix's goal came from short range after Mike Knuble and Petr
Nedved worked the puck low in the Edmonton zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers appeared to score what would have been a game-winning
goal in the final minute, when Bill Guerin put a rebound past Mike
Richter. But the goal was disallowed after video review because
Aleksandr Selivanov was illegally in the goal crease.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky has 1,071 goals in both the World Hockey Association and
the National Hockey League, including both regular season and
playoffs. The number equals that of Gordie Howe, who also played in
both leagues. Howe's career began in 1946 and ended in 1980.
Gretzky's career began in 1978-79, the final year of the WHA. He
played most of the season with Edmonton after beginning the season
with Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only appearance here this season for Gretzky and the
Rangers. The sellout crowd arrived early, many to watch Gretzky in
warm-ups. The Great One's road appearances are always a bigger deal
than his home games, and no city welcomes him with more emotion
than Edmonton, where he played for 10 seasons, one in the WHA and
nine in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   When the preparation for the game began, Gretzky was the last
Ranger to take the ice, and his first step was greeted with a big
cheer and a burst of flashbulbs. High above the ice, just below the
Molson Canadian billboard, was a large handmade sign, black
lettering on a white sheet, that said, ``We Still Miss You,
Gretz.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky is without a goal in seven games and has scored but one
in his last 17. For the season, he has eight goals and 48 assists
while playing in all 57 Rangers games.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sixth game in 10 nights for the Rangers, who play
their seventh in 11 when they visit Calgary on Monday night to play
the Flames. In their only previous meeting with the Oilers this
season, the Rangers won a 3-2 decision at the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers played again without Todd Harvey, their aggressive
right wing, who missed his second consecutive game with a fractured
right thumb. They also were without defensemen Jeff Beukeboom and
Peter Popovic. Beukeboom is out for about two more weeks with a
concussion. Popovic has blood in his right eye because he was hit
in the eye with a puck a week ago. The healthy scratches were Derek
Armstrong and Rumun Ndur.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in goal for the Rangers was Richter, who had failed to
finish the first period in two starts last week. Richter gave up no
goals in the first period Sunday night and stopped 17 Edmonton
shots in those 20 minutes. The one that got by him, by Mironov, hit
the goal post.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 12 minutes of the game, the Rangers were outshot by
13-3. They improved in the next eight minutes and Kevin Stevens hit
a goal post behind Oilers goalie Bob Essensa.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, the Rangers played better, but the Oilers
got the only goal of the session and held a 1-0 lead after 40
minutes. Mike Grier scored, shaking off a checking attempt by
Nedved and putting a rebound past Richter.
</P>
<P>
   The most effective Ranger forward in this span was Adam Graves,
Gretzky's left wing, who leads the team with 27 goals. Graves put
on some stick-handling displays, not usually his style, one of them
drawing a penalty against McSorley late in the period. Gretzky set
up a couple of scoring chances, the best by Ulf Samuelsson, who
took the right-to-left pass and fired from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the third period, the Oilers had a 27-19 edge in
shots on goal. Gretzky had one of the Rangers' shots. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
