<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3930 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     02-22 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUMPED-UP POLYNICE IGNITES SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ ``OK, let's go. Stop talking,'' Gary Payton said
Sunday, sticking his razor-clean head into the scrum of reporters
surrounding the Sonics' star of the day, Olden Polynice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's enough of that,'' Payton said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' guard was thrilled with the team's new center, even
if Payton was harping on Polynice to quit yakking and get dressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I'm sorry,'' Polynice said. ``But I'm loving this.''
</P>
<P>
   You bet Polynice is loving this.
</P>
<P>
   Call it escape from Sacramento, where before Chris Webber, Vlade
Divac and Jason Williams showed up, it was 82 games of pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't wait to get out of there,'' said Polynice, who used
to look jealously at the standings, knowing his then-former team
became a contender after he was traded away in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Polynice wakes up every day and makes a point of
reading the NBA standings. He likes to see his Sonics are in first
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is new to me. The other guys may be used to being in
first place, but I'm loving it. I could be working nine to five
right now. I could be making minimum wage. I could be living in a
Third World country. I could still be in Haiti right now, still
suffering,'' Polynice said.
</P>
<P>
   And you can bet Payton and the Sonics are loving Polynice, too,
especially after the center went toe-to-toe with Shaquille O'Neal _
hand-to-hand, too _ and came out on top.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' 92-89 victory was courtesy of their new man in the
middle, who 15 seconds into the game opened the scoring with a
17-foot jumper and spent the rest of the game shaking, rattling and
rolling O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, it was the raw emotion that Polynice injected that
helped lift the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's brought up the whole morale of the team,'' Kobe
Bryant said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Polynice's raised arms and pumping fists and words of
encouragement gave the Sonics an edge, especially over the
bickering Lakers, whose problems can only get worse _ with or
without Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   It was 39 minutes for Shaq and 39 minutes for Polynice _ who won
the psychological battle under the boards even of O'Neal later
protested about all the pushing and shoving that NBA refs are not
calling.
</P>
<P>
   It was 27 points for Shaq, whom you can't really stop, but it
was 17 big boards for Polynice.
</P>
<P>
   Where there once was Jim McIlvaine and a prayer holding up the
middle ground in the Sonics' rotation, there is now O.P.
</P>
<P>
   Where there once was McIlvaine averaging 3 points and 3 rebounds
in 15 minutes, there is now O.P., who Sunday hung 15 points, 17
rebounds and one bone-jarring blocked shot against Shaq and the
Land of the Lost Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the dumb plays when I tried to block his dunk.
When I blocked it, my hand hit the rim. You don't think about that
kind of thing during the game, you just play,'' Polynice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the smartest thing to try and do but at the same
time, I had to challenge him and let him know it wasn't going to be
an easy night.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice has been waiting for these kinds of games. In
Sacramento, NBC did not send Bob Costas and Ahmad Rashad to many
Kings games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only NBC I saw were the games I watched on TV,'' Polynice
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the games Polynice saw were the Sonics' playoff
match-ups, including the Lakers' resounding second-round slaughter
of the overrotating Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the whole thing. I saw what happened. McIlvaine
didn't play much, but I thought regardless, he should have played.
He's got six fouls. He's big enough to bang and beat Shaq. But they
tried to put Vin (Baker) on him and that was tough for Vin. I mean,
shoot, that was tough on me tonight. I'm ready to go home and lay
down and this was just one game,'' Polynice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vin isn't used to guarding someone like that for five games.
It was tough on him. They were able to spot up. Eddie Jones could
shoot jumpers. But it was different tonight. I knew coming in, that
was one of the things the (Sonics) needed. Our whole thing is to
get between the big fella and the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it helped that Polynice was tuned in to all the bad
karma swirling around the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can hear them yelling and cussing at each other during the
game. I mean, there was one play and someone said, `You're not
going to talk to me that way.' There were a lot of cuss words and I
was like, whoa,'' Polynice said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Polynice had any advantage over Shaq, perhaps it came
from a summer of workouts. Polynice lives in Los Angeles with his
wife and two kids and, during the lockout, he worked out with the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers even told Polynice to hang around, that they would
sign him. But after the Lakers signed Travis Knight, the Sonics
called up Polynice and told him to pack his bags and head north to
take the place of McIlvaine, whom Sonics president Wally Walker
shuffled off to New Jersey for ... it doesn't matter. McIlvaine was
gone and there was someone potent to take up that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real good piece of the puzzle for them,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about the caliber of player that Jim is and the
caliber of player that Olden is, there's no comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   It might have been backhanded, considering McIlvaine's
considerable shortcomings, but Polynice should take it as a
compliment.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
