<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-LAKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS GET PHYSICAL WITH LAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Well after the locker-room rush had subsided, Sonics
center Olden Polynice still was inebriated by the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   He stood in a towel, sweat-drenched and chatty about his
encounter with mammoth Shaquille O'Neal. A 15-round heavyweight
boxing match might have been easier, although Polynice was far from
punch drunk.
</P>
<P>
   That was O'Neal and the Los Angeles Lakers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After Polynice delivered the first blow, it did not take long
for the rest of the Sonics to join in and deflate the Lakers 92-89
in a nationally televised game at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   The victory snapped the Sonics' two-game losing streak and gave
the team's offense a much-needed shot in the arm. With five players
scoring in double figures, the Sonics (7-2) threw every weapon they
had at the Lakers (6-4) in rebounding from Saturday's 30-point
drubbing at Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were embarrassed,'' Sonics forward Vin Baker said of the
Utah game. ``(Sunday) wasn't a strategy game. It was about playing
hard and playing with fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice was the spark from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   His 15 points and 17 rebounds were not identical to O'Neal's 27
points and 10 boards. But Polynice stood up to the Laker giant and
kept him from totally dominating the paint.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of performance that the Sonics had not been used
to against the league's dominant centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not intimidated by anyone. I respect people's game, but if
you're intimidated, you've already lost,'' Polynice said. ``I know
he wants to dunk the ball. I wanted to limit the dunks. ... I had
to challenge a couple of them to let him know it wasn't going to be
an easy night.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice stirred things up so much that O'Neal vented afterward,
talking more about the officiating than his Sonic counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does what everyone else does: Two hands in the back and
push,'' O'Neal said. ``They (the officials) did an awful job. They
are some cheating bastards. They make up (expletive) rules and
don't enforce them. You can fine me, double-fine, triple-fine me. I
guess I'm going to have to start breaking people up.''
</P>
<P>
   When told of O'Neal's comments, Polynice wondered if the two had
just played the same game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a superstar so I know I'm not being protected,''
Polynice said of the officiating. `` ... If that's how he feels,
maybe he should talk to (commissioner) David Stern and maybe they
can work something out. I just went out there and did what I had to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice scored eight of the Sonics first 14 points _ all on
strong moves to the basket _ and established his inside presence by
blocking one of O'Neal's early dunk attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice played recklessly from the start, leaning on O'Neal and
holding him to 5-for-14 shooting and just 10 points in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice was so effective that Sonics coach Paul Westphal
rotated his center in and out of the game with O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that really helps a lot is to have a center that
makes the other center earn whatever he gets,'' Westphal said. ``We
don't expect him to score big. The thing about Olden is he can
score if the ball comes to him. We're not running plays for him,
but at the same time he knows what to do with it when he gets the
ball, and he's all over the offensive boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice's willingness to bang with O'Neal led to the Sonics'
45-44 rebounding edge. The Sonics also played straight-up defense
most of the game and were were the aggressors on both ends of the
floor from the opening tip.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Sonics attacked the basket. They immediately
took advantage of mismatches in the paint with Baker and Detlef
Schrempf making concentrated efforts to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   Baker finished with 19 points and Schrempf added 15 in two of
their better offensive outputs so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think about how I've been playing _ standing
around _ and I wanted to do something about it,'' Schrempf said.
``I've been a postup player for many years. I might take some
postups from Gary (Payton) and Vin, but I have to take advantage of
my height and get some easy baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics never trailed in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to see Det and Vin doing what they did last year,''
said Payton, who led the Sonics with 26 points after scoring a
season-low seven on Saturday. ``If they play like that
consistently, we're going to be a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' biggest lead was 65-50 after Schrempf sank a
16-footer with 4:44 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers made several runs, but each time the Sonics responded
with a big shot. Baker's dunk with 33.5 seconds left in the game
put the Sonics ahead 88-80 and iced the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a roller-coaster and crazy league, a crazy Western
Conference,'' Westphal said. ``After playing the way we did
(Saturday), we came back and played the way we think we can play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
