<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3942 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUTH-VOTE-2TAKES-LAD     02-22 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-VOTE-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS TURN TO TEEN ACTIVISTS IN CAMPAIGNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY YVETTE CABRERA  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The lowrider car club member, the straight-A
Mission College sophomore and the teen-age mom from the Pacoima
housing project _ at one time political candidates dismissed these
young adults and others as inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates and political consultants alike say the race for the
7th District Los Angeles City Council seat may hinge on who
marshals the biggest and best army of young volunteers. Candidates
in the Northeast San Fernando Valley increasingly rely upon
teen-agers to get out their message and enlist support in wards
where the young have influence with newly registered Latino voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were absolutely a phenomenal force in my race,'' said
Richard Alarcon, who left the 7th District council seat to run for
the state Senate seat that he won. ``I believe when you compare the
volunteer operation of my campaign to my opponent's campaign,
clearly the youth made the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine a 15-year-old who weighs 100 pounds and looks like
she's 12 knocking on your door saying, `Why haven't you voted? I
can't vote, but you can.' It really has a compelling impact and
gets voters out,'' said Alarcon. ``It's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   The opponent he defeated, former Assemblyman Richard Katz,
credited Alarcon and state Assemblyman Tony Cardenas with using
young volunteers effectively in their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy and dynamics that young people bring to the
campaign is irreplaceable,'' said Katz, an eight-term assemblyman
for the 39th District who also recruited young volunteers for his
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Alarcon drew 150 volunteers, while Cardenas more than
doubled that figure in 1996 with 350. Last spring, Alarcon had a
volunteer machine of more than 650 volunteers, and more than half
of them were teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   In Alarcon's council campaigns, youngsters entirely ran his
absentee ballot program.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, D-Panorama City, agrees that young volunteers are
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were instrumental in bringing a great, great energy to my
campaign,'' said Cardenas. ``They got people to recognize me as a
viable candidate. Without a doubt they were instrumental in my
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   In a twist to traditional politics where adult volunteers bring
their children on the campaign trail, the young volunteers in
Cardenas' campaigns got their parents involved.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 400 volunteers knocking on doors, stuffing envelopes
and staffing phone banks, other neighborhood residents saw
teen-agers and young adults in action and were inspired, Cardenas
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People commented that they were going to vote for me because
they saw that I was working with youth and that youth were doing
something positive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon is not entirely new but has gained new momentum
in the Northeast San Fernando Valley, where persuading new citizens
and newly registered voters to take part in the political process
goes beyond traditional campaign work, according to political
consultant Leo Briones.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Alarcon, Cardenas and former San Fernando
Mayor Raul Godinez II inspired teen-agers to participate in
unprecedented numbers, said Briones, founder of the Los
Angeles-based political campaign firm Centaur North Strategic
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers, many of whom were bilingual, were trained to
explain the ballot process to first-time voters, said Briones.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a hard-working, grass-roots effort, and (for) the
youth working those campaigns, it's not just doing phone banking
and reading a script. It's a lot of hard work and dedication,''
said Briones.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's more than politics that has gone up in the San
Fernando Valley. To me it's been the campaigns that have provided
hope for people,'' said Briones.
</P>
<P>
   According to public affairs consultant Richard Lichtenstein,
political volunteerism has waned in the last decade and been
replaced by advertising in most regions, but the volunteer force in
the Northeast Valley has steadily grown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why youth volunteers have had an extraordinary impact.
There's no question Alarcon won the state Senate race by that
(narrow) margin because of his ability to surpass Katz's ground
campaign,'' said Lichtenstein, president of Marathon
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful draw for young, minority volunteers has been the
chance to work for candidates with similar backgrounds, said
Lichtenstein.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: with similar backgrounds, said Lichtenstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a brand new phenomenon for these (minority volunteers)
and these cultures to participate this way,'' said Lichtenstein,
who worked on Alarcon's first council race.
</P>
<P>
   The message is not lost on Barbara Perkins, a candidate for the
7th District race who said she has recruited young volunteers.
Youthful volunteers have the energy to commit themselves to
intensive campaign work, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign is going to be impacted by who can walk that
district, not by who can get the larger political endorsements,''
said Perkins, a community college executive. ``I think it is about
people to people, and my campaign is focused on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The intergenerational dialogue that will take place between
precinct-walking teen-agers and other residents is what society
needs, said Perkins, a resident of the Sylmar community in the San
Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people should see that our young people are doing more
than hanging out on a corner,'' said Perkins. ``The youth are
sending the message that they're productive citizens. The only
difference is they're young.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon and Cardenas said they put their faith in a combination
of high-achieving teens and teens who had been largely ignored and
at risk of being alienated from the political system. During his
first Assembly campaign in 1996, Cardenas' concern was that
Northeast San Fernando Valley teen-agers were stereotyped as having
no ambition and not encouraged to go on to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our youth deserve to have a choice, and when they get involved
in politics they realize that's another choice they have,'' said
Cardenas. ``Not only are they capable of doing that, but they make
a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon said he also saw a void in opportunities for teens when
he ran for the 7th District council seat for the first time in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an outcry for youth involvement and, being a former
teacher and carrying a very strong youth agenda, I rallied for
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he considered it imperative for teen-agers and young
adults to get involved in political campaigns because many of the
7th District's issues _ such as gangs, graffiti, unemployment and
education _ affect them personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we integrated them into every aspect because youth
volunteers make every difference in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They include Alejandro Padilla, 25, who organized the young
force in Cardenas' 1996 campaign and tapped into the same network
to buoy Alarcon's successful campaign last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Now Padilla is running himself _ for the 7th District council
seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volunteers were significant,'' said Padilla about the two
campaigns he helped run for others. ``There were so many of them
involved. I don't think we would have achieved the level of success
we did without their help.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Padilla began recruiting young volunteers the only way
he knew how: He thumbed through phone books for cousins, friends
and acquaintances, even former Little League pals. Cardenas headed
to the local schools to speak to government and politics classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response was tremendous,'' said Cardenas. Many of the
volunteers were green, but that didn't stop Padilla. The campaign
office held orientation sessions every day. On any day 30
volunteers were likely to show up to help, Padilla said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We literally walked through the process of this is a precinct,
this is a list of voters, this is what you say when you go to the
door,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each election cycle created a bigger batch of young volunteers
who returned time and again.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
