<HEADER>
A3946 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HOLT-HNS &LR;      02-22 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HOLT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ There has been nothing special or out of the
ordinary about the Astros' first week of spring training, which
amounts to little more than games of catch-and-toss.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just don't tell Chris Holt.
</P>
<P>
   Holt no longer takes for granted the simple task of throwing a
ball _ albeit at speeds approaching 90 mph. Nor does he ignore the
pain when his arm says it has had enough. Not this time around.
</P>
<P>
   And if he needs a reminder, he only has to stare at the scar
along his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   It was here last spring that Holt, still in the recovery process
from offseason rotator-cuff surgery, arrived behind schedule but
optimistic he could start the season with the rest of his
teammates. Instead, he encountered a dead end everywhere he turned,
and what was supposed to be the second year of his major-league
career was wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   A year older and wiser and feeling a lot less pain, the
27-year-old righthander is ready to put his 16-month ordeal behind
him and start relocating the touch that made him a key contributor
for the Astros' 1997 division winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm back to square one,'' Holt said. ``I've got to
battle and make this team. I know if I'm healthy I can. They know
what I'm capable of doing. It's just coming back from arm surgery
that you don't know how someone is going to bounce back. They have
their concerns, and so do I.''
</P>
<P>
   Who could blame him? Holt missed all of last season after a
failed attempt to rebound from what he originally described as
nothing more than ``an annoyance.'' It wasn't until the end of his
rookie season in October '97 that Holt had his shoulder examined,
but the pain originated 3{ months earlier. After the Astros were
eliminated from the playoffs, surgery was performed to correct the
problem, and the original prognosis had Holt missing three weeks of
the following season at most.
</P>
<P>
   But his last appearance in a game remains a one-inning relief
outing against the Cubs on Sept. 25, 1997, in which he struck out
three batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I tried to heat it up, I would start feeling it,''
Holt said. ``I would shut it down for a week, then I would go for
another couple of weeks and feel good. I was thinking I would be
ready to go, and there was another setback. Finally, it became a
fact it constantly was bothering me.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring training 1998 proved to be one long disappointment. Some
days were better than others, but each almost always ended with
some kind of setback. A couple of days of pain-free pitching were
offset by several days when it felt impossible for Holt to throw a
baseball. The Astros purposely held him out during stretches to see
if things improved.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the club left camp, Holt was nowhere close to being
ready to begin the season. During the next several weeks, he
pitched countless simulated outings _ ``Pretty soon they were
calling me Mr. Simulator,'' he says _ and flew halfway across the
country to work game situations in the organization's farm system.
Holt underwent a second surgical procedure in June to relieve
tightness in his shoulder, officially ending his hopes of pitching
for the Astros in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a constant roller coaster that he was on that
created an enormous frustration level for all of us to the point
where he finally realized pitching in 1998 was probably not going
to happen,'' general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``This clearly
was a more difficult recovery than the normal recovery from an
operation, in that when he came to spring training (last year), the
expectation was he would be behind but only for a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing couldn't have been worse for Holt, who despite the
pain pitched his best ball in the second half of the 1997 season.
He finished 8-12 with a 3.52 ERA, logging 210 innings and 32
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no good time to be injured, but for a kid that had
just gone through his rookie year and just gotten his feet on the
ground, to have a major setback like this has to be difficult,''
Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   But Holt is prepared to put everything behind him and start
afresh. He had a successful 1{-month stint in the Puerto Rican
Winter League, continues to do rehab exercises and feels less pain
each day. The Astros' goal isn't to rush Holt's recovery but rather
take it at his speed.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker says it's too early to pronounce Holt's shoulder fully
recovered or even to think he can withstand the rigors of pitching
on a regular basis. Because of the nature of his injury, the Astros
are reluctant to use Holt in a relief role, so it's likely his only
chance to make the roster is to win a spot in the starting
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to be answered this week or next week or the
following week,'' Hunsicker said. ``It's probably not going to be
answered for another couple of months until we see whether his arm
can physically go through that routine without having any
significant setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on his short time here (this spring), he's a totally
different pitcher than he was a year ago. Last year, he was stiff,
he couldn't get his arm loose, couldn't extend his arm on his
follow-through. This year, there is none of that. He looks as good
as I've ever seen him. Having said that, it's easy to get overly
optimistic the first week of camp. It's important that we don't get
the cart before the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   For Holt, it's a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's all behind me,'' he said. ``If I'm healthy, I
know I'm a big-league pitcher. I've proven that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
