<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3947 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     02-22 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ORLANDO, Fla. _ The road-weary Rockets awoke Sunday morning to a
pleasant surprise from a thoughtful, considerate, faraway source.
</P>
<P>
   A note slipped under their hotel-room doors told them Charles
Barkley was picking up the tab for breakfast. Too bad he couldn't
be at the O-rena to stop them from losing their lunch.
</P>
<P>
   This was precisely what you might have expected from a team on
bald tires with an empty gas tank, playing its fifth game in its
fifth city in six days.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic was the windshield, and the Rockets were the bugs.
Armadillos with their stubby little legs sticking straight up into
the air. Roadkill.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight afternoon, the Rockets ran into a club
that plays aggressive, suffocating defense. And for the second
straight time, they could not breathe.
</P>
<P>
   On back-to-back days, the Rockets suffered a third-quarter
meltdown, this time scoring just 10 points against the Magic. Coach
Rudy Tomjanovich pondered whether drinking Diet Pepsi or coffee at
halftime would give them a jolt of energy.
</P>
<P>
   They turned the ball over 22 times. They were taken out of their
offensive rhythm. They lost their poise and eventually their
dignity in getting mauled 109-83.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a lot of this all season,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``You have the combination of the incredibly hard schedule
and no practice time, and it's going to make for some breakdowns
that will occasionally put good teams on bad streaks. Traveling or
playing just about every day means you don't get a chance to work
things out.''
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 games into this scrambling season, Rudy T is doing more
frantic improvisation than a one-armed paperhanger with his hair on
fire. He has been forced to hold chalk-talk sessions on the run and
pre-game walk-throughs in hotel ballrooms. At any opportunity, he
has tried to tutor and nurture all of his young, green talent with
a timely comment or observation.
</P>
<P>
   They need practice time and rest time that will never come. Not
with the schedule delivering them back to Houston for a pair of
rugged home dates with Seattle and Atlanta before immediately
slingshotting them back on the road to Vancouver and LA for another
match with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   What they also need desperately is Barkley, and not just for 19
points and 17 rebounds per game or his generosity in buying meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Charles as a kind of security blanket when we get into
those helter-skelter situations,'' Rudy T said. ``Things are going
on wild and crazy, and we can call his play to settle us down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Charles to run our offense through him,'' said Hakeem
Olajuwon. ``With him on the floor, it changes the whole game for
us. It opens things up and makes it easier to play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Charles for his veteran leadership,'' said Scottie
Pippen. ``Right now, we're showing a lack of poise in a lot of
situations, and we need him to be a kind of calming influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that. Next we'll have calls going out for Calvin Klein
to lead the fight for restraint in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, they do miss Barkley in so many different ways,
not the least of which is his ability to slow down the offense,
draw double-teaming defenses and open up the rest of the floor for
his teammates, precisely the thing that infuriates his critics.
</P>
<P>
   While all they see is Barkley yo-yoing the ball with his dribble
while the 24-second clock runs down, he is also making it easier to
get the ball to Olajuwon and creating the open shots on the
perimeter that are half the ingredients in the Rockets'
bread-and-butter diet.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's absence may, in large part, be responsible for the
disappearance of Matt Maloney from the offense. Maloney was benched
in favor of Cuttino Mobley, and though he made some good plays on
his own, the rookie did not set up the inside game.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's presence prevents defenses from consistently fronting
Olajuwon, who looked fresh at the end of the trip with 21 points
and 10 rebounds but could have and should have been milked for
more.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's return will take the burden off Pippen, who is
obviously straining at times to force himself into the picture.
</P>
<P>
   We know Barkley will use sheer determination to get more than
his share of boards and find a way to score inside by cleaning up
all the garbage. But what makes him so invaluable _ and what the
Rockets miss as much _ are the other personality traits. Picking up
Maloney or a Michael Dickerson and telling him to keep gunning even
if the shots don't fall. Putting a lid on the precocious Mobley's
play when it boils out of control. Making individual challenges to
his teammates and himself. And backing them up with his pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be different when Charles comes back,'' Olajuwon said.
``We will be our real selves again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That isn't for a few more weeks,'' Pippen said. ``We can't
just sit back and wait. It's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   That the genial host, Charles Barkley, can only pick up their
meal tabs, not their game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
