<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3948 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MAGIC-HNS     02-22 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MAGIC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ORLANDO, Fla. _ For most of their first grueling road trip of the
season, the roof was sagging badly on the Rockets, springing leaks,
threatening disaster. But they repeatedly found ways to prop it up,
even raising the roof in an overtime win in New Jersey.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, with the Rockets lacking the strength or savvy to fix
the holes again, the roof caved in. The Orlando Magic blew out the
Rockets in the second half Sunday for a 109-83 rout to send the
Rockets home from their four-games-in-five-days road trip with just
one victory and a long list of questions.
</P>
<P>
   Starting an all-rookie backcourt for the first time in franchise
history, the Rockets collapsed under the weight of the Magic's
ball-hawking defense. Matt Maloney, a starter in all 167 games of
his NBA career, was benched, playing only the last four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen enjoyed a dazzling second quarter in which he
carried the Rockets from a 13-point deficit to within three. But he
then had his second scoreless half in as many days and was ejected
after being called for his second technical in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And though Hakeem Olajuwon and Othella Harrington continued the
torrid shooting pace that has made the Rockets one of the most
accurate shooting teams in the NBA, they again could not get enough
chances to carry the offense or set up the Rockets' collection of
shooters.
</P>
<P>
   When it began to crumble, it all fell apart around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran into a buzz saw, a great defensive team,'' Rockets
coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``That happens a lot. I call it the
dam breaking. They're like piranhas. They smell that blood.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had bled in every game throughout the four-game road
trip. But against the Nets and Heat, they were able to regroup and
rally, beating the Nets and giving themselves a chance to catch the
Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, after a largely ineffective afternoon in Miami, carried
them back out of another hole in the second quarter, scoring 16 of
his 19 points in the period as the Rockets rallied from 13 down to
within 46-43 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was phenomenal,'' Tomjanovich said of Pippen's run. ``I was
ready to take him out. He has been playing a lot of minutes. But I
pulled the guy back twice, he was going so well. He's a
tremendously conditioned guy. He played 42 minutes (Saturday) and
24 minutes in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets turned the ball over eight times in the first half,
but that didn't offer a hint as to what would come. They outshot
and outrebounded the Magic and trailed only because they could not
get the ball inside to Olajuwon or Harrington with any regularity.
</P>
<P>
   But for the second consecutive afternoon, the Rockets collapsed
in the third quarter. After scoring nine points in the third
quarter Saturday, the worst third quarter in franchise history,
they managed 10 against the Magic. But instead of failing to get
good shots and shooting poorly, the Rockets could not run their
offense, committing 10 turnovers in the quarter and falling behind
72-53.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the difference in the game,'' Pippen said. ``We
didn't execute in the second half. We turned the ball over a lot in
the third quarter, and they took over the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to start executing better under pressure. The
turnovers (the Rockets finished with 22) really hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   The rookie backcourt did not collect turnovers as rookies often
will, as later demonstrated by Bryce Drew. But Cuttino Mobley and
Michael Dickerson had trouble running plays, particularly against
the pressure of Darrell Armstrong off the bench with Penny Hardaway
and Bo Outlaw roaming the passing lanes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets shot well inside with Olajuwon getting 21 points and
making nine of 13 shots, and Harrington scoring 12 on 6-of-10
shooting. But between them, they took just 10 shots in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a second late realizing this is the play we're
running and you've got an aggressive defensive team, you can't even
make the entry pass,'' Tomjanovich said. ``Our young guys are
learning a lot. We wanted to isolate to run some plays for Michael,
but he couldn't get open. Those are growing pains. They're going to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said playing five games in six nights, the last four
on the road, was a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't wish it on anybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule might have shown up in the Rockets' outside
shooting. Matt Bullard missed all seven of his attempts, Brent
Price missed two, and Dickerson was 2-of-6.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets pointed to their inability to attack the Magic's
defensive pressure. Outlaw pressured Pippen in the second half, and
the Magic guards disrupted plays before they could get started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Bo at halftime, `Keep playing Scottie physically,'''
Hardaway said. ``He was giving him too much space in the first
half, and he got going. I said, `Get out on him, and if he gets by,
we'll help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to come in as a rookie and play myself and Nick
(Anderson). We're big guards. Once Cuttino committed himself to one
side, I overplayed that side and they couldn't get into the offense
until the shot clock was running down.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, Pippen was about to be run off the court and the
Rockets had run out of comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a tough one,'' Olajuwon said. ``We made a lot of
mistakes. We have every once in a while a game like this. We have
to go home and regroup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
