<HEADER>
A3949 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-22 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Being a part-time musician and budding
entertainer, Jose Lima is familiar with the term.
</P>
<P>
   One-hit wonder.
</P>
<P>
   In this otherwise virtually worry-free spring training, it is
the one question and concern hovering over Lima and the 1999
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Was it the real Jose Lima? Or Vanilla Ice?
</P>
<P>
   With the likes of proven veterans Craig Biggio, Jeff Bagwell and
Ken Caminiti holding down the 1999 offense and Shane Reynolds and
Mike Hampton having proved their stability on the mound, the
legitimacy of Lima's 16-8 record last year is an easy target.
</P>
<P>
   Before Lima's breakout season of last year, his professional
baseball career was more like that of a garage band than a
headliner. Lots of noise, little to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   There was a no-hitter in the minor leagues a few years back,
then some decent outings in Detroit. Scouts all over talked about
Lima's potential.
</P>
<P>
   But then there proved to be more forgettable outings than good
ones and growing concern that the potential of this fun-loving
salsa aficionado never would be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Lima was called up to Motown one day, sent back to the minors
another. He wanted his game to bounce like Tito Puente, but it was
more like Tito Jackson. He compiled a three-year record of 8-16 in
Detroit with a 6.24 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a real chance to start in Detroit,'' Lima said.
``That's what I am. I am a starting pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the development of a wicked if inconsistent changeup,
a few nice winter seasons in the Latin American leagues and then
the trade to Houston, which offered new hope.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Astros, it was back to the pen, and at first the
calls to Lima were made out of necessity. The results were mixed.
In 52 appearances (51 in relief) with the Astros in 1997, Lima was
just 1-6 with a 5.28 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   He contended throughout that being a starter would change
everything. But as recently as last spring, after an unimpressive
Grapefruit League season and an exhibition outing against the
Kansas City Royals in which nearly every pitch Lima tried was
shredded, his status with the team was tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   He was called into a meeting with Astros manager Larry Dierker
and general manager Gerry Hunsicker and told that the starting job
about which he dreamed instead would go to Pete Schourek.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were honest with him,'' Hunsicker said. ``We told him he
wasn't ready.''
</P>
<P>
   But days later, a nagging shoulder injury forced Schourek out,
and Dierker gave the ball to Lima.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job became Jose's by default, really,'' Hunsicker said.
``He didn't have a very good spring, but then look what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima took the ball and danced around opposing batters, stunning
the league with his fiery attitude, confounding changeup and grit
on the hill.
</P>
<P>
   He became a fan favorite. He showed not just skill as a starter
but poise, consistently pitching out of trouble and coming up big
in big games.
</P>
<P>
   On the day the Astros traded for Randy Johnson, Lima was
concerned his starting spot again would be in jeopardy. He went out
and pitched a 10-strikeout five-hitter against Pittsburgh,
declaring in the clubhouse afterward, ``I hope I sent a message. I
should be in the rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, his game was a smash hit. But was it real?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unreasonable to want him to prove it wasn't a
fluke,'' Hunsicker said. ``What he did last year he'd never done
before. I want him to prove it, too. But based on his age (26) and
where he is in his career, there's no reason to believe he's going
to take a step backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is one question constantly being asked this spring:
Will Lima's 1998 season go the way of Billy Ray Cyrus _ winning
achy, breaky hearts one year but crumbling into oblivion the next?
</P>
<P>
   Lima, like all Astros pitchers, has yet to face live action this
spring. On Sunday, there was some concern when he sat out pitching
drills with a sore back and throwing shoulder. But by the end of
the workout, he was running with pitchers and promising to provide
answers for the critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear those things,'' Lima said. ``I told people last year
that I would be a starting pitcher and I would win 15 games.
Everybody laughed. But what did I do? I won 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I got the opportunity, and it changed my life.
Right now, I am telling you that if I'm healthy, I'm going to pitch
good again and I could win 20 games. Why not? With this team, I'm
going to win. People will say, `Jose Lima can't do it.' But I can.
I'm going to make my noise on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The stage is set. But Lima, the consummate entertainer, should
know one thing more than anyone else. The toughest part of the show
is the encore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
