<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3957 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITIZENS-COMPLAINTS-L     02-22 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIZENS-COMPLAINTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZEN COMPLAINTS HIGH ON INTERIM LAPD INSPECTOR GENERAL'S
PRIORITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While Deirdre Hill is cautiously approaching her
job of interim LAPD inspector general, she believes a number of
issues need close attention, including charges of retaliatory
complaints between officers and police treatment of citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Christopher Commission issued its landmark report on
the Los Angeles Police Department in 1991, the department's citizen
complaint procedures have improved dramatically, Hill said in an
interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But she said more study is needed to see if discipline for
police misconduct against citizens is adequate and whether internal
disciplinary processes are fair.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who served as Police Commission president from 1993 to
1996, took over the post seven weeks ago from former Inspector
General Katherine Mader, who resigned early this year amid
frustration with department brass and conflicts with commission
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The department's citizen complaint procedures are vastly more
open and accessible than in the past, and discourtesy toward
citizens is viewed more seriously, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said, it's unclear whether cases of misconduct
toward civilians receive discipline commensurate to the severity of
the offense, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a question as to how the department values
misconduct related to citizens and whether that evaluation is in
accordance with what the public would expect,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department has been historically hard on its internal
policies and procedures and not as hard on use of force and civil
rights violations,'' she said, adding that historic distrust of
police persists in the inner city despite recent reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Investigation by the Inspector General's Office would confirm
whether the investigation of civilian complaints is serious and
thorough, and the discipline appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that the department is doing an excellent job at it,
as has been the perception, but people need to know it is being
looked at, for deterrence'' of future offenses, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, the internal complaint process must be
examined for fairness and consistency. Worry about those issues has
rippled through the ranks in recent months, but systematic analysis
is needed to discover whether those fears are based on fact, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the department, the employees have always been
concerned that there may not be consistency between discipline at
the level of the command staff, for example, and the patrol officer
on the beat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's concern that discipline may change from one Board of
Rights to another for the same event. And there are other questions
of inequity that the goal of this office is to look at. Whether or
not that perception is reality I don't think we know for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   She said retaliation between officers is pervasive, and that the
internal complaint process has become a tool with which some
officers lash out at others to stall promotions or strike back for
complaints filed against themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really astonishing the number of complaints that
employees bring against each other,'' she said. ``And in a
private-sector environment, you would never see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said her office must look at the extent of that retaliation
and the time period for resolving those matters for officers on the
promotional list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there preference given to someone whom the management wants
to be promoted?'' she asked. ``Is it inordinately long for someone
who is not a favored son?''
</P>
<P>
   Mader said she agrees with Hill's areas of concern and added
that some of her own studies validated those complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We documented numerous instances of retaliation, and I agree
with Deirdre that retaliation against persons, particularly on the
inside who try to report misconduct, is a very serious issue,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD Cmdr. Dave Kalish said the department supports Hill's
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department's position is that's healthy and that's what
the inspector general should be doing: auditing and looking at
systems and outcomes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
