<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Rambouillet, France) _ After alternatively
cajoling and scolding the suddenly recalcitrant members of the
ethnic Albanian delegation here, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright decided to say in public on Sunday what she had been
telling them in private: if you don't sign up, NATO won't bomb the
Serbs. The ethnic Albanians have long argued that air strikes were
the best way to end the repression by the Serbs in Kosovo and to
force them to a peace deal. By Jane Perlez. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-DECLINE (Kasigo Extension 13, South Africa) _ The
euphoria of 1994 has dissipated. High crime, unemployment and white
flight are just some of South Africa's problems as May elections
loom. The African National Congress will win, but has much less
enthusiastic backing than five years ago. By Suzanne Daley. With
photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (Lahore, Pakistan) _ The prime ministers of India
and Pakistan pledged Sunday to take immediate steps to reduce the
risk of nuclear war and seek solutions to a half-century of raging
disputes, including their most volatile source of discord, the
conflict in Kashmir. By Barry Bearak. With map.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-RUSSIA-MISSILES (Moscow) _ Worried that the millennium bug
might increase the risk of accidental nuclear war, the Pentagon has
proposed that Russia and the United States set up a center in
Moscow to share missile warning data. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-SPECIALWEAPONS (Undated) _ A study to be issued Monday by
the government's own auditors is highly critical of a key part of
the Clinton administration's effort to stop the spread of nuclear,
biological and chemical weapons by helping to employ scientists
from the former Soviet Union on peaceful projects. By Judith
Miller. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-RACISM (Birmingham, England) _ For years, black and
Asian Britons have complained about what they see as overt and
tacit police racism, and except at times of particular upheaval,
like the riots in Brixton in 1981, no one in authority in Britain
has paid much attention. But in the last few months, the issue has
been at the forefront of the country's consciousness. By Sarah
Lyall. With map.
</P>
<P>
   SAIPAN-ADDRESSLESSNESS (Saipan, Northern Mariana Islands) _ No
place on this entire island, a tropical teardrop of land in the
Pacific Ocean, has an address. By Seth Faison. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-ENVIRON (Undated) _ An ambitious $8-billion plan to
restore the Florida Everglades to ecological health over the next
several decades is coming under fire from experts who say that, as
now conceived, the proposal will actually do little in the way of
restoration. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-POLITICS (Atlanta) _ Voters in Georgia's 6th
Congressional District will choose an heir to former speaker Newt
Gingrich on Tuesday, and the only suspense seems to be whether
Gingrich's hand-picked successor, Johnny Isakson, the state school
board chairman, will win without a runoff in a nonpartisan race
against five opponents. By Kevin Sack. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   POW-WOW-SEASON (Denver) _ In the far-flung archipelago of Indian
country, Denver is emerging as the informal capital. Denver has the
nation's largest concentration of national Indian groups, about 15
associations ranging from the leading Indian law firm to the
leading scholarship fund. By James Brooke. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GOVS-MEET (Washington) _ In the bluntest possible terms,
governors of both parties meeting here at the National Governors'
Association conference told Clinton and Congress to abandon the
poisonous partisanship of the impeachment proceedings and get back
to work on education and other issues of immediate concern to
voters. Within hours of arriving in Washington for their winter
meeting, the governors tried to elevate the political debate from
the depths to which they said it had sunk. By Robert Pear. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   EEOC-REFORM (Washington) _ After decades of being considered the
basket case of federal departments, the Equal Employment
Opportunities Commission has been quietly transforming itself into
an effective agency. By Steven A. Holmes. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-POLITICS (Washington) _ Sounding very much like a
candidate for the Senate in 2000, New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani used interviews on three local and national television
news programs Sunday to criticize Hillary Rodham Clinton and to
tout his own potential as New York's next junior senator. By James
Dao.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-PROJECTORS (Los Angeles) _ The movie industry is on the
threshold of what most experts agree is a major technological
breakthrough. Within two years, movie theaters are expected to
begin abandoning their old film projectors and installing the first
generation of digital projectors. Reels of 35 millimeter film will,
at long last, disappear, a change that could have a far reaching
impact on the theatrical experience. Now, if only the industry can
decide who will pay for the new technology. By James Sterngold.
With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ The Microsoft trial has shed
light on the symbiosis between the largest PC maker and the biggest
PC software company. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ And soon the other big
computer-industry antitrust trial will begin: the government vs.
Intel. Here are the issues, and how legal experts expect things to
play out. By Stephen Labaton. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI-TELECOM-ITALIA (Undated) _ The planned takeover effort
by Olivetti of Telecom Italia is turning out to be more an Italian
operetta than a big new play in European telecommunications. And
yet, the libretto speaks volumes about the odd confluence of
Italian politics and business, set on the stage of a supposedly
open European telecommunications market. By John Tagliabue and
Laura Holson. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-COLUMN (New York) _ Though comparatively small in number,
and nearly invisible in the greater New York Internet and new-media
industry, black Internet entrepreneurs are organizing a support
network, outlining steps to success and finding their own role
models. By Janet Stites.
</P>
<P>
   RETIREES-CONSULTANTS (Undated) _ It is certainly not news when
retired people are pulled into the computer age by a desire to
e-mail their grandchildren or check their stock portfolios on the
Internet. But the 389 chapters and 12,400 volunteer counselors of
the Service Corps of Retired Executives are going farther than
that. Recognizing that they cannot bill themselves as
small-business experts without fully understanding what the
Internet has added to the party, they have immersed themselves in
the nuances of the World Wide Web. By Claudia H. Deutsch. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-SURGERY-MEDIA (Undated) _ AHN.com, the Web extension of the
cable TV channel American Health Network, has made its name
broadcasting surgeries live on the Web. Monday's episode: double
knee replacements for a woman who loves ballroom dancing but has
been sidelined by arthritis. Is this consumer health information,
as the company contends, or is it gruesome voyeurism? Maybe both?
By Lisa Napoli. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NAVAJOS-RADIO-MEDIA (Undated) _ Why the Navajos want a low-power
radio station. By Andrea Adelson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SALESMAN-DENNEHY (New York) _ Actor Brian Dennehy and director
Robert Falls discuss their triumphant 50th anniversary revival of
``Death of a Salesman.'' By Bruce Weber. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ Singapore's dictator, Lee Kuan Yew
_ a friend and sometime adviser to China's leaders _ told reporters
in Europe recently that he saw ``a tinderbox quality'' in the
dissatisfaction rampant in China's coastal cities. By William
Safire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN (New York) _ &UR;  &LR; For weeks leading up to Sunday's
Knicks-Bulls game, I'd been troubled by a feeling that I couldn't
place. The feeling had actually been present ever since the owners
marched their players into camp and put them to work after the
lockout. Then I recognized the gnawing feeling inside. It was the
same sinking feeling that followed me throughout the National
Football League's humorous, humiliating ``replacement player''
games in 1987. Sports column by William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS (Port St. Lucie, Fla.) _ There was no surer sign that
it was a new year here at the Mets' spring training facility than
when Manager Bobby Valentine greeted his everyday catcher with a
kiss. Story on Mike Piazza. By Jason Diamos.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS (Tampa) _ Once the Yankees completed their 125-victory
season with a World Series sweep last fall, forgotten was the fact
that the team did possess weaknesses in the long year. Through most
of July and August, Manager Joe Torre fretted about what the
condition of his middle relief might be in October. Spring training
developments. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-IRABU (Tampa, Fla.) _ Their lockers are about three
feet from each other, separated only by a television and a
videocassette recorder. Those items should not be a hindrance to
Hideki Irabu in his attempt to watch, to absorb and to learn from
Roger Clemens, the legendary pitcher to his right in the Yankees'
clubhouse at Legends Field. By Jack Curry. With photo.
</P>
