<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 03:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4014 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILAN-IMMIGRATION-SFC     02-22 1736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-IMMIGRATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TOLERANT MILAN BECOMES TERRIFIED OF IMMIGRANTS  &HT;     By FRANK VIVIANO 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN _ The Milanese have long taken pride in being ``the least
Italian'' of Italians. In a nation plagued by bureaucratic anarchy,
emotional excess and resistance to change, they were paragons of
efficiency, restraint _ and a cosmopolitan openness to new people
and customs.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; ``We had a strong tradition of tolerance, a belief in the
value of diversity,'' says Franco Mirabelli, local secretary of
Italy's ruling Democrats of the Left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italians awake!'' read a flyer plastered on walls all over the
city in January. ``Rise up against the arrogance of the immigrant
thugs of every race and color in our streets. Take back our
neighborhoods!''
</P>
<P>
   Milan the tolerant, in 1999, has become a metropolis of fear _ a
testing ground for urban Europe's ability to remain tolerant, once
its population diversity reaches critical mass.
</P>
<P>
   Geography explains why that critical mass has been reached in
Milan. It commands nearly all of the major highways and rail lines
that link the Italian Mediterranean to the rest of Europe. One
result is that Milan is the richest city in Italy, a world banking
and fashion capital with a per capita gross domestic product higher
than western Germany's.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that it is a major destination on the clandestine
road between the Third World and the affluent heart of the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 1,200 emigrants are landing daily on the southern
Italian coast, mostly illegally, from as far away as China and Sri
Lanka. All but a few head immediately for the industrial north, and
Milan is where the north begins.
</P>
<P>
   The city is now home to more than 100,000 undocumented
foreigners, according to police sources, plus thousands more who
spend a few months working in Milan as menial laborers before
crossing the European Union's open internal borders en route to
teeming immigrant communities in France, Germany, Holland or
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the undocumented arrive with nothing in their pockets,
and many are burdened with substantial debts to the underworld
syndicates that preside over Europe's enormous traffic in
clandestine immigrants. Like Italy's own immigrants to the United
States before World War I, they find themselves caught between two
unsavory options: acute exploitation or crime.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 18 months, says Milan Mayor Gabriele Albertini, his
city has seen ``an intolerable growth in episodes of small-scale
criminality,'' such as purse-snatching, muggings and petty
burglary.
</P>
<P>
   But far more worrisome, he says, is evidence of
``ever-increasing violence, tied to clandestine immigration,'' and
the recruitment of undocumented newcomers in protection rackets and
sex rings.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study published by La Repubblica, Italy's leading
daily newspaper, 25,000 of the estimated 30,000 full-time
prostitutes in the country today are foreigners, chiefly from
Eastern Europe and Africa. More than a third are girls under 18,
many of whom have been forcibly kidnapped in their homelands and
sold to middlemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must stop calling them prostitutes,'' says Maria Stella
Conte, a Roman journalist who has written extensively on the
immigrant flesh trade. ``They are slaves. The private property of
human dregs. Meat to chew and spit out.''
</P>
<P>
   Milanese anxiety over the crime problem skyrocketed in early
January, when immigrant gang wars over prostitution and drug turf
took nine lives in the first nine days of the year. It reached
crisis proportions January 21 with the fatal knifing of Father
Renzo Beretta, a 78-year-old priest who ran a homeless shelter in
the suburban town of Chiasso, by a undocumented Moroccan immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be a code of behavior, even among criminals: You
don't hurt children or women. You don't kill priests,'' says
Massimo Turci, legislative director for the National Alliance party
in Lombardy, the region surrounding Milan. ``These new criminals
from outside of our borders have no code, no scruples at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Milan industrialist Silvio Berlusconi's Forza Italia, the
neofascist National Alliance and the separatist Northern League _
the right-wing political parties that dominate local politics _ led
protests against crime that drew tens of thousands of marchers in
January and February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clandestine immigration is the new barbarian invasion,''
thundered Umberto Bossi, founder of the violently xenophobic
Northern League. ``We say no, not now or ever, to a multiracial
society in Lombardy.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, multiracial society has already taken root in the large
cities of the European Union, and its chief expression is not crime
but an explosion of rudimentary free enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Albertini's office estimates that 2,000 newcomers per
week, legally and illegally, are settling in Milan. They are the
vanguard of a revolution _ visible and hidden _ in the city of 4.2
million, assembling an American-style ethnic mosaic on the Lombard
plain between Lake Como and the River Po.
</P>
<P>
   The blocks north of the Cathedral of Milan in the city center
have bloomed with Eritrean restaurants, Senegalese beauty shops and
Tunisian grocery stores. When a visiting reporter sat down recently
to a dish of risotto Milanese at the Ristorante il Capriccioso near
the Public Gardens, he was startled to learn that the owners and
head chef were from Nanjing, China.
</P>
<P>
   Their counterparts elsewhere in the EU include the proprietors
of 35,000 Turkish-owned businesses in Germany, and France's
ubiquitous ``petits Arabs du coin'' _ ``little Arab corner
groceries,'' usually open to midnight, that supply Paris with
late-night vin rouge and Brie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to work longer hours, for less money, than most
Italians. It's as simple as that,'' said Mohammed Moharam, the
Egyptian founder of Milan's Pyramid Cleaning, echoing the classic
refrain of immigrant entrepreneurs in San Francisco and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Pyramid offers janitorial services for homes and offices, window
washing, furniture moving, junk removal and painting, all at
``prezzi modici,'' reasonable prices. Its staff is a rainbow team
of Arabs, Sir Lankans and East and West Africans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a high, unfilled demand for basic labor in northern
Italy,'' says Mirabelli. ``The immigrants accept jobs that very few
Italians are prepared to consider anymore, even if they are
unemployed.''
</P>
<P>
   In France, ``it's taken for granted nowadays that the dirtiest,
hardest tasks will be carried out by black people,'' notes Mohamed
Djalo, a social worker in a heavily African Paris neighborhood and
himself an immigrant from Guinea. ``They're the ones who are paid
by the day, without benefits, to carry loads of bricks on their
backs at construction sites. They're the cleaning ladies and the
street sweepers.`'
</P>
<P>
   Yet Arab corner groceries, Turkish entrepreneurs and the
crushing labor of Africans do not command headlines. It is the
stabbing of a priest or the outbreak of a gang war that drives
political campaigns and popular opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the Lebanon of the '80s, or Algeria,'' Italian
Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema reminded the Milanese in a public
meeting with Mayor Albertini. Warning against ``racist hysteria,''
he pointed out that ``organized crime is nourished only partly by
clandestine immigration and remains for the most part absolutely
native (Italian).''
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema was rewarded for his efforts with a volley of rotten
eggs thrown from the audience, and he eventually agreed to
subsidize 600 extra police in Milan.
</P>
<P>
   In France, the extremist National Front has been a significant
political force for a decade, thanks to relentless diatribes
against ``lawless foreigners.'' Its founder, Jean-Marie Le Pen, and
his rival Bruno Megret, who leads an extremist splinter group, have
both exploited growing concern over the role of organized crime in
the immigration crisis.
</P>
<P>
   A Chronicle investigation found evidence that half a dozen
well-established mafias, from the Sicilian original to its
spin-offs and collaborators in Eastern Europe, Asia and Africa, are
deeply involved in the clandestine influx.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoned by human rights-preaching Europe and the United
States, the self-proclaimed ``liberation armies'' of Kurds in
Turkey and Iraq, Tamil Tigers in Sri Lanka, Kosovo Albanians and a
host of ethnic separatist movements in black and Arab Africa, have
effectively thrown their lot in with the dons. In return for arms,
money and places in smuggling networks that land their human cargo
on the Italian and Spanish coasts, many are now foot soldiers in
the empire of organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a diabolically vicious circle, say worried human
rights activists, in which immigrant crime feeds directly into
anti-immigrant xenophobia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Front and the drug dealers are de facto allies,''
says Fode Sylla, president of SOS-Racism, the leading pressure
group against anti-immigrant discrimination. ``Neither has any
interest in seeing troubled areas get out of the mess they're in.
As long as nothing changes, the extreme right will continue to play
on people's fears, and the dealers will tranquilly pursue their
establishment of Mafia rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1988 and 1995, the National Front became the top
vote-getter among working class Frenchmen with its call for the
forcible repatriation of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   A similar right-wing backlash is brewing in Italy, where the
center-left government has proposed regularizing the status of
nearly 300,000 undocumented immigrants at a single stroke, on the
theory that it is precisely their clandestine existence that drives
them to crime. In response, ``the question of public security, and
an alleged immigrant threat to it, are being pushed very hard by
the Italian right,'' says Mirabelli. ``They see it as the major
issue on which they can court frightened voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for rightist parties are quick to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illegal immigration and crime are the first concerns of the
National Alliance,'' says Massimo Turci. ``After 6 p.m., it's the
foreign gangs that govern here. That can't go on, we tell voters.''
</P>
<P>
   The effects will be clear in June, when national elections are
held in Italy. ``But we already know, from our own public opinion
surveys, that our prospects have become much better as a result of
this crisis,'' Turci said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
