<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 04:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4034 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPOLITICS-IMMIGRAT     02-22 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPOLITICS-IMMIGRATION-SFCHRON(W/MILAN-IMMIGRANTS) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW-AND-ORDER POLITICS: LEFTISTS COMPETE WITH THE RIGHT
FOR  HARD-LINE STANCE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (sidebar to MILAN-IMMIGRANTS) 
 &HT;     By FRANK VIVIANO 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Immigrant crime _ and mounting hysteria over it _ are not unique to
northern Italy.
<P>
   Since 1987, nearly 2 million refugees have poured into Germany,
legally and illegally, part of an overall immigrant or foreign-born
population of 10.7 million. As in Italy, a small but conspicuous
number of them have drifted into the underworld.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Poles are especially active in organized car theft.
Prostitution is dominated by the Russian mafia, and drug dealers
come most often from southeast Europe or black Africa,'' Social
Democratic Party chief Gerhard Schroeder said in a 1997 speech,
prior to his election as German chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those (foreigners) who violate our hospitality, there is
only one solution,'' Schroeder said: ``Get out of Germany, fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Riots in France's ``quartiers difficiles'' _ the bleak high-rise
immigrant suburbs of Paris, Lyon and other large French cities _
have become commonplace in the past few years, with 8,000 cars
burned by mobs of young people in 1998 alone.
</P>
<P>
   Schools in these areas have witnessed a sharp increase in
delinquency since the decade opened. Between 1995 and 1996, in the
largely nonwhite suburb of St. Denis where last year's soccer World
Cup final was held, the number of schoolyard assaults rose by 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Under public pressure to act, the Socialist government of Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin has proposed sending an army of 7,000
additional policemen into immigrant neighborhoods, building 50 new
detention centers and 87 reform schools for juvenile offenders in
the troubled districts, and imposing a nighttime curfew on
youngsters under 12.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin's police measures, like Schroeder's speech, reflect a
stark paradox in the assumption of power by center-left political
parties across much of Europe in the late 1990s. To win election,
and remain in government afterward, mainstream socialist parties
have been drawn into an acrimonious law-and-order competition with
the political right.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, law and order has been redefined as ``immigrant
control,'' pushing the debate into dangerous terrain for centrist
parties of any stripe, government critics warn. Politicians who
play this card ``exploit the theme of fear, allowing people to
believe that waves of foreigners are out to destroy the well-being
of Germans,'' says Gunter Verheugen, a Social Democratic expert on
foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The dangers are greatest for the immigrants themselves. On
February 14, in what has become a grimly familiar drama in Germany,
a 28-year-old Algerian immigrant severed an artery in his knee and
bled to death while trying to escape a band of neo-Nazi bullies in
the eastern state of Brandenburg.
</P>
<P>
   The political consequences of fear hit home for the Social
Democrats in regional elections February 7. Waging a mudslinging
assault on government plans to make citizenship possible for as
many as 4 million of the 7.3 million legally settled immigrants in
Germany, the conservative Christian Democratic Union won control of
the western state of Hesse for the first time since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   In national polls, just 39 percent of Germans say they support
the proposed new citizenship policy.
</P>
<P>
   The election results in Hesse _ Germany's richest state and the
location of its financial hub, Frankfurt _ also meant the loss of a
Social Democratic majority in the Bundesrat, the upper house of the
national legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term winners are likely to be extremists, says
Verheugen. An anti-immigrant campaign strategy ``is very dangerous,
and makes a comfortable bed for the extreme right in Germany.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
