 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2522 - February 22, 1999   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2522 -- Feb. 22, 1999 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. BITTER HARVEST : TURKEY'S PRIME MINISTER ON THE ARREST
</P>
<P>
   OF THE KURDISH LEADER Bulent Ecevit, 73, became prime minister
of Turkey last month for the fourth time. In this exclusive
interview, Ecevit fiercely defends Turkey's arrest of the Kurdish
chief Abdullah Ocalan. He says European governments, particularly
those of Germany and Italy, bear partial responsibility for the
rioting and deaths that followed the arrest because they tolerate
the presence of terrorists on their soil. Ecevit says that with
Oclan's arrest, Kurdish separatism is near its end. From Der
Spiegel. 800 words (English translation available.) Q&AMP;A format. 2.
WHAT DID YOU DO IN THE WAR, MAMA? During Salvador's nightmarish
civil war, hundreds of babies and young children were taken from
villages by the military. Now, nearly a generation later, many of
those who survived are being reunited with their biological
families. It isn't always an easy occasion because sometimes
politics can be thicker than blood. By Tina Rosenberg. From The New
York Times Magazine. Full-length (8,500 words) + edited article
available. 3. BURYING KHOMEINI The Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
returned to Iran from exile 20 years ago to spark an Islamic
revolution that, in the eyes of many, dragged Iran back to the
seventh century. In fact, it was a pure product of this
blood-soaked century and its excesses. By Fouad Ajami. From The New
York Times Magazine. 1,000 words. 4. THE REBEL CODE Free to anyone
on the Internet, the Linus operating system, created by a
journalist's son, has mutated in recent months from a geek fetish
to a challenger to Microsoft Windows. By Amy Harmon. From The New
York Times Magazine. 2,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
From NEW SCIENTIST magazine (N/A Australia, New Zealand, Brazil)
</P>
<P>
   A. TOO MUCH, TOO YOUNG Children are not simply miniature adults.
They react to chemicals quite differently. Few drugs are tested on
children, so doctors are having to gamble on suitable doses - often
with dangerous consequences. By Janet Fricker. 1,000 words. B.
WHAT'S THIS VOLCANO TRYING TO TELL US? Deep gurgles and belches
from far underground could be the early warning volcanologists have
been waiting for. Daniel Pendick listens in. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   C. HOLD IT RIGHT THERE What keeps a fetus's fingers or a fly's
wings growing, and then stops when it's just the right size?
Stephen Day investigates. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   D. GALACTIC VISIONARIES Europe's astronomers reckon they can
build a telescope bigger than all its predecessors put together,
and thousands of times more powerful than the best we have today,
says Marcus Chown. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   E. ALMOST HUMAN Are chimps, orang-utans and other great apes
really so similar to people that they should have specific legal
rights? By Rachel Nowak. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   F. ZAP IT AND SEE Could ultrasound reduce the stress of tumour
surgery? By Duncan Graham-Rowe. 400 words. 6. From NATURE NEWS
SERVICE N/A France and Spain. Embargo : 19h00 GMT Wednesday, Feb.
25
</P>
<P>
   A. SPRING FORWARD, FALL BACK Spring is springing earlier in
Europe. Certainly, as far as plants and animals are concerned - 6
days earlier than it did thirty or so years ago. And autumn sticks
around for 5 days more than it used to. The shifts can be
attributed to changes in air temperature.
</P>
<P>
   B. MAKING A DIN FOR SOME DINNER How does the single cuckoo chick
- the imposter in the nest - trick its foster parents into
providing it with as much food as they would normally provide for a
whole brood of their own chicks? How does it get them to feed it at
all?
</P>
