A4127 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-MATH-KAN &LR;      02-22 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-MATH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUST ME, NO MATH IS SIMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter who says what, I'm not a math illiterate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, I can multiply, say, 10 by 11 on a calculator and
get, uh, whatever the answer is. I can balance my checkbook. And I
can find the numbers on my phone to dial my wife's office, though I
don't need to anymore because I'm clever enough to have put her on
speed dial (in case I need a quick reminder of what she told me
earlier today that I've already forgotten). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But as for topology, well, what I know about topology you could
put in a tiny 2-hectare (or whatever) thimble. In fact, I confess
that although the word topology seems uncomplicated _ almost common
_ I'm not sure I'd ever heard of it before I read a recent
Sacramento Bee story. (Oh, that is, too, the name of the newspaper
there, but it's not something I'd brag about.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Topology, it turns out, is a modern form of math that might or
might not be related to geometry. If I have space later I'll
explain it more. If not, look it up. In my encyclopedia it comes
not long after Topeka, a name that may mean ``a good place to dig
potatoes.'' Really. You could look that up, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Topology (not Topeka) figured in the recent Sacramento story
because a famous math puzzle that, the Bee said, had confounded
experts for at least 70 years, recently was solved. The guy who
mastered it was an alumnus of Sacramento State University, which no
doubt was why the Bee cared anything about this news, its ``Math
Section'' being no larger than that of your average daily American
newspaper. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (As for something that has confounded experts for some 70 years,
Strom Thurmond also comes to mind. But I can't imagine any branch
of math that could help us unravel that mystery, so let it go.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mathematician-painter who solved this long-standing puzzle
is Vladimir Akis, who teaches math at a Los Angeles college. Akis
recently returned to his alma mater to present his solution. Among
those in the audience was his mentor, Charles Hagopian, a
Sacramento State math teacher who had tried for three decades to
figure out the puzzle himself. Hagopian had the decency not to
gripe about Akis' cleverness. Instead, he called it a ``happy
day.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to pretend to explain both the puzzle and Akis'
solution, but you would discover almost immediately that my
explanation comes from someone who has no idea what he's talking
about, which would remind you of Strom Thurmond again, and I'm
doing my best to keep Strom Thurmond out of this altogether. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So instead I'll pass on some of the results of my semi-vast
research into topology. That information, after all, may help you
win a radio quiz or some such almost immediately, whereas the
puzzle explanation would have to be so long and bizarre that you'd
give up in exhaustion if you tried to grasp it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A name prominently associated with topology (which does not, by
the way, have to do with the study of toy tops) is L.E.J. Brouwer,
a Dutch mathematician and founder of ``Intuitionism'' who lived
from 1881 to 1966. One source I consulted said his most important
work in topology was done between 1909 and 1913, which made me
wonder how he blew the rest of his life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L.E.J., by the way, stood for Luitzen Egbertus Jan, which
explains why he went by the initials. Brouwer postulated something
called a fixed-point theorem, which says, roughly, that if you
change the shape of a flat surface from a square to a triangle
using the same material, at least one point in the reshaped
triangle will lie exactly above the point where it originally lay
in the square. Can you imagine figuring out such a thing? Me
either. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But that's not surprising. I also can't imagine what I would
have said if I'd had enough space to explain topology to you. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
