<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-YANKS-CLEMENS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL'S GREATEST TEAM GETS A PITCHER TO MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(DUPLICATION WARNING: also sent with `s' code) 
(bl) 
 By ALLEN BARRA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The story is that when David Wells first came here
from Baltimore, he wanted to wear Babe Ruth's No. 3. They had to
explain to him that the number was retired; he settled for wearing
one of Ruth's old caps.
</P>
<P>
   If Roger Clemens asks for No. 3, they ought to at least think
about it. One aspect of the Clemens-for-Wells deal that hasn't been
discussed is that it gives two of the game's greatest entities a
crack at something neither has ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, the best starting pitcher in baseball over the last 15
seasons and one of the 8 or 10 best of all time, gets a chance,
possibly his last, for the World Series ring that will validate his
career. The Yanks get the best pitcher of his era, in his prime or
close to it.
</P>
<P>
   That last statement seems incredible, but think about it. Who is
the greatest pitcher in Yankee history? Most fans would say Whitey
Ford, and that's a pretty good guess. Ford was 236-101 in 16
seasons with a 2.75 earned run average, and he's in the Hall of
Fame. Everyone acknowledges that Ford was a great big-game
performer, and along with Mickey Mantle and Yogi Berra he remains a
symbol of the Yankees' era of dominance in the 1950s and early
'60s.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody ever called Ford the best pitcher of his time. This
season, when Clemens wins his fourth game, he'll have passed Ford's
career win total.
</P>
<P>
   Waite Hoyt, perhaps? The star of the Yankee staff in the 1920s
was a fine pitcher for 8 or 9 seasons and lasted in the Bigs for
21, posting a 237-182 record. Clemens is 233-124 going into spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   How many other great pitchers have the Yankees had? Red Ruffing
and Allie Reynolds were pretty good. Ron Guidry was almost great.
But isn't it one of baseball's puzzles that, in a game that is
supposedly mostly pitching, the winningest team in history has
never at any time had a pitcher who could be called the game's
best?
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has posted a 2.95 career earned run average in an era
when, unlike Ford's, runs are cheap. He has led the league in ERA
six times; only Lefty Grove, generally regarded as the greatest
starting pitcher ever, has led more (nine). That's the pitcher's
equivalent of winning the batting title six times, which no Yankee
has ever done.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has won five Cy Young awards; for a pitcher this is like
winning five Most Valuable Player awards, which only Ruth would
have achieved (if there had been an MVP award early in his career).
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to the departed Boomer, the pairing of
Clemens and the Yankees is a natural. The only regret should be
that it took 80 years to happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
