<SLUG> BC-R-TOY-FAIR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYLAND 1999: SHUT THAT THING UP! 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(bl) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Remember Giga Pets? Not long ago, the little
hand-held computers that children fed, watered and nurtured by
pressing buttons were all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to imagine how a toy company could top that
craze, but get ready for Giga Monsters, designed for ages 5 and up.
Here the object is to make the virtual pets die.
</P>
<P>
   The persnickety monsters keep coming back to life as the
diligent child tries to hasten their destruction. They live in tiny
coffins, or ``uniquely stylized cabinets,'' in the words of the
toy's creator, Tiger Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost enough to make one nostalgic for the days when toys
died because they ran out of batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The Giga Monster was but one of many startling items on display
last week at the 96th American International Toy Fair in New York,
where 1,700 exhibitors gathered to peddle their wares to 20,000
buyers. Most of the toys and games haven't hit stores yet. Some are
still prototypes and failed in demonstrations; others succeeded in
demonstrations and will still fail in stores.
</P>
