GoRu Products for ages 8 and up, but comes with a simplified
version that 5- to 7-year-olds can enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Checkers, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Children are certainly capable of dealing with morality,
character or crime _ after all, they encounter such issues in fairy
tales and in the schoolyard. And, of course, classic games have
always tackled the big themes: Chess explores war, Monopoly takes
on greed and in many games players meet their metaphorical deaths.
But the latest toys tend to be more literal, making announcements
like, ``Your toy just died.''
</P>
<P>
   The new heavy-handed gadgets, plus Jerry Springer board games
and Rock-'n-Roll Elmo, are part of a $20 billion-a-year industry.
Even Bill Gates has gotten in on it. Anyone who thinks Microsoft or
the Teletubbies are intent on world domination will be alarmed to
hear that they have forged an alliance. Microsoft Teletubbies
ActiMates are dolls that a conspiracy theorist could love.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who believes the purple Teletubby is secretly gay
obviously did not attend this year's toy fair. Secrecy and subtlety
were not at a premium: Toys for 1999 tell about themselves in
painstaking detail, and they won't shut up. They will tell you if
they are dead or alive or sad. The Kissy-Kissy Baby, courtesy of
Irwin Toy Ltd., will pucker if you kiss her mouth, will say ``Kiss
my boo-boo better'' if you kiss her hand and ``I love you, Mommy''
if you kiss her cheek. Her responses are ``moisture-activated.''
</P>
<P>
   Even lipstick gets a word in. Funrise Toy is offering electric
lipstick equipped with a sound module that says things like ``You
go girl!''and ``Looking Good!'' The lipstick presumably provides
the encouragement that young girls may not otherwise be getting.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of the sound chip, toys can broadcast all kinds
of messages out loud. Girls' white shoes, for example, could once
connote innocence, or summer, or membership in the wedding party.
But now tots with marital ambitions can slip on a pair of Funrise's
Sound Shoes without any ambiguity. The shoes play ``Here Comes the
Bride'' as the girl walks.
</P>
<P>
   But in a stride against blonde stereotypes, Mattel's Chatty
Cathy now comes in new hair and eye colors. The doll, who
incessantly says things like ``Please carry me,'' can now be a
brunette, too.
</P>
<P>
   Technology also allows toys to relate to one another. According
to Plato, Aristophanes suggested that human beings were once
two-headed creatures, then were split in half and condemned to
spend the rest of their lives seeking to re-attach to their
original mates. Dubbels, a toy by Rumpus, uses the latest
recognition technology chips to prove Aristophanes right. Somewhere
out there, the perfect mate awaits each L-shaped bean-bag creature.
They just need to be fit together.
</P>
<P>
   If two incompatible bean-bags join, the toy will complain,
``You're cute, but you're not my Dubbel.'' The crestfallen child
will then probably demand that another $5.99 be invested in the
Dubbel's search for romance. The payoff comes when it finds its
bean-bag fantasy mate and announces, ``Baby I've been waiting for
you my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   With recognition technology this advanced, subliminal messages
are unnecessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 0903EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
