<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 09:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4157 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CONSERVATIVES-MORAL     02-22 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CONSERVATIVES-MORALS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FAR RIGHT SEES THE DAWN OF THE MORAL MINORITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Alarmed, heartsick and still baffled over
President Clinton's acquittal by the Senate, some of his most
ardent detractors have come to an extraordinary conclusion, one
that may carry grim implications for the conservative movement.
They blame not themselves for mishandling the whole sorry episode
but a public whose moral standards have collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Their message is audacious, perhaps even arrogant: Americans
just don't get it. Why can't they see we were right?
</P>
<P>
   In the most striking example, Paul Weyrich, an unflinching moral
crusader for three decades, embarked last week on a rampage against
society rather than against Clinton. The man who suggested to the
Rev. Jerry Falwell that he name his organization the Moral Majority
now contends that the name is an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   ``I no longer believe that there is a moral majority,'' Weyrich
wrote in a letter to hundreds of thousands of supporters of his
organization, the Free Congress Foundation. ``I do not believe that
a majority of Americans actually shares our values.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking his fury a step further, Weyrich said that while he was
``not suggesting that we all become Amish or move to Idaho,'' he
believes that ``we have to look at what we can do to separate
ourselves from this hostile culture.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked: ``What steps can we take to make sure that we and our
children are not infected? We need some sort of quarantine.''
</P>
<P>
   That's easy for Weyrich to say _ he's not an elected official
accountable to voters. But for those who do run for office, blaming
the public can be risky, particularly in an age when politicians _
no matter how much they grovel at the feet of voters _ find that
public to be increasingly aloof. For all his private
contemptuousness and fury at liberals, President Richard M. Nixon
was careful not to publicly denounce the prevailing public will.
</P>
<P>
   President Jimmy Carter was not as prudent. He isolated himself
from the electorate in 1979 when he said ``a moral and spiritual
crisis'' was gripping the nation. ``Too many of us,'' he said,
``now tend to worship self-indulgence and consumption.''
Republicans traded for years on what was dubbed ``the malaise
speech,'' citing it as Exhibit One of a Democratic Party that was
out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't shame people into changing the way they look at the
world,'' said Dan Schnur, a Republican strategist in California.
``You have to lead by example. And if the people won't follow your
example, it's really not as much their problem as it is yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while Weyrich is the most panicked, he is not alone.
Other conservatives are eager to fault the public rather than
themselves for misreading the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that ordinary Americans reacting to Clinton's conduct
``are complicit in his corruption,'' William Bennett, the former
education secretary who has since built his career on talking and
writing about morality, said: ``I will not defend the public.
Absolutely not. If people want to pander to the public and say
they're right, they can. But they're not right on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he rejected the ``canard that conservatives are
putting out that we didn't make our case.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Smith of New Hampshire, in formally announcing his
long-shot bid for the Republican presidential nomination last week,
could not resist a dig at the public: ``The president's acquittal
is a sad commentary on the prevailing values in America today.'' In
an interview, Smith sneered at polls showing _ week after week,
month after month _ little public appetite for impeachment. ``My
wife likes to say they must be polling people coming out of Hooters
on Saturday night,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Craig Shirley, a longtime conservative public relations
consultant, said: ``A certain portion of the American public is
cowed by popular culture. They do not want to be thought of as not
being modern or sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   Such scorn for the will of the people may be an obvious
manifestation of conservatives' frustration. Again and again, they
replay the tape: A president whom they already believed to be
immoral has an affair with an intern in the Oval Office, lies about
it _ and remains as popular as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they are so demoralized and bitter because many
conservatives convinced themselves that sooner or later the
nation's pent-up outrage would surface. The Weekly Standard, a
conservative magazine, was positively gleeful after Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr sent his impeachment referral to Congress
last September. Jumping off the cover was an illustration of a
beaming Starr at bat, with the headline, ``Starr's Home Run.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of conservatives said, `Wait, there's another woman.
There's another affidavit. It will all turn around,''' Bennett
recalled. ``But at each point they found out more about Clinton his
approvals went up.''
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton ventured back to this state last week _ where seven
years ago he pronounced himself the ``Comeback Kid'' _ his
detractors still could not contain their rage. In a front-page
editorial in The Union Leader of Manchester, publisher Nackey Loeb
advised the president to ``stop by Washington just long enough to
pick up his toothbrush, turn in his resignation and head back to
Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   Many conservatives were not as defeatist as Weyrich, who went so
far as to write off the Republican Party's ability to connect with
society. In his letter, Weyrich complained that ``we have probably
lost the culture war'' and said the cultural collapse was ``so
great that it simply overwhelms politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Weyrich said in an interview that he was not particularly
concerned that conservatives might alienate voters, because he
viewed his causes as larger than partisan politics. ``I've never
been one who is very active in the party to begin with,'' he said.
``It hasn't been my forte. I will be a good citizen and participate
appropriately. But I've never been consumed with the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Weyrich does not have to worry about his own electoral
fate. But perhaps the bashers of Joe Citizen who are still
committed Republicans can take solace in the example of at least
one successful politician who found that loathing voters is not
political suicide: Sen. Stephen Young, D-Ohio, who served from 1959
to 1971. In vituperative letters, he traded indignities with
constituents and interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Young wrote one constituent, ``Buster, your insults show that
you are the east end of a horse going west.'' He called another
constituent ``lower than a snake's tail in a wagon rut.'' He
exploded at still another, calling him a ``low-down skunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Young was re-elected in 1964, the beneficiary of the landslide
for President Lyndon B. Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 0906EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
