<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TABLOIDS-TEXT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERMARKET SHOCKER: TABLOIDS BECOME OLD GRAY LADIES! 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forecasters see a lot of unsettling trends in the aging of the
American population, from rising medical costs to falling arches.
But they may have missed one: the geezer-ization of the supermarket
tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   Now more than ever, the tabs read like versions of Modern
Maturity edited by Rupert Murdoch hopped up on Fibercon _ what with
their persistent dwelling on Liz Taylor and sundry celebrity
candidates for artificial life support.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even though there are more older people nowadays, the tabs
aren't thriving. Blame the increasingly sensationalized mainstream
media for stealing their act, and readers.
</P>
<P>
   The National Enquirer and the Star, for example, have seen their
circulations tumble in the last five years as the median age of
their readers has risen from just over 35 to around 40. Last week
the two tabs were bought by an investment firm led by Robert
Altman, a former Treasury big shot, which plans to rejuvenate their
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with a gray future in store, we've probably not seen the
last of headlines and quotations like those below, gleaned from
just the past two weeks' offerings at checkout counters.
</P>
<P>
   _ TOM KUNTZ
</P>
<P>
   Tony Curtis: I'm Just Starting to Live at 73! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I could never be married to a woman my own age,'' says
the actor. ``I'm 45 years older than Jill and I haven't been this
happy in a long time. Because of her, I feel like a 30-year-old
newlywed.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Globe, Feb. 23
</P>
<P>
   Mama Mia! Look at Sexy Sophia
</P>
<P>
   64-year-old star bounces back from health crisis _ in a
miniskirt! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quote: WOW! Looking fit as a fiddle and just as curvy, a
miniskirted Sophia Loren showed off her shapely legs and proved the
thigh's the limit following her amazing recovery from a terrifying
heart scare six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Globe's exclusive photos show the sexy 64-year-old movie legend
posing like a 20-something starlet while getting out of limo during
a visit to a New York bookstore where she signed copies of her
tasty new tome, ``Sophia Loren's Recipes and Memories.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Globe, Feb. 16 &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Liz to Wed Rod Steiger _ PLUS: Ex-Husband Larry's Tragic Plunge
</P>
<P>
   Quote: The balding actor, 73, has been wining and dining the
violet-eyed screen legend, 66, all over Tinseltown during the past
14 months.
</P>
<P>
   But pals say it wasn't until Taylor landed in Cedars-Sinai
Medical Center just nine days before Christmas that Steiger's
sudden bedside proposal over a heartfelt poem and Taylor's teary
acceptance took them both by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   _ National Examiner, Feb. 16
</P>
<P>
   Why James Brown Is Still a Sex Machine
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Godfather of Soul James Brown is still wowing the women
at 65 _ thanks to potency pill Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm single, I want to mingle,'' he laughs. . . . ``I love the
women. Any man that don't love the women, I'm not by him.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Star, Feb. 16
</P>
<P>
   Red Buttons Takes the Cake At His 80th Birthday Bash
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I want to give a big `Thank you' to ENQUIRER readers
for helping me to celebrate my 80th birthday. . . . I finally got a
dinner!'' quipped the birthday boy.
</P>
<P>
   _ National Enquirer, Feb. 23
</P>
<P>
   GLOBE Reveals . . .Tales of the Playboy Mansion
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``A lot of people want to come and play,'' says Hef, 72.
</P>
<P>
   _ Globe, Feb. 23
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan _ MAN WHO PLAYS GOD WITH YOUR CASH
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Now 72, Greenspan started his economic wizardry early.
His mother Rose would amuse guests by having 5-year-old Alan add a
pair of three-digit numbers in his head. The number-crunching kid
developed a deep love for statistics _ and baseball. He got his
first taste of fame in the 1940s as a swinging sax player for the
Henry Jerome Swing Band!
</P>
<P>
   _ Sun, Feb. 23
</P>
<P>
   My Favorite Martian Ray Walston reveals: THE DAY A UFO BUZZED MY
HOUSE!
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``About 20 years ago, my wife Ruth and I were living in
the Hollywood Hills,'' recalls Walston, 79. ``It was a quiet
afternoon and I'd taken a cold drink out on the patio and was
sitting at a table under an umbrella looking out over the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly I noticed an object floating in the sky directly
overhead. . . .'' _ National Examiner, Feb. 16
</P>
<P>
   TALK-SHOW STAR FRIDGES
</P>
<P>
   TV's big-bucks talk-show stars must stock their refrigerators
with champagne and caviar. Right? Think again!
</P>
<P>
   Quote, on Regis Philbin's icebox: No fast-food fixes for the
65-year-old ``Live!'' host. ``In my refrigerator, there are about
10 bottles of vitamins,'' he confides.
</P>
<P>
   _ Globe, Feb. 23
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lord's Wife Bids Aloha To ``Hawaii Five-O''!
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Marie Lord, 92, stunned guests when she turned up at a
reunion of former ``Five-O'' cast members exactly a year and a day
after Alzheimer's-stricken Jack died of heart failure at age 77.
</P>
<P>
   _ Globe, Feb. 16
</P>
<P>
   America's Oldest Cop Still Prowls The Mean Streets _ at Age 82
</P>
<P>
   56-year veteran has . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Saved Lives
</P>
<P>
   _ Dodged bullets
</P>
<P>
   _ Routed mobsters
</P>
<P>
   _ Guarded Elvis
</P>
<P>
   _ &AMP; he ain't done yet!
</P>
<P>
   Quote: At age 82, Andrew F. Anewenter is a lieutenant with the
Milwaukee, Wis., police department, where he works 50 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Age is for wine and cheese _ not cops,'' he told The Enquirer.
</P>
<P>
   _ National Enquirer, Feb. 16
</P>
<P>
   Bionic Granny: Docs Replace 8 of Her Major Joints
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Meet Norma Wickwire _ a real life Bionic Granny!
</P>
<P>
   Norma has made it into the ``Guinness Book of Records'' for
having more artificial joints than any other human being. . . .
both hips, both knees, both shoulders, an ankle and an elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a heck of a way to get famous,'' quipped the lively
Inverness, Fla., grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   _ National Enquirer, Feb. 16
</P>
<P>
   Cher Needs a Man _ And We've Got Some Candidates &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Possible beau: Senator John Warner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quote: One of Liz Taylor's exes, this 72-year-old is no stranger
to Tinseltown. (He) can also get Cher (52) involved in Senate
social circles and put her a notch above Sonny's widow in the House
of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ National Examiner, Feb. 23
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Monroe's Loving Message To Joe DiMaggio
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Late legend Marilyn Monroe has sent a moving message from
the beyond to ailing baseball great Joe DiMaggio: ``I'm waiting for
you in heaven, honey!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Globe, Feb. 23 &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
