<HEADER>
A4165 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TA     02-22 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flying on the Super Cheap &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Granted, April in Paris is hard to beat, but one thing that
beats it is being able to spend April in Paris thanks to an airline
ticket costing less than the regular fare between Seattle and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A rash of bargain fares this winter from an industry that, in
the words of one airline official, ``has more seats available than
fannies to put in them,'' has placed many European cities within
reach for the next two months _ plenty of time for Americans to
enjoy spring elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Through Wednesday of this week, United, American, Delta, British
Airways and other carriers are offering an array of low-cost
roundtrip tickets, including New York or Boston to London for $228,
or Los Angeles and San Francisco to London for $358. Air France's
$270 roundtrip fare between Chicago and Paris can be purchased as
late as this Friday, as can its $300 roundtrip to Madrid or $380
roundtrip to Rome or Milan. The fares are larded with restrictions,
and not all airlines have identical discounts or travel dates.
</P>
<P>
   If it is true there'll always be Paris, airline officials say,
you must remember this: it may be a long time before there'll be
Paris this cheap again. The discount fares do not include
Casablanca.
</P>
<P>
   _ EDWIN McDOWELL
</P>
<P>
   Turning Midlife Crisis Into Bliss &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a nation of rapidly aging baby boomers, it was very good
news: Never mind those heartburn commercials and wrinkle cream ads.
Middle age is not so bad after all.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said Dr. Orville Gilbert Brim, director of the
MacArthur Foundation Research Network on Successful Midlife
Development, which just released the first wave of results from a
10-year study of nearly 8,000 Americans, ``midlife is the best
place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from supporting the Madison Avenue stereotype of middle age
as a time of questioning and emotional upheaval, the MacArthur
study found that most people experience the years between 35 and 65
_ particularly the decades between 40 and 60 _ as a period of
psychic equanimity, good health and productive activity. They feel,
for the most part, a high degree of satisfaction with their
marriages and with their relationships with children _ and a
greater sense of control in many areas of life. Most say they feel
better about their lives than they did 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And while the term ``midlife crisis'' is so familiar that 95
percent of Americans can define it, only 23 percent of participants
in the study reported having a midlife crisis, and of those, just a
third described the crisis as a time of personal turmoil brought
about by the realization that they were aging.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the MacArthur study is the MIDUS survey, an
in-depth telephone and mail survey of 3,000 adults from 25 to 74
years old, designed to tap a variety of life domains. About 5,000
other subjects participated in 11 related studies, whose results
will be released in future reports, Brim said.
</P>
<P>
   The study is the most comprehensive to date of middle-aged
adults. But while its message is upbeat, the findings suggest many
Americans may have trouble believing it: Fully 87 percent of those
surveyed told the researchers they would like to be younger than
they are.
</P>
<P>
   _ ERICA GOODE
</P>
<P>
   China Frees a Journalist Before an American Meeting  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before the visit to Beijing of Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, China granted early release to a journalist who
was imprisoned after writing about internal politics in Hong Kong
publications. Diplomats read the release of Gao Yu, 55, whose case
had been publicized abroad, as a gesture to soften U.S. rights
concerns as the two countries plan a visit to Washington by Prime
Minister Zhu Rongji in April. But the gesture was not overwhelming:
Ms. Gao had served all but nine months of a six-year term.
</P>
<P>
   _ ERIK ECKHOLM
</P>
<P>
   Deciphering a Deadly Flu
</P>
<P>
   Scientists reached a milestone in their attempts to uncover the
face of one of the most deadly viruses ever known _ an influenza
virus that swept the world in 1918, killing perhaps as many as 40
million people. Using shards from lung tissue preserved since 1918,
they deciphered the entire sequence of an essential viral gene.
Unfortunately, this gene did not explain the virus' lethality. The
scientists are moving on to the virus' seven remaining genes.
</P>
<P>
   _ GINA KOLATA
</P>
<P>
   Graft This Side of the Border
</P>
<P>
   After years of sporadic charges about corruption within the U.S.
Customs Service, a Treasury Department report concluded that the
agency's front-line role in the war against illegal narcotics had
left it vulnerable to drug traffickers willing to pay enormous
bribes to low-paid officers willing to look the other way. The
report found that the agency's internal affairs system was too
ineffective to determine the scope of the problem, but said that
Raymond W. Kelly, the former New York Police Commissioner who was
recently appointed Customs Commissioner, had taken steps to more
aggressively police employee dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Online Magazine Free, Again  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten months after deciding to charge readers $19.95 a year, the
publisher of the online magazine Slate announced in an e-mail
notice to subscribers that the magazine is now available free on
the World Wide Web. The fee was an important test of one facet of
Internet commerce: Would readers pay to read a magazine _ even a
really good one _ online? The answer, for now, is no.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Power to One Person
</P>
<P>
   A former leader of the Black Panther Party, Elmer (Geronimo)
Pratt spent 27 years behind bars for a murder he insisted he did
not commit; in 1997 a California judge threw out the conviction,
saying critical evidence had been withheld. Now, with the judge's
decision upheld on appeal, Los Angeles County District Attorney Gil
Garcetti said Pratt, 51, would not be tried again. Prosecutors,
Pratt said, ``did not come clean,'' about ``their complicity with
this frame-up, this 27-year trauma.'' He plans a civil lawsuit
against the state of California.
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Stealing Home
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees based their arbitration argument with the All-Star
shortstop Derek Jeter strictly on numbers. Jeter has only three
years in the big leagues, club officials argued, and he shouldn't
be paid more than $3.2 million-a-year. But Jeter's agent took a
different tack, mentioning the 24-year-old's star quality in
supporting his request for $5 million _ how many endorsements he
does, how many Web site inquiries on Jeter's name and how teen-age
girls squeal when they see him. Jeter won, and the award is one of
the largest in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   _ BUSTER OLNEY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
