<HEADER>
A4191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN24-CO     02-22 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Before chickens were bacteria-laden
 &HT;    For release Feb. 24, 1999.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year-old article I finally caught up with the other day
reported that nearly two-thirds of all chickens bought at retail
stores carry the germ campylobacter, described in the dispatch as
``the most widespread cause of food poisoning in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The same article quoted others as saying the warning, from
Consumers Union, was alarmist, and it strongly implied that the
persons most endangered by campylobacter were those who ate raw
chicken _ which, presumably, most of us do not.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a conversation with old friends about how we were
served chicken when we were kids. Each Friday night, I would eat at
Grandma's house, she an old-country woman who believed every part
of the chicken was a delicacy and who, after koshering it in a bath
of rock salt, cooked her chicken so long that no bacteria could
hope to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the chicken parts Grandma Ida forced onto our plates no
longer can reach the table via our retail stores; they're now being
used to improve our balance-of-trade situation.
</P>
<P>
   I can recall having a misstated ``appetizer'' concoction of the
chicken's yellow feet, a bony ring from its neck and the part that
went over the fence last being placed on my plate either in honor
of my youth or for punishment for my school grades; I forget which.
</P>
<P>
   Now chicken feet are a prime export to Asia, particularly Japan.
Necks, gizzards and dark meat also head off to Asia, although I
confess to liking dark meat.
</P>
<P>
   When I would balk at eating chicken feet on those uncomfortable
Friday nights, Grandma Ida would admonish me with the words heard
so often by Jewish-American children of the World War II years:
``If you don't eat it, Hitler will.''
</P>
<P>
   I tried, without success, to impress upon this woman that the
war would be shortened considerably if Hitler did eat those chicken
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Another item Grandma Ida served during the Friday night dinner
also could have had an effect on the length of the war. She called
it ``kremsl.'' This she made of ground matzoh, eggs, some spices
and, I am certain, heavy water that later was to be used in the
development of the atomic bomb.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the shape of a half-inch-thick pancake, at least. And
each must have weighed better than a pound.
</P>
<P>
   This was served with the main course, an overboiled chicken leg
and thigh that slipped off the bone the moment I tried to raise it
from the plate.
</P>
<P>
   I would whisper to my grandmother that the best use of a kremsl
was to drop it from Allied planes over Germany, the kremsl having
some of the same properties of a 500-pound bomb. A couple of good
kremsl raids, I insisted, would bring Hitler to his knees. Or, I
also suggested, instead of bombing his cities with kremsl, make him
eat it. He'd be on his knees quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my misgivings about portions of the meal, the Friday
night dinners were a major part of my growing up and were not yet
known to be contaminated with something called campylobacter.
</P>
<P>
   These days, it seems to be a rule of the table to analyze the
food for its properties rather than its taste or appearance. Words
such as salmonella, listeria and campylobacter creep into our
market shopping or dinner table planning.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not certain how frequently these bacteria affect humans but
I know that Grandma Ida lived a long time _ well into her 80s _
while never being cognizant of them.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what finally caused her to die was a compilation of
these myriad bacteria, but if you ever saw my Grandma Ida chewing
away on a yellow chicken foot, you'd never get the impression she
was killing herself.
</P>
<P>
   To her, that and boiled fish heads were great delicacies. Ah,
those Monday night boiled fish heads!
</P>
<P>
   But that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
