<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4192 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN24-COX     02-22 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: On tax cuts, public sees through GOP again
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans are reworking themselves from the
impeachment party to the tax cutting party, pushing for a 10
percent federal income tax cut, but although tax cutting is a cozy
comfort zone for Republican politicians, it is not clear that tax
cuts play much better with the public than impeachment did.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, everyone gripes about taxes. Always have, always will. Few
would turn down a cut.
</P>
<P>
   But survey after survey finds tax cuts low on voters' wish
lists, and the last market test wasn't promising. Bob Dole bid a 15
percent tax cut if folks would just elect him president. He is
currently hustling against erectile dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, as in impeachment, the public seems to have a
sounder grip on reality than GOP agenda writers.
</P>
<P>
   For all our bellyaching, the fact remains, as it has for
decades, that Americans are among the least taxed of industrial
peoples. The latest figures from the authoritative Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development put the United States in the
bottom five among the 29 leading economies in taxes as a percentage
of Gross Domestic Product. Only the Japanese (just barely),
Koreans, Turks and Mexicans pay less.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the taxes paid by typical American families have
remained essentially constant for years.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of whipping up support, the keenest would-be
tax-cutters usually resort, and are again, to phony numbers. This
season's holy-cow figure has Americans paying an average of 40
percent of their income in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that's sort of true _ but utterly misleading.
</P>
<P>
   To gimmick up the figure, the scare-mongers first round up from
the conservative Tax Foundation's figure of 36.7 percent. That's
some pretty steep rounding. Then they fail to mention that the
average includes capital gains and estate taxes -- overwhelmingly
paid by the well-off.
</P>
<P>
   The only big tax ``increase'' of late has come from investors
harvesting profits in a boom stock market, and estate taxes don't
even kick in until the inheritance hits $625,000. Lumping those
taxes into the average wildly inflates what typical families pay.
</P>
<P>
   The Tax Foundation and other 40-percenters have federal taxes
alone taking 26.1 percent of average two-earner households. The
independent Congressional Budget Office and Joint Committee on
Taxation put the figure for typical families between 16 and 19
percent.
</P>
<P>
   And most voters can do enough math in their heads to see who
wins big from a 10 percent cut. Not them. More than 60 percent of
the boon would go to the top 10 percent of incomes. Many households
would be lucky to pocket $2 a week. Whee?
</P>
<P>
   A tax cut in a growing economy could ignite inflation _
provoking higher interest rates that in effect would take back the
cut and give it to bankers. Better to use budget surpluses to make
modest investments in the future, through improved schools, for
instance, and to pay down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   That would make the public life we all share a little better,
rather than funding still-sweller lives for folks already living
well.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
