<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Ga. governor does battle with DOT
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes still winces over the slogan his
opponent, Guy Millner, used in the last election: ``Roy Barnes _
too liberal for Georgia.'' But it is precisely because there's
nothing liberal about Barnes' record or style that he's been able
to sell a progressive transportation initiative to a Legislature
that moves like molasses.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he says, he would have told any politician he was
nuts to try it. But the Legislature is poised to approve Barnes'
bill, maybe this week.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has mastered a key political lesson _ it's how you
say it that counts. When he tells suburban politicians _ who think
local control is woven into the American flag _ their economic
future demands putting regional interests first, they believe him.
When he tells legislators from Vidalia and Valdosta that fixing the
metro problem is the only way to guarantee Georgia gets the federal
money to complete their rural highways, they believe him, too.
</P>
<P>
   At a Georgia Conservancy growth strategies seminar last week,
Barnes included one of the ``country boy from Cobb County'' stories
that help him win over all who are suspicious of a transportation
superagency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a county that's as protectionist as any I know,''
he said. ``We once had some politicians who suggested we put
piranhas in the Chattahoochee and stand at the bridge to keep
anything from Atlanta from getting in. Let me tell you something _
they're there.'' There's always a major point after Barnes says,
``Let me tell you something.''
</P>
<P>
   And his point was that you can't tell today where Cobb County
ends and Atlanta begins. That we're all in this together when it
comes to saving the region from the traffic and pollution that are
tarnishing Atlanta's economic shine.
</P>
<P>
   I love hearing the governor speak, maybe because I'm a native
with deep roots in south Georgia. But underneath all of that
Southern storytelling and preacherlike fervor is an intellect I
admire too. It enables Barnes to get tedious legal details right,
plot strategies that corner potential opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders love Barnes on transportation, but many aren't
crazy about him on health care. He's determined to make HMOs liable
for medical decisions they make, and businesses worry lawsuits
could increase costs. Chambers of Commerce have joined with
insurance lobbyists in opposing patients' rights in the past. But
not this year_ at least, not visibly. They need Barnes' good will
too badly on growth issues.
</P>
<P>
   The battle I'm waiting for on transportation, though, will come
when Barnes' new regional authority tells the state Department of
Transportation its plans don't include enough money for alternative
modes of transportation. The DOT, which operates under its own
board and controls most of its own budget, has allocated only 2.2
percent of its annual $540 million in federal dollars for
alternatives over the past five years. That's despite the fact that
nearly two-thirds of those dollars could have been used for such.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes is showing just how good he is at changing the political
dynamics of local decision-making. But I'm waiting for him to say
``Let me tell you something'' _ about decision-making at DOT.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
