A4261 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN23-C     02-22 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K COMMENTARY: U.S. mood is closer to glee than gloom
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The arrival of 2000 will have special meaning for Christians,
marking the end of their faith's second millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar that we use today was designed in the sixth
century, under orders of Pope John I, to honor Jesus Christ. It
declared that Christ was born in year 1.
</P>
<P>
   On the calendar Christians agree, but not on how to view the
impending arrival of a third millennium.
</P>
<P>
   As 2000 approaches, some evangelical Protestants are saying the
new year could trigger the ``end times.'' These Christians say the
New Testament's Book of Revelation foretells a battle of
Armageddon. And they believe 2000 could mark the launch of this
epic fight between good and evil.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church is taking the opposite approach. Pope John
Paul II has declared 2000 to be the Great Jubilee Year. ``The
journey of believers toward the third millennium is in no way
weighed down by the weariness which the burden of 2,000 years of
history could bring,'' the pope said in declaring the jubilee year.
``Rather, Christians feel invigorated. May the joy of forgiveness
be stronger and greater than any resentment.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he says Christians have an obligation to celebrate on
New Year's Eve. ``Let no one in this jubilee year ... behave like
the elder brother in the Gospel parable who refuses to enter the
house to celebrate'' (Luke 15:25-30), Pope John Paul II said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Protestant evangelicals and the Catholic pope are both
Christians, why do they see New Year's Day 2000 so differently?
</P>
<P>
   ``The year 2000 seems to be a far more loaded date for
Protestants than for Catholics,'' said Joanne Maguire, an assistant
professor of religious studies at the University of North Carolina
at Charlotte. ``Catholics tend to believe the Second Coming could
come at any moment of any day,'' so they don't focus much attention
on a particular date, such as Jan. 1, 2000, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, more Catholics are seeing visions of the Mary.
``Protestants have had a culture of apocalypse ... while Catholics
have a long-standing tradition of seeing visions,'' said Victor
Balaban, a psychologist at Emory University who studies religious
beliefs and millennial events. As Protestants and Catholics respond
to their ``millennium anxieties,'' each takes comfort from whatever
feels familiar within their own traditions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Marian Library-International Marian Research Institute at
the University of Dayton in Ohio reports that in recent years, more
than 200 new apparitions of Mary have been reported around the
world, with more than a dozen in the United States in the 1990s.
And now the visions are increasing as we approach 2000. In Georgia,
for example, tens of thousands of people have gathered throughout
this decade in Conyers to hear Nancy Fowler reveal her messages
from Mary.
</P>
<P>
   So will 1999 be filled with yet more predictions of Armaggedon
and sightings of the blessed mother? Perhaps. But maybe not as many
as religious scholars once expected, according to Mark Silk,
director of the Center for the Study of Religion in Public Life at
Trinity College in Hartford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are really pretty good'' for most Americans these days,
Silk said. ``I don't see people in a state of high distress.''
</P>
<P>
   With the nation at peace, the economy in good shape and crime
decreasing, people may be less wary of the new millennium than they
would have been in harsher times. Regardless of religion, we're
more inclined to follow the pope's advice and ``enter the house to
celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mgeewax(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
