<HEADER>
A4262 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX     02-22 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: I can relate to the ``Mouth of the South''
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. _ Former CNN chief, and one-time outdoor
advertiser, Ted Turner, seems to spend an awful lot of time trying
to pry his foot out of his mouth. On Tuesday, in an address to the
National Family Planning and Reproductive Association in
Washington, he tells a Polish joke in reference to the pope.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday he issues an apology to the Catholic League, an
anti-defamation group that didn't think he was very funny. And that
was last week. Wonder what he's up to this week.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Turner and his wife, Jane Fonda, promised $1 billion
to the
</P>
<P>
   United Nations for programs encouraging population control.
Sounded good to me, but a few of my more conservative friends had a
different idea. ``Commie Pinkopropaganda!'' they howled. ``He
married ``Hanoi Jane'' and now he's playing Charlie McCarthy to her
Edgar Bergen.'' I tell them I doubt that and remind them Turner was
roiling the waters of polite society long before he ever met
Henry's daughter. Think America's Cup, and Turner's acceptance
speech, just before
</P>
<P>
   his tipsy tumble from the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I read of another outbreak of Turner's foot-in-mouth
disease, I can't help chuckling. It's not always pretty, and often
rude, but somehow I can identify with Mrs. Turner's bad boy.
</P>
<P>
   One of my earliest recollections is of my mother explaining to a
group of ladies gathered in her parlor what a lovely child I had
been before I learned to talk. ``Don't blurt!'' she'd warn as she
pulled me aside, pinching my elbow for good measure. And when it
became obvious that I wasn't catching on, she'd rat on me to my
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry, I have to tell you what your daughter did today,'' was
the way the conversation would usually begin. I don't remember
being particularly upset over these dinnertime harangues, but
looking back on it, I suspect my father often wished he could have
skipped the evening's show and tell.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently, Mother would insist my father do something about his
daughter which invariably prompted him to remind me that some folks
might be unreceptive to my verbal eruptions. ``Weigh your words,''
he'd sagely advise. ``Think before you speak.'' I would promise to
try harder but
</P>
<P>
   somehow, I always blew it - like the time I warned our kindly
neighbor, Mrs. Sullivan
</P>
<P>
   who wore a fiery red wig, that her hair was on crooked.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, my behavior would rock my mother's social
equivalent of the Richter scale so badly she'd have a ``sinking
spell'' and take to her bed for hours, sometimes days, refusing all
nourishment (except chocolate-covered cherries) and hibernate until
she'd regained her strength. If I dared intrude, I'd be met with
the words every kid dreads: ``I just hope that when you
</P>
<P>
   grow up and have children they behave the way you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother lived to see her wish come true. One afternoon,
thirty-some years later, we were sitting in a downtown Atlanta tea
room with my two-year-old
</P>
<P>
   son between us. As we ladled and silently sipped our cold
cucumber soup, the
</P>
<P>
   child played quietly on the tray of his high chair, a Matchbox
bulldozer in one
</P>
<P>
   hand and a crumbling cracker in the other. Mother had no sooner
commented on his exemplary behavior, noting how different it was
from the only child she had raised, than he let out a shriek and
pointed to the lady at the next table. ``Momma! Look at that hat!''
</P>
<P>
   Mortified, I grabbed for the offending finger and tried to
shoosh little big mouth. My mother leaned back in amusement. ``It's
impolite to point,'' I whispered firmly. He caught on and holstered
the deviant digit. But I had forgotten to mention the yelling part.
``But, Momma!'' he bellowed again, this time using his elbow as a
pointer, ``isn't that a funny hat?'' My mother did everything but
slap her thighs in unladylike amusement at my discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I'm not in the same league with the fearless Ted Turner.
Now he's lobbying for a recall of the Sixth Commandment (adultery).
Can't wait to see how he gets out of this one.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
