<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-ALAN-JACKSON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALAN JACKSON: MILES GONE AND MORE TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of country singer Alan Jackson 
 By JENNIFER GERLOCK  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's been a long road from Newnan, Ga., for the man in the white
hat, country superstar Alan Jackson.
 &HT;    When he left Newnan, he took with him only a guitar and his
high-school sweetheart. Today, Jackson can claim more than 25
million albums sold, a 30,000-square-foot mansion by a lake in
Franklin, Tenn., and a wall of awards that hardly another
entertainer could match.
 &HT;    The man who owns that mansion shows no signs of having ``gone
Hollywood,'' however. The soft-spoken, regular-guy image which
catapulted him to stardom is still very much in evidence.
 &HT;    Jackson is best known for his breakthrough hits ``Here in the
Real World,'' ``Chasin' That Neon Rainbow,'' ``Don't Rock the
Jukebox'' and ``Chattahoochee,'' all from his first album, ``Here
in the Real World'' (1989). Nine years, seven albums, more than 24
No. 1 songs and 63 awards later, Jackson is still in his prime.
 &HT;    His current album, ``High Mileage,'' debuted at No. 1 on
Billboard's country charts in September 1998. Within a month of the
disk's release, it had sold more than a million copies and earned
him his 28th top-five record, not to mention his highest-debuting
single ever, the soulful ``I'll Go On Loving You.''
 &HT;    The title ``High Mileage'' appealed to him because it seemed to
resonate with his life, the singer says.
 &HT;    ``I just felt like it was a good title for where I am in my
career, in my life,'' Jackson says. ``I compare it to a car. It's
not that old but it's been driven a lot, so it's got high mileage
on it. A lot of times old cars like that run better than the one
that has been just sitting around. It's rusty, but that doesn't
mean it's bad. Like me _ I've been through a lot in my life.''
 &HT;    He was planning the record and writing five of its songs during
a time of particular crisis in his life, the 40-year-old Jackson
recalls. He and Denise, his wife of 18 years and, yes, his former
high-school sweetheart, had split up, leading the singer to
re-evaluate his priorities.
 &HT;    The result of that soul-searching was a step back along the
path: After a five-month separation, the Jacksons reconciled late
last year. On Dec. 15, 19 years to the day after they were first
married, they renewed their vows.
 &HT;    ``I think I just reached a point where I learned that the career
wouldn't make me happy and the toys didn't make me happy,'' he
says. ``You've got to have a relationship _ the main relationship
in your life, with your partner, your wife or whatever _ and it has
to be right. We had grown apart, and had for a long time. We
learned a lot about ourselves ... and we're better than ever now.''
 &HT;    Jackson believes that his personal trials have not only made him
a stronger individual, but also lent a greater substance to his
work.
 &HT;    ``I like this album better than any album I've made overall,''
he says. ``I think there is a lot of heart and soul in this. Some
of the songs that I was a writer on came at a time when there was a
lot going on in my life, and there is a lot of emotion there. I
think it comes through in some of the music. I hope people hear
that.''
 &HT;    The notes for the album include thanks from Jackson to many of
his musical heroes, singers and/or songwriters such as Hank
Williams, George Jones, Tammy Wynette and Merle Haggard, for their
influence on his career and music.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to thank some people who didn't directly have
anything to do with this album, but in a lot of ways these are the
people who made me want to do this for a living,'' the singer says.
``I am still fans of theirs. That's why I wanted to, because I
don't know that I have ever had a chance to thank them personally
for what they contributed to my ending up in the music business.''
 &HT;    Even after almost a decade of stardom, however, Jackson is
uncomfortable with the idea that there may be younger singers and
songwriters who are drawing similar inspiration from his own work.
 &HT;    ``I don't know that I'll ever impact people the way George Jones
or Hank Williams has,'' he says. ``If anything, I hope I'm keeping
a little bit of traditional country music alive for the next
generation, so they'll know what it is.''
 &HT;    Jackson is taking the country-music tradition he grew up with
out on the road this year. He has modeled his current tour, ``Alan
Jackson's High Mileage Road Show,'' after the Grand Ole Opry road
shows of the 1950s, where a multiartist bill would tour, anchored
by a big-name artist.
 &HT;    ``I thought that this would be a good idea, seeing as it's so
hard to get a leg up in the business,'' Jackson says. ``I remember
those days. The first artists who gave me a hand were Randy Travis
and Alabama. I believe in carrying on the traditions and supporting
some of the great new talent in country music.''
 &HT;    Touring with Jackson in the road show are country newcomers Chad
Brock, Clint Daniels, Sara Evans, Andy Griggs and Danni Leigh.
Further following the Grand Ole Opry model, each of the artists
will have the opportunity to perform three or four selections of
his or her own material.
 &HT;    This approach creates a diverse musical experience for the
audience, which is exactly Jackson's aim.
 &HT;    ``You know, sometimes when you get so caught up in the business,
you forget how the fans listen to the music,'' the singer says. ``I
know I'm that way. I get more and more critical of songs, and even
get to where I can't listen to them just like a fan would.
 &HT;    ``You forget that the people out there listening aren't that
serious about it,'' Jackson continues. ``It's not their life, so
most of the time it's just background music for them. They're not
analyzing every line, every steel-guitar part or something.
 &HT;    ``A lot of times you tend to get too mechanical with it. I have
to really work to try not to get so into my own world and forget
what everything else is really like.''
 c.1999 Jennifer Gerlock  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jennifer Gerlock is a Mount Juliet, Tenn.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
