w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILLY-CRYSTAL-IN-ANAL     02-22 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLY-CRYSTAL-IN-ANALYZE-THIS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ANALYTICAL WORLD OF BILLY CRYSTAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Billy Crystal with Robert De Niro in a
scene from ``Analyze This.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's the Oscars that you'll never see, with Billy Crystal
returning as the 1999 host and, as in past years, insinuated into
the top films through the magic of digital technology.
 &HT;    ``I know what I would have done with `Saving Private Ryan,'''
the comedian says, chuckling. ``As Tom Hanks was coming ashore, I
probably would have been a Nazi shooting at him and screaming, `He
wins every year! Well, not this year, buddy!'''
 &HT;    Crystal enjoys the laugh. At 50, trim with a still-boyish face,
he's relaxing in a sweater and jeans at Manhattan's Essex House
hotel and indulging his favorite pastime _ riffing spontaneously
on, for example, ``Shakespeare in Love.''
 &HT;    ``I might have been Shakespeare's therapist,'' he says. ``Will,
let's explore your feelings about relationships, because things
aren't working. Whoops, Will, your 50 minutes are up.''
 &HT;    Actually, that last one sounds vaguely plausible. In his latest
film _ ``Analyze This,'' opening March 5 _ Crystal plays a
psychiatrist who finds himself treating a troubled mob boss (Robert
De Niro).
 &HT;    The timing of the film's release, in fact, is why Crystal turned
down an invitation to handle this year's Oscar-hosting duties.
 &HT;    ``I work so hard to make the Oscars look easy, but it is a lot
of work,'' he says. ``Basically, I wanted to have a more relaxed
spring.
 &HT;    ``The worst part of not hosting is that I ended last year's show
by saying, `See you next year,''' he adds. ``The moment I said it,
I was like, `What have I done?'''
 &HT;    De Niro _ who's had an Oscar night or two himself _ may seem an
unlikely co-star for the irreverent comedian, but Crystal insists
that the two actually worked well together.
 &HT;    They were introduced years ago by Robin Williams, a longtime
friend of Crystal who worked with De Niro in the film
``Awakenings'' (1990).
 &HT;    ``One night I went to dinner with Robin, who said, `Hey, Billy,
do you mind if Bobby De Niro joins us?' I was like, `Yeah, I do
mind,''' he says sarcastically. ``Of course I want to eat dinner
with Robert De Niro!''
 &HT;    Over the salad course, Crystal says, he learned that De Niro was
a fan of his ``City Slickers'' films.
 &HT;    Fast forward to 1997, when ``Analyze This'' went into
preproduction. Crystal, as co-producer, wanted to offer the
mob-boss part to De Niro, despite his lackluster record in
comedies.
 &HT;    ``I call Bob and say, `Hello, how are you?''' he recalls. ``I
hear on the other end of the receiver, `Hello. You got a role? Well
... maybe ... um ... I don't know ... OK ... uh ... huh.'
 &HT;    ``You can't shut him up once he starts going,'' Crystal jokes.
 &HT;    On the New York set, the comedian learned to interpret De Niro's
cryptic mumbles.
 &HT;    ``We would have conversations where Bob would say, `We gotta fix
... you know ... I know you know ... you know what I mean?'''
Crystal says, laughing.
 &HT;    ``I knew exactly what he meant.''
 &HT;    De Niro is legendary for his intensity, both on and off the
screen, but Crystal says he didn't find the Oscar-winner difficult
to work with.
 &HT;    ``He plays intimidating characters,'' he says, ``but when you're
with Bob, he's a very open, friendly guy, and even shy in some
ways. He's also collaborative.''
 &HT;    In fact, Crystal says, De Niro _ most of whose films have been
heavy-duty dramas _ took to comedy quickly. In one scene, for
example, his character was supposed to confess to a sexual
dysfunction.
 &HT;    ``He has to tell me that his character can't get excited,''
Crystal recalls. ``I say, `In bed?' And Bob ad-libbed, `No, I can't
get excited about the big game against Michigan State.' He loved
that joke.
 &HT;    ``Afterward,'' he adds, ``De Niro turned to me and said, `Billy,
I should do a Neil Simon play. I love this comedy stuff.'''
 &HT;    If ``Analyze This'' is the hit which many predict, it will be a
welcome novelty to Crystal, whose career has been in the doldrums
in recent years.
 &HT;    After starting as a stand-up comic, the native of Long Beach,
N.Y., moved on to a ground-breaking role on ``Soap'' (1977-1981) as
the first gay character on a mainstream television series, a stint
on ``Saturday Night Live'' (1984-1985) and then hit movies
including ``When Harry Met Sally'' (1989) and ``City Slickers''
(1991).
 &HT;    Things have been less rosy lately, however. A 1994 sequel to
``City Slickers'' failed at the box office, as did other recent
vehicles including ``Mr. Saturday Night'' (1992), ``Forget Paris''
(1995) and ``My Giant'' (1998).
 &HT;    Crystal makes no bones about his recent dry spell.
 &HT;    ``Of course, I would be lying if I didn't say I had fleeting
thoughts of `What if they don't want to see me?''' he admits. ``In
many ways, when a movie fails, it's a rejection.
 &HT;    ``The great thing is that I've been able to work,'' the comedian
says. ``On the other hard, you do get scared. I kept saying, `Wow,
that was a good movie. Why didn't they go?' And then you understand
that you need to look at everyone's careers. People have ups and
downs.''
 &HT;    He shrugs.
 &HT;    ``The only solution is to do good work,'' he concludes. ``You
can't run scared. You can, however, wake up in the middle of the
night going, `What's happening?'''
 &HT;    Crystal was comforted by Janice, his wife of 28 years. Even now,
his eyes brighten when he mentions her name.
 &HT;    ``We met at summer camp, when we were counselors,'' he recalls.
``I remember all the details. It was the summer of 1966, and on our
first date _ on July 30 _ I took her to a Mets game. The problem
was, I didn't exactly have a driver's license. But I had a date who
said, `Sure I want to go,' So I drove. We started laughing that day
and have never stopped.''
 &HT;    Recently, Janice surprised her husband with an elaborate
50th-birthday party at Los Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel. The 400
guests included their daughters, 25-year-old Jennifer and
21-year-old Lindsey, while the gifts included a New York Yankees
championship ring from team owner George Steinbrenner and a
surprise visit from boxing champion Muhammad Ali.
 &HT;    ``Ali and I are old and dear friends,'' Crystal says. ``I did my
first TV appearance at an awards show for him. He liked me so much
that afterward he said, `You are my little brother.' Since then he
has shown up anytime I've called him.''
 &HT;    Crystal almost tears up when describing how, on the night of the
birthday party, Ali was tired and ill.
 &HT;    ``He was still there for me.''
 &HT;    Crystal himself can have the same kind of impact. At a recent
appearance on Rosie O'Donnell's talk show, Crystal says, a member
of the production staff slipped him a note.
 &HT;    ``He wrote that he was a gay teen when I did Jodie on `Soap,'
and the role meant something to him.'''
 &HT;    Crystal pauses.
 &HT;    ``That makes me feel so good,'' he says softly.
 &HT;    Not every form of recognition is so welcome, of course.
 &HT;    ``A few months ago, I was in a Las Vegas men's room,'' Crystal
says. ``All that was sticking out of the stall was my shoes. All of
a sudden, this guy on the outside shouts, `Billy Crystal?'
 &HT;    ``I look up and down. My pants are around my shoes, and this guy
is yelling my name and insisting he's my biggest fan. He even
shoved some paper under the stall and said, `Billy, could you sign
this?'''
 &HT;    Nonplused, Crystal obliged.
 &HT;    ``The guy looked at my shoes again and yelled, `By the way,
Billy, you look mah-velous.'''
 &HT;    ``Not right now I don't,''' Crystal replied.
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
