<HEADER>
A4257 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SARAH-MICHELLE-GELLAR     02-22 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARAH-MICHELLE-GELLAR-IN-CRUEL-INTENTIONS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INTENTIONAL' GROUNDING: SARAH MICHELLE GELLAR MOVES BEYOND
`BUFFY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Sarah Michelle Gellar in a scene from
``Cruel Intentions.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Buffy the Vampire Slayer may need her mouth washed out with soap
after this.
 &HT;    Sarah Michelle Gellar, television's erstwhile Buffy, curses like
a sailor in Roger Kumble's ``Cruel Intentions,'' and she says she
relished every scandalous, R-rated second of it.
 &HT;    ``When I sat down to meet with Roger Kumble, he asked, `So can
Buffy say these things?''' the speed-talking actress says
excitedly. ``My response was, `F--k, yeah!'''
 &HT;    Audiences used to Gellar kicking undead butt on ``Buffy'' are in
for quite a shock when ``Cruel Intentions,'' the latest reworking
of the classic French novel ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses,'' opens
nationwide on March 5.
 &HT;    Kumble updates the sordid tale, sets it on Manhattan's ritzy
Upper East Side and introduces spoiled seductress Kathryn (Gellar),
who challenges her gigolo stepbrother Sebastian (Ryan Phillippe) to
try to deflower the ultravirginal Annette (Reese Witherspoon). If
he wins, he gets Kathryn as well.
 &HT;    Gellar assumes the role played by Glenn Close in ``Dangerous
Liaisons'' (1987) and by Annette Bening in the little-seen
``Valmont'' (1988). Speaking by telephone from a Los Angeles hotel,
where she's promoting ``Cruel Intentions,'' Gellar claims that she
felt no pressure tackling a part so well executed by others. After
all, she had followed in the admittedly somewhat-less-imposing
footsteps of Kristy Swanson, who played Buffy in the 1992 film on
which the series is based.
 &HT;    ``I think that I'll be able to avoid most of the comparisons,
because `Cruel Intentions' is so different from `Dangerous
Liaisons,''' she says. ``I was actually more worried about
comparisons to the `Buffy' movie when I started the television
show.
 &HT;    ``Obviously, my `Cruel Intentions' character is different from
Glenn Close's in `Dangerous Liaisons,''' she adds. ``Our film is
not set in the 18th century, and we've got modern-day teen-agers in
New York City.
 &HT;    ``It was probably much harder for Annette Bening, because people
were really making comparisons between `Valmont' and `Dangerous
Liaisons.'''
 &HT;    Crafting ``Cruel Intentions'' for a younger audience practically
guarantees that ``Liaisons'' purists will attack the film as an
exercise in dumbing down a classic saga in order to make a quick
buck. However, Gellar urges naysayers to give the film a chance.
 &HT;    ``We're taking great material and reworking it, retelling the
story,'' she says forcefully. ``The wonderful thing about the
story, about the novel, is that it's like Shakespeare _ no matter
how many times you tell the story, it's fresh and there's something
new to tell. It's genius.
 &HT;    ``Our version'' _ Gellar slips into an evil cackle _ ``tells you
lots of things the previous versions didn't.
 &HT;    ``When you update material, it has to change,'' she adds. ``What
was a sin in the old days is not really a sin anymore. So we've put
in a few modern sins.''
 &HT;    ``Cruel Intentions'' follows Gellar's cutesy-sweet performance
in the romantic comedy ``Simply Irresistible.'' The actress played
the owner/chef of a failing Manhattan restaurant who became a
world-class cook and met her dream guy (Sean Patrick Flanery) after
an encounter with an supernatural crab salesman.
 &HT;    The film, released in early February, proved to be both
complicated and resistible, at least by audiences.
 &HT;    It was a rare career misstep for Gellar, however. ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer'' continues to thrive. Now in its third season on
the WB, the series ranks as one of television's most popular shows
among the viewers most desired by advertisers, 18-to-34-year-old
males and females.
 &HT;    Gellar plays Buffy, a young woman struggling to lead an ordinary
life, complete with friends, lovers and school, without neglecting
her responsibilities as The Chosen One, the Slayer who must kick,
crush, gut and burn a ceaseless parade of villains and fiends,
among them Angel (David Boreanaz), her
boyfriend-turned-demon-turned-good-guy-again.
 &HT;    ``I think the show is just now hitting its stride,'' Gellar
says. ``I think the biggest risk we took was when Buffy had sex
with Angel and he went bad ...
 &HT;    ``Angel's going bad was really the ultimate metaphor,'' she
says. ``It was the ultimate example of having sex with someone and
the guy doesn't call the next day.''
 &HT;    Boreanaz is about to leave the series to star in a spinoff,
``Angel,'' due to air next fall in the WB's post-``Buffy'' slot.
Gellar isn't worried about possible overkill, however, any more
than she frets about the current glut of supernatural shows _
``Charmed,'' for example _ stealing ``Buffy's'' thunder or eroding
its ratings.
 &HT;    ``If people are demanding more of this genre, then there's room
for more,'' Gellar says. ``There's only one `Buffy,' and no matter
how much is out there, there will still only be one `Buffy.'''
 &HT;    This 21-year-old clearly does not lack for confidence. But then,
she's already a veteran of nearly two decades of performing, having
made her first Burger King commercial as a tot. She later attended
New York's High School for the Performing Arts, and first tasted
fame with her role as Susan Lucci's daughter on the soap opera,
``All My Children.''
 &HT;    Gellar and Lucci reportedly never hit it off, and the
often-been-nominated-but-never-won Lucci was said to be less than
thrilled when Gellar won a 1994 Emmy Award for her work on
``Children.'' In any event, the younger woman left the show shortly
thereafter.
 &HT;    Gellar's other credits include a couple of stage plays and the
films ``Funny Farm'' (1988), ``I Know What You Did Last Summer''
(1997) and ``Scream 2'' (1997). The latter two films, combined with
her renown as Buffy, could easily pigeonhole her as a horror star,
but Gellar is determined to keep mixing it up, switching gears from
tough on ``Buffy'' to tender in ``Simply Irresistible'' to catty in
``Cruel Intentions.''
 &HT;    She also hopes that her fans will not confuse her with her
characters _ any of them.
 &HT;    ``People have to remember that I'm an actress and that none of
the characters is Sarah,'' she says. ``They're characters that I
play.
 &HT;    ``I don't ever have to remind myself of that,'' she adds. ``I
have a very, very clear understanding of who I am, and I'm none of
these people. I am Sarah.''
 &HT;    She protects that identity by drawing a sharp line between her
public and private lives, trying to keep perspective despite the
spotlight's glare.
 &HT;    ``There's a part of all this that makes it very hard to keep my
feet on the ground,'' she says. ``It's all a little surreal. But I
work hard to have a life, a private life separate from what I do.
That's how I keep my sanity.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
