<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Justice grinds slowly ahead in Jasper trial
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The Jasper County courtroom resembles a modest
Methodist church sanctuary, with stained-glass windows behind the
bench, an arched ceiling, and gold-tinted globe lights hanging
down, feathered by thin strands of cobwebs hanging out of reach of
whoever is in charge of keeping things clean.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of former judges line the walls. Wooden blinds mute
the sunlight of this springlike day. There are 20 benches in the
courtroom, with padded seat cushions that add to the churchlike
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   On the fourth day of testimony in the murder trial of James
King, there surprisingly is plenty of room inside the courtroom. A
metal detector is set up just inside the courthouse. DPS troopers
and sheriff's deputies patrol the lawn, and private security
officers sit inside the courtroom. Still, a friend and I walk
inside after passing inspection and find a seat with no difficulty
as eight ceiling fans whir lazily above the spectators.
</P>
<P>
   King is the first of three men to go on trial in the horrific
dragging death of James Byrd Jr., a murder that is being cast as
racially motivated. After months of national publicity and nearly
two weeks of jury selection, testimony finally began last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One side of the courthouse is lined with television station
trucks from the large Texas cities and CNN. A few dozen cameras are
set up on the lawn, and camera operators lounge outside, smoking
cigarettes and waiting for the day's testimony to end so they can
get a quick standup. A still photographer is rigging a camera to a
stair rail in order to shoot a dramatic shot of King from the
ground up as he leaves the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no circus here in what's being dubbed as the East
Texas Trial of the Century. Hardly anybody is milling around the
square. We found a parking place just off the square. Cops
outnumber hangers-on outside. Inside, the media seem to outnumber
other spectators, evidenced by notebooks and pens at the ready, as
well as a uniformly bad wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   I counted four sketch artists hard at work, two in front of us.
I watch, fascinated, as a courtroom scene comes to life with
charcoal during the two hours we watch the trial. First the
backdrop is sketched, the windows and globe lights, the simple
bench from which Judge Joe Bob Golden presides with no robe and
little pomp. He doesn't bother to make anyone stand when he returns
from recess, just gets things going again. During a break, he
ambles to the back of the courtroom and visits with a couple of
folks.
</P>
<P>
   As I watch, the artist draws a witness, then the judge, and a
few members of the jury. Soon, a courtroom scene develops on paper.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, John William King, is dressed like a yuppie, in a
dark-green plaid shirt and khakis, the long sleeves hiding the
absurd collection of tattoos that have marked him in earlier
photographs. He looks impossibly young and clean-cut to be accused
of such evil, to already be a convicted felon who's served prison
time.
</P>
<P>
   His father is seated in a wheelchair next to the first row
behind the defense table, his nostrils hooked to an oxygen bottle.
After the first afternoon break, he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   To the right of the defense table is a large color map, perhaps
10 feet in length. It shows the 3.08-mile route of James Byrd's
final moments, from the initial scuffle to where his headless torso
was found.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the prosecution's table sit members of the Byrd family. A
few come around and admire the work of the sketch artists during
the break.
</P>
<P>
   The jury seems attentive, though the testimony this afternoon is
almost breathtakingly dull: An FBI forensic examiner and an expert
in tire treads and footprints testify that tracks at the murder
scene match those of the truck believed used in Byrd's dragging
death, and sandals taken from King's apartment. Compared to
previous days' testimony, today's drags on, simply continuing to
build the prosecution's case with little drama, just dry scientific
conclusions from the physical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The tires in question are lined up against the rail behind the
defense table.
</P>
<P>
   The sandals came from Pay-Less.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Guy James Gray is methodical, not flashy or
histrionic. Neither is the defense team for King. In the two hours
I watched, not a single objection was raised. It will be
interesting to see exactly what the defense will be in this case.
</P>
<P>
   As we leave, we run into Sheriff Billy Rowles and Walter
Diggles, executive director for the Deep East Texas Council of
Governments. They're widely credited for herculean efforts in
keeping this racially charged incident from destroying their town.
They both look weary as they talk about dealing with the New Black
Panther Party, which showed up earlier in the week looking for a
little TV time. In the past months, the KKK has also weighed in,
unwelcome, of course. Rowles chats a while, spits some tobacco
juice into a trash can and heads back outside after a few moments.
Like most Jasper residents, they're ready for this ordeal to end,
for justice to be done, and for life to get back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Life seems pretty normal in Jasper, actually. I notice as we
pull out of town that a motel parking lot is full, with most of the
spaces taken up by pickups pulling large bass boats. There's
probably a fishing tournament going on this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, inside the Jasper County courthouse, justice slowly
grinds ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
