A4259 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTRESS-KIMBERLY-ELIS     02-22 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTRESS-KIMBERLY-ELISE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD OBSERVER: KIMBERLY ELISE IS TAKING NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Kimberly Elise with Oprah Winfrey in a
scene from ``Beloved.'' 
 By JON KRAMPNER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    At the Hollywood Hills Coffee Shop, a Los Angeles site famous as
a stomping ground for young film stars, Kimberly Elise is having
Sunday brunch when she spots someone.
 &HT;    ``Is that Jennifer Love Hewitt?'' she asks, indicating a young
woman with sunglasses on her head near the cash register.
 &HT;    It's hard to tell if the young woman in question is the star of
``Party of Five'' and the ``I Know What You Did Last Summer''
teen-slasher films. And even if she is, she may be asking someone,
``Is that Kimberly Elise?''
 &HT;    The 31-year-old Elise _ full name: Kimberly Elise Trammel Oldham
_ is an up-and-coming star in her own right. She recently played
Oprah Winfrey's daughter in ``Beloved'' (1998), in a performance
which had been widely touted for a Best Supporting Actress Oscar,
though she ultimately wasn't nominated.
 &HT;    The young actress had previously caught critics' eyes in ``Set
It Off'' (1996) as an inner-city cleaning lady who joins a gang of
bank robbers. She's also been seen in ``The Ditchdigger's
Daughters'' on cable television.
 &HT;    Thoughtful and unaffected by her newfound celebrity, Elise has
large brown eyes and laughs easily and often. She is dressed all in
black _ ``it's slimming,'' she says, although she doesn't appear to
need much help _ and is relaxed and poised even when, as on this
occasion, she is breast-feeding her month-old daughter at a corner
table of the coffee shop.
 &HT;    This poise and lack of pretense is impressive in someone who's
been getting the kind of press notices Elise has. Many reviewers
judged that her performance outshone that of Winfrey and of Thandie
Newton as the title character.
 &HT;    ``Her quiet but forceful performance is the film's great
revelation,'' a Newsweek review said. ``Elise is astonishing as
Denver: Her transformation from outcast to independent woman gives
the movie its defining arc.''
 &HT;    Although Elise has had a life vastly different from that of
Denver, the child of a poverty-stricken former slave whose
long-dead sister unexpectedly reappears, she still identifies with
her, particularly her eventual decision to leave the security of
the yard where she's grown up.
 &HT;    ``I relate to my character in that there was a difficult
adolescence,'' the actress says. ``My life wasn't as profound as
hers, but I had a difficult adolescence.''
 &HT;    Elise says she was quiet and solitary as a teen, growing up in
the Minneapolis suburb of Wayzata. She had big plans for the
future, and was eager to get there.
 &HT;    ``It wasn't until I got out of the bubble of Wayzata and home
and Minnesota that I was able to blossom,'' she says. ``When I was
able to leave the yard, so to speak.''
 &HT;    Elise is one of four children of a business executive and a
third-grade teacher. Although her acting talent was apparent early,
she remembers having trouble getting parts in class plays because,
as one of only a few black children in her school, she looked so
different from everyone else.
 &HT;    Today the actress finds her race to be less of an obstacle, even
in frequently racially troubled Los Angeles, where she now lives
with her husband, photographer Maurice Oldham, and their daughters
Ajableu and Jaelarose. It's sexism that rouses her ire.
 &HT;    ``Maybe it's an industry thing, but you really have to fight for
your respect as a woman in this town,'' she says. ``And as a black
actress, there's the hurdle of having to fight for people to see
beyond your color.''
 &HT;    As committed as she's always been to acting, Elise has never
taken an acting class. At the University of Minnesota in
Minneapolis she was a speech major, though she did help to pay for
college by appearing in a commercial for Wendy's.
 &HT;    ``I have this fear of public speaking, which is weird, but I
do,'' she says. ``I just clam up. So I decided to face it head on.
I could always act, hide behind a character, but to be Kimberly in
front of groups of people was very scary to me. So it was a lot of
speech classes.''
 &HT;    She avoided acting classes, Elise says, because she wanted to
retain a naturalness to her style.
 &HT;    ``They work great for some people,'' she says. ``But I always
wanted my work to be free-spirited, organic and natural and to not
rely on a process or system.''
 &HT;    Instead, she's pursued a lifetime of independent study. Even at
college, she spent hours carefully watching the people around her,
observing their gestures and making mental notes.
 &HT;    ``But it's not like I was looking for bizarre or strange
people,'' she says. ``It's the everyday people.''
 &HT;    For example, take the seemingly mundane activity of standing in
line.
 &HT;    ``There's an `acting' waiting in line and there's a sincere
waiting in line,'' she says. ``How do you honestly wait in line?
You don't look at your watch, tap your foot and this and that. When
you're really waiting in line, you don't do all those things.''
 &HT;    She's continued her studies in Los Angeles, where she frequently
rides the bus _ rare for car-owning Angelenos, especially
celebrities _ and goes to the park, the library or simply out for a
walk.
 &HT;    ``I was dreading the release of `Beloved,' because it would sort
of blow my cover, and to a degree, it has,'' she says, laughing.
``It's been sort of frustrating, because life is my school. I just
live and observe. People change when they know you and recognize
you _ I'm not as anonymous.''
 &HT;    When she first came to Los Angeles, Elise certainly had that
anonymity. She was not even there as an actress _ her student-made
short film, ``The Joy of Mama's Recall,'' earned her a director's
fellowship to the American Film Institute, where she made another
film, ``The Race.''
 &HT;    Since breaking through as an actress Elise has done no
directing, but she says it is helpful to have that arrow in her
quiver.
 &HT;    ``I'll never move away from being an actor,'' she says. ``But
when the right opportunity comes, I'll direct. I think it's a
necessity, actually, as a black actress, to be as much of a creator
as you can be and not wait on people to create for you.''
 &HT;    Shortly after leaving AFI Elise began to land acting roles in
Hollywood, but she doesn't see herself as an overnight success.
 &HT;    ``It doesn't seem quick to me,'' she says. ``It seems quick to
other people, but I've known it as my destiny since I was very
young, and it's been years of learning, a long process.''
 &HT;    The actress doesn't have her next part lined up yet, but is
quick to say that she won't be taking any time off because of the
birth of her daughter.
 &HT;    ``Not deliberately,'' she says, smiling. ``I'll work when I find
what I want to do. If I found something this week, I'd start
working this week. And if I don't find anything for six months,
it's six months. The baby is real portable, and as long as she's
close to me, she's happy.''
 &HT;    It helps that her husband has a flexible schedule, and can come
along with Elise and their girls to whatever movie set she visits.
It's a particularly satisfying resolution to the classic
family-vs.-career conflict.
 &HT;    ``Family comes first, and that makes every decision easier,''
the actress says. ``My husband and children come with me. We all
pack up and go wherever we're going, and have a ball living out of
a hotel for three months.''
 c.1999 Jon Krampner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jon Krampner, author of ``The Man in the Shadows: Fred Coe and
the Golden Age of Television'' (Rutgers University Press, 1997), is
a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
