<HEADER>
A4267 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-CABLE23-COX     02-22 2109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CABLE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Snakes behind the television set
 &HT;    WITH ART on Cox Server
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The front of the average home entertainment
system is elegant black and silver surfaces with lighted indicators
and buttons. The front view says ``high-tech efficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   But pull that sucker away from the wall and the intimidating
tangle of wires behind the system says ``Death Valley rattlesnake
pit.''
</P>
<P>
   You have no reason to despair, however. If you grab the wires
one at a time and trace where they begin and end, you'll find their
purposes are fairly obvious.
</P>
<P>
   So take a deep, calming breath to prepare yourself. You're about
to master the connections that bring cable television into your
home.
</P>
<P>
   If you can understand what you're doing and you have the proper
equipment, you should be able to do what most cable customers have
given up on: taping one program while watching another.
</P>
<P>
   But that's advanced stuff. Let's start with the basics.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE 101
</P>
<P>
   Think of your cable service and your television set as a food
delivery system. The cable system brings program signals, which are
basically recipes, into your home. The television set uses the
program signals to assemble programs in the way an automated
kitchen might use recipes to assemble meals.
</P>
<P>
   The cable signal that enters your home has dozens of program
signals bundled together like recipes in a box. You need a tuner to
select one program signal from the many available signals, and to
send that signal to the television to be assembled.
</P>
<P>
   This is where people tend to get confused. Your television has a
tuner. Your cable service box has a tuner. Your videocassette
recorder has a tuner. But most people use only one tuner at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Most people only use the tuner on their cable service box. The
cable service wire comes into the house carrying its dozens of
program signals and that wire is connected directly to the cable
service box.
</P>
<P>
   The tuner in the cable service box selects one program signal
and sends it on to the television and to the videocassette recorder
if you have one.
</P>
<P>
   But in this set-up, only one program signal reaches the
television and the VCR. The tuners in the television and the VCR
don't have a chance to select from the dozens of program signals
the original cable wire brought into the house.
</P>
<P>
   The key to getting the most out of your cable service is giving
more than one of your tuners a chance to pick a program signal to
record or view.
</P>
<P>
   WITHOUT A CABLE BOX
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Hayden, technical supervisor for TCI Cablevision, said
almost all TCI customers use a cable service box. In TCI's case,
the box is called a digital consumer terminal, or DCT for short.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want a cable service box, you can take the cable
service wire as it enters the house and plug it directly into the
input connection on a cable-ready television. The cable wire is a
coaxial cable, and it fits onto the television's coaxial cable
input port. The port will be marked something like ``input from
cable or antenna.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cable-ready'' means the tuner built into the television is
capable of choosing from among the dozens of program signals
available on the cable wire.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden pointed out, however, that even cable-ready televisions
aren't able to tune into premium channels. The cable company
encodes the premium channel signals in such a way that only their
cable service box can decipher them.
</P>
<P>
   Also, not all cable-ready tuners are created equal, Hayden said.
Some older cable ready sets are capable of tuning into programs
transmitted at a frequency of up to about 350 megahertz. If your
cable service transmits signals on frequencies beyond your
television tuner's capabilities, you won't be able to watch all the
channels included in the basic service without a cable service box.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to add a VCR to a set-up without a cable box. And it's
easy with this set-up to watch one program while taping another.
</P>
<P>
   Take the main cable wire where it enters the house and screw it
into the input port on your VCR.
</P>
<P>
   Near the input port you'll find a second port marked something
like ``out to TV.'' Run a length of coaxial cable from the output
port on the VCR to the input port on the television.
</P>
<P>
   To watch a program on television in this set-up, you turn the
VCR off and use the tuner on the television to select your program.
</P>
<P>
   When you're watching a recorded program you don't need the tuner
on your television. To play a tape, you push the play button and
the VCR ``reads'' a recorded program signal from a videotape. The
signal on the tape is the same kind of program signal that is found
bundled with other signals on the wire connecting your home to a
cable company.
</P>
<P>
   As you play a tape, there will only be one program signal on the
wire coming from the VCR, so you simply turn the television tuner
to channel 3. Channel 3 is the setting you use to receive a single
signal from another device such as a VCR or a cable service box.
</P>
<P>
   Every videocassette recorder has a TV/VCR switch of some kind.
When you are using the VCR to send a signal to the television, this
switch should be set to VCR.
</P>
<P>
   When you want the television tuner to select a signal from the
cable wire, the TV/VCR switch should be set to TV. That lets the
original cable signal containing its dozens of program signals to
reach the television's tuner.
</P>
<P>
   To record a program and watch the same program, you'll use the
tuner on your VCR to select one signal from the program signals
available on the cable wire. Set the TV/VCR switch to VCR so the
VCR sends the signal it has selected on to the television. Tune the
television to channel 3.
</P>
<P>
   To record one program and watch another, you have to use both
your tuners.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the tuner on the VCR to the channel you wish to record.
Turning the VCR tuner to channel 7, for example, tells the
recording system this is the signal you want to record. Push the
record button at the time the program you are recording is to
start.
</P>
<P>
   Now set the TV/VCR switch to TV. If the switch is on VCR, the
VCR will send the channel 7 program signal along the wire to the
television, and that's not what you want.
</P>
<P>
   With the TV/VCR switch on TV, all the signals available on the
cable wire reach the television, and you can use the television
tuner to pick the show you want to watch.
</P>
<P>
   STRAIGHT LINE SET-UPS
</P>
<P>
   The main drawback to having cable service without a cable
service box is that you don't have access to all the cable extras
like premium channels, pay-per-view programs, music services and so
on. So most cable customers use a cable service box.
</P>
<P>
   And most cable service box users hook their components together
in a straight line _ the cable wire from outside the house goes to
the input jack on the cable service box, a line goes from the
output port on the cable service box to the input jack on the
television.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a videocasette recorder it is placed between the
cable service box and the television. In other words, the line
leading from the cable service box goes to the input port on the
VCR, and another wire goes from the output port on the VCR to the
input port on the television.
</P>
<P>
   This arrangement is easy to use, but it's not flexible. It uses
only one tuner, the one in the cable service box. It doesn't allow
you to watch one program while taping another.
</P>
<P>
   In a straight line set-up the television and videocassette
recorder are always tuned to channel 3.
</P>
<P>
   To record a program, you use the tuner in the cable service box
to pick a program. You set the VCR to channel 3 and push the record
button when the program you want to record starts.
</P>
<P>
   To play a recording, simply push play. The TV/VCR switch will
automatically set itself to VCR if it isn't already set that way.
</P>
<P>
   The VCR sends its signal to the output port, and it travels
along the cable wire connecting the VCR to the television's input
port. Your television, set to channel 3, receives the signal and
uses it to assemble the program that is recorded on the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   This system is generally goof-proof, but you have to remember to
leave both your VCR and television set on channel 3. That may mean
you have to reset them after a power outage so they're on the right
channel.
</P>
<P>
   SPLITTING THE SIGNAL
</P>
<P>
   You can have all the frills and premium programs associated with
having a cable service box and the flexibility of using your
television tuner by splitting the cable signal entering your house
into two streams.
</P>
<P>
   All you'll need are a two-way signal spitter, a few short
lengths of coaxial cable wire and an A/B switch. All these items
are available at electronic stores and most discount stores, and
you can get everything you need for about $30. Your cable company
may even have the stuff in stock and can install them for you.
</P>
<P>
   If you're buying your own equipment, avoid the cheapest
equipment on the rack. Gold-plated connections and shielded cables
deliver the best picture quality with the fewest problems.
</P>
<P>
   Start by connecting the main cable wire coming into your house
to the input port of a two-way signal splitter. You may see
amplified splitters in electronic stores, but you want an
unamplified splitter for this job. It's a simple device with one
input port on one side and two output ports on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Run a line from one output port on the splitter to the input
port on the cable box. Run a line from the cable box output port to
the input port on your VCR. Run a line from the VCR output port to
the input port marked A on the A/B switch. We'll explain the A/B
switch in a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Now go back to the two-way signal splitter. Screw a coaxial
cable cable onto the empty output port on the splitter. Connect the
other end of that line to the B input port on the A/B switch.
</P>
<P>
   Connect the last coaxial cable connector to the port on the A/B
switch that is marked ``out to TV.'' Naturally the other end of
that line is screwed onto the input port on the television.
</P>
<P>
   An A/B switch, like the two-way splitter, is a simple device. It
has two input ports, one marked A and one marked B. It has one
output port linking it to the television.
</P>
<P>
   It also has switches or buttons marked A and B. Push the A
button and the signal passing through the cable service box and
then through the VCR reaches the television.
</P>
<P>
   In the A position, this set-up functions exactly like the
straight-line set-up described earlier: the signal from the cable
company goes into the cable box, and the cable box is used to
select a program. That program is sent along to the VCR and to the
television.
</P>
<P>
   Push the B button, however, and the television is getting the
original signal from the cable company with its dozens of programs
included.
</P>
<P>
   In the B position, you can use the tuner in the television to
select the program you'd like to see. Remember, though, that the
tuner on your cable-ready television will not be able to decipher
encoded premium channels.
</P>
<P>
   While you're using your television to select a program from the
B signal stream, you can use the tuner in the cable service box to
tune in a channel on the A signal stream. Since the VCR gets its
signal from the cable service box, you can record the program on
the A signal stream while watching something on the B signal stream
on the television.
</P>
<P>
   Most people using a two-way splitter put their VCR on the same
stream as the cable service box so they'll be able to record
premium channels and pay-per-view events.
</P>
<P>
   When you're finished recording, you can push the A button on the
A/B switch and turn your television back to channel 3. Now you're
ready to watch the recording you have just made or watch the
premium channels that only your cable service box can tune in.
</P>
<P>
   If you find all this too confusing, your cable company should be
willing and able to go over your options with you.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden said TCI is starting to distribute a new type of cable
service box that has a built-in system that will allow customers to
watch one program and record another. He said customers interested
in the new box, called the DCT 2000, should call to inquire about
replacing their current boxes free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   While you're talking to your cable company about video hook-ups,
you should also ask about using RCA-style plugs in your home
theater set-up.
</P>
<P>
   The red, white and yellow coded plugs can link your cable box
directly to your stereo system and possibly improve your system's
sound performance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
