<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Device sends TV sound to headphones
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A New York company is marketing a set of
headphones that promise not only high performance but marital bliss
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Unisar Inc. of New York City, the makers of the TV Listener
Infrared Cordless TV Headset System, have trademarked the slogan
``The Marriage Saver'' because they think the product can settle
disputes within families.
</P>
<P>
   The TV Listener allows one person to listen to television or
music without disturbing a sleeping partner, for instance. And it
lets a person with hearing problems listen at high volume up while
other people in the room listen at normal levels.
</P>
<P>
   The TV Listener comes in two parts. A transmitter sits on top of
the television and is connected to the set's audio output port. The
system comes with a selection of adapters to connect to differing
output ports, and It has a microphone attachment for sets without
an output port. The transmitter can also be attached to other sound
equipment such as a stereo system.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the system is a pair of headphones. The
headset weighs only a few ounces and has volume controls.
</P>
<P>
   The transmitter sends a signal to the headset using infrared
light like a remote control. Unisar says the infrared system
delivers better stereo sound quality than radio transmission.
</P>
<P>
   The TV Listener, which won an innovation award at this year's
International Consumer Electronics Show, is not yet widely
available through retail stores. It sells for $59.99 by phone at
(800) 233-1196, or it can be ordered from the Unisar Web site at
unisar.com
</P>
<P>
   Also available on the Web site are Unisar devices that allow
expectant parents to listen to the sounds made by their unborn
children in the womb.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
