<HEADER>
A4269 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNOBUDDY23-COX     02-22 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fixes may be needed, but your PC won't self-destruct Jan. 1
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seldom do I return to a specific topic within a few weeks of
writing about it. After all, my beat _ technology _ is so broad
that it covers everything from Nintendo games to computers to HDTV
to ham radio. If it has batteries, computes or makes beeping sounds
from time to time, I have probably written about it.
</P>
<P>
   But e-mail from a concerned (and intelligent) reader guides me
to return to the Year 2000 problem. Now, this is a subject that has
received enough ink to float a battleship. But there are still
smart people out there _ like the reader who sent me the e-mail _
who are mixed up about the impact of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what happened. Last week, I wrote a column that treated
the question of whether to replace an older PC. The reader's e-mail
said he was irritated because I had failed to mention the most
serious reason to replace an old PC. He said these older machines
are doomed to stop working in just a few months because of the Y2K
problem and need to be replaced now.
</P>
<P>
   That just isn't so. And there's no criticism of the reader in
that. The criticism is aimed at myself and at others who write
about computers. We just haven't done a good enough job when
intelligent people who read the newspaper still have that fear.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a PC, even an old one, the Year 2000 problem will
not magically turn the PC into a useless collection of chips,
capacitors and resistors. Unless you spill a Mountain Dew into the
PC, there will be no sizzling sound, no smoke, no strange wheezing
noise on Jan. 1, 2000. The hardware will survive.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible _ maybe even likely _ that an old PC and old
software for it will have some problems. For one thing, most
computer clock hardware, even on fairly recent machines, isn't
completely Y2K-compliant. For another, the BIOS chip (the chip that
keeps track of basic information such as the address and type of
your hard disk, the time and date, etc.) is almost certain to have
problems. And if your software is the same age as the computer,
some spreadsheet and money management programs are likely to have
problems as well.
</P>
<P>
   But none of these problems is likely to cripple your computer.
You may have to manually reset the date after Jan. 1, 2000 (and
with very old computers, you may have to buy a program that will
reset the date each time you turn on the computer). You may need to
replace some of the financial and spreadsheet software.
</P>
<P>
   But _ and I can tell you this without worrying that I am wrong,
since I always double- and triple-check my thinking on things like
this with real-world Y2K experts _ your PC will still be able to
process letters, play games, check e-mail, and _ with new software
_ balance your budget.
</P>
<P>
   What I'm saying is that your old computer may be out of date and
need replacing, but Y2K problems shouldn't be the reason. Because
here's the kicker: Even some new Pentium-class machines have clocks
and BIOS chips that won't properly handle the change in dates. The
good news, for owners of new and old machines, is that there are
resources to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some things you can do. First, worry about your
software, especially software that uses dates. Check with the
manufacturer's Web site to see if there is an update to fix Y2K
problems. If not, replace the software.
</P>
<P>
   Second, worry about your operating system. Even Windows 95 and
Windows 98 are not totally compliant. Go to the Microsoft Web site
at http://www.microsoft.com/technet/year2k/ and find out which
updates you need. These updates are free for the downloading.
</P>
<P>
   Third, don't check to see if your PC clock or BIOS chip is
faulty by setting the date ahead on your computer. You'll read this
advice elsewhere, but don't follow it. You take a chance of making
a mess of the programs you have. Instead, go to this Web site
(http://www.nstl.com/html/nstly2k.html) and download the software
mentioned there. It'll check your clock and BIOS chip without
hurting anything.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, even for clocks and BIOS chips that can't be replaced,
there are programs available commercially (Norton, the manufacturer
of the well-known utility programs makes one) that will manually
reset the time and date each time you turn the computer on.
</P>
<P>
   So don't give up. That old computer of yours will probably die
of natural causes before the Y2K problem kills it.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
