<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4270 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCHER23-COX     02-22 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCHER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL behavior rules tough to pin down
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   America Online, the nation's largest online service, has had its
virtual wrist slapped time and time again for censoring its highly
popular message boards and chat rooms. A letter-writing campaign is
now under way from members who want to be able to send their own
newsletters to AOL subscribers but are finding themselves violating
the company's legendary ``terms of service.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is convenient to blame AOL for everything from the hole
in the ozone to the end of free speech on the Net, it's important
to remember that with roughly 20 million users, somebody is bound
to be offended by the comments of someone else. As Michael
Bloomberg, founder and CEO of Bloomberg News, said recently, ``You
could stand on a street corner handing out thousand-dollar bills
and you're bound to find somebody who's going to complain.''
</P>
<P>
   So, AOL finds itself caught between two very unappealing
options: vigorous enforcement of its community rules and
guidelines, or total anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   I know this better than most AOL members. Once, I was in the
prickly position of trying to enforce those regulations as a chat
room co-host.
</P>
<P>
   The prime directive for me and the wise, witty co-hosts I was
paired off with each week was simple: Enforce AOL's policies with
vigilance but without stomping on the rights of members to talk
about whatever they wanted to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   For the first few months, hosting was easy. I sat in front of my
home PC once, maybe twice a week, greeting members as they came
into the room, announcing what the current topic was and gently
reminding people that typing with all capital letters was impolite,
hard to read and looked like shouting _ all of which are true,
according to accepted rules of Netiquitte.
</P>
<P>
   Things went along like this until ``that woman, Miss Lewinsky''
became big news last January. Then my co-hosts and I and seemed to
be surrounded by vocal representatives from both the far right and
the far left.
</P>
<P>
   In the year that followed, I heard more tasteless jokes about
Monica Lewinsky than I care to remember or recount.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people were fond of typing ``Impeach Clinton'' over and
over again in big letters.
</P>
<P>
   An equal amount of people were found of typing ``Impeach Starr''
in equally large letters.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the women who identified themselves simply as
``wives and mothers'' who suggested we stop talking about the
scandal altogether out of respect for Hillary and Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a group who kept pleading with me to do something
to stop the online sloganeering so the people who really did want
to talk politics could talk politics.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this point that being an AOL chat host went from being
an amusing diversion to a weekly crisis of conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Where does an AOL member's right to say whatever they like
interfere with the rest of the online community? At what point do
you take steps to warn or punish someone who goes beyond anything
resembling intelligent conversation or good taste?
</P>
<P>
   I thought I knew where the line was one night last spring when
yet another wise guy decided to share the same tired jokes the chat
room regulars and I had heard night after night for months. Just as
I was about to take the first step toward warning the joke teller
to re-read the terms of service, my chat co-host sent me an instant
message:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ha,'' she wrote, ``That's one of the better ones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But isn't he violating the TOS?'' I typed back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, maybe,'' she conceded. ``But how can you not with a
topic like this?''
</P>
<P>
   If it had been up to me, I would have issued an ``OSW,'' or
on-screen warning, to the joke teller, because in my opinion he had
violated AOL's rule prohibiting ``abusive and disruptive
language.'' However, my co-host saw it as a harmless joke related
to the steamy subject matter. We chose not to take official action
against the joke teller, but some members in the room took action
of their own. They told him to knock it off. And it worked.
</P>
<P>
   True, some people do need to be formally warned. Some are truly
vulgar, hateful or doing things that are clearly illegal. However,
most just need to know what rules the community has set for itself,
whether it's a chat about ``Dawson's Creek'' or international
relations.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, that's community: People setting their own
standards of acceptable behavior, without waiting for the long arm
of AOL to do if for them.
</P>
<P>
   Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
