A4276 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIFE-COX     02-22 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tough sentencing laws face Florida legislators
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ Education and tax cuts can wait _ Florida
legislators will open the 1999 session next week with their
toughest sentencing legislation since the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   And it's backed by an unusual coalition of gun control advocates
and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Two ideas borrowed from California are expected to pass:
``10-20-Life'' and ``Three Strikes You're Out.'' They provide
mandatory sentences for certain offenses, such as 25 years to life
for injuring someone with a gun in the course of a crime, or life
in prison for committing a third, violent felony.
</P>
<P>
   The only no votes on Three Strikes in the House Corrections
Committee last week came from the two black members, who complained
that the law would disproportionately hurt black men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have the goal of filling all the prison beds that we
have?'' asked Rep. Frederica Wilson, a freshman Democrat from
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Answered sponsor Rep. Victor Crist, R-Temple Terrace, ``It's a
crime when we have beds available to have violent criminals on the
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   In fine print, legislative staff research warns it is impossible
to prove that mandatory sentences deter crime, and adds that the
cost of keeping more people in prison longer _ modest for the first
few years _ could mushroom later.
</P>
<P>
   None of that is likely to knock 10-20-Life out of a chance to be
the first legislation to pass this session and land on the desk of
Gov. Jeb Bush. There is no doubt Bush will sign _ he made it a
prominent part of his 1998 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-20-Life plan requires a minimum sentence of 10 years if a
criminal commits a crime with a gun in his possession, 20 years if
he uses it, and 25 to life if he injures someone with it. Current
law requires a three-year minimum sentence, or eight years for an
automatic weapon.
</P>
<P>
   In committee meetings, there has been little opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some members have questions, but nobody wants to be
labeled soft on crime,'' said Senate Democratic leader Buddy Dyer.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates agree. ``This 10-20-life is really a tough
punishment and our organization always has been a proponent for
tough punishment,'' Joe Sudbay, director of state legislation for
Handgun Control told The Associated Press. The group is run by
Sarah Brady and her husband, Jim, who was seriously wounded in the
1981 assassination attempt on then-President Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate analysts estimate that it will cost $32 million
to $35 million by 2005 if the state prison system has to build new
beds for 10-20-Life, and another $8 million or so for Three
Strikes. Some 4,500 beds are open now. But no one is projecting
costs beyond a half-dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we need to think about is the long-term health-care
costs of keeping that many people that long,'' Dyer said. ``Is
someone still dangerous at 65? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally law-abiding gun owners might find themselves in for
long prison terms for relatively modest offenses because they had a
holstered gun with them for protection, some have suggested. Others
are concerned that mandatory sentences in general prevent judges
from exercising discretion and taking the circumstances of each
case into account.
</P>
<P>
   Crist cited dramatic reductions in crime in California as
evidence the laws have been effective there. He looked at Fresno,
home of the activist who championed both laws, Mike Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Assaults with firearms were down 38.6 percent in Fresno in the
year since 10-20-Life went into effect on Jan. 1, 1998. Gun murders
were down 43.2 percent, robberies 44.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But a longer look makes clear such crimes have been falling for
several years. Gun assaults, for instance, actually dropped more in
the year before the law, 45 percent, than afterward, 38.6 percent.
Fresno police acknowledge other factors, such as the fact they put
more police on the street.
</P>
<P>
   The same logic could be used to say that because Florida's crime
rate is falling, not having 10-20-Life or Three Strikes must be the
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is confident this bill will have a positive impact and will
be effective,'' said spokesman Cory Tilley.
</P>
<P>
   Crist said, ``When we get the word out to violent felons that
using a gun will put them in prison for at least a decade and maybe
a lifetime, our declining crime rates will drop even further.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Three-Strike Violent Felony Offender Act,'' which cleared
its second committee Wednesday in the Florida House, would force
judges to give stiff sentences to criminals committing their third
violent felony within five years of either committing their second
or getting out of prison from committing their second. Drug dealers
would also face minimum mandatory prison sentences again.
</P>
<P>
   Three Strikes is on a bit slower track, but 10-20-Life is the
first substantive legislation scheduled to reach the House floor
March 4, after a few revisions and housekeeping matters.
</P>
<P>
   It's a similar story in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect it to move early,'' said a spokeswoman for Senate
President Toni Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Shirish Date contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Elmore and Date write for the Palm Beach Post
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
