<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-PTECH 0219 -- Back in the Dark Ages before home
computers, anyone preparing his income tax returns had to sit down
with pencil, paper and a calculator and shuffle through a box of
records for hours to get the job done. Now that person can sit down
in front of his computer screen and accomplish the same thing.
(Cummings, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TECH TOOLS -- A talking parrott on your PC? Every so often an
idea of such surpassing brilliance arrives via e-mail that I cannot
but share it with you. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS -- FamilyPC magazine, in its March 1999 issue, takes
a look at the issue of brand names as related to technology
products. It attempts to answer this question: When it comes to
computers, is label-consciousness anything more than simple vanity?
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY -- If you have plenty of money and want a new
computer, then there are good reasons for buying one. But if you
are one of those people who have to count pennies, and who have to
make decisions between buying a new computer and going to New
Orleans on vacation, or paying the mortgage, then don't feel blue
or compelled to buy just because you have this vague notion that
you need more. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the week of Feb. 19. The
layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CABLE _ The front of the average home entertainment system
is elegant black and silver surfaces with lighted indicators and
buttons. The front view says ``high-tech efficiency.'' But pull
that sucker away from the wall and the intimidating tangle of wires
behind the system says ``Death Valley rattlesnake pit.''
</P>
<P>
   So take a deep, calming breath to prepare yourself. You're about
to master the connections that bring cable television into your
home, make them neater and regain some functions your VCR lost when
you got cable. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) 55. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-LISTEN _ A New York company is marketing a set of
headphones that promise not only high performance but marital bliss
as well. The TV Listener allows one person to listen to television
or music without disturbing a sleeping partner, for instance. And
it lets a person with hearing problems listen at high volume while
other people in the room listen at noral levels. (Cummings, Dayton
Daily News) 6. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-INVESTING _One of the good things about the Internet is
that it cuts out the middleman. So far, that's meant less-expensive
books and CDs and, in some cases, cheaper stock buying. If you're
buying a book, most of the time losing the middleman is a fairly
innocuous omission, maybe saving you some small talk at the cash
register. But in a stock transaction, it could cost you money.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Seldom do I return to a specific topic within a few
weeks of writing about it. After all, my beat _ technology _ is so
broad that it covers everything from Nintendo games to computers to
HDTV to ham radio. If it has batteries, computes or makes beeping
sounds from time to time, I have probably written about it.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ For those who think the generation gap is marked in
distance with PCs, with the young on one side of the chasm and
older folks on the other, take a look at a book from Intel that
hopes to bridge that gap. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCHER _ America Online, the nation's largest online
service, has had its virtual wrist slapped time and time again for
censoring its highly popular message boards and chat rooms. A
letter-writing campaign is now under way from members who want to
be able to send their own newsletters to AOL subscribers but are
finding themselves violating the company's legendary ``terms of
service.'' (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ The World Wide Web is actually a useful place these
days. If you need demographic information from Des Moines, the
average rainfall for Medford, Ore., or a list of the books written
by Winston Churchill, you can find it with a few clicks of a mouse
button. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ The next ``Star Wars'' movie will be released
Memorial Day, and the Web is already buzzing with rumors about the
film. Read about the latest rumors and where you can find them in
the February issue of Yahoo! Internet Life. There's gossip about
who will play the lead roles, about the story line and about other
movies to come in the ``Star War'' series.. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ You know it must be tax time when Intuit releases
its latest version of MacInTax. This year's update is a keeper.
Intuit has made great strides in improving MacInTax's ease of use.
The program is both easier to navigate and configure.. (Haddad ,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ For those who think the generation gap is marked
in distance with PCs, with the young on one side of the chasm and
older folks on the other, take a look at a book from Intel that
hopes to bridge that gap. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMET-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   GRAMMYS-PREDICT _ A category-by-category look at the Grammy
nominees with predictions of winners. (Corcoran, Austin
American-Statesman). 50.
</P>
<P>
   IMPRESSIONIST-SHOW _ ATLANTA _ Art review. Two important new
shows opening Feb. 23 at the High. ``Impressionism, Paintings
Collected by European Museums'' is the largest collection of
impressionism ever show in the southeast. More than 60 paintings by
such artists as Monet, Renoir, Cezanne, Degas, Manet and van Gogh.
20-25. (Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MONET-REVIEW _ ATLANTA _ Art review. Also opening Feb. 23 at
High. ``Monet &AMP; Bazille: A Collaboration'' a collaboration of
scholarly interest because of the unique relationship between the
two artists leading up to the advent of Impressionsism. (Both shows
organized by the High and touring after closing here on May 16.)
(Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 17-20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ELTON-CONCERT _ ATLANTA _ Setup story for tonight's concert in
Atlanta, which will be an evening of firsts. Elton John plays the
Fox Theatre for the first time, doing an acoustic (piano only) act
for the first time and doing only old stuff for the first time in a
long time. (MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
