<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4285 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV28-NY     02-22 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PAVING FOR THE MIDDLE OF THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 28)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics. Double parentheses
should be set as brackets.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A specter is stalking world politics, as Karl Marx might have
manifested it _ the specter of the  &UR; third way &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``The  &UR; third way &LR;  is part of the politics of the center and
center left,'' said Tony Blair, the British prime minister, last
month. ``In Britain, it means New Labor.'' He defined his  &UR; third
way &LR;  as a place where ``economic dynamism and social justice can
live together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``European governments spend and tax heavily,'' noted Laura
D'Andrea Tyson, former chairman of the Clinton Council of Economic
Advisers, ``but the architects of the new Europe see them as a
human  &UR; third way &LR;  between old-style socialism and the supposed
divisive social consequences of the American way.''
</P>
<P>
   Her former boss saw the way more benignly. In Bill Clinton's
1992 campaign, he said, ``I thought we ought to have a  &UR; third
way &LR; ,'' and in his 1998 State of the Union declared, ``We have
found a  &UR; third way &LR; .'' Last month, he told the Economic Club of
Detroit: ``We are working with business to use technology, research
and market incentives to meet national goals. Some have called this
political philosophy `the  &UR; third way &LR; .'''
</P>
<P>
   Those ``some'' can also be found in Moscow. ``Former Deputy
Prime Ministers Anatoly Chubais and Boris Nemtsov accused Moscow
Mayor and born-again centrist Yuri Luzhkov of `economic
illiteracy,''' wrote Harry Kopp of the Jamestown Foundation's
Monitor. ``Luzhkov, who recently returned from Tony Blair's
Britain, said Russia must choose `a  &UR; third way &LR;  between total
socialism and vulgar liberalism.'''
</P>
<P>
   Where there's a way, there's a will; in this case, Will
Marshall, head of Washington's Progressive Policy Institute, who
says that Mr. and Mrs. Clinton ``think a  &UR; third way &LR;  approach to
governing is his legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, left and right take their pops at it. Liberals see
self-contradictions in such a ``slippery center.'' ``The  &UR; Third
Way &LR;  assumes a basic political symmetry,'' wrote Jonathan Chait in
The New Republic, ``an unreconstructed left, a radical right and a
 &UR; Third Way &LR;  nestled in between.'' But this is self-defeating:
``When the  &UR; Third Way &LR;  takes power, it alters that equation ((and))
no longer sits between the two poles of the political spectrum; it
 &UR; is &LR;  the left pole. The calculus has changed, and, in order to
retain the center, the  &UR; Third Way &LR;  must shift right again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Lamar Alexander, of the Campaign for a New
American Century (its onset is getting ever more likely), slams the
way from the right. ``The  &UR; third way &LR;  is no way,'' he claims.
``Supposedly, this is an alternative to free-market capitalism, on
the one hand, and socialism on the other. When you peel the layers
off this particular onion, however, what you get is `social
democracy' _ the ever-expanding, cradle-to-grave welfare-state
programs that hobble most European countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Where did the latest moniker for the middle of the road come
from? You can find the phrase in theology (between the second and
fourth ways of St. Thomas Aquinas) and among the ways of
phenomenology.
</P>
<P>
   In politics, the historian H.A.L. Fisher traced it to the French
emperor Napoleon III, who steered between internal revolution and
foreign war to choose a  &UR; third way &LR;  of liberalism. In the United
States, early centrists working toward a third party between
Federalists and Republicans were called Quiddists, from the Latin
 &UR; tertium quid &LR; , or ``third thing.''
</P>
<P>
   HOTSPUR!
</P>
<P>
   ``He must find a way out among moderate Republicans and
Democrats,'' the New York Times editorialist wrote of the Senate
majority leader, Trent Lott, ``even if Republican  &UR; hotspurs &LR; 
object.''
</P>
<P>
   Every dictionary worth its spurs notes that the word  &UR; hotspur &LR; 
was the sobriquet of Sir Henry Percy, son of the earl of
Northumberland, killed in 1403 in the rebellion against Henry IV.
(A  &UR; sobriquet &LR;  is a descriptive appellation, like Gov. Jesse ``the
Body'' Ventura, which geezers will fondly recall followed, by two
generations, Marie ``the Body'' McDonald.)
</P>
<P>
   The earliest citation of  &UR; hotspur &LR;  was in a chronicle a
half-century later: ``Herry Percy the yonger, whom the Scottis
clepid Herry Hatspore.'' Shakespeare then used the word in his
``Henry IV'': ``A haire-brained Hotspurre, gouern'd by a Spleene.''
</P>
<P>
   Tangent time: those citations show us (1) that  &UR; Henry &LR;  led to
 &UR; Harry &LR;  by way of  &UR; Herry &LR; , or Herry was the progenitor of both, and
(2) that the Shakespearean spelling of  &UR; haire-brained &LR;  is a source
of the confusion about that word's meaning. It has nothing to do
with hair found on the scalp on top of the skull that encases the
brain. Rather, it is a  &UR; hare &LR; , or rabbit, which was thought to have
an especially small or weak brain. End of tangent.
</P>
<P>
   But what is the metaphoric basis of  &UR; hotspur &LR; ? Why not
 &UR; coldspur &LR;  or  &UR; hotsaddle &LR;  (as in the discomforting title of the Mel
Brooks movie ``Blazing Saddles'')? When an equestrian rides
impetuously or cruelly, spurring his horse constantly, the spurs
are seen to become hot from the friction _ if not literally, at
least figuratively. That's what harebrained Henry (not
haire-brained Herry) did, and why they clepid, or yclept, or named
him that. And that is also why profoundly literate editorialists
still use  &UR; hotspur &LR;  to mean ``a rash, impetuous, hard-driving
person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4287 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-MEDIA23-COX     02-22 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The buzz is about a movie far, far away
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next ``Star Wars'' movie will be released Memorial Day, and
the Web is already buzzing with rumors about the film. Read about
the latest rumors and where you can find them in the February issue
of Yahoo! Internet Life. There's gossip about who will play the
lead roles, about the story line and about other movies to come in
the ``Star War'' series.
</P>
<P>
   You got a hot new game for Christmas, but how the heck do you
master it? Pick up some tips on some popular new PC games in the
February issue of PC Gamer. You'll find advice on such games as
``Half-Life,'' ``Grim Fandango,'' ``Tomb Raider III,'' ``Blood
II,'' ``Railroad Tycoon II,'' ``Caesar III,'' ``Delta Force'' and
``Shogo.'' Concerning ``Railroad Tycoon II,'' for example, PC Gamer
shows you how to improve your stations by adding hotels, saloons
and roundhouses.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM: One of the world's greatest game developers, the
creator of such classics as ``Civilization'' and ``Railroad
Tycoon,'' has released his latest strategy game, ``Alpha Centuri.''
This game is very much like ``Civilization,'' except it is set in
space. The object of ``Alpha Centuri'' is to build a new
civilization on an alien planet. You discover new technologies,
build bases and conquer enemies. The game is available only for
Windows PCs.
</P>
<P>
   It has gone from deer to elephants _ and 3-D elephants, at that.
It, of course, is the computer game ``Deer Hunter.'' Now the latest
version, published by WizardWorks, is called ``African Safari
Trophy Hunter.'' The hunted include zebras, elephants and kudus.
The game is available only for Windows PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Online: The Web has quickly become an electronic library. You'll
find all kinds of basic references that help with everything from
writing a paper for school to a memo at work. Some sites, such as
Britannica Online, charge a fee. But many others are free. Among
the free ones is Information Please, a one-stop resource that
provides quick answers on things from sports to first aid. You'll
find Information Please at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.infoplease.com. Another good quick reference is the online
version of Merriam-Webster's Collegiate Dictionary and Thesaurus.
You'll find Merriam-Webster at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .m-w.com.
</P>
<P>
   Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
