u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-REPORT23-COX     02-22 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PC advice for dazed parents
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those who think the generation gap is marked in distance
with PCs, with the young on one side of the chasm and older folks
on the other, take a look at a book from Intel that hopes to bridge
that gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PC Dads Guide to Becoming a Computer-Smart Parent,'' which
retails for $12.95, hopes to ``come to the rescue of parents
befuddled by computers.'' The authors, Mark Ivey and Ralph Bond,
are Oregonians, parents and senior managers at Intel. Ivey started
his career writing for newspapers in the late 1970s. Bond was
originally a part-time art history teacher. The pair geared the
book for technology lightweights, focusing on topics like how to
use a computer to help your child learn to read.
</P>
<P>
   Topics include Digital Parenting _ Five Easy Tips; Ten Things
You Can Do With Your Kids on a PC; Booting Up Baby; Eight Ways to
Make a Kid PC Kid-Friendly; Boys, Guns or Roses: What to do About
Game Addiction and Violent Software; Raising a Computer-Smart
Daughter; and Cybersafety.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, check the PC Dads Web site,
http://www.intel.com
</P>
<P>
   /intel/educate/pcdads/index.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking the language
</P>
<P>
   If you have an upcoming trip to the land of the Zulu and you
want to brush up on the native tongue, there's a Web site to help.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.101language.com is a site for foreign language
programs. The products are not cheap. The Spanish-language program
runs $299. But like most e-commerce sites, the selection is
impressive. Language product topics range from Arabic to Zulu. The
site sells more than 100 products for languages including Swahili
and Igbo, plus books on international customs, foreign slang and
accents.
</P>
<P>
   A toll-free help line lets prospective customers find out which
program is better-suited for their needs. 101language.com also
offers a five-part, no-interest payment plan. The company is based
in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Extra-strength search engine
</P>
<P>
   If the free search engines available on the Web aren't helping
you cut through the clutter, a California company has released a
$45 search engine that might.
</P>
<P>
   ImaginOn released WebZinger 6.0 this month. The Java-based
application works on Windows-based PCs. A version for the Macintosh
and Sun Solaris platforms is expected to be released soon.
</P>
<P>
   The software program is available for purchase at two Web sites,
http://www
</P>
<P>
   .unboxed.com or http://
</P>
<P>
   webzinger.com.
</P>
<P>
   The theory behind WebZinger is that database processing and
playback technology turns information: The result is a search
engine that searches, locates, evaluates, downloads, formats and
plays back search results in the form of a multimedia slide show
while you use other desktop applications. Elapsed time is about 30
minutes. At any time during the 30-minute presentation of search
results, the user can click on a Web site, get more information,
then click back and resume the presentation. If 30 minutes is too
long, there's a feature that creates a one-minute search results
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   A review in the Jan. 27 issue of PC World gave the product high
marks for the speed, efficiency and relevancy of its searches. A
free trial version is available for download at
http://www.imaginon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Estate planning program
</P>
<P>
   E-Z Legal, the company that mass-marketed do-it-yourself
lawyering, is offering a software version of its estate planning
program.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida company's Legacy program lets you arrange for the
distribution of your worldly possessions without getting a
$300-an-hour lawyer involved. The Windows-based CD-ROM comes with
instructions, information and the forms to write your own will,
living trust, durable power of attorney for health care and living
will. The product will be available this month for a suggested
retail of $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
