<HEADER>
A4294 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE23-COX     02-22 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For silly info, try these sites
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The World Wide Web is actually a useful place these days. If you
need demographic information from Des Moines, the average rainfall
for Medford, Ore., or a list of the books written by Winston
Churchill, you can find it with a few clicks of a mouse button.
</P>
<P>
   But, if you wanted useful, you would have purchased a vacuum
cleaner, not a computer and an all-you-can-eat subscription to an
Internet provider. The secret vice of most Internet users isn't the
X-rated Web sites or the online gambling casinos. What most Web
users crave is stupid, silly, useless information. If you are
looking for ways to fritter away your workday or sites that will
provide you with an excuse to avoid any sort of a normal family
life, you've come to the right place.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with a site that seeks the Tackiest Place in
America. You'll find this high-minded site at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .thepoint.net/(tilde)usul/text
</P>
<P>
   /tacky.html. Once there, you can read reviews of some nominees,
including the United Equipment Co. office in Turlock, Calif. It has
a building shaped like a bulldozer, something you are unlikely to
see outside Turlock. Or perhaps you'll favor the sculpture of a
black widow spider, created in Nevada using a trashed VW bug and
cheesy yellow letters. Once you've met the contenders, maybe you'll
have a nominee of your own to make.
</P>
<P>
   Now we'll move on to Lark and Mark's Virtual Jell-O, a
cyber-celebration of the quivering dessert. You'll find this site
at http://www.efn.org
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)larkw/jello.htm. A lot of serious time-wasters are here,
everything from a section of Jell-O poetry to a place where you can
vote on your favorite flavor (lime is the runaway choice, but you
have a chance to get in your vote for strawberry), plus a tacky
food department where you can learn to make several desserts
unlikely to find their way onto the pages of Gourmet magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, you're looking for wild and exotic fun. You want something
that is interactive and challenges your creativity. In that case,
the obvious choice is the Build-a-Monster page at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.rahul.net/renoir
</P>
<P>
   /monster/monster.html. You'll be able to use your mouse and _ if
done right _ create something truly ugly and worthless.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps you find that too intellectually challenging. What
you want is something really simple. Well, follow me to a page
buried way deep over at GeoCities (http://www.geocities
</P>
<P>
   .com/CollegePark/Field/1688
</P>
<P>
   /feedback.htm). Now, someone finally wants your opinion on
important issues such as your favorite color and other equally
weighty topics. Just select your answers from the menu and go along
your way knowing you took the time to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Now we will amble over to http://www.amused.com
</P>
<P>
   /homepage.html, where you will find a page named in the spirit
of today's column: The Centre for the Easily Amused. Mostly this is
a page of links to other pages, including a Web camera where you'll
literally be able to watch paint peel (given you have a few days of
steady watching time to spend).
</P>
<P>
   One of the best features of this page is the Drive-By. Select
that feature and you'll be transported automatically on a tour of
all the Web site's links. You select the amount of time you'd like
to spend at each page, then sit back for hands-free browsing. For
the lazy and bored, this is premium stuff. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
