</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETNEWS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK GROUPS ON USENET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Charles Stough is an editor at the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News)  
 By CHARLES STOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the doomsayers? They talked, as the Internet was
spawning, of the end of the printed word: No more pencils, no more
books, we'll be online in our cyber-nooks. The last drop of ink
would be used to print the last page of the Donkey Kong manual.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not in this millennium. Not only are books one of the
hottest items of commerce in the Net, talking about books and
trading books is a hot topic in discussion groups. Just look at
some of the Usenet groups open to the world: alt.books,
alt.marketplace.books, alt.publish.books, misc.books,
rec.arts.books, alt.fiction, and rec.arts.books.hist-fiction.
</P>
<P>
   There are author fan clubs and groups where readers post reviews
of books. There are flea market groups for traders. One could
exhaust one's joy of reading by just reading about reading.
</P>
<P>
   And for readers, the groups are a joy. The first investors in
private computers for Net exploring were very literate people. They
established the etiquette (write anything ALL IN CAPITAL LETTERS
and someone will tell you to stop shouting) and laid down a
foundation of wit and wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   In the book groups, this wit is most apparent. Observe this
dialogue when someone posted a query in rec.arts.books recently:
</P>
<P>
   ``I recently was reminded of a book I read a fair while ago. I
remember what it was about but not who wrote it or what its title
was. Is there anything that anyone could suggest? Thanks for any
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't know the title or author or what the book was about? Ripe
for the challenge, a contributor posted: ``Might it have been
either The Ambassadors by Henry James or Joy Luck Club by Amy Tan?
If you wish, I can come up with some other titles ....''
</P>
<P>
   From another, undaunted: ``I think it must have been The Gods
Themselves by Isaac Asimov. I mean, it's perfect: when one person
forgets about a book it pops into someone else's head, ping! And
I've thought about this book several times since a fair while ago.
Numerous instances; why, people must be forgetting this book left
and right. Proof positive that my theory is spot on.''
</P>
<P>
   And, ``It was either The Good Soldier by Ford Madox Ford,
Maigret et Son Mort by Georges Simenon, or the Iliad. What was it
about?''
</P>
<P>
   And, ``Judging by the incredibly precise information that you
have provided, the book you are referring to is Mme.Solange's Rien
de Tout, ou la Consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   And, ``No. It has to be If on a Winter's Night Three Farmers,
because I can never remember the title or author of that one
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the original supplicant posted, ``Thanks for all the
sarcastic answers. I was looking for something along the lines of
maybe a newsgroup dedicated to that sort of thing. It was a science
fiction novel about a world in which assassins were created which
had two bodies ....''
</P>
<P>
   ``The newsgroup to try is rec.arts.sf.written.''
</P>
<P>
   The inquirer went to search. Meanwhile rec.arts.books started a
thread on telephone solicitors who weren't even selling books.
Mike, one of the group regulars, had taken a late call from a
peddler who gave him chills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman, Jennifer, is someone she says who called Martha a
year ago as a telemarketer,'' Mike posted. ``Martha called her a
prostitute at that moment for engaging in telephone solicitation,
and she was calling Martha (a year later, and after we have just
moved) to inform Martha that she, Jennifer, had Martha's new
number.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh boy! Not all the drama is in books, is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Calling them prostitutes isn't going to make them or you feel
any better,'' another regular offered. ``I say 'I'm not interested,
thanks very much' and hang up the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Another person chummily added, ``That, of course, is best. I
prefer to tell them `I'm sorry, you must have a wrong number. I
don't have a telephone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that would shorten the dinner interruptions, even if one
never gets the 40 percent off long distance to odd-numbered friends
or a credit card that rebates pecan fudge.
</P>
<P>
   But who is the vixen Jennifer, brandishing that razor-sharp
phone dialler, and how goes her vendetta? For the continuing saga,
tune in rec.arts.books, on an Internet service provider near you...
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stough is an editor for the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   His e-mail address is copyboy(at)dma.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
