<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Feb. 22, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONTAMINATED-SUTURES (San Francisco) _ Patients all over the
United States have charged that they suffered stubborn, unusual
postsurgical infections because of contaminated medical sutures
supplied by the Ethicon Corp. By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKING-ARRESTS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco police and
public health officials have busted 48 smoking offenders, including
eight tavern owners, in a three-week-old sweep that has re-ignited
debate about California's controversial law snuffing out smoking in
bars. By MACKENZIE WARREN.
</P>
<P>
   INS-INFORMANTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Immigration officials in New
York rely heavily on a small pool of informants among labor
activists who regularly tip off authorities when they find
undocumented immigrants working in the area, according to
interviews with immigration and labor officials. By MELISSA GRACE.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-RACE (San Francisco) _ Spending $300 million over 15
years to desegregate San Francisco's schools bought students
computers, culturally sensitive teachers, two new schools and the
chance to sit next to kids of other races in class. It failed,
however, in its first and most fundamental goal: getting black
children to do well in school. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-WORKERS (San Francisco) _ Being young, female and poor can
make you invisible in the traditional work world of America. It
shouldn't be so, says the Young Women's Work Project, which
recently issued the first national study of the work experiences of
young poor and working-class girls under 21. By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   ALBANY-POPULATION (Albany, N.Y.) _ Experts say Albany's
declining population will level off at slightly more than 100,000
in the 2000 census, narrowly averting getting shoved into the urban
minor leagues. The city isn't going to experience anything like
dynamic growth, but experts believe the population is stabilized.
By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-JOBS (San Francisco) _ When Mike Gnoss was looking for
a job last December, he did not pick up the newspaper and pore over
the classifieds as generations before him have done. Instead, he
turned to the Internet. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SATELLITES (Albany, N.Y. ) _ A war between satellite program
providers and over-the-air broadcasters has resulted in a federal
court in Miami late last year that consumers with satellite dishes
cannot receive distant network feeds from CBS or Fox if they are in
areas where they can get local affiliate broadcasting via either
cable or an antenna. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MILLIMETER (Los Angeles) _ In his new film, ``Eight
Millimeter,'' director Joel Schumacher takes Nicolas Cage on a
journey into the abyss, an exploration of the dark subculture of
pornography, kinky sex, addictions and redemption. If there's one
person who would seem to be a fitting guide for Cage, it's the
filmmaker himself, who knows a thing or two about hell. By CRAIG
MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-COOL (Undated) _ ``Be Cool,'' by Elmore Leonard, is
just so-so. Leonard, author of ``Hombre,'' ``Get Shorty'' and half
a dozen other books that were made into films, has been served well
by Hollywood, with stars like Paul Newman, Steve McQueen, Charles
Bronson and John Travolta taking their turns at the material. By
EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS (San Francisco) _ Hidden in valleys, ravines and small
canyons throughout the Bay Area are dozens of little creeks, all of
them riparian watersheds that once created a paradise for fish,
birds and wildlife. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
