<HEADER>
A4328 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-LIZ-TAYLOR-ART-N     02-22 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-LIZ-TAYLOR-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNSINKABLE ELIZABETH TAYLOR 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a color slide of Liz Taylor before her 1997 birthday party
and a black-and-white print of the actress in ``Cat on a Hot Tin
Roof.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    She's one of the most famous women in the world, and on Feb. 27
she'll turn 67. She's lived virtually her whole life in the
spotlight, in a dog-eat-dog world where cynics abound.
 &HT;    Yet, her current boyfriend says, ``I'm amazed that for a person
who has been out there since she was 9 years old, she's so trusting
and naive _ in the best sense of the word.''
 &HT;    Oscar-winning actor Rod Steiger is talking about his friend
Elizabeth Taylor, and he insists that _ despite her much-chronicled
trials and tribulations, her many husbands and consorts, her
numerous health crises, the acres of newsprint devoted to her
so-called scandals _ ``She has not become a hardened person.''
 &HT;    The couple have become close friends, dodging the paparazzi to
slip away for a quiet lunch each week.
 &HT;    Their relationship began, Steiger says, when he met her to
discuss a film script and was stunned to discover that, except for
AIDS fundraisers, she hadn't been out to lunch in two years.
 &HT;    Despite the gossip columns, however, the actor insists that he
and the much-wed Taylor are not contemplating marriage.
 &HT;    ``Some of the papers have played it up as heavy romance,'' he
says. ``I have a great deal of respect for her and her courage.
We've both had a lot of pain _ we are sympatico.''
 &HT;    So much so in fact that, in her late 60s, Taylor is going back
to work to star opposite Steiger in a modestly budgeted movie
entitled ``Somewhere,'' which Steiger will direct.
 &HT;    The actor calls it, ``a little picture about Dorothy later in
life, wanting to go back to Oz at the age of 60.''
 &HT;    At 67, Taylor is bouncing back from her most recent back
problems and minor sinus surgery. At last count she has had more
than 30 major surgeries.
 &HT;    ``Elizabeth uses hospitals the way other people use resorts,''
her second husband, Michael Wilding, once said _ and that was when
she was still in her 20s.
 &HT;    Today Taylor is looking well again. She stays actively involved
with her AIDS charity work, and continues her efforts to promote
her signature White Diamonds and Passion perfumes.
 &HT;    Her seesaw life continues to captivate the world. One week she's
fat, the next week she's thin. One week she's glamorous in diamonds
and designer duds, the next she's in an ambulance being rushed to a
hospital. One minute she's giving an impassioned speech about AIDS,
the next she's flashing her $4 million diamond ring as if she'd
never had a serious thought in her life.
 &HT;    Taylor has made her whole life a study in how not to mature.
When she hit 60 she invited her assorted pals to live it up with
her _ at Disneyland. At 65 she was thrown a huge, celebrity-studded
birthday bash which became a television special to benefit AIDS.
 &HT;    And still she's the center of the tabloid universe. Whether it's
her relationship with Steiger or her public display of concern
after her former husband, 47-year-old Larry Fortensky, fell down
the stairs at his home and sustained a brain injury.
 &HT;    But privately she mostly stays home in her $5 million Bel Air
mansion, meeting with producers and filmmakers who want to entice
her back to the big and small screen. And she enjoys visits from
her extended family, grandkids and all.
 &HT;    She has little left to prove, having already lived enough for
six lifetimes. She's won Oscars for ``Butterfield 8'' (1960) and
``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf'' (1966) and made dozens of other
movies, some of them great, some not so great. She's made
headlines, some good and some embarrassing. She's dumped husbands
and lovers and given us a vicarious ride with her yachts, her
jewels, her kids and her animals.
 &HT;    And with all that, it's been hard for us to accept that the
gorgeous little 9-year-old who showed up on screen in ``National
Velvet'' (1944) is on the Medicare rolls.
 &HT;    Elizabeth Taylor Hilton Wilding Todd Fisher Burton Warner
Fortensky is no longer a box-office star. Yet she's a huge draw
when she makes personal appearances to peddle her perfumes or to
raise money to help lick the disease that killed her longtime
friend Rock Hudson.
 &HT;    The last film she starred in was the television movie ``Sweet
Bird of Youth'' (1989). The last time she worked on the big screen,
it was a mere cameo role in ``The Flintstones'' (1994).
 &HT;    Yet the world is apparently endlessly fascinated by this woman,
even if her main claim to fame these days is that she's more famous
for being famous than any other woman in the world.
 &HT;    She keeps bouncing back, more than earning her title of
Hollywood's Queen of Survival: There's not much she can't handle,
not even that curse of great beauties everywhere, aging.
 &HT;    ``I feel the same inside,'' she says. ``But, you know, that's
because I don't look in the mirror much. It depends on how I feel
in the morning on any given day. But I don't look back _ only
forward.''
 &HT;    She says she tries to think positively.
 &HT;    ``I don't live with regret in my life,'' Taylor says. ``I really
don't say, `Oh God, I wish I hadn't been under contract.' I don't
live to regret any of it. It's too late, anyway. I didn't realize
I'd go along for so long _ I'm like a bad penny, hard to get rid
of.''
 &HT;    She laughs.
 &HT;    ``I don't watch my old movies,'' she adds. ``No way. I never
look at them, and if one comes on TV I switch off quickly. It makes
me very self-conscious.''
 &HT;    Perhaps in her late 60s, forgoing the grand passions that always
seemed to get her in so much trouble, she seems to be settling for
companionship. At least that's what Steiger thinks.
 &HT;    ``We're like a couple of old gunfighters _ Wild Bill Hickok and
Wyatt Earp,'' the actor says. ``We've both been through a lot of
crap. I believe talented people should help and protect each other.
Whenever we see each other we have a nice time, because we've both
been there _ and back.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.) &LR; 
 &UR; (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) &QL; 
