<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Just say no _ or yes
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I may be slow on the uptake, but did I hear Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright correctly? She said, I think, that the United
States would not bomb the Serbs if both sides turned down a peace
agreement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The way I get it, we would like to bomb someone. For peace. OK
so far? If someone says yes, whoever says no gets bombed. If both
sides say no, nobody gets bombed. If both sides say yes, they can
go back to breaking agreements.
</P>
<P>
   If I were a Serb or a Kosovonian, I would figure the best thing
to do was to say yes, claiming I was all for peace, then let the
recalcitrant side get bombed. In a pinch, I might say no real quick
and hope the other side said no simultaneously. Then, just having
been unbombed by America, I would resume slaughtering civilians.
For peace.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomacy is the cruelest art.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
