<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SATELLITES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATELLITE VIEWERS FACE LOSS OF SOME PROGRAMMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The truth may be out there, but ``The X-Files''
and other Fox shows won't be for long for some owners of satellite
dishes.
</P>
<P>
   And ``JAG'' will be shot down, ``Diagnosis: Murder'' killed off
and other CBS shows blocked as the result of a court order with
nationwide ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   The programs are caught in the cross fire of a war between
satellite program providers and over-the-air broadcasters. The only
thing the two sides can agree on is that the viewers are caught in
the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are counting down the days to one of the biggest consumer
outcries we have seen in years,'' said Harry Thibedeau of the
National Rural Telecommunications Cooperative, which represents
satellite companies.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court in Miami ruled late last year that consumers
with satellite dishes cannot receive distant network feeds from CBS
or Fox if they are in areas where they can get local affiliate
broadcasting either by cable or an antenna.
</P>
<P>
   NBC and ABC are not affected, but could be down the road if they
decide to take action.
</P>
<P>
   In order to legally receive such a distant feed a dish owner
must get approval from local affiliates in the form of a waiver.
Granting a waiver is based solely on the quality of reception in a
given home.
</P>
<P>
   How good a reception? Satellite providers said it should be
perfect, while broadcasters and the law say it should be close
enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Satellite Home Viewers Act, which granted the right to
waivers in the first place, is set to expire at the end of this
year without congressional reauthorization and is being debated. A
House subcommittee on satellite television reform is scheduled to
meet this week.
</P>
<P>
   (Another vital issue to television viewers may or may not be
waged on Capitol Hill. On March 31, federal price controls on cable
television rates are set to expire. The controls, part of the 1996
Telecommunications Act, did not stop rate increases.)
</P>
<P>
   The satellite issue is a tricky, divisive topic. Satellite
providers say many consumers will be left with no service. These
viewers live in rural areas where cable is not available and ground
contours like hills and valleys limit if not block
over-the-air-transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (broadcasters) want to protect _ let's call it what it is
_ a local monopoly on network programming,'' Thibedeau said. ``Is
it wrong? No. But does it make good public policy? It comes down to
an issue of fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Fairness is right, the broadcasters argue. They say that for
years the satellite companies were selling customers a product they
had no right to sell, arguing the affiliates are the only ones who
should able to do so unless consent is given.
</P>
<P>
   ``The satellite folks had a systematic business strategy of
signing up as many illegal customers as they possibly could,'' said
Dennis Wharton, spokesman for the National Association of
Broadcasters. ``Once they were caught, they unleashed all these
consumers who were duped into buying this service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, `Let's break the law and after we get caught, let's
get the law changed.'''
</P>
<P>
   To the local affiliates, CBS is not any CBS, and Fox not just
any Fox. The local stations are arguing they pay for exclusivity
for local network rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if they are watching Denver,'' said Doreen Wade,
general manager of CBS-affiliate WRGB in Albany. ``I want them to
watch WRGB.''
</P>
<P>
   The affiliates and their representatives said the very fate of
free, local television could be riding on the issue. If people can
pluck other markets down from satellite, fewer will watch local
feeds and local news, which will affect advertising and
community-based information, which will affect survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we look at it is, these distant signals affect our
business,'' said Chris Sehring, general manager of WXXA, the Fox
station in Albany. ``Pretty soon the economics take their toll on
the local affiliate.''
</P>
<P>
   The shut-offs will come in two phases. Subscribers to services
after March 11, 1997, will be shut off on Sunday. Those who
received Fox and CBS before that are grandfathered until April 30.
More than 300,000 subscribers could be affected nationwide,
Thibedeau said.
</P>
<P>
   There could be common ground on the horizon, called
``local-to-local'' satellite broadcasting, where local signals are
beamed to a satellite and right back down to just that community.
The technology is coming. But it won't be here by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
