<HEADER>
A4451 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NHAMPSHIRE-PRIMARY-2T     02-22 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NHAMPSHIRE-PRIMARY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE TAKING ROOT IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ From an office set in a woodland sanctuary,
former governor Hugh Gregg relentlessly protects New Hampshire's
first-primary status, using books, newsletters and phone calls to
take on anyone who would change the Granite State's powerful role
in picking presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But when Gregg steps outside his home in this increasingly
crowded border town, he faces a landscape overcome by change. He
often does not recognize anyone, and when he looks at the political
shape of the state, he barely recognizes that, either. Last week
Gregg, a Republican, received the most surprising news of all: that
the GOP-controlled House had kept alive a proposal for a 4 percent
income tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new millennium,'' Gregg, 81, said, shaking his head.
``In the last millennium, a broad-based tax was considered death.''
</P>
<P>
   While enactment of the tax is by no means certain, the House's
action underscored political, economic and cultural change in New
Hampshire, forcing presidential candidates to reconsider their
campaign focus for the primary that, if past years are a guide,
would be held one year from Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire, with a Democratic woman as governor, a Democratic
state Senate and one of the nation's lowest poverty rates, is a
different place today than it was 10 and especially 20 years ago.
Migrants outnumber natives and, in many ways, are reshaping the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Independents, for the first time, are on the verge of
outnumbering Republicans. For a state that was mired in recession
in the early 1990s, New Hampshire may be at its economic high-water
mark, with a 2.9 percent unemployment rate and the nation's highest
percentage of high-tech workers.
</P>
<P>
   By national standards, New Hampshire has a tiny minority
population and a wide income disparity. But after years of being
criticized for being so atypical, yet wielding so much power in the
presidential candidate selection process, New Hampshire has become
more urbanized and more like the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates have been quick to notice many of these
changes and have re-engineered their campaigns accordingly. When
Vice President Al Gore campaigned here earlier this month, he gave
a lengthy speech about the importance of ``livability'' and the
dangers of suburban sprawl and shopping malls, a speech he could
have delivered in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aide Chris Lehane said the vice president recognizes that
many potential supporters ``are folks who got stuck on Route 128''
outside Boston ``and are now concerned that will happen in New
Hampshire. They feel, `God help us if that happens here.' There is
a huge wave.''
</P>
<P>
   To lifelong residents such as Gregg, the wave can be daunting.
``New Hampshire used to be a state where you knew everybody, a
small homogeneous place,'' Gregg said. ``Now the new immigrants in
the southern tier, they don't give a hoot about the north country,
they spend time flying around the world on this `cyberstuff' and
they have an entirely different philosophy, and they don't
participate in state affairs as much.''
</P>
<P>
   But to newcomers such as Kurt Mueffelmann, that ``cyberstuff''
is the state's future.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half ago, Mueffelmann, a Boston businessman, bought
a software company in Manchester, thinking he might move the
110-employee RealWorld Corp. to Massachusetts. ``New Hampshire
seemed like a sleepy town to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But within weeks, Mueffelman became so enamored of the state and
its lower costs that he took the opposite tack, moving his family
to the Granite State. At his company, located in a renovated mill
by the Merrimack River, salaries are 30 to 50 percent lower than in
Massachusetts, and rent is cheaper by half, he said. New
Hampshire's lovely lakes, the spell of the seasons and the nearby
White Mountains are an incalculable bonus, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the days when the economy could be summed up in three
words _ forestry, shoes and textiles _ are but a memory. Now, of
every 1,000 residents in the state, 84 are high-tech workers, the
highest percentage in the nation, according to the American
Electronics Association.
</P>
<P>
   Mueffelmann, who rarely thought about presidential politics
until just before an election, has surprised himself by becoming
caught up in the state's first-primary politics, paying attention
to the words of former Vice President Dan Quayle, watching a
television biography of Senator John McCain of Arizona and
attending a dinner featuring Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a feeling, of `Wow, I can really go out and make an
impact,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mueffelmann is one of thousands of people, many from
Massachusetts, who have transformed the state. Planning officials
estimate that 60 percent of the residents are not natives, up from
50 percent in 1980. But as people arrive, problems follow,
including traffic, crime and overcrowding. That, in turn, has
unsettled the state's political dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is this change more evident than in Nashua. The bustling
city made headlines in 1997 when Money magazine named it America's
best place to live. But local officials, while proud of the
dizzying success, tell cautionary tales about the city's doubling
in size to 83,000 since 1960. The owner of an average $150,000 home
pays $4,200 per year in property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But even such high property taxes have not been enough to pay
for the education of the city's growing school-age population. The
city's public high school needs a renovation and expansion that
could cost $70 million. Even with state contributions, that could
add another $400 in taxes to every homeowner's tax bill, according
to David Fredette, president of the board of aldermen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
