<SLUG> BC-TRIALS-HISTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND SIMPSON CASES HIGHLIGHT DEEP DIVISIONS IN US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that President Clinton's impeachment trial is
quickly fading from daily consciousness, we can begin to see its
place in history. And, oddly enough, that place is right beside _
and inescapably linked to _ that other trial that dominated our
attention in the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   The trials of Bill Clinton and O. J. Simpson could not, at first
blush, appear more different: a president accused of high crimes
and misdemeanors for covering up an affair with a former intern vs.
a former football star charged with brutally murdering his former
wife and an acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   But the extraordinary way these two high-profile events unfolded
and resonated in America's voyeurististic culture leave them with
much in common.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and O. J. Simpson were both found not gulity
of criminal acts that a majority of Americans believe they
committed. Both trials fed the public's appetite for 24-hour cable
news, and stoked its fascination with celebrities as defendants.
And both trials illuminated the nation's racial divide _ with
blacks backing the defendant in disproportionate number, although
for different reasons in each case.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, these two trials highlighted deep ideolgical divisions
present in the nation on the eve of a new millennium. They also
underscored the notion of public trials as sporting events, with
winners and losers, especially when race is a subtext.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, a president who began his second term promising to
heal society's breaches, the analogies must seem ominous.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, that second term began with his State of the Union
address competing on the split-screen with the verdict in the
Simpson civil trial. `The parallels are there, and one leads right
into the next,'' said Gary Weaver, a specialist in American
culture, political amusement, and human behavior at American
University. ``Both O. J. and Clinton have been demonized _ not only
demonized, but dehumanized.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, just hours after Friday's Senate vote to
acquit Clinton of perjury and obstruction of justice charges,
presidential spokesman Joseph Lockhart was forced to confront the
comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the acquitted president would golf with the
acquitted former football player, considering the two men's
fondness for the sport, he said, ``Mmmmm, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a faint acknowledgment of the dilemma, Lockhart said,
``It's something that's hard, when the public believes that you
have done something that you don't believe you have done.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordeals of both men polarized the nation, and sparked heated
exchanges not only about their guilt or innocence, but about the
appropriate punishment for their alleged crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The analogies also held away from the trial. Time magazine took
the unusual step of darkening Simpson's face, The New York Times
magazine made Clinton's face fuzzy. During the cable networks'
nonstop impeachment trial coverage, the lawyers we had come to know
in the Simpson case popped on the screen as the legal pundits in
the Clinton case.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia professor and author of a
book on the Washington media titled ``The Feeding Frenzy,'' said
that aside from the view of most blacks and whites that Clinton
should not be removed from office, the racial dimension of both
trials was strong.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of whites in public opinion polls said Simpson was
guilty and should go to prison, while a majority of blacks
disagreed. Blacks overwhelmingly approved of Clinton during his
trial, while his numbers were much shakier among whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both had an unshakeable base in the black community that
got them through the toughest time,'' Sabato said of Simpson and
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks backed Clinton because, in short, of who his opponents
were. ``As a cultural figure, Clinton represents those things that
this movement of radical conservatism has wanted to overthrow,''
said Ronald Walters, a political scientist at the University of
Maryland, who is writing a book on what he loosely calls ``white
nationalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Simpson trial ``did not manufacture polarization
around race or racism, but provided us with an opportunity to see
it as a very fractured movement in American history,'' Walters said
the Clinton trial exposed the political fissures in the largely
party line vote to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them are symbolic forces,'' Walters said. ``O. J. was
very much symbolic of the racial problem in America, in a
relatively narrow sense. Clinton is representative of the larger
cultural crisis that we face surrounding liberalism and
conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Simpson, the problems for Clinton may not be over, despite
his acquittal by the Senate, said Berry, the civil rights
commission chairwoman. She noted that independent counsel Kenneth
W. Starr must decide whether to indict the president, which could
come either before or after he leaves office, just as Simpson was
found liable in a civil trial after his acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   And like Simpson, Berry said, Clinton may have to overcome the
burden of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presidents can ususally do anything they feel like doing once
they leave office,'' she said. But, in Clinton's case, some might
say, ```Well, he doesn't have the moral authority to do X, Y, and
X.'''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``Those who feel he should have been convicted and
kicked out of office will forever feel he's tainted by this
process, like damaged goods. And damaged goods don't market as well
as undamaged goods.'' Anyone who doubts that can ask Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Ann Scales is a member of the Globe's Washington bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
