<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL SCIENCE AS A FUN THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ His short-range view evokes the zoo. His
long-range understanding of American government is rich, deep, and
tinged with a teasing attitude toward his own profession. Nelson W.
Polsby can make fun of political science because he works so hard
at it.
</P>
<P>
   He perceives, and documents, larger trends in American politics
that poll-driven pontificators miss. About post-impeachment
politics, ``the word you hear is `disarray,' '' which makes the
director of the Institute of Governmental Studies at the University
of California wonder: ``What's `array' for an American political
party?''
</P>
<P>
   When H. L. Mencken was asked why politics fascinated him, he
replied, ``Why do people go to zoos?'' a question echoing in
Polsby's conversation about today's role reversal in American
politics. ``Here's the culture shock that you and I are
suffering,'' he says. ``We have become accustomed to plodding,
purposeful Republicans and crazy, weird, self-destructive
Democrats. However, the virus seems to have leapt from the
chimpanzees to the baboons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Newt Gingrich ``revolution'' is still stuck in reverse
because of ``a pattern of continuity. First, getting Jim Wright,
then making another scandal, the House bank, out of nothing, then
closing down the government and trying to impeach the president.
It's all negative strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Political scientists often argue that parties should be
``responsible,'' that is, coherent and confrontational. Polsby
remembers when the cozy bipartisanship that once ruled Congress
vanished in a post-impeachment uproar.
</P>
<P>
   Polsby delivered several lectures at Oxford in the last academic
season, explaining how dozens of eager new Democrats rode
post-Watergate fever in 1974, arriving with disdain for Republicans
and a demand for more power in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the pressures of the Democratic caucus bore down on
committee chairmen, many of them felt the need to spend far more
time and energy seeing to the preferences of more junior Democrats,
and less on being solicitous of Republicans, no matter how senior,
knowledgeable, and willing to work. Party responsibility, beloved
of so many political scientists, reared its ugly head. It became
seriously no fun for Republicans to come to work, to find
Democratic thumbs in their eye day in and day out, and nobody
interested in their substantive ideas,'' Polsby told the Oxford
dons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reports started coming out of Washington about a new spirit of
ugliness on Capitol Hill, about unprecedented levels of partisan
rancor, and so on. If you adhere to the belief that precedents only
last as long as the memory of the oldest journalist in town not
afflicted with Alzheimer's disease, this was, more or less, true.''
</P>
<P>
   Polsby recalled an earlier era in his lecture, comparing
Gingrich to the late Senator Joseph R. McCarthy of Wisconsin: ``The
atmosphere in Washington in those days, in the early 1950s, was
plenty acrid, and a fair amount of it was caused by fallout from
the willingness of respectable Republicans to go along with an
adventurer in their midst who might just throw a bomb that would
jar loose the Democratic hold on the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Polsby's lecture is footnoted with the best of political
science, that is, stuff sitting unexplored in the US Statistical
Abstract: how air-conditioning helped change the South from mostly
rural in the 1930s to less rural than the rest of the nation today
(1.3 percent rural to 1.7 elsewhere.)
</P>
<P>
   His first Oxford lecture in 1997 foresaw the fall of Gingrich,
``trying fitfully to make his way closer to the ideological
center.''
</P>
<P>
   Newt didn't get there. In the post-Gingrich era, will
Republicans?
</P>
<P>
   ``When are the Republicans going to find it worth their while to
come back to a get-along, go-along strategy?,'' Polsby asks. ``That
will require some bribery by the Democrats, who I suppose will not
be inclined to do it. We may be stuck in this mode a while
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
