<HEADLINE>
`BE COOL' FALLS SHORT OF LEONARD'S OTHER MYSTERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you turn out three dozen books over a writing career that
criss-crosses between Westerns and mysteries, some are going to be
brilliant, some just so-so, some no good at all. ``Be Cool,''
Elmore Leonard's latest, is just so-so.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, author of ``Hombre,'' ``Get Shorty'' and half a dozen
other books that were made into films, has been served well by
Hollywood, with stars like Paul Newman, Steve McQueen, Charles
Bronson and John Travolta taking their turns at the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be Cool'' (Delacorte Press. New York. $24.95. 292 pages), a
spinoff of ``Get Shorty'' that changes the venue from the movie to
the record business, has all the earmarks of another Hollywood
project. But it'll take some major rewriting to make it to the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard brings back Chili Palmer from ``Get Shorty'' and starts
things off with a gangland shooting at a Beverly Boulevard sidewalk
cafe in the first chapter. The first half of the book goes quickly
because Leonard hasn't lost his touch for everyday conversation _
he has a great ear for the sound of American prattle _ and no one's
better at describing what the eye sees as a scene unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Be Cool'' reads more like a piece of patio writing than a
serious attempt to break into the Hollywood ranks. Characters that
start out funny or tender end up serious and self-centered while
whole scenes seem to scream, ``Short attention span!''
</P>
<P>
   Chili Palmer, witness to a sloppy sidewalk shooting, sees the
killing as the opening for a new film (coming on top of ``Get Leo''
and its sad sequel, ``Get Lost''). He figures he'll center the new
picture on the story of Linda Moon, a true singing talent wasting
away in a Spice Girls sound-alike group. ``Be Cool'' follows
Palmer's attempts to crack into the recording business, which he
knows nothing about, while keeping the movie idea alive.
</P>
<P>
   The usual Leonard suspects are there _ truly stupid crooks,
truly smart women and a gangland subculture that is both gruesome
and funny. There's a black pimp fond of cowboy boots, his gay
Samoan-black bodyguard, a motormouth promo hack _ a part Palmer
already sees as being played by Steve Buscemi _ and more beautiful
women, young and middle-aged, than 292 pages can hold.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a connect-the-dots feel to the whole business. The
killings come equally spaced, reminders to the reader that ``Be
Cool'' is supposed to be a gangland-suspense novel. The love
stories are the kind that appeal to graying men who see themselves
as attractive to women half their age, and the recording industry
angle is a curiosity, nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on Stephen Davis of Aerosmith and his book ``Walk This
Way,'' as well as friends from the recording industry, Leonard
barely scratches the surface of the business, not having near as
much fun with it as he could have.
</P>
<P>
   But even when he's sleepwalking through a novel, Leonard can
still pull it off. The scene between pimp-cowboy Raji and Italian
hit man Joe Loop in Canter's deli is good stuff, and so is Palmer's
ongoing banter with Derek, lead singer for Roadkill. Too often,
though, Leonard loses touch with his characters and, in the case of
Palmer, that's deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard wants Palmer to come off as a tough guy, but the deeper
you get into the book the more he sounds like a jerk. And the more
Palmer pretends to be tough, the worse ``Be Cool'' gets.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Palmer double-crosses Moon, tarting up one of her
songs with studio backwash without letting her know, there's no
reason left to like him. There's not much reason to like Moon, for
that matter, or any of the other people who have made it this far.
</P>
<P>
   In the end ``Be Cool'' comes out worse than ``Hombre,'' better
than ``Maximum Bob,'' worse than ``Get Shorty,'' better than ``Mr.
Majestyk.'' Just so-so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
