<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-OSCAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL OSCAR CHOOSE LOVE OR WAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of us the Oscar race for best picture was over last
July. Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan'' was the heavy
favorite then, and remains the heavy favorite now. And should be.
It's a tremendous feat of filmmaking, quite apart from its
instantly legendary opening Normandy Beach D-day landing scene.
It's a film that challenges itself to stir deep feelings, and does.
One has only to compare it to another best picture nominee,
Terrence Malick's ``The Thin Red Line,'' to realize to what extent
the GIs in ``Private Ryan'' grab us and to what extent the GIs in
``Thin Red Line'' mostly seem part of the tremendous cinematography
to which all else is subordinated in Malick's films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' is the perfect Oscar winner. It's a big
film about a big event executed in a big way. It's the kind of film
that Hollywood uses to present itself to the world as a class act.
Not even Hollywood's reluctance to bestow upon Spielberg the kind
of honor commensurate withhis unparalleled financial success should
stand in his way this year. He and ``Saving Private Ryan'' should
get the best director and best picture statues simply because they
deserve them. If there's to be an upset, however, I wouldn't want
it to be anything but ``Shakespeare in Love.'' It's less about the
love of Shakespeare the young writer for the unattainable woman who
was to become his Juliet than about the giddy love of everyone
connected with it, and, by extension, all of us, for theater
itself.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nonstop delight that simply never touches ground. I can't
think of a happier ending for it than the news that Judi Dench has
acquired the movie's historically accurate Rose Theatre. It won't
be used for firewood, but for staging plays and training actors to
inhabit the kind of space for which Shakespeare wrote. Not for
nothing is Dench a dame with a capital D. She also will, I think,
figure in one of the other races in which ``Shakespeare in Love''
will prevail. So let me race ahead of the neat categorizing that
usually accompanies these Oscar speculations and start by saying
that I can't see the original screenplay going anywhere but to Marc
Norman and Tom Stoppard for their brilliant script for
``Shakespeare in Love.'' The only sad aspect of this race is that
Warren Beatty and Jeremy Pikser's wonderfully audacious script for
``Bulworth,'' which I also loved, will go home empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   As long as we're scrambling the usual order of categories, and
putting writing this high up _ and why not in a year of
Shakespeare? _ I happily scramble out on a limb and declare for
Scott Smith's ``A Simple Plan'' for best adapted screenplay. Smith
wrote the novel, too, which accounts in large part for the way this
beautifully crafted film is able to preserve the integrity of its
characters. Scott Frank's script for ``Out of Sight'' is
sophisticated and dense while always seeming playful, no small
feat. But the surprising depths of feeling in ``A Simple Plan''
start with Smith's screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to best supporting actor. There isn't a
performance here that's less than excellent. If the Oscar were
given for sheer acting power alone, Robert Duvall would get it
hands down for his perfectly modulated old shrewdie in ``A Civil
Action.'' If this is one of those years where career achievement is
the decider, I would have no trouble watching James Coburn take it
home. His performance as a brutal old alcoholic abuser of a father
in ``Affliction'' is so primal it's scary. But the best supporting
actor category just as often is the place where Hollywood likes to
show it's receptive to new blood and new faces. Billy Bob Thornton
isn't that young or that new, but the academy has never given him
an acting award, and the fact that his slob who turns out to have
more soul than anyone else in ``A Simple Plan'' will tip the
balance in his favor, since his is the most vivid and sympathetic
character of the five contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason I lean toward Billy Bob Thornton is that Tom
Hanks will beat the odds and take home his third Oscar for his
heartbreakingly decent American Everyman in ``Saving Private
Ryan.'' It's a role so perfectly aligned with Hanks's own persona
that I predict he'll get the nod, despite what might be the
reluctance of many academy voters to seem lazy by picking him
again. If I were a voter (I'm not), I'd give it to Nick Nolte for
the role of his career as a cop struggling to grow past his
upbringing and the patterns of male violence in his family in
``Affliction.'' But everyone has seen ``Saving Private Ryan,'' and
I'm not sure everyone has seen or will see the much smaller,
bleaker, more uncompromising ``Affliction.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as I was disapoointed to see Jim Carrey passed over, I
was pleased to see the gifted Edward Norton recognized for his
neo-Nazi who sees the light in ``American History X.'' Norton will
get an Oscar, but not this year, when his nomination will be his
reward. Similarly, Ian McKellen is brilliant as British horror
movie director James Whale in ``Gods and Monsters,'' but the banal
psychodrama that composes _ and compromises _ too much of the film
will work against him. The rapturously received Roberto Begnini,
the Italian Charlie Chaplin, seems destined to content himself with
the best foreign film Oscar for his high-impact ``Life Is
Beautiful.'' While he enjoyed the rare distinction of seeing his
film nominated for best picture as well as best foreign picture, he
doesn't have a chance in the former category. I wish the slot had
recognized ``The Truman Show,'' one of the best jobs Hollywood has
ever done of making controlled wholesomeness seem creepy.
</P>
<P>
   Discussion of the actress categories brings us back to
``Shakespeare in Love.'' I think Cate Blanchett is going to emerge
as one of the foremost actresses of the next century. Certainly
she's enormously impressive as ``Elizabeth.'' But I don't think
this will be her year. Emily Watson already is one of the most
impressive members of the younger generation, but ``Hilary and
Jackie,'' in which she's so compelling, is, like ``Elizabeth,'' a
film without mass distribution. While Meryl Streep was flawless as
a gallant mom dying of cancer in ``One True Thing,'' her film came
and went. Fine as Fernanda Montenegro is in ``Central Station,''
the limited circulation of her foreign-language film from Brazil
will cost it. My choice here is the obvious one, Gwyneth Paltrow's
radiant embodiment of ardent romantic yearning, as much in love
with theater as with Shakespeare in the universally and deservedly
beloved ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   I think the ``Shakepeare in Love'' wave will bring Dench the
best supporting actress Oscar. She doesn't have much screen time,
but she projects enormous zest as old Queen Bess, playing goddess
and enjoying every minute of it, contributing more than her share
of the high spirits that are sweeping ``Shakespeare in Love'' into
crossover popularity. There's something to be said for Kathy Bates
(``Primary Colors''), Brenda Blethyn (``Little Voice''), Lynn
Redgrave (``Gods and Monsters'') and Blanchett's Australian
compatriot, Rachel Griffiths (``Hilary and Jackie''). Joan Allen,
who would get my vote if she had been nominated, as she should have
been for her '50s mom afraid of change yet excited by it in
``Pleasantville,'' also deserves acclaim. But ``Saving Private
Ryan'' and ``Shakespeare in Love'' _ and its women _ are, I think,
going to be the big winners this year. But that's me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
