<HEADLINE>
NEW HAT IN DERBY RING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tired of trainer Bob Baffert winning the Kentucky Derby? Had
enough of D. Wayne Lukas? Want something new in the Derby picture?
Then try this: The Godolphin Stable, owned by Sheik Maktoum al
Maktoum, the ruler of Dubai, is going to take a big run at the May
1 Derby, and the wealthy outfit is going to do it in a way never
before attempted.
</P>
<P>
   Godolphin nominated eight horses to America's greatest race _
Aljabr, Always Believe, Breathtaking View, Chermes, Comeonmom,
Festive Bid, Prado's Landing, and Worldly Manner. Worldly Manner,
who used to be trained by Baffert and won the Del Mar Futurity
before Godolphin purchased him privately, is considered an
outstanding prospect. Comeonmom, who won the Remsen at Aqueduct
before being bought, also is promising.
</P>
<P>
   Making the situation even more intriguing, Godolphin racing
manager Simon Crisford intends to take a novel approach and will
not race any of the Godolphin nominees in the traditional Derby
preps held in the United States. Instead, they will run against
each other in at least two trial races at Nad al Sheba Race Course
in Dubai. Crisford will decide which of the sheik's horses will be
entered in the Derby based on those contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at the Kentucky Derby project very seriously,''
said Crisford. ``Obviously, this is one of the best races in the
world and it is a race in which we want to take part, and, more
than that, we want to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert has conditioned the last two Derby winners, Silver Charm
and Real Quiet, and is a nose short of having won three in a row,
as Grindstone just nipped his Cavonnier in the 1996 Run for the
Roses. Grindstone was, of course, trained by Lukas.
</P>
<P>
   For this year's 125th Derby, Baffert has five of the top
contenders. Exploit is the 8-1 choice in the advance betting
sponsored by Churchill Downs. General Challenge is 12-1, and Prime
Timber 20-1. Baffert also has the two most prominent fillies,
Silverbulletday, at 10-1, and Excellent Meeting at 15-1, although
he has insisted he will not run fillies in the Derby if his colts
are doing well.
</P>
<P>
   With Worldly Manner at 15-1 and Comeonmom at 30-1 in the
Churchill line, Godolphin has a long way to go to catch up with
Baffert. But, hey, it's different.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Canaveral grounded
</P>
<P>
   Team Lukas suffered a blow when Cape Canaveral, owned by
Overbrook Farms, suffered a stress fracture to his right front shin
and was declared out of the Derby. The son of Mr. Prospector had
won both of his starts impressively, most recently the San Miguel
Stakes at Santa Anita Jan. 9, but there was some question as to
whether the horse, which has high early speed, could handle a
distance of ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's doubtful that he'll need surgery, but the Derby is out,''
said Ric Waldman, general manager of Overbrook, adding that Cape
Canaveral would need several months to recover.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nothing ventured . . .
</P>
<P>
   Cape Canaveral was 15-1 in the Churchill odds. Churchill quickly
withdrew his name, and only $388 in advance bets were lost. A
winter book wager is a loser if the horse does not start . . . The
Dubai World Cup Committee invited 10 horses based in the United
States to the $5 million race March 28. On the list are defending
champion Silver Charm; Malek, who finished fourth last year; Puerto
Madero; Real Quiet; Event of the Year; Victory Gallop; Sir Bear;
Dr. Fong; Lazy Lode; and the filly Banshee Breeze. Of the 10, only
Event of the Year, Lazy Lode, and Banshee Breeze have been declared
out of the race . . . Countess Diana, the 2-year-old filly champion
of 1997, has returned to training at Hialeah. Countess Diana, who
had been plagued by ulcers and a weak cannon bone, has not raced
since finishing off the board in the Gazelle Handicap at Belmont
Sept. 12. ``She looks good and has gained back a lot of weight,''
said owner Rick Caster, who turned her over to trainer Mary Jo
Lohmeier. ``If she is anything less than 100 percent, she will not
race.'' . . . This turf writer voted for every Eclipse Award winner
announced Tuesday night and has nothing more to say on the subject,
other than: Congratulations to the winners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Schedule set
</P>
<P>
   Rockingham Park, which opens a 100-program meeting June 6, has
announced a stakes schedule of 12 races. The key events are the
$200,000 New Hampshire Sweesptakes, a Grade III event at a 1 1/8
miles on the turf June 19; the $75,000 Rock Breeders' Cup, at a
mile and one-16th on the grass for fillies and mares July 4; and
the $75,000 Spicy Living Sweepstakes, also for fillies and mares on
the grass, but at 1 1/8 miles Aug. 1. The other nine contests carry
a purse of $25,000 . . . Soldier Boy, a popular horse on the New
England circuit who won the Massachusetts Handicap in 1981, passed
away recently from colic at the age of 26. Soldier Boy, who was
bred in Kentucky, became a fixture in Massachusetts breeding after
his racing career ended and his progeny have earned more than $1
million. He was a versatile sort and set a grass course record at
Suffolk, going 7 1/2 furlongs in 1:33 3/5 in '81. Trained by Dom
Imprescia, Soldier Boy was off at 23-1 when he pulled the MassCap
shocker, becoming the first Boston-area horse to win the event in
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from racetrack publicity departments was used to prepare
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4462 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NHAMPSHIRE-PRIMARY-2N     02-22 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NHAMPSHIRE-PRIMARY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 NASHUA, N.H.: ... of alderman.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The growth is more of a negative on the city versus the
positive,'' Fredette said. ``With all the new homes and the
companies that have moved into the city, we have a lot more crime,
a lot more traffic and our roads aren't built to take the
traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Fredette said, is that the newcomers have arrived
partly because of New Hampshire's reputation as a low-tax state but
are upset when they encounter a lack of services. ``They want
everything they had in the last place, but they don't want to
pay,'' Fredette said. Fredette, a Republican and third-generation
native, said he would probably have been aghast at the idea of a
state income tax five years ago, but now he thinks it may be the
fairest way to solve the state's problems.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire is paying the price for what has long been a
source of pride and a drawing card: the lack of a general sales or
income tax. In 1997, the state Supreme Court ruled that the
reliance on property taxes for education is unfair, noting that
many students in poorer towns are not receiving as good an
education as those in richer towns. As a result, the Legislature is
struggling to come up with a tax system that will distribute the
levies more equitably and ensure a better education system.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to keeping alive the 4 percent income tax proposal,
the House approved a 25-cent-per-pack increase in the cigarette tax
and considered plans for a statewide property tax. Governor Jeanne
Shaheen said in an interview that she is keeping ``my options
open'' on an income tax, as she anticipates meeting the court
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   One of the clearest indications of New Hampshire's changing
makeup can be seen in the voter registration rolls. Just five years
ago, Republicans held a decisive edge, with 252,199 voters,
compared to 210,865 Democrats and 198,627 Independents. But by last
November, Independents had nearly become the majority. The 1998
registration included 272,115 Republicans, 271,715 Independents and
203,567 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire allows Independents to vote in either the
Democratic or Republican primary if they temporarily switch to a
party identification.
</P>
<P>
   That helps explain why presidential prospects such as Senator
John McCain, the Arizona Republican, believe they can do well in
New Hampshire. McCain, like his New Hampshire chaperone, former US
Senator Warren Rudman, is an independent-minded maverick who
believes the state's reputation for rock-ribbed conservativism is
misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and others could also be affected by the changes in media
power within the state. Two decades ago, the Union-Leader of
Manchester and its publisher, William Loeb, influenced many aspects
of state policy. Today, while the newspaper still has influence,
politicians can win without it, Rudman said. The center of media
power has shifted to Channel 9, which operates out of a graceful
new building in downtown Manchester notable for its architectural
bow to the city's historic red brick mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very different state than it was in the '70s,'' Rudman
said. ``People who campaigned there back then wouldn't recognize it
today. The state has become more like America. It has become more
affluent, more educated and less stable in terms of its
population.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's ethnic makeup has, however, changed little. Fewer
than 8,000 of New Hampshire's 1.1 million people are black, and
there are only 12,000 Asians. New Hampshire ``contines to change,
but so far not enough,'' said the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who
campaigned for president here in 1984 and 1988 and visited the
state this month amid speculation that he might run again.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson chastised lawmakers for allowing New Hampshire to be the
only state without a day honoring Martin Luther King. But in
another sign of shifting winds, the Legislature, pushed by Shaheen,
appears on the verge of joining the rest of the country in
approving the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire's defenders note that other states with much
larger minority populations offset the demographics of the Granite
State. For example, an early and possibly decisive primary will be
held in California, which has the nation's largest Hispanic and
Asian populations, and the third largest number of blacks.
California is scheduled to hold its primary on March 7. New
Hampshire may hold its primary on Feb. 22, 2000, but the date would
be moved up if other states try to hold their primaries earlier
than that. New Hampshire law requires that its primary be held a
week ahead of any other.
</P>
<P>
   With New Hampshire's economy in such good shape, the 2000
campaign is likely to be different from the last two campaigns
here, when many candidates focused on issues such as job loss and
free trade.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, conservative commentator Patrick Buchanan won the
primary, perhaps reinforcing the state's image as a bastion of the
right. But Buchanan won with only 27 percent of the vote. Two more
moderate candidates, Bob Dole and Lamar Alexander, picked up a
combined 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, many Republican prospects are once again
casting themselves as the most conservative candidate in New
Hampshire. These prospects, including Quayle, publisher Steve
Forbes and former Reagan aide Gary Bauer, expect that the most
conservative Republicans in the state will be the most active and
most likely to vote. But if all it took to win the New Hampshire
primary were the most conservative credentials, then the state's
own Senator Bob Smith would be riding high in the polls. Smith, who
barely won reelection in 1996, is considered a long shot. Texas
Governor George W. Bush, meanwhile, is touting his ``compassionate
conservatism,'' which may appeal to Independents.
</P>
<P>
   As for Elizabeth Dole, she could benefit from the electorate's
willingness to back women for high office.
</P>
<P>
   But the big question is whether the current fight over taxes
will have an effect on the presidential primary. Some argue that if
a broad-based tax is approved, it might spark some kind of voter
uprising that will benefit an anti-tax candidate. But others say
the battle has sensitized the citizenry to question any claim by a
presidential prospect that taxes can easily be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen, who helped engineer Gary Hart's 1984 primary victory,
warned against drawing any early conclusions. She noted that when
Alexander and Forbes tried to step into the state controversy over
taxes, ``they engendered some emnity for trying to tell us what to
do.'' Despite all the changes here, she said, the people of New
Hampshire haven't given up their treasured independence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
