A4464 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH-SEAT-BOS &LR;      02-22 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-SEAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SOUTH GOP LIKELY TO CHOOSE GINGRICH SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDY SPRINGS, Ga. _ In the first post-impeachment election,
voters in this suburban Xanadu of fashionable retail chains and
fast-food franchises north of Atlanta will elect a successor to
Newt Gingrich Tuesday. It is, by any measure, an inhospitable
starting point for the Democrats' drive to reconquer the House.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Isakson, a well-known Republican with 17 years in the
Georgia Legislature and two statewide campaigns behind him, is a
heavy favorite to win Gingrich's seat and maintain the GOP's hold
on a modernized version of the South.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-month campaign, Isakson said, ``Impeachment has
not come up in any forum I've attended. The only people who ask me
about it are the media.'' Instead, he said, he is questioned about
transportation issues, Social Security, taxes, and education, and
his reputation as a successful businessman and fiscal conservative
seems to fit the district's interests.
</P>
<P>
   The 6th Congressional District, which bites into four heavily
populated counties, is the antithesis of Tara, the mythical Georgia
plantation in ``Gone with the Wind.'' In the 25 years since Jimmy
Carter was governor, the area has grown from a rural hinterland
into a sprawling network of subdivisions and strip malls peopled
with newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a stereotypical, affluent American district, a
mainstream conservative district,'' said Whit Ayres, a Republican
pollster who moved from Iowa to make his own home here. Choosing
one suburb as an example, Ayres said: ``Five years ago half the
current voters in Alpharetta did not live in Georgia. They came
here for work from the Northeast, the Midwest, from other parts of
the South.''
</P>
<P>
   And they helped transform the old ``Solid South'' that once sent
only Democrats, albeit conservative Democrats, to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1996 book, ``Dixie Rising,'' Peter Applebome called Cobb
County, the epicenter of the district, ``Exhibit A'' of the
``South's death by bleaching'' into the ``Anywhere U.S.A. corporate
iconography of Bennigan's and Blockbuster Videos and Taco Bells.''
</P>
<P>
   In a state that is nearly 30 percent minority, the district
population is 90 percent white. Only 10 other congressional
districts in the country have a higher concentration of college
graduates. Of the 435 districts, Georgia's 6th ranks 23d nationally
in median family income. It votes 2-to-1 Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich moved to the 6th in 1992 to escape a redistricting
scheme to defeat him by the Democratic Legislature. He found the
area receptive. In a Republican primary that year, an opponent
accused Gingrich of ``carpetbagging.'' But the expression is not so
insulting here, and Gingrich went on to become speaker of the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the blame for Republican losses last November, Gingrich
quit. But Democrats will have to look elsewhere to pick up the six
seats they need to control the House, and their chances seem no
better in a second upcoming election. A district in Louisiana with
similar demographics will vote in May to replace Bob Livingston,
another Republican leader who fell victim to the politics of
personal exposure this winter and resigned after admitting to
having been unfaithful to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia's special, nonpartisan election, Isakson dominates a
field of seven candidates. If no one wins a majority Tuesday, a
runoff between the top two candidates will be held March 16.
</P>
<P>
   The only Democrat in the race is Gary ``Bats'' Pelphrey, who
made a weak challenge to Gingrich three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson's chief foe is Christina Jeffrey, a political science
professor at Kennesaw State University. She gained notoriety four
years ago when Gingrich named her House historian, then rescinded
the appointment after she was linked to anti-Semitic statements.
Her multimillion-dollar lawsuit against Gingrich and several
members of Congress is pending.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old Jeffrey is the favorite of the Christian
conservative movement and has drawn praise for her views from
publications like the Weekly Standard, though the magazine's
editors expect Isakson to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson's greatest concern, says said Bill Byrne, a Republican
and chairman of the Cobb County Commission, which administers local
government, is a low turnout. ``In a Republican primary, the
conservative wing dominates. . . . Johnny always had difficult
times in Republican primaries because of that. If he doesn't win
outright Tuesday, he'll lose the runoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Isakson has been endorsed by Gingrich. If elected, Isakson said
his voting record will be similar to Gingrich's, though his style
will not be as confrontational.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my conservative credentials,'' he said in an
interview, ``and I'm not going to be drawn into a war'' with the
far right. ``It's important to put a human face on issues important
to a fiscal conservative. If we can reduce welfare by putting
people to work, that's compassion. The best insurance against
unbridled entitlement programs is education.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke with pride of his consensus-building experiences in a
Georgia Legislature filled with Democrats, but scoffs at Jeffrey's
charge that he is tax-raising, closet liberal, and said: ``I'm not
going to get down to the depths of her level.''
</P>
<P>
   Isakson, 55, built a fortune in commercial real estate. He is
the grandson of a Swedish stonemason, rather than a descendant of
the Scots-Irish yeoman farmers indigenous to the area. His home, he
said, is ``Cobb County,'' rather than any incorporated town. He
moved from Atlanta 30 years ago. ``If you look at my neighbors,
only two out of 100 are from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he personified the 6th District, Isakson said, ``I
think I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
