<SLUG> BC-SCI-ELECTRIC-DRIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STRESSMOBILE' LEAVES HIM UPTIGHT IN BEVERLY HILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS _ Here is your basic uptight Yankee behind the
wheel of a cherry red sportscar, cruising down Santa Monica
Boulevard at sunset, just as the beautiful people start coming out
to see and be seen.
</P>
<P>
   And all I can think about is the number 19. That's how many
miles before my battery-powered EV1 runs out of juice, according to
the big, glowing gauge on the dashboard. If I run out, it's not
like I can get a can of gas; a tow truck would have to haul me to a
charging station.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should call this the stressmobile,'' says my passenger.
</P>
<P>
   But when we reach the crowded Century City Mall with juice to
spare, I begin to relax. There, like a red carpet rolled out before
me, is an ``electric vehicle only'' parking space near the door,
equipped with a battery charger to dispense free electricity while
I have dinner. This, I can get used to.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, driving an electric vehicle is a bit of an art.
You don't have 300 miles to the next re-fuelling (the EV1 gets 50
miles to the charge, the Honda EV Plus closer to 100), nor a
service station every few miles, so you plan trips from charging
break to charging break. A smart electric vehicle driver knows the
good restaurants near public charging stations.
</P>
<P>
   As a novice, I drove more than 250 miles each in the two main
electric vehicles available to California consumers, the EV1 and
Honda's EV Plus, and never ran out of charge. What's more, I
stopped worrying and found the charm of electric cars.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturn salesmen call it ``the EV1 smile,'' that look of
pleasure drivers get when the acceleration knocks them back on the
seat. With only a single gear, the electric drive system picks up
speed very smoothly, allowing the EV1 to leave other sports cars
behind in a turbo-hum not unlike the Batmobile.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a station wagon guy, but there's a likeable swagger to the
EV1's low-slung profile, reflective windows and Star Trekky
interior. I felt a swell of pride when a guy in the next car rolled
down his window and yelled, ``Where'd you get that car?''
</P>
<P>
   The EV Plus, by contrast, is a pokier, more family-friendly
vehicle, a two-door sedan that feels like a mini-van because the
seats are so far up off the road. Even though I drove the car in
Massachusetts _ where there are almost no public charging stations
_ I fretted less about running out of charge because of the more
powerful nickel-metal hydride battery.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the most striking thing about the EV Plus is how
ordinary it seems. Aside from quirks such as silent ignition, no
exhaust, and plug-in-at-home charging, the EV Plus drives much like
a gas-powered car.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's hard to think of these as real alternatives to
today's cars as long as the driving range is so limited, the prices
so high, and the charging system so embryonic. Joe, the guy at EV
Rental who rented me the EV1, had it about right when he told me,
``You are a pioneer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4466 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALASKAN-HERITAGE-RESE     02-22 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKAN-HERITAGE-RESEND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKAN CULTURES COME TOGETHER IN NEW ANCHORAGE CENTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Resent to restore dropped name in lede)  
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Perry Eaton peers intently at the map of Alaska
he has spread out before him. ``There are no roads ... here,'' he
says, applying his entire palm to the western portion of the state
with an audible slap.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to get from point to point out here is by air. Or
foot. Or boat. Or, during most of the year, something with runners
on it.
</P>
<P>
   And it might be difficult for residents of the lower 48 to
appreciate the vastness of these distances. Overlay this same map
on the contiguous United States, and Ketchikan is at Jacksonville,
Fla., Point Barrow is just a few miles south of Fargo, N.D., and
the Aleutian chain runs into the Pacific Ocean, 170 miles west of
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The geographic and meteorologic realities quickly conspire
against any tourist who wants to examine the native cultures of any
of Alaska's five main indigenous groups.
</P>
<P>
   The solution? Bring the groups to the tourist.
</P>
<P>
   The consummation of this plan is the Alaska Native Heritage
Center, which will open in Anchorage _ the state's largest city _
on May 1. Eaton, born into the Aleut/Alutiiq culture 54 years ago
on Kodiak Island, will serve as its president, and he could barely
contain his enthusiasm for the project on a recent visit to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   This won't be a static museum. Rather, representatives of each
native group will gather in village environments to build kayaks,
make moccasins, prepare food, sing, dance _ all for the purpose of
familiarizing outsiders with their worlds. Imagine a rough hybrid
of Williamsburg, Va., and Hawaii's Polynesian Cultural Center, but
established several latitude lines to the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call Alaska the last frontier,'' Eaton said, ``and, in that
regard, you can extend that assumption and say the indigenous
people there are on the frontier also. So if the visitor were
actually to go into the village, it would be like entering a
village in the frontier back at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alaska is unique in the American Indian experience because
there was no Indian removal here. These people are still residing
in our original villages, so the context of the culture is unique
to America. What we're endeavoring to do with the center is bring
you closer to that original baseline culture and share some of the
real beauty of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The center, a nonprofit educational enterprise with
representatives of all five native regions on its board, will be
housed on a 26-acre site on the northeastern edge of the city.
Tourists will first enter the Welcome House, a 26,000-square-foot
structure containing interpretative displays, a theater and an area
for dance performances and storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this building will be a small lake, surrounded by
re-creations of villages. A walking path, which will be
wheelchair-accessible, will connect them.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will be able to survey working environments for all
five major cultures: Athabascan from central Alaska; Yup'ik/Cup'ik
from the west; Inupiaq/St. Lawrence Island Yupik from the north;
Aleut/Alutiiq from the Aleutian Island chain in the southwest; and
the Eyak, Tlingit, Haida and Tsimshian peoples from the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to present ourselves as a live, living, functional
culture,'' said Eaton, an Anchorage banker who has been active in
native affairs throughout his career. He cited several examples:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A woman making moccasins won't be behind glass. You're going
to walk in and have a conversation with her. She'll tell you about
the deer hide, where she gets it today, where she got it yesterday,
where her mother got it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``You might see how different cultures treat salmon. In
August, we will be splitting fish and drying fish, and different
cultures have different ways of doing it. We might even ask you to
help.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``You might see some elders teaching some youth on
kayak-building. You don't just get to see it made, you get to see
the sharing and how it comes down traditionally between the
generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton added: ``We want you to know that we still make these
things. This is not a dead culture in which you're going to handle
artifacts from many years ago. And the goal of the center is to
celebrate and to perpetuate and to share the traditions. We want
you to see us the way we are.''
</P>
<P>
   For some visitors, some of those details might be shocking, even
troubling, but that will be part of the educational process, too.
Native Alaskans hunt whales, seals and sea otters for food and
other products. It's an integral part of a cycle of sustenance that
has been in place for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton, who admitted that the seal and sea otter harvests, for
example, are conducted ``out of sight,'' was asked if some
urbanites would be horrified by the practice. ``Totally,'' he said,
``and that's a real dilemma. And that's real important for the
center to educate (outsiders). There is no shortage of seals, and
we don't go around clubbing the babies the way the Canadians do.
And we don't just harvest them for the hides. And it's not in any
danger at all. But because of perception, it makes it very
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alaska Native Heritage Center will seek to convey these
messages, among many others. These native people, according to
center officials, are under tremendous pressure from policies made
thousands of miles away in Washington, D.C. When a duck-hunting
season is defined, and bag limits are set, what specific impact
does that have on an Inupiaq village along the Colville River in
northern Alaska?
</P>
<P>
   This might provide a prime opportunity to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need to go to the Amazon rain forest to find
indigenous people who are threatened in their environment,'' Eaton
said. ``It's right here in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The project is being launched in part as a response to surveys
conducted by Alaska tourism officials. Visitors, it was learned,
have a profound curiosity about native life in this largely
untracked wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Morris, of the Anchorage Convention and Visitors Bureau,
said, ``When visitors come to Alaska, they're looking for scenery,
wildlife and native culture. You can usually guarantee the first
two, but people just don't have the time or energy or wherewithal
to get out to the different villages.''
</P>
<P>
   Another anticipated benefit of the center will be to provide an
environment in which the native groups themselves can interact and
share experiences. Those vast distances and forbidding conditions
have prevented them from having significant contact, too.
</P>
<P>
   But the primary function is tourism. The entrance fee will be
$20 for adults and $15 for children under 12, and center officials
have wisely worked with cruise lines to set up shore excursions for
passengers. One agreement is already in place with Princess, and
final details of another are being worked out with Holland America.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how outsiders get there, the center's leaders are
seeking to make the experience a profound one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
