<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ELECTRIC-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUCK IN PARK 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Actress Jasmine Bleeth drives a slick electric car
in the TV show ``Nash Bridges.'' The cinematographer for the
program ``Star Trek Voyager'' loves his electric so much he made
radio ads touting the technology. The film editor for the series
``Ellen'' drove his electric car halfway across the country just to
show it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   If Hollywood were the battleground in the crusade to switch
California automobiles from smog-causing gasoline to emission-free
battery power, the war might be over. The biggest challenge to the
internal combustion engine's supremacy in decades, watched closely
across the country, has lots of celebrity endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part is convincing everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after Saturn dealers began selling the first mass
production electric cars here, they have made almost no impact on
ordinary Californians. Fewer than 2,000 are on the roads, a far cry
from the 20,000 vehicles regulators once hoped to see sold in 1998
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the obstacles to building an electric vehicle that
is both affordable and high-performing become clear, officials have
twice retreated from regulations that would have mandated the sale
of more than 250,000 electric vehicles by 2003. Now, the
requirement has been cut to just over 40,000, and the state
increasingly emphasizes other types of ``clean'' cars.
</P>
<P>
   Most wounding have been the brickbats from the media, which has
been widely skeptical of vehicles that cost more than comparable
gas-burning cars and must recharge for an hour or more after less
than 100 miles of driving. Electric vehicle advocates, already
battling powerful oil and auto interests, had counted on a friendly
press to get the word out that electric cars are a fun and clean
way to meet most driving needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a vicious attack, and I don't really understand
the agenda,'' said Kris Trexler, the Emmy Award-winning film editor
for the series ``Ellen'' and a big fan of the EV1 electric car sold
by Saturn. ``The public is totally naive,'' he says, in part
because the media hasn't educated them.
</P>
<P>
   Three thousand miles away in Massachusetts, state officials can
only watch and hope. Former governor William Weld was one of the
nation's top boosters of electric cars, going to court to defend a
mandate identical to California's. But a quirk in federal law
forced Massachusetts to drop its requirement until 2003, and that
made California the nation's testing ground.
</P>
<P>
   But, far from giving up, government agencies, utilities,
environmentalists and some corporations here are pressing ahead to
lay the foundation for an electric future. More than 300 public
charging stations have been set up at parking lots, agencies such
as the US Postal Service are buying electrics, and the first
electric car rental agency just opened in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an uphill fight all the way,'' said electric car
pioneer Clare Bell as she assembled a Xebra, a new electric
sportscar already getting TV exposure on ``Nash Bridges.'' ``We
were really looked at as fringe loonies not so long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   To Bell and other fans, the long range outlook for electric
vehicles is good, as oil supplies dwindle and their ``clean fun''
message gets out, but the fight won't be won quickly. They point
out that other technological breakthroughs, from the personal
computer to the advent of the automobile itself, took decades to
win wide public acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why else would we be willing to throw $1 billion away with no
chance of getting it back? We want to be the Xerox of the electric
vehicle industry,'' said Robert Randall, Saturn and GM's chief of
electric vehicle sales in southern California, referring to the
company that pioneered and for many years dominated the photocopier
business.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of less environmentally pure but more practical
alternatives are challenging electrics to be the car of the future
_ from vehicles running on natural gas, to cars that are
part-electric/part-gas, to cleaner versions of the gas-powered cars
that own the roads now.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, electric vehicle developers face the risk that,
unless costs come down and driving range increases, their products
could end up less like Xerox and more like the eight-track tape
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that the automobile represents freedom, battery
vehicles just cannot be successful at the present level of
technology,'' says Eric Noble, an industry analyst at AutoPacific
Inc. in Santa Ana.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the EV1 represents the return of electric cars to
the American landscape. Early in the century, before the low cost
Model T revolutionized transportation, electrics were a popular
alternative to loud, smelly, breakdown-prone gas-powered cars. But
batteries simply didn't have the power of gasoline, and, by 1915,
less than 2 percent of US autos were electric.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-five years later, however, American cities were reaping
the smoggy harvest of millions of internal combustion engines. Los
Angeles, surrounded by hills that trap air pollution, became the
nation's smog capital, suffering more than 150 unhealthy air days
each year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
