<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4468 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ELECTRIC-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     02-22 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ELECTRIC-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 LOS ANGELES: ... each year.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In response, the California Air Resources Board ordered major
automakers to begin by 1998 to sell ``zero emissions vehicles,'' a
category that only electric cars could satisfy. Electrics are so
clean they don't even need a tailpipe, though generating the
electricity that goes into the batteries usually pollutes.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers fought the requirement, but General Motors, which had
dabbled in electric cars since the 1960s, quickly emerged as the
industry leader. While others retooled existing models in an
attempt to meet the law, GM designed a brand new car, the
futuristic, two-seat EV1. With its aerodynamic shape and powerful
acceleration, the EV1 drew crowds wherever it went, and GM decided
to test market the cars in Arizona and California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vehicle represents a wonderfully well-integrated new mode
of transportation,'' said Michael Gage, president of the
alternative car development consortium Calstart, in 1996. ``It's
what a compact disc is to a long-play record.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. From the beginning, the EV1 had a limited market,
because it had only two seats, a $34,000 sticker price, and a
real-life range of only 50 miles before recharging.
</P>
<P>
   However, Saturn strategists hoped there were enough affluent,
environmentally conscious technology buffs in trend-setting
California to make the vehicle a success. The likely customer,
Saturn calculated, was male, well educated, earning $150,000 a
year, and owning several cars already.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the people who spent $1,000 for a VCR or bought cell
phones the size of a suitcase,'' said salesman Randall. ``They are
willing to take a chance to be first.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a lease rate of roughly $520 a month, Saturn has found so
far only 600 customers, a drop in the bucket compared to the
million new cars sold in California each year, and less than many
people connected with the program had hoped. But those who do buy
are among the most loyal customers in automotive history.
</P>
<P>
   Trexler loves his EV1's near-silent power and makes a game of
leaving sports cars in the dust at stop lights. To underscore the
durability of the EV1, he set off on a highly publicized
3,000-mile-trip from California to Michigan, lining up scores of
recharging stops and posting his trip journal on the web.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think it's more amazing than I did,'' recalls
Trexler. ``I just had a good, fun vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Other drivers have been no less enthusiastic, copying Trexler's
feat, defending the cars publicly and forming an active EV1 club.
In addition, celebrity EV1 drivers such as actors Ted Danson, Danny
DeVito and Ed Begley Jr. gave the vehicle cachet.
</P>
<P>
   But other major carmakers have made little attempt to reach
consumers, preferring to concentrate on businesses and governments
that use fleets of vehicles over short distances. When the state
dropped the requirement that 2 percent of 1998 new vehicles run on
batteries, carmakers scaled back even more.
</P>
<P>
   Only Honda has joined GM in pitching to consumers, selling a
more family-friendly sedan called EV Plus. However, the company
made just 300 of them and does little promotion. At Honda of
Hollywood, salesmen said only one customer has ever asked about the
EV Plus.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, carmakers have sold or leased between 1,000 and
2,000 electrics in California, which the Los Angeles Times called
``dismal public acceptance of battery-powered vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   But electric car advocates say it is too soon to write them off.
They admit the original electric vehicle sales quotas were too
ambitious, but they say the regulations set off a wave of
innovation that the public has scarcely seen.
</P>
<P>
   At Calstart's alternative vehicle research and development
facility in Alameda, for instance, a Norwegian company called PIVCO
just completed tests of a plastic-bodied two-seat car that would
sell for $18,000 or less. Though critics say the small, low speed
vehicle won't sell here, Ford just bought a controlling interest in
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the city of Alameda is supporting research on a
zinc-air battery system that propelled a postal van more than 1,000
miles before the drivers quit. ``Frankly, I think they were just
getting tired of driving 35 miles per hour in a big circle,'' said
Jim Baak of the city's Bureau of Electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with many improvements is cost. General Motors will
soon offer EV1s equipped with new nickel-metal hydride batteries
that double its current 50 miles per charge range, but the sticker
price is $9,000 higher, too. And that's a bargain since the battery
packs cost $35,000 apiece to make.
</P>
<P>
   Some engineers suspect there won't be a battery that is both
powerful and affordable enough before 2010. Donald R. Sadoway,
materials science professor at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, told Design News magazine that researchers are caught
``in the scientific equivalent of quicksand.''
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a breakthrough, environmentalists and public
officials increasingly promote ``hybrid'' vehicles that have both a
gas engine and an electric motor, giving them greater driving range
but less emissions than conventional vehicles. Toyota is already
selling such a hybrid, the Prius, in Japan, and the company plans
to offer it here next year.
</P>
<P>
   To ease the way for hybrids' introduction, the California Air
Resources Board voted last November to allow carmakers to meet most
of their 10 percent ``zero emissions'' sales quota in 2003 with a
patchwork of low-polluting vehicles such as the Prius, rather than
insisting on pure electric vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But electric advocates say hybrids should be seen as only a
bridge to cleaner electric vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   With hybrids, ``you still have oil and exhaust and heat being
produced,'' said Edmund Fitzgerald, fleet manager for Costco
stores, which strongly supports electric vehicles. ``I don't want
it cleaner. I want it clean.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, electric vehicle supporters continue the unglamorous
work of installing charging stations, confident that their day will
come, though perhaps later than they once hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to predict the development of technology,'' said
Roland Hwang of the Union of Concerned Scientists. ``If we're off
by 5 years, that isn't such a bad thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
