<HEADLINE>
FOR FREQUENT FLIERS, IRS PAYMENT OPTION ADDS INSULT TO INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Doug Randlett heard about a new IRS program allowing people
to pay their federal taxes this year with a credit card, he got all
excited about a windfall of frequent-flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, he thought, earning frequent-flier miles by paying with
his credit card would take the sting out of his hefty tax bill this
year, which totaled $25,000 because of a major sell-off of assets
in preparation for his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger ouch was yet to come. When the Milton, Mass. man
called American Express to get the details of the program, he
learned that putting $25,000 of Internal Revenue Service tax debt
on his card would come with a $656 ``convenience fee'' imposed by
the credit card issuer and a third-party processor of the
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   That more than wiped out any advantage of paying by plastic: For
the 25,000 frequent-flier miles he would earn toward a free
domestic round-trip ticket, he could buy such a ticket for much
less than $656.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a stupid arrangement,'' said Randlett, a newly
retired food distributor. ``There's no advantae to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with only a few exceptions, there seems no reason for
people to consider this IRS pilot program, which is run primarily
by US Audiotex and accepts American Express, MasterCard, and
Discover. (Visa declined to take part this year.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a lousy deal,'' said Gerri Detweiler, education
adviser for Debt Counselors of America in Rockville, Md., and
author of the Ultimate Credit Handbook.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're a convenience credit-card user (you pay off your
balance each month) or a revolving card user (you routinely carry a
balance and pay interest on the borrowed amount), we find most
people are better off writing a check to Uncle Sam or, if you don't
have the cash, borrowing from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts state taxes, however, are a different story. If
you file your state return by phone, you can charge your tax
balance on Visa or Mastercard with no extra fees.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS payment program, however, comes with the sizable
``convenience'' fee of anywhere from 1.5 percent to 3 percent of
the total tax bill. This is because federal law prohibits the
government from coughing up the usual fees merchants pay when
accepting a credit card. So these fees get passed on to the
consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the average tax balance last year was about
$2,700. If you called US Audiotex to charge that balance, you would
gain 2,700 miles on your frequent-flier program or _ assuming
frequent-flier miles are generally worth about 2 cents a mile _ a
$54 value. But your convenience fee would be $68.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're willing to pay this extra money for the
frequent-flier miles, make sure your particular card gives miles
for tax payments. While American Express and Discover seem to treat
tax payments like any other charge, a MasterCard spokesman
indicated to us that some of its affiliated frequent-flier programs
may consider tax payments differently.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have the cash to pay your IRS tax bill in April,
you're generally better off borrowing from the federal government
than charging it on your credit card. Currently, the average
interest rate on a credit card is roughly 18 percent. Compare that
to the IRS installment plan that comes with a 7 percent interest
rate, which is a bargain even if you factor in the $43 one-time
installment fee and the .25 percent failure-to-pay additional
charge imposed each month on the outstanding tax balance.
</P>
<P>
   One economically distressed group may benefit from the charge-it
plan: Those who are rejected for the IRS installment plan.
</P>
<P>
   One other angle: According to credit card analysts, once a
person declares bankruptcy, taxes owed to the IRS are debts that
follow that person for a lifetime. But credit card bills, which are
unsecured debts, could be wiped away under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   For those at the other end of the economic spectrum, such as a
taxpayer who owes the IRS close to $100,000, you may find the
avalanche of frequent-flier miles will earn you a first-class or
business-class international ticket. And the value of that ticket
may far exceed the convenience fee.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if you need just a few thousand extra miles to earn a free
ticket, you may not mind paying the extra convenience fee to get
that free trip.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the financial rewards of the IRS credit-card program are
not great, there may be psychological benefits. If you think of the
IRS as a heartless bully, you may prefer to owe money to a
commercial bank than the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Still, credit card analysts say most people should just pay with
an old-fashioned check. ``For most consumers, it's not worth the
trouble,'' said Robert McKinley, president of CardWeb Inc., which
tracks the credit card industry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fuming over bank fees
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russell Gale was fuming last week when he received a letter from
BankBoston informing him that he would be slapped with a $15 fee if
he uses the overdraft protection offered by the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The new fee takes effect in April. Currently, depositors who
have overdraft protection can write a check for more money than
they have in their checking account and the bank will cover it. The
bank charges interest on the loaned amount, but the interest is
usually far less than the $22 penalty for a bounced check.
</P>
<P>
   Now BankBoston says it will charge a $15 annual fee if overdraft
protection is used. Tisha Capello, the bank's director of consumer
product management, said 60 percent of the bank's customers use the
overdraft protection at least once a year.
</P>
<P>
   Capello said the new fee was necessary because overdraft
protection generated a lot of work for the bank but little income.
She said the average outstanding overdraft was $300. She asserted
the fee is comparable to what other banks charge and is imposed
only if the service is used.
</P>
<P>
   But Gale was still fuming. He said the bank may not be making
much money on overdraft protection now, but the new fee will ensure
it does in the future. He said he believes the proliferation of
banking fees is a byproduct of past banking mergers that have
reduced competition in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Magazine expiration dates
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seemed reasonable that when you sign up for a year's
subscription of a weekly magazine, you would expect 52 issues to be
mailed to your door.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Toney Hopkins expected when she signed up for Time
magazine. In fact, she paid for two years and expected to get 104
issues lasting until February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   After a column we wrote about the need to check expiration dates
on mailing labels, she found her expiration dates on that two-year
subscription kept shifting to earlier dates. It started accurately
as February 2000, but then last spring the expiration date on the
mailing label said January 2000 and as of last December, it was
December 1999.
</P>
<P>
   What gives?
</P>
<P>
   When we called Time magazine, Ken Godshall, vice president of
circulation for the company, said special issues released each
year, which can be put out based on news events, count toward the
52 issues in a year. They can even release a special double-issue,
which will count as two issues.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, a customer's expiration date can shift earlier and
earlier depending on the number of special issues the company
chooses to release in a given year. In the last 12 months, for
example, he said Time had three double-issues, mostly as part of
its Time 100 series that featured prominent Americans in this
century. Customers would have found their expiration date adjusted
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   While he said the company ``attempts to communicate this to
subscribers,'' he acknowledged that some may not realize the length
of their subscription may be adjusted. He said that if subscribers
complain, the magazine will attempt to satisfy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to consider adding an issue or two just to keep
their business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
