<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENDER-GAMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRLS GET BARBIE, BOYS GET SKILLS, THRILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago, the creation of computer games was heralded as a
fresh chance to break out of the gender-tracking mold and create
entertainment designed for boys and girls, equally.
</P>
<P>
   But all one need do is look at the top selling girl games today
to know that the opportunity is passing us by.
</P>
<P>
   The market is dominated by a plastic doll that has been around
for 40 years. In fact, the top six selling computer games for girls
in 1998 were all Barbie games. PC Data, a market research firm,
says that among the top sellers are Barbie Nail Designer and Barbie
Magic Hairstyler. And then there is the computer game juggernaut,
Barbie's Fashion Designer, which sold an astounding 500,000 copies
in the first two months it was released. The object of the game? To
design clothes that can be printed out and used on a Barbie doll.
</P>
<P>
   So, one might argue, at least girls are using computers _ a
pastime that many still think of as a boy's domain _ and becoming
acquainted with the software, right? But those who study the issue
say that the most of computer games being marketed for girls tend
to instill stereotyped gender messages and develop different skills
than boys' games do.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, manufacturers have even slowed down the action on some
of the games designed for girls, making them less challenging than
the standard-issue games.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Miranker, a children's software specialist and co-curator
of the Children's Gallery in the Boston Computer Museum, says that,
for the most part, the computer games marketed to girls are ``not
exemplars of what is exciting in the world of computing, although
they might be exciting in the world of marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jo Sanders, director of the Center for Gender Equity at the
Washington Research Institute in Seattle, takes it a step further.
``It makes you absolutely gag,'' she says. ``Computer games like
Barbie reinforce the dimension of girls that has nothing to do with
their role in the world and everything to do with their personal
private sphere of appearance. This is not healthy in 1999 for girls
to be focusing so exclusively on themselves as opposed to the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   For boys _ who use computers in the classroom and in
after-school programs much more frequently than girls _ games are
frequently a virtual world where the enemy is vanquished, where
space is explored and aliens are battled, where blood and violence
spreads across the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Whether violent games are appropriate amusements for young boys
is a matter of some debate _ some would say as debatable as an
afternoon spent with Barbie _ but what concerns many is the
different experiences that youngsters take from the games and carry
through life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble is that to the extent that computer games are a
stand-in, or a precursor, for a skill that can later affect our
economic life, it matters if they are sex-segregated,'' says
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   So if sex-segregated computer games are a problem, who is to
blame? Barbie and Barbie-type computer games dominate the market
because that is what manufacturers know will sell. In the
competitive world of computer game marketing, one can hardly expect
them to think or act otherwise. After all, games that do not sell
quickly lose their shelf space to more popular titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry finds one thing, sports or action, and does it
over and over and over,'' says Henry Jenkins, a Massachusetts
Institute of Technology professor and co-editor of the new book
``From Barbie to Mortal Kombat: Gender and Computer Games.'' ``The
energy for change comes from smaller start-ups.'' Jenmkins says.
``What is exciting about the girl games movement is that a lot of
start-ups are trying different things.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they survive, then their impact will force change and could
well lead to a more androgynous games,'' Jenkins says. ``If they
are bought up too quickly, then it is quite possible we will have
Barbie and Doom and nothing in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   The news last week on the survival front was not good. Purple
Moon _ a California-based company that has been touted as a model
in the world of computer game producers marketing games exclusively
for 8- to 12-year-old girls _ announced Thursday that it was
shutting down immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using an established character, Purple Moon had
gained acclaim for how it researched the ways girls play, and then
developed new multicultural characters for games heavy on
decision-making as well as narrative and relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The company created the Rockett Movado series of games. In the
game called Rockett's New School, for example, the player
experiences a first day in eighth grade and has to make a series of
decisions that affect Rockett's emotions on her first day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is highly original compared to most of the other
girl-oriented product out there,'' says Miranker. ``It was
tremendously courageous thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But such acclaim was, apparently, not enough to keep the company
up and running. In a terse press release it announced that it had
``ceased operations and laid off all its employees.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While computer games are still a relatively new medium, they
bring with them all the baggage of the toy industry. And there are
few things in our culture are more biased than toys and games.
</P>
<P>
   The dearth of female action figures in computer games _ as in
regular action figure play _ is an ongoing concern for some parents
and educators, given that the boys playing the games today will be
the colleagues on the job of tomorrow. The lack of strong female
characters, the kind that boys will eventually come to know in the
office or workplace, does not serve boys or girls well.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, says Jenkins, ``The issue of violence in video games
for boys may be overblown. . . . There may be a real argument that
women need to play with power to prepare for the professional world
where they are competing with men, guys who were raised on blowing
up planets.''
</P>
<P>
   Boys, certainly, should be able to play games that offer more
than the chance to satisfy a trigger-happy urge. ``They should have
games that have deep interactivity and hard fun,'' says Justine
Cassell, an MIT professor and co-editor, with Jenkins, of ``From
Barbie to Mortal Kombat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason girl games came on the market was that studies
showed that spatial skills and hand-eye coordinations improved by
playing computer games, and any computer game meant a boy's game.''
So games targeted at girls were created, says Cassell, and ``for
the most part, girls' games teach about social relationships and
boys' games teach about power and mastery.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassell says there is a contingent of women who thrive on
playing computer games that are normally considered boys' games.
These so-called Game Grrls stress female empowerment throught
competing with men and ``fragging'' them.
</P>
<P>
   And there is at least one female action figure in the virtual
world, Lara Croft. The hero of Tomb Raider games, Croft is a female
Indiana Jones, an archeologist who can shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a strong action protagonist for girls with a larger-
than-life embodiment of female competence. She can handle a gun,
she can take back the night,'' says Jenkins. ``On the other hand,
she is designed by men to reflect an erotic fantasy and they don't
yet trust the girl market to support the product.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins and Cassell assert that male dominance in ``high power
computer jobs is not accidental. Computer and video games provide
an easy lead-in to computer literacy, and so those children who
aren't playing them at young ages may end up disadvantaged in later
years.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason alone, getting girls to use computers, to feel
comfortable around them, is worthwhile. And if Barbie is the
conduit, they say, then so be it.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, while boys' games remain firmly anchored in a
virtual world, Barbie's Designer Fashion game creates something _
dolls' clothes _ that is then used in the real world. ``I think
that opens up the prospect of thinking about computers a little
differently,'' says Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   But should there even be girl games, if so many of them create a
learning ghetto? Cassell would like to rephrase the question:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if the question is `do there have to be games for
girls,' the answer is `yes,' she says. ``Do they have to be girl
games? No.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
