A4478 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-22 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS AMNESIA IS THE SHOCKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, you were ``horrified'' to discover that the
Massachusetts child protection agency doesn't protect children.
</P>
<P>
   This week, you are ``appalled'' to discover that the
Massachusetts board responsible for physician discipline has never
met a doctor it didn't like.
</P>
<P>
   What's next, Governor Cellucci? Next week, will you be
``shocked'' to discover that the Massachusetts welfare department
is hostile to the poor?
</P>
<P>
   I thought you were the fellow elected last November on the
strength of his experience as William Weld's ``co-governor?'' No
emasculated lieutenant, you. You and Weld assured voters that you
co-captained this ship of state for eight years, filling its sails
with hot air about reducing the role of government, deregulating
business, and privatizing services to those most in need.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it just a little disingenuous now to express surprise at
where you've steered us?
</P>
<P>
   You were in charge during myriad reviews of the long
dysfunctional state Department of Social Services. Didn't you read
those blue-ribbon reports of understaffing, inadequate resources,
and politically-driven management?
</P>
<P>
   You were also in charge during multiple investigations of the
state Board of Registration in Medicine. Didn't you read those
blue-ribbon reports of understaffing, inadequate resources, and
politically-driven management?
</P>
<P>
   Did you forget the audit that found a backlog of almost 1,000
complaints against physicians? Did you forget the report that
concluded the panel failed to protect the public from incompetent,
negligent or exploitive doctors?
</P>
<P>
   You tell us you are irate to learn that the board took no action
against Dr. Marcos Ramos of Boston, who was indicted this week for
the rape of one patient and the sexual molestation of three others.
Ten other women have come forward in the last few days also to
accuse Ramos of misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this is news to your physician-dominated medical
board _ its members all gubernatorial appointees. Over the years,
it received 15 complaints about Ramos. It dismissed 13 of them and
took no action on the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Were you this irate in 1996 when the medical board announced it
was de-emphasizing its investigation of sexual misconduct
complaints to concentrate on cases of substandard care? If memory
serves, you were silent on that policy shift. Do you expect us now
to exempt you from responsibility for it?
</P>
<P>
   Were you this irate when the board engineered a change in its
conflict of interest provision to allow relatives of doctors to be
appointed to the only two consumer slots on the seven-member board?
</P>
<P>
   The physician bias of the Massachusetts medical board is a
longstanding national disgrace. For the last decade, it has
consistently ranked near the bottom of surveys by both the
Federation of State Medical Boards and the Public Health Citizen
Research Group for its record of serious disciplinary action. The
latter group ranked the state 45th in 1997. (Since Massachusetts
ranked 48th in 1993, I await your press release noting that all
progress is incremental.)
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has more doctors per capita than any other state,
as well as many of the nation's premier hospitals, medical schools,
and research centers. That equals economic and political clout for
doctors and impotence for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   That power imbalance did not begin with Weld and Cellucci, of
course. It began almost as soon as the Legislature established the
Board of Registration and Discipline in Medicine in 1975. The word
discipline was deleted from the board's title in 1979 after Dr.
Louis Alfano, then president of the Massachusetts Medical Society,
called the use of it an ``affront.''
</P>
<P>
   For a brief period in the mid-1980s, the board did its job.
Under the direction of Barbara Neuman, it took serious action
against 117 doctors. (Last year, it took similar actions in only 38
cases.) Doctors reacted with fury, calling the board a ``star
chamber'' and a ``scalp-hunter.'' Governor Dukakis buckled. Neuman
was fired. By 1990 the number of disciplinary actions had dropped
to 40.
</P>
<P>
   Under Weld-Cellucci, the medical board _ like DSS _ operates in
the shadows until a scandal drags its ineptitude into the
spotlight. It is crisis management and the governor is right: We
should be horrified and appalled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
