<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4479 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-MILLIMETE     02-22 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MILLIMETER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EIGHT MILLIMETER' OFFERS A BIT OF DEJA VU FOR DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In his new film, ``Eight Millimeter,'' director
Joel Schumacher takes Nicolas Cage on a journey into the abyss, an
exploration of the dark subculture of pornography, kinky sex,
addictions and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   If there's one person who would seem to be a fitting guide for
Cage, it's the filmmaker himself, who knows a thing or two about
hell.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher's father died when he was 4. At 9, he started
drinking. He had sex at 11, and was on drugs and out of the family
house in Brooklyn the summer he turned 16. Schumacher knows about
survival, even if it took him more than 40 years to clean up.
</P>
<P>
   Lounging in an over-stuffed chair in the Presidential Suite of
the Century Plaza Hotel, decked out in a casual-chic black sport
coat over a T-shirt, Schumacher's tough road is easy to read in the
lines surrounding eyes that peek out from his long, gray-black
hair. But any new lines are more likely to have been etched by his
constant laugh. He'll be 60 this year, he's turned out blockbusters
like ``Batman Forever'' and ``A Time to Kill,'' and he's excited
about his latest release.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conversations around this film tend to be a lot more
interesting,'' he says with deliberate understatement about a work
that involves Cage's character's attempts to learn if a ``snuff
film'' _ a filmed murder _ is real. The path to discovery is
littered with hustlers and junkies, and Schumacher carried both
labels for parts of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hustled in the sense that I always had to find a way to eat,
a way to afford my habit,'' Schumacher admits. ``Did I ever sell my
body for money? Yeah, but in slightly different ways. I was never
out there standing on the street corner, flagging cars. But I would
pick people up and have sex with them if they would buy me a meal
or give me some money. Being a drug addict for years you do a lot
of things you might not be too proud of.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to AA, they tell you that all addicts are liars,
cheats, thieves and whores, and that if you can't accept that, you
won't make it. I was just like, `Yep, that's me all right.' It's
true, you put your addiction before your kids or your lover or your
wife or your God,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   One cold winter day in January 1970, Schumacher went out to
Central Park and dug a deep hole and buried all of his needles
along with the rest of his works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dug way down so no other sorry soul would find my stuff and
use them,'' he says. ``But my problem was, I thought, `Well, OK,
I'm over that now. What's wrong with a few drinks and some
recreational drugs now and then?' Only it wasn't `now and then.' I
beat that one habit, but it took me a very long time to get
clean.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other moments during the filming of ``8MM'' that
blurred the line between fiction and reality. Schumacher used a lot
of sex-industry actors and actresses to simulate the pornographic
action necessary to push the plot. But for one scene that required
sadomasochism, things got a bit too real.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two dominatrixes came in and they brought their own
slave,'' Schumacher recalls. ``He had paid them something like $250
to carry all their suitcases and be humiliated. Well, they stripped
him down to a little black G-string, tied him up, put a ball gag in
his mouth, wrapped Saran Wrap around his head with just a tiny
opening to breathe through and just proceeded to beat the living
tar out of him. It was the only point in the movie where it was not
a movie anymore _ we were watching somebody's pathology.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher credits screenwriter Andrew Kevin Walker, who also
wrote ``Seven'' in 1995, with creating an original work that helped
lure an excellent cast. He also said he had no problem with the
premise of using a snuff film to anchor a plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``As opposed to what, cannibalism in `Silence of the Lambs?'''
he laughs. ``This movie works on a lot of levels, it's a thriller,
a private-eye story, one man's journey to a dark place. But it
takes a turn that's very unusual. Most scripts are retreads or
recycled schlock. I'd never seen something like this before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1338EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4481 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-22 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH LAWS NEEDED TO TAKE POLITICS OUT OF IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the impeachment trial that never should have been is
over, scholars should ponder how Andrew Johnson and William
Jefferson Clinton _ and the Congresses that impeached them _ should
be characterized in history and textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, it seemed that every mention of Johnson was
followed by the phrase ``the only President to be impeached.'' Now
Clinton is often referred to as ``only the second President to be
impeached.'' Both men wear their descriptions much like Hester
Prynne was forced by the Puritans to wear the scarlet ``A.''
</P>
<P>
   The labels unfairly punish Johnson and Clinton, whose
impeachments had more to do with the twisted motives of a partisan
Congress than their own shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's time for historians, and the journalists whose
stories will become part of our history, to put this issue in
proper perspective. Perhaps it's time to reconsider who should wear
these labels.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``impeachment'' should no longer be given the respect
or weight that our well-intentioned founding fathers _ who would no
doubt shudder to discover how both Congresses reduced the
impeachment process to a partisan political weapon _ once gave it.
</P>
<P>
   While both Johnson's and Clinton's staunchest critics believed
they should be impeached and removed from office, a wiser mind in
the Johnson impeachent, and wiser senators in the Clinton case, saw
the damage done by trying to remove a president on charges that did
not come close to the ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' envisioned
by the authors of the impeachment language.
</P>
<P>
   As history has proved, Johnson never should have been impeached,
and the motives for his removal were purely political. And Clinton
should never have been impeached, never mind removed, for his
adulterous sexual conduct with Monica Lewinsky, as reckless and
dishonoring as it was to the office.
</P>
<P>
   At most, Clinton should have been censured, as the Democrats
proposed. But Republicans saw an opportunity, through impeachment,
to remove their nemesis from office. Of course, the stories of what
happened to the pursuers of both the fictious Moby Dick and the
fallible Bill Clinton are very similar in their results.
</P>
<P>
   With the House Republicans' failure to remove Clinton, it is
unlikely another impeachment attempt against a president will come
in the foreseeable future. The pain and misery that the impeachment
process put Congress and the American people through will stay with
this nation for years. But it should not be assumed that
impeachment will never be used again.
</P>
<P>
   As bipartisan as the Nixon impeachment hearings were, and as
serious and legitimate as the charges were against him, that did
not make the process any less painful for members of Congress or
the voters on either side of the political aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, with the nation now more aware of the downside of the
impeachment process because of what Johnson, Nixon, and Clinton
have gone through _ as well as what the respective Congresses have
endured _ Congress may be more inclined to find a way to make the
impeachment process less readily available.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the legal or legislative threshold for
impeachment should be so high as to ensure that any charge levied
against a president involves an issue or circumstance that truly
endangers this nation if he or she were to continue in office.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, House Republicans, by diminishing the original
purpose of the impeachment process, also diminished the presidency,
even more than Clinton's own conduct. By lowering the impeachment
bar when they went after Clinton, the House Republicans lowered the
great caution that comes with using such a powerful process.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Congress _ right after it gets rid of the
independent counsel statute _ should write laws making it harder to
impeach a president simply because one party outnumbers another. If
the impeachment process cannot be written out of the Constitution,
it should at least be made very difficult for any Congress to use
again without solid bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   As for Johnson and Clinton, the taint of impeachment should be
not on them, but on the irresponsible members of Congress who did
more harm to this country than either president. There should be a
consequence to Congress's reckless, partisan ways.
</P>
<P>
   It's time that the taint of the impeachment label was shifted
from Johnson and Clinton to the members of Congress who turned this
once noble idea into a shameful disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
