<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GRAMMYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUNDTRACKS LEAD THE GRAMMY FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Searching for Grammy trends is an annual, brow-furrowing
exercise. This year, most pundits will take the easy way out by
pronouncing 1999 the ``Year of the Woman.'' After all, two of the
Top 3 awards _ for best record and best album _ are dominated by
female nominees Lauryn Hill, Celine Dion, Madonna, Brandy, Monica,
Sheryl Crow, and Shania Twain. Never have the men trailed so badly,
with the lone male entry for record of the year being the Goo Goo
Dolls for ``Iris.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet women have been leaping the barricades for the past several
years. That's nothing new. Instead, the most startling trend at
this year's Grammys is the unprecedented impact of soundtracks. The
Goo Goo Dolls figure into that, too, since ``Iris'' is from the
``City of Angels'' soundtrack, which also spawned the Alanis
Morissette hit ``Uninvited.'' And that song just happens to be up
for female rock vocal performance.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Titanic'' soundtrack, which posted 26 million in global
sales, leads the way with five nominations for Dion's `My Heart
Will Go On,'' a song that was so pervasive that you might turn off
the radio if you heard it again today. But the numbers don't lie.
``Titanic'' was not only No. 1 on Billboard's year-end Top 200
sales chart, but was one of 22 soundtracks to make that list during
a year that saw soundtrack sales rise by 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other soundtracks reaping their share of Grammy nominations
include ``Armaggedon'' (which single-handedly revived Aerosmith's
career with the No. 1 pop hit ``I Don't Want to Miss a Thing''),
``Hope Floats,'' ``Bulworth,'' ``Soul Food,'' ``Dr. Dolittle,'' and
``How Stella Got Her Groove Back.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point last summer, three of the Top 5 albums were
soundtracks: ``Armaggedon,'' ``City of Angels,'' and ``Dr.
Dolittle.'' So it makes sense that Wednesday's Grammy telecast from
Los Angeles (on WBZ-TV, Channel 4, at 8 p.m.) will include a
special salute to music in movies that features Aerosmith
performing its hit. That will be followed by film composers James
Horner (``Titanic'') and John Williams (``Star Wars'') taking turns
with music of their own. Clip packages of memorable motion pictures
scenes will be shown behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The connection between soundtracks and films has never been
more vibrant,'' said Michael Greene, president of the National
Academy of Arts and Sciences (the voting bloc for the Grammys)
during a phone interview this week. ``Not only have there been more
soundtracks issued, but you have to back up and remember some of
the reasons why _ not least of which is that many of the film
companies are also the owners of the music companies. So they've
found a good way to cross-promotionalize the music and films to
everybody's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sign of what's going on retail-wise,'' adds Greene. ``A
lot more soundtracks are released and when the public gets
interested in a film, they buy the soundtrack. And it doesn't hurt
if there's a hit or two lingering around in that soundtrack,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Those hits can mean Grammy glory. Aerosmith, for instance, is up
for best performance by a duo or group for ``I Don't Want to Miss a
Thing.'' It's a song they didn't write (Diane Warren holds that
honor) and took only two days to record. Getting a Grammy
nomination is a nice payback for such a small investment of time.
</P>
<P>
   Soundtracks help promote veteran bands and expose new acts,
while also giving consumers a compilation they can't get anywhere
else. But it's not all a silver lining, according to Butch Vig of
the band Garbage, which is up for album of the year for ``Version
2.0'' and had an earlier hit, ``Number One Crush,'' on the 1996
``Romeo and Juliet'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soundtracks can be dangerous for an artist,'' Vig said. ``It's
easy to get one song out, and it's an easy marketing tool. But it's
harder to have a career these days because of the quick fix and the
one-hit wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Grammys are also notable for a few landmarks:
</P>
<P>
   --Hill, the hip-hopper with the soulful voice, is the first
woman to ever land 10 nominations.
</P>
<P>
   --Twain is the first country singer to be nominated for the Top
3 awards _ record, song, and album of the year.
</P>
<P>
   --Kirk Franklin is the first gospel artist to get a nomination
for song of the year. It's for ``Lean on Me,'' which he'll perform
Wednesday with U2's Bono and Mary J. Blige. (Other performers on
the show include Twain, Hill, Madonna, Will Smith, Crow, Vince
Gill, Luciano Pavarotti, Dion and Andrea Bocelli in a duet, and
Wynton Marsalis in a Duke Ellington tribute.)
</P>
<P>
   --This is the first year for several new awards, two for dance
music, and one each for Latin, crossover classical, and traditional
R&AMP;B. All worthy additions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
