<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!! 1/2 ``October Sky'' Beautifully-crafted real-life story of
how a NASA scientist-to-be blasted out of his West Virginia
coal-mining town after Sputnik inspired him (and scared everybody
else). Jake Gyllenhaal is on target as the home-made rocketeer,
Chris Cooper is moving as his conflicted father and Laura Dern
snatches the role of an encouraging teacher from cliche. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR) !! 1/2 ``Office Space'' Beavis and Butt-head mastermind Mike
Judge gives nine-to-fivers something to cheer about in this comedy
about three drudges who decide to break out of their cubicles and
stick it to the corporate viciousness that's ready to chew them up.
The satire on bottom-line ruthlessness is fun, the other stuff less
so. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``The 24 Hour Woman'' Nancy Savoca's comedy about a professional
woman, Rosie Perez's TV producer, driven around the bend by the
conflicting demands of career and parenting is sympathetic. But its
unrelieved shrillness and its readiness to too quickly consign to
hysteria an obviously accomplished woman detract from its simpatico
energies. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
! ``Jawbreaker'' A dull-as-dishwater mess which delusional enough
to think itself a dark comedy about high school cliques, and the
lengths some girls will go to to retain their status. Unfunny,
unimaginative, and wholly unnecessary. (R) (Renee Graham)
</P>
</TEXT>
