<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GROSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXAMINING SOME SURPRISE ENDINGS AT THE BOX OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GROSS 
The Hits, the Flops: The Summer That Ate Hollywood 
By Peter Bart 
St. Martin's Press, 311 pp., $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We know what they did last summer at the movies. The question is
_ how did they do it?
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Gross,'' author Peter Bart delivers a behind-the-scenes
look at the surprise hits and flops, the ego battles between stars
and producers, the marketing strategies that succeeded and failed,
and the zany insanity of last summer's movie season.
</P>
<P>
   Bart, editor in chief of Variety and a former studio executive
at Paramount and MGM/UA, is in a unique position both to gain
access to the players and confidently assess their remarks. Many of
the studio heads talk to him because they think he's one of them,
while stars and directors take his calls because of his unique
position as the editor of Hollywood's bible.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone interested in the inner workings of the movie
business, ``The Gross'' details many of the intriguing events
surrounding the making and release of films such as ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' ``Deep Impact,'' ``The Mask of Zorro,''
``Armageddon,'' ``Godzilla,'' ``The Horse Whisperer,''
``Bulworth,'' ``There's Something About Mary,'' and ``Bulworth.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the questions raised and answered by Bart:
</P>
<P>
   Why did ``Godzilla,'' the most heavily hyped movie of the
sunmmer, fail? How did the intense rivalry between Robert Redford
and Warren Beatty influence the release of their pictures, ``The
Horse Whisperer'' and ``Bulworth''? How did long-shot contender
``Deep Impact'' bury the the big summer favorite ``Armageddon'' at
the box office?
</P>
<P>
   One part of the movie equation that doesn't escape Bart's sharp
eye is the entertainment media. The press prognosticators _ trying
to guess which films will be hits _ are often seen as adjuncts to a
film's advertising budgets. In fact, one of the reasons
``Godzilla'' failed so badly is that expectations, created by
summer preview articles, were so high. Time critic Richard Corliss
predicted that ``Godzilla'' would be the top film of the summer and
that the only issue was ``which film would come in second.''
</P>
<P>
   Since almost all of the movies are now on home video, the book
makes for an indispensable companion for those viewers captivated
by the many routes a movie can take on its way to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems with ``The Gross'' is that it's not
footnoted and there are a bundle of unattributed quotes. Bart's
reputation is solid enough that there's no reason to question the
authenticity of the remarks, but it does diminish the overall
impact when anonymous executives get to take potshots without fear
of retribution. Bart focuses on so many films that there are times,
particularly in the case of ``Saving Private Ryan'' and the casting
of Tom Hanks, when you wish he spent more time on those details and
less on the relatively insignificant ``Small Soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that Bart, the Variety editor, is an
essential part of the problem as outlined by Bart, the author of
``The Gross.''
</P>
<P>
   Bart accuses the media of playing along with the studios by
publishing the gross receipts for a film's opening weekend. This
sort of publicity, provided by the studios and theaters, plays
right into the hands of the marketing machinery. As soon as the
first weekend grosses were published in the general media, studios
began shooting for the quick hit weekend score to generate
business. Subsequently, they started producing movies aimed for an
explosive opening, thus upping the ante for big-budget potential
blockbusters and diminishing the chances for smaller, more
sophisticated art films to break in through word-of-mouth. Yet it's
his publication that popularized the publication of weekend
grosses.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of these minor criticisms, ``The Gross'' is an
intelligent and informed tale of a business based more on gambling
than foresight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
