<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-FLYING RHETORIC ON CLEMENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hyperbole Hotline has been inundated in recent days with
calls from Red Sox fans bewildered by what they've been hearing and
reading about Roger Clemens moving to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Confused callers have been tying up our lines day and night,
begging for help. As we've seen so many times in the past, there is
nothing like a Red Sox-related crisis to drive local commentators
to use figures of speech, hyperbole included.
</P>
<P>
   As a public service, here are a few Clemens questions typical of
those the Hyperbole Hotline has been catching on the fly, so to
speak.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I read on the editorial page of Saturday's Boston Globe that
Clemens put the kibosh on spring by signing with the Yankees: ``Red
Sox pitchers and catchers report for spring training today, one of
the first signs of spring for New Englanders, but to many fans it
feels like the crocuses have frozen permanently in the ground.
Roger Clemens, the pitcher who got away, has compounded Boston's
loss by signing with the arch-foe . . .'' Is this hyperbole? Does
this mean that because Tom Tupa signed with the Jets there'll be no
autumn?
</P>
<P>
   A. The crocus reference is not hyperbole but a metaphor
representing the Eternal Winter that has descended upon the hearts
and minds of Sox fans because Clemens has seen fit to join the
Yankees. Even the normally sober denizens of the Globe's editorial
page can become unhinged when the Yankees stick it to the Sox. As
for your Tupa inquiry _ please, it's not in the same league.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I keep hearing people refer to the Clemens deal as a
``tragedy.'' Is this hyperbole?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. It's a simple statement of fact. Clemens in Yankee
pinstripes is a tragedy for Red Sox fans. They have brought
themselves low by their inability to deal with adversity, i.e., the
fact that the Yankees have a long and glorious history of
humiliating the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I read in the sports pages that Clemens signing with the
Yankees is ``a nightmare scenario.'' Hyperbole?
</P>
<P>
   A. Hyperbole, as we at the Hyperbole Hotline never tire of
explaining, is an exaggeration or extravagant statement used for
emphasis or effect. Sometimes hyperbole, like beauty, is in the eye
of the beholder. Clemens's move to the Yankees may literally give
some Sox fans nightmares. For most, though, applying the phrase
``nightmare scenario'' to the Clemens situation would be an
exaggeration. It's merely the latest chapter in the continuing Red
Sox ``nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In all the media weeping and gnashing of teeth over the
Clemens deal, I was surprised to read in one sports column that
he's over the hill, that he won't do a thing for the Yankees, and
that the Red Sox' chances have never looked better. Is this
hyperbole or what?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's not hyperbole but delusion, typical of the mania that
normally grips Sox fans this time of year. Boston fans have long
suffered from a kind of mass manic depression. Early in the season,
they exhibit classic symptoms: elation, grandiosity, inflated
expectations. Usually, the depression phase kicks in at midseason.
But this year the shock of the Clemens deal has brought it on
prematurely, although apparently not in the sports columnist in
question.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I heard one commentator say that Clemens signing with New
York is worse than Harry Frazee selling Babe Ruth to the Yankees.
This is hyperbole, surely.
</P>
<P>
   A. Indeed it is. Boston fans are so crazed with hatred and
resentment of the Yankees they tend to overlook the fact that
Clemens spent the last two seasons playing for Toronto. Thanks, by
the way, for giving the Hyperbole Hotline the opportunity to use
the name Harry Frazee, crazy name, crazy guy, to borrow a phrase
from one of our favorite publications.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
