<HEADER>
A4492 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ARTS-BOS &LR;      02-22 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ARTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE MEN CAN RAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's always been a hard-knock life for white boys who love black
noise.
</P>
<P>
   As a generation before heard the Beatles and Stones and picked
up guitars of their own, two decades of white kids have been raised
on the rhythm, the rhyme of rap. Listening to Run-DMC, Public
Enemy, and, more recently, the late Tupac Shakur and DMX, they
traded their guitar-hero dreams for two turntables and a
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Yet like Rodney Dangerfield, they get no respect.
</P>
<P>
   They've been called ``wiggers,'' a pejorative both cunning and
cruel. They've been publicly sullied as wack-wannabes by the
Offspring in the yowling punk-slap ``Pretty Fly (For a White
Guy).'' Typical lyric:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friends say he's trying too hard
</P>
<P>
   And he's not quite hip
</P>
<P>
   But in his own mind
</P>
<P>
   He's the, he's the dopest trip.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Beastie Boys, who Spin magazine once lovingly called
``the boychiks with the most flava,'' have been around since the
1980s, and have enjoyed multiplatinum success, the most recent
being ``Hello Nasty.'' But when you get right down to it, they're
all dope samples and no skills whatsoever. 3rd Bass, with MC Serch
and Pete Nice, were the first white rappers with enough mike
prowess and street cred to catch the ear of urban radio in 1989
with ``The Cactus Album,'' but they quickly disbanded, although
there have been recent rumors of a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Everlast headed House of Pain, all shamrocks
and Sinn Fein tattoos, and spat out the fine malt lyrics of ``Jump
Around,'' before he had a heart attack, got acoustic, and started
strumming the white-boy blues on his current hit, ``What It's
Like.''
</P>
<P>
   But really, young white men in hip-hop have been defined _ and
defiled _ by knuckleheads like Vanilla Ice and Marky Mark, who sold
mad records, far more than most black rappers at the time, and made
just about every other white boy in a b-boy stance with a rhyme on
his lips instantly suspect. Like jazz, rap is an indigenous
African-American art form, and soon white rappers found themselves
victimized by the kind of ``Crow Jim'' mentality that dogged some
white jazz musicians in the 1960s _ if it's white, it ain't all
right. What Vanilla and Marky never received and never deserved is
what is essential to be taken seriously as a rapper _ props from
African-American audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as rap music and hip-hop culture slide into their third
decade, there's a new posse of white rappers out to show-and-prove
that hip-hop is about skills, not skin color.
</P>
<P>
   Due to drop Tuesday is ``Slim Shady,'' the debut offering from
Eminem, whose video for the single ``My Name Is'' has been in a
Buzz Clip baby for the past few weeks on MTV. With its hilarious
spoofing of President Clinton, Monica Lewinsky, and Marilyn Manson,
it's also in heavy rotation on the station's urban music showcase,
``MTV Jams.'' Now, to be blunt, the blond-haired, baby-faced rapper
looks more like a member of teen dreck hitmakers 'N Sync than the
protege busting rhymes for Dr. Dre, a founding member of N.W.A. and
the man who discovered Snoop Dogg and Warren G. Eminem. Eminem,
born Marshall Mathers and raised in a predominantly black Detroit
neighborhood, had been an underground freestylin' rage before Dre
caught the hype and and produced his debut.
</P>
<P>
   Let's ignore for a moment the same-old, same-old of Eminem
diatribes against women and gays _ hey, white folks have always
been as adept at hateful rhetoric as black folks. But more
important, and worth noting before the inevitable controversy
swamps everything else, is his embrace by the rap community, and
the big-ups he has received from such luminaries as Missy
``Misdemeanor'' Elliot and the monthly hip-hop bible, The Source.
He's being judged for his considerable abilities, not his race, and
he's proof that it's time to finally close the chasm between black
and white rappers.
</P>
<P>
   And, if anyone has a problem with that, they can take it up with
no less an authority than Chuck D, of the seminal rap group Public
Enemy, who recently told Rolling Stone, ``It's really irrelevant
what a person looks like and where they're from. . . . Saying `Just
because I'm black, I'm more hip-hop than you' _ that's got nothing
to do with skills.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, play that funky music, white boys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
