<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALCULATING IRA WITHDRAWALS; DETERMINING COST BASIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I will turn 70 1/2 on March 6 of this year. To avoid any IRS
penalty, when must I start making minimum withdrawals from my
traditional IRA and 401(k) accounts _ before April 1, 1999 or April
1, 2000? At the end of last year, the IRA balance was $44,052, and
the 401(k) balance was $257,019. Based on this information, what
will be the minimum amount of my withdrawals? Can you suggest a
safe investment for the withdrawals? Are there any mutual funds or
tax-exempt investments that would earn more than bank savings
accounts or certificates of deposit?
</P>
<P>
   B.M., Framingham, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You don't need to make a withdrawal before April 1, 2000 _
but you might decide it's wiser to make the first before the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The rule specifies that the first withdrawal must come by April
1 of the year following the year in which you reach age 70 1/2. But
it also specifies that this is the withdrawal for the tax year in
which you reached that age milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if you waited until April 1, 2000, to take the first
withdrawal, you would face two mandatory withdrawals falling in the
same tax year _ the one for 1999, when you reached 70 1/2, and
another for tax-year 2000. Therefore, chances are that you would
have a lower overall tax bill if the first withdrawal were taken
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of the withdrawals depends not only on your age, but
also on the age of your beneficiary. In these calculations, your
age is determined as your age at your birthday for the year in
question.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose you and your beneficiary are both the same age.
You would look in the IRS charts under age 71, and get a joint life
and last survivor life expectancy of 19.8 years. You use that
figure as a divisor, so you would have to withdraw $2,225 from the
IRA and $12,981 from the 401(k) account.
</P>
<P>
   If your beneficiary is younger, the amount of the required
withdrawal would be lower; the figure would be higher if the
beneficiary is older than you are.
</P>
<P>
   As for a potential investment vehicle for the proceeds of these
withdrawals, why not consider Fidelity Spartan Massachusetts
Municipal Income fund, which provides a yield that is free of both
federal and state taxes?
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar Mutual funds, which rates this fund above average,
lists the current yield as 4.8 percent _ lower than some CD rates,
but much higher on an after-tax basis. Such a fund is not, of
course, as safe as CDs and other insured bank accounts _ the value
of your shares will rise and fall inversely to interest rate
changes.
</P>
<P>
   But over the long haul it should supply you with an attractive
tax-free income stream. The minimum initial investment in this fund
is $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. People write in stating that they have $500,000 here or
$700,000 there, or they will become multimillionaires by the time
they retire. Lucky them. But one subject I have never seen broached
is the question of how the poor little Schmo who has a modest IRA
should withdraw money from it. I know of two alternatives _ the
recalculated method and the time-certain method. The time-certain
method involves a fixed amount withdrawn each year based on life
expectancy, which continues to be paid to the estate each year
after death, without the remaining money being taxed. The
recalculated method is just that, with the withdrawal amount
recalculated each year based on the remaining life expectancy. But
I also understand that with the recalculation method, the IRA
account becomes subject to immediate lump-sum taxation either if
one spouse or both die. Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   J.L., Oceanside, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. With the time-certain method of calculating IRA withdrawals,
you begin with an initial determination of life expectancy and then
simply reduce that number by one as each year passes. It's not a
flat-rate withdrawal amount, as your explanation suggests.
</P>
<P>
   One result: If you or your beneficiary outlive the initial
projection of life expectancy, the account will be depleted while
the owner or beneficiary is still alive. With the recalculation
method, the divisor is reduced by less than one as each year
passes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you and your beneficiary are both age 71, the
tables project a life expectancy of 19.8 years; five years later,
when you are both 76, the figure has fallen only to 15.7. With the
recalculation method, the owner of the IRA is never required to
completely empty it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's let J.K. Lasser's ``Your Income Tax'' explain what happens
when an IRA owner or beneficiary dies: After the death of a
recalculating owner or recalculating spousal beneficiary, that
person's life expectancy is reduced to zero starting in the year
after the year of death.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if your spouse is your designated beneficiary and he or
she dies first, you must use your single life expectancy to figure
your minimum required distributions.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when you die, your secondary beneficiary will have to
receive the entire account by the end of the year following the
year of your death. If you use the time-certain method, the
sequence of withdrawals that you began may be continued by your
beneficiary, following the same sequence that would have applied
had you lived.
</P>
<P>
   But alas, it's not the case that these withdrawals are tax free;
the benefit is simply that the new owner can spread the
withdrawals, and therefore the attendant tax liability, out over a
longer period of time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I purchased 200 shares of Citizens Utilities B stock on June
6, 1995 for $2,408. All dividends were paid in stock (and were
nontaxable until sold). On Sept. 15, 1998 I sold my entire position
for $1,648.82. How do I determine the correct cost basis for this
transaction?
</P>
<P>
   M.D., San Clemente, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your cost basis is $2,408, and you realized a $759.18 capital
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the dates upon which you received the additional
shares as stock dividends, you can treat the entire transaction as
a long-term capital loss, since the holding period of a tax-free
stock dividend or stock received in a split starts from the time
you acquired the original stock, according to J.K. Lasser's ``Your
Income Tax.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What would you advise for a 79-year-old widow with only
$300,000 to invest? I know absolutely nothing about the stock
market. The money is now in five CDs, with $200,000 worth maturing
this year and the other $100,000 in 2003. With the drop in interest
rates, it will be a daunting task to reinvest. I get $657 a month
from Social Security and the rest of my income comes from the CDs.
A brokerage firm suggests a wrap account, starting at $100,000, but
charging 1.5 percent to 2 percent to manage. In a previous column,
you thought well of AARP's GNMA and U.S. Treasury fund. Is this a
possibility for me?
</P>
<P>
   B.R., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure, it's a good fund, and designed for people in your
situation.
</P>
<P>
   But I wouldn't put all of my eggs in that basket. I would put
half of the money from maturing CDs in this fund, reinvesting the
other half in new CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Since the AARP fund currently has a yield of about 6.5 percent,
chances are that even with the lower yield on the new CDs that
you'd be buying, you would end up with about the same income stream
as you now enjoy. There would be additional risk _ the fund invests
in federally guaranteed bonds, but their current market value rises
and falls as interest rates change.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a conservative and well-managed fund, and over the
long haul you should enjoy a good income stream and see little
change in your principal value.
</P>
<P>
   But you should read the prospectus carefully and understand that
such funds can provide a bumpy short-term ride, and if you're
uncomfortable with the effect of choppy bond markets on your
principal, you shouldn't buy the fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
