u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-KETAMINE-BOS &LR;      02-22 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-KETAMINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY RENEWS DEBATE ON PSYCHOSIS-INDUCING RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A study showing that the anesthetic ketamine kills brain cells
in developing rats has added to a debate over using it in pregnant
women and children, and it has injected a surprising new element
into a controversy over psychiatric research involving the
chemical.
</P>
<P>
   One national organization of anesthesiologists discussed the
implications of the finding this weekend at a scientific meeting in
Las Vegas, although no action was taken, and a second group plans
to take up the issue in May in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of psychiatric studies using ketamine seized on the rat
brain research, published in the journal Science. They have
attacked as unethical several federally-funded studies that
involved giving ketamine and other drugs to mentally ill patients
to induce symptoms of psychosis. The studies were a focus of a
Globe series in November, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While the authors of the rat study and anesthesiologists say
it's too soon to draw conclusions about effects in humans based on
the animal data, they say the results call for further
investigation. Ketamine is no longer widely used for anesthesia in
pregnant women or children, but under certain circumstances it
still offers benefits that outweigh any risks, say
anesthesiologists.
</P>
<P>
   But the study's authors say it's not too soon to issue a warning
to pregnant women based on the study's findings: Don't abuse
ketamine _ used on the streets for its hallucinogenic properties
under the name ``Special K'' _ or any other drugs, including
alcohol, laughing gas or the street drug PCP, that appear to act on
the same so-called NMDA receptor in the developing brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main message that should be conveyed to the public is that
abusing these drugs during pregnancy is very unwise _ in fact,
irresponsible,'' said Dr. John W. Olney, professor of psychiatry
and neuropathology at Washington University School of Medicine in
St. Louis, and one of the authors of the study in the Jan. 1 issue
of Science.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which involved newborn and fetal rats, found that up
to 30 percent of developing neurons in parts of the rat brain
committed ``cell suicide'' _ apoptosis _ when exposed to ketamine,
PCP (also known as angel dust), MK-801 and another drug that blocks
the cells' NMDA receptors.
</P>
<P>
   Such cell death was observed about 24 hours after a single high
dose of one of the drugs was given to block NMDA receptors for at
least eight hours. The blocking action apparently prevents certain
brain chemical messengers, or neurotransmitters, from fitting into
the NMDA receptors at a critical point in brain development,
leading to cell death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many millions, probably billions, of nerve cells have that
receptor . . . in the context of a brain that has trillions of
nerve cells,'' said Olney in an interview. ``The number of neurons
that can be deleted from the brain by this mechanism is somewhere
in the range of probably 10 million or so.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies of NMDA receptors in Olney's lab and elsewhere
have led to the hypothesis that the receptors are somehow involved
in schizophrenia. That helped prompt a recent line of psychiatric
research using ketamine to induce psychotic symptoms in people with
schizophrenia and in healthy volunteers, in an attempt to
understand the biology of psychosis and perhaps one day come up
with better treatments.
</P>
<P>
   One leading critic of this research said the new rat study
raises even more questions about administering ketamine to induce
psychotic symptoms in people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really confirms further the Boston Globe series, that the
use of these toxic substances without medical benefit to these
patients was inappropriate,'' said Adil Shamoo, a University of
Maryland bioethicist who co-founded, along with Vera Hassner
Sharav, a New York-based advocacy group called Citizens for
Responsible Care in Psychiatry and Research.
</P>
<P>
   But Olney said he did not believe his latest study has a bearing
on the psychiatric research, since it looked at developing rat
brains, not adult rat brains.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for it to be relevant, these studies would have to be
performed on pregnant women. I don't know that they are being
performed on pregnant women. I certainly don't think they are,''
said Olney. ``If they chose to admit some subjects to their study
who are six-month-old infants, then there might be some relevance.
But I don't believe anybody is doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Olney's co-authors, Dr. Chrysanthy Ikonomidou of Humboldt
University in Berlin, said the study suggests that cell death
prompted by ketamine in the developing brain could be linked to
schizophrenia later in life. A number of human studies have found
an association between abnormalities in cells with NMDA receptors
and schizophrenia in adults, without establishing why the
abnormalities occurred, she said. Animal research is now being done
to look at cause and effect.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier animal study out of Olney's lab did look at ketamine
and adult rat brains, and it found that high doses of the chemical
created temporary vacuoles, or cavities within cells.
</P>
<P>
   While Olney said the formation of vacuoles ``is a form of
toxicity,'' the cavities closed up on their own, suggesting that
there's probably nothing to worry about in adult humans exposed to
smaller doses, as in some of the psychiatric research.
</P>
<P>
   For Shamoo, however, the important question is not whether
animal studies have proven that ketamine causes permanent brain
damage, but whether giving ketamine to people with mental illness
to study psychosis is ethical at all, when there is no medical
benefit from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't use people as a means to an end,'' Shamoo said. He
also doesn't buy the argument that because the animal research has
documented only temporary vacuoles in adult rat brains, it is safe
for the psychiatric research can go on.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven E. Hyman, director of the National Institute of
Mental Health, has suspended clinical involving ketamine at the
institute's own facilities on the grounds that they lack scientific
merit, and the federal agency is reviewing its funding of similar
outside research.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman declined in an interview earlier this month to discuss
whether the animal studies involving ketamine have a bearing on the
psychiatric research. Psychiatric researchers say animal studies
involve doses of ketamine much higher than those used in their
research.
</P>
<P>
   The dosages in the Science rat study are also much higher than
those used to anesthetize humans, researchers say, though the agree
the findings suggest a need for more research.
</P>
<P>
   Ketamine was more widely used as an anesthetic about 15 years
ago, until its hallucinogenic effects were noted. (Ketamine causes
such effects only in adults, not children.) Better anesthetics have
since become available, but ketamine has the advantage of not
lowering blood pressure or blocking airways and is still useful for
patients in shock or with severe asthma, say anesthesiologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a leap to incriminate ketamine based on that
article,'' said Dr. David Birnbach, president of the Society for
Obstetric Anesthesia and Perinatology, which will be discussing the
study at its annual meeting in May. But, he added, ``I do believe
there are some subtle risks we do now have to investigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank McGowan, an anesthesiologist at Children's Hospital in
Boston and an officer of the Society for Pediatric Anesthesia,
sought to reassure parents worried about children undergoing
anesthesia. ``Our drugs are very safe,'' said McGowan, whose
society discussed the study over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In the years that ketamine was more widely used, no long-term
consequences were documented, McGowan noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the issues raised by the article are in fact real''
and bear further investigation, he said, but ``it still is a drug
that has its place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
