<SLUG> BC-SCI-IVBAGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IV BAG HAZARDS ARE ALLEGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most IV bags and tubing used in US hospitals can leach trace
amounts of a toxic chemical into the veins of patients, according
to a coalition of health and environmental groups, posing
particular risk for kidney dialysis patients or others who need
extensive intravenous treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Health Care Without Harm, an alliance of 160 groups such as the
American Nursing Association and Physicians for Social
Responsibility, were to issue a national ``health alert'' Monday
(Feb. 22) warning that IV bags and tubing made of polyvinyl
chloride contain the same toxic ingredient that manufacturers
removed from toys under pressure from federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Federal lab tests show that some of the ingredient, called DEHP,
leaches into the intravenous fluid and is infused into patients
along with their medication. Already, the makers of drugs such as
Taxol recommend against the use of vinyl bags when administering
the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the manufacturers of medical products to phase out
polyvinyl chloride use and switch over to safer materials,'' said
Dr. Ted Schettler of Greater Boston Physicians for Social
Responsibility. ``There is compelling evidence that patients are
being exposed to this chemical at levels that are of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Baxter Health Care Corp., based in Deerfield, Ill.,
the top manufacturer of vinyl IV bags, said that 40 years of
experience with millions of patients had shown no ``significant
adverse affects'' from exposure to chemicals in their IV bags.
</P>
<P>
   However, the company issued a statement acknowledging that some
customers have raised concern about the safety of DEHP. ``To meet
the preferences of these customers, Baxter has developed a variety
of containers made without DEHP,'' according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at Pennsylvania-based B. Braun/McGaw, the leading
supplier of IV bags without DEHP, said Baxter isn't giving up
easily. They said Baxter recently supplied vinyl bags under an
unusually low bid to win over one of B. Braun/McGaw's biggest
customers, the Department of Veterans Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 80 percent of the 500 million IV bags sold annually
in the United States are made of polyvinyl chloride. To give IV
bags their characteristic flexibility and transparency, DEHP, a
member of the chemical family called phthalates, is added.
</P>
<P>
   The main alternative, a multilayered film bag, is stiffer than
the polyvinyl chloride, but widely accepted in hospitals. B.
Braun/McGaw controls 20 percent of the US market, including
hospitals such as Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Institute in New
York. In Boston, New England Medical Center is studying a switch.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the controversy, the health effects of DEHP remain hotly
debated. The Environmental Protection Agency lists DEHP as a
probable cause of liver cancer, based on tests in rodents, but some
scientists say the results are irrelevant to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce Burlington at the Food and Drug Administration said
DEHP is toxic in high doses _ it's been linked to heart, testicle
and liver damage _ but not in the extremely small quantities
getting into IV fluids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that IV bags, blood administration sets and the
other uses of PVC, including dialysis tubing are safe,'' said
Burlington, director of FDA's center for devices and radiological
health.
</P>
<P>
   But Health Care Without Harm activists say health care providers
shouldn't take needless risk with DEHP, which can reach
concentrations in intravenous solutions up to 830 times higher than
EPA allows in drinking water, according to an analysis by the
environmental group, Greenpeace.
</P>
<P>
   Schettler conceded that people are exposed to DEHP from a
variety of sources, including food containers, and that exposure
from a single IV bag is usually modest. However, Schettler said
that the danger becomes significant for patients who require
repeated infusions, especially young children.
</P>
<P>
   Some drugmakers are already taking precautions. Taxol, used to
treat AIDS-related Kaposi's sarcoma as well as ovarian and breast
cancer, and Taxotere, a breast cancer medication, carry a warning
against administering them in polyvinyl chloride bags.
</P>
<P>
   Activists at Virginia-based Health Care Without Harm questioned
why regulators hadn't already taken action on IV bags. The Consumer
Product Safety Commission called for voluntary restrictions on DEHP
in toys in 1986, pushing toymakers to remove a similar phthalate
from a few rattlers and teething toys last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration ``has been asleep at the wheel
on this,'' said Bill Ravenesi of Health Care Without Harm's Boston
office.
</P>
</TEXT>
