<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-WHITAKER-BOS &LR;      02-22 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-WHITAKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE SUBSTANCE, LESS STYLE FROM   WHITAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pernell Whitaker's game always has been about
deception, but Saturday night he was only deceiving himself.
</P>
<P>
   For 27 years Whitaker has been one of the most masterful boxers
in the sport's long history. A sleight-of-hand expert since he was
8, Whitaker followed in the footsteps of the Hartford Will o' the
Wisp, Willie Pep, often winning rounds without having to throw a
punch and winning fights by inflicting more mental damage than
physical on his often bewildered and always frustrated opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday night at Madison Square Garden, Whitaker was beaten
up for the first time in his life. Time did the damage, with
assists from International Boxing Federation welterweight champion
Felix Trinidad and Whitaker's out-of-the-ring lifestyle. Together
they broke his jaw, cut his right eyelid, knocked him down, and
beat him back without beating him down.
</P>
<P>
   For seven rounds, the 35-year-old Whitaker was still Sweet Pea,
although not quite as sweet as before a self-imposed 16-month
layoff for twice testing positive for cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   For seven rounds, he dipped and dodged and jabbed, jabbed,
jabbed, drawing first blood by turning Trinidad's nose red and
leaving dots of crimson on the younger man's white, satin shorts.
</P>
<P>
   But by then he'd also been dropped once by a straight right hand
so fast and true he neither could avoid it nor react to it anymore,
and in that seventh round _ his last as Sweet Pea _ he twice hurt
Trinidad but got clipped again himself. After that he would go down
five times, none of them knockdowns but all of them signs his body
had begun to surrender to the calendar and its 26-year-old
representative from Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   He went down from a push, from a low blow, from bad balance and
good judgment, and several times simply because after he went into
his trademark low squat to avoid a punch his legs refused to push
him back up. Instead they buckled as he slipped to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Six times Whitaker hit the canvas, often without a punch
landing. Six warnings that it was time for him to leave the stage.
Whitaker had promised before the fight he would do just that if he
could see the tools were no longer there, saying, ``If they're gone
and I can't do what I've always done, I know they won't come back
the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet when it was over and he had lost a unanimous 12-round
decision by a wide margin to Trinidad, Whitaker's pride and
gameness _ two things that allowed a man who stands only 5 feet 6
inches to win six world titles in four weight divisions _ took over
and he refused to admit he had been defeated.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he did worse. He insisted he had won when it was
obvious he had not. To be sure, Whitaker had not disgraced himself.
He had, in fact, made the younger, bigger, stronger, faster man
look bad at times, especially before Whitaker suddenly began to age
in the eighth round. But by the end of the fight no one but
Whitaker still was trying to make a case for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``More punches, better punches,'' said Lou Duva, who has handled
Whitaker's career since his gold medal days on the 1984 Olympic
team. ``The other guy won.''
</P>
<P>
   The words had to have been bitter ones for Duva to spit out but
he is a realist in a game of dreamers. He knew the night they gave
the nod to Jose Luis Ramirez in 1988 and the draw to Julio Cesar
Chavez in 1993 and maybe even the decision to Oscar De La Hoya two
years ago that the judges had lied or been blind or both. Those
nights belonged to Pernell Whitaker regardless of the fiction on
the scorecards, but this one did not.
</P>
<P>
   This time the two 118-109 cards might have been a bit harsh but
the 117-110 wasn't far off. The Globe saw it a more kindly 116-112,
but nobody saw it close over the final five rounds.
</P>
<P>
   That probably included Whitaker, although he never could admit
it. If he was that kind of guy he never would have lasted this long
or won so often, so for this one night you let him live a fiction
on the way to St. Vincent's Hospital to get his possibly fractured
jaw examined and hoped in a week or two he would remember what he
said in a Las Vegas hotel room a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the tools aren't there Feb. 20, I won't go in again,'' he
said. ``The 13 years have been great. I've done some great things.
I'm happy with those 13 years. What I've done is in the record
books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I was the best pound-for-pound. I don't have to
pronounce that. It's on paper. No one could fight my style. You
can't teach what I got. When I'm gone, no one will ever be able to
fight that style again.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night Felix Trinidad couldn't fight that style, and so
even though he won a battle he lost the war of public opinion to
his World Boxing Council rival, De La Hoya, who had fought far more
furiously against undefeated Ike Quartey in defending his share of
the 147-pound championship a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is, Pernell Whitaker couldn't fight that style
anymore either. Trinidad connected with 54 percent of the 512
punches he threw, landing 44 more blows than Whitaker, even though
Whitaker launched 237 more punches.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson in that is one Whitaker will understand if he chooses
to heed it. The lesson is no one can fight his style anymore. Not
even him.
</P>
</TEXT>
