A4509 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     02-22 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFERENT TRAINING CAMPS LIKE SALT AND PEPPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ They are salt and pepper, ebony and ivory,
Kennedy and Nixon, Schwarzenegger and DeVito.
</P>
<P>
   There is the Yankee spring training camp in Tampa and then there
is the Red Sox spring training camp in Fort Myers. I went back and
forth over the weekend and the contrast was painfully clear.
</P>
<P>
   The world champion Yankees had their first formal workout for
pitchers and catchers Thursday. Roger Clemens _ who used to arrive
late when he worked for the Red Sox _ reported to the Yankees
Saturday and began workouts immediately. He said he would ask for
no special treatment in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox pitchers and catchers worked out for the first time
Sunday and the Sox' $75 million ace, Pedro Martinez, was absent,
reportedly because he's back in the Dominican for his father's
birthday party. Meanwhile, Rich Garces was absent with the
proverbial visa problems (could it be he didn't make weight at
customs?).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees worked out in shiny new Legends Field, across the
street from the giant stadium where the Tampa Bay Buccaneers routed
the Patriots in the infamous mosh pit game of 1997. Yankees fans
sat in the stands and watched the action. The Red Sox worked out at
their minor league complex in the swamplands of Fort Myers. Sox
fans stood around behind ropes.
</P>
<P>
   There's a huge ownership presence in the Yankee camp. General
George Steinbrenner wheels into the stadium lot each day and prowls
the premises, making sure everything is done right. The Boss is
available for comment on any and every issue. He'll even talk about
the potential Senate race between Hillary Clinton and Rudy
Guiliani.
</P>
<P>
   There is no ownership presence at the Red Sox practice site,
unless you want to count limited partner Dr. Arthur Pappas, who
Sunday administered physicals to Red Sox players. The Red Sox are
owned by an Oz-like invisible trust and invisible man John
Harrington is the caretaker of that trust. Say what you want about
Steinbrenner, at least he is an accountable owner with his own
money invested in the franchise. He doesn't hide or complain about
``60 years of unfair criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have a cadre of full-time and spring training
coaches who inspire memories of the franchise's golden days. Rich
Gossage, Willie Randolph, Ron Guidry, and Chris Chambliss were
among those leading the charge out of the dugout Saturday. All of
them appeared in the 1978 playoff game at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox boast Jim Rice as a hitting coach, and a group of
hard-working instructors with little history in the Boston
organization. Carl Yastrzemski will be down later to work with Sox
minor league hitters. Happily, the Sox camp is also graced by the
ubiquitous presence of 79-year-old Johnny Pesky.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees camp features a horde of Japanese media covering the
continuing saga of Hideki Irabu. Camp Red Sox this spring is being
shared by the Samsung Lions of the Korean professional league. The
blue-and-white-clad Lions work at least eight hours per day at the
complex. Their presence quietly mocks the short work day of major
league ballplayers in Florida. The Lions drill hour after hour,
then return to the camp at night for batting practice in the cages.
</P>
<P>
   There are a million interesting stories in Yankee land. Darryl
Strawberry is recovering from a bout with cancer and battling to
win back the left field job. ``El Duque'' Hernandez is the subject
of a book and possible television special. And now there is
Clemens, joining David Cone and Andy Pettitte atop the New York
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' top stories will be the arrival of Jose Offerman, the
$26 million replacement for Mo Vaughn; the emergence of Nomar
Garciaparra as franchise player; Jeff Frye's recovery from knee
surgery; and Trot Nixon's long-awaited debut as a starting right
fielder.
</P>
<P>
   En route to Legends Field, there's a billboard touting the
Yankees as 24-time world champions. The marquee outside the stadium
cites Time magazine's declaration that the 1998 (125-win) Yankees
were the greatest team ever. The Red Sox no longer boast about
1918.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most chilling contrast is that of the respective
general managers. Yankees GM Brian Cashman, a 31-year-old whiz kid,
walks around the field, the clubhouse, and the press area,
available for comment on any and every baseball issue. He's
refreshingly candid, loves talking baseball, and actually said,
``Part of our job is to anticipate questions you might ask.''
Cashman readily explained the sequence of events that led to New
York's offseason signing of Bernie Williams and the conversations
that resulted in the Clemens trade.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Myers, quote-starved reporters wait for some word from
joyless GM Dan Duquette. The Duke hasn't been around all week. His
arrival was delayed until  &UR; today &LR;  by the flu that's hit so many New
Englanders this winter. In his absence, the Sox issue statements
that always sound like they were scripted by the Tass News Agency.
The releases usually start, ``Executive Vice President and General
Manager Dan Duquette announced  &UR; today &LR;  that . . .''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 9, Duquette announced that Sox first base coach Dave
Jauss managed his team to the Caribbean World Series title. Why
does Duquette have to announce Jauss's triumph? The games were on
television. This is akin to the Sox releasing a statement reading,
``Executive Vice President and General Manager Dan Duquette
announced last night that the Red Sox lost to the Yankees, 11-2.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this means anything this morning. The Red Sox and
Yankees remain tied atop the American League East with identical
records of 0-0. But the Yankees were 22 games ahead of Boston last
year and just added Clemens. The Sox subtracted Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably too much to expect the Sox to compete with the
Yankees. But the Duquette Sox are in danger of committing a more
grievous sin.
</P>
<P>
   They might be boring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
