<SLUG> BC-SMOKING-ARRESTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAR OWNERS FUME OVER ANTI-SMOKING ENFORCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MACKENZIE WARREN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The police and public health officials have
fined 48 smoking offenders, including eight tavern owners, in a
three-week sweep that has re-ignited debate about the California
law snuffing out smoking in bars.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco was slow to begin enforcing the law because of
complaints from bar owners that it would destroy business, but
recently began enforcement under pressure from health
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that they're stepping up to the plate to enforce
the law finally,'' said Diane Kaiser of the American Lung
Association's Smoke-Free Bar Program.
</P>
<P>
   The lung and heart associations lobbied City Hall hard last year
to enforce the law, getting little support from Mayor Willie Brown.
City Attorney Louise Renne brokered a deal that led to the current
enforcement program.
</P>
<P>
   Compliance has been far from uniform. A recent survey by the San
Francisco Department of Public Health revealed about half the bars
in the city were ignoring the no-smoking rule.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Breslin, the senior health inspector coordinating the
enforcement operation, said for the next two weeks, a four-person
task force, including two police officers, would target
establishments that have drawn the most complaints about ignoring
the law. A wider and more random strategy will follow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a resistance movement is evolving. Bar owners or patrons
warn others of the sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd set up a phone tree,'' Breslin said. ``When we went in
these places, there was smoke everywhere, but nobody had any
cigarettes. It was frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 11 letter, health director Mitchell Katz and Police
Chief Fred Lau warned the nearly 900 bar owners in San Francisco to
expect enforcement action to follow. Within two weeks, the task
force was writing tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Among those slapped with a $76 fine: Norman Hobday, 65, who
poured his first whiskey shot 47 years ago. Hobday, the owner of
Eddie Rickenbacker's Hat in the Ring, said that for as long as he
can remember, has lighted his cigars for a moment to add flavor
before he chews them.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a health inspector cited him for smoking in his own
bar; Hobday said the stogey wasn't lighted for more than 30
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just putting it out,'' Hobday said.
</P>
<P>
   Hobday said he and other bar owners have taken a financial hit
because of the law. ``It's a killer. Business is off 15 to 20
percent here. It doesn't make a lot of sense to do that to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, passed in 1994, is intended to protect restaurant
employees from the dangers of secondhand smoke. Stand-alone bars,
which hold 11 percent of liquor licenses, were phased into the
regulations in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Despite complaints from restaurant and bar trade associations
about lost business, figures from the state Board of Equalization
show tax receipts from bars and bar-restaurant combinations were up
in the first quarter of 1998 _ the first year the ban covered bars
_ compared with the same period the year before.
</P>
<P>
   A report last year in the American Journal of Public Health
found no change in revenue at establishments in San Luis Obisbo,
Davis, Palo Alto and several other California jurisdictions where
local smoking prohibitions preceded the state rule.
</P>
<P>
   Not all bartenders oppose the law.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Metika of Uncle Bert's Place in San Francisco's Castro
district said she was alarmed when her doctor asked her almost two
years ago how long she had been smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even smoke,'' Metika said.
</P>
<P>
   She quit the bar job, but returned early last year when the
smoking ban took effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
