<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-INFORMANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIONS AID INS IN OUSTING ILLEGAL IMMIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MELISSA GRACE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Immigration officials in upstate New York rely
heavily on a small pool of informants among labor activists who
regularly tip off the authorities when they find illegal immigrants
working in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials acknowledge they make efforts to root out
illegal immigrants, though they say it is in the interest of
ensuring better working conditions for everyone. U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service officials say that about one-fourth of
their cases in the region come from union tipsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of different types of policing of construction
projects because many of these agencies are so short staffed. We
help ourselves out, we help them out,'' said Daniel M. Boody,
secretary of the painters and glaziers union in Buffalo. Boody said
he coordinates with the INS and other agencies regularly.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical example in January, 10 undocumented Mexicans were
detained by INS agents near a hotel construction in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The tip came from the local painter's union, whose members
walked the site and talked to workers.
</P>
<P>
   Union workers say they are helping to ensure that work is done
in safe conditions, at standard wages and in a regulated
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are breaking the law and undermining existing
conditions _ wage and safety conditions _ that is what our job
is,'' said Harold L. Joyce, president of the Tri-City building
trades. ``That is what we do: We try to make working conditions
better for all workers.''
</P>
<P>
   But some critics wonder if they are overstepping their bounds by
acting as the eyes and ears of the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would almost seem counterproductive for unions, who
represent the interest of workers ... to report them to the
immigration service,'' said Christina Chavez Cook, an attorney with
the Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund in
Washington, D.C. ``It leaves the worker without a job and does
absolutely nothing to the employer.''
</P>
<P>
   When INS finds illegal workers at a site, the immigrants are
detained and normally deported. The employers are investigated and
can be fined up to $2,000 per worker if it can be proved they
knowingly hired illegal workers.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials welcome the help from a network of labor
informers. ``I have a small staff,'' said Gary L. Hale, the officer
in charge in Albany. ``We develop the lead as much as possible and,
when we get a good guy who gives us good information, we take the
leads very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials elsewhere say they take a different approach.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen McInnis, a district council representative for the New
York City District Council of Carpenters, said his organizers focus
on problems involving safety and other regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our agents might use the INS. It's a discretionary
thing,'' he said, adding that the urge to call the INS may be born
out of frustration with either the inaction or inefficiencies of
the other enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Union agents in upstate New York say they don't hesitate to call
immigration officers. ``They are a public authority, we have their
phone number, and when we know for sure there may be undocumented
people working, then we call,'' Boody said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not against immigrants,'' said Austin Devine, a member
of the International Brotherhood of Painters and Allied Trades in
Albany. ``We are against illegal immigrants that come into the
area, take our work, take our money, don't pay taxes and who don't
leave any of it behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Devine is an immigrant who arrived from Belfast, Northern
Ireland, in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin R. Hick of the United Brotherhood of Carpenters and
Joiners of America said, ``We feel like our members are part of
this community, and they should be doing the work in this
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Joyce: ``If I find what I believe to be illegal workers, I
call INS. Who you going to call _ ghostbusters?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
