<HEADER>
A4568 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     02-22 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Feb. 23.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CERVICAL-CANCER (Undated) _ The National Cancer Institutes
recommends a major change in the treatment of invasive cervical
cancer, a disease that kills nearly 5,000 women a year. The change
is based on a study that shows chemotherapy substantially improves
chances of recovery. By Denise Grady. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MASSACRE-ANTHROPOLOGY (Guatemala City) _ Based on accounts
of four survivors and people in neighboring communities, 376 people
in an isolated Mayan hamlet of Guatemala died in a massacre by army
troops in 1982. Now, 17 years later, forensic anthropologists led
by the eminent scientist Dr. Clyde Collins Snow are confirming
their accounts, in all too graphic detail. By Malcolm W. Browne.
(2150 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-THERAPY (Philadelphia) _ A colony of 54 rhesus monkeys
are pioneers in a bold medical frontier, the treatment of disease
by reprogramming the body's genetic instructions. Gene therapy, as
it is hopefully known, has long been a field of high promise and
low fulfillment. But inserting genes into human cells in full
working order has proved to be exasperatingly difficult. Along with
a batch of recent experiments at other universities, the Penn
monkeys represent one of the few rays of hope in a series of
setbacks. Not only do six of them now carry a newly inserted gene
that makes a therapeutic protein, but the gene can be switched on
at will by giving the monkey a simple pill. By Nicholas Wade. (2100
words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MADCOW-DEER (Undated) _ As a 30-year-old deer hunter lies
dying at his home near Salt Lake City, consumer activists and
government regulators are squabbling over a terrifying question
that cannot be answered to anyone's satisfaction: Is it possible to
contract a version of mad cow disease from eating deer or elk? By
Sandra Blakeslee. (1950 words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SYNESTHESIA (Undated) _ For years, people with a condition
known as synesthesia _ in which the customary boundaries between
the senses appear to break down, sight mingling with sound, or
taste with touch _ received little attention. But in the past 10
years, the arrival of imaging techniques and other new technologies
for studying the brain at work has revived interest in synesthesia
by a core of researchers who hope that the condition will give a
greater understanding of all kinds of perception or even shed light
on the nature of consciousness itself. By Erica Goode. (1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VIBRATOR (Undated) _ In a new book, a scholar describes the
surprising history of an unlikely medical device, the vibrator. An
essay by Natalie Angier. (1550 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GERBA-GERMS (Tucson, Ariz.) _ Scientist at Work: Dr. Charles
Gerba is best known in his field of environmental microbiology for
his work in uncovering how viruses infiltrate drinking water from
sewage and other sources, and has consulted for American cities and
other countries on how to improve water quality. His findings about
household germs in the kitchen sink, in the laundry and in the
bathroom are chillings. By Wendy Marston. (1150 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LICE (Undated) _ How to deal with the predators that often
attack schoolchildren. By Susan Gilbert. (550 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: In most
households, emergency knowledge and equipment for pets is often
sorely neglected. What pet owners need to do to protect their pets,
and where people can turn for help. By Jane E. Brody. (1450 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ New treadmills are coming out with a variety of features,
ranging from CD players to changing surfaces from smooth to gravel
to sand. Another changes the pace of the track based on heart
rates. (340 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Siblings are fighting as much as ever, but many parents are
letting them go at it, according to a new study that surveyed
parents about conflict management strategies they felt confident
exercising. Although most parents didn't feel that non-intervention
was the best conflict management response, while being observed
they used it three times as often as other strategies. (375 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A review of medical studies linking religious faith to an
improved prognosis for patients found little empirical support for
claims, according to an article in the current issue of the medical
journal Lancet. (333 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEDICAL-HOTELS (Undated) _ For people seeking medical
options after surgery or other debilitating treatments, medical
hotels and post-operative recovery centers are offering patients
and their families new choices. By Andree Brooks. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-FEET (Undated) _ With just a few basic cautions,
weekend athletes can avoid pain and crutches from injuries to the
feet. By John O'Neil. (750 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: Can you be
cursed for going into an ancient tomb? Cursed at, certainly. And
many tombs contain warnings for those who deface the contents. (300
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: horse teeth and
evolution, talking Neanderthals who probably didn't talk after all,
plans for a new SETI observatory. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
</TEXT>
