<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-BAALBEK-$ADV2     02-22 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-BAALBEK-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAVISH STONE CARVINGS AND MONUMENTAL TEMPLES MAKE BAALBEK
SPECTACULAR
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With LEBANON-NIGHTLIFE-$ADV27; LEBANON-BOX-$ADV27.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Feb. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAALBEK, Lebanon _ Details make any story come alive. The ruins
at Baalbek tell their story so vividly that it's easy to imagine
the sacrifices, decadence, pagan worship and hard labor that took
place here 1,700 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the detail of Baalbek are lavish stone carvings of snarling
lions and bulls, mourning women, leafy vines and intricate
geometric designs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the monumental architecture gives lasting credence to
old myths that the city was built by giants. Still standing are
some of the largest columns in the world and several 800-ton,
60-foot-long foundation blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Baalbek is considered perhaps the most spectacular example of
Roman architecture in the world and among the most impressive
archaeological sites in the Middle East. Now, nine years after the
end of the bloody Lebanese civil war, the country and Baalbek are
reopening to the world.
</P>
<P>
   A new Baalbek museum, tucked away in ancient tunnels below the
ruins, provides a comprehensive modern explanation of the layers of
history above it. The museum, which opened in November, shows
delicate artifacts along with an excellent English narrative of
Baalbek history -- filled with conquering Phoenicians, Greeks,
Romans, Byzantine Christians and Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the two-hour drive from Beirut to Baalbek (cabs can
be hired for around $100 round-trip and service taxis cost as
little as $15 round trip) is itself a lesson in the current
turbulence of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Baalbek is in the Bekaa(CQ) Valley. It's a stronghold of
Hezbollah, the Iranian-backed ``Party of God,'' which is fighting a
war against Israeli troops occupying south Lebanon. Posters of
Iranian and Hezbollah clerics line the roads, as do yellow banners
with slogans in Arabic like, ``We must destroy the Israeli
cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Syria controls Lebanon and posters of Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad are common. So are Syrian secret police, wearing their
black leather jackets and toting assault weapons. Uniformed
Lebanese troops also keep checkpoints, backed up by tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department in 1997 lifted a ban on American
travel to Lebanon, images of a bomb-out Beirut barely faded from
their memories. Ominous travel warnings about the Bekaa -- for
example, noting that a grenade was fired at the U.S. embassy in
June -- are not entirely a thing of the past. But there have been
few other incidents of violence against foreigners recently, common
street crime is relatively uncommon and a few U.S. travel agencies
are sending groups.
</P>
<P>
   Heading to Baalbek, take your passport for the checkpoints.
Don't take photos of the soldiers or police, and stick to the
tourist areas and Baalbek's small town center. Then relax. Overall,
people are friendly and eager for tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Entrance to the ruins costs 10,000 Lebanese lira each, or about
US$6.60. Guides can be hired for 15,000 to 20,000 lira per group,
and you can cover the ruins and the museum in under three hours.
</P>
<P>
   The city gets its name from Baal, a Phoenician god of fertility.
The Greek empire rolled in in 330 B.C., lead by Alexander the
Great. They rededicated the temples to Venus, Jupiter and Mercury.
Julius Caeser's Roman troops took over in 47 B.C. and the great
building -- much of it with slave labor -- began.
</P>
<P>
   The Temple of Jupiter, which was completed before in 60 A.D.,
still has a portion of its ornate ceiling ledges held up by six of
the largest columns on earth -- seven feet wide, and nearly 70 feet
tall.
</P>
<P>
   With the extravagant Temple of Bacchus as the backdrop, guides
weave tales of pagan decadence to eager tourists. The floor -- once
a mosaic -- may have been the site of orgies. Stone carvings show
grapes and poppies, the ingredients of wine and opium.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, most of the 1,850-year-old temple remains, though the
ceiling, once of 45-ton blocks, has collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Near the Temple of Bacchus, underground, is a small new museum
showing artifacts from Roman graves excavated within the last few
years. The eerie vaulted passageway is now home to a stone
sarcophagus, covered in glass, containing the bones of the deceased
and the carved gold disks that used to adorn the body and head.
</P>
<P>
   The larger wing of the museum, opened by the Lebanese
antiquities agency and a German archaeological institute, is in a
long tunnel near the entrance to the ruins. Once, possibly, used as
housing for bulls being prepared for sacrifice, the arched tunnel
is both a piece of, and showcase for, the Baalbek history.
</P>
<P>
   These days, though the idolatry has stopped, the ruins still
perform a living function. Each summer, revived after the civil
war, thousands of music lovers come for the Baalbek arts festival.
Singer Ella Fitzgerald and dancer Rudolf Nureyev have performed in
the Great Court at the base of the Temple of Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
