<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-BOX-$ADV27-CO     02-22 0268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-BOX-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIPS FOR TRAVEL IN LEBANON
 &HT;    With LEBANON-NIGHTLIFE-$ADV27; LEBANON-BAALBEK-$ADV27.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GETTING THERE: No U.S. carriers fly directly into Lebanon, but
flights are available from throughout Europe. Swiss Air and
Lebanon's own carrier, Middle East Airlines, are common carriers.
</P>
<P>
   VISA: U.S. passport holders can get short-term visas easily upon
arrival at the airport in Beirut for 25,000 Lebanese lira, or about
$16. Since Lebanon does not recognize Israel, you may be refused a
visa if your passport has any Israeli stamps in it.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. ADVISORIES: In 1997, the U.S. State Department lifted a ban
on Americans traveling to Lebanon. The state department officially
warns that Americans should not travel there unless they have a
``compelling reason.'' But, Americans are arriving to study, work
or for tourism.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL AGENTS: Katrubes(CQ) Travel, in Boston, books week-long
trips to Lebanon starting at about $2,500, including airfare,
lodging and guides. Call 1-800-878-8566(CQ) or see e-mail:
Ktravel(at)world.std.com
</P>
<P>
   LODGING: Beirut has many hotels. Top-end choices include the
Summerland, a beach resort, the Commodore, the Marriott and
LeVendome Intercontinental. Mid-range choices include the Cavalier
and the Napoleon.
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE: Arabic is the main language, but English and French
are common in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1518EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-NIGHTLIFE-$AD     02-22 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-NIGHTLIFE-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FROM UNDERGROUND DANCE HALLS TO ARTS BARS, BEIRUT NIGHT LIFE IS
BOOMING
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With LEBANON-BAALBEK-$ADV27; LEBANON-BOX-$ADV27.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Feb. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ From above, the rusty trapdoors in the large
expanse of pavement look like the cover of a missile bunker or
maybe a hide-out for one of James Bond's villains.
</P>
<P>
   But, late at night, the hydraulic panels grind open and a large
mirror gives passing drivers a blurry view of what's below --
dancing and drinking in Beirut's booming night life.
</P>
<P>
   The club is B018 (say it, ``Beezero-18''), located on the site
of a notorious 1976 civil war massacre in the portside Quarantine
neighborhood. The name comes from an old apartment number. The
bar's youthful owners used to listen to records in the apartment
back when the civil war made it hard to bar hop.
</P>
<P>
   Hard, that is, but not impossible. Even during the carnage from
1975 to 1990, Beirutis would wait for breaks in the shelling to
head to the bars.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they had a reputation to maintain. Despite the city's
teeming slums and the civil war, which laid bare Lebanon's
religious strife, Beirut has for decades clung to its slogan as the
``Paris of the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   The French did govern here until 1943 and the city, with about
1.5 million people, still has a European flavor. Though it is split
between Christian and Muslim sectors, the downtown is largely
secular and it's easy to find people who supplement their Arabic
with English or French.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly 10 years after the war, Beirut is literally being
rebuilt. Scaffolding wraps much of the downtown and night spots are
popping up like mushrooms in the shadows of the bombed-out
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   There's the Sports Cafe, where you can catch games off of a
satellite feed and rub shoulders with a champion Lebanese rally car
driver or a snowboarding star. If you're a homesick American, check
out the autographed basketballs from Michael Jordan or NBA center
Rony Seikaly, a Lebanese-American and occasional customer.
</P>
<P>
   You can go to Caracas to hang out with the leftist crowd --
Lebanon's Greenpeace director was there recently -- and listen to
vintage blues albums.
</P>
<P>
   If you seek the arts with your spirits, go to Zinc in the Sodeco
neighborhood. Located in a 70-year-old mansion that still has
bullet holes in the facade, artists and musicians line the bar.
Lebanese art is featured in a nightly slide show, while the smell
of chestnuts roasting in a drum wafts over the patio.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can always go with the traditional. In the Arab
world, that means mellow hours listening to Arab music and smoking
the ``hubbly-bubbly'' water pipes.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the Cafe Grand sits on the Mediterranean coast --
next door to the not-so-traditional TGIFriday's.
</P>
<P>
   At least two traditional coffee shops offer the same in the new
Solidere district, a rebuilt promenade near Martyr's Square.
Solidere is good for shopping or watching the modern Beirut crowd
-- women in slacks, short skirts and leopard skin jackets, and men
in turtlenecks and blazers; and everyone, it seems, toting a
cellular telephone.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   But no night scene is complete without snobbery, and there are
several night-spots in Beirut with bouncers trained to keep out the
uncool. One of the latest is Gotha, a downtown disco near the
``Green Line'' border between the Christian and Muslim sides of
town.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that large rats scurry between abandoned buildings
nearby, you can't get into Gotha unless you look chic. After
midnight -- when the clubs truly get going -- the streets nearby
are lined with Range Rovers and Mercedes-Benzes.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, anyone is welcome down the dark stairs into B018, a
bar uniquely modern and Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   Opened last April -- the new trap doors were made to look rusty
and industrial -- the tables inside are made of marble and resemble
tombstones. On each, is a red rose in water, a memorial candle and
a framed picture of an American musical great, such as Miles Davis
or Ella Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Sparse furnishing allows the entire space to be used for
dancing. The chair backs fold over so you can dance on top of them
for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of exhibitionism in that. It's a very Lebanese
thing,'' explains co-founder and co-owner Bernard Khoury.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, drinks are brought by attentive servers in all-white
uniforms that create, as Khoury says, the ``asylum'' look.
</P>
<P>
   The overall effect is of a friendly dance party in a wartime
bunker. But, when the ceiling retracts and the bar opens up to the
starlit Beirut sky, you are reminded that, these days, it's safe to
go outside.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
