   Heading to Baalbek, take your passport for the checkpoints.
Don't take photos of the soldiers or police, and stick to the
tourist areas and Baalbek's small town center. Then relax. Overall,
people are friendly and eager for tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Entrance to the ruins costs 10,000 Lebanese lira each, or about
US$6.60. Guides can be hired for 15,000 to 20,000 lira per group,
and you can cover the ruins and the museum in under three hours.
</P>
<P>
   The city gets its name from Baal, a Phoenician god of fertility.
The Greek empire rolled in in 330 B.C., lead by Alexander the
Great. They rededicated the temples to Venus, Jupiter and Mercury.
Julius Caeser's Roman troops took over in 47 B.C. and the great
building -- much of it with slave labor -- began.
</P>
<P>
   The Temple of Jupiter, which was completed before in 60 A.D.,
still has a portion of its ornate ceiling ledges held up by six of
the largest columns on earth -- seven feet wide, and nearly 70 feet
tall.
</P>
<P>
   With the extravagant Temple of Bacchus as the backdrop, guides
weave tales of pagan decadence to eager tourists. The floor -- once
a mosaic -- may have been the site of orgies. Stone carvings show
grapes and poppies, the ingredients of wine and opium.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, most of the 1,850-year-old temple remains, though the
ceiling, once of 45-ton blocks, has collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Near the Temple of Bacchus, underground, is a small new museum
showing artifacts from Roman graves excavated within the last few
years. The eerie vaulted passageway is now home to a stone
sarcophagus, covered in glass, containing the bones of the deceased
and the carved gold disks that used to adorn the body and head.
</P>
<P>
   The larger wing of the museum, opened by the Lebanese
antiquities agency and a German archaeological institute, is in a
long tunnel near the entrance to the ruins. Once, possibly, used as
housing for bulls being prepared for sacrifice, the arched tunnel
is both a piece of, and showcase for, the Baalbek history.
</P>
<P>
   These days, though the idolatry has stopped, the ruins still
perform a living function. Each summer, revived after the civil
war, thousands of music lovers come for the Baalbek arts festival.
Singer Ella Fitzgerald and dancer Rudolf Nureyev have performed in
the Great Court at the base of the Temple of Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
