<SLUG> BC-FALL-FASHION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST MESSAGE FROM FASHION SHOW: YOU CAN WEAR THESE THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pale colors, sleek silhouettes, A-line skirts, luxe
sportswear for evening and knee-high boots (flat or with heels) are
key to fall '99 fashions.
</P>
<P>
   Those messages _ too loud to ignore _ were sent by designers to
retailers and media gathered here last week to preview their
collections.
</P>
<P>
   But the best message of all is these are very wearable clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Skirt hems hover around the knees for day. They move easily.
Narrow, ankle-length skirts that have made walking hazardous aren't
part of the fall '99 lineup. Even long skirts now have a bit of
fullness.
</P>
<P>
   Skirts or pants worn with sweaters could become uniforms for day
or night. They were staples in almost every collection _ a
turtleneck or twinset with an A-line skirt for day, perhaps a
cropped or jeweled sweater with a full satin skirt or silky pants
for evening.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in years, little black dresses were not just
upstaged, they weren't even invited to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Allard, creator of the Ellen Tracy line, put a pumpkin
pullover sweater over a taupe shetland wool skirt for day and
showed a cropped beaded cardigan with satin pants for late day.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren featured ballgown-sized skirts of duchess satin
with patterned pullovers (Nordic-inspired) cropped short to show a
little skin between sweater and skirt. A black and white sweater
with a red skirt was powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren's collection was colorful. Although he opened his show
with an unobtrusive pale blue turtleneck sweater and light gray
skirt, he moved right into pink, periwinkle, lilac, fuchsia, lime,
yellow and red _ bright hues that could be worn alone or paired
with neutrals.
</P>
<P>
   But like almost every other New York designer, Lauren included a
heavy dose of cream clothing. Whites, off-whites and cream appeared
throughout fashion week. So did pale camel tones sometimes labeled
``champagne.''
</P>
<P>
   Add the pastels shown by everybody from Tommy Hilfiger to Oscar
de la Renta and it's apparent that these pale tones are no longer
just for the winter holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Pleats have been erased from pants, along with waistbands.
Pants, whether they rise to the waist or end at the hips, are
close-to-the body on top, with pant legs ranging from very wide to
narrow.
</P>
<P>
   Tight denim jeans have been on runways, part of a very subtle
Western influence in the fall '99 fashion mix. It shows up in
lumberjack checks, shearling, leather, serapes, ponchos and plaids
faded like old flannel shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kors and Marc Jacobs showed spotted calfskin skirts and
jackets. Ccowboy boots were seen on several runways. But it wasn't
head-to-toe Western wear.
</P>
<P>
   A more powerful influence is outdoor wear: Satin parkas with fur
trim, jackets with map pockets in the back, pants with built-in
pouches. At times it looked like New York designers had been
inspired by Seattle's own Filson, Eddie Bauer and REI.
</P>
<P>
   But take away the details and the design influences, and the
over-all silhouette is narrower. There are darts, princess pieces,
shapely coats with slightly higher arm holes. Drawstrings have been
used on dresses; even blowses snug fabric into an empire line.
</P>
<P>
   Knit dresses cling to the body. Sheath dresses double as jumpers
with a sheer, skin-tight sweater under them.
</P>
<P>
   Closures are hidden. There was an unconfirmed rumor that some
designers were using magnets, like those on handbags, to hold
skirts together. Others used Velcro closures, old-fashioned hooks
and eyes, and hidden zippers. Buttons were almost always behind a
placket.
</P>
<P>
   Because the fall '99 fashions were previewed about six weeks
earlier than previous years, it means smart shoppers can visit
markdown racks now for things to wear next fall.
</P>
<P>
   What to look for? Pastels, off-whites, sweaters, pants without
pleats, anything with a fur trim, shiny leathers and skirts with
flare _ short or long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
