<SLUG> BC-WILSON-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON FORGOES PRESIDENTIAL BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ With a growing field of Republican
candidates and little time left to raise enough money, former
California Gov. Pete Wilson said Monday he would not to run for
president next year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wilson has the resume of a presidential candidate _
including stints as mayor of San Diego, state lawmaker and U.S.
senator _ the daunting prospect of raising at least $20 million to
capture the 2000 nomination appeared too great for Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, 65, had spent the past several weeks huddling with his
close political associates and fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reluctantly, I'm compelled to conclude that it is just not
practical to pursue a candidacy for the Republican presidential
nomination in 2000,'' Wilson said in statement.
</P>
<P>
   He will continue the work he started at the Bear Flag Forum, a
nonprofit public policy foundation in Century City, where he has
moved with his wife, Gayle.
</P>
<P>
   He also will join forces with the Hoover Institute at Stanford
University and is sponsoring a state ballot measure to reform
California's juvenile justice system.
</P>
<P>
   If he had decided to run, Wilson faced expensive, grueling
campaigns in states that hardly know him, and rivals that could
include Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Other hopefuls for the Republican nomination are former Vice
President Dan Quayle, millionaire publisher Steve Forbes, former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio and Sen.
Bob Smith of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The problems for Wilson were varied. He leaves the state with a
Republican Party hurt in recent elections, including the defeat of
the party's candidate for governor, Dan Lungren, to Democrat Gray
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who is pro-choice on the abortion issue, faced a primary
system that favors conservatives. And Wilson's short-lived run for
the Republican presidential nomination in 1996 could have haunted
him as well.
</P>
<P>
   Even the lure of California's primary being among the earliest,
giving a candidate a boost of credibility, wasn't enough. The
problem is that about 10 other states _ including New York,
Massachusetts, Maryland, Florida and possibly New Jersey _ also
plan to hold primaries the same day as California, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   That will require candidates to be stretched and tremendous
amounts of money for advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and his advisers determined he could raise up to $8
million, not enough to run an effective campaign, despite his high
name recognition in California.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law prohibits presidential primary candidates from
accepting any amount over $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means 15,000 separate, maximum contributions,'' Wilson
said. ``I've waited too long. The last two years we kind of ran up
the score as governor because it's what I wanted to do. If you're
going to govern California, it's a full-time job. But now it's too
late to raise that kind of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has a rich donor list from 32 years in politics, but he
faced the task of convincing them and hundreds of Republicans
nationwide that he was a viable national candidate compared to the
others.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson still owes money from his unsuccessful campaign for the
1996 presidential nomination. Records show his principal
presidential campaign organization is $347,691 in debt, up nearly
$47,000 from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson piled up the new bills by meeting with political
consultants, traveling and paying for mailings during his last year
as governor. His three federal campaign committees had a total of
$377,305 in the bank as of Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of money killed Wilson's bid for the 1996 nomination.
He kicked off his presidential campaign near the Statue of Liberty
with a fierce attack on ``the oppression of federal tyrants'' in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The operation uncharacteristically dissolved in just a month,
hampered by a lack of money and organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
