<HEADER>
A4697 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FITNESS-FEET-ART-     02-22 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-FEET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY FEET FOR WEEKEND QUARTERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ind.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Foot injuries are a major problem for recreational athletes,
particularly those past their bright college years. Because feet
that spend Monday through Friday under a desk literally bear the
brunt of the weekend athlete's Saturday enthusiasm, there is an
awful lot of limping on Monday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this is unavoidable. The foot is, after all, a
complicated structure that has to absorb the force transmitted from
the body to the ground _ up to eight times body weight in a running
jump.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent review of foot injuries of the adult recreational
athlete did have some suggestions for ways to avoid the
orthopedist's office.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen M. Simons, the associate director of the family
practice program at St. Joseph's Medical Center in South Bend,
Ind., said in the article, in a recent issue of The Physician and
Sports Medicine magazine, that such weekend flings account for up
to 15 percent of all athletic foot injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The most common, he said, are problems of the Achilles' tendon,
connecting the back of the heel to the calf muscles, and of the
plantar fascia, the tissue between the heel and toe.
</P>
<P>
   Because of tales of ruptured Achilles' tendons, with the sudden
agony and the months on crutches, Simon said, some weekend athletes
_ ``myself included'' _ have given up basketball altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The classic case, he said, is a man of about 38 who ruptures the
tendon in his left heel on a weekend while jumping for a shot or a
rebound. (``Right-handed people tend to jump off their left leg,
because the right leg can swing up faster,'' he said.)
</P>
<P>
   Treatment usually comes down to surgery or immobilization.
Simons said that a review of case studies found that patients who
were operated on were more likely to return to playing sports at
the same level, and only 2.8 percent ruptured the tendon again.
</P>
<P>
   Those who used the more conservative treatment, a cast, had a
reinjury rate of 11.7 percent. But the benefits of the cast are
quicker recovery _ 8.2 weeks on average compared with 10.5 with
surgery _ and fewer minor complications.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of players have pain in their Achilles' tendons without a
rupture. But Simons said people who suffer acute injuries often
have no warning signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that the person who's not hurting doesn't temper
their activity,'' he said. ``As you fatigue, the muscle does not
relax as well. That means that if in your fourth hour of basketball
you come down with a rebound, the calf muscle is not as good a
shock absorber as it was, and a consequence of that is an increased
chance of rupture.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution, he added, is to ``hang it up when you're not too
tired,'' though few are willing to do so.
</P>
<P>
   If Achilles' tendon problems are the most common trauma to the
foot, the less well-known plantar fasciitis is the most common
overuse injury. Simons described its usual symptoms as ``insidious
onset of heel pain'' that is worse after inactivity.
</P>
<P>
   The plantar fascia is a layer of fibrous tissue that runs from
the heel to the toes. When a person is walking or running, the
plantar fascia can take on the shape of a bowstring _ ``and you can
get a lot of tension in that bow,'' Simons said. That tension puts
strain on the tissue's attachment point in the heel, which can
gradually become inflamed.
</P>
<P>
   People often put up with the nagging problem, which only
prolongs the pain, Simons said, because prompt treatment usually
means better results.
</P>
<P>
   Common treatments in less serious cases include wearing more
supportive shoes, minimizing barefoot walking and taking
anti-inflammatory drugs. He also suggests tying shoelaces as
tightly as tolerable to help provide support.
</P>
<P>
   The best way of staving off either of these injuries _ and other
strains, breaks and fractures to small toe bones _ is perform
activities during the week that are similar to those involved in
the weekend sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get in just a little of the same activity, you're
going to have a better chance of conditioning the tissues to stand
that specific stress,'' Simons said. ``If that's not possible, find
some sort of stretching or strengthening exercise that comes close
to the kind of forces the foot is going to be subjected to.''
</P>
<P>
   He also urged people to resist the temptation to stay off their
sore feet all week to rest them for a big game on Saturday. Doctors
have a term for that, Simons said: ``straining tissue instead of
training it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
