<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4706 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN23-CO     02-22 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: A golden parachute for Y2K
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ Stopping by the post office the other
morning, I ran into a couple of fellows I've known since school
days.
</P>
<P>
   I could tell they were excited, and they couldn't wait to tell
me why.
</P>
<P>
   Their gold shipment had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   They opened up the boxes to show off their booty, a couple of
rolls of gold coins about the size of dimes, each valued at
one-tenth of an ounce of gold, about $32 at current prices.
</P>
<P>
   If events develop as they expect, those coins will be worth much
more, come the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Y2K thing _ I wouldn't understand _ but when the
computers freeze up as the clock ticks down next New Year's Eve,
we'll be back on a barter system at best and gold will be worth its
weight in ... well, gold and then some.
</P>
<P>
   Surely you've heard all about it, that our computers weren't
designed to service civilization past 1999, and as the millennium
turns over, the computers will be trying to turn the clock back to
1900.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be a disaster something on the scale of gravity trying to
reverse itself.
</P>
<P>
   So say the naysayers who are expecting the worst and then some,
as water faucets dry up and generators grind to a halt, ATM
machines go tilt and our computer-pampered way of life goes poof.
</P>
<P>
   Call me a cockeyed optimist, but I can't see it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not buying gold, I'm not drilling my own water well, I'm not
stocking up on food stuffs and I'm certainly not arming myself to
the teeth.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of it, too, the prospect of fighting off your
neighbors when they try to take from you what they didn't have the
good sense to put back for that rainy day. Shoot-fire, it'll be
raining bullets.
</P>
<P>
   My old friends made no bones about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I look down the road and see you hungry SOBs coming toward
my house, I'll be ready for you,'' one said and the other agreed.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``By the way. Just how long you think you can go
without nourishment?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question. About the noontime most days.
</P>
<P>
   But I had to ask:
</P>
<P>
   What are you going to do if you're wrong? Won't you look like a
fool, fool's gold and all?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yeah,'' I was told. ``But we can always cash in the
gold, drink the water and eat the food we've saved back.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused and then added:
</P>
<P>
   ``But what are YOU gonna do if I'M right?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
