<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4709 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     02-22 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE IT OR NOT, AMERICANS WANT TO KEEP CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like it or not, people are still talking about impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mr. Thompson:
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Sunday column contained a major misrepresentation of
fact: `Most Americans didn't want Clinton removed from office. ...'
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong!
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, you too have been falsely persuaded by national
poll results and/or you insulated yourself from what most Americans
really wanted from the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every one friend, relative and business associate of mine
who wanted Clinton to stay, ten others have expressed to me the
opposite desire. I am among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 60 years as a citizen, I have not once been polled by
someone representing himself as national media. I do not know a
single individual in all my experience who has been contacted by
such organizations. Who are the people polled? Where are the people
polled? How are these people selected?
</P>
<P>
   ``What Clinton did was despicable. He defiled our highest public
office. He should have been ousted and disbarred. However, because
of a group of spineless Senators, scared for their own political
future, we are left to try explaining another failure of the system
to our children.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a pathetic charade our elected officeholders perpetrated.
Now we have a President whom most of my friends, relatives and
business associates want no part of. They do not want to see him,
hear him or read about him, period!
</P>
<P>
   ``Our President now is without credentials. He is viewed as a
joke. And, we have this White House jester for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arlington, Texas, reader who wrote this letter signed off
with ``Sincerely,'' and it was heartening to learn that he was
sincere in his viewpoint. If there is one thing I can't stand, it's
a reader who rips me to shreds and isn't sincere about it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most people who despise Bill Clinton are as sincere
as sincere can be. Clinton-haters loathe Slick Willie with an
intensity that defies description.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I have no use for Clinton. I enthusiastically
supported Bob Dole last time around _ and I figured out long before
Clinton ran for re-election that he was a lying, double-dealing
worm.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody needs to tell me that what Clinton did in the
sex-and-lies scandal was despicable. For Clinton, despicableness is
an art form.
</P>
<P>
   But from the moment that the scandal exploded into the headlines
right up until the Senate voted him not guilty of perjury and
obstruction of justice, I never believed that Clinton should be
removed from office against the wishes of most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I've said it before, and now I'll say it again: Most
Americans did not want Clinton removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   That is a fact _ a fact supported by poll after scientific poll.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, the president's detractors would like to believe
that the polls are wrong or maybe even rigged. If you are
absolutely, positively certain that the president should be booted
out of the White House, it's plenty disconcerting to think that 60
to 70 percent of your countrymen disagree.
</P>
<P>
   It also stands to reason that a person with strong opinions on a
controversial topic will communicate those opinions most often to
people who are likely to agree. Most of us gravitate toward folks
who think as we do.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: Polling your family, pals and co-workers is no
way to gauge the attitudes of the public at large. Past performance
has shown that scientific, nationwide polls such as those
commissioned by major newspapers and television news organizations
are extremely accurate.
</P>
<P>
   There might be an argument here if the impeachment polls had
been all over the map _ if one said that 70 percent of Americans
wanted Clinton removed and the next said that 70 percent wanted him
to stay. But virtually every poll turned up the same result:
Somewhere between 60 and 70 percent wanted Clinton to finish his
term.
</P>
<P>
   You can disagree with the majority opinion that the polls
reflect. But you're deluding yourself if you insist that the polls
are wrong just because you don't like the results.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
