<P>
   GOVS-EDUCATION (Washington) _ The nation's governors and
President Clinton square off on education. Many governors,
especially Republicans, say requirements attached to federal aid
hamstring their ability to use it effectively. Clinton tells them
there can be both flexibility with the funds and accountability to
Washington, assuring that the money is being spent appropriately.
By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   VENTURA-BRITE (Washington) _ While ordering George W. Bush of
Texas to ``get on the bus'' as he and other governors prepare to
leave the White House, Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura makes some
colorful remarks about Texans. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-PENALTY (Washington) _ In a case that could affect death
row inmates around the country, the Supreme Court weighs whether
jurors in a Texas murder case were so confused by the judge's
instructions that they mistakenly opted to sentence a man to death.
By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-OIL (Washington) _ Energy Department officials meet with
Texas Railroad Commission Chairman Tony Garza to discuss the impact
of sagging oil prices on the nation's oil and gas industry. By MARK
HELM. Story will also be filed in the FINANCIAL\BUSINESS (``f'')
category.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Jasper, Texas) _ A pathologist testifies that
James Byrd Jr. was alive as he was dragged along a country road
until he hit a concrete culvert, severing his head and right arm.
The jury in the murder trial of John William King, 24, also is read
notes indicating that King called another murder defendant a
``snitch'' and adding that they may get the death penalty, but at
least they made history. PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   WILSON-2000 (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Former Gov. Pete Wilson
announces he will forgo a campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination. Wilson, who launched a short-lived campaign four years
ago, cites the costs to mount a campaign and an already crowded
field of potential GOP candidates. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Investors who don't catch the stock at
the right price can find themselves paying more for a stock than
they wanted or selling it for less than they had hoped. We examine
the dangers of buying and selling when stock prices are gyrating
wildly. By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ When leaders of the religious right
deplore a national decline in morality, they point to President
Clinton's survival and Congress' failure to enact their social
agenda. But they are selective about the sins they oppose. Most of
them are silent about the spread of gambling, which was considered
a major moral problem until Republican candidates discovered the
joys of the gambling industry's political contributions. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush and the
Texas Senate, which unanimously approved a bill to tackle social
promotions in the public schools, are absolutely right. Children
shouldn't be advanced to the next grade if they haven't mastered
the necessary skills. But this bill, assuming it passes the House
in a form with which the Senate and the governor can agree, is only
a first step. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKW-PERROT (Houston) _ Kim Perot, the popular guard of the
two-time WNBA champion Houston Comets, is expected to discuss her
brain tumor Thursday afternoon. By W.H. STICKNEY.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ We take a look at the Houston Rockets as
