<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4742 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     02-22 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO HALT INDEPENDENT COUNSEL INSANITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Bar Association is advising Congress to end the law
that authorizes the appointment of independent counsels. Congress
should heed that advice. Let the flawed experiment lapse.
</P>
<P>
   The power that law confers on an unelected individual to dictate
the nation's agenda while harassing private citizens and high
public officials, including the president, is more power than any
good man or woman should want _ and clearly more than a bad one
should have.
</P>
<P>
   Our republic managed well enough for almost 200 years without an
independent counsel. The Founding Fathers foresaw no need for one.
Our three constitutional branches of government sufficed.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the mischief that might have bedeviled this infant
nation if Congress had endowed some ambitious barrister with
subpoena power and sufficient public funds to mount an inquisition
into rumors questioning President Jefferson's chastity in the years
after his wife's death. Should the House then have impeached him if
he denied those rumors?
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson's private relationship with Sally Hemmings, whatever
it may have been, cannot diminish the luster of his life, the
vision that inspired the Louisiana Purchase, or the living legacy
of Jeffersonian principles embodied in the Declaration of
Independence and the Virginia Statute of Religious Toleration.
</P>
<P>
   What a tawdry pity if Thomas Jefferson, instead of being
remembered for these enduring treasures, were recalled chiefly as
an eccentric inventor who messed around with a slave girl. Who
among us would be better off?
</P>
<P>
   If America has learned nothing else from the great embarrassment
we've endured for the past 12 months, it should be that we really
don't need a battery of gumshoes _ whether motivated by political
hatred, professional zeal or moralistic voyeurism _ traipsing
around trying to find crimes with which to accuse our elected
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the independent counsel law was to divorce
investigations of executive branch officials entirely from
politics. It arose from the Nixon era. But even Leon Jaworski, who
came to symbolize the nonpartisanship for which everyone yearned,
was aware of the proper limitations upon an investigative lawyer's
powers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress intended, by authorizing the appointment of someone
outside the Justice Department, to protect the investigator's
objective independence from any possible presidential pressure to
go easy on sitting officials. Congress never intended that the
counsel should have a hostile attitude toward the target of his
investigation, or a predetermined plan to find guilt. One extreme,
obviously, would as bad as the other.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the idea was to investigate a specific complaint or
enumerated list of charges. The counsel was expected to respect
those boundaries, not search out additional excuses for pursuing
his prey. In theory, the counsel was an adviser, not a combatant.
His mission was not to get a conviction but to learn whether
serious infractions had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the line, the counsel began to see himself not
as an objective adviser but as a prosecutor whose job it was to win
a conviction of some sort _ if not on the matter he was initially
appointed to investigate, then on some other charge if he could
find or develop one.
</P>
<P>
   This warped misconstruction of original congressional intent was
manifest in the arbitrary action of a three-judge panel in
summarily removing Robert Fiske, originally appointed as the
independent counsel investigating allegations of Whitewater abuses,
and replacing him with Kenneth Starr. The stated rationale was that
Fiske, although a Republican and possessed of distinguished legal
credentials, was not proven to be sufficiently adversarial. In
Starr, the Republican judges had someone with a record of
conservative political activism and a demonstrable predisposition
to give the president no slack.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is easier, against the peculiar background of his
appointment, to see how Starr _ or at least some of his more
zealous prosecutorial assistants _ may have come to infer that it
was the mission of the outside counsel to ``get'' President
Clinton. This end, so desirable in the minds of some, came to
justify the sometimes questionable means employed by the
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone can doubt that the Starr prosecution efforts
during the past five years at a taxpayer cost of some $50 million
have raised serious issues of prosecutorial discretion. In the
opinion of some of the nation's top legal authorities, they've set
off a series of grievous abuses of power.
</P>
<P>
   These include the constant shift of focus from one unrewarding
allegation to another until the discovery of Linda Tripp's
illegally taped conversations brought Starr's attention to rest
upon Monica Lewinsky, whose relationship with Clinton had nothing
whatever to do with the questions that Starr was appointed to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The numerous press leaks; the flagrant breaches of grand jury
security; the holding and grilling of Lewinsky for several hours
without her lawyer, accompanied by the intimidating threats of
legal action against her mother; the spiteful imprisonment of Susan
MacDougal because she refused to swear to things she declares
untrue; and finally the taunting public boast of Starr that he had
the power to prosecute the president even while he's in office _
all these contribute to a pattern of arrogance and overreach.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this the unnecessary waste of tax money and good people's
reputations by other special prosecutors seeking their own
aggrandizement at the expense of former Cabinet officers Mike Espy
and Henry Cisneros. Think of the pettiness of the charges against
each of these two, measured alongside the overbearing zeal with
which each has been hounded. There's no excuse for prolonging this
sort of madness.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1618EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
