r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTONMAKEOVERS-TEX     02-22 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTONMAKEOVERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WILL TAKE MORE THAN A MAKEOVER TO MAKE THIS CROWD LOOK GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hey there, Bill, Hillary, Linda, Monica and Paula. You're all
lookin' good. Well, better, anyway. OK, actually, Bill's looking a
mite more haggard, but we can pass that off to age, if not stress.
</P>
<P>
   But there's something your mamas apparently didn't tell you:
Pretty is as pretty does. No matter how good you look after your
makeovers, most of you Clintonesque celebrities have simply
misbehaved too much to really look good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, given the dosage we've had of all these people after
this long a period of time, that it will take more than a
Vaseline-covered lens to fix their image,'' said Lisa LeMaster, a
Dallas communications consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you're trying. There's Linda Tripp on the ``Today'' show,
losing the glasses and the tent of hair for a demure swept-up 'do.
There's Monica Lewinsky, taming her own big hair and going to a
physical trainer before appearing for a deposition (and, not
coincidentally, a book-cover photo shoot). There's Paula Jones,
sporting a new nose.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, you've all found out what it's like to be a media
star _ and that it's not always fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every comedian in the world has done Linda Tripp, because she
had such bad hair and bad makeup,'' said Leon Hall, co-host of
``Fashion Emergency'' on the E! Entertainment Network. ``All these
women started out like caricatures. Artists go for the big noses or
small noses or big mouths because they're easy to draw.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Paula, Monica and Linda finally saw themselves
as other people did. It wasn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see our true selves in the mirror,'' Hall said.
``When you see yourself on camera, you see yourself from the side,
the left, the right, under the chin, over the chin, and it can be
shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton had a head start on the others, long ago
ditching the headbands of '92 and then the too-girlish long tresses
of '95. Now she looks more like a president's wife. (Or, perhaps,
senatorial?) And President Clinton _ uh, well ... he really didn't
do all that much, did he?
</P>
<P>
   It's not fair, but Bill probably wasn't expected to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, men are accepted in the way they look,'' said
Kathryn Bryan, owner of Kasal Image Consulting and Boutique in Fort
Worth. ``Women are under a lot more pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   For both sexes, however, it's unclear whether looking better
actually helps one's image. Despite Bill Clinton's distinguished
gray hair and carefully tailored suits, people still are aware that
he's an acknowledged adulterer. Perhaps Linda Tripp looked better
on ``Today,'' but people still remember that she surreptitiously
taped conversations with her one-time friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the general public, I'm not sure it does much good,'' said
Susan Huston, a Fort Worth personal development and etiquette
consultant. ``For the person, though, it gives them more
self-confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, however, disagrees that the damage is done. He believes
that the notoriety is going to make Linda, Monica and Paula
happening babes on the social circuit. Especially Monica.
</P>
<P>
   ``She will always get invited to the best parties in the
world,'' Hall said. ``And they will all feel better about
themselves when they walk into a room.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, take heart. The impeachment hearings are behind us, and
although people might remember you more now for what you did than
how you look, that won't last.
</P>
<P>
   After all, who really remembers Fawn Hall, Jessica Hahn or Donna
Rice?
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
