<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4745 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAMMYSPREVIEW-1200(2     02-22 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYSPREVIEW-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VIEWERS GUIDE TO THE 41ST ANNUAL GRAMMY AWARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dominated by women and chock-full of Texans, the 41st annual
Grammy Awards show comes to CBS on Wednesday _ with silly
nominations, potentially great live music and, we hope, enough
genuinely weird moments to keep you watching for three hours.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, the Grammys combine the formal atmosphere of an
award ceremony with the what's-gonna-happen-next excitement of a
good rock 'n' roll show. You may or may not remember who won Best
Album last year, but who can forget that half-naked guy who painted
``Soy Bomb'' on his chest and somehow made it onstage to dance with
Bob Dylan?
</P>
<P>
   This year's Grammys show is ... well ... shaping up fairly
nicely. There's a good mix of live performers (Madonna, Lauryn
Hill, Alanis Morissette), some interesting races, and several
Texans _ including Kirk Franklin, who is up for one of the most
coveted awards, Song of the Year, for ``Lean on Me.''
</P>
<P>
   And who knows? Maybe Soy Bomb will make a repeat appearance.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BEST RACES
</P>
<P>
   SONG OF THE YEAR: It's a long shot, but we're pulling for Kirk
Franklin's ``Lean on Me.'' And anything's preferable to Shania
Twain's gooey ``You're Still the One.''
</P>
<P>
   ROCK PERFORMANCE BY A DUO OR GROUP WITH VOCAL: Four of the five
nominees _ Aerosmith's ``Pink,'' Fastball's ``The Way,'' Hole's
``Celebrity Skin'' and the Verve's ``Bitter Sweet Symphony'' _
provide an interesting stylistic range. The Wallflowers' cover of
David Bowie's ``Heroes'' is atrocious. We'd like to see the Verve
get it; they've never gotten the Stateside popularity they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   POP COLLABORATION WITH VOCALS: Highlights are Elvis Costello and
Burt Bacharach's ``I Still Have That Other Girl'' and the Van
Morrison/Chieftains summit meeting, ``Shenandoah.'' It would be a
crime for the diabetes-inducing ``I'm Your Angel'' by R. Kelly and
Celine Dion to win, but we're not betting against 'em.
</P>
<P>
   CONTEMPORARY FOLK ALBUM: Talk about a lot of great music in one
place: Steve Earle's ``El Corazon,'' Lyle Lovett's ``Step Inside
This House,'' Lucinda Williams' ``Car Wheels on a Gravel Road,''
Emmylou Harris' ``Spyboy'' and the Billy Bragg/Wilco collaboration
``Mermaid Avenue.'' All are deserving, but Williams' CD is the best
of the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WEIRDEST NOMINATION
</P>
<P>
   John Hiatt's ``Have a Little Faith in Me'' is up for Male Rock
Vocal Performance and Rock Song. It's not a bad song _ in fact it's
a good song. It's just that it's been out since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SMART MOVES
</P>
<P>
   Now, show some respect. Sometimes the Grammys really do have
their finger on the pulse of pop music. This year's proof:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lauryn Hill's 10 nominations. While that may be a few too
many, there's no question her first solo CD was a hip-hop benchmark
and well worth all the attention.
</P>
<P>
   _ All the attention paid to Dallas' own Dixie Chicks, because we
like them, and they worked long and hard to get to where they are.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nominations for both BR5-49 and The Mavericks in the Country
Performance by a Duo or Group With Vocal category. Recent CDs by
both bands didn't sell well, so it's good to see their merits
recognized.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recognizing Johnny Cash, Mel Torme, William ``Smokey''
Robinson, Otis Redding and Sam Cooke with Lifetime Achievement
Awards. They all certainly deserve them.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   NEW STUFF
</P>
<P>
   No contest; the Grammys have too many categories. But these new
ones actually make sense:
</P>
<P>
   BEST TRADITIONAL R&AMP;B VOCAL PERFORMANCE. This is a good way to
honor the urban acts out there who aren't 22 years old and making a
mint off one hit CD. The nominees are Regina Belle, Patti LaBelle,
Aaron Neville, The Temptations and Luther Vandross.
</P>
<P>
   BEST CLASSICAL CROSSOVER ALBUM: So many classical artists record
in other genres, or team up with pop artists, that this was a
natural move.
</P>
<P>
   BEST TEJANO MUSIC PERFORMANCE: Setting this apart from all other
Mexican/American music makes perfect sense. The nominees are
Fiebre, Jaime y Los Chamacos, Flaco Jimenez, Leyendas y Raices and
Little Joe y La Familia.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WORST RACES
</P>
<P>
   OK, sometimes this show just misses the boat. Our biggest
complaints:
</P>
<P>
   POP ALBUM: Eric Clapton's ``Pilgrim'' is here basically because
it's by Eric Clapton; Brian Setzer's ``The Dirty Boogie'' is hardly
the best swing CD, just the one featuring the guy with the most
name recognition. Look for Celine Dion's ``Let's Talk About Love''
to win, even though the best choice (at least in this company) is
Natalie Imbruglia's ``Left of the Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   ALTERNATIVE MUSIC PERFORMANCE: Again, several nominations for
subpar efforts from name artists, including Tori Amos' ``From the
Choirgirl Hotel'' and Smashing Pumpkins' ``Adore.'' Radiohead's
``Airbag/How Am I Driving?'' is easily the best choice here.
</P>
<P>
   POP PERFORMANCE BY A DUO OR GROUP WITH VOCAL: Or, let's put a
bunch of songs we're all really sick of in one category.
Aerosmith's ``I Don't Want to Miss a Thing,'' Barenaked Ladies'
``One Week'' and the Goo Goo Dolls' ``Iris'' are the worst
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   HARD ROCK PERFORMANCE: When a so-so song by Pearl Jam (''Do the
Evolution'') is the best bet, you know a category is weak. Kiss'
``Psycho Circus'' and Marilyn Manson's ``The Dope Show'' are
horrible, and Jimmy Page and Robert Plant's ``Most High'' is a mere
shadow of their former glories in Led Zeppelin.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   PERFORMANCES TO WATCH FOR
</P>
<P>
   Possibly in an attempt to keep folks watching, the show won't
list a schedule of performances, and some artists may be added at
the last minute. But here are the ones we're looking forward to:
</P>
<P>
   LAURYN HILL. Last year's ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill'' was
so good, and besides, she's never played around here as a solo act.
</P>
<P>
   MADONNA. Fun to watch, just to see what she's going to wear.
</P>
<P>
   KIRK FRANKLIN _ with Bono (yes, you read that correctly, the
lead singer of U2), Mary J. Blige and Crystal Lewis. How cool is
that?
</P>
<P>
   SHERYL CROW. We always like Sheryl Crow.
</P>
<P>
   ALANIS MORISSETTE. Because she's, well, Alanis.
</P>
<P>
   WYNTON MARSALIS. He'll lead a tribute to Duke Ellington, who
would have been 100 this year, and he'll be joined by Natalie Cole
and the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT THAT HOST
</P>
<P>
   The relentlessly perky Rosie O'Donnell is this year's host.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, why? O'Donnell tirelessly promotes Broadway on her afternoon
talk show, but what connection does she have to rock 'n' roll?
</P>
<P>
   Some better ideas:
</P>
<P>
   STING. He's poised, he's handsome, and he isn't getting many
nominations these days.
</P>
<P>
   BILL MURRAY. He's funny, he's hot again thanks to ``Rushmore,''
and he could do that lounge-singer guy murdering ``Stairway to
Heaven,'' just like on the old ``Saturday Night Live'' skit.
</P>
<P>
   JENNIFER LOPEZ. Because there's no such thing as too much
Jennifer Lopez. The music connection is that, um, give us a second
_ ``Out of Sight'' had a great soundtrack. Yeah. That's it.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA GOODING JR. OK, no obvious music connection here either.
But he's just so darned cool. And enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TEXANS
</P>
<P>
   Man, are there a lot of Texans up for Grammys this year _ more
than two dozen, from Arlington's Kirk Franklin to Dallas' Erykah
Badu and Dixie Chicks to Houston's Yolanda Adams and Clint Black.
Some we'd really like to see win _ or who may actually do so:
</P>
<P>
   KIRK FRANKLIN. He's the underdog for Song of the Year and Best
R&AMP;B Song, but he looks like a lock for Best Contemporary Soul
Gospel Album.
</P>
<P>
   THE DIXIE CHICKS. They deserve that Best New Artist trophy, but
we can also see them crossing the stage for Best Country Album and
Best Country Performance by a Duo or Group With Vocal.
</P>
<P>
   LUCINDA WILLIAMS. No, she wasn't born here and she doesn't live
here anymore, but she did live in Texas for nearly 20 years. We're
betting she takes Best Contemporary Folk Album; her shot at Best
Female Rock Vocal Performance is not nearly as strong.
</P>
<P>
   BRAVE COMBO. This is the second time the Denton institution has
been up for Best Polka Album. Here's hoping.
</P>
<P>
   FASTBALL. The Austin trio is up for both Best Rock Performance
by a Duo or Group and Best Long Form Music Video for ``They Wanted
the Highway.''
</P>
<P>
   THE LIGHT CRUST DOUGHBOYS (in collaboration with the James
Blackwood Quartet) have a shot at Best Southern, Country, or
Bluegrass Gospel Album for ``They Gave the World a Smile: The
Stamps Quartet Tribute Album.'' Good luck to 'em.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PARING DOWN
</P>
<P>
   There are 95 Grammy categories. Way too many. Our suggestions
for a leaner, meaner show:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make ONE metal category by combining Hard Rock Performance and
Metal Performance. We don't need both, and in either case we don't
need Judas Priest's ``Bullet Train.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Make ONE country collaboration category by combining Country
Music Performance by a Duo or Group With Vocal and Country
Collaboration With Vocals. Repeat after me: We don't need both.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep the Pop/Contemporary Gospel Album category, and lose the
Rock Gospel Album category. If they're not exactly the same thing,
they're close enough.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's the difference between Traditional Blues Album and
Contemporary Blues Album? Both feature mainly veteran performers,
such as Etta James, B.B. King and Otis Rush. So one last time: We
don't need both.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
