<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAILLEBIBLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINISTRY BINDS TOGETHER BRAILLE BIBLE VOLUNTEERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ For years, members from Grace Lutheran Church
car-pooled from Arlington to neighboring Fort Worth to help make it
possible to bring the Scriptures to the blind and visually
impaired.
</P>
<P>
   Once a month, sometimes more, they'd make the trek to Zion
Lutheran.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't really matter where they worked; their goal was
simple, if lofty: producing books of the Bible in Braille.
</P>
<P>
   When volunteers asked about the feasibility of having their own
center last summer, Grace Lutheran gave them the go-ahead to open
one in the church basement. And in September, the center was
dedicated in memory of E.O. Voge, one of the team's charter
members.
</P>
<P>
   Less than six months later, under the leadership of husband and
wife Harvey and Ruth Brown, the Grace Lutheran team has produced
more than 500 Braille versions of books of the Bible for
distribution throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   This, the Browns say, is their ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I are retired, and it's something that's really
needed,'' Ruth Brown said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Nine teams _ five from Grace Lutheran, two from Cross of Christ
in DeSoto, one from Holy Cross in Arlington and one from Christ
Lutheran in Fort Worth _ meet at the Arlington church.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the teams at Grace Lutheran, 13 others, including
three youth groups, meet at Zion Lutheran Church in suburban
Watauga under the leadership of Verna Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   The teams are part of a network of more than 7,000 volunteers
nationwide who make up the Lutheran Braille Workers, based in
Yucaipa, Calif. Their work is financed by donations and gifts from
churches and other groups across the country.
</P>
<P>
   At Grace, teams make the book of Numbers in Spanish and a
Mustard Seed devotional titled ``And When You Pray'' in English. At
Zion, it's the book of Psalms in English, Corinthians in Portuguese
and the Sermon on the Mount in Sinhalese.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning at Grace Lutheran, a dozen volunteers were
deep in an assembly-line process.
</P>
<P>
   The operation begins with one person punching holes in white
81/2-by-11-inch sheets of paper. The next volunteer puts the paper
between two zinc plates that contain the bumpy Braille imprints.
</P>
<P>
   Each set of zinc plates contains one page of a book of the Bible
in Braille. Then the plates are put inside a metal jacket and run
through the press.
</P>
<P>
   When the plates come out of the jackets, the paper goes through
a binding process, and part of the book is made. The whole
procedure lasts about two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Lutheran Braille Workers began some 55 years ago when Helene
Loewe and her father, Carl Loeber, learned from a Lutheran magazine
that Braille religious books were needed in Germany because so many
were destroyed during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Brown and her husband have been Lutheran Braille Workers
volunteers for more than 20 years. So has Verna Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was enchanting to think that we could make books of the
Bible for the blind,'' Montgomery said. ``And it's fun and I feel
that God really called me to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Both women, though, would like to spread their work to other
churches in the county. Letters seeking help have been sent out to
nearly every church in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're Lutheran, but this doesn't mean other churches can't
participate,'' said Ruth Brown. ``These books are going all over
the world, and not just to Lutherans.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in volunteering with the Braille teams or
anyone who would like a Braille Bible, should call Ruth Brown at
(817) 274-8600, Verna Montgomery at (817) 831-6622 or Lutheran
Braille Workers at (909) 795-8977, or write to Box 5000, Yucaipa,
CA 92399.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
