</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOPPING SOCIAL PROMOTIONS ONLY A FIRST STEP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush and the Texas Senate, which
unanimously approved a bill to tackle social promotions in the
public schools, are absolutely right. Children shouldn't be
advanced to the next grade if they haven't mastered the necessary
skills.
</P>
<P>
   But this bill, assuming it passes the House in a form with which
the Senate and the governor can agree, is only a first step. After
years of failing to meet the needs of thousands of young people,
state educators and policy-makers are going to have to make a huge
commitment of time, energy and money _ and keep making it, long
after Bush and today's lawmakers have departed from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The need for reform is great. Some 42,000 third-graders _ more
than one-third of the students at that grade level _ failed the
Texas Assessment of Academic Skills, the state's standardized
measurement of student achievement, in the spring of 1997. But
38,000 of the failing students were advanced to the fourth grade
anyway. They were ``socially'' promoted to keep up with their age
group.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that many Texas employers have difficulty finding
young workers with more than minimal literacy skills.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, also, that ending social promotions was a key part
of Bush's re-election campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the governor proposed that students simply be held
back a grade if they failed the TAAS test. It was a
three-strikes-and-you're-out proposition because a child would have
had three chances to pass the exam or be held back.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush revised that proposal in the face of opposition from
some lawmakers and school officials. Some parents, myself included,
also believe it is not right to pass or fail a child simply on the
basis of one standardized test. The test should be an important
factor, but human input also is needed from those who know the
students and their overall capabilities the best _ their teachers
and parents.
</P>
<P>
   The bill approved by the Senate is an improvement over the
governor's original plan and may be an acceptable compromise. But
perhaps the House can improve the measure some more. Several House
members already have said they will try.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would still make the TAAS test the major factor
in determining promotions for third-, fifth- and eighth-graders,
beginning with the third-grade class of the 2002-2003 school year.
Those are the children who will be starting kindergarten this
August.
</P>
<P>
   The changes wouldn't affect students already in school.
</P>
<P>
   Third-graders, beginning in the spring of 2003, would have to
pass the TAAS reading test to be promoted to the fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   When they reached the fifth grade, they would have to pass the
reading and math sections of TAAS, and in the eighth grade they
would have to pass reading, math and writing sections of the exam.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary, students would be given three chances in each year
to pass the test, and those who fail would be assigned to intensive
remedial classes.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's initial plan was changed by the Senate to give
students who fail the required sections of the TAAS _ even after
three attempts _ an opportunity to still be advanced to the next
grade. A failing child could be promoted if a committee that would
include his parents, teacher and principal approves. Even then,
though, the student would have to take remedial classes.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal committee would provide a subjective look that may be
important in some students' cases. But to keep the appeals process
from being misused to gut the reform effort, the number of social
promotions that a school allowed would be considered by the Texas
Education Agency in grading a school's performance on the exemplary
to low-performing scale.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate plan, the state would spend $203 million for
remedial classes and teacher training. But some House members
already are questioning whether that is enough money, and minority
lawmakers, in particular, are concerned about the effect of the
bill on minority children, who make up a large portion of the
failing students.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing the Legislature's sometimes-neglectful track record,
state Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas, convinced the Senate to adopt an
amendment that will release school districts from enforcing the new
program if the state doesn't adequately fund it in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the Senate bill ``sent a strong message that no child
will be left behind in our state, that when a child is identified
with a reading deficiency we'll correct it early before it's too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   There's certainly nothing wrong with strong messages, but this
exercise better be much more than a message. Without adequate,
continued funding for the all-important remedial instruction _ and
it won't be inexpensive _ the new program will be little more than
a cruel joke on Texas children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
