<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-LETTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH MAINTAINS BRIDGE TO PAST BY KEEPING LETTERS FROM WWII
HEROES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A few months before D-Day, the 6th of June,
1944, Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower received a letter from boys in a
Sunday school class at Fort Worth's Broadway Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   In Portsmouth, England, at the time, preparing for World War
II's momentous invasion of Normandy, Eisenhower dictated this reply
on Jan. 19, 1944:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very interested to hear what you are doing. I am a firm
believer in the power of prayer and it gladdens my heart to hear
that you are praying for me and all the armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Information about Eisenhower's letter _ and similar letters of
reply in the same wartime year from Gen. George S. Patton, Adm.
Chester W. Nimitz and Adm. Ernest J. King _ came to light in a
chance conversation between church members.
</P>
<P>
   Opal Carson, who had kept the letters in her personal files,
learned that the letters from the military leaders might be
valuable when she told a fellow Sunday school worker about them.
Her late husband, Fort Worth lawyer Robert C. Carson, had taught a
World War II-era Sunday school class for boys ages 12 and 13.
Letters of support written by the class elicited the responses from
the military leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Opal Carson, who died last year, said she would like to donate
the letters so the church could sell them to help pay for its $3.5
million project to buy a new organ and renovate its sanctuary. The
project was completed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Opal Carson's son, Robert Carson II, and his wife, Judy, are
members of Broadway, and they encouraged the donation idea.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials made inquiries and learned from New York
auction authorities that the letters were valued at more than
$3,000.
</P>
<P>
   But before the letters were offered for sale, church members
stepped forward and donated $3,700 to the church's
organ-and-building fund so the generals' letters could remain a
part of church history, church spokewoman Martha Newton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Steve Shoemaker, pastor, said the church's finance
committee chairman, Walt Jennings, led the way in getting people to
donate money for the letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was absolutely the widow's mite,'' said Larry Borne, one of
several church members who urged church officials to keep the
letters. Borne said Opal Carson had a desire to make a generous
donation to the church, and the letters allowed her to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the letters and photographs of the generals will be framed
and placed on display in the church. Former U.S. Rep. Pete Geren, a
church member, said he worked with the Library of Congress to
obtain photographs of the generals that had been taken about the
time the letters were written.
</P>
<P>
   James Lowe, a New York autograph expert recommended by Sotheby's
auction house, analyzed the letters, said Newton.
</P>
<P>
   Patton's signature was the most valuable and would bring between
$2,500 and $3,000, Lowe said in an interview. All the signatures
except Eisenhower's are authentic, he said. Eisenhower's name was
signed by his aide, Kay Summersby, according to Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   Patton scrawled ``G.S. Patton'' to this typed note:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear friends: Please accept for all the members of your class
the sincere thanks of myself and the soldiers whom I have the honor
to command for the prayerful words in our behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   Nimitz, a Fredericksburg, Texas, native who commanded the
Pacific Fleet and engineered the crucial Midway victory, wrote:
``It is always gratifying to hear from young men of such high
ideals. I deeply appreciate your prayers for me and the officers
and men of the Fleet, and assure you we are doing our best to
defeat the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   A note from King, the chief of naval operations, declared: ``It
is good to know of the interest taken by your class in the welfare
of military leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Borne said Opal and Robert Carson both had been his Sunday
school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were humble, dedicated people,'' he said. ``I think
historically this is a wonderful thing for the church.''
</P>
<P>
   LaVonne Wilson, retired pastor's administrative assistant at
Broadway, said Opal Carson was a good friend who kept volunteering
for church jobs even into her mid-90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the most gentle lady you ever saw, one you would want
to emulate as a Christian person,''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
