<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4772 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MASSACRE-ANTHROPO     02-22 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MASSACRE-ANTHROPOLOGY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURIED ON A HILLSIDE, CLUES TO TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Okla.)   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (Eds: please note sub dateline)  
 (af)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO DE NENTON, Guatemala _ On the morning of July 17,
1982, a convoy of army trucks made its way up a nearly impassable
trail to this remote Mayan Indian hamlet and unloaded a company of
troops. Soon afterward a helicopter arrived with the unit's
officers.
</P>
<P>
   As the troops spread out they ordered the village men to round
up some cows for a feast. But meanwhile soldiers corralled the rest
of the people into the huts that dotted the site _ a magistrate's
tiny office, a chapel and mud-walled dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next was a butchery that left all but four of the
village's inhabitants dead and all the buildings razed. According
to contemporary accounts by people who lived in neighboring
communities, many of the women were ordered to disrobe and were
raped.
</P>
<P>
   Children were torn from mothers' arms and eviscerated by knives
or beheaded by machetes. The rampaging troops killed all they
found, shooting some villagers, blowing some up with grenades,
hacking some to death, burning some or crushing them under the
walls of falling buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and acquaintances of the victims compiled a list of
376 villagers believed to have perished. For the last 17 years
there had been no serious effort to check this list or details of
the massacre by independent means, but finally the light of
scientific inquiry has begun to expose material evidence of the
atrocity.
</P>
<P>
   The facts unearthed by scientists who have been working here in
the last few weeks appear to corroborate contemporary accounts all
too graphically.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of San Francisco de Nenton was common throughout
Guatemala in the 1980s, as the government, which had support from
the United States, sought to crush rebel guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 the country's 36-year civil war formally ended, and with
peace came an end to massacres (although isolated cases of
political violence have continued). The present government has
sought to heal some of the wounds of war, and recently sentenced
three men to death for murders of civilians they were accused of
having committed while serving in the dreaded paramilitary Civil
Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   But the tally of dead and missing victims of Guatemala's reign
of terror is far from complete, and a band of volunteer forensic
anthropologists, acting with the government's blessing, has set out
to decipher a few of the massacre sites, gathering evidence from
shattered bones, spent bullets and domestic objects including the
pitiful remnants of children's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have absolutely no political objectives,'' said Fredy A.
Peccerelli, a forensic anthropologist who heads the Foundation for
Forensic Anthropology of Guatemala. ``What we're attempting to do
is check the accounts of witnesses and wherever possible to apply
the techniques of forensic science to set the record straight. We
examine massacre sites using many of the same techniques police use
at crime scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   Money for the project is all but nonexistent, except for
sporadic donations by the George Soros Foundation and some other
philanthropic groups. Despite the lack of money, the volunteers,
supported mainly by their wives and husbands, have come from
various countries to join their Guatemalan forensic colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they apply their experience as anthropologists,
archeologists and osteologists in sifting truth from legend as they
pick through the rubble of recent history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never exhume and investigate all the many massacre
sites in Guatemala,'' Peccerelli said, ``but our work in San
Francisco de Nenton will stand as a symbol of all the communities
that were wiped out.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their lack of material resources the team is rich in
experience. In the San Francisco project as in dozens of other
projects involving massacre sites in Guatemala, the group has had
support and guidance from Dr. Clyde Collins Snow, 71, a forensic
anthropologist who lives in Norman, Okla. Snow, a legend among
forensic experts, has investigated massacres in 20 countries in
Latin America, Africa, the Balkans and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   One of his best-known cases was an investigation of the identity
and manner of death of a young woman slain, along with about 10,000
other people, by Argentina's military regime in the ``dirty war''
of the 1970s. At a 1985 trial in Buenos Aires of military officers
charged with the murders, Snow presented such compelling and
detailed evidence of judicial crime that several high-ranking
officers were convicted and jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the young Argentine anthropologists who worked with Snow
in his investigation was Dario Olmo, who went on to investigate
massacre sites elsewhere, including Bosnia, Kurdistan and,
rejoining Snow, here in Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   The place where San Francisco de Nenton stood covers a cluster
of picturesque hills a few miles south of the Mexican border.
Adorned by an ancient Mayan pyramid, the site would make a lovely
picnic ground.
</P>
<P>
   But just beneath the grassy surface lies the horror the forensic
team is unearthing, as it measures, photographs and catalogs the
grim remnants before transporting them to Peccerelli's combination
home and laboratory in Guatemala City. There, the bones will be
X-rayed and further examined.
</P>
<P>
   At one of a half-dozen burial sites discovered at San Francisco
de Nenton so far, Renaldo Acevedo, a Guatemalan anthropologist,
paused to look into a shallow pit where he and several colleagues
had been digging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dos ninos o ninas,'' he murmured as Snow arrived. A cluster of
children's bones covered by the faded but still colorful clothing
of an adult Indian woman lay exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Snow carefully dislodged one of several jaw bones in the pit and
held it close to his glasses. Speaking carefully in a slow Texas
drawl as if addressing a tape recorder in the Oklahoma City morgue
where he often works, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the site of a house said to have belonged to one
Felipe Sylvestre. We have here a juvenile skull with several
fractures, probably post-mortem. Two of the teeth are deciduous but
one molar has erupted. This child was between 6 and 7 years old.
Sex undetermined, but may be inferred from laboratory measurements
and a statistical computer program called discriminant function
analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   The program, he explained to an onlooker, ``is essentially a
tool for comparing measurements taken of one individual with a huge
data base accumulated over many years.'' Of its accuracy, he said,
``The computer picks the sex correctly about 90 percent of the time
but gets the race right in only about 80 percent of the cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Acevedo held up a handful of cartridge cases he had found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Snow said. ``These are all .223-caliber M-16 rounds.
That means that the troops who shot these children were regular
army, not Civil Patrol men, who carried only .22-caliber sporting
rifles.
</P>
<P>
   He paused and added, ``Poor little kids.''
</P>
<P>
   A hundred yards away, working with a dental pick and toothbrush,
Claudia Rivera and several other Guatemalan archeologists were
excavating the village magistrate's office. So far, they had found
skull parts and the jaws of 11 bodies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
