<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-WORKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS SURPRISING NUMBER OF GIRLS WORK TO SURVIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANNIE NAKAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A surprising number of girls and young women
work while attending school, and nearly a quarter either support
themselves or others in often illegal employment situations,
according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco-based Young Women's Work Project recently
issued its first national study of the work experiences of poor and
working-class females under 21. The national nonprofit organization
surveyed 865 girls and women, ages 12 through 20, from 26 states
and the District of Columbia who worked with community agencies.
Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ More than two-thirds of those surveyed worked between seven
and 35 hours per week event though they attended school;
</P>
<P>
   _ 27 percent worked illegally because they were too young for
legal jobs;
</P>
<P>
   _ 22 percent supported themselves and, in many cases, others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results smash the stereotypes,'' said Lateefah Simon,
executive director of the Center for Young Women's Development in
San Francisco, which established the Young Women's Work Project
last year. ``They argue for a shift in how we view and enforce
child labor laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The center advocates for employment for young women while
providing them with leadership training and job opportunities. The
new project takes that concept nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, laws designed to protect children from labor
exploitation work against young women seeking work by pushing them
into illegal jobs, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Even in legal jobs, young girls are frequently unaware of job
protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It amazes and saddens me that 43 percent of those questioned
said they didn't know they could take a 10-minute break on their
jobs,'' said Kelly O'Neill, co-founder of the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young women really, really want the opportunity to do things,
learn things, be leaders and make a difference,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1636EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4774 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MASSACRE-ANTHROPO     02-22 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MASSACRE-ANTHROPOLOGY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SAN FRANCISCO DE NENTON, Guatemala: 11 bodies.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a painstaking process of sorting and matching, the first
batches of bones and artifacts were packed in plastic bags and
cardboard cartons. The team's pickup truck doubles as a hearse,
transporting the forensic treasure through the bandit-infested
Guatemalan highlands to Peccerelli's laboratory in Guatemala City.
There the skeletons are being laid out on tables for closer
scrutiny and measurement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much the same as excavating an archeological site,'' Ms.
Rivera said. ``As the years pass, everything in a site like this
decays, and it gets harder to interpret, just as ancient sites are
hard to interpret. But for us this is not academic archeology. This
place _ how shall I say? _ it has special meaning for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow said, ``We see some straight-edged machete cuts on the arms
and skulls of the men who died in this building, with many shell
cases and bullets all over the place. Witness accounts spoke of
soldiers forcing men into this building, bringing them out 8 or 10
at a time and shooting them.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the troops fired their weapons into the men still
inside the building, and then tossed in one or more grenades.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Ms. Rivera said, ``we've found many bullets that seem
to have come from the door. There are traces of an explosion. The
house was apparently set on fire _ we've found the charred wooden
door lintel and other evidence of burning. Then the troops
collapsed the walls of the house to bury the corpses.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow pondered the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strange thing is that we are seeing lots of fragments of
skulls, pelvises, vertebrae and ribs, but almost no femurs.
Scavenging animals could have carried off small bones, but probably
not femurs, so what became of the femurs?''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, let's imagine a hypothesis and see if we can find some way
to test it,'' he continued. ``We know that all the sites we've
found in San Francisco so far have been disturbed, and we know from
witnesses that some time after the massacre troops came back to
tidy things up and conceal the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   ``By then the bodies would have partly decomposed. It could be
that the legs of a lot of victims were protruding from the
collapsed building walls. When the troops tried to pull them out
the legs could have separated from the bodies, and the soldiers
might have buried the legs somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   About then there arrived a local man named Mateo Perez Ramos,
who had narrowly escaped being herded into the magistrate's house
and who had fled Mexico. Perez said he had seen the burial of three
large sacks of loose bones some months after the massacre, and he
pointed to a place between two trees.
</P>
<P>
   But even aided by a bulldozer, Peccerelli's group failed to find
the bones in the first few days of work.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of bones elsewhere, however. Skeletons turned
up under the collapsed walls of the village chapel and in a house
where coffee beans seemed to have been roasting just before the
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen skeletons from San Francisco and other massacre sites
have already arrived at Peccerelli's Guatemala City laboratory,
grotesquely arrayed on tables around a front-yard swimming pool.
Each set of bones was assembled as completely as possible,
post-mortem breaks in skulls were glued together, and case dossiers
were opened.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the massacre victims had managed to get extensive dental
repairs in their lives, including gold crowns and dentures. These
and healed fractures in arm and leg bones are being compared with
medical records.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic teams sometimes make as many as 200 skeletal
measurements in pursuing identities. For example, slight
disparities in the lengths of the radius and ulna arm bones can
reveal a person's handedness. Another useful gauge is the degree of
fusion between two adjoining pelvic bones (the pubic symphysis),
which indicates an adult's age quite accurately.
</P>
<P>
   The ratio of an eye socket's width to its height, the distance
between brow ridges, the width of nose bridges and many other
facial characteristics can suggest kinships that help in tracing
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where relatives (and money) are available, DNA analysis
is a powerful identification tool, Snow said. Even in badly decayed
skeletons, hard shells of dentine usually protect the pulp cavities
of teeth, preserving the DNA inside.
</P>
<P>
   Some skeletons show evidence of torture before death; one man
showed marks left by wires that had bound his wrists while he was
assailed on all sides by machete. Another skeleton's pelvis was
riddled with bullet fragments; the man apparently remained alive
until he was dispatched by a machete blow.
</P>
<P>
   The copper cladding of military bullets leaves traces on bone
when it corrodes, depositing indelible green stains that help
forensic experts reconstruct events.
</P>
<P>
   On one of the many forensic expeditions he has made to Guatemala
since 1991, Snow examined the skeletons of people whose lumbar
vertebrae had been smashed before death by shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out,'' he said, ``that the Civil Patrol troops had a
habit of tying their victims to trees and then forcing relatives in
the village at gunpoint to chop away at the prisoners' backs with
machetes. When the troops got bored they would shoot the dying
victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rivera said: ``I just cannot understand how people can do
these things to each other. How can a man cut a child's throat?
Must these things go on forever?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
