<HEADER>
A4812 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-22 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 50, IT'S TIME TO LOOK UNDER THE HOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As you are reading this, I am about to do to my guts what your
mechanic does when he boils out your radiator and back-flushes your
cooling system.
</P>
<P>
   They call it a pre-surgical catharsis. You and I would call it a
real pain in the whatchamacallit. But my innards must be squeaky
clean for tomorrow's surgery to remove a couple of polyps from my
colon.
</P>
<P>
   And with a sort of pre-surgical hindsight, I feel compelled to
share this with you not only to explain my subsequent temporary
absence from this space, but also to urge you to have your own
pipes checked.
</P>
<P>
   I am by no means a guru of gesundheit (literally,
``healthiness''). I'm at least 10 percent overweight. I suffered a
heart attack almost 15 years ago. I am something of a binge eater.
And my exercise is limited primarily to noontime walks and
strolling the aisles of hardware stores. My recommended daily eight
glasses of water are hidden in as many cups of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, I can endorse and pass-along this general
recommendation from my several doctors: By the time you turn 50,
male or female, you should have some sort of periodic colo-rectal
exam. The polyps discovered in my colon last year have about a 25
percent chance of becoming cancerous, I was told. Samples cut from
the polyps were benign, they said, but little cuttings don't tell
the whole story.
</P>
<P>
   There was no need to rush, I was advised, but neither could I
put it off like waiting for my muffler finally to fall off
somewhere along Mercer Street.
</P>
<P>
   Preventive maintenance isn't a guarantee. I eat a whole lot of
what the experts say is good stuff to ward off gastro-intestinal
cancers, including brussels sprouts, broccoli and cauliflower, oat
meal, bran cereals, fresh fruit, tomatoes, olive oil, Vitamin E,
and garlic ... boy, do I love garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I also love steak and chicken, especially
barbecued. And who doesn't like pizza or a large serving of french
fries? And candy. Charred meats and fish have been linked to cancer
in numerous studies. So has sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there are no guarantees, even with clean, healthy living.
Some people are predisposed genetically to colon cancer. But the
rest of us also are at risk. More than 95,000 new cases of colon
cancer were diagnosed in the U.S. last year. That's diagnosed, as
opposed to Lord only knows how many undetected.
</P>
<P>
   We certainly don't have to wait like New York Yankees outfielder
Darryl Strawberry, who was sidelined last year after discovery of a
cancerous tumor almost blocking his colon. Or the too-late
discovery of a colon cancer that a year ago killed NBC-TV legal
commentator Jay Monahan, husband of ``Today'' show co-host Katie
Couric.
</P>
<P>
   Best options for most of us are three, according to Dr. Peter
Justus, the gastroenterologist who will perform a colonoscopy to
dye-mark my polyps before Dr. E. Stan Lennard, the surgeon, does
his thing.
</P>
<P>
   1. Periodic fecal-smear samples for occult blood, that nasty
little do-it-yourself thing where you try to stab elusive targets
with a little wooden stick and smear samples on a flimsy piece of
cardboard. This is supposed to help detect blood in your bowel. It
should be combined with a sigmoidoscope exam every five years, one
of those doctors-office exams where they tell you that ``this may
feel a little uncomfortable'' as they peer into the lower third of
your colon.
</P>
<P>
   2. Colonoscopy every 10 years. Done under anesthesia, a 3-foot
scope is threaded through all 4 or 5 feet of your colon. This is
how they found my polyps.
</P>
<P>
   3. Air or double-contrast barium enema with X-ray. Frankly, this
is the most uncomfortable procedure, although when used in
combination with sigmoidoscopy is considered almost as good as a
colonoscopy.
</P>
<P>
   At your end, so-to-speak, any of these tests is better than
sticking your head in the sand ... or anywhere else. The casual
discovery of my two polyps _ I displayed no symptoms or problems _
came not during an earlier routine sigmoidoscopy, but when a
routine colonoscopy went the whole nine yards, or 4 feet.
</P>
<P>
   That exam revealed two tubulovillous adenoma, or, polyps that
could progress to cancer. And unlike some, which are like little
mushrooms on stalks, mine are ``sessile'' (from the Latin word for
``sitting''), and more likely to become cancerous.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what got me sitting where I am right now. And I am so
full of good intentions that I may eventually address another of my
potential health problem. But then, I already know they won't let
me smoke cigars in the hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1702EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4813 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-     02-22 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: GETTING A MASTER PLAN TO ADD ON DOG YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chances are your medicine chest is well stocked with first-aid
supplies to help you cope with the myriad injuries that sooner or
later befall every man, woman and child _ Band-Aids, bite and burn
ointments, cold packs, perhaps even a first-aid manual.
</P>
<P>
   But what have you got for your dog? In most households, this
beloved member of the family, even if regularly groomed, carefully
trained and fed a specially formulated diet, is sorely neglected
when it comes to first aid.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know what to do, for example, if your dog should choke,
break a leg, injure an ear, cut a foot pad or swallow poison? Do
you have on hand the first-aid supplies needed to prevent further
damage and safely transport your dog to the vet? And what if a
disaster should strike _ a fire, earthquake, hurricane or flood _
that forces you to evacuate in a flash? Do you have a disaster plan
in place to rescue your pet?
</P>
<P>
   Knowing full well that for the vast majority of dog owners, the
answer to these questions is invariably no, veterinary specialists
at Purdue University have put together a manual called ``Rescuing
Rover: A First Aid and Disaster Guide for Dog Owners,'' written by
Dr. Sebastian E. Heath and illustrated by Andrea O'Shea (Purdue
University Press, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anticipating calamities is antithetical to the
American spirit of optimism. But let's face facts: Accidents do
happen, to dogs as well as to people. Dogs love to jump but can
land badly and break a leg. They can step on glass and cut a foot
pad, which may gush like a geyser.
</P>
<P>
   They can get hit by a car, tear their flesh on a jagged edge, be
bitten by another dog or a snake or kicked by a horse. Or, as my
dog Max did twice (do they ever learn?), they may bite a porcupine
and end up with a mouth full of quills.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, you'll need to know how to restrain your pet
so that first aid can be applied without your being bitten. An
animal that is frightened and in pain may snap at even the most
adored owner, especially when a painful injury is being treated.
You may also be called upon to restrain your dog while the vet
administers treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the area involved, there are two ways to restrain a
pet: with the animal lying down or sitting. With the dog lying on
its side, place your knees against the animal's back, one forearm
on its neck and the other on the dog's flank. With each hand, hold
the limbs that are against the floor and shift your weight over the
dog.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases the dog will need to be muzzled so that no one
gets hurt. If you do not have a muzzle, you can fashion one with a
four-foot strip of two-inch gauze tape. Circle the dog's mouth and
tie a half-knot above the nose. Then bring the ends back under the
jaw and tie another half-knot, bring the ends under and behind the
ears and tie a firm bow at the back of the neck. After you've
muzzled your dog, you're ready to bandage a leg or paw or treat an
injured eye or ear.
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, your dog breaks a leg or dislocates a joint
above the knee or elbow, applying a splint can keep matters from
getting worse on the way to the vet. Or if the dog's foot pad is
cut, apply pressure to stop the bleeding, flush and clean the wound
with saline solution (one heaping tablespoon salt in one gallon
water), then an antiseptic like triple antibiotic ointment, dry the
foot and cover the injured area with a nonstick dressing and gauze
squares. Then wrap the foot in cotton wool covered by a tight wrap
of stretch gauze (but not so tight that it impedes circulation).
</P>
<P>
   If your dog ingests or inhales a poisonous substance or absorbs
poison through the skin, prevent further exposure to the poison and
avoid poisoning yourself. Wear protective clothing and wash the
contaminated skin liberally with water and soap (not detergent).
See a vet without delay (if possible, bring the poison with you) or
consult (for a fee) the National Animal Poison Control Center at
(800) 548-2423.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you'd be wise to keep your pet out of urban park areas
that have been treated with rat poison. The bait is as attractive
to dogs as it is to rats, and just a few pieces can kill an animal
of 40 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs are famous for trying to eat things that no sensible owner
would give them. Sometimes the object, a bone, for example, gets
stuck and impedes the dog's ability to swallow or breathe. The
animal is likely to gag and retch, shake its head, paw at its mouth
or cough persistently. First restrain the dog, then try to remove
the obstruction by sticking your hand down the dog's throat. If
this proves unsuccessful, see a veterinarian without delay.
</P>
<P>
   If the dog (or cat) is choking and unable to cough because the
object was inhaled instead of swallowed and has totally obstructed
the windpipe, the Heimlich maneuver can save the animal's life.
Time is of the essence; by the time you reach a veterinarian, the
animal will be dead. If the dog is medium-sized or large _ say, 30
pounds or more _ Dr. Ann Hohenhaus, who heads the department of
medicine at the Animal Medical Center in New York, suggested the
same approach you would use on a person who is choking. Stand
behind the animal and wrap your arms around it, with your hands
just below the rib cage. Make a fist with one hand and wrap the
other hand over it. Then thrust up and forward sharply.
</P>
<P>
   If your pet is very small, the Heimlich maneuver for infants
would be more appropriate. With the animal lying on its side,
thrust upward with one fist placed just below the rib cage.
Hohenhaus said that one woman used this approach to rescue her cat,
who had inhaled instead of swallowing a pill and then was unable to
breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Another life-threatening emergency involves bloat, the buildup
of gas in the dog's stomach that, if severe, can compress the
animal's heart. Veterinary help must be obtained as soon as
possible. Owners should take care to avoid the problem by feeding
the dog small meals at regular intervals and keeping it from
strenuous exercise for at least two hours after the animal eats. If
for some reason the dog has not eaten for more than a day,
reintroduce food gradually, giving small amounts at a time and
allowing time in between for the animal to digest each serving.
</P>
<P>
   When falling bricks and a collapsed crane forced hundreds of
people to evacuate their homes in Manhattan last year, many ran
out, leaving the pets behind. Days passed before all the starving
animals could be rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to include your dog in any disaster preparations you
make for yourself and your family. Remember that your dog is
completely dependent on you for its survival in case of fire or a
weather-related crisis. Vaccinations should always be up to date
and the dog should always wear a collar with identification tags
indicating its name, your name and address and the vet's name and
address. You can also have an identification tattooed on the animal
or a microchip implanted under the dog's skin.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the American Red Cross' Family Disaster Plan
brochure. A copy is available at www.redcross.org/disaster on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Establish a surrogate caretaker for your pet should you become
incapacitated or unavoidably separated from the animal. Make sure
the dog is familiar with the surrogate and the area you are likely
to escape to in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Your pet is most likely to survive an emergency if it is
obedience-trained, responsive to commands and accustomed to being
transported in a crate. When a disaster strikes, crate the dog
immediately, before it tries to hide. Be sure to have with you any
medications the dog must take, as well as a list of what they are.
Finally, practice evacuating your home until you are sure you can
get your family and your dog out safely in a few minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
