<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH UPGRADES FOR RUNNING IN PLACE  
 WHEN SIBLINGS FIGHT, PARENTS SHRUG 
RELIGIOUS FAITH AND A PATIENT'S PROGNOSIS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.Y.)   (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the past decade, treadmills have exploded in popularity,
and technology has sped along at a clip. And if several new models
unveiled at last week's sporting goods extravaganza _ the Super
Show in Atlanta _ are any indication, treadmills may soon do
everything but the running.
</P>
<P>
   The ProForm CD Coach, for example, has a CD player built into
its console. The treadmill comes with an interactive CD that
contains two 30-minute workout programs designed by certified
personal trainers. Digital impulses from the CD soundtrack
automatically adjust the speed and incline of the treadmill to
coincide with the workout. The machine is available only at Sears,
Roebuck &AMP; Co. and sells for about $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another new model, the True 500, allows the user to change the
feel of the running surface. A manual dial on the side of the
treadmill includes 12 manually adjusted settings, ranging from
bouncy to firm.
</P>
<P>
   What purpose does this serve?
</P>
<P>
   ``Walkers tend to like a springier surface that's close to the
feel of wet sand while runners usually prefer a surface that's more
rigid, like hard packed dirt or asphalt,'' said Richard Cotton, the
chief exercise physiologist at the American Council on Exercise.
Prices start at $3,700.
</P>
<P>
   The Life Fitness 4500HR treadmill comes with a heart rate zone
training program designed to work much like the cruise-control
setting on a car: The treadmill automatically adjusts the speed and
hill incline to keep the user's heart beating at a steady rate.
Users must wear a heart rate monitor strapped to the chest or
abdomen to activate this feature. This model costs $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cotton says all this technology can be fun and
motivating, he cautions treadmill buyers to hold their enthusiasm
in check and look for a high-quality machine that is well
constructed and built to hold up through years of regular use.
</P>
<P>
   He recommends shopping at a reputable dealers who specialize in
exercise equipment, and he urges consumers to pay close attention
to warranty and repair service offered.
</P>
<P>
   _ LIZ NEPORENT
</P>
<P>
   Childhood
</P>
<P>
   Siblings are fighting as much as ever, but many parents are
letting them go at it, according to a new study that appears in the
current issue of the American Psychological Association's journal,
Developmental Psychology.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 88 two-parent, two-sibling households, with
children ages 3 to 9, the researchers asked the parents to describe
strategies they used to resolve sibling conflicts and which
strategies they felt confident using.
</P>
<P>
   ``If parents believe that a certain strategy is most effective,
they are less likely to use it unless they also feel comfortable
enacting it,'' said Dr. Laurie Kramer, an associate professor in
the Department of Human and Community Development at the University
of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, and co-author of the study with
the late Dr. Lisa Perozynski.
</P>
<P>
   Although most parents did not choose nonintervention as the best
strategy, observation showed that they used it three times as often
as strategies like helping their children communicate with each
other or asserting parental authority.
</P>
<P>
   The parents' sex also made a difference. When dealing with
shouting matches, when parents were confident in their abilities to
perform specific disciplinary techniques, mothers believed that
child-centered interventions, like helping their children talk with
each other, were more effective than other strategies and felt more
comfortable using them than fathers did.
</P>
<P>
   Fathers, on the other hand, said they were more comfortable with
parental control tactics and believed such tactics to be most
effective.
</P>
<P>
   When siblings pushed and kicked, mothers and fathers were both
more likely to endorse parental authority methods as the
appropriate intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still controversy in the advice given to parents as
to how to respond to their children's fighting,'' Dr. Kramer said.
``Parents' concerns about how to handle the conflict that occurs
between their children may be best addressed by helping parents to
identify the goals they have for their children's relationship and
helping them to formulate a plan for achieving their goals.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   Patterns
</P>
<P>
   A review of medical studies linking religious faith to an
improved prognosis for patients found little empirical support for
claims, according to an article in the current issue of the medical
journal Lancet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the best studies, the evidence of an association
between religion, spirituality and health is weak and
inconsistent,'' concluded Dr. Richard Sloan, director of behavioral
medicine at Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center in New York. ``We
believe therefore that it is premature to promote faith and
religion as adjunctive medical treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan and his colleagues spent more than a year looking at
methodology used in hundreds of published studies that examined
religion and the physical outcomes of disease.
</P>
<P>
   The review excluded studies involving mental health outcomes and
health behaviors like smoking or drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The one consistency they found was the inconsistency of
methodology and findings even among well-conducted studies. ``The
findings were all over the place,'' Sloan said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Applying standards of medical scientific reliability and
statistical soundness, researchers faulted murky definitions of
religious activity, failure to control for variations like sex and
education and inappropriate statistical methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some degree, lack of consistency is characteristic of an
evolving field and may be the product of differences in study
design, definitions of religious and spiritual variables and
outcome variables,'' the researchers found.
</P>
<P>
   Because of these inconsistencies as well as ethical questions,
Sloan, a psychologist, concluded that health professionals should
not ``intrude'' in the area of religious beliefs and practices.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he said, there is a danger that failure of
religious activity to produce a cure could lead to guilt feelings
in a patient.
</P>
<P>
   _ NANCY BETH JACKSON
</P>
</TEXT>
