<HEADLINE>
WILD STOCK PRICES PROVE CHALLENGING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's volatile investment markets have a way of turning what
looks like a triumphant moment into a financial Waterloo.
</P>
<P>
   Take the example of Golden Books Family Entertainment, a
children's book publisher.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare occurrence last week, the stock of the New York
company had the dubious distinctions of being the biggest
percentage gainer and the biggest percentage loser _ all in one
day, and all within a period of about two hours _ because of
Internet stock fever.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who didn't catch the stock at the right price would
have found themselves paying more for the stock than they wanted or
selling it for less than they had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Buying and selling at exactly the price you want can prove
impossible when stock prices are gyrating wildly.
</P>
<P>
   ``During a fast market, orders are submitted to market makers
and specialists at such a rapid pace, there's likely to be a
backlog that can create significant delays, sometimes exceeding 30
minutes,'' Charles Schwab, chairman of Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., told
customers in a recent report on trading in fast markets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TAKE STEPS TO REDUCE RISK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While you can't control the pace of markets, you can take some
steps to help reduce your risk.
</P>
<P>
   The first is to buy stable, large capitalization stocks whose
prices don't dance around.
</P>
<P>
   But if you love the thrill of buying and selling in a
fast-moving market, place a ``limit order'' instead of a ``market
order.''
</P>
<P>
   A market order is an order to buy or sell a stock at the best
available price. Market orders are executed on a first-come,
first-served basis.
</P>
<P>
   In rapidly moving markets, in the short time between when your
market order is placed and when it's executed, orders in line ahead
of yours can significantly shift a stock's price.
</P>
<P>
   By placing a limit order, you set the highest possible price
you're willing to pay for a stock or the lowest price at which
you're willing to sell a stock.
</P>
<P>
   If a stock is rising, your limit order may not be filled because
sellers hold out for the highest possible price, said James Angel,
associate professor of finance at Georgetown University in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a serious investor, investing for the long term,
the best way is to put in a limit order,'' said Frank Lallos,
senior analyst at Gomez Advisors in Concord, Mass., consultants to
online brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   Before deciding whether to place a market order or limit order
for a stock buy, determine how soon a stock's price will rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, if you think that the stock is about to make a
major move, then you are better off getting the immediate execution
of a market order, rather than running the risk that your order may
not be filled and the stock may run away from you,'' Angel said.
</P>
<P>
   Set a limit order that allows for little less than perfect
execution so you don't waste your time placing orders that don't
get filled all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't pay to get really greedy with limit orders,'' Angel
said. ``If you really want to buy this stock, put in a limit order
pretty close to the current bid price because if you bid too low,
the chances of your getting your order filled fall dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   The bid price is the price at which you're prepared to buy a
stock.
</P>
<P>
   The asked price is the price at which the owner of a stock
offers to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have to execute the trade immediately, consider
placing a limit order at the bid price or even lower for a stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're doing is saying, `I can be patient because at some
time during the day, its natural volatility will take it through
the (price) level,''' Angel said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ONLINE TRADING DELIVERS QUICKLY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're trading online, market orders aren't as risky because
execution is quicker, Angel said. Still, lightning-speed markets
can throw that off.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to find out which online brokers best execute trade
orders, go to Gomez Advisors' Web site at www.gomez.com and click
on ``Internet Broker Scorecard.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, click on ``Select A Category'' and ``Customer
Confidence'' and you'll see how Gomez ranks online brokerages in
such areas as phone response time and the quality of the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better the Customer Confidence ranking, the more likely
they are to have a high level of execution,'' Lallos said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is justice.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the stock of Golden Books was taken off the Nasdaq
Stock Market because the financially troubled publisher's stock
price had fallen so low. It's also negotiating a bankruptcy
reorganization plan with its creditors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
