<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4858 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX     02-22 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD-BITTEN AND CYNICAL? ONLY SOME OF US
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL HARRAL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newspaper executives, alarmed at surveys showing a dropping
level of credibility for their papers, commissioned an extensive
examination of this issue in 1998 under the auspices of the
American Society of Newspaper Editors.
</P>
<P>
   We've been working our way through that study in this column,
and today we'll consider what it called Major Finding No. 2: ``The
public perceives that newspapers don't consistently demonstrate
respect for, and knowledge of, their readers and their
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Urban &AMP; Associates Inc. did the study for the ASNE, using a
national stratified random telephone survey of 3,000 interviews, 16
focus groups and a random, stratified sample of 1,714 journalists
at American newspapers with daily circulation of 5,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   For years, journalists themselves and television and movie
producers have worked hard to establish a sort of persona of the
typical reporter or editor. Some of these were kind. More often,
they were portrayed as hard-bitten, cynical, hard-drinking and
aggressive people.
</P>
<P>
   My mother wanted me to be a preacher. When I told her I was
going to be a journalist, she was mortified _ picturing, I'm sure,
a guy in a trench coat with a pint of whiskey stuck in his hip
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   It's an image that has been around for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   A popular book among wire service journalists is ``Kansas City
Milkman,'' an out-of-print spoof of the old United Press. In it,
the central character at one point tells friends that if they ever
see his mother, they're not to tell her he's a journalist. They are
to tell her that he plays piano in a house of ill repute.
</P>
<P>
   We've been wildly successful in establishing that persona,
according to the results of the study. People think that
journalists are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Motivated _ 78 percent think journalists pay more attention to
what their editors want than what readers want.
</P>
<P>
   _ Smart _ 75 percent think journalists are better informed than
average Americans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cynical _ 67 percent think journalists are more cynical than
other professionals, ``although most agree that they share the same
kinds of ethical and personal values as most Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Hard-bitten _ only 28 percent believe that journalists would
tone down a story that could hurt the lives of the people they are
writing about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether these are professional virtues or vices, then, this
persona is a prevailing operational profile in how the public views
journalists, and 53 percent believe the press is out of touch with
mainstream Americans,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the Fort Worth Star-Telegram puts millions of dollars
back into the communities it covers through direct sponsorships,
promotional assistance and advertising, special sections and other
forms of community involvement.
</P>
<P>
   We publish highly customized editions for the three major
divisions of our county so that we can emphasize local and
community news, and we do it in the most expensive way possible:
delegating decision-making to almost completely autonomous editors
in separate newsrooms located in the geographic areas we are
covering.
</P>
<P>
   We print ``Hometown Stars'' in some communities to cover even
more highly local news that cannot be fitted into the main
newspaper, and we have Sports Zone sections that take coverage of
high school athletics to levels that none of us have seen before.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen reporters writing stories with tears in their eyes.
I've met with staff members so disturbed by the scenes they had
witnessed at tragedies that they wondered whether they could remain
in the profession.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not the perception. In one focus group, a woman told
the researchers: ``You wouldn't be a good reporter if you were a
nice person.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other disconnects _ educational and economic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of the U.S. population lives in households with total
incomes of below $47,000 per year (54 percent of them achieving
that income level with two or more full-time workers). Only 34
percent of U.S. adults are college graduates _ 39 percent never
went beyond high school,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the study suggested that when ``the public
perceives a bias toward wealthy people, then it's not inconceivable
to believe that many suspect that individual journalists make a
salary more substantial than their own.''
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting about that statement to me is that I've
always thought there might be a bias ``against'' wealthy people,
not in favor of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When newspaper readers see feature articles about ways to make
an elegant presentation of artichoke hearts, many study the
photograph to find out what, exactly, an artichoke looks like,''
the study said. ``When adjectives like church-going or right-wing
or suburban or radical appear in print or broadcast news stories,
they sense that judgments are being made by folks not very much
like themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But we are mothers and fathers and sons and daughters. Some of
us are very religious, and some are not. Some keep their desks tidy
(well, actually very few), and some do not.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of us coach youth teams or work in PTAs or serve in Boy
Scout or Girl Scout troops and volunteer at other not-for-profit
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   And some of us are cynical and hard-bitten.
</P>
<P>
   What we are not very good about is telling our own story _ who
we are and what we do. Some of that is self-defense, I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   But assuming that the ASNE study is accurate, we're going to
need to get a lot less defensive and much better at letting you see
who we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's specious to dismiss these criticisms by assuming that the
public is being sloppy in their judgment by lumping the media
together with ... other large or powerful institutions, or to
assume that the public tars newspapers with the same brush they use
on supermarket tabloids,'' the study said. ``They know the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is reader advocate for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. His e-mail address is harral(at)star-telegram.com.
You may telephone him at (817) 390-7692 or write him at P.O. Box
1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
