<HEADLINE>
COURT EXAMINES TEXAS JURY'S DECISION TO IMPOSE DEATH PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a case that could affect death row inmates
around the country, the Supreme Court on Monday weighed whether
jurors in a Texas murder case were so confused by the judge's
instructions that they mistakenly opted to sentence a man to death.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a U.S. District Court jury in Lubbock, Texas, found
Louis Jones Jr. guilty of kidnapping Air Force Pvt. Tracie Joy
McBride, 19, from a laundry room on the Goodfellow Air Force Base
in San Angelo, beating her over the head with a tire iron and
leaving her dead body under a bridge on the night of Feb. 19, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After the jurors found him guilty, Judge Sam R. Cummings read
them the 1994 federal death penalty sentencing law. He said that if
they did not come to a unanimous decision for capital punishment or
life in prison without the possibility of parole, ``the court shall
impose any lesser sentence that is authorized by law.''
</P>
<P>
   After deliberating for nearly two weeks, the jury sentenced
Jones to death.
</P>
<P>
   Jones appealed, arguing that some jurors were confused by the
judge's instructions and by four verdict forms that he gave them.
It was possible that some jurors who favored life in prison without
parole feared that if the jury failed to reach a unanimous
decision, he would receive a lesser sentence, such as life in
prison with the possibility of parole. So these jurors opted for
the death penalty to make sure Jones received a tough sentence, the
appeal said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones contended that the jury should have been told that in his
case, there was no lesser penalty than life in prison without
parole.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the U.S. 5th Circuit Court of Appeals rejected Jones'
argument, saying that the judge's failure to give clarifying
instructions had no legal effect on the jury's recommendation for
death.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the appeals court gave little weight to
affidavits from two jurors saying they would have spared Jones'
life had the judge said life in prison without parole was the only
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's decision in the case, which is expected by
July, could open the door to appeal for many of the 20 inmates now
on death rows who were sentenced under the Federal Death Penalty
Act of 1994. It could also affect dozens of defendants awaiting
trial under the law.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing before the high court, Jones' lawyer, Timothy Crooks of
Fort Worth, Texas, urged the justices to give his client a new
sentencing trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these instructions, jurors who don't want the death
penalty will believe that if they don't cave in, the defendant
might get off with a lighter sentence that he didn't deserve,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Antonin Scalia told Crooks, ``I don't understand why
you think it would be the people favoring life in prison without
parole who cave in. It seems to me that the people favoring the
death penalty have more to lose, so to speak, because if they don't
give in, not only is this guy going to avoid the death penalty,
he's going to have the chance to get out of prison someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department attorney Michael Dreeben, arguing against
Jones, said the jury was not instructed to consider what might
happen if it could not reach a unanimous decision. Therefore, he
contended, each juror should have considered only the two options
of death or life in prison without parole and should not have given
any thought to the consequences of a hung jury.
</P>
<P>
   However, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg questioned whether Dreeben
was being realistic. ``It would difficult for these jurors not to
completely disregard what happens if they can't come to
agreement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
