<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MEDICAL-HOTELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOVERING AFTER SURGERY, WITH ALL THE AMENITIES
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By ANDREE BROOKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I recently scheduled a long-overdue operation that could have
been readily carried out in a doctor's office or in a hospital on
an outpatient basis. It was nothing serious, but even so, my
elderly mother begged me not to rush home because I lived alone.
Instead, she urged me to remain in the hospital overnight, in case
I needed attention.
</P>
<P>
   It's not possible, I argued, explaining with a hint of cynicism
that procedures have become so sophisticated and coverage so
restrictive that, in all but the most serious cases, patients are
supposed to climb right off the operating table and march out the
door. Try anyway, she admonished, ``just so I won't sit here
worrying.''
</P>
<P>
   It prompted me to ask the surgeon about options. In turn, he
introduced me to the expanding world of medical hotels and
postoperative recovery centers _ facilities used by patients who
would otherwise have to travel a long distance, who do not have a
caregiver at home or who are well-to-do and prefer the comfort and
convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Louis F. Reuter 4th, the executive vice president at New York
Presbyterian Hospital, which is considering a hotel at its
Washington Heights complex, said these kinds of centers were
proliferating to meet the changing patterns of health care.
</P>
<P>
   Although outpatient surgery has become more common, some
patients still ``prefer to recover in the hospital milieu,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the specialization of hospitals means that patients may
come from far away, sometimes accompanied by family members who
also need somewhere to stay. Centers like the Inn at Mayo Clinic in
Jacksonville, Fla., operated by Marriott International, offer
mini-apartments for $89 to $109 a night for longer-term stays.
These are useful to patients having extensive tests or are too weak
to travel after chemotherapy or bone marrow transplants. And, such
centers cater to family members, normally charging only a nominal
fee, about $25 a night, for added guests and assuring that extra
beds are available.
</P>
<P>
   Some private physicians, particularly in those in cosmetic
surgery, have picked up on the trend. Two years ago, for example,
Dr. William Beeson, president of the American Academy of Cosmetic
Surgery, built four luxury recovery suites at his surgical offices
in Carmel, Ind. He offers his patients _ most of whom are business
executives recovering from face lifts, nose jobs and hair
transplants _ all-night physician and nursing care. ``We can better
control pain and there's less worry,'' he said. Beeson, who
includes one night's stay in the cost of surgery, estimated that an
overnight stay in such a center would cost $300 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is the social benefit: ``You don't want your
doorman finding out you just had a face lift,'' said Dr. James R.
Lyons, a plastic surgeon in Hamden, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance generally does not cover the entire cost of staying in
a recovery center, though many patients qualify for partial
reimbursement, depending on their carrier and the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Some centers provide nursing; others do not. Among those that do
not include medical care, the range of luxury is almost as broad as
the hotel industry itself. Multipurpose recovery centers like the
62-room Tower Inn, run by Methodist Hospital in Indianapolis, can
cost as little as $50 night. Most are within a block or so of the
hospital or surgical unit and patients can bring their own nurses
or caregivers, if needed. The hourly cost for those nurses may also
be covered by insurance, especially if nursing care would have been
provided at home, hospital administrators said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonmedical centers offer amenities like wide hallways and doors
for easy wheelchair access, shower stools in each bathroom, medical
waste disposals in each room and large easy chairs for daytime
lounging.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, New York University-Cornell Medical Center's
midtown hospital complex offers the the 96-suite Helmsley Medical
Tower and Residence, connected by underground walkway. The cost
ranges from $160 to $210 a night. Mount Sinai-New York University
Medical Center opened its 17-room Mount Sinai Guest Residence two
years ago by redesigning two floors of its staff residential
building. Nightly charges are $145 to $195. Both are expanding
because of heavy demand. Neither includes nursing.
</P>
<P>
   But the one I chose did. I stayed at the Temple Recovery Care
Center, a specially designed floor of the New Haven Hotel in
downtown New Haven and near St. Raphael's hospital, where I was
having surgery. The center, with 20 beds, has Colonial-style
private rooms with equipment like electric beds and services like
bedside meal delivery.
</P>
<P>
   A hotel driver picked me up in a van after surgery. I did not
even have to get dressed. He returned me to the surgeon's office
the next morning for the removal of bandages, after which I really
was ready to go home.
</P>
<P>
   The room was so cozy and the care so special that I was tempted
to stay longer, were it not for the $483 per night out-of-pocket
expense. A nurse was at my bedside within in a minute of two of my
call, eager to fix bandages, order a meal, check my vital signs or
refill my jug of ice water and even get me to the doctor's office
on time.
</P>
<P>
   I enjoyed the pampering and felt secure knowing a doctor or
nurse was at hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
