<SLUG> BC-CALIF-WILSON-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR WILL NOT SEEK PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ending months of speculation about his political
future, former Gov. Pete Wilson of California announced Monday that
he would not seek the Republican presidential nomination next year
because he had concluded that he could not raise the $15 million to
$20 million it would take to wage a credible campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reluctantly, I'm compelled to conclude that it is just not
practical to pursue a candidacy,'' Wilson wrote in a four-page
letter to supporters released Monday, adding: ``I won't pretend
that I don't feel genuine disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, 65, was forced from office by term limits last month,
and he had said he would spend several weeks telephoning potential
fund raisers and supporters around the nation to assess his
presidential prospects. But one former aide said Monday that, in
the end, Wilson had made hardly any calls and had concluded on his
own that he simply could not raise enough money to compete with the
likes of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and the magazine publisher
Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson faced formidable obstacles, including lingering bad blood
among some California Republicans who thought he had hurt the party
with his outspoken stands against illegal immigration and
affirmative action. Last month, a majority of the California
Legislature's Republican caucus wrote a letter to Bush, asking him
to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've waited too long,'' Wilson told George Skelton, a
political columnist for The Los Angeles Times, who first published
news of Wilson's decision in Monday's editions. Wilson said he had
spent the last two years consolidating his efforts as governor in
the face of the state's economic rebound, ``because it's what I
wanted to do,'' and added: ``If you're going to govern California
it's a full-time job. But now it's too late to raise that kind of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson flirted with the presidency four years ago, but his
campaign collapsed for lack of money and support after throat
surgery left him unable to speak for three months. By starting that
campaign, he broke the pledge he made in his 1994 re-election not
to seek the White House, and supporters said Monday that his
current prospects had been badly hurt by that aborted effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question,'' said Dan Schnur, a former senior aide.
``If he had not run in 1995, he'd be viewed now not just as a
candidate but as one of the party's strongest. That's the kind of
toll a campaign like that can take.''
</P>
<P>
   Schnur said some people wanted Wilson to give the race another
shot. ``There was a strong argument,'' he said, ``to running a $5
million to $7 million live-off-the-land kind of campaign, hope you
finish first in Iowa and New Hampshire and then blow that into
California and New York.'' But in the end, Schnur said, ``He just
decided he was better positioned to influence the debate at both
the state and national levels as an elder statesman than as one of
a pack of candidates hoping to break through.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has formed a nonprofit group, the Bear Flag Forum, to
work on behalf of issues he supports. He plans to form a political
action committee to support Republican candidates, and he has
accepted a post as a visiting fellow at the Hoover Institution, a
conservative think tank at Stanford University. He also plans to
write a book.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's spokesman, Sean Walsh, said the former governor was
visiting his father in Ohio Monday and would not be available for
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to supporters, Wilson said: ``Don't expect me to
go quietly into the night. I'm not going to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
