<SLUG> BC-SCI-LICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS LICE RESIST TREATMENT, THE BATTLE ESCALATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By SUSAN GILBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting rid of head lice used to be a straightforward affair. An
insecticidal shampoo or rinse was slathered on the hair at night,
and the lice were gone the next morning. But that has changed in
the last few years, with the pest that is scientifically known as
Pediculus humanus capitis showing resistance to standard remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, children are missing days, even weeks, of school because
they cannot get rid of head lice. ``I know of kids who've been left
back because they missed two months of school,'' said Terri Lynn
Meinking, an assistant professor of dermatology at the University
of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard J. Pollack, an entomologist at the Harvard School of
Public Health, studied head lice resistance to permethrin, the
active ingredient in some over-the-counter products. Because the
study has just been accepted for publication in a medical journal,
he would not comment on the research. But he and other researchers
did say that there have been thousands of anecdotal reports of
resistance to permethrin and pyrethrum, a similar ingredient in
other lice treatments. And studies in Europe and Israel have
documented resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Parents doing battle with bugs often get conflicting advice, and
the Internet abounds with entrepreneurs selling unproven herbal
lice treatments, said Deborah Z. Altchuler, president of the
National Pediculosis Association, a nonprofit education
organization. And the pediculosis group itself has been criticized
by consumers and manufacturers for bias against de-licing products
other than Lice Meister, the lice comb that it sells.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the missed days of school and work, to say nothing of
the discomfort of a lice infestation, reports of treatment failures
have led to another problem. More doctors are prescribing lindane
shampoo, an old remedy whose overuse can cause neurological damage
in children, Ms. Meinking said. Because of this risk, the Food and
Drug Administration recommends that lindane be prescribed only for
people who cannot use other approved therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated with or frightened by the standard therapies, many
parents are turning to home remedies, such as petroleum jelly,
olive oil and mayonnaise, in hopes that these substances, when
applied to the scalp, smother the lice.
</P>
<P>
   But when Ms. Meinking tested these preparations in a small study
last year at Key Largo Elementary School in Florida, she found that
none killed all the lice on the children's heads. The most
effective alternative remedy that she used was HairClear 1-2-3,
which contains anise oil, ylang-ylang oil and coconut oil in
rubbing alcohol. But even that product did not kill all the lice
with one application, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meinking said that in all cases she had to comb through the
children's hair to get rid of the eggs, or nits. She said that the
Lice Meister comb was the easiest to use and the most effective,
adding that an advantage of using HairClear or olive oil was that
they loosened the nits, making it easier to comb them out.
Petroleum jelly, on the other hand, ``was more trouble than it's
worth because it makes the nits hard to see and remove,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there is some evidence that new treatments get rid
of the lice without laborious combing or harmful side effects. Dr.
Lawrence Schachner, a spokesman for the American Academy of
Dermatology, said that many doctors get good results with
ivermectin, an oral drug approved in this country for treating
intestinal parasites. ``More and more of the cutting-edge doctors
are prescribing it,'' he said. Side effects, which are rare,
include dizziness or low blood pressure, Schachner said.
</P>
<P>
   Another promising treatment is trimethoprim sulfanethoxazole, an
oral antibiotic that kills bacteria in the lice's gut that are
necessary for their survival, Schachner said. And Ms. Meinking said
that she has been involved in testing new herbal and insecticidal
products. Though she said she could not yet discuss the
preparations or their makers, she described some of the treatments
as ``exciting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
