<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Feb. 23, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A narrow swath of moderate snow will blanket parts of the Middle
West on Tuesday as a weakening low-pressure system and a trailing
jet stream disturbance cut across the middle Mississippi and lower
Ohio River Valleys. Snow, from 2 to 4 inches, is possible from
eastern Missouri to southern Illinois, southern Indiana and
southwest Kentucky. Broken areas of sleet and possibly snow are
possible farther south in parts of Tennessee, northern Mississippi
and northern Alabama, where the air is further cooled as some of
the precipitation evaporates into the initially dry air.
</P>
<P>
   Showers of rain, with isolated peals of thunder, will develop
within a few hundred miles of the Gulf Coast across parts of
Louisiana, Mississippi and Alabama. With humidity levels over the
northern Gulf of Mexico relatively low, the risk of heavy rain will
be practically nil.
</P>
<P>
   North of the low-pressure system, broken areas of generally
light snow will fall across the southern Great Lakes region as far
north as Chicago and Milwaukee, but accumulations, where they
occur, will generally be light.
</P>
<P>
   Rain and wind will intensify Tuesday night in the Pacific
Northwest as a potent jet stream disturbance approaches from the
Pacific. Increasing winds from the southwest will build to 25 to 50
mph along the Oregon and Washington Coasts by Wednesday morning,
with gusts to 60 mph or more possible over exposed beaches. Rain
will become heavy Tuesday night in western Washington and western
Oregon, with rainfalls of 2 inches or more on west-facing slopes of
the Coastal Range.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Bay-effect Snow
</P>
<P>
   The Great Lakes do not own a monopoly on lake-effect snow. Early
Monday, ``bay-effect'' snow fell at Norfolk along the southeast
coast of Virginia as Arctic air was moistened in transit over the
comparatively tepid waters of Chesapeake Bay. Because of the
narrowness of Chesapeake Bay, only a narrow range of wind
directions typically produce bay-effect snow at Norfolk. Indeed,
Arctic winds must blow from the north or north-northeast, a small
window in wind direction that maximizes the distance and time that
Arctic air spends over the moistening waters of Chesapeake Bay. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
