<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-RACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH EDUCATION CHOICES AWAIT DISTRICT IN DISARRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Californians spent $300 million over 15 years to
buy computers, news classrooms and hire teachers to help
desegregate schools in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But the money failed its first and most fundamental goal:
getting black children to do well in school.
</P>
<P>
   The failure is undeniable. The districtwide grade point average
for black high school students was 1.81 in spring 1998. While
blacks are 16.6 percent of the district's 62,000 students, they
represent half of all students suspended and just 1.28 percent of
those who take advanced placement exams.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP, which has made its name fighting segregation,
acknowledges the limits of court-ordered integration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you do things such as train teachers to deal with a
class of students from different cultures, integration by
assignment alone is superficial,'' said Michael Harris, a lawyer
for the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1983, the schools have been governed by a federal consent
decree requiring them to enroll students through a rigid racial
formula: No more than 45 percent of students at any school could be
of one race and at least four ethnic groups had to be represented
at each school.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, to settle a lawsuit brought by Chinese-American
families kept out of elite public schools because of quotas, the
district agreed to stop using race in admissions. Now the district
must craft a new enrollment policy.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Bill Rojas said Schools have to play a balancing
act, giving certain children what they need to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race alone is not sufficient, and race alone is not allowable
in determining admissions,'' he said. ``So we must now set up
alternative plans that use more than race but still lead us to a
desegregated system.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has a long and tumultuous history of trying to
integrate schools. Busing began in 1971, following a lawsuit filed
by the NAACP. But the level of integration varied from school to
school, prompting the NAACP to push for the 1983 federal
desegregation order.
</P>
<P>
   But the promise of desegregation is dimmed by disparities in the
quality of schools and the persistently low performance of black
students.
</P>
<P>
   The district has also failed to accomplish key goals of the
court order, ranging from hiring more minority teachers _ 17.7
percent of the district's 2,350 teachers are minorities _ to
reducing suspensions of black students.
</P>
<P>
   And while the desegregation order has achieved integration in
schools, it has failed to keep classrooms from becoming segregated.
</P>
<P>
   An independent review of the district last July found that
``within-school segregation in San Francisco today is an issue of
monumental importance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the money, despite all the efforts of integration
over 15 years, what I want to know is why hasn't there been a
perceivable increase in test scores for those who were supposed to
be helped?'' said John Yoo, professor of law at the University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key question that must be asked is, `Has integration, to
the extent it occurred, helped students become better students?'''
</P>
<P>
   Test score data and grade point averages by ethnicity are not
available before 1983 because the district did not track such
scores before the court order. But educators say it is hard to
imagine scores of black students being much lower than they are
today.
</P>
<P>
   While the average grade point average for black high school
students in the city is 1.81, the average GPA is 2.84 for
Chinese-Americans, 2.51 for whites and 1.98 for Hispanics. Grade
point averages above 4.0 are possible if students take
advanced-placement courses, which assign 5.0 grades for an A.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement reached last week requires the district to draft
by October a new admissions formula that is blind to race.
</P>
<P>
   The district is considering redrawing boundaries around schools
to draw children from ethnically diverse neighborhoods, or giving
preferences to children who face personal and economic hardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did research looking at what would happen if you went from
a race-based policy to a policy based on socioeconomics,'' state
Superintendent of Public Instruction Delaine Eastin said. The
results were similar, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, she added, policies based on
socioeconomics ``are perceived to be fairer _ and won't stir
resentment.''
</P>
<P>
   If San Francisco is able to integrate schools successfully by
using such factors as whether a child resides in public housing,
there is ``a lesson for the whole country,'' said Gary Orfield, a
Harvard University professor and specialist on school
desegregation. ``This will be harder for them to implement than the
desegregation order,'' he said, but could provide a valuable
national model for how to achieve affirmative action without
considering race.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco has to figure out what to do when there is no
other model _ and do it with great urgency,'' Orfield said. ``The
question is not so much how they will do it, but can San Francisco
do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
