<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4882 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     02-22 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV24-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THRILL OF BEING DULL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday Feb. 24)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There nothing like getting together with a group of people with
whom you have something in common, which is why I'm thinking of
joining the Dull Men's Club.
</P>
<P>
   Administered by the National Council of Dull Men located,
appropriately enough, in Washington, D.C., the Dull Men's Club is
the place for guys whose idea of a good time is watching the
airport baggage carousel go 'round and 'round and who ride the
elevator for hours at a time so they can listen to the music.
</P>
<P>
   Dull men spend a lot of their time alone in a room staring at a
computer screen, like I am doing right now. So it stands to reason
that dull men would have their own dull Web site,
http://www.dullmen.com/
</P>
<P>
   (The Dull Men's Club is not to be confused with the Boring
Institute or the National Association of Wheat Growers, although
there are some obvious similarities.)
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't sure if I had what it takes (or lacks) to be a member
of the Dull Men's Club, so I took the test. Although I was stumped
by the first question ``Name the three most exciting things you
have ever done,'' I think I did OK on the others:
</P>
<P>
   - Do you prefer luggage carousels that go clockwise,
counterclockwise, or are you undecided? (Undecided.)
</P>
<P>
   - Do you like airplane food? (I can't remember having anything
more elaborate than peanuts in the last 10 years, but they were
delicious.)
</P>
<P>
   - Do you like English food? (Any national cuisine that includes
such items as bangers and mash and toad in the hole is fine with
me, especially reheated.)
</P>
<P>
   - Do you like Vegemite? (That depends. Is that a food or a brand
of housepaint?)
</P>
<P>
   - Do you like macaroni? (I'd shoot it straight into my vein if I
weren't afraid of needles.)
</P>
<P>
   - Do you think women should be allowed in the club? Why not? (I
have not met a woman yet who appreciates the subtle pleasures of
watching wood warp, and many have trouble accepting Spam as a
vegetable.)
</P>
<P>
   - Does your wife think you are dull? (Does the sound of corn
growing make me giddy? She doesn't call me Mr. Excitement for
nothing.)
</P>
<P>
   - Have you ever had an urge? How did you get over it? (I once
had an urge to watch some airport baggage carousels go 'round and
'round but I overcame it with lots of bed rest.)
</P>
<P>
   - What is your favorite shade of gray? (Pale.)
</P>
<P>
   Now that the impeachment trial is over, many dull men are
wondering how they will fill those long empty hours. Watching the
Weather Channel is one possibility, though the sight of approaching
cold fronts may be too exciting for men who have spent the past
several weeks absorbing the wit and wisdom of Henry Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there are several events remaining in the month of
February to help dull men wean themselves from the wacky
shenanigans of Chief Justice Rehnquist and reaccustom themselves to
everyday dull life.
</P>
<P>
   For example, February is Return Shopping Carts to Supermarkets
Month, an event you may have overlooked while you were busy folding
your socks. While I, personally, do not have any shopping carts
that need returning, I'm thinking of stealing one and immediately
returning it just so I can participate in this event and feel that
I made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   February is also National Winter Bird Feeding Month, though if
you haven't thought of feeding your winter birds before now, it's
probably too late. The National Council of Dull Men does not
explain why feeding winter birds is duller than feeding summer
birds, though I think it's safe to say anyone who would pose such a
question is deserving of membership.
</P>
<P>
   After you have finished disposing of the dead winter birds
littering your yard, you may want to take advantage of the fact
that February is National Embroidery Month.
</P>
<P>
   Some guys like to do embroidery while listening to corn grow,
but that strikes me as a trifle too adventurous.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
