<HEADER>
A4890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHIU-PIANO-REVIEW-NYT     02-22 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIU-PIANO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY ROMANTIC WITH A SALON AMBIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before beginning his recital on Sunday afternoon at
the Frick Collection, the pianist Frederic Chiu told his audience
that he was greatly relieved not to be playing, for once, in some
generic concert hall before an audience of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   He has made a specialty of the early Romantic piano repertory,
and the Frick's intimate, oval music room struck him as similar in
ambiance to the Parisian salons where the works on his program by
Mendelssohn, Liszt and Chopin would have been played, often by the
composers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Chiu has absorbed the atmosphere of Parisian salons firsthand:
though born to Chinese immigrants and raised in the United States,
he now lives in France. Through his chatty remarks to the audience
(in which he pretended to be a gracious host at a fabled salon) and
his informal attire, the young ponytailed pianist further evoked
the mood he was after.
</P>
<P>
   He began his program dashingly, with Mendelssohn's Introduction
and Rondo Capriccioso. Following this were transcriptions by Liszt
of four songs from Schubert's ``Schwanengesang,'' fascinating
works, more like transformations of the songs than mere
transcriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Even the sprightly ones are pianistically formidable. In
``Abschied,'' for example, the evocation of the vocal line is
situated where it belongs, in the piano's tenor range, with the
leaping, chordal accompaniment figurations surrounding it above and
below. There were also accounts of Chopin's gripping Ballade in G
minor and the whimsical, seldom-heard Rondo in E flat.
</P>
<P>
   Chiu has a palpable connection to this music and an idiomatic
feeling for the style. Yet he brings his own touches to it,
including a spare use of pedal and an interesting penchant for
slightly dry, articulate textures. His technique is resourceful and
often impressive, as his traversal of Chopin's daunting 12 Etudes
(Op. 10) in a neat 30 minutes during the program's second half made
clear.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he often seemed to be pushing at the limits of his
technique, which accounted for some uncertainty, dropped notes and
glossed-over passagework. He may have been struggling with the
Frick's Yamaha concert grand piano, an instrument with a very
bright top range, which, given the room's reverberant acoustics,
cannot be easy to control.
</P>
<P>
   Chiu was at his best and most musical in the works that did not
tax his pianism, especially Chopin's Four Mazurkas (Op. 24), played
with lilting grace, a vivid ear for nuance, and intimacy. For a
moment, we might have been in the candle-lit salon of a Parisian
duchess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1750EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
