<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4893 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANSKY-MOVIE-NYT &LR;      02-22 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANSKY-MOVIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: COME BACK, LITTLE CAESAR, TO SHOW THEM HOW IT'S
DONE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What made Meyer Lansky run? ``Lansky,'' David Mamet's dreamy
version of the life and tribulations of the Jewish brain behind the
Italian muscle that once controlled bootlegging, gambling and
associated diversions and gave us Las Vegas in all its glory and
squalor, suggests that Lansky's character somehow was developed by
watching a pogrom as a lad in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   But Mamet doesn't seem particularly persuaded of that dubious
and derivative proposition or with much else that might explain the
Lansky genius or his line of work. What these two hours, to be seen
on HBO on Feb. 27, provide instead is a reflective essay, dotted
with Mametisms, of an aged and ailing man at the end of his tether.
</P>
<P>
   In putting his trust in so sedentary a figure as Lansky, Mamet
was bucking the proven conventions of the crime drama, a risky
endeavor. This playwright's hope seems to have been to challenge
the cartoon nature of Mafia movies, to invest his subject with an
offbeat originality, with an air of poignancy and inklings of
social significance. As the poker player in Mamet must have known,
the odds were against him. His ambition collided with the crime
formula at its strongest point.
</P>
<P>
   Mamet's problem in turning Lansky into the sort of gangster who
provides a writer with the stuff that fans of the form have come to
cherish is built into the man's image. No creature of the
underworld comes closer to the evocative description by the movie
critic Robert Warshow in his rewarding 1948 rumination on the great
gangster movies of the 1930s and 40s, yet is further removed from
it.
</P>
<P>
   Warshow wrote: ``The gangster's activity is actually a form of
rational enterprise, involving fairly definite goals and various
techniques for achieving them. But this rationality is usually no
more than a vague background; we know, perhaps, that the gangster
sells liquor or that he operates a numbers racket; often we are not
given even that much information. So his activity becomes a kind of
pure criminality; he hurts people. Certainly our response to the
gangster film is most consistently and most universally a response
to sadism; we gain the double satisfaction of participating
vicariously in the gangster's sadism and then seeing it turned
against the gangster himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lansky, the vaunted mastermind operating the strings for some
grand criminal enterprise, lacks the jolt of sadism offered by the
characters memorialized by Edward G. Robinson, Paul Muni and many
of the later Goodfellas. Once Mamet gets past his hero's youthful
high jinks, the inherent violence surrounding the man's calling is
mainly consigned to surrogates. He himself is as peaceable as any
conventional accountant; he is as likely to be caught carrying an
adding machine as a machine gun.
</P>
<P>
   That makes things tough for the crime writer. It's like trying
to keep ``The Godfather'' crackling without its big, smartly staged
scenes of mayhem. In models like ``Scarface'' and ``Little
Caesar,'' Warshow noted, the criminal's temporary success assures
his ultimate destruction; somebody is always out to kill him and
the movie succeeds along with the assassin.
</P>
<P>
   But Lansky the bureaucrat falls victim not to bullets but merely
to the paperwork of other bureaucrats. There are no shootouts to
help the dramatist along, and although the screenplay may be more
realistic than bloodier crime chronicles, it is wan as drama.
</P>
<P>
   Starting from the grave of his grandfather in Jerusalem (a few
lines of Yiddish, a Jewish tune), where a beset Lansky (Richard
Dreyfuss) is trying to find sanctuary from American crime hunters,
the story drifts somewhat confusingly over the decades as a fairly
familiar account of a kid from New York's Lower East Side who falls
in with the likes of Benjamin Siegel (Eric Roberts) and Charlie
(Lucky) Luciano (Anthony LaPaglia) while managing to steer clear of
their propensity to murder and batter.
</P>
<P>
   If a scene or two seems to have been borrowed from more
original, violent and ambitious works, that comes naturally to an
imitative genre. (The patient viewer is promised yet another
variation on NBC in the fall, about the childhood friendship of
Lansky and Luciano.)
</P>
<P>
   Mamet faces up to the dry fact that the Lansky career was short
on the color of those of more visceral pals in the syndicate. You
can't imagine this man laying a bat to anybody's skull. His pal,
Ben, may erupt at any moment (if you're looking for trouble, just
call him ``Bugsy''), but Lansky goes his calculating way with never
a frisson of threat. In search of character Mamet finds himself
relying on his own patented sort of wit and wisdom, which turns out
to be a frail substitute for action.
</P>
<P>
   Young Lansky learns early not to gamble ``unless it's your
gamble'' and never to fight fair: ``Who wants to get involved in a
fair fight?'' Somebody says, ``You get nuttin' for nuttin', '' and
Arnold Rothstein, fabled gambler, counsels, ``Never write it down;
keep it in your head,'' before being killed over a poker hand.
</P>
<P>
   Such fruits of the criminal life might have come straight from
the street-hardened Scarface, who shared his secret of success with
his henchmen: ``Do it first and keep doing it!'' But in that
enduring movie, the cheap lesson is accompanied by the killer gun
battles that reward moviegoers for their patience.
</P>
<P>
   No such rewards are forthcoming, as Lansky falls into the
tiresome role of a wandering Jew with a weak heart and strong
opinions, being pursued from Israel to Paraguay to Panama and
finally to Miami Beach. His ultimate lesson: ``Nobody is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he is certifiably right about that: Scarface and Little
Caesar and the Godfather and most of the other unforgettable screen
criminals learn that lesson but in a more entertaining way, with a
lot less whining. ( Warshow observed that if a major character in a
gangster movie finds himself alone on screen, you can be pretty
sure he's about to be wasted. But Lansky seems always to be alone
and nobody takes advantage of it to shut him up, although by the
end of this show many viewers may be hoping.)
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfuss does what he can with an ungiving script, but there's
more kvetcher than character for him to work with. Mamet's Lansky
evidently thinks of himself as a savior of the young Jewish state
as well as a provider of a universally popular pastime, gambling in
its various forms, who is hounded by hypocritical Washington
officials, politicians and other Jew-baiters. His laments and rants
verge on incoherence, but his loyalty to his old pals, Ben and
Charlie, is portrayed as steadfast.
</P>
<P>
   The period style can be engaging, but the tough stuff of the
classic crime yarn is lost in a failed search for a wise guy's
wisdom. Scarface and Little Caesar and their offspring knew how to
settle matters in a blast of bullets. What we are left with in
``Lansky'' is an affable buddy movie with aspirations, or maybe
they are just affectations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
