<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTORNEYS-FEES-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TEXAS CASE ABOUT LEGAL FEES COULD AFFECT THE STATE'S TOBACCO
SETTLEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LINDA P. CAMPBELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The case file in Burrow vs. Arce _ or Arce vs. Burrow, as it's
also known _ gushes superlatives worthy of a raging clash over
attorney fees.
</P>
<P>
   Did attorneys for Carol Arce and other plaintiffs engage in a
``deplorable spectacle'' of signing up victims of a chemical plant
explosion in Pasadena, Texas, and then conduct a settlement
``charade'' that left the clients ``shocked and disappointed'' and
the lawyers rolling in dough?
</P>
<P>
   Or are David Burrow's dissatisfied clients motivated by
``suspicion and jealously'' that ``drove them wild'' because they
believed that co-workers represented by other lawyers got better
deals?
</P>
<P>
   The fight could have been the final chapter in litigation over
the 1989 explosion at Phillips Petroleum Co.'s Houston Chemical
Complex that killed 23 workers and injured many others.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the case's significance has mushroomed in light of
state Attorney General John Cornyn's investigation of the private
attorneys who helped Texas extract a record $17.3 billion
settlement from the tobacco industry for the public costs of
treating ill smokers.
</P>
<P>
   There's talk that the Texas Supreme Court's ruling in the
Phillips litigation could determine whether Cornyn has a legal hook
for trying to rescind all or part of the $3.3 billion in fees that
a federal arbitration panel awarded the legal team headed by the
firms of attorneys Walter Umphrey, Wayne Reaud, John Eddie
Williams, John O'Quinn and Harold Nix.
</P>
<P>
   Lest the potential import of the case escape the Supreme Court,
a friend-of-the-court brief filed in January by Texans for
Reasonable Legal Fees spells it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court's decision in the present case, although it will of
course not directly determine any tobacco fee case and should not
prejudge it, will affect the law under which Attorney General
Cornyn can investigate the tobacco fee facts,'' says the brief,
written by Austin lawyer Pete Schenkkan, who represents the fee
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Cornyn must decide whether the facts show sufficient
breaches of fiduciary owed by those lawyers to their client, the
state of Texas, to warrant the state filing a breach of fiduciary
duty suit against the lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Texans for Reasonable Legal Fees, a coalition of business and
``lawsuit reform'' groups, formed last year to oppose the size of
the tobacco attorneys' payment. The group's brief proposes that, as
a general rule, a lawyer should have to give up all fees in a case
involving ``clear and serious breaches'' of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Political conspiracy theorists in the state capital see all
sorts of ominous possibilities in the explosion case. Here's one
way the dots get connected:
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, now all-Republican, already has a reputation
for a conservative philosophy that tends to favor business
interests over plaintiffs _ and their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, Cornyn was a member of that court. After he
left the court and announced his run for attorney general, Cornyn
sued to protest the huge fees that the tobacco lawyers stood to
gain, although he later dropped the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush appointed four current court members and
named a fifth to a lower appellate bench from which she
successfully ran for the high court last year. Bush, too, has
loudly criticized the fee award and, earlier in the process, also
went to court trying to block the lawyers from collecting. In fact,
the governor's latest court appointee was Al Gonzalez, who as
Texas' secretary of state helped represent his boss in the tobacco
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cornyn have been advised by Republican political
consultant Karl Rove, a former Philip Morris lobbyist, and lawsuit
reform groups have given generously to their campaigns. For
instance, Texans for Lawsuit Reform's political action committee
and 24 of the group's members combined for more than $1 million in
contributions to Cornyn's campaign for attorney general, according
to a recent report from a government watchdog group, Texans for
Public Justice.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the tobacco attorneys are well-known major
donors to Democratic candidates. The five lead firms reportedly
gave more than $1.8 million to the Texas Democratic Party last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ergo, some thinking goes, a ruling that opened the door to axing
the tobacco fees would prevent that money from being channeled into
political races against Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The theorizing does sidestep the likelihood that any fee suit
that Cornyn filed in state court probably would get sent back to
the Texarkana federal court that oversaw the tobacco litigation.
</P>
<P>
   And the tobacco lawyers are wealthy even without the massive
fees and can be expected to continue their pattern of giving
generously to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely unfortunate that this has become a partisan
political game,'' said Patrick Woodson, a spokesman for the tobacco
attorneys' team.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there are any facts that would merit'' a suit
or loss of fees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schenkkan said the political impact makes no difference if an
investigation shows that the tobacco lawyers sold the state short
in their handling of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conspiracy talk about this on either side ... is simply
irrelevant to the legal issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All sorts of ironies surrounding the explosion case help fuel
the undercurrent of intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the plaintiffs originally sued five lawyers in
1992, three of whom later joined the state's tobacco team. Those
three _ Reaud, Umphrey and Williams _ settled with the explosion
plaintiffs several years ago, leaving David Burrow and F. Kenneth
Bailey as defendants in the case.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, one of the plaintiffs' current attorneys,
William Skepnek, also has represented asbestos maker Raymark
Industries. And some of the tobacco lawyers have made fortunes
suing asbestos companies.
</P>
<P>
   In another coincidence, the tobacco attorneys' ethics advisers,
University of Texas law professors Charles Silver and Lynn Baker,
filed a friend-of-the-court brief in the explosion case in
November, arguing against the plaintiffs' position.
</P>
<P>
   The professors say in their brief that they were not paid to
write it and that they ``speak only for ourselves'' as academics
who have written on aggregate settlements.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion case ``could affect every case in which a lawyer
represents a client,'' Silver said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single instance is threatened'' by what the plaintiffs
are arguing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion clients say their original attorneys railroaded
more than 40 Phillips victims and their relatives into a mass
settlement that did not take into account their individual cases.
That kind of settlement is barred by lawyers' ethics rules unless
all the clients are informed and agree to it.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs contend that because their individual interests
weren't adequately represented, the attorneys should forfeit the
millions they made in fees.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys counter that they represented their clients
properly. And even if that were not true, they argue, the
plaintiffs should lose the case because they didn't prove they were
harmed. And even if the clients don't have to prove they were
harmed, the lawyers argue, they shouldn't have to relinquish all
their fees _ just a fair amount determined by a judge.
</P>
<P>
   A Houston judge ruled for the lawyers without a trial, but the
14th Court of Appeals disagreed. The appeals court said the
plaintiffs could make their case simply by proving the lawyers
breached their duty _ harm or no harm _ but that even lawyers who
let down their clients don't have to forfeit all their fees.
</P>
<P>
   Silver and Baker argue that lawyers should not have to forfeit
their fees unless the clients show they were harmed by their
attorneys' breach of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If fee forfeiture makes any sense at all, it makes sense only
when violations are `clear,''' the professors wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said that threatening lawyers with forfeiting their fees
for any breach of duty no matter the impact could make it
impossible to sue companies for dangerous products that cause mass
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn acknowledged knowing about the explosion case but said
recently: ``It's really premature to talk about our office filing
any lawsuits. We are merely at this point trying to figure out what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   One aspect that Cornyn's office is looking into is the work done
by Marc Murr, a Houston lawyer long connected to former Attorney
General Dan Morales, who initiated the tobacco suit. Murr claimed
he was due at least the $260 million in fees that a secret state
panel said he was entitled to, but late last year the federal
arbitration panel awarded him $1 million. Morales has called Murr
an essential consultant in the litigation, but the other private
attorneys have said they don't know what work he did.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn confirmed that federal officials also have been asking
questions about Murr and said his office would cooperate in that
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Cornyn's investigation have suggested that he could
topple the entire state settlement if he tries to capture the
attorney fees for the state. Schenkkan called that a ``scare
tactic.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry spokesman Scott Williams called the fees ``a matter
between the state and their attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement agreement specifically provides that the tobacco
industry will pay _ over more than two decades _ the attorney fees
separately from the amount going to the state. Although forfeited
fees in a typical case would return to the client, it appears that
the tobacco settlement would make any forfeited fees the property
of the industry paying them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlement with the state is concluded,'' Williams said.
If the state were to try to capture some of the attorney fees for
itself, ``that would probably result in litigation,'' he said, but
``that would not impact the settlement itself.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Cornyn is saying little about his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't reached any conclusions because we don't have all
the evidence yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue our investigation and let the chips fall
where they may.''
</P>
<P>
   (Senior reporter Linda P. Campbell covers legal affairs for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at (817) 390-7867.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
