<SLUG> BC-GENEROUS-GIRL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE PRINCESS DI, 7-YEAR-OLD HELPS SICK CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENIFER HANRAHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jeff and Paige Dunham felt they had done something
right when their then-6-year-old daughter, Bree, said she wanted to
give away her birthday presents to sick children.
</P>
<P>
   Our child is so sweet, the San Fernando Valley couple thought,
figuring she'd certainly forget about her plan by the time she
turned 7. That's a long time in kid years.
</P>
<P>
   But sure enough, eight months later, Bree reminded them of her
wish.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Dunhams included a letter in her birthday party
invitations requesting that everyone bring a toy to donate instead
of a gift for Bree. Bree felt so good about her accomplishment that
she decided to try it again last Christmas. This time they asked
everyone on their Christmas card list to send a donation.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Bree raised $3,500 that she donated to the Ronald
McDonald House, a residence for the families of children
hospitalized with serious illnesses. For her selflessness, Bree was
named February's ``Kid of the Month'' by Radio Disney KDIS-AM
(710).
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not stage parents pushing a child to do something,''
said Jeff Dunham. ``She honestly wants to do this and enjoys doing
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bree got the idea for the toy drive when she asked her mom about
the pretty lady on the cover of all the magazines. It was Princess
Diana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to know who she was and why my mom liked her so
much,'' Bree said. ``So, my mom told me about her and what she did.
She went around the world helping sick children and giving poor
children and children who need stuff like toys and clothes. I
started to want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The family plans on continuing the toy drive and getting Bree's
two younger sisters involved.
</P>
<P>
   When she grows up, Bree wants to be a horseback rider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm probably going to grow up to be someone like
Princess Diana and still be a horseback rider. I think I'm going to
keep on doing this for a long time because all the kids looked so
happy when I did it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
