<P>
   LEVIS-LAYOFFS _ Levi Strauss will close 11 of its 22 plants in
North America, including two in Tennessee, and lay off about 5,900
employees as it struggles with slumping sales. It is 30 percent of
its work force in the United States and Canada. It will shift
production to plants overseas, which will enable it to spend more
time and money on product design and marketing, two areas where it
has been lagging. Sales fell 13 percent last year to $6 billion. It
was the second year of disappointing results. (Tharpe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LEVISTRAUSS _ Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. will close 11 of its 22 plants
in North America, including four in Texas, and lay off about 5,900
employees, or 30 percent of its work force in the United States and
Canada, as the jeans maker struggles with slumping sales.
(Harmon-Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   CARSON-ANDREWS _ Carson Inc. President and Chief Executive Greg
Andrews, 47, died from apparent natural causes during a business
trip in South Africa. The company named Malcolm Yesner, 41, acting
chief executive. Yesner remains president of Carson International
and chief executive of Carson Holdings. Carson makes hair-care and
skin-care products. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GAS-MERGER _ AUSTIN _ Southern Union Company says proposals have
been made to create the nation's largest gas-only distribution
company by merging with Southwest Gas Corporation. (Golz, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EEOC-Deluged with employment discrimination cases, the EEOC
unveils alternative dispute resolution program to help companies
resolve employment discrimination disputes. More companies are
seeking mediation programs to avoid costly court battles. (Joyner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GAS-DREGULATION _ Georgia natural gas deregulation is expected
to move into the next phase with the release of the latest count of
Atlanta Gas Light customers who have switched to marketers. Several
areas are expected to have reached the threshhold for random
assignment to suppliers. The whole process could take months but
customers will be on notice to make their selections as soon as
possible. We also survey the latest prices offered by the most
active marketing companies. (Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-PTECH 0219 -- Back in the Dark Ages before home
computers, anyone preparing his income tax returns had to sit down
with pencil, paper and a calculator and shuffle through a box of
records for hours to get the job done. Now that person can sit down
in front of his computer screen and accomplish the same thing.
(Cummings, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TECH TOOLS -- A talking parrott on your PC? Every so often an
idea of such surpassing brilliance arrives via e-mail that I cannot
but share it with you. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS -- FamilyPC magazine, in its March 1999 issue, takes
a look at the issue of brand names as related to technology
products. It attempts to answer this question: When it comes to
computers, is label-consciousness anything more than simple vanity?
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY -- If you have plenty of money and want a new
computer, then there are good reasons for buying one. But if you
are one of those people who have to count pennies, and who have to
make decisions between buying a new computer and going to New
Orleans on vacation, or paying the mortgage, then don't feel blue
or compelled to buy just because you have this vague notion that
you need more. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
