<HEADER>
A4902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEONY-OPERA-REVIEW-NY     02-22 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEONY-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPERA REVIEW: A `PEONY' FINALLY ARRIVES, IN TRADITIONAL STYLE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The big news of the Lincoln Center Festival last
summer was a production that did not in the end take place: a
complete, 18-hour staging of Tang Xianzu's ``Peony Pavilion,'' a
late-16th-century Chinese opera that has come down as the classic
of the Kunqu regional style. At the time, members of the Kunqu
Society of New York made no secret of their objections to the
unseen staging, which, as conceived for the Shanghai Kunqu Opera
Company by Chen Shi-Zheng, a New York director, was to draw on
aspects of Chinese opera tradition now lost as well inject touches
of naturalism into a medium that has become rigidly stylized.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center was finally forced to cancel the production when
bureaucrats in Shanghai, who also presented themselves as guardians
of Kunqu tradition, refused to let the troupe leave China. And soon
afterward, the Kunqu Society announced plans for its own
large-scale production of ``The Peony Pavilion,'' under the
auspices of the China Institute. That version, directed by Shen
Xiao-ming, was presented last weekend at the Kaye Playhouse.
Drawing on nine of the epic work's 55 scenes, and thus steering a
middle course between Chen's epochal compleatism and the typical
presentation of a mere two or three scenes, the production ran
three hours.
</P>
<P>
   In this sequence, the beautiful young Du Liniang is seen
distracted in a classroom; strolling in a garden, where, in the
Peony Pavilion, she dreams of a handsome young lover; pining to her
death for want of him; languishing in the netherworld, and
resurrected after Liu Mengmei, her dream lover's real-life
counterpart, has discovered her self-portrait.
</P>
<P>
   It was gratifying on one level finally to see such a substantial
representation of the work, with much artistry and expertise
lavished on it. Du Liniang was played by Hua Wenyi, famous for her
portrayals of the role over the decades and now also part of Peter
Sellars' touring production of the work, which turns up next week
in Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the disruption of Chinese opera tradition caused by
the Cultural Revolution, older performers have become familiar in
youthful roles, and Ms. Hua's artistry (if not always her voice)
was often such as to encourage a suspension of disbelief. (A viewer
was inevitably reminded of the older Margot Fonteyn in Prokofiev's
``Romeo and Juliet.'') Sie Jiehua was fetching as Fragrance, but
Wang Taiqi portrayed the dashing hero with resources grown slender
and fragile.
</P>
<P>
   The production offered beautiful costumes and, in the
netherworld scene, skillful acrobatics. But the Blossom Fairies
seemed to have wandered in from a Las Vegas stage, and the lighting
was often garish. The music seemed diluted to appeal to bland
Western tastes (though some lack of impact in the drums and cymbals
undoubtedly resulted from the stifling acoustics of the Kaye
stage).
</P>
<P>
   If the attempt was, as it was made to seem, to show the one true
way to draw on a venerable tradition, it left a neophyte admirer of
the art form unpersuaded. Tradition, after all, is manifold, and
nobody owns it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
