<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-TECHNO-ARCHIVE-     02-22 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-TECHNO-ARCHIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING THE EPHEMERAL, BY PENCIL OR A LAPTOP
</HEADLINE>
   (See related DANCE-TECHNO) 
(ms) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Archivists were among the first to use technology in
dance. And preservationists of all stripes attended the symposium
on the topic at the Joyce SoHo Theater last spring, including a few
low-tech participants, as David Vaughan, the white-haired longtime
archivist of the Merce Cunningham Dance Company, dryly described
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Dance technocrats were well represented, too, bent over laptop
computers in the dark theater and muttering about Macs and
megabytes as they sent small arrows flying across wall projections
of complex multimedia diagrams representing the latest in CD-ROM
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Norton Owen, director of the Jose Limon Dance Institute in
Manhattan and director of preservation at the Jacob's Pillow Dance
Festival in Becket, Mass., managed to bridge the two worlds,
endearing himself to the crowd by casually referring to the subject
matter as ``stuff'' in the panel discussion ``Library and Archival
Initiatives.'' Owen looks like the proverbial mild-mannered
scholar, but he presides nonchalantly over gleaming IBM computers
and video decks in his Limon and Pillow offices and yearns for an
editing system.
</P>
<P>
   One of the computers is being used to catalog the Pillow's
archival holdings on the Web site of the Dance Heritage Coalition,
which the festival joined last summer. The site,
www.danceheritage.org, an ambitious three-year project to catalog
dance collections throughout the world, was developed with seven
national library and academic institutions, including the American
Dance Festival and the Duke University Library in Durham, N.C.
``When we talk about the wonderful things to be done with the
technology, I think mainly of that access to information,'' Owen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Owen and his archival staff now videotape interviews with
visitors who have stories to tell. The interviews are stored in a
climate-controlled ``cocoon,'' along with 1,200 current and
historical performance videotapes, some of which had been in danger
of disintegrating. They were copied with a preservation grant from
the ubiquitous National Initiative to Preserve America's Dance.
``There is not very much we don't tape these days,'' Owen said.
``People's stories are tangential in one sense, but in another way
they are the threads that make up the fabric of history,'' he
continued. ``It is the anecdotal things that get lost, because they
are not earth shaking. I think sometimes about the Bourgeois
Gentilhomme learning the difference between poetry and prose and
suddenly understanding that he is speaking prose.''
</P>
<P>
   He talks of Vaughan and how his fabled and exhaustive index-card
archival system started. ``No one ever told him how to do it or
that he should. As a teen-ager he had made lists of performances of
ballets.''
</P>
<P>
   Will there be a place for the David Vaughans and Norton Owens in
the brave new technological world?
</P>
<P>
   ``The tools are wonderful, but I don't want to see them used as
a barrier,'' Owen said. ``I don't want people to say that something
cannot be preserved or documented because they don't have the
tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Owen contributed to ``An Unfinished Memoir,'' a recent book by
and about Jose Limon. ``His tools were a No. 2 pencil and a legal
pad. Those are still available to us and shouldn't be overlooked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
