<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4934 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT23-COX     02-22 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE TO TAKE MICROSOFT TRIAL OFF THE STAND
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Government lawyer David Boies abruptly cut off his
cross-examination of a key Microsoft Corp. manager Monday after the
judge voiced concerns that the lengthy trial may have spun out of
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything in the interest of economy,'' an exasperated U.S.
District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson told defense attorney
Michael Lacovara in granting Lacovara's bid to question his
witness, Dan Rosen, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, Boies had suddenly sat down, leaving several
planned avenues of attack unexplored, after seeing Jackson
repeatedly rolling his eyes and staring at the courtroom ceiling in
response to Rosen's erratic testimony. Lacovara, unprepared for the
turn of events, asked that he have overnight to recover.
</P>
<P>
   The brief delay in the proceedings came after a frazzled Jackson
ordered a recess for the end of the week, when the last of the
three remaining Microsoft witnesses is expected to finish
testifying.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of the world's largest software firm on broad
antitrust charges will not resume until some time after April 12,
depending on when two other cases _ one involving Jackson and the
other involving Boies _ are over.
</P>
<P>
   After the long break, as many as six rebuttal witness are to be
heard.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Jackson had been told by both sides in the landmark
case that it would take no more than six to eight weeks to
complete. In a further effort to speed things up, Jackson had
limited each side to a dozen witnesses and cut the time spent in
the courtroom to only cross-examinations.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge's efforts proved to no avail as a flood of
documents, including once super-secret e-mails, were offered into
evidence. Fresh material was still being produced Monday, when the
trial entered its 18th week.
</P>
<P>
   Boies showed Rosen, Microsoft's manager of new technology, a
memo Rosen had drafted in May 1995 entitled ``Internet Direction.''
He then sought to show that in the memo, Rosen had called on
Microsoft to step up its effort to control the personal computer
desktop through the dominance of its Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The memo was important because, in his direct testimony, Rosen
had cast himself as the leading Microsoft official to press for a
friendly strategic alliance with Netscape Communications Corp.,
thereby avoiding a bruising Internet browser war.
</P>
<P>
   On the stand, Rosen denied he had ever e-mailed the memo to
anyone, saying he had merely used the memo to sort his thoughts.
But, subsequently, upon being shown documentary evidence, he
acknowledged that he had in fact sent his memo to at least one
Microsoft official, Ben Slivka.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on, this lapse seemed to be least of Rosen's
problems. He repeatedly failed to square his pre-trial deposition
with his direct testimony. And he continually sparred with Boies
over what seemed to be the plain meaning of such words as
``browser'' and software ``client.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen denied that he had ever heard anyone at Microsoft use the
terms ``browser'' or ``browser battle'' at any time between 1995
and 1997. He denied Boies' contention that Microsoft sought to gain
browser market share, at Netscape's expense, during the three-year
period, despite Microsoft memos and e-mail messages citing that
fact. Instead, he asserted that Microsoft was interested merely in
``usage share of Internet technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   At several points, courtroom spectators erupted in skeptical
laughter as Rosen rebuffed Boies' attempts to show that Microsoft
executives _ from Microsoft co-founder Bill Gates on down _ had
used those terms.
</P>
<P>
   The final straw came when Boies showed Rosen an e-mail from
another Microsoft employee, Chris Jones, that said the object of a
key June 21, 1995, meeting with Netscape's top brass was to ensure
that the competitor's Navigator browser would not evolve into a
substitute for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would not be a platform competitor,'' Boies said. ``Isn't
it what this says?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not correct,'' Rosen shot back.
</P>
<P>
   Boies said: ``I have no further questions.''
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
