<HEADER>
A4936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONET-REVIEW23-COX     02-22 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONET-REVIEW23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Monet &AMP; Bazille': Detective work
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In 1863, Claude Monet and Frederic Bazille met as
students in the studio of Charles Gleyre in Paris. That meeting
sparked a friendship that resulted in a relationship that
contributed to the development of impressionism.
</P>
<P>
   Like its larger counterpart, ``Monet and Bazille: A
Collaboration'' can be enjoyed purely on a sensual level. Indeed,
Monet's ``The Bodmer Oak, Fontainebleau Forest, the Chailly Road,''
which reveals both the influence of the Barbizon painters and
Monet's talents at a young age, is one of the highlights of both
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   But this show, organized by High Museum of Art curator David
Brenneman, is built on an intellectual investigation. It started
with a comparison of Bazille's painting ``The Beach at
Sainte-Adresse,'' owned by the High, and Monet's ``Seaside at
Sainte-Adresse'' from the Minneapolis Museum of Art, long thought
to be the source of Bazille's composition, and broadened into a
study of the relationship of two young artists between 1863 and
1870 and the role it played in the development of this radical
painting style.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of impressionism can be traced in the pictures.
(Chronologically speaking, it should be viewed before the larger
impressionism show also at the High.) The smooth neoclassical style
and classical setting of Gleyre's ``The Bath'' exemplifies the
mainstream art of the period, which Monet and Bazille chose to
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Their mentors are Courbet, represented by a seascape, and the
Barbizon School, whose members painted outdoors in the forests of
Fontainebleau, exemplified by Theodore Rousseau's ``Sunset over the
Plains of Barbizon,'' dominated by pillowy, back-lit clouds
reddened by the sinking sun.
</P>
<P>
   One of the early paintings in the other show, ``A Seascape,
Shipping by Moonlight'' is Monet ``doing'' Courbet. But that
painting, as the seascapes in this show document, was a clumsy
aberration in his journey toward his own style.
</P>
<P>
   What hasn't been explored before is how Bazille, with whom he
shared a studio and went on excursions to the seaside and
Fontainebleau, helped move him forward. Though suggested in the
wall texts in labels, it takes reading the catalog to fully
understand. Kermit Champa, one of the catalog essayists, described
it as co-dependence, with Bazille providing the admiration and
financial support that Monet needed at that time. Bazille, in turn,
got a mentor.
</P>
<P>
   The High's Bazille is perhaps the most material example of his
dependence on Monet. Yet, it is clear that Bazille was no mere
imitator. Even his copy of Monet's study (he was not yet painting
completely out-of-doors, if indeed he ever did) reveals important
stylistic differences. Whether intentionally or not, Bazille does
not blend his colors and brush strokes like Monet does to achieve
an evenness in the picture surface. He doesn't emulate Monet's deep
space either. Bazille's version is a more post-impressionist and
pre-impressionist: His additions, the figure and sailboat in the
foreground, are outlined in black and keep your attention to the
surface, which is thicker than his counterpart's. Bazille's
painting seems to be an imagined landscape rather than one painted
on the site, even though he had visited Sainte Adresse before.
</P>
<P>
   As Monet during this period was concluding that his forte was
the landscape rather than the figure or integrating the two (note
his study ``Strollers''), Bazille was discovering the opposite. In
1868, two years before he died in the Franco-Prussian War, he
seemed to be on the way to finding his own artistic personality: In
``View from a Village,'' Bazille depicts a woman in the foreground
of a landscape gazing at the viewer in an engaging and convincing
way Monet couldn't accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Brenneman has packed a lot of information, including a broader
context for a painting in permanent collection, in an exhibition of
20 paintings, and lovely ones at that. He makes good on his
contention that ``more is not necessarily more.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: cfox(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
