<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Political advice flows freely for first lady
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The newsweeklies devote major space to Hillary Rodham
Clinton's flirtation with elected office. Newsweek ($3.50) calls
Clinton the ``hottest commodity in American public life,'' ranking
somewhere between Gwyneth Paltrow and Princess Diana. In a guest
column, George Stephanopoulos hints that the Senate would be a step
down for Clinton, and suggests aiming higher, post-Gore, with a
campaign that begins in Manchester (N.H.), not in Manhattan. In
addition to gauging Clinton's chances against Rudolph Giuliani,
Time ($2.95) offers free advice from Ed Koch (go for it) and Jimmy
Breslin (forget about it). U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($2.95) says
it's likely that a campaign would be ``nasty, brutish and long. For
a woman reeling from the Year of Monica, it could be a very
unpleasant way to spend her remaining 23 months as first lady.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Filming the apocalypse: In a story about the difficulty of
putting World War II on the big screen, Forbes American Heritage
($4.95) surprises us with the information that American documentary
units covering the war included such filmmakers as John Huston,
Darryl Zanuck and David O. Selznick. In the same magazine, novelist
Larry McMurtry writes about the battle at Little Bighorn, where Lt.
Col. George Armstrong Custer, ``that erratic egotist,'' did what he
had always done: ``push ahead, disregard orders, start a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Into the teeth of the storm: Some of the bravest (or craziest)
National Guard members can be found among Alaska's 210th Rescue
Squadron, with the Air National Guard. These bravos jump from
airplanes, rappel out of helicopters, and snatch foolish
adventurers off of mountains and out of churning arctic seas. Men's
Journal ($3.95) shows the 210th at work trying to save an errant
climber on Mount McKinley. Also inside: the droll P.J. O'Rourke
offers a guide to spring break for grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fresh air: Vladimir Joseph, the 25-year-old founder of Inner
Strength, leads inner-city Atlanta kids on hiking, rafting or
camping trips to prove to them that there are ``things that are
beautiful and brilliant'' outside the grim reality of the ghetto.
Read about Joseph, a reformed gang member and throwaway kid, in
People ($2.99).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blood brothers: Billy Bulger was, for 17 years, president of
the Massachusetts state Senate. His brother Whitey Bulger was,
during the same time period, a bloodthirsty gang leader in Boston's
Irish underworld. In George ($2.95), Peter Maas and Mike Barnicle
write about the odd duo, and explore the question: Was Whitey
working for the FBI, or was the FBI working for him?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Assembled by humans, not robots: The Morgan sports car, with
its wooden frame, whale-mouth grille and leather strap across the
bonnet, is the most elegant of the open-air two seaters, says Polo
($4.95). No argument here.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Works on girlfriends too: Cartoonist Jeff MacNelly explains to
Cigar Aficionado ($5.95) that he doesn't smoke cigars socially,
calling his habit a form of crowd control. ``Fire up a cigar and
everyone leaves. It's kind of nice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pot wars: Last year, after the British medical journal the
Lancet concluded that ``moderate indulgence in cannabis has little
ill effect on health,'' the FBI released statistics showing that in
1997, 695,000 people were arrested for pot. That number represents
twice the arrests in 1992. Rolling Stone ($3) hammers home the
irony that a president who has admitted smoking has had more
Americans imprisoned for marijuana than at any other time in U.S.
history.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
