<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALTERS-MONICA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewinsky interview puts `exclamation' on story
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ She laughs, she almost cries. Will she be better than
``Cats''?
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Walters' two-hour interview with Monica Lewinsky, airing
at 9 p.m. March 3 on ABC in an extended ``20/20,'' has the former
White House intern detailing her relationship with President
Clinton from ``the day of that famous thong,'' Walters says, to
Lewinsky's feelings about the president ``to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts an exclamation point finally on this year,'' Walters
said Monday from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Walters interviewed Lewinsky on Saturday in New York for about
190 minutes. Held inside a ``20/20'' studio, tricked up with
furniture to make the setting more homey, the two talked for 90
minutes, after which Lewinsky took a 20-minute break and ate a
roast beef sandwich. They then talked another 90 minutes, stopped,
and spent another 10 minutes taking publicity photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is open, expressive, sometimes very touching, funny and
extremely articulate _ she is not a Valley girl,'' Walters said.
``There are times when she's very emotional, where she is I think
teary, but it's not a sobbing interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Walters landed the interview over a parade of competitors,
including both ``60 Minutes,'' all the ``Datelines,'' Oprah Winfrey
and ``Roseanne.'' Fox reportedly dangled $3 million to get her.
</P>
<P>
   For her interview, there were few restrictions placed on
Lewinsky as part of her immunity agreement with Ken Starr's Office
of Independent Council: She could not describe the events of when
she was questioned by Starr's office, most notably during her first
encounter, on Jan. 16; and she couldn't contradict her grand jury
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's agreement with Lewinsky allows the network to air the
interview only once, though excerpts can be used during newscasts
and likely will be used to promote the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the president in a way I'm not sure you have been able
to see him before, you understand the role of her mother,
understand how she feels about Ken Starr,'' Walters said.
``Watching her expressions, she is reliving in this interview what
happened in a way that she could not with the Senate and the grand
jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Lewinsky is still in love with the president, Walters
said coyly, ``I'm not going to give you the answer. Just say I know
the answer.''Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
