<HEADER>
A4940 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPRESSIONIST-SHOW23-     02-22 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPRESSIONIST-SHOW23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    rf/x5622/4-607-8463f
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The impressionist exhibit at the high museum of art: More than
just pretty pictures
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Step beyond the velvet curtain and into the serene
world of impressionism. On view at the High Museum of Art are 88
paintings of the countryside, the seaside, Paris and its
inhabitants, most of them depicted in the flickering brush strokes
and cheerful palette that is synonymous with the most beloved
movement in modern history.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have a grand time viewing these two impressionist
exhibitions. They will certainly not disappoint the viewer happy
just to luxuriate in pretty pictures. Both shows, however, offer
more than immediately meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impressionism: Paintings Collected by European Museums''
examines the intersection of art and commerce and the role the
latter played in the acceptance of a movement that was _ as
difficult as it is to imagine now _ viewed with horror and contempt
a little more than a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The impressionists set in motion the art world ecology _ artist/
dealer/collector/museum _ that exists today. Because of their
rejection from the Salon, at that time the ultimate venue for
seeing and selling art, these renegades organized their own shows
and began using art dealers such as Paul Durand-Ruel to sell their
work. The maroon color of the High's first gallery, replete with
molding and wainscots, replicates the walls of Durand-Ruel's
gallery _ an homage to the man whose missionary zeal was largely
responsible for his clients' eventual acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   The High has installed a reproduction of his storefront in the
second gallery. Inside are photographic blowups of what the gallery
looked like and synoptic histories of major collectors, dealers and
museum directors. A few of the most important collectors were
impressionist artists themselves. The paintings Gustave Caillebotte
bought from his less-moneyed friends are the nucleus of the Musee
d'Orsay's fabled collection. Caillebotte had willed them to the
French nation, much to the horror of museum personnel, who took
only about half the collection, and that after two years of
wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most courageous players in this drama were the
museum directors who made acquisitions when such decisions were, as
managing curator Michael Shapiro says, still ``fraught with
danger.'' The Kaiser ultimately sacked Hugo von Tshudi because of
his purchases for the Berlin Nationalgalerie.
</P>
<P>
   Though chosen because they were among the earliest to make it up
the food chain, so to speak, into Europe's museums, these
paintings, assembled by Shapiro and guest curator Ann Dumas, must
succeed on their visual impact as well. Despite some questionable
moments, the show is a special opportunity for Atlantans to see
fine examples by the major participants in the movement as well as
the less famous who merit more attention.
</P>
<P>
   Renoir's ``Woman with a Parasol in a Garden,'' painted the year
of the impressionists' first independent exhibition (1874), is an
archetypal, casually composed view painted with flecks of color
that almost flatten the image into a weaving. The landscapes by
Sisley, Monet and others similarly revel in the beauty of nature
and seasonal effects. They show the continuum of impressionism,
from Pissarro's more structured approach to Monet's ``Hoarfrost,
near Vetheuil,'' in which the world seems about to dissolve into
color and light.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, viewers expecting a parade of ``textbook''
paintings will be disappointed. On the other, those looking for a
less, say, predictable, sample of impressionism will have a fine
time. Portraits by the four women in the show are good examples.
Berthe Morisot understood perfectly how to apply impressionist
principles to the figure. Marie Bracquemond demonstrates her
compositional, figurative and paintings skills in ``On the Terrace
at Sevres,'' a flurry of short, dynamic strokes that build a lively
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Though considered marginal because of his smoother style,
Gustave Caillebotte's delightful ``Le Pont de l'Europe'' embodies
impressionist immediacy and interest in urban life. The strong
diagonal of the new-fangled bridge draws the viewer into the
painting, right behind the dog in the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   On the down side, why devote a wall to formulaic late Renoir
portraits, in which all the female subjects bear rouged cheeks,
beady, astigmatic eyes and what the great collector Henry McIlhenny
dismissively described as bovine figures? The post-impressionist
section is sketchy and the quality inconsistent. True, Cezanne, van
Gogh and Gauguin went through impressionist periods before arriving
at their mature styles, but their presence, especially the Cezanne
examples, seem almost token as if suddenly the show has become a
historical survey.
</P>
<P>
   No need to be all things to all viewers. The premise, which
initially seemed to be just another excuse to trot out crowd
pleasers, is actually quite illuminating. An artwork is not
complete until someone other than its maker can see it. Exploring
how that happens reiterates one point : It takes individuals with
vision.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Impressionism: Paintings Collected by European Museums'' and
``Monet &AMP; Bazille: A Collaboration.''
</P>
<P>
   High Museum of Art, 1280 Peachtree St. N.E. Through May 16. 10
a.m.-5 p.m. Saturdays-Wednesdays; until 9 p.m. Thursdays and
Fridays. Admission weekdays: $13; $10 seniors, students, groups; $8
members; $5 school groups. Weekends: $15; $12; $8. Tickets:
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff Arts Center box office, Ticketmaster outlets; by phone,
404-733-5000 or
</P>
<P>
   404-817-8700; or online at:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.high.org
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.ticketmaster.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.impressionism.org.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A visual feast, but definitely more to learn than
meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: cfox(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
