<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, Feb. 23. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Rambouillet, France) _ The Kosovo peace talks are
on the verge of breakdown, as five guerrillas from the Kosovo
Liberation Army refuse the exhortations of Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to sign an agreement and are unpersuaded by a
last ditch visit from the Supreme Commander of NATO, Gen. Wesley
Clark. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HARASS (Pristina, Serbia) _ The Serbian police beat and
harassed cease-fire monitors in Kosovo, the monitoring group says
as reports arrive about attacks on villages and of fighting between
Serbian troops and ethnic Albanian rebels. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CERVICAL-CANCER (Undated) _ The National Cancer Institutes
recommends a major change in the treatment of invasive cervical
cancer, a disease that kills nearly 5,000 women a year. The change
is based on a study that shows chemotherapy substantially improves
chances of recovery. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   BOX-LAILA-ALI (Los Angeles) _ Laila Ali went to her father's
Beverly Hills hotel suite three weeks ago to get his blessing on
her decision to follow in his footsteps. Women's professional
boxing is a sport struggling for stature. While the number of women
in its ranks have grown greatly in recent years, with women
fighting in gyms across the country and even on the undercards of
some major prizefights, female professional boxing is desperate for
true stars, but also concerned that it not be turned into just a
curious sideshow. And so the prospect of Laila Ali, a woman with a
marketable name and no proven skills, turning pro has infused the
sport with a sense of both promise and worry. By Timothy W. Smith.
1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-LAWSUIT _ For nearly a century, American Indians have
been asking the federal government for a simple accounting of money
and land held in trust for them since days of treaty signing. On
Monday, two Cabinet secretaries who oversee these accounts are held
in contempt of court by a federal judge who accused the government
of deceit and neglect in responding to the largest lawsuit ever
brought by Indians. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   LEVI-CUTBACK (Undated) _ Levi Strauss, whose jeans sales have
been sluggish and which warned employees several weeks ago that it
would be closing some facilities, says it will close 11 of its 22
North American plants and lay off 5,900 workers, or 30 percent of
its North American labor force. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DRUNK-DRIVERS (New York) _ At least two cars are seized under
a new police crackdown on drunk drivers. By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-MAYORAL (Chicago) _ Mayor Daley heads for resounding
re-election Tuesday with strong support from black voters. By Dirk
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINE-U.S. (Moscow) _ Folo on the detention in New York of
Pavlo Lazarenko, a former Ukraine prime minister, who is wanted on
charges of corruption. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-STEEL (Washington) _ Russia agrees to limit steel
shipments into the United States, avoiding punitive tariffs that
had been sought by the U.S. steel industry. The agreement was
announced by Commerce Secretary William Daley. He said it will mean
a cut of almost 70 percent in Russian steel shipments coming into
the United States. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MASSACRE-ANTHROPOLOGY (Guatemala City) _ Based on accounts
of four survivors and people in neighboring communities, 376 people
in an isolated Mayan hamlet of Guatemala died in a massacre by army
troops in 1982. Now, 17 years later, forensic anthropologists led
by the eminent scientist Dr. Clyde Collins Snow are confirming
their accounts, in all too graphic detail. By Malcolm W. Browne.
2,150 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map. (MOVED)
</P>
</TEXT>
