<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-STANBURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAMELA COOK STANBURY, 44; ANTHROPOLOGIST, US ADVISER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A funeral service will be held Tuesday for Pamela Cook Stanbury,
an anthropologist who was an adviser to the US Agency for
International Development.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stanbury died of cancer Saturday in her home in Silver
Spring, Md. She was 44.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Brookline, Mass. She graduated from Sarah
Lawrence College and earned a doctorate at the University of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Following her marriage to fellow anthropologist David
Groenfeldt, she lived in Sri Lanka, where she held a postdoctoral
fellowship with the International Irrigation Management Institute.
</P>
<P>
   After moving to the District of Columbia area in 1989, she was
awarded a fellowship with the American Academy for the Advancement
of Science to work with the US Agency for International
Development, where she most recently was a land tenure adviser with
the office of agriculture. She also taught at George Washington
University.
</P>
<P>
   Besides her husband, she leaves two daughters, Margot and Julia;
her parents, John and Jean Stanbury of Chestnut Hill, Mass.; two
brothers, John Jr. of Wellesley, Mass. and David of Alabama; and
two sisters, Sarah of Brookline, Mass. and Martha of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral will be held at 4 p.m. in Adelphi Friends Meeting in
Adelphi, Md.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1834EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
