<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4958 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVS-EDUCATION-HNS &LR;      02-22 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVS-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND GOVERNORS GO HEAD-TO-HEAD ON EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and the nation's governors
squared off Monday on federal education rules that some governors
characterized as burdensome and evidence that big brother in
Washington still thinks he knows what's best.
</P>
<P>
   Those governors, many from the 31-strong Republican contingent,
complained that laws aimed at reducing class size in grades 1-3 and
assisting students with disabilities, require huge expenditures of
state funds. The governors said they should have freer rein to
spend federal education dollars on problems that arise at the local
level.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a former governor, assured the governors that there is
flexibility in federal regulations when it comes to education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some will say the federal government should be giving states
more flexibility, not demanding more accountability,'' Clinton told
the governors. ``I say it's a false choice, and the federal
government should be giving you more of both.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the Republican-controlled Congress last year
approved his plan to reduce class size in early grades by hiring
100,000 teachers. This year Clinton is focusing on renovating or
building 6,000 new classrooms, ending social promotion of students
not performing up to grade level, and insisting on effective
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   But governors said they made clear to Clinton that they felt
hamstrung by regulations imposed by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government should be a limited partner, not a
general partner,'' said Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a leading
contender in early speculation about the GOP's presidential
nomination in 2000. ``If they feel like sending money back to the
states, fine. But don't tell us how to run things.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki of New York, also a Republican, said only
state and local officials are in a position to determine the needs
of schools in their areas.
</P>
<P>
   Washington shouldn't dictate to states ``whether they should be
investing in teachers, computers, new boilers, new roofs or new
schools,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   While he welcomes the administration's emphasis on higher
standards and discipline, Pataki said that ``when it comes to the
actual decisions as to where to allocate the funds, the differences
between Buffalo and Batavia (in New York state) are enormous, let
alone the differences between New York and Wyoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat from California, attending his first
Washington governors meeting as the state's newly elected top
official, said that asking for waivers from federal regulations is
cumbersome but achievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the best of all worlds, (Washington would) just give us the
money and hold us accountable for results,'' Davis told reporters
after the meeting. ``But that's a long process to change ... I'm
happy to work within the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' staff distributed a Feb. 19 letter fron California's
superintendent of public instruction, Delaine Eastin, to Education
Secretary Richard Riley, requesting a waiver from requirements that
federal funds go to reducing class size in early grades.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the letter said, California wants to reduce class size
in about 100 districts drawn to serve students only in grades 7-12.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said California has succeeded in reducing class size in
grades K-4 to about 20, and now needs to concentrate on the upper
grades. ``I hope we'll get there,'' he said, adding that as a
former governor, Clinton was ``as receptive and as flexible as you
could possibly ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Several governors also complained that the $4.3 billion in
federal aid this year for educating six million children with
disabilities actually forces states to spend their own money to
comply with federal mandates.
</P>
<P>
   Requirements in federal law dating back to 1975 require schools
to provide ``to the maximum extent possible'' a ``free, appropriate
public education'' in the ``least restrictive'' environment.
</P>
<P>
   At the local level, that often means significant extra
expenditures for staff to teach disabled children, building
modifications and instructional equipment _ everything from
specialized furniture to books on tape to computers that talk.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bradshaw, spokesman for the U.S. Education Department, said
federal money accounts for only 10 percent of the money necessary
to educate disabled children. The remainder, he said, must come
from state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the request we are making (to the states to share the
funding) is a fair one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mike Leavitt of Utah, a Republican who is vice-chairman of
the National Governors' Association, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Republican and Democratic governors want is a national
agenda for reform of education, not a federal agenda,'' Leavitt
said. On special education, ``our message (to Washington) is make
it more reasonable and fund it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Governors also expressed concern over talk that the Clinton
administration wants to grab a big share of the $195 billion
tobacco settlement reached between the states and the tobacco
industry last year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the governors that the Justice Department believes
Washington must try to recoup money the federal Medicaid program
has expended on those with smoking-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said that Clinton ``doesn't want the money back.'' But,
Davis added, Clinton wants to make sure states use money from
tobacco settlements for anti-smoking programs, especially those
aimed at teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing that anyway (in California) so we don't see a
problem with that,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican governors were more skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was encouraged that the president said he wasn't
trying to take the states' money,'' said Gov. John Engler of
Michigan, a Republican. ``We couldn't see if the fingers were
crossed or not.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One item that did not come up was the prospect of First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton campaigning in 2000 to be a senator from New
York. Asked about a potential bid by Mrs. Clinton, Pataki said:
``We've got 18 million bright, talented, capable residents of New
York State. We should be able to find one ... who is able to
represent us well in Washington.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1838EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
