A4960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COWARD-THEATER-REVIEW     02-22 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWARD-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OH, COWARD!': WORLD WEARY? SAIL AWAY, FOR STARTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Noel Coward's Champagne seems a lot like beer by the
time the well-meaning but lackluster revue ``Oh, Coward!'' winds to
its end.
</P>
<P>
   Bright looking but fundamentally bland, this generous little
show playing through March 14 at the inviting Irish Repertory
Theater, offers more than 30 of Coward's bright songs, plus
snippets from his writings.
</P>
<P>
   So here, divided into such categories as England, Travel, Love
and Women, are Coward gems like ``London Pride,'' ``Why Do the
Wrong People Travel?,'' ``Mrs. Worthington,'' ``Mad Dogs and
Englishmen,'' ``Mad About the Boy'' and ``I'll Follow My Secret
Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The three performers, William B. Hubert II, Brendan Powers and
Maggie Runfola, accompanied at the piano by Stephen Vasta, try
earnestly to summon up the panache needed to deliver this bright,
brittle material. But in this context, the importance of being
earnest is that earnestness weighs heavily on these songs. The
Cowardly way through this repertory calls for blithe spirits.
</P>
<P>
   So the plus fours, vested suits, white nautical blazer and, in
the second act, the white tie, tails and a deep blue gown provided
by Geraldine Dusk can carry the cast only to the shores of
sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the journey must be propelled from within, and while
the spirit of the three young performers may be willing, the flash
is weak. All too often, insubstantial interpretations result in
renditions without flair, and eventually a certain monotony
pervades the show, devised by Roderick Cook and directed by
Augustine Towey.
</P>
<P>
   While the three principals give evidence of sufficient talent to
suggest that they would be at home playing specific roles in a
musical, none radiates the convincing worldliness, intelligent
insight, mischievous wit and considered affection that a performer
like Steve Ross, currently at the Firebird Cafe, brings to much of
the same Coward repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Coward's songs remain a lighthearted pleasure, but regrettably
``Oh, Coward!'' slogs along when it ought to sparkle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `OH, COWARD!'
</P>
<P>
   Based on the life and works of Noel Coward, originally devised
by Roderick Cook; directed by Augustine Towey; sets by Charlotte
Moore; costumes by Geraldine Dusk; lighting by Jason Cina;
choreography by Lynn Kurdziel-Formato; musical director, Donald R.
Jenczka; production stage manager, Elizabeth Larson; produced by
Ciaran O'Reilly. Presented by the Irish Repertory Theater, Ms.
Moore, artistic director; O'Reilly, producing director, in
association with the Irish Classical Theater Company.
</P>
<P>
   With: William B. Hubert II, Brendan Powers, Maggie Runfola and
Stephen Vasta on piano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1840EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
