<SLUG> BC-WOMAN-BICYCLIST-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVENTUROUS SPIRIT CHALLENGES HERSELF WITH 12,000-MILE BICYCLE
JOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By CAROL BIDWELL 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Megan Timothy looks back on her life, there
are no ``if onlys'' or ``I should haves.'' And with a lifetime of
different careers and exploits behind her, at 59, the
Rhodesian-born North Hollywood woman is heading into her biggest
adventure ever: a 10-month, 12,000-mile solo bicycle journey around
Western Europe and part of Africa, equipped with less gear than
most people pack for a weekend at a country inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to have adventures in the world anymore,'' the lean,
gray-haired Timothy says with a tinge of wistful sadness in her
voice. ``The world is so small, and there are no challenges left. I
was born in the wrong century. I should have been born in the
1800s, when they still had frontiers. The last frontier is the
outer galaxy, and I don't have enough money to go there. So I'm
doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll fly to Paris on Monday to begin a personal odyssey she's
been planning for a year, ever since she felt like Wonder Woman
after pedaling a rented bike 800 miles around France's Loire Valley
_ and then learned that an English schoolteacher had spent the
summer biking 10,000 miles around Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I can do better than that,' and decided I would,''
Timothy said.
</P>
<P>
   She sold her historic, stained glass-filled showpiece of a home
in North Hollywood, her well-worn Honda Civic and nearly all her
possessions and bought a lightweight bicycle with saddlebags to
hold her gear. When she's not riding around the Valley to get in
shape, she's learning to repair her bike in case it malfunctions on
the long trek.
</P>
<P>
   And she's spent the past six months reading guidebooks,
collecting maps and planning a detailed route that'll take her
through France, Spain, Morocco, Italy, Greece, Turkey, Bulgaria,
Romania, Hungary, Austria, the Czech Republic, Germany, Holland,
Belgium, England and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   She'll likely spend her 60th birthday, June 21, in Italy,
reveling in the sights and sounds and smells of somewhere she's
never been before.
</P>
<P>
   With time off to rest up and see the sights along the way,
Timothy figures to end her journey Nov. 3 in Paris, closing the
loop.
</P>
<P>
   It's only the latest adventure for the screenwriter, who's
finishing up one last script before climbing on the plane for
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy is driven by curiosity _ always has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is so interesting, that's my problem,''' Timothy
said. ``It's the learning that's exciting. Once I know about it _
or how to do it _ I feel that I'm stagnating. Then there's
something else to pursue.''
</P>
<P>
   After a brief career as a horsewoman and horse trainer, she left
her African homeland, now called Zimbabwe, for Hollywood in the
early 1960s. Even with an untrained voice, Timothy _ who could play
the guitar _ found work as a folk singer, performing at
coffeehouses and entertaining U.S. troops in Vietnam on USO tours.
</P>
<P>
   After a 14-month stint as a Playboy bunny in Hollywood, Timothy
got fired when she set fire to a patron's beard while trying to
light his cigarette and put the fire out by throwing a glass of
water in his face.
</P>
<P>
   Time for another job, this time as an actress. Timothy had a
number of bit parts and even appeared in the 1969 Elvis Presley
movie ``Charro'' before adventure called.
</P>
<P>
   She and a companion built a raft, lashed airplane wings beneath
it for buoyancy, put the hull of an old travel trailer on top for a
cabin and set off down the Mississippi, braving a hurricane along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   The travel ``fix'' worked _ for a while. A decade later,
wanderlust beckoned, and Timothy headed to Brazil because she'd
heard it was a gorgeous country. Joining some other travelers she
met on the plane, they headed off with two native guides on an
unplanned trek through the headhunter country of the Amazon jungle
by canoe, taking quick dips in the river and scrambling out before
flesh-eating piranhas could swim near and sleeping in a hammock to
thwart the fire ants that swarmed over the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Back at home, she became fascinated with stained glass and
decided to learn the craft. Eventually she filled her home _ a
historic house built in the 1920s _ with more than 100
stained-glass windows. The house became such a showplace, she
turned its guest houses _ also filled with stained glass _ into a
bed-and-breakfast inn, where she doubled as chef. Expanding her
culinary repertoire, she learned to make fantasy wedding cakes so
elaborate they were featured in Chocolatier and Good Housekeeping
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   That was followed by a stint as a caterer, then a movie
stuntwoman, before she became a screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wake up one morning and decide I'm going to do
something,'' she said simply. ``Then I do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So Timothy woke up one morning and decided to take a nice long
bicycle ride _ through much of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But for this adventure, she's made meticulous plans, right down
to what she'll wear, what she'll pack, what she'll eat, where
she'll sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an adventurous person, but I don't think I'm a reckless
person,'' she said matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her mother has kept meticulous scrapbooks chronicling her
daughter's many journeys, and she said she's never worried about
her yen for adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very self-sufficient sort of person,'' said Helen
Timothy. ``She can take good care of herself ... She knows what she
wants, and she goes for it. And 95 percent of the time, she's
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Timothy radiates competence, she admits she's a bit
frightened as time to begin her journey nears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared,'' she said. ``I'm scared of traffic. I can't
compete with 18-wheel trucks, so I'll stay on side roads. I'm
scared of smokers running amok, which they do in Europe (she's a
nonsmoker). I'm worried about someone being so kind to me that they
put a big slab of some poor, dead animal on my plate (she's a
vegetarian). I'm worried about things like being able to get dental
floss in Turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   She expects language to be a bit of a problem on her trip but
plans to overcome difficulties with a smile, a handshake and her
own version of charades.
</P>
<P>
   Friends Nancy and Richard Wedeen of North Hollywood, members of
the Los Angeles Wheelmen for 20 years, have helped Timothy prepare
for her trip _ Nancy coaching her in riding techniques and safety,
and Richard teaching her how to do bike repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she'll be ready for anything, any time,'' Nancy said.
``Even if she doesn't have all the skills, she'll learn along the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Hoffman, owner of North Hollywood's Pedal Shop and
Timothy's outfitter, said her 21-speed bike should carry her
anywhere she wants to go. Most of his customers are male and
decades younger than Timothy, he said, admitting to be amazed by
``the fact that she's a lady _ and just the sheer independence of
her, that she's doing this alone. But it'll be an adventure of a
lifetime for her.''
</P>
<P>
   To make sure all goes smoothly, a tiny tool kit, an extra tire,
brake cables and spokes are among her luggage.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a lightweight tent, sleeping bag, water bottle,
bedding, camera and first-aid kit, she'll take only her itinerary
and a few maps.
</P>
<P>
   Her wardrobe will be basically the clothes she has on her back.
In a resealable plastic kitchen bag, she'll carry a change of
underwear, an extra Lycra top, a couple of extra pairs of socks.
She'll do laundry every night so she'll have clean clothes the next
morning. If they're not dry, ... well, the next day will be a wet
ride.
</P>
<P>
   She'll subsist on yogurt, bananas, dried fruit, rice and fresh
vegetables, with an occasional restaurant meal as a luxury. But
most meals will be cooked over a campfire in a stainless-steel
bowl, which will double as a serving dish. That, a Swiss Army
knife, a spoon and a fork are all the utensils she'll take.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most ominous challenges in her route will come
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first part of my trip is going to be pure misery,''
Timothy said. ``I expect it to be cold and rainy all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten days into the trip, she'll cross the Spanish border and then
pedal over the snow-covered Pyrenees.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the long journey will be relieved by an occasional
ferry or hydrofoil (a high-speed boat) trip _ from Spain to Morocco
and back, from Italy to Greece, from Bulgaria to Turkey _ and one
short train trek, through Italy's steepest mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Along with learning the routes she'll be traveling, she's had to
learn the rules and customs of the countries she'll visit.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in Bulgaria, she must have her visitor's card
stamped by an official every night. If she misses more than two
nights, government agents will start looking for her; when they
find her, they'll throw her out of the country if she's lucky _ or
imprison her if she's not.
</P>
<P>
   During the height of the summer, when she'll be pedaling through
Italy (``1,000 miles of sweating and swearing''), Greece, Turkey
and Bulgaria, she plans to be on the road by 5 a.m. With five hours
a day of pedaling, she plans on covering about 50 miles, six days a
week.
</P>
<P>
   She figures the trip will cost about $35 a day, ``which will
take some creativity. But I'll be camping a lot, and that only
costs about $4 a night (at campgrounds with bathing facilities). I
know I'll go over budget in France and Italy the first three weeks,
but it's going to be cold and wet, and I'm going to cuddle up under
some nice down comforter in an inn somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's too cold and wintery once she reaches Belgium, she'll
cut the England/Ireland leg of her journey short and head back to
Paris and home, armed with photographs and memories.
</P>
<P>
   What'll she do for an encore?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll think about that next year,'' Timothy said with a grin.
``I'll fall out of bed one morning and say, `How about this?' or
`How about that?' and off I'll go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
