<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4981 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BINLADEN-NETWORK-TEX     02-22 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BINLADEN-NETWORK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS SAY TERRORIST NETWORK LINKED TO NORTH TEXAS CITY
</HEADLINE>
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: Story is being filed in ``a'' general and
``i'' international categories)( 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KIMBERLY DURNAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Federal prosecutors are preparing their case
against an international terrorist network that they allege
stretches from East Africa to a mosque in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   It's a case against suspects whom officials believe are
responsible for killing more than 200 people in the bombings of two
U.S. embassies Africa on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely connection for the 290,000-population city halfway
between Fort Worth and Dallas began in October with the arrest of
38-year-old Wadih el Hage, who is being held without bail in a
high-security prison in New York City. He is charged with
conspiring with Osama bin Laden to bomb U.S. embassies in Nairobi,
Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   El Hage has pleaded not guilty, but he acknowledges that he
worked as personal secretary to bin Laden, the wealthy Islamic
militant whom U.S. prosecutors say ordered the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The few people who would talk about el Hage describe him as a
devout Muslim and family man who wouldn't have participated in
terrorism. Yet the people who are closest to him are reluctant to
talk and have made themselves unavailable to counter the
government's allegations. If convicted, el Hage could get the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Now federal investigators say that a second man from Arlington
is connected with the embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   During a pretrial hearing for el Hage, federal prosecutors in
New York connected Moataz Al-Hallak, imam of the Islamic Society of
Arlington mosque, to their case.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they have records showing that Al-Hallak has been
a longtime contact in the bin Laden organization al Qaeda, which
means ``the base'' in Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   The link came from el Hage's files found in a bin Laden charity
organization in Kenya. The documents included coded correspondence
that referred to Al-Hallak, Assistant U.S. Attorney Patrick
Fitzgerald said during the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moataz Al-Hallak has served as a contact between members of
the bin Laden organization,'' Fitzgerald said. ``This is a case
about murder and conspiracy to murder, not about religion. The fact
that he is an imam is irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about these allegations, Al-Hallak referred questions
to a spokesman at the mosque. Messages left at the mosque were not
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Mosque board member Hassan Shishakly said the imam was not
political with those who worship at the mosque.
</P>
<P>
   ``The imam doesn't talk that much,'' Shishakly said. ``He just
encourages us to be pious people. I never heard any speech to go
fight or to do something bad, just to help your family and your
neighbor. That's all we have heard from him.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a high-profile case that brings international intrigue
close to home.
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, el Hage and his wife, April Ray, led a quiet
existence in a two-bedroom apartment on Cooper Street near the
University of Texas at Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   El Hage is a Lebanese immigrant who became a citizen after
marrying Ray, a U.S. citizen. He worked at Lone Star Wheels &AMP; Tires
in Fort Worth, earning $1,600 a month to support his wife and their
seven children. The family worshiped regularly at the mosque on
Center Street in central Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said the family members kept to themselves, rarely
coming out of their apartment except to do laundry or take the
children to school or to the mosque.
</P>
<P>
   In a pretrial hearing this month in New York, el Hage's
court-appointed attorney, Bruce McIntyre, asked that his client be
released on bail so he could support his family.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre said el Hage is a well-respected member of his
community who serves on the mosque board and on the board of the
mosque's elementary school. He also protested el Hage's limited
contact with his family. He has only been allowed to call home
seven times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has never been charged with any crime of violence,''
McIntyre said during the hearing. ``He has been married to the same
woman for 14 or 15 years now. He has seven children. He is working
in a responsible job as a manager of the store. He is the sole
support for his family. He is active in his community. He has no
reason to flee.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the mosque said el Hage isn't being treated
fairly by federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Hage is just a regular person. He's just trying to make a
living,'' Shishakly said. ``It's not fair. He's an American citizen
and should have the right to talk to his family. His wife and kids
need him.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge denied bail after prosecutors painted a different
picture, one that portrayed el Hage as a key player in bin Laden's
terrorism against Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said el Hage acknowledged buying guns in Arizona for
Mahmud Abouhalima but never delivered them. Abouhalima was
convicted in the World Trade Center bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said El Hage lied to the FBI when he said he
traveled across Kenya to Lake Victoria, where hundreds died in a
ferry boat accident, including Abu Ubaidah al Banshiri, who was a
top military commander in al Qaeda. El Hage said he wasn't looking
for Banshiri but for another acquaintance, Adel Habib. Prosecutors
found papers belonging to el Hage that say Adel Habib is an alias
for Banshiri.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing also revealed allegations that el Hage was
intimately associated with Fazul Abdullah Mohammed, whom
prosecutors say is the principal person who organized the bombing
in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked for Wadih el Hage, lived with Wadih el Hage, used
his phone, used his car, used his computer,'' Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also say el Hage lied to FBI agents and a grand jury
when he said he did not know Mahamed Sadiq Odeh. But Odeh, who was
also indicted in New York and charged with conspiracy in the
bombing, told the FBI that el Hage attended his wedding in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Hage's role in the organization was to be a front man who
established businesses, to move money, to engage in coded
correspondence, and a particular role of his was to lie,''
Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
