<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4984 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONTAMINATED-SUTURES-     02-22 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTAMINATED-SUTURES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTURES LINKED TO BAFFLING HEALTH PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dozens of Americans who had surgery in 1994
developed unusual, debilitating post-operative infections, some
later traced to a rapidly growing bacteria found in dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Because of inaction by federal regulators, the nationwide
outbreak has never been investigated. But the chief suspect in the
stubborn, aggressive infection that caused months or even years of
suffering appears to be the medical sutures used to stitch up
wounds.
</P>
<P>
   In case after case, according to court documents and U.S. Food
and Drug Administration records, patients got sick after their
surgeons used sutures sold by Ethicon Inc., a manufacturer whose
new, high-tech sterilization system had repeatedly malfunctioned a
few months before. The outbreak has affected about 100 people in
California, Connecticut, Oklahoma and other states.
</P>
<P>
   In a flurry of lawsuits and reports filed with the FDA, patients
and doctors contended that the illnesses were linked to sutures
contaminated with infectious bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Vigliotti of Orange, Conn., said her illness had struck
with ferocity six weeks after she underwent reconstructive surgery
following a mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so sick I was saying a Hail Mary,'' said Vigliotti, who
had to go back into surgery for removal of a breast implant and the
sutures.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up from surgery, they had me packed in ice _ my
temperature was up to 106,'' she said. ``One more day and a few
more hours, and I would have been dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethicon, a division of Johnson &AMP; Johnson of New Brunswick, N.J.,
has denied in legal documents that the sutures caused any outbreak
of infection.
</P>
<P>
   But federal records show that in September 1994, after prodding
by FDA inspectors, Ethicon issued a recall for 3.6 million packages
of its trademark Vicryl sutures, acknowledging that a new $50
million sterilizer at a San Angelo, Texas, factory had
malfunctioned repeatedly some five months before.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the recall, the FDA issued a warning letter to
Ethicon, faulting the company for continuing to sell sutures to
hospitals after the malfunctions were discovered, and for failing
to conduct a proper investigation of what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The specific violations noted in this letter ... may be
symptomatic of serious underlying problems,'' Dallas FDA Director
Douglas C. Payne wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Odenthal, Ethicon's director of communications, said the
sutures processed by the malfunctioning sterilizer had posed a very
low risk to patients.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, the company voluntarily decided to recall the
sutures, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patient safety was first and foremost our objective'' in all
the company's actions, she said. ``The fact that we initiated this
whole recall speaks to our interest in patient safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of the infection outbreak shows the haphazard way in
which investigations into public health problems like the outbreak
are begun, and the cloak of secrecy that can be draped over a
medical problem because of the threat of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta are
superbly equipped to unravel medical mysteries, and in 1981 the CDC
launched a massive investigation, including DNA testing, to find
the source of a similar infection outbreak that affected only six
patients in a single hospital in Texas, medical journals show.
</P>
<P>
   But the CDC has never investigated the cause of the larger 1994
outbreak nor sought to track down its victims, said Dr. Teresa
Smith, a CDC epidemiologist. The CDC has no power to investigate an
incident unless invited by another agency and no invitation ever
came, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the FDA made no move to call in the CDC because it
thought the sutures posed only a ``low or moderate'' risk to the
public, FDA spokeswoman Sharon Snider said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way the system ought to work, said Dr. Richard
Wenzel of the Medical College of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you identify a problem that has even potential for harm,
you should take a very active, proactive approach to it,'' said
Wenzel, a specialist in hospital-acquired infections.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, lawyers for infection victims contend that Ethicon
sought to keep the extent of the suture problem a secret and
resisted identifying potential victims.
</P>
<P>
   Ethicon denies seeking to keep the lid on the infections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that we were very responsive and cooperative
in all those legal proceedings,'' Odenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some infection victims said they had learned of the suture
problems only by happenstance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is quite likely that of those bazillions that went
out, those millions of packages, that many people got infections,''
said Philip Minter, the lawyer for Robert Beverage, a Mountain
View, Calif., man who said he had suffered from uncontrollable
infections after a shoulder operation.
</P>
<P>
   Ethicon is a $1.2 billion medical powerhouse that dominates the
sutures market in the United States. Founded after World War II by
Johnson &AMP; Johnson, Ethicon sells more than 80 percent of the
sutures used by physicians, dentists and veterinarians to bind up
surgical incisions and stitch wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The company's trademark Vicryl is a strong synthetic that
dissolves as a wound heals, eliminating the need for a doctor to
remove stitches after an operation.
</P>
<P>
   Ethicon makes suture components at plants in Georgia and Puerto
Rico. Needles are attached and packets assembled at an
1,800-employee factory in the west Texas town of San Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   A new sterilization system developed problems in early 1994. At
first, the sterilizer seemed to work _ lab tests on sample lots
showed that the Vicryl sutures were free of bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records and a report written by an Ethicon
scientist, the new system may have begun to fail as early as March
8. On April 2, according to scientist John Paulson's report, the
company found evidence of what it called an ``aseptic break'' _ a
breach of sterile conditions. Later lab tests indicated
intermittent failures.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Paulson wrote, Ethicon salvaged sutures from runs
where samples showed evidence of contamination. The company said it
resterilized them and shipped them to customers.
</P>
<P>
   When tests continued to show some sutures contaminated with
bacteria that included a form of staphylococcus, Ethicon couldn't
figure out why, Paulson later testified. And so, on May 23, it shut
the new sterilizer system down and resumed use of the older one.
</P>
<P>
   But Ethicon made no move to recall any of the sutures it had
sold. Nor did it warn its customers about the problems or potential
health risks to patients.
</P>
<P>
   The company has denied that it recklessly endangered surgical
patients. A recall wasn't necessary, Paulson later wrote to one
doctor who complained. The failures had been infrequent, and the
contamination was so slight that there was little chance anyone
would get sick.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he wrote, ``because surgical patients are always
monitored for signs of wound infection, we knew safeguards were in
place to protect the patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethicon began to change its mind about the need for a recall in
late July, when an FDA inspection team toured the Texas plant and
discovered that the new sterilizers had been shut down. The FDA
investigated, and on Aug. 17 it issued a warning letter to Ethicon,
charging that the company had violated federal safety rules by
continuing to ship Vicryl sutures after the malfunctions began.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, the FDA threatened the company with ``seizure,
injunction and/or civil penalties'' if it did not correct the
problems.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 6, Ethicon issued a recall of about 3.6 million packets
of Vicryl sutures that had been run through the new system five
months before. But in its recall notice, Ethicon said the sutures
posed only a ``remote possibility of serious health consequences.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
