<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4985 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-LAILA-ALI-ART-2TA     02-22 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LAILA-ALI-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAUGHTER OF MUHAMMAD ALI PLANS TO TAKE HER PLACE IN A BOXING
RING
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Laila Ali went to her father's Beverly Hills hotel
suite three weeks ago to get his blessing. She had decided she
wanted to box, to follow in his footsteps and perhaps one day earn
some six-figure purses. But Ms. Ali, 21 years old and her hands
already bearing the scars from her early work in the ring, did not
know how to begin, and so she sat down across from her famous
father and just blurted it out in one long stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Daddy,'' she said, recalling her conversation with her
father, ``I want to tell you I'm going into professional boxing,
and I love you, and I want your support, and I want to tell you
that even if I don't have your support, I'm going to do it
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali, his face an expressionless mask as the result of
Parkinson's disease, dropped his head and paused. ``But I don't
want you to get hurt,'' Ms. Ali said her father told her, his voice
barely above a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, I'm not going to get hurt,'' she reassured her father.
``I'm going to be fighting women, not men. And I have your
genetics.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali laughed. Then, he asked his youngest daughter among nine
children to stand up and show him her best pre-fight stare-down. He
told her to keep her hands up, and the two, father and daughter,
reluctant tutor and aspiring protege, pretended to throw jabs at
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be like Dad's son that he never had, and I don't
mean to sound rude,'' said Laila Ali, whose older brother has shown
no inclination to fight. ``I'm the only one who can do it. I've
always been a big healthy girl. I've always been aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's professional boxing is a sport struggling for stature.
While the number of women in boxing have increased greatly in
recent years, with women fighting in gyms across the country and
even on the undercards of some major prize fights, female
professional boxing is desperate for true stars but also concerned
that it not be turned into just a sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   And so the prospect of Laila Ali, a woman with a marketable name
and no proven skills, turning pro has infused the sport with a
sense of both promise and worry. If she is good, she could be a
godsend. If she is not, she could be a setback, perceived as the
product of a cynical stunt.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing talent, after all, is not a surefire inherited trait, and
because Ms. Ali has yet to throw her first professional punch, it
is impossible for anybody to say with confidence whether she will
be a star or a flop. The records of sons following famous fathers
into the ring is mixed at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is well aware of Laila, and everybody is waiting to
see what she is going to do,'' said Jackie Kallen, the former
commissioner of the International Female Boxing Association and now
the director of female boxing for Magic Johnson Productions. ``She
has the looks, the background, and if she has the skills, she will
be the whole package.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Laila's earning potential is going to be better than another
girl who just takes up the sport, because of who her father is,''
Ms. Kallen added. ``The marketing factor alone is going to set her
apart from everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ali, who does not yet have a promoter, does not apologize
about her potential advantage in appeal, and she is as interested
in the possible paydays her career may bring as in continuing her
father's legacy. That said, no one appears to begrudge Ms. Ali any
career jump-start she might enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Christy Martin, the top female boxer in the game, said Ms. Ali
could be a great bonus for the sport. Ms. Martin earns $100,000 to
$150,000 a bout, while female boxers at the start of their career
typically make about $200 a round.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she has to use her father's name, that's absolutely fine,''
Ms. Martin said. ``If you have a break, use it to its fullest. I'm
not going to be envious or jealous of anyone who uses what they
have to make it in the sport. She is Muhammad Ali's daughter, and
that's fine. If it were Muhammad Ali's son, he'd get the same
breaks as she would.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at some point, she's got to prove that she can fight,''
Ms. Martin said. ``People are really going to be waiting to see
that. It won't last long if she can't fight. It won't take many
fights, may be two or three, before people turn away.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5 feet 10 inches tall and 160 pounds, Laila Ali is
statuesque. She can be both petulant and playful, but there is no
hint of insincerity in her expressive eyes. If her boxing is a
publicity stunt, she is going to great lengths to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``She comes to the gym every night like clockwork,'' said
Richard Allen, the owner of the L.A. Boxing Gym where the
lightweight world champion, Shane Mosley, works out. ``She really
works hard. She wants to learn. And she's not a prima donna.''
</P>
<P>
   As a group of kick boxers smacked a row of heavy bags with their
feet, and other boxers, men and women, jumped rope and pounded the
speed bags, Ms. Ali sat in a corner of the expansive, two-story
L.A. Boxing Gym in downtown Los Angeles recently and talked about
her decision. For the past five months she has been coming here.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Ms. Ali's biggest opponent is a heavy bag, and she
admits she is a neophyte. She said she wants to box because it is
in her blood and she believes she has a natural appetite and
ability. Her trainer, Kevin Morgan, agrees. He thinks Ms. Ali, who
runs a beauty salon as her day job, will be ready for her first
professional bout in about six months. Her training until then will
include sparring and perhaps some simulated fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started out, we sparred,'' Morgan said. ``I
wanted to see what she was going to do when she got hit. If she
turned her back when she was hit, there wasn't anything I could do
with her. She turned, but then she came back with a punch. She's
fast, and she hits hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Laila Ali is one of two daughters Muhammad Ali had with his
second wife, Veronica. The two divorced when Laila was 7. She never
saw her father box in person, and she said she has few memories of
living under the same roof with him.
</P>
<P>
   But by boxing, Ms. Ali believes her father will gain a greater
appreciation for her as his child.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's naturally going to see himself in me,'' she said. ``I'm a
lot like my mother and a lot like my father. But for the first
time, I think he actually can see that this is my child.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Her determination to fight with or without his approval, she
said, only underscored that sense of recognition on her father's
part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad never listened to anybody,'' she said with a smile, ``so
what can he say?''
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, her father's approval is grudging, at best.
</P>
<P>
   A long-time friend of Muhammad Ali, who refused to be
identified, said he had once asked Ali what he would do if his
oldest son, Ibin Muhammad, who is now 25, wanted to box.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said first he would try everything he could to talk him out
of it and then he'd do everything he could to help him,'' the
friend said. ``I would think he's probably on that first stage with
Laila right now. He probably wants to see how she's going to look
in her first couple of bouts.''
</P>
<P>
   The friend also said that as of two years ago Ali had opposed
female boxing because it went against his Muslim beliefs. Ali also
was not keen on the decision of another daughter, Miriam, to be a
standup comedian. Lonnie Ali, the former champion's wife, said the
elder Ali had no comment on Laila's decision to box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't read anything into that,'' Lonnie Ali said of her
husband's lack of public comment. ``This is something that Laila
wants to do. It has nothing to do with Muhammad.''
</P>
<P>
   But Laila Ali said her father, while alarmed, was still allied
with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that it was a dirty business,'' Ms. Ali said. ``He
let me know it's a hard business, and he let me know that he
supported me. That was my main concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ali said that she and her sister, Hana, grew up in Malibu,
Calif., with their mother but that she was always trying to escape
her neighborhood's comforts. She said she had several street fights
growing up, mainly after venturing into tougher neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of those kids who was trying to get into the ghetto
when everyone else was trying to get out, because I wanted to
experience the other side,'' she said. ``When people find out
you're Muhammad Ali's daughter, they try to take advantage of you.
I never backed down from a fight. It's just natural for me.''
</P>
<P>
   She is convinced, then, that she can at least take a punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that I can get my eyes busted and my nose broken
no matter who I'm fighting,'' she said. ``Hopefully, it won't
happen. But if it does, it's just boxing. And if it bothers me that
much, I can get plastic surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of pain, then, does not deter her, nor does her
father's physical condition. While Ali has Parkinson's disease,
which has reduced his speech to a whisper and has given him
tremors, his daughter is convinced there is a direct link from his
fight career to his physical limitations. But she said she had no
intention of taking as much punishment as her father took.
</P>
<P>
   Much remains to be seen. Bridgett Riley, a featherweight whose
record is 7 wins and 2 losses with 7 knockouts and who expects to
fight on the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis card at Madison Square
Garden on March 13, works out in the same gym as Ms. Ali. Riley has
met Ms. Ali, but because they come to the gym at different times,
she has never seen Ms. Ali work out. But she worries about the
sport's standing, and hopes nothing, including Ms. Ali's fledgling
career, contributes to the sense that the sport is a circus act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already under a microscope,'' Riley said. ``People are
sitting back, waiting to pick us off. Hopefully, she's good. I
really hope she can fight and she can be taken serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Laila Ali believes that is a fair enough challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think I'm just trying to use my father's name,''
she said. ``That's why I'm going to let it all be seen when I get
in the ring. Right now it's just hype, because people don't know
whether I can box or not. But when I get into the ring, it's really
going to be a lot of hype when I'm knocking people out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
