<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4987 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-REFORM-BOS &LR;      02-22 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-REFORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDS OFF MEDICARE, AMERICANS SAY IN STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Congress poised to overhaul Medicare, Americans say they
generally like the national health insurance program for the
elderly and disabled, flawed though it may be, according to a study
jointly released Monday by the Kaiser Family Foundation and the
League of Women Voters.
</P>
<P>
   The message to Washington: tread carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Like Social Security, Medicare enjoys strong positive feelings
among Americans who see the program as a safety net for the
nation's 39 million elderly and disabled, according to the study.
The report included findings from focus groups held in July in nine
US cities, and discussions with 6,500 Americans in town hall-style
meetings in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study shows that people across generations, gender and
race really like and value Medicare,'' said Patricia Neuman, senior
policy analyst with Kaiser.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Americans understand that Medicare is in desperate need
of fiscal and programmatic changes if it is to remain robust in the
coming decades as soaring medical costs threaten to thrust the
program into insolvency as early as 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Washington lawmakers say they are set to tackle the problem this
year and have set up a 17-member bipartisan commission to recommend
sweeping changes to fix Medicare. The commission is expected to
present its report to Congress by March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kaiser and the League of Women Voters say they are
seeking to inject grass roots voices into the debate with their
report. Among the problems perceived by people interviewed :
excessive fraud and abuse by health care providers who receive over
$200 billion a year from Medicare and inefficient management of
program resources.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what they believed was wrong with Medicare, 48
percent of the 3,700 who responded to a questionnaire cited the
lack of prescription drug coverage, while 45 percent said fraud and
abuse by doctors and hospitals, and 29 percent said poor management
by the government. Respondents were allowed to cite more than one
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, however, were deeply ambivalent over how to resolve
the problems. While many supported expanded coverage for such
things as nursing homes, far fewer wanted to raise premiums or
taxes to pay for the added benefits. And while Americans believe
doctors and hospitals are overpaid, they worry that cutting
reimbursements could hurt the quality of and access to health care.
Americans were also divided over whether it was better to raise the
eligibility age from 65 to 67 years to save money, or whether to
lower the age to 62 in order to increase access to health care.
</P>
<P>
   One theme appeared to be consistent in the report: people want
Medicare to cover prescription drugs, even if it means paying more.
The finding is notable given that previous polls have indicated
that support for added benefits tends to melt when respondents are
confronted with the question of how to pay for the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more aware of the burden of prescription
spending,'' said Neuman. ``As medications become a more common form
of medical treatment and people pay more out of pocket, this issue
will become more prominent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
