<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES EXAMINE DECISION TO IMPOSE DEATH PENALTY IN TEXAS CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A public defender Monday urged the Supreme Court to
spare the life of a Texas murderer, arguing that the judge and jury
who condemned the man acted unconstitutionally in sentencing him to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Crooks, an assistant federal public defender in Fort
Worth, told the high court that U.S. District Judge Sam R. Cummings
of Lubbock should have told the jurors that Louis Jones Jr. would
be sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole if
they failed to vote unanimously for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, believing that Jones could be paroled in a matter of
years, voted to condemn him for the 1995 beating death of Air Force
Pvt. Tracie Joy McBride, Crooks argued. The attorney told the
justices he had affidavits from two jurors saying they would have
spared Jones' life if the judge had said life in prison without
parole was the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was tried in federal court because the killing fell under
the federal kidnapping statute. In Texas courts, jurors do not have
the option of sentencing a defendant to life without parole.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found Jones guilty of capital murder for kidnapping
McBride from a laundry room on the Goodfellow Air Force Base in San
Angelo, taking her to a remote location, beating her over the head
with a tire iron and leaving her body under a bridge in February
1995.
</P>
<P>
   In handing down its sentence in November 1995, the jury
considered the 19-year-old victim's youth, small size,
unfamiliarity with San Angelo and effect of her death on her
family.
</P>
<P>
   Crooks argued that this personal information about the victim
was ``vague'' and not relevant for the 12-member jury to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy U.S. Solicitor General Michael Dreeben, pressing the high
court to uphold the death sentence, said the judge was under no
obligation to tell jurors that Jones would remain in prison for the
rest of his life if they did not sentence him to death.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department lawyer also said the jury's consideration
of McBride's physical, emotional and familial characteristics was a
``harmless error'' and that the panel would have sentenced Jones to
death anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The high court, which is expected to render its decision by
July, appeared to be just as divided as the lawyers. Several
justices questioned whether the judge's instruction had any effect
on the jury and if the jurors were swayed by McBride's youth, small
size, naivete and family.
</P>
<P>
   In a blow to Crooks' argument on the jury instruction, Justice
Stephen G. Breyer said requiring judges to give complete
information to juries regarding sentencing might result in more
death penalties. If jurors know that a judge generally has wide
discretion in sentencing when a jury is deadlocked, they might feel
compelled to vote unanimously for death, lest the judge render a
relatively light punishment, Breyer added.
</P>
<P>
   But Crooks argued that judges have an obligation to tell jurors
all their sentencing options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Full disclosure of accurate information cannot be a bad thing
in death-penalty cases,'' Crooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg questioned whether the impact of a
victim's death on family members should be a special factor for
juries to consider in sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every victim is going to have a family,'' Ginsburg said,
noting that there are exceptions. ``Every victim is going to have a
personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter said ``you are really putting a thumb on
the scale'' in favor of the death penalty when the government
introduces emotional testimony from family members at the
sentencing phase.
</P>
<P>
   But Dreeben responded that the views of family members are
relevant in criminal cases. ``His crime caused harm, and this is
the harm that it caused,'' the attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
