<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTECTING THE BEAUTY THAT SURROUNDS US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hidden in valleys, ravines and small canyons
throughout the San Francisco Bay area are dozens of little creeks,
all of them riparian watersheds that once created a paradise for
fish, birds and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The first explorers from Russia, France and Spain described this
paradise in their diaries, unearthed by historian Malcolm Margolin,
describing the abundance in fantasy-like portrayals:
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not any country in the world which more abounds in
and game of every description,'' wrote French sea captain Jean Le
Perouse. Geese and ducks ``rise in a dense cloud with a noise like
that of a hurricane. (The land has) inexpressible fertility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never have seen game in such abundance,'' wrote Russian
explorer Otto von Kotebue. ``There is a superfluity of game.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the paradise were the streams and wetlands,
which provided habitat for beavers and otters, steelhead and
salmon, bobcat, mountain lions and wolves, quail, ducks and geese,
grizzly bears, elk and antelope.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's almost all gone.
</P>
<P>
   Most all of the streams have had their freshwater flows diverted
or channeled, polluted or trashed, with many turned into
near-lifeless trickles. What's left in the region are islands of
habitat at the 125 parks in the foothills, protected greenbelt and
man-made reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a chance that in the coming years at least a small
resemblance of that former paradise can be reclaimed. Small groups
of volunteers are working to restore several of the streams in the
Bay area that once defined the abundance of the region.
</P>
<P>
   The streams with restoration programs and volunteer groups
include, north to south: Adobe Creek in Petaluma, Napa River in
Napa, Lagunitas Creek in Fairfax, Wildcat Creek in the Richmond
hills, Redwood Creek in the Oakland hills, Alameda Creek in Niles
Canyon, San Francisquito Creek in Palo Alto, Pescadero Creek on the
San Mateo County coast, San Lorenzo River in Santa Cruz and Carmel
River near Monterey.
</P>
<P>
   How does a stream get destroyed? A classic example is in Marin
County, a region known for environmental awareness, where Lagunitas
Creek has been pillaged for its water to support urban growth and
mega-money real estate deals, regardless of the effect.
</P>
<P>
   Lagunitas Creek, also called Papermill Creek by some, starts as
a trickle on the north flank of Mount Tamalpais, then runs its way
through canyons and valleys for roughly 25 river miles to Tomales
Bay, picking up additional flow from dozens of small feeder creeks.
It was once the crown jewel of coastal streams, with bigger coho
(silver) salmon and steelhead than anywhere else in California: The
state record coho, 22 pounds, was caught here in 1959, and the
largest steelhead ever documented in the state, 30 pounds, was
caught here in 1906.
</P>
<P>
   Now the coho are nearly extinct on Lagunitas Creek and the
steelhead are an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Where did the fish go? It started when four dams
were built, creating Lagunitas Lake, Bon Tempe Lake, Alpine Lake
and Kent Lake, in addition to seasonal dams placed during summer to
divert water for private ranches. Suddenly the steelhead and salmon
were blocked from their spawning grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The water was then diverted to support dense urban growth in a
chain of towns that are virtually connected as one, Sausalito,
Marin City, Corte Madera, Mill Valley, Larkspur, Ross, San Anselmo,
Fairfax, San Rafael and others.
</P>
<P>
   As mitigation, the public gets access to the watershed lands for
hiking and biking. But even though there are now eight lakes in the
area, no boating of any kind is permitted at any of them, not even
floating around in a raft, an unbelievable rip-off, and there are
no fishery programs in place either, another rip-off, save for the
Department of Fish and Game dumping some dinker-size planter trout
in a few times a year in Bon Tempe, Phoenix and Lagunitas.
</P>
<P>
   How do you like the tradeoff for ruining the best steelhead
stream in the state? Lagunitas Creek is but one affidavit of the
nightmare that has occurred throughout the Bay area, area by area,
stream to stream.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you know somebody with a time machine, the clock cannot
be turned back, but conditions can be made a lot better if people
support preservation efforts and groups like the Greenbelt
Alliance, which seeks to protect open space.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it is growth that allows officials to trade off open
space, streams, lakes and wildlife resources without conscience to
the damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
