<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT HEARS FIRST CASE UNDER FEDERAL DEATH PENALTY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, La., Okla, Calif., Nev., Va.) (nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hearing its first case under the 1994 federal Death
Penalty Act, the Supreme Court on Monday began the process of
interpreting and applying the law that extended the death penalty
to more than 40 federal crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutionality of the law was not at issue in the appeal
by a retired Army Ranger, convicted and sentenced to death in 1995
for kidnapping a 19-year-old private from an Air Force base in
Texas and murdering her at his nearby home. But it was evident that
the justices found aspects of the statute confusing and
troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal dealt with two aspects of the case: whether the jury
received adequate instruction on procedures for arriving at its
sentence, and whether it was an error for the government, in the
sentencing phase of the trial, to introduce evidence of the
victim's youth, other personal characteristics and the impact of
the murder on her family.
</P>
<P>
   In upholding the death sentence for the retired Ranger, Louis
Jones Jr., the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeal, in New Orleans,
ruled last year that this evidence should not have been admitted,
but that the error was ``harmless'' in that the jury would have
sentenced Jones to death even without the sympathetic testimony
about his victim, Tracie Joy McBride.
</P>
<P>
   While the case is unlikely to produce a sweeping ruling, the
argument Monday marked the start of what is likely to be a long,
case-by-case process by which the court resolves the statute's
ambiguities and instructs the lower federal courts, which have gone
a generation without confronting a general federal death penalty,
on how the law should be carried out.
</P>
<P>
   The last federal execution was in 1963, and it has been 50 years
since the court decided a federal death penalty case. The cases in
the 1970s by which the justices established the current
constitutional framework for capital punishment all dealt with
state laws.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen people have been sentenced to death under the 1994 law,
including Timothy J. McVeigh, who was convicted of murder and
conspiracy in the bombing of the federal building in Oklahoma City
in 1995 that killed 168 people. McVeigh is on death row for killing
eight federal law enforcement agents.
</P>
<P>
   Five additional federal death row inmates were sentenced under a
narrower 1988 law, which authorized the death penalty for so-called
drug kingpins. Prosecutions are now under way in 154 cases that
could lead to imposition of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   One death penalty expert who has studied the new law, Professor
Rory K. Little of Hastings College of Law in San Francisco, said in
an interview Monday that the case before the court was ``a
message-sending case for the broad question of how the law will be
administered.'' He said the justices were likely to want to set
clear guidelines for the lower courts in this case, Jones vs. U.S.,
No. 97-9361, so that the court could avoid a flood of federal death
penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   One obvious ambiguity that was unresolved by the argument Monday
is what happens if the jury cannot agree on a sentence with the
unanimity that the law requires. The statute says that if the jury
can agree on neither a death sentence nor on life without parole,
the judge will determine ``some other lesser sentence'' as the law
permits. But for a kidnapping that results in murder, as in this
case, the law permits no other option; following a conviction, life
without parole is the minimum sentence allowable.
</P>
<P>
   At the sentencing phase of Jones' trial, the judge refused a
defense request to instruct the jury that if they could not agree
on a sentence, the judge would impose a sentence of life without
parole. In the absence of such an instruction, the defense
maintained, the jury might have the misimpression that a deadlock
could open the door to the defendant's eventual release, and thus
might drive wavering jurors to eliminate that prospect by voting
for a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   At the argument Monday, some justices questioned that
assumption. Might not a split jury avoid that outcome by simply
agreeing on life without parole? Justice Antonin Scalia asked
Timothy Crooks, a federal public defender from Fort Worth who
represented Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Crooks replied that in such a case, the jury deliberations
become ``a game of chicken,'' where ``those most stubborn will
prevail.'' The randomness of such an outcome is what the court's
modern death penalty cases have sought to avoid, he said, adding
that in any event, ``full disclosure in a sentencing hearing cannot
be a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael R. Dreeben, a deputy solicitor general representing the
government, said the jury instruction proposed by the defense had
been properly excluded. He described the instruction as ``an open
invitation to any individual member of the jury to hang the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Dreeben said, the government took the position that
a deadlocked sentencing jury did not necessarily result in the
judge making the sentencing decision. Rather, the prosecutor could
request a new jury at this phase, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After several justices questioned the basis for the government's
view, Dreeben acknowledged that the law was unclear and to some
extent internally contradictory on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The government's position that the evidence of the victim's
personal qualities was properly introduced as a sentencing
consideration also drew fire from the court because at an earlier
phase of the case, the government had appeared to concede that the
evidence was invalid.
</P>
<P>
   The court met Monday for the first time since the end of the
Senate impeachment trial 10 days ago, an event to which Chief
Justice William Rehnquist made no allusion as he began the
morning's proceedings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The following were among other developments Monday:
</P>
<P>
   _ Without comment, the court refused to hear a challenge to a
1997 Virginia law that requires girls under 18 to inform at least
one parent before obtaining an abortion. Among several issues in
the case, Planned Parenthood vs. Camblos, No. 98-984, the
challengers attacked the adequacy of provisions for a girl to go
before a judge and obtain a waiver of the notice requirement. The
4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Richmond, upheld the law last
year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Accepting an appeal from a convicted murderer in Nevada, the
court agreed to decide whether a state inmate forfeits the right to
be heard by a federal judge on constitutional issues that were not
included in an initial, abandoned, petition for a writ of habeas
corpus. Antonio Slack, convicted of committing a murder when he was
19, withdrew his first petition to pursue an appeal in the Nevada
courts, and then sought, this time with the help of an appointed
lawyer, to file a new, more complete petition. But the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, in San Francisco, barred the additional
issues. The case is Slack vs. McDaniel, No. 98-6322.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
