<SLUG> BC-DOMENICI-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE'S CHIEF BUDGET NEGOTIATOR ASSAILS CLINTON PLAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate's chief budget negotiator Monday
dismissed President Clinton's plan to use budget surpluses to help
preserve Social Security as an accounting gimmick that would do
little to shore up the program and rob Americans of much-deserved
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   At a luncheon with reporters, Senate Budget Committee Chairman
Pete Domenici said the president's plan to funnel surplus money
into the Social Security Trust Fund and then invest it in
government bonds would simply fill the program's coffers with
``IOUs'' that would eventually have to be repaid.
</P>
<P>
   He called it a blueprint for ``borrowing our way right into
solvency.'' When coupled with the new spending increases outlined
in Clinton's 2000 budget, the New Mexico Republican said it would
leave almost no room for major tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody advising the president is scared to death that there
might be a real surplus left over that could be used to cut
taxes,'' Domenici said. ``I would say the president has gone
through huge hoops to avoid leaving any money around for tax
cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the Republicans have staked out Social Security as a
major legislative battleground for this year. While both sides
advocate using some of the surplus to help extend the retirement
program well into the next century, they disagree over how best to
use it.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides disagree on whether to allow investments in the
stock market and on whether to use a large portion of the surplus
to help pay for tax cuts, which Domenici said would be a priority
for Republicans in budget negotiations with the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that some estimates show a budget surplus over the next
10 years of about $787 billion, Domenici said the black ink
``represents a rare opportunity for some kind of tax reform.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he favors phased-in, ``across-the-board tax cuts'' that
could amount to 10 percent or more. Some Republicans, however,
support targeted tax reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici also announced Monday that he hopes to propose a 40
percent increase in education spending over the next five years.
His increase would be paid for primarily by cutting other federal
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to put some real money where our rhetoric has
been,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici said Republicans would also like to provide the states
with more ``direct funding,'' which would eliminate many of the
Washington requirements on how the money should be spent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
