<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CERVICAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY URGES CHANGE IN TREATMENT FOR CERVICAL CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Cancer Institute urged doctors around the world
Monday to change the way they treat cervical cancer on the basis of
surprising results from five separate studies.
</P>
<P>
   Combining chemotherapy with radiation reduces a woman's chances
of dying from advanced cervical cancer by as much as 50 percent
compared to the standard, radiation-only treatment, the federal
agency said in an advisory mailed to thousands of cancer
specialists _ only the fourth such alert the cancer institute has
ever issued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really surprised. It's rare to see such a dramatic
difference,'' said Dr. Mitchell Morris of M.D. Anderson Cancer
Center in Houston, who directed one of the studies. ``This is the
first major change in the treatment of cervical cancer in 40
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancer of the cervix _ the neck of the womb _ strikes 13,000 to
16,000 American women annually and kills about 5,000, numbers
dwarfed by the annual breast cancer toll of 175,000 new cases and
44,000 deaths. Pap screening has made cervical cancer one of the
most preventable and curable malignancies since the test was
introduced in the 1950s. But 40 percent of all new cases have
already spread beyond the cervix at the time of diagnosis, sharply
reducing the chances of cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early cervical cancer causes very few signs or symptoms,''
Morris said. ``By the time it causes pain it's usually very far
advanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Rose of University Hospitals in Cleveland, who led one
of the new studies, said two-thirds of women with cervical cancer
have not had regular Pap smears. ``They're so busy taking care of
their families they don't take care of themselves,'' he said. ``Or
they lose their health insurance and just stop going to the
doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem I see are women in their 50s or 60s who
had not had a Pap smear since they last delivered their last child
_ a period of up to 15 years,'' said Dr. Harrison G. Ball of UMass
Memorial Health Care in Worcester, Mass., who participated in one
study. ``They just aren't seeing a doctor, or their family
physician doesn't do Pap smears.''
</P>
<P>
   The five studies, which involved a total of 1,700 women, show
that combining standard radiation treatments with a platinum-based
chemotherapy drug sharply improves a woman's chances of beating
advanced cervical cancer. Standard therapy for early-stage cervical
cancer is surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Journal of Medicine, which will publish three of
the studies in its April 15 edition, took the unusual step Monday
of releasing the articles early on its web site, citing their
``implications for public health.''
</P>
<P>
   Another study will be published this spring in the Journal of
Clinical Oncology while a fifth will be presented March 22 at a
meeting of the Society of Gynecological Oncologists in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The National Cancer Institute is mailing notices of the findings
to members of that group, the American Society for Clinical
Oncology, and two other specialty groups here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward Trimble of the Cancer Institute said the agency hopes
doctors will embrace the new findings immediately to give women
their best shot at survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The treatment we're recommending is not terribly complex or
unusual,'' Trimble said in an interview. ``Potentially they could
be used tomorrow in any hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Combining radiation and chemotherapy has a greater effect on
cervical cancer cells than either would be expected to have alone.
This synergistic effect may result from chemotherapy making cells
more vulnerable to radiation, or vice versa. ``We think the drugs
prevent the cell from repairing the DNA damage caused by
radiation,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   In studies lasting three to eight years, researchers found that
combining radiotherapy with a drug called cisplatin _ with or
without other drugs _ reduced women's chances of death by 30 to 50
percent compared to those who were randomly assigned to standard
radiotherapy alone.
</P>
<P>
   This improvement is called relative risk reduction. In absolute
terms, it meant that combination therapy improved a woman's chances
of being alive three years after diagnosis from 47 percent to 65
percent in one study. In other studies, women on combination
treatment gained about 10 percentage points in their chances of
survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's reasonable to say that for women with advanced cervical
cancer, chemotherapy with radiation should be viewed as the new
standard of therapy,'' said Dr. Ross Berkowitz, co-director of the
Gillette Center for Women's Cancers at Dana Farber Cancer Institute
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Berkowitz was on a 1996 federal consensus panel that found no
convincing evidence that combining chemotherapy with radiation
improved cervical cancer survival rates. He said the new studies,
taken together, were large enough and long enough to demonstrate a
significant difference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
