<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UKRAINE-U.S.-ART-660&AMP;     02-22 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UKRAINE-U.S.-ART-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER UKRAINE PRIME MINISTER, ACCUSED OF CORRUPTION, DETAINED BY
U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Ukraine's former prime minister, the target of
corruption inquiries there and in Switzerland, is being held by
American Customs agents after he tried to enter the United States
on a tourist visa, American officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Federal immigration agents detained the former prime minister,
Pavlo Lazarenko, at Kennedy Airport in New York on Friday
afternoon, said the chief spokesman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, Russell Bergeron. Both American and
Ukrainian officials had previously refused to comment on a report
from Moscow that he had been detained.
</P>
<P>
   Bergeron said Lazarenko held an expired diplomatic passport and
a valid tourist visa. But he was detained after immigration
officials interviewed him and concluded that he had not come to the
country merely for a casual visit, as the rules governing visitor
visas require.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss officials arrested Lazarenko in December as he crossed the
Swiss border for what he said then was a meeting on legal matters.
They later charged him with laundering millions of dollars through
numbered bank accounts there.
</P>
<P>
   He left Ukraine on Wednesday, two days before the nation's
Parliament voted to strip him of the immunity that protects all
elected Ukrainian officials against criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   He told Parliament in a written statement last week that he was
going to Greece for treatment of a stress-related heart ailment.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Monday whether Lazarenko arrived in New York on
a flight from Greece or from some other country. His family
apparently was not traveling with him.
</P>
<P>
   By many accounts, all of which he denies, he made millions of
dollars in the last decade through schemes ranging from the sale of
overpriced goods to the government to a complex deal involving the
granting of monopoly franchises to natural-gas suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   President Leonid Kuchma appointed Lazarenko prime minister in
mid-1996 but removed him less than a year later as rumors and news
reports of corruption began to taint his administration. Lazarenko
later took a seat in Parliament, and the two men have since become
bitter political enemies as well as opponents in this year's
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, after Parliament withdrew Lazarenko's immunity,
Ukrainian prosecutors issued a warrant for his arrest on charges of
embezzlement and misuse of government funds.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen to Lazarenko next is anything but clear.
</P>
<P>
   American immigration officials are reviewing the circumstances
of his attempt to enter the United States to determine whether he
is entitled to entry or should be expelled. That process,
``expedited removal,'' is supposed to be rapid but could easily be
tied up by legal challenges, particularly if he decides to seek
asylum in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarenko has contended repeatedly that he is a victim of
political persecution by the Kuchma government and that the
criminal investigations in Switzerland and Ukraine are part of a
plot to destroy him.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States ultimately decides to expel Lazarenko, he
has a number of options. Although Ukraine could seek his return for
prosecution, it is unlikely to succeed because the United States
and Ukraine do not have an extradition treaty. He cannot be
repatriated against his will unless he is legally expelled from the
United States and no other country will agree to accept him.
</P>
<P>
   That seems unlikely. Lazarenko also holds a Panamanian passport,
for instance, although he has denied that he has citizenship there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should not be presumed that if he's found to be removable,
he will be sent to Ukraine,'' Bergeron said. ``It's far too early
in the process to judge what the final outcome of this might be.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Switzerland do have an extradition treaty,
but it is not clear whether the Swiss either are seeking his return
or plan to. The Swiss hold $3 million in bail as insurance for
Lazarenko's return for a trial.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Ukraine, Lazarenko is politically unpopular, but he has
gained a sort of celebrity for his supposed wealth and his
undeniably brazen nature. He is given to expensive suits and has a
large private office studded with photographs of his visits with
world leaders. A large blowup of a handshake with President Clinton
occupies the most prominent spot.
</P>
<P>
   But going by the financial disclosure statements he filed while
prime minister, he is an ascetic, earning only about $2,600 in
1997, driving a Lada, an inexpensive Russian car, and owning no
property beyond a small walk-up apartment.
</P>
</TEXT>
