<HEADLINE>
GETTING IT AND SPENDING IT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's on the horizon for the next 1,000 years, says W, a
magazine for fortunate fortune-tellers, is having a lot of money
and spending a lot of money. ``Years ago, when someone was a
millionaire, that actually meant something,'' said  &UR; Alexis de &LR; 
 &UR; Rede &LR; , who is described as a Parisian socialite. ``Now, we're
getting quite used to the idea of billionaires.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 190 billionaires in the world in 1988; 10 years
later, there were 450. ``The avalanche of billionaires on American
society has not yet had the time, in their frenetic acquisition of
wealth, to spend anything,'' said  &UR; John Loring &LR;  of Tiffany &AMP; Co.
``But their children will in the next 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Carla Fendi &LR; , head of the Italian maker of luxury products,
seemed optimistic: ``As our society becomes more global, buying
tendencies will grow.'' Novelist  &UR; Tom Wolfe &LR;  put it another way:
``I think huge fortunes will be much more common in the next 25
years. People will spend until they drop.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIMBAUGH THE LESSER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rush Limbaugh &LR;  has lost 80 pounds, and  &UR; Al Franken &LR; , who wrote
``Rush Limbaugh Is a Big Fat Idiot and Other Observations,'' is
taking credit for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started losing the weight as soon as the title of my book
came out,'' said Franken. ``I personally believe that I halted his
slide into food-assisted suicide. And the worst part of it is he
hasn't thanked me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPILLING THE BEANS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In an astonishing breach of confidentiality,  &UR; Jeremy Gursey &LR;  of
Mocha Kiss Coffee Co., which specializes in serving TV and film
crews, revealed to Los Angeles magazine that:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Harrison Ford &LR;  drinks double espresso;  &UR; Tom Cruise &LR;  drinks
sugar-free ice-blended mocha;  &UR; Calista Flockhart &LR;  drinks
ice-blended vanilla;  &UR; Michael Keaton &LR;  drinks double cappuccino with
one Equal; and  &UR; Julianna Margulies &LR;  drinks decaf sugar-free mocha
with soy milk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ One of the heartbreaking issues being debated in the divorce
battle between  &UR; Ronald Perelman &LR;  and ex-wife  &UR; Patricia &LR; 
 &UR; Duff &LR; , as reported in the Wall Street Journal: ``Whether security
guards should use the nanny's bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A survey conducted by the American Animal Hospital Association
has found that 11 percent of cat-owning Americans have ``ended a
personal or romantic relationship because of their pet.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Hugh Hefner &LR; 's three current girlfriends, reports the New
York Times, are  &UR; Brande Roderick &LR; , 24, and the identical twins
 &UR; Mandy &LR;  and  &UR; Sandy Bentley &LR; , 20. This means there's still room for a
Candy, Randy or Andy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sunday People, a British magazine, says  &UR; Prince Edward &LR;  wants
to ban the BBC and ITV from covering his wedding on June 19,
instead employing his own production company, which would sell the
footage to British and foreign stations.  &UR; The Queen &LR;  is not said to
be pleased with such a plan, which would net her son's company big
bucks (or heavy pounds).
</P>
<P>
   _ Laura Ashley Holdings, which retails home furnishings, has
made  &UR; Pat Robertson &LR; , founder of the Christian Coalition, a member
of its board. The Advocate quotes the company's announcement of
this appointment, which explained that Robertson, a ``noted media
pioneer, educator, philanthropist and religious broadcaster,''
understands the consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   _ To the relief of linguistic nitpickers, P.O.V. answers the
question at last: Is  &UR; Chico  &LR; (ne Leonard)  &UR; Marx &LR; 's first name
pronounced ``Cheek-o'' or ``Chick-o''? The latter, because he was
given the name for chasing ``chicks.''
</P>
<P>
   _ For those just too tired to clap, a $49 voice-activated light
switch described in the latest issue of Wired allows the user's
voice, saying a simple ``Lights,'' to turn the lights on in a room.
``Lights low'' turns them on dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
