<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-MONUMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON WASHINGTON'S BIRTHDAY, MONUMENT'S DOORS REOPEN 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hundreds of people lined up Monday, George
Washington's birthday, to visit the Washington Monument, which had
been closed since Oct. 5 while a scaffold was constructed around it
to permit workers to inspect and repair its marble skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the middle of the renovation, it is nice that they let
people in,'' said Shoshana Deitch, a tourist from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Deitch and the others who stood in line in a brisk, chilly
wind for 25 minutes were lucky that the monument was open at all,
because repairs are running a bit behind schedule. The National
Park Service is working to finish the project by the Fourth of July
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The park service will shut the monument again later this year to
begin the last phase of the work: renovations of the observation
deck at the 500-foot level and an area with a souvenir shop at 490
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Miner, an employee in the workers compensation office in
Salem, Ore., who was waiting in line as her 7-year-old son,
Matthew, looked for the mitten he had just lost (he found it in his
jacket sleeve), admired the shroud of metal and fabric around the
monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unique, actually,'' Ms. Miner said. ``It looks like a
cellophane bag over it.''
</P>
<P>
   The covering was designed by the architect Michael Graves. It
has the outline of oversized marble blocks printed on it, with bold
stripes mimicking the mortar joints of the monument. It runs the
full height of the 555-foot obelisk.
</P>
<P>
   Earle Kittleman, a spokesman for the National Park Service, said
that the cost of restoration was estimated at $9.4 million, of
which the Target store chain and its corporate partners have
donated $5 million. The restoration is the most extensive since the
monument opened in 1888.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 36,000 pieces of marble,'' Kittleman said, ``and
each one will be examined for damage and repaired on the spot if
that is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The need for repairs is evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten so bad that water gets through the joints and into
the interior,'' Kittleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the work so far has been the replacement of the
machinery that runs the elevator, although the elevator has not
been speeded up and still takes 65 seconds to make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   During the ascent and descent of the elevator, workers could be
seen restoring the state and foreign plaques that are cemented into
the interior walls. The staircase that allows the plaques to be
viewed has been closed for the renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Vaandrager, a grain elevator worker from Sheldon, Iowa,
took the people elevator to the observation deck and pointed his
camera through the windows but without success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to take a picture because of the scaffolding,''
Vaandrager said, ``but we're happy just to get a chance to get up
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
