<HEADER>
A5042 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      02-22 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS, BRUINS SEEK PATH BACK TO WINNING WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He has called for reinforcements in the person of
sports psychologist Fred Neff. He has raised his voice for emphasis
during practice. He cranked up the intensity of the workout Monday
to the point where the Ristuccia Center in suburban Wilmingfton
looked like a cross between the first day of training camp, with
scuffles breaking out between veterans, and the start of the
playoffs, when everyone is focused and all business.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Pat Burns is pulling out all the stops in an effort
to right his listing ship of a team, and he hopes his players will
do the same.
</P>
<P>
   There are 26 contests left in the regular season, and if the
Bruins don't play better, that will be the end of their year. As of
Monday, they were in ninth place in the Eastern Conference, 2
points out of the last playoff spot. Of their remaining games, 22
are against Eastern opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Boston ended a three-game losing streak with a 6-3 victory over
the awful Blackhawks in Chicago Sunday, but Burns's attitude was,
in a nutshell, ``big deal.'' Tuesday's opponent _ the Ottawa
Senators, whom the Bruins host at the FleetCenter _ is among the
best teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team we beat (Sunday) is not a team right now that you're
going to be able to test your (team against),'' said Burns. ``We
can feel good about the win but we can't feel that good about it.
You have to be able to beat teams in your conference and your
division to be able to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning gives us a little boost. But the Ottawa Senators
aren't the Chicago Blackhawks. They're in control, they're a
well-coached, disciplined team. They have a lot of talent and we
have to give them a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Ottawa (last Thursday), we gave them a game, we came out of
there with nothing. We probably had a couple of more scoring
chances than they did, but the fact is, they scored two goals and
we scored none.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said if his team wasn't convinced by their last meeting,
they should be convinced by something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against the Flyers, who are an excellent hockey club, (the
Senators) beat the Flyers, 4-1, in their own building,'' said
Burns. ``So that tells us you'd better tie your skates and be
prepared to play a hockey game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins appeared to break out of their offensive rut with six
goals against the lowly Hawks, but Burns didn't want to hear that.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it means diddly squat,'' he said. ``That's exactly
what it means for me. Their goaltender wasn't very good. I think
(Jocelyn) Thibault struggled. It's a big 2 points and it's all nice
and fine up on the board. Let's see how we fare against excellent
goaltending and a good defensive team.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's workout was one of the most spirited in recent memory.
During one set of drills, defenseman Don Sweeney and right wing Rob
DiMaio starting whaling away at each other when the contact got a
little too intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was nothing,'' said DiMaio. ``It was just game-situation
stuff, three-on-three and five-on-fives, and sometimes hacks and
whacks happen and guys respond and retaliate. It was nothing, it
was just part of practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Byron Dafoe said he was thrilled to see the increase in
intensity among the team. He watched in horror Sunday as the Bruins
nearly blew a 4-0 lead, allowing the Blackhawks to pull within 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe went in for the third period, relieving Rob Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time I've seen it from the bench,'' he said.
``You can see guys on the bench, their heads start to sink, the
bitching starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we were up a goal going into the third. If
you had said we'd be up a goal going into the third at the start of
the game, I think everyone would be happy, but no one was happy at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point of the year, it's a mental game. It's all
upstairs. We have to get into that playoff atmosphere, Otherwise,
we're not going to see it. I thought it was a very good practice.
It was very high-tempo. Guys are starting to get really serious.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a frailty about his squad that Burns is particularly
worried about, it's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practice doesn't mean nothing at this time of year,'' he said.
``Players are in fine physical condition. What the players realize
now is how well your head is, how well your confidence level is.
We've been feeling sorry for ourselves because of injuries. But I
like this team. When this team wants to play as a team, we can beat
anybody on any given night when we've all got our heads together
and we're playing hard. If we take a run at every single game, we
have a damn good chance to be in there.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes it has finally sunk in. It's desperation time. Not next
week, but now. The players must get the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't, I've got the sports psychologist in this
morning, maybe he can get it to them because I think about it every
single minute,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Heinze went on the ice after the workout, skating for the
first time in several days. He has a hip flexor strain and is
listed as day to day.
</P>
</TEXT>
