<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WALTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEARS, AND MORE, FROM LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, Monica Lewinsky does shed tears in her interview with
Barbara Walters, as countless other newsmakers and celebrities have
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   But Walters maintained Monday that Lewinsky travels the full
gamut of emotions during her first television interview, reliving
her relationship with President Clinton and the year of scandal
that followed in a conversation that Walters claimed has ``a sense
of history about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC is opening up two hours of prime time for the interview on
March 3, hoping for blockbuster ratings on the last day of the
``sweeps'' period.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when she is emotional, and where she, I think,
is teary,'' Walters said Monday during a telephone conference with
TV writers. ``This is not a sobbing interview; this is not an
interview in which every 10 minutes she's crying. But this is very
painful material for her.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does Lewinsky talk about? According to Walters, the
former White House intern describes ``her torment, her terrible
fright'' at being the center of a sex scandal that became worldwide
news, and at being the object of ``endless ridicule.'' Walters said
Lewinsky describes her past and present feelings about President
Clinton, offering ``some insights into him you may not have heard
before.'' (Walters said Lewinsky answered her question on whether
she is still in love with Clinton, but declined to say what that
answer was.) Lewinsky also gives her opinions of Hillary Clinton
and independent prosecutor Kenneth W. Starr, though again Walters
declined to be specific.
</P>
<P>
   And though Walters said it is ``not a prurient interview,''
Lewinsky does discuss the infamous blue dress in response to a
question that, according to Walters, was prompted by e-mailed
queries from viewers of her morning talk show, ``The View.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You understand the history of the relationship really from day
one, the day of that famous thong,'' said Walters. ``You see the
president in a way that I'm not sure you have been able to see him
before, because she has not characterized him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You understand the role of her mother; you understand how she
feels about Ken Starr,'' she added. ``And you understand what she
went through this past year more graphically. The emotions of this
past year, from the time she finds out she is on that list, are
simply staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the one-hour conference Monday, Walters treaded
carefully the thin line between hype and full disclosure. She did
say, however, that she was surprised by Lewinsky's admission that
the most painful question grand jurors asked her was why she had
become involved with married men.
</P>
<P>
   Walters conceded that she wasn't always able to keep her
incredulity at bay as the 24-year-old told the tale of her
dalliance with the president. ``There were times when I would say,
`But Monica, how could you?' '' said Walters.
</P>
<P>
   Walters's interview with Lewinsky took place on Saturday, amid
much secrecy, in the same New York studio where ``20/20'' is taped.
The two-hour interview will air March 3 from 9 to 11 p.m. as a
``special edition'' of ``20/20 Wednesday.'' ABC News president
David Westin said that, under an agreement with Lewinsky, the
interview will air only once, though he said excerpts may be used
on ABC newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   The interview had been delayed because Lewinsky's immunity
agreement with Starr prohibited her from talking publicly about her
affair with Clinton until Starr gave the green light. Even when he
did so after Clinton's impeachment trial ended in acquittal, Starr
insisted on certain conditions: that Lewinsky have an attorney
present during the interview, that she not contradict the evidence
she gave to the grand jury, that she not, in Westin's words,
``characterize the conduct'' of Starr's office. That prohibited
Walters from asking questions about last Jan. 16, the day Starr's
lawyers first questioned Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that, in her quest for a new image or
bestsellerdom, Lewinsky has chosen to tell her story first to
Walters, the one TV personality who gives her the best shot at
attaining both goals.
</P>
<P>
   A weepy, confessional interview with Walters has become
virtually de rigueur for celebrities bent on redemption or
newsmakers intent on spin control. Spilling the beans to Walters _
whose subjects include Fidel Castro, Anwar Sadat, Colin Powell, and
innumerable movie stars _ has a cachet Lewinsky could not have
achieved by accepting the offers she got from Roseanne and Oprah
Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``She felt the most important thing for the rest of her life was
to establish credibility, and she felt she could do it with ABC and
me,'' said Walters.
</P>
<P>
   The interview with Walters will kick off the marketing of
Monica, an effort that will gather steam on March 4, when a book
written by Andrew Morton (with Lewinsky's cooperation) will be
published and a British TV interview of her will air. Westin said
ABC's deal with Lewinsky stipulated that the network's interview
would precede the book and the British interview.
</P>
<P>
   Walters declined to say whether she would have been interested
in an interview with Juanita Broaddrick, an Arkansas woman who says
that Clinton sexually assaulted her 21 years ago, and who has
reportedly been interviewed by NBC. Westin said an interview with
Broaddrick was ``raised as a possibility'' for ABC News, but ``we
declined.'' ``It's a very difficult subject, it's inflammatory
potentially, it is more than 20 years old, and there have been
conflicting reports about it from the parties involved,'' said
Westin.
</P>
<P>
   Though she insisted the Lewinsky interview was not ``a puff
piece,'' Walters is clearly sympathetic to Lewinsky. ``She is open,
she is expressive, she is sometimes very touching,'' she said,
conceding that ``sometimes, when she describes herself, you realize
she can be very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Walters said she believes the interview ``puts an exclamation
point, finally, to this year'' of scandal, though she made one
exception. ``Unless the president sits down and does the same
interview, and we'd be happy to do that,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
