</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black programming lives beyond February
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The cruelties of February are not limited to sweeps
scheduling, when the networks throw hype, specials and new episodes
against one another. February is also Black History Month, time for
television to suddenly, and somewhat ostentatiously, get on the
bus.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night for example, TBS ran Ted Turner's annual Trumpet
Awards ceremony celebrating African-American accomplishment, with
Bryant Gumbel, Jessye Norman and Smokey Robinson among those
honored. Meanwhile, another Turner channel, TNT, was premiering
``Passing Glory,'' a new movie about black-white relations starring
Andre Braugher. The local UPN affiliate reran Spike Lee's ``Malcolm
X,'' and Showtime had a new drama with Sidney Poitier, ``Free of
Eden.''
</P>
<P>
   Come March, such programming won't dwindle away to nothing, but
you're unlikley to see four such high-profile shows dedicated to
African-Americans opposite one another on the same night.
</P>
<P>
   But some shows built around African-Americans will go on, such
as ``The PJs'' (8:30 tonight on Fox) and ``The Hughleys'' (8:30
tonight on ABC).
</P>
<P>
   ``The PJs'' is that weird Foam-ation show from Eddie Murphy, who
stars as the voice of Thurgood Stubbs, a mean ol' superintendent in
the housing project. Even after six weeks or so on the air, it
still has a startling, disorienting look along with some enjoyable
risks in its content (which also make it iffy for younger
children).
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Thurgood is suffering from high blood pressure, but not
quite high enough to qualify for an experimental drug. So he sets
about trying to raise his blood pressure, salting his fried pork
chop sandwiches more than usual and deliberately seeking out
frustration and aggravation. (The drug, when he gets it, also has
the side effect of acting like Viagra.) Joking about a middle-aged
black man's keeling over from hypertension is far from politically
correct, but ``PJs'' pulls it off by stopping just short of
cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hughleys,'' on the other hand, could use a little dash of
mean-spiritedness now and then. Stand-up comic D.L. Hughley has
some vinegar to him, but nowhere to spray it; his wife, Yvonne, and
neighbors are just so darn nice they don't deserve his rants.
</P>
<P>
   So finally, in a two-parter that concludes next week, Hughley
gets a foil who deserves to be squashed: Sherman Hemsley, guest
starring as Yvonne's dad. Twelve years ago, when Darryl and Yvonne
got married, dad almost ruined the wedding, and when the couple
plans to renew their vows in a bigger-bucks ceremony, dad comes
back to sow more discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a sour, mean little troll,'' Hughley spouts off to
Helmsley, who is. ``If the bridge fits, you should live under it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Helmsley's character and Thurgood are so similar in their nasty
bluster, you could put on a blindfold and click back and forth, and
you'd have trouble telling who's who.)
</P>
<P>
   Grades: ``PJs'': B
</P>
<P>
   ``Hughleys'': B-
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
