<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, Feb. 23. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY-EXPORTS (Washington) _ Details on a pending decision
by the Clinton Administration about exports of technology. This
story is competitive; the nature of the exports will be disclosed
when the story moves. (We plan to move the story by 9:30 p.m. ET in
``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center:
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-LAWSUIT _ For nearly a century, American Indians have
been asking the federal government for a simple accounting of money
and land held in trust for them since the days of treaty signing.
On Monday, they finally got the attention of the highest levels of
government, as a federal judge held in contempt two Cabinet
secretaries who oversee Indian trust accounts. In a scathing
denunciation of the government's handling of the trust fund case,
Judge Royce Lamberth of U.S. District Court in Washington, found
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and Treasury Secretary Robert
Robert Rubin in civil contempt for failing to produce records of
the trust funds. By Timothy Egan. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET
in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo reefer to: KOSOVO-HARASS; story inside.
</P>
