   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-IRAQ-CIA (Washington) _ New details are emerging that
suggest the CIA was much more deeply involved in the U.N. weapons
inspection missions to Iraq than has been previously disclosed. By
Philip Shenon. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   reefer: UKRAINE-U.S. (Moscow) _ Ukraine's former prime minister,
Pavlo Lazarenko, the target of corruption inquiries there and in
Switzerland, is being held by U.S. Customs agents after he tried to
enter the United States on a tourist visa. By Michael Wines. (The
story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   BOX-LAILA-ALI (Los Angeles) _ Laila Ali, 21 years old and her
hands already bearing the scars from her early work in the ring,
recently asked for her father's blessing on her decision to follow
in his footsteps. Muhammad Ali, his face an expressionless mask as
the result of Parkinson's disease, dropped his head and paused.
``But I don't want you to get hurt,'' Ms. Ali said her father told
her, his voice barely above a whisper. ``Daddy, I'm not going to
get hurt,'' she said. ``I have your genetics.'' Women's
professional boxing is a sport struggling for stature. While the
number of women in its ranks have grown greatly, female
professional boxing is desperate for true stars, but also concerned
that it not be turned into just a curious sideshow. And so the
prospect of Laila Ali, a woman with a marketable name and no proven
skills, turning pro has infused the sport with a sense of both
promise and worry. By Timothy W. Smith. (The story has moved in
``s'' news file.) 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CERVICAL-CANCER (Undated) _ Cancer experts are recommending
a major change in the treatment of advanced cervical cancer, urging
that chemotherapy be added to the standard treatment: radiation.
The recommendation is based on five new studies showing that the
combination reduces death rates from the disease by 30 percent to
50 percent. By Denise Grady. (The story has moved in ``a'' news
file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   LEVI-CUTBACK (Undated) _ Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. announces that it
will close half of its manufacturing plants in the United States
and Canada and lay off 5,900 employees, or 30 percent of its North
American work force. The jeans manufacturer, which saw its sales
decline 13 percent in 1998 to 6.1 billion, says the move will allow
them to compete more cost-effectively with rivals who largely
manufacture overseas and to concentrate on better marketing the
brand, which has been losing favor among younger consumers in
recent years. By Leslie Kaufman. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET
in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   NY-DRUNK-DRIVERS (New York) _ Kicking off a new crackdown on
drunk driving in New York City, police officers seize the cars of
three drivers _ including one from a Staten Island librarian with
no prior arrests and another from a 57-year-old Queens man with a
long record of driving while intoxicated. The seizures come as
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani hints that he may make the crackdown even
tougher. By Ginger Thompson. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-STEEL (Washington) _ Russia agrees to limit steel
shipments into the United States, avoiding punitive tariffs that
had been sought by the U.S. steel industry. The agreement was
announced by Commerce Secretary William Daley. He said it will mean
a cut of almost 70 percent in Russian steel shipments coming into
the United States. By David E. Sanger. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MASSACRE-ANTHROPOLOGY (Guatemala City) _ Based on accounts
of four survivors and people in neighboring communities, 376 people
in an isolated Mayan hamlet of Guatemala died in a massacre by army
troops in 1982. Now, 17 years later, forensic anthropologists led
by Dr. Clyde Collins Snow are confirming their accounts, in all too
graphic detail. By Malcolm W. Browne. (The story has moved in ``a''
news file.) 2,150 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
