<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICAGO-MAYORAL-840&AMP;A     02-22 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-MAYORAL-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALEY'S COURTSHIP OF BLACK VOTE IS EXPECTED TO PAY OFF IN
RE-ELECTION BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In an astonishing turnabout from the bitter racial
divisions here a decade ago, Mayor Richard M. Daley appears poised
to win a landslide re-election victory on Tuesday with a big share
of the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, who won election in 1989 in the most racially polarized
vote in the city's history, is winning more black votes than his
black challenger, Rep. Bobby Rush, according to polls. Those polls
indicate Daley could win 70 percent of the total vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's worked assiduously to court the black community,'' said
Don Rose, a liberal political consultant here who has worked
against Daley in earlier campaigns. ``And he's done a lot of it
with classic Chicago political wiles _ deals, jobs. He's made
terrific allies.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning black support, Daley has apparently found a strategy
that has eluded many other big city leaders, including Mayor
Rudolph Guliani of New York, whose strained relations with blacks
have worsened with the recent police shooting death of an unarmed
West African immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, in his first successful bid for mayor, won less than 7
percent of the black vote. At the time, many black political
leaders branded him a racist, a charge that stemmed in part from
bitterness toward his father, the late Richard J. Daley, longtime
mayor and legendary boss of Chicago's fabled Democratic machine.
</P>
<P>
   In that election, one prominent black clergymen villified Daley
as ``pharoah's son,'' and many other black political leaders warned
that City Hall, which had been opened to blacks and other
minorities by Harold Washington, the city's first black mayor,
would revert to a traditional domination by white men, usually with
Irish surnames.
</P>
<P>
   But Daley was smarter than that. He started with a base of
support among the white, working-class who make up the so-called
Bungalow Belt on the Southwest and Northwest Sides, a group that
was unlikely to bolt for any black candidate. To broaden his reach,
Daley has worked from the start of his tenure to cultivate support
among blacks, white liberals, Hispanic voters and homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Daley has appointed blacks to key positions, steered
multi-million dollar developments to black neighborhoods and
cleaned up dilapidated sections that had long been neglected. He
has pushed strongly for hiring programs that would enhance racial
diversity in the police and fire departments.
</P>
<P>
   He delivered a forceful denunciation of racism and police
brutality after the beating of a young black man in 1997, a case
that angered many police officers, who contended that the man had
started the violent altercation. Daley has also won praise for
improvements in the public schools, where the student body is
mostly black.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's popularity is also riding the crest of the economic boom
that has lifted cities across the country, including Chicago, out
of their financial doldrums. New houses and condominium projects
have been sprouting from glass-strewn parking lots all over the
city, including spruced-up neighborhoods on the South Side that
have become fashionable among prosperous black professionals. A
study by the Woodstock Institute, a non-profit research group here,
found that homebuying among blacks during between 1990 and 1996
grew at a rate of more than 125 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a growing black middle class in Chicago, and they
approve of what Daley is doing,'' said Paul Green, an author of
books on Illinois politics. ``Property values are property values.
People with investments want stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Corruption among some City Council members, including a close
ally to Daley, has not much resonated among voters in Chicago, a
place that has long been accustomed to politicians of negotiable
virtue. And none of the charges of wrongdoing have reached the
mayor's office.
</P>
<P>
   According to a poll published Sunday in the Chicago Tribune,
Daley was garnering 65 percent of likely voters, compared to 13
percent for Rush, with 20 percent undecided. Among black voters,
the poll showed Daley leading Rush 33 percent to 28 percent, with
the remainder undecided. Three-quarters of the voters held a
favorable opinion of Daley, while only 9 percent viewed the mayor
unfavorably. The poll has a potential margin of error of four
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   In the racial breakdown of Chicago, blacks account for about 42
percent of the population, with whites making up about 38 percent
and Hispanic voters about 20 percent. Chicago has elected just one
black mayor, Harold Washington, a charming, bearish man with a
charisma that set a standard black mayoral hopefuls have found
difficult to approach.
</P>
<P>
   In his longshot campaign, Rush, who had been a member of the
militant Black Panthers in the '60s, has been unable to muster
financial resources, with even most black business interests
supporting Daley.
</P>
<P>
   And with Daley refusing to debate him, Rush has run a
shoe-string campaign that has sometimes tried to win notice by
making strong statements, sentiments that have sometimes had a tone
of stridency and desperation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Daley has picked up endorsements from the Chicago Defender, the
city's largest black newspaper, and from some blacks on the City
Council. One of his chief critics as he entered office 10 years
ago, Alderwoman Dorothy Tillman _ a woman once known for fiery
speeches that condemned ``plantation politics'' _ is now viewed as
something of an ally of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   His father, who died in 1976, had owed more than one of his
early elections to black support, especially in 1963, when Ben
Adamowski, ran a conservative campaign against Daley. At his peak,
the elder Daley racked up about 90 percent of the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   But he became estranged from the civil rights and anti-war
movement in the late '60s and early '70s. During his last primary
election in 1975, he carried less than half the black vote, with
the remainder going to two more liberal rivals, one of them black
and one white.
</P>
<P>
   By some measures, the son has Chicago sewn up tighter than his
father ever did. About one-third of the 50 Chicago aldermen were
originally appointed by the younger Daley, people who can be
expected to be steadfastly loyal. Vociferous critics of Daley on
the City Council can be counted on one hand, with a few fingers to
spare.
</P>
</TEXT>
