<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5054 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      02-22 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
PATHOLOGIST DETAILS VICTIM'S STRUGGLE IN DRAGGING death 
 
(Eds.: Jury deliberations to begin after closing arguments heard
Tuesday) 
 
By PATTY REINERT 
and RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ James Byrd Jr. struggled to the end, contorting
his body in a vain attempt to escape the intense pain as he was
being dragged to death down Huff Creek Road, a pathologist
testified Monday as prosecutors wrapped up their case against a
white supremacist accused of killing the black man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Byrd was alive up to the point where he hit the culvert
and his head separated from his body,'' Dr. Tommy J. Brown told
jurors in gruesome testimony that drove some of the victim's family
from the courtroom, along with the defendant's father.
</P>
<P>
   As Byrd changed from one excruciating position to another, his
hands, elbows, heels and knees were ground to the bone, and his
penis and testicles were shredded from his body, Brown told a
hushed courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was very painful to him, and he was attempting to relieve
the pain by moving from side to side, swapping one portion of his
body for another as he was being dragged,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's agony ended when his head slammed into the concrete
culvert, and he was torn in two. The next morning, his mangled
torso was found in the middle of the road outside the gates to a
black cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   If jurors believe Brown, they could decide that John William
``Bill'' King, an ex-con from Jasper, both kidnapped and killed
Byrd by dragging him behind a pickup June 7. Both crimes must be
proved for King to be convicted of capital murder and for him to
qualify for a death sentence. His two co-defendants will be tried
later.
</P>
<P>
   King's lawyers presented only three witnesses in their one-hour
defense Monday afternoon. The jury of 11 whites and one
African-American will begin deliberating on King's guilt or
innocence following closing arguments Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Before resting their case Monday morning, prosecutors also
introduced more handwritten messages from King, 24, including a
note he passed to co-defendant Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr. shortly
after their arrests, bragging that they had ``made history.''
Prosecutors also showed slides of racist graffiti from King's jail
cell.
</P>
<P>
   And as the bells of the Jasper County Courthouse tolled 11 a.m.,
reverberating through the building like a death knell, lawyers for
the state ended their presentation with a dramatic, 11-minute
silent videotape, driving the trail of Byrd's death.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors were riveted, clutching booklets containing the color
photos of Byrd's beaten, dismembered corpse. The victim's family
held hands in the front two rows of the courtroom as the video
rolled, showing mile after mile of the winding road through the
Piney Woods east of Jasper. King sat emotionless, chin in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Several quiet minutes passed before the appearance of the
culvert where Byrd's head, shoulder and right arm came off, 2.1
miles from a clearing in the woods where the 49-year-old disabled
man had been stripped and chained to the pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, prosecutors produced a jailhouse note or ``kite'' that
King wrote to Brewer shortly after their arrests. The message was
intercepted and photocopied by jailers before being passed on to
Brewer through a trusty nicknamed ``Spiderman.''
</P>
<P>
   In the note, King discussed bloodstained clothing and shoes at
his apartment and explained to Brewer, a former prison buddy, that
prosecutors would have to prove that Byrd was kidnapped in order to
get a capital murder conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't find us guilty of kidnapping but do find us
guilty of murder, it will be a simple first degree murder, bro,''
he wrote. ``No death sentence!''
</P>
<P>
   He ended the note: ``Seriously though bro, reguardless (sic) of
the outcome of this, we have made history and shall die proudly
remembered if need be ... Gotta go. Much Aryan Love, Respect and
Honor my brother in arms.''
</P>
<P>
   The note was signed ``Seig Heil (Hail Victory), Possum.''
Possum, with the s's drawn as lightning bolts signifying Hitler's
storm troopers, was King's nickname in a racist prison gang, the
Confederate Knights of America. The nickname also was found etched
into a cigarette lighter found at the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors also saw slides of graffiti from King's cell at the
Jasper County Jail, in which he called a third defendant,
24-year-old Shawn Allen Berry, ``a snitch ass traitor'' for turning
them in to police. King also scratched ``White Pride'' into his
cell door, and left his signature autograph and a triangular symbol
for the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors theorize that King and Brewer, who also belonged to
the Confederate Knights of America, had planned to form a chapter
of the white supremacist organization in Jasper, which they would
call the Texas Rebel Soldiers. Byrd's brutal killing could have
been the initiation rite for the group's first new member, Berry,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   After 4 1/2 days and more than 40 prosecution witnesses, defense
lawyers C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr. and Brack Jones Jr. called
prison tattoo artist John Mosley, who testified that white
prisoners in the Beto I prison at Tennessee Colony, either fought
black prisoners or gave them money and sexual favors. King and
Brewer, 31, served time in the unit for burglary from 1995-97.
Mosley is serving 10- and 15-year terms for burglary and sexual
assault.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley said many of King's tattoos, earlier characterized as
being racist or demonic, had little meaning in prison. ``Somebody
just got them out of a tattoo magazine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination prosecutors provided a letter Mosley, known
in prison as ``Big Moe,'' wrote to King's girlfriend telling her he
``jammed'' another inmate who was going to testify against King.
The other inmate didn't testify, but Mosley denied threatening him.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Cunningham, who called himself a longtime friend of
King, said King didn't mention his Texas Rebel Soldiers, but did
use racial slurs in conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Symmack of Jasper said he hired King to help him put up
metal buildings. He said King would often talk about the Aryan
race, and about the history of the group. ``He seemed to be very
smart,'' Symmack said. ``He was very educated about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Symmack said he and King parted ways when King refused to do
jobs the way he wanted him to. ``He told me to kiss his ass.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
