<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DEADLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO PEACE TALKS HEAD TOWARD DEADLINE UNRESOLVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _- The Kosovo peace talks at Rambouillet appeared on the
verge of collapse as both the ethnic Albanians and Serbs continued
their opposition for different reasons to an agreement solving the
crisis in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   With the three-day extension to last Saturday's deadline set to
expire Tuesday at 9 a.m. EST, there is a strong sense of deja vu
for frustrated diplomats and a world that has heard the western
powers repeatedly threaten to bomb Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic into comprise.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike last Saturday and last October, when Milosevic's
intransigence tiggered the threat of NATO bombing, it is also the
refusal of the ethnic Albanians to countenance a settlement without
a guarantee of an independence referendum that may scuttle the
six-nation Contact Group's attempt to resolve the bloodshed in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   By rejecting US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's pleas
that they accept a settlement sidesteping a referendum on their
future independence, ethnic Albanian negotiators effectively
neutralized the leverage the western allies wielded over Milosevic
to compromise on Kosovo or face NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Albright has repeated that Serbian military targets would not be
bombed if the ethnic Albanians refused to accept the settlement
brokered by the Contact Group, which consists of the United States,
Britain, France, Germany, Italy and Russia. These countries had
assumed that the Albanians would accept the compromise while the
Serbs would reject it.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs are equally intransigent, refusing even to discuss the
Contact Group's insistence that 30,000 NATO troops be deployed in
Kosovo to enforce the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The stubborness of the ethnic Albanians was a surprise to the
Contact Group. In fact, diplomats at Rambouillet, the French town
where the talks have been held for the last 16 days, had remarked
privately that the ethnic Albanians were faring well in the deal
considering that the fighting in Kosovo has gone on only for about
a year.
</P>
<P>
   But members of the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) within the
ethnic Albanian delegation are reported to have fought hard against
provisions in a proposed settlement calling on them to disarm
without the guarantee of a referendum on independence after three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Because some 90 percent of the 2 million people in Kosovo are
ethnic Albanians, the KLA believes passage of such a referendum is
guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   But the diplomats who have supported the compromise, fashioned
largely by Christopher Hill, the US envoy to Kosovo, have concluded
that the only way to satisfy the Serbs is to leave vague the
question of Kosovo's future.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, one European diplomat said the only chance for a
settlement was to assume that the Albanian intransigence was a
negotiating tactic that would fade shortly before the deadline.
This change would then put all of the pressure on Milosevic to drop
his opposition to a NATO peacekeeping force. But that diplomat,
like others, was doubtful that such a scenario would occur.
</P>
<P>
   As the talks at Rambouillet remained at an impasse, new fighting
broke out near Pristina, the capital of Kosovo. International
observers reported that a convoy of Serbian military vehicles came
under fire from KLA fighters. The Serbs then shelled several
villages, creating hundreds more of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to appease the Serbs at Rambouillet angered Gabrielle
Kirk McDonald, the American judge who is the president of the
Yugoslavia war crimes tribunal. At a news conference Monday, she
lashed out at reports that the proposed settlement on the table at
Rambouillet does not provide for war crimes prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs are suspected of mass killings of unarmed civilians in
a scorched-earth policy aimed at ending KLA support. The most
recent massacre, at Racak last month, left 45 dead and prompted the
Contact Group to convene the peace talks at Rambouillet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am extremely alarmed concerning the pace and the content of
negotiations as I understand them at Rambouillet,'' McDonald said.
``I am advised that significant language has been removed. That in
my mind is a very, very short-sighted and dangerous action. There
can be no lasting peace unless the International Criminal Tribunal
is involved.''
</P>
<P>
   According to State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin, Albright
spoke Monday by telephone with NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and officials in
Tirana, the Albanian capital. That last phone call, diplomats said,
was to persuade officials in the country with which Kosovar
Albanians share a common language and culture to impress upon them
the favorable provisions for them in the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin sought to portray the Serbs as the main obstacles to a
settlement. While the ethnic Albanians ``continue to move forward
toward an agreement,'' Rubin said, ``the Serbs are not engaged
seriously on the military part.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs, meanwhile, appeared to relish the new spin that the
ethnic Albanians posed problems. Serbian President Milan
Milutinovic strolled the streets of Rambouillet, telling reporters
the Serbs were prepared to sign an agreement that gives autonomy to
Kosovo. Milosevic revoked that autonomy in 1989 as part of a
repressive crackdown against ethnic Albanians. That loss in large
part provoked the current conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright stressed that the Serbs could not accept the
political piece of the settlement without accepting the NATO troops
to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   People in Yugoslav capital of Belgrade, meanwhile, reacted to
the tension in Rambouillet with a collective yawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not concerned any more. We are used to it,'' said Maria
Redic, a 21-year-old law student. ``You can't go into someone
else's playground and tell them what to do, and what not to do,''
she said as she waited for one of Belgrade's run-down trams.
</P>
<P>
   The heavily guarded U.S. embassy in Belgrade operated with a
skeleton staff Monday. Provisions have already been made to close
the embassy quickly and have another government guard it in case of
an air assault, said Chief of Mission Dick Miles.
</P>
<P>
   Miles, who personally reported several threats received by the
U.S. embassy, said the Yugoslav police assured him U.S. diplomats
would be protected. ``We could not confirm the reports, but we took
them seriously,'' Miles said, adding that he did not feel
frightened or ``personally threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-American sentiment in Belgrade is higher than ever, fueld
by assertions in the state-run media that the West -- the United
States, in particular -- is trying to punish Serbs both by taking
Kosovo away from them and by threatening them with air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Susan Milligan contributed to this report from
Belgrade.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
