<SLUG> BC-CARSON-ANDREWS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yesner appointed acting chief at Carson after death of CEO
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Carson Inc., the Savannah, Ga.-based ethnic personal
products company, faces its second leadership change in eight
months following the death of Chief Executive Gregory J. Andrews
during a business trip to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The company's board named Malcolm Yesner, 41, acting chief
executive, pending a meeting later this week. Yesner has been
Carson's president-international and CEO of its fast-growing Carson
Holdings subsidiary, based in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   It's expected Yesner will be a candidate for the job
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews, age 47 and a veteran of the personal care products
industry, joined Carson last summer from Colgate-Palmolive. He had
shuffled management and begun an effort to refocus strategy around
core products.
</P>
<P>
   The company, in a statement Monday, said he died of ``apparent
natural causes'' while in South Africa. A spokesman said Andrews
was found in his Johannesburg hotel room after he failed to keep a
breakfast appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Wasik, chairman of Carson's executive committee and
president of Morningside Capital, a major stockholder, said Andrews
``left an indelible mark on the company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg was a man of vision who ... put together an excellent,
experienced and dedicated management team which is fully capable of
carrying out the program he put in place and which was yielding
highly tangible results,'' Wasik said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed he was making strides and was really out there
working hard,'' said Baunita Greer, an analyst with Cromwell,
Miller &AMP; Greer. ``This is untimely and unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer said Yesner is well regarded for the growth of the South
African unit and for a recent deal to distribute Carson products in
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Carson makes such flagship products as Dark &AMP; Lovely, Magic
Shave and AfroSheen. Revenue jumped 50 percent in the third quarter
of 1998, but the company posted a $3.6 million net loss, largely on
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Carson in December completed two moves that analysts said
improved its prospects. It got an $83 million loan to cover an
acquisition of Johnson Products hair care line, and it sold its
Cutex nail care unit for $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, however, Standard &AMP; Poor's lowered its
rating on some of Carson's debt amid concerns that the company's
financial position may weaken. That followed a decision by Moody's
Investor Service a month earlier to maintain its debt rating
because of what it saw as brighter financial prospects since the
company reduced its debt and got the $83 million loan.
</P>
<P>
   Carson stock was unchanged Monday at $3.25.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
