<SLUG> BC-SECURITY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Security First lands $14 million
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta's Security First Technologies got $14 million
and a strong vote of confidence for its Internet financial services
software Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It announced Hewlett Packard has taken a $10 million equity
stake and that Andersen Consulting has added $4 million to the pot.
Security First comes away from the strategic alliance with more
than money. It'll also have the benefit of Hewlett Packard's sales
and marketing clout and Andersen's consulting expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted favorably to the news with Security First
Technologies closing up for the second day in a row at $51.37 1/2
up $3. Hewlett-Packard's ownership in the company ``won't be big,''
said James S. Mahan III, Security First chief executive. Mahan said
he believes Security First offers the solution for consumers who
want to do business on the Web, but needs partners like HP and
Andersen to make the idea a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Security First pioneered online banking in 1995 by launching the
world's first Internet bank. The company began life in the mid-'80s
as a marriage of two components, a banking side and a technology
side. The technology side, originally called SecureWare, grew out
of Georgia Tech's business incubator program. Security First
Network Bank was sold by the company to the Royal Bank of Canada
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mahan said the Andersen and HP investments will give the company
``unlimited bench strength'' to grow its business.
</P>
<P>
   HP will help Security First develop what the company calls the
``next generation'' of Internet-based financial services focusing
first on North America and eventually expanding globally. The two
companies hope to help everyone from banks to department stores
conduct financial transactions online.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen Consulting will work to help financial instutions
develop online business strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Doyle, Forrester Research's director of money and
technology strategies, said Monday's deals will strengthen Security
First's position as a leading provider of financial services
software.
</P>
<P>
   This is a mutually beneficial relationship for all parties,
Doyle says, ``but Security First benefits the most. Now they have
HP's sales force marketing their product and Andersen has
Andersen's consultants inside the banks and insurance companies
helping customers make the move to the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle said the online financial market had plenty of room to
grow. He said of 100,000 households surveyed recently, 3.4 percent
were paying bills and transferring funds online at the beginning of
1999.''By 2003,'' he says, ``Forrester estimates 29 million U.S.
households will be banking online.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
