<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EEOC23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EEOC set to launch mediation program
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hoping to ease its backlog of cases, the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission plans to start a nationwide
mediation service to help workers and their bosses resolve disputes
and avoid costly and protracted court battles.
</P>
<P>
   The program was scheduled to be announced today.
</P>
<P>
   Under the EEOC's Alternative Dispute Resolution, charges of job
discrimination will be resolved within two months, said William
Snapp, ADR coordinator in Atlanta, which has had a pilot program on
mediation since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, it takes EEOC investigators nine months to investigate
a case and at least two years to resolve the ones that end up in
court. Litigating a job bias case often costs a company and the
employee more than $100,000 between them.
</P>
<P>
   Mediation programs will be set up in all 23 EEOC district
offices by the end of the month. In fiscal 1998, 79,591 job
discrimination charges were filed with the EEOC nationwide, down
slightly from 80,680 the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   The number of retaliation charges _ when a company takes adverse
action against a worker who has filed an EEOC charge or who speaks
out against job bias _ has increased sharply over the past four
years and accounts for 24 percent of the current charges, Snapp
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cases in Atlanta mirror that trend.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta district office, which covers all of Georgia, had
4,562 job discrimination cases filed last year _ a significantly
higher number compared with other districts, Snapp said. The most
common employment discrimination charges involved race.
</P>
<P>
   ``By having prompt mediation available, we can bring faster
justice to more people,'' Snapp said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's pilot ADR program mediated 150 cases last year.
Eighty-four of those cases were resolved and included nearly $1
million in monetary relief. The remaining cases are still under
investigation. In 1997, 20 of the 69 cases were resolved and more
than $250,000 was paid in settlements, Snapp said.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta program will have six EEOC employees. Outside
mediators _ mostly attorneys _ will be used.
</P>
<P>
   Mediation is the latest effort by the federal agency to address
long-standing problems of red tape and inefficiency. The agency has
been criticized for letting cases languish, sometimes for years.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, the federal agency has reduced by more
than half the number of pending cases. In October 1998, 52,000
cases were pending, down from 65,000 the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Atlanta office has made similar reductions,'' said Snapp,
who served as the EEOC's regional attorney handling case
development and litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses are increasingly using mediation as a way to reduce
workplace conflicts, says Carl Deus, president of Education and
Management Solutions Inc., a suburban Atlanta-based training and
consulting firm that specializes in mediation.
</P>
<P>
   Mediation has its roots in labor-management disputes some 60
years ago and has become widely used, from divorce courts and
custody cases to environmental issues and health care disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The use of mediation has not been without controversy. The
securities industry now requires new employees to sign agreements
to resolve job disputes through mediation instead of the courts,
according to Les Hough, director of the Usery Center for the
Workplace at Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts have taken mixed views on the industry's
practice,'' Hough said. ``This is a highly controversial issue. Can
one give one's rights up?''
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the mediation program, call
404-562-6821.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
