A5062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVIS-LAYOFFS23-COX     02-22 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVIS-LAYOFFS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Blue' day for Levi as company closes 11 plants
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ San Francisco-based Levi Strauss said it was closing
11 plants in the United States and Canada as it tries to regroup
amid falling demand for its product. A total of about 5,900 workers
will lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Following other competitors, the privately owned company said it
would shift production to less-costly plants overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 Levi Strauss plants being closed are half the company's
22 plants in North America. The company said the move overseas will
enable it to spend more money on product design and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``These steps are crucial if we are to remain competitive,''
said John Ermatinger, president of the North American division of
Levi Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Raynor, secretary-treasurer of the Union of
Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees, or UNITE,
criticized the decision to close the plants. The company employs
6,000 union members.
</P>
<P>
   Raynor blamed the North American Free Trade Agreement between
the United States, Mexico and Canada, saying the pact has made it
easier for companies to move operations to Mexico to take advantage
of cheaper labor to increase profits. Among the companies he cited
were Ralph Lauren, Guess? and Warnaco, owner of Calvin Klein Jeans,
which recently announced plans to move some operations to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said that NAFTA would send U.S. jobs to Mexico; retailers
and the apparel industry said no,'' Raynor said. ``Unfortunately,
we were right, and they were lying. North American workers
understand that without equitable trade laws, more jobs that
sustain families will leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss hasn't said where it will move its operations.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at Levi Strauss, which also makes Dockers and Slates
slacks, fell 13 percent last year to $6 billion, the second year of
disappointing results for the company. Since it is privately owned,
it does not release earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it will provide benefit packages to the
laid-off employees, including eight months of regular pay from the
layoff date; up to three weeks of severance pay per year of
service; extended medical coverage up to 18 months, depending on
years of service; and up to $6,000 toward training, education,
relocation, and business start-up expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
