<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5063 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-2TAKES-N     02-22 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO PEACE TALKS ARE NEAR COLLAPSE AFTER ETHNIC ALBANIANS RESIST
TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also KOSOVO-HARASS) 
(fe) 
 By JANE PERLEZ 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMBOUILLET, France, _ The Kosovo peace talks were on the verge
of breakdown Monday night, as five delegates from the ethnic
Albanian guerrillas refused the exhortations of Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to sign an agreement and were not persuaded by a
last-ditch visit from the NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Albright spent much of Monday huddled in a small conference room
of the 14th century chateau where the talks are taking place here
trying to sell the peace agreement to the guerrillas of the Kosovo
Liberation Army _ who until the talks began two weeks ago had a
hit-and-run insurgency operation in an obscure part of southern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle of the little-known rebels holding the United
States at bay and undermining the Clinton administration's strategy
for a peace agreement that had been seen as disproportionately
benefiting the ethnic Albanians flabbergasted the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to agree to sign a peace settlement, the guerrillas
were preventing the United States and its allies from pressuring
the guerrillas' enemy, President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia,
to agree to allow NATO-led peacekeeping troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas also appeared likely to be responsible for
putting on hold the movement of thousands of NATO troops, including
more than 2,000 U.S. Marines. The NATO forces are preparing to
enter Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians and Serbs has been battling
for a year.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo on Monday, attacks on villages and fighting between
government troops and rebels intensified, and the agency providing
monitors for a fading cease-fire accused Serbian troops of
attacking and harassing monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas' main objection to signing appeared to be the
absence of the word ``referendum'' in the political document of the
peace proposal, even though the draft calls for an international
conference to assess the ``will of the people'' at the end of the
three-year interim period. A referendum on independence has been a
rallying cry of the guerrilla group.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has been adamantly opposed to the prospect of having
NATO-led troops in Kosovo, and NATO has threatened air strikes if
he does not agree to them.
</P>
<P>
   But by Monday night the threat of air strikes appeared virtually
meaningless, and administration officials seemed almost resigned to
folding the talks at the already extended deadline of 3 p.m. on
Tuesday, French time. The European group has not said how the
collapse of peace talks would affect its commitment to keep the
cease-fire monitors in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Albright left the talks just before midnight on Monday without
an answer from the guerrillas. A senior Western diplomat said they
did not expect a positive one.
</P>
<P>
   Several Western diplomats said they were mortified by the
pleasure that Milosevic _ who had been postulated as the certain
adversary to any agreement _ must be reaping from the unexpected
turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go to Milosevic without a yes'' from the rebels. said
a senior Western diplomat. ``We've applied all the diplomatic
tricks in the bag. If we're not there, we try to freeze it and see
where we go.''
</P>
<P>
   After Albright failed to make headway over three days of
meetings with the ethnic Albanians in the elegant chateau here, the
United States decided to call in General Clark, whose military
stature and explanation of what his NATO ground troops would do in
Kosovo was intended to impress the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   He flew from NATO headquarters in Mons, Belgium, to a military
airfield near the chateau here and spent about half an hour with
the five guerrillas late this afternoon, Western diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter between General Clark and the guerrillas did not
go well, the diplomats said. The guerrillas returned to the chateau
to caucus with the other members of the 16-member ethnic Albanian
delegation and to give Albright, who had been left cooling her
heels, a final word during the night.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they were far from confident that
the guerrillas would agree to the terms of the settlement even
though the ethnic Albanians have been calling unequivocally for a
NATO deployment as a way to stop the conflict and to protect their
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of a referendum is important to the rebels because it
is seen as a guarantee of separation from Serbia, of which Kosovo
is now a province. Serbia is one of two republics in Yugoslavia.
Ethnic Albanians make up more than 90 percent of the population of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But making a referendum part of the peace agreement would ensure
rejection of the peace deal by Milosevic. And a referendum is not
entirely supported by the West, which backs autonomy for Kosovo but
not independence.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas have also been unhappy about the demands in the
proposed peace agreement that they disarm over a period of about
six months. They have doubts that this is in their interests, they
argue, when the Serbian police force would be allowed to keep 2,500
members in Kosovo, and the Yugoslav Army would keep 1,500 soldiers
on the borders.
</P>
<P>
   The main opponent to signing the agreement among the ethnic
Albanians was Hashim Thaci, a 29-year-old political science
graduate from a university in Switzerland, who is leader of the
political directorate of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The tall and lanky Thaci is described by Western diplomats who
have dealt with him in Kosovo as tough, enigmatic and ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   He was described by a diplomat who knows him as being
particularly anti-Serb and the only member of the ethnic Albanian
delegation who does not speak Serbian. Like several other members
of the delegation, he does not speak English, making it somewhat
more difficult for the Americans to negotiate with him.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of his opposition to a peace agreement was
apparently heightened after he left the peace talks Friday and flew
to Slovenia to meet Adem Demaci, the spokesman for the political
wing of the Kosovo Liberation Army and a hard-liner on the question
of independence.
</P>
<P>
   Demaci refused to attend the peace talks, and diplomats
speculated he had told Thaci to remember that independence of
Kosovo was the immediate goal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What administration officials perhaps found most frustrating was
their lack of understanding of the guerrillas, a relatively new
group that sprang on the scene last year. Thaci was variously
described Monday as ``Hamlet like'' and ``not understanding the
interests of his people.''
</P>
<P>
   As the hours trickled away on Monday, the American negotiators
desperately tried to come up with a way to get the ethnic Albanians
to sign on.
</P>
<P>
   While the guerrilla constituted only five of the 16 members in
the delegation, their opinions carried far greater weight than
those of the others, diplomats said. One member of the group here,
Ibrahim Rugova, has twice been elected president in Kosovo in
elections that are not recognized by Serbia. But he has had minimal
influence at the talks.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the Americans thought that they had Thaci isolated
and that they would be able to persuade the rest of the ethnic
Albanian delegation to sign on without him. But then, Jakup
Krasniqi, another powerful member of the insurgents _ whom the
Americans thought they had successfully wooed _ wavered.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere inside the castle on Monday was described as both
chaotic and gloomy, with the chief American negotiator, Ambassador
Christopher Hill, and an assistant secretary of state, Marc
Grossman, approaching members from the Kosovo Liberation Army to
present them to Albright in the conference room.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, diplomats from four European countries and
Russia, which with the United States make up the Contact Group on
the Balkans, which sponsored the talks, waited for what one called
``Madeleine's magic'' to work. But for Albright, who has invested
large amounts of political capital in the success of the talks, the
day was particularly frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   In what appeared to be a move of final desperation, the American
negotiators appealed to the new Prime Minister of Albania, Pandeli
Majko, to try to persuade the Kosovo Liberation Army to endorse an
agreement. Majko made a public statement urging the guerrillas to
sign and said he would send his foreign minister, Paskal Milo, to
the talks.
</P>
<P>
   On the Serbian side of the peace conference, little evolved,
diplomats said. The French foreign minister, Hubert Vedrine,
visited the castle and talked with the Serbian President, Milan
Milutinovic, who has been designated by Milosevic as his man at the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   It had been planned that once the ethnic Albanians agreed to the
peace agreement that attention would turn to Milosevic, who has
remained in Belgrade. But on Monday night any plans to visit him
with a final demand appeared to be on hold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
