<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5070 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      02-22 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HOME, NO ONE'S IN THE DARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes I forget to turn off the outside light, the one in the
carport. I'll be all the way to the bedroom door when I sense the
light still on, its glow filtering through windows like a
smoldering fire.
</P>
<P>
   So I turn around and walk back to the front door and flip off
the switch, and everything disappears into darkness. I could turn
on another light to see my way but I never do, not after all these
years.
</P>
<P>
   A step or two from the door I reach out to the bookshelf on the
north wall. The tips of my fingers brush along the spines of
hardbacks, guiding me book by book, shelf by shelf, to a hallway.
</P>
<P>
   I touch the wall as I continue, fingertips reading every little
bump and groove as if they were the Braille of memory.
</P>
<P>
   This house, which we've lived in for a long time, sold after
only two days on the market, and now we have no choice but to move.
</P>
<P>
   We signed papers on a lovely place north and west of here, a
house with more room, as this one's too full of us and our
reminiscences.
</P>
<P>
   The hallway I walk in is the same one the girl used to lead us
down, in the dark, on Christmas morning; the same one the girl's
younger brother now leads us down, in the dark, on Christmas
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way is the door to the room that used to have bunk
beds in it, but doesn't anymore. And the room that used to be an
office, but isn't anymore.
</P>
<P>
   And the room my mother stayed in during her final visit, the one
we have on tape. She sits on the bed with her granddaughter,
laughing and talking, until she notices the camera in a son's hand
and asks, ``Is that on?''
</P>
<P>
   And he answers, ``No.'' &QL; 
THERE'S MEANING &QL; 
It's an easy home to get around in. It's been that way since the
day I returned to find the woman who usually sits at a computer,
writing newspaper articles, swinging a sledgehammer at a kitchen
wall.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up in a house that meant everything to the people who
lived there, and so all the houses I've lived in mean something to
me. Even this house in Phoenix, where homeowners too often are
called transients.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever completely leaves a house.
</P>
<P>
   Houses are vaults for dreams, the walls like sponges absorbing
our stories.
</P>
<P>
   There are names painted on the old grapefruit trees in the back
yard, where the girl first practiced riding a two-wheeler hoping
grass wouldn't skin her knees.
</P>
<P>
   The brick patio in front covers a spot where shade from the
chinaberry tree wouldn't allow grass to grow. On the patio to the
south, near the picnic table, you can make out chips of white paint
on one of the bricks. It's the spot we found Maggie the cat after
she'd been hit by a car. She couldn't quite make it inside. &QL; 
SIGNS OF LIVES &QL; 
Under the carport are the oleanders that just won't die. Out front
are patches of grass that won't quite live. The writer with the
sledgehammer planted the rose bushes and lemon tree. The chalk
marks on the driveway will wash off, eventually. They always do.
</P>
<P>
   I'll drive by here after we leave. I still drive by the
apartment on 28th Street where we first brought the newborn girl.
And the small rental house near the canal in Sunnyslope where she
strolled with her grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   On trips back East I visit my old neighborhood, which everyone
says has gone downhill and is too dangerous to visit. But it isn't.
Not if you've lived there and know the ghosts living in the walls.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only bricks and mortar we leave behind when we move
from one house to another, not if it's a HOME. It's more like
walking from a sunny spot and having your shadow remain, unwilling
or unable to follow you.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, what you bring to a new house isn't only
furniture and books, clothes and dishes and bicycles. It's all the
memories to come.
</P>
<P>
   I'm learning all over that it's not enough for us simply to have
a place to go when it gets dark outside. It must also be a place in
which we can find our way when the lights go off.
</P>
<P>
   E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 2015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
