<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.S.-ART-NYT     02-22 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN 3 RAIDS, ALLIED PLANES HIT TARGETS IN IRAQ NO-FLIGHT ZONE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In three separate raids, U.S. and British warplanes
struck targets on Monday in southern and northern Iraq, hitting
communication facilities, missile sites and weapons depots in a
wide swath of territory within the ``no-flight zones,'' according
to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said all three allied attacks were prompted by Iraqi
challenges to allied air patrols of the zones, including the
intrusion of Iraqi MiG warplanes and antiaircraft fire on U.S.
jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi government of Saddam Hussein was also trying to
control the third day of protests by Shiite Muslims sparked by the
assassination of one of their leading clerics. Ayatollah Mohammad
Sadek al Sader and his two sons were killed last Friday, and, in
the ensuing protests, Iraqi security forces were reported to have
killed demonstrators, according to the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   The no-flight zones were established to protect the Shiite
minority in the south, and the Kurds in the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``This assassination follows a period of great and widespread
repression in the South,'' said James B. Foley, deputy spokesman
for the State Department. ``Mohammad al Sader is the fourth senior
Iraqi religious leader to be assassinated in less than a year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton administration officials were hesitant to draw any
connection between the punishing allied air attacks and the
strength of the Shiite demonstrations following this latest
killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The protests were triggered by the assassination,'' said
Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman. ``We need more time to know
if the Shiites have become more emboldened by the air attacks. But
it is clear that since Desert Fox, Saddam Hussein has become more
concerned about internal security.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first attack in the southern zone, U.S. F-15 fighters and
British Tornado jets struck two communications facilities and two
weapons depots near the Iraqi town of Basra, the Pentagon said. The
bombings were in response to two Iraqi MiG crossing into the
no-flight zone.
</P>
<P>
   Five hours later, the U.S. jets struck a second time, after the
Iraqis fired at them with antiaircraft guns, the officials said.
The allied jets hit targets near the cities of As Samawah, Ar
Rumaylah and Al Kaharm in an arc stretching from 75 miles to 300
miles southeast of Baghdad. The targets of the second attack were
more communications facilities and a surface-to-air missile site,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the north, U.S. aircraft dropped precision-guided bombs on
Iraqi artillery and radar sites near Mosul after being fired upon
by Iraqi artillery.
</P>
<P>
   All allied planes returned safely to their bases, the Pentagon
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a busy day,'' said Lt. Col. Patrick Sevigni, a Pentagon
spokesman. ``But there's no real pattern here, it just kind of ebbs
and flows.''
</P>
<P>
   The damage wrought by this low-level war of attrition on Iraqi
air defenses has been significant, the Pentagon said. Cmdr. Tom Van
Leunen of the European command said that while it is difficult to
assess the full extent of that damage, the bombing raids over the
past two months have destroyed surface to air missile sites,
antiaircraft guns, radar and the communication facilities necessary
to tie together Iraq's integrated air defense.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those losses, the Pentagon planners believe the Iraqis
will continue to challenge international patrol of the zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent weeks, the fact that we hit them one day doesn't
mean that the next day will be quiet,'' Van Leunen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
