<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5073 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HARASS-ART-500     02-22 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HARASS-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN POLICE REPORTEDLY ATTACK KOSOVO PEACE MONITORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BC-KOSOVO-TALKS) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By CHARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The Serbian police beat and harassed
cease-fire monitors in Kosovo, the monitoring group said on Monday
as reports arrived about attacks on villages and of fighting
between Serbian troops and ethnic Albanian rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The troops entered a cluster of ethnic Albanian villages near
Vucitrn, 18 miles northeast of the provincial capital, Pristina,
witnesses said. The troops reportedly used tanks to destroy houses
and set fire to others as soldiers and police officers smashed
windows with rifles.
</P>
<P>
   The office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
said 4,000 people, mostly women, children and the elderly, had
fled. The agency said five villagers were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Truckloads of soldiers from the Kosovo Liberation Army, the
ethnic Albanian rebel group, also were reported in the area. The
Serbian-run Pristina Media Center said rebels attacked a Serbian
village in the area, killing one person and wounding two others.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which
provides 1,300 monitors to police the increasingly shaky
cease-fire, said it had lodged a strong protest with the Serbian
government.
</P>
<P>
   The group said two monitors were beaten on Sunday in northern
Kosovo, one of a number of violent incidents against its staff. The
monitors, from Lithuania and Luxembourg, were following a police
convoy in their official orange vehicle near Podujevo.
</P>
<P>
   Two uniformed officers from the Interior Ministry left their bus
and asked for the monitors' identification and then ordered them
out of the car, the international organization said. When the
monitors refused, the officers punched them several times and
pulled them from their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The monitors were operating under the rules of the cease-fire
that started in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very violent act of aggression and in complete
violation of the agreement we have with the government,' a
spokeswoman for the European group here, Beatrice Lacoste, said.
</P>
<P>
   The monitors, neither seriously hurt, were in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian officers were ``either incredibly undisciplined or
under orders,'' Ms. Lacoste said, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have issued a statement condemning the increasing violence
toward our people. It is totally unacceptable and intolerable.''
</P>
<P>
   The government has not responded.
</P>
<P>
   The harassment report followed other incidents of police
harassment of foreigners over the weekend in a sign of intensified
aggression, the organization said. The attacks raise questions
about the monitors' safety, with a possibility of NATO air strikes
if peace talks, in France, fail.
</P>
<P>
   The monitors are on alert, ready to leave in eight hours if the
talks break down. For now the monitors continue working, verifying
the cease-fire and the movements of military and security forces.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has assurances from the authorities that the
monitors will be allowed to leave. But after the last few days, few
experts expect a trouble-free evacuation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The heavy fighting of last summer has apparently been reduced by
the presence of the foreign observers. But the people of Kosovo
continue to suffer daily violence, with gunfire and shellfire by
day and stealthy killings by night. The violence has increased in
the last week.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Kosovo, a prosperous farming village, Studenace, was
turned into a ghost town on Saturday after the residents fled
fighting between government troops and rebels. The villagers said
they were frightened by bursts of gunfire and the explosions of
mortars on the edge of the village.
</P>
<P>
   A few men returned on Sunday morning to feed their cows and
chickens. But they said they would not be staying long. Bilal Sopi,
a widower, was already tramping through the mud to join his
relatives, who had taken refuge in the next village.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth time in a year of fighting that they have been
forced to flee a Serbian army attack, Sopi said. This time, they
hid in the basement for three hours and, then, as the shelling
intensified, joined hundreds of others fleeing on foot or on
tractors.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear what started the exchange of gunfire. But it
was the heaviest fighting in the district in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the accord forged in October by a special American
envoy, Richard C. Holbrooke, the two sides clash almost daily. It
is evident that without NATO troops to force them apart, the
conflict could rapidly flare into full-scale war again.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, where 90 percent of the residents are ethnic Albanians,
once had a high degree of autonomy. But Slobodan Milosevic, the
Serbian leader who is now president of Yugoslavia, reimposed
Serbian rule. He sent in the troops last spring as a separatist
rebel movement began gaining headway. The resulting fighting caused
thousands of residents to flee their houses. Serbia is one of two
republics in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Serbian military columns headed by armored cars with
antiaircraft guns are almost the only traffic on the deserted main
roads that cut across and down Kosovo. Heavy weaponry is supposed
to be confined to military bases under the cease-fire. But the
Serbs have largely disregarded their commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Few ethnic Albanians dare risk traveling to the towns because
that means passing through Serbian police checkpoints, and the
occasional local bus carries few passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Off the main roads, along the muddy tracks that link farming
villages, armed guerrilla fighters pack into small private cars to
move around, and they appear at ease among the residents.
</P>
<P>
   There are two main points of persistent conflict, and both are
strategic areas for the Serbian forces, Podujevo in northern Kosovo
and Suva Reka in the south.
</P>
<P>
   In both, rebel positions lie within close range of Serbian
positions, and clashes are frequent. The hostilities have denied
the Serbian authorities complete control. The areas they control
south of the capital are largely empty of people, the houses
shell-scarred and burned, and the police posts sandbagged and
heavily guarded.
</P>
<P>
   Villages in rebel territory, by contrast, are swamped with
people. Samodrazae has doubled its size with refugees from
surrounding villages, among them new arrivals from weekend fighting
in Studenace.
</P>
<P>
   No one would go back while the Serbs remained in their positions
a mile away, said Sopi, who transported 17 relatives, including six
children, on his tractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another example that without NATO troops there will be
no peace,'' he said. ``Look at what happened here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
