<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNING PARTY IN MEXICO WINS 2 STATE ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The party of President Ernesto Zedillo won
decisive victories in two state elections on Sunday, showing how
resilient it remains after dominating Mexico for seven decades and
pointing up the vulnerability of a divided opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In the state of Quintana Roo, the governing party candidate,
Joaquin Hendricks, won the governor's post with about 43 percent of
the vote, preliminary results showed. The closest contender, Gaston
Alegre of the left-of-center Party of the Democratic Revolution,
known as the PRD, took 34 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The victories in Quintana Roo and a second state, Hidalgo, by
the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, were an
indication of its enduring strength in impoverished rural areas
where many farmers depend on the government dole for health care
and agricultural assistance.
</P>
<P>
   In Hidalgo, where the countryside is among the most desperately
poor regions of the country, the PRI candidate, Manuel Angel Nunez,
won by 53 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In that election the opposition paid a high price failing to
agree on a single candidate. The conservative National Action
Party, or PAN, refused to unite with the PRD, and both groups lost
ground. The PAN finished with 32 percent of the vote and the PRD
took only 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide polls show that the overall percentage of the PRI,
which has won every presidential election since the 1920s, is
declining and no longer has the favor of the majority. But it
continues to win elections, in spite of frequent accusations of
corruption, because the two major opposition parties split the
anti-government vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
