<HEADER>
A5075 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVERNORS-VENTURA-TEX     02-22 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVERNORS-VENTURA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BODY TAKES ON THE PRESS. NO CONTEST.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MARIA RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, former pro wrestler,
political newcomer and emerging media star, took on the Washington
press corps on Monday. It was a body slam.
</P>
<P>
   In a luncheon speech at the National Press Club, Ventura brought
his plain-speaking, tough-guy, outsider style to the
inside-the-Beltway crowd and tweaked the political establishment at
every opportunity. The crowd loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten to the point now with the press that when I say a
joke, I look at them and say, `That was a joke' _ so that they
understand it,'' Ventura said to the roars of a sold-out audience.
</P>
<P>
   The new governor, known as Jesse ``the Body'' Ventura in his
wrestling days, stunned political forecasters with his
come-from-behind win in a three-way race in November. The colorful
Minnesotan, a member of the Reform Party founded by Dallas
billionaire Ross Perot, has since captured the public imagination
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura was in Washington for the winter meeting of the National
Governors Association. The media throng that follows his every move
was rivaled only by the equally intense swarm that follows Texas
Gov. George Bush, a front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I are bonding,'' Bush said of Ventura when asked about
the ``other'' celebrity governor as the state executives' afternoon
session was about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good man,'' Bush went on. ``We had a great visit on the
bus on the way to the White House. As you know, we hammed it up for
the cameras a little bit. He's a breath of fresh air. I like him a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura and Bush did not see much of each other during the
weekend, but they seem to have hit it off. After the governors
visited President Clinton at the White House yesterday, Ventura and
other state leaders filed into a waiting bus to return to their
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush tarried with reporters, prompting the waiting governors
to dispatch the imposing and still well-built Ventura to fetch the
Texan. ``Come on, George, you got places to go,'' he said, making
his way to Bush's side. Bush introduced his new friend to the Texas
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Texas press corps?'' Ventura asked. ``Well, I
haven't met a Texan yet that hasn't told me about drinking dirty
water from a hoofprint. That's John Wayne from True Grit.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to Bush's relief, Ventura told the press club luncheon
that he would not run for president in 2000 but left open the
possibility of a later run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a commitment to the state of Minnesota that I wanted to
be their governor for four years. ... But 2004? Well, who knows?''
Ventura said. ``I could end up down the street here in that big
white house, or I could end up living in a hut on the beaches at
Kona,'' in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura and Bush attended a dinner at the White House Sunday
night with the other governors. The Minnesotan, who has often been
critical of President Clinton, seemed overwhelmed by the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased last night, my wife and I, to make our
first trip to the White House. And it was exceptional. It humbles
you. It makes you feel good you're an American,'' Ventura told the
press club audience.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to relate how he and his wife danced next to Clinton
and the first lady and the four of them later discussed Ventura's
first proclamation _ last week's Rolling Stones day, honoring the
veteran rock 'n' roll band's performance in his state. The governor
has a personal connection to the Stones _ he used to be their
bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura was not so kind to lobbyists, another favorite target.
``I come with no strings attached,'' Ventura said as he motioned
with his hand over his head.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesotan, elected on a shoestring budget of $400,000,
credited his name recognition for his success but called for
campaign finance reform to help other would-be politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't answer the question whether someone else can do it,''
he said. ``But I think what it does tell me is that in order for
someone else to do it we need campaign finance reform and we need
it badly.''
</P>
<P>
   He also took a jab at the major political parties. ``I think I
was a wake-up call to them,'' Ventura said of the Democrats and
Republicans. ``If I am not a wake-up call to them, I think they're
going to suffer more losses.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he was not going to take a leading role in
developing the Reform Party, adding: ``I have a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about more wrestlers running for office, Ventura said,
``Well, look at it this way. We've got certainly enough lawyers
there, and look what they've done. I don't think the wrestlers
could do any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Ron Hutcheson contributed to this report. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
