<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5080 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-WASHINGTON23-COX     02-22 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-WASHINGTON23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush skips media corps to talk with new political friends about
plans
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The voice rumbled through the frigid air like the
engine of one of the buses parked in the White House driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on George, we got places to go,'' former pro wrestler and
current Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura growled to his new friend,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, when the latter lingered on the lawn
after a governors' meeting Monday with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Ventura, Bush and his possible presidential bid
are dominating discussion here at the National Governors'
Association meeting. But while Ventura has played to the national
media, appearing on a Sunday morning television talk show and
donning a feathered and fringed leather jacket for the cameras,
Bush has declined talk show appearances and interviews with
national reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather talk to the Texas press _ that's what my job is,''
Bush said during a discussion with Texas reporters in his hotel
suite. ``I'm more interested in fulfilling my obligations to people
in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, the nation's only Reform Party governor, continued
headline-hunting Monday with a luncheon speech at the National
Press Club. He warned Democrats and Republicans that his improbable
win last November could be the harbinger of political things to
come. ``If I am not a wake-up call to them, I think they're going
to suffer more losses,'' Ventura said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is corralled by a mob of reporters whenever he enters
or leaves a meeting, has avoided political predictions of any kind.
Of himself, he would only repeat that he is ``warming to the task''
of a presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, another potential Republican White House
contender bowed out. Former California Gov. Pete Wilson, who made a
brief race for the 1996 presidential nomination, said he was
``compelled to conclude that it is just not practical to pursue a
candidacy'' next year.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson made no mention of Bush, but Sean Walsh, the
ex-governor's press aide, called the Texas governor a ``fresh,
interesting candidate on the national scene'' and said Bush's
popularity was a strong factor in Wilson's decision.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing _ not Wilson's exit, not the increasing support from
his fellow Republican governors and not polls showing him running
ahead of probable Democratic nominee Al Gore _ has moved Bush to
make any definitive statement about getting into the race.
</P>
<P>
   He remains officially undecided, but could form an exploratory
committee within weeks to begin raising money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behave yourself,'' he told a reporter who asked whether he was
measuring the White House windows for drapes during the meeting
with Clinton. ``I didn't take any silverware either.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Bush has been talking to his fellow GOP governors,
and perhaps others, about his presidential prospects. The governor
has skipped some of the official events to meet with unidentified
people about unspecified topics _ fueling speculation that he is
talking to GOP strategists and fund-raisers about a White House
bid. On Monday afternoon, he ducked out of an education seminar for
meetings on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Bush coyly deflected questions about a mysterious Saturday night
dinner, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't remember,'' he replied when asked about his dining
partner or partners. Bush wouldn't even reveal where he ate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give you a hint: You ever heard of a Big Mac?''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bush appears to enjoy the media attention he's
gotten at the conference _ for the most part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say that the rumors I'm hearing around here are totally
ridiculous,'' Bush said of capital speculation about youthful
indiscretions he has acknowledged but declined to catalogue. ``I
would hope that the Washington press corps would be careful about
gossip and rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also isn't enamored of the abstract policy discussions that
have dominated the official agenda here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like the old four corners in basketball before the
time clock: We just keep passing the issue around but nothing gets
resolved,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   As his old Harvard business school Professor Michael Porter
droned on about ``economic cluster-building'' at one Sunday morning
seminar, Bush spent much of the time whispering with his friend
Gov. John Engler of Michigan. When Porter mentioned Engler by name,
Bush quickly clammed up, straightening in his chair like a guilty
schoolboy.
</P>
<P>
   Even such policy-wonking sessions didn't offer a respite from
The Question. Engler has been talking to other GOP governors about
a Bush presidential bid, and he said Monday that ``indications are
good'' that Bush would earn the support of a majority of his GOP
colleagues if he decided to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you noticed today, but a couple of governors
came over in the midst of the discussion _ and they weren't telling
me to straighten my tie,'' Bush said. ``They were saying, 'What are
your plans?' and I was telling them about where I am in the
decision-making process.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting with Clinton offered more in the way of policy
specifics. Bush said the president and the governors discussed
whether the federal government should kick in more money for the
special education programs it mandates. They also talked about the
tobacco settlements won by Texas and other states, with the
governors urging Clinton not to let the federal government take any
of that money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was warning all along that the federal government may want
to get their clutches on some of the money I think ought to stay in
the state,'' Bush said. ``Now that we've got the settlement in
place, I'm strongly in favor of it staying in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Bush has made a new friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I are bonding,'' he said of Ventura. ``He's a breath of
fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press and Cox
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
