<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX-SCARE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anthrax scare empties offices hit by '97 bomb
 &HT;    By Brad Schrade
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The office building targeted with an abortion clinic
bomb two years ago got a scare Monday from an envelope that
resembled others containing anthrax hoaxes and sent to other U.S.
abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   An employee at Compassionate Services called police about 10:30
a.m. Monday to report that a suspicious letter _ which remained
sealed _ had arrived at the office building.
</P>
<P>
   Compassionate Services is an administrative office for Atlanta
Northside Family Planning Services, the abortion clinic bombed in
January 1997. It had received a fax bulletin last week from a
feminist group, warning of letters from ``PAACO Surgical
Instruments,'' which when opened contain threats of anthrax
exposure. At least 14 abortion clinics and Planned Parenthood
centers have received similar letters in the past week, including
one Monday in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The suspicious letter in Sandy Springs, a suburb northeast of
Atlanta, listed ``PAACO'' as the sender. Authorities evacuated the
Sandy Springs Professional Building for nearly three hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a police car, then the fire engines. I said, `Oh, no,
what's going on now?''' said businessman Dan Katz, whose office has
been in the building for five years and is next to Compassionate
Services. ``It's such an inconvenience. It ties up your day.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta hazardous material units turned the envelope over to an
FBI agent, who carried it away in a sealed clear plastic bag. It
was sent to be tested, but the FBI reported no findings.
</P>
<P>
   While employees milled about outside, the scene was a reminder
of the double bombing that occurred at the same three-story office
building Jan. 16, 1997. Some of the same police and firefighters
were there in 1997 when a second bomb exploded in the parking lot.
That bombing plot, along with the Centennial Olympic Park bombing
and others, has been tied by police to Eric Rudolph, now believed
to be on the lam in the North Carolina mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic, Atlanta Northside, moved to an undisclosed location
outside Sandy Springs after the bombing, but Compassionate Services
provides administrative support.
</P>
<P>
   An anthrax hoax had the metro area on edge Feb. 4, when a letter
sent to the NBC news bureau in a Midtown office building purported
to carry the deadly bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
