<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: STEWART SAYS CLEMENS HAS OCTOBER BAGGAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNEDIN, Fla. _ From the rear of a David Wells news conference
in which the only news was that Wells showed up, Dave Stewart
wasn't saying he preferred Wells on his pitching staff to Roger
Clemens. He merely wanted to point out that while Toronto now has a
proven postseason pitcher to anchor its staff, the Yankees may have
acquired, along with their five-time Cy Young Award winner, some
potential October baggage.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, Roger hasn't proved anything yet in a
postseason,'' Stewart said Monday, hiding two of the steeliest eyes
major league hitters have ever seen behind a pair of wraparound
shades. ``He hasn't been in the postseason in a while and when he
was, his teams weren't that successful. Fact is fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Should we blame the ace when his team gets hammered by a
superior opponent? Blame is too strong a word for what Stewart, in
his new role as the Blue Jays' assistant general manager, was
suggesting. Which was that Clemens has indisputably failed several
times to alter the playoff fate of the Boston Red Sox, to take the
ball and rise to a level that can't be measured by earned run
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I was just egotistical, but I always felt that I could
be and was the difference,'' said Stewart, a World Series winner in
Oakland and Toronto. ``Roger wanted to go someplace and be part of
something already set.''
</P>
<P>
   There is history between Stewart and Clemens, all of it, for
Clemens, ranging from annoying to depressing. A decade ago, Stewart
believed he deserved the Cy Young awards that Clemens was winning,
and turned their every matchup into Game 7. Stewart already had a
run of seven straight victories against Clemens, on Oct. 11, 1990,
a bizarre playoff afternoon in the bright sunshine of the Oakland
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Obscured somewhat in the excruciating way the Red Sox lost Game
6 of the 1986 World Series to the Mets was that Clemens didn't
exactly howl in anger over his removal with the lead, three innings
away from winning it all. Bostonians have their opinions, their
theories, but, above all, Clemens was young. It was his first
October.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, he didn't have that excuse when, ahead of the
A's and Stewart by 1-0 in Game 1 of the League Championship Series,
he handed the ball without protest to, gulp, Larry Andersen. The
Red Sox promptly surrendered that game, the next two and went back
to Clemens, on three days' rest, facing Stewart again and a
four-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely hyper that whole series, Clemens, a Red Sox coach
mused that day, was to the point of complete distraction. With a
run in in the second inning, his fastball not humming, Clemens
walked Willie Randolph on a 3-1 pitch that was clearly high, and
picked an argument with the umpire, Terry Cooney. They exchanged
the standard taunts, but Clemens soon after erupted with a string
of obscenities. Cooney ran him from the game.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart will do everything but sign a sworn affidavit to the
charge that this was clearly a case of Clemens shouting, a la
Duran, ``No mas.'' ``Something happened,'' he said. ``He blew.''
Stewart called it ``one of the worst things I've seen in
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the postseason ace, he said, is assuming responsibility
for all. It's the service game you can least afford to lose. You
battle. You scratch. You stick around. From the San Diego bench,
Stewart, the Padres' pitching coach, watched Wells do exactly that,
without his best pitch location, in Game 1 of the Series last year.
``He pitched deep enough into the game,'' he said. ``The cavalry
came. Once you get to the postseason, you just try to find a way to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't want to overdo the Psychology 101 _ ``I'll let you
decide,'' he said _ but there had to be a reason why Clemens, after
choosing Toronto's free-agent cash over George Steinbrenner's two
years ago, suddenly found the now-dominant Yankees to his liking
when exercising his contractual trade demand. The Yankees were not
his childhood dream, as they were for the crestfallen Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying he's trying to get anyone to carry him,''
Stewart said. ``That's tough to say. But I question it, not because
I'm with the Blue Jays but because, competitively, I pitched, I won
and helped build a club.
</P>
<P>
   ``This club here is so close to winning. If I've got the
opportunity to be the difference between winning and losing, I'm
going to go for that. There's more in that for me. He's great, a
Hall of Famer, but how much more can he add to the Yankees?''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Clemens can throw his October baggage on
board, and take a smoother postseason ride.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
