<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE TO SPEAK, SORT OF, LEWINSKY GIVES A LONG-SOUGHT INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Finally unmuzzled by the independent counsel Kenneth
Starr, Monica Lewinsky gave her exclusive interview to Barbara
Walters of ABC News on Saturday, although she was not permitted to
talk about the conduct of Starr's staff members toward her, ABC
executives said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under her immunity agreement with Starr, Ms. Lewinsky had to get
his permission to speak to any journalist. Ms. Walters and David
Westin, the president of ABC News, said in a telephone news
conference on Monday that Ms. Lewinsky had gained that permission
after agreeing to certain restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to not talking about the conduct of the independent
counsel's office, they said, she was forbidden to contradict any of
her grand jury testimony or to discuss any potential future legal
proceedings. She was also required to have a lawyer present.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Walters said Ms. Lewinsky was not allowed to describe the
events of the night of Jan. 16 when she was first questioned, for
hours, by prosecutors and the FBI. ``However,'' Ms. Walters said,
``everything that happened that night is a matter of record now,
and is something we can talk about,'' referring to plans to weave
taped segments into the interview to fill in parts of Ms.
Lewinsky's story.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Walters said Ms. Lewinsky had been ``very full and frank
about her emotions'' concerning the night of Jan. 16 and concerning
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The interview will be broadcast on Wednesday, March 3, from 9 to
11 p.m. ET on the program ``20/20.'' It took place at an ABC News
studio in New York, and lasted about three and a half hours,
interrupted by a lunch break. Westin said that the lawyer for Ms.
Lewinsky, Sidney Hoffman, had been on the set, ``at some distance,
but able to hear,'' and raised no objections during the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Walters said one answer from Ms. Lewinsky had surprised her.
Asked what was the toughest question she faced last year, Ms.
Lewinsky said it had come from a grand jury member who wanted to
know why she had a history of relationships with married men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 2036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
