</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-STEEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA AGREES TO ROLL BACK SALES OF STEEL TO U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W.Va.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration announced an agreement
with Russia on Monday to strictly control Moscow's surging exports
of steel to the United States, an effort to balance the bitter
complaints of American steelmakers with Washington's efforts to
keep from worsening Russia's economic slide.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord, Russia has agreed to roll back its sales of
steel to the United States to the amount it shipped in 1996 and the
first half of 1997, before the collapse of the country's currency
led to a surge of shipments. Steel production accounts for 7
percent of Russia's gross national product, and it is a huge source
of scarce hard currency for the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to respond to the steel industry's concerns
without bringing Russia to its knees,'' Commerce Secretary William
Daley said at a press conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the agreement left American steel companies and
steelworkers dissatisfied, and some in Congress are threatening to
press legislation that would virtually cut off steel imports
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, seeking to act ahead of Congress, the Commerce
Department ruled that steel from Japan and Brazil had been
``dumped'' in the American market _ sold at prices well below the
cost of production _ and announced that it would impose huge
tariffs against imports of hot-rolled steel from both countries.
The Department also concluded that Russian makers had dumped their
steel, but penalities were not announced because negotiations over
the agreement announced Monday were already under way.
</P>
<P>
   Assessing Russia's share of the American steel market is not
easy. By the end of last year foreign producers accounted for about
30 percent of all steel sold in the United States, up from about 20
percent the previous year. Russia accounted for about a third of
all the hot-rolled steel that surged into the American market last
year, but the Commerce Department says there are no reliable
estimates of how much of the market it commanded for other steel
products.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiating the agreement, Washington held most of the cards.
Russia's alternative was the imposition of the kind of tariffs
applied to Japan and Brazil, tariffs so steep that it would
essentially stop all the shipments. Instead, those shipments will
be reduced by about 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shipments from Russia of hot-rolled steel will come down to
levels that existed prior to 1996. Sixteen other types of steel
will be limited to levels in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``These agreements deliver on the administration's commitment to
respond vigorously to the surge in imports that has threatened the
livelihoods of communities and workers around the nation,'' Daley
said. But it also responds to the concerns of Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin, who has been involved in the International Monetary
Fund's negotiations over resuming aid to Russia, and of the
National Security Council, which fears that a further economic
breakdown in Moscow could further destabilize the government of the
ailing President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a legitimate concern about taking Russia to its
knees,'' Daley said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., complained that the Commerce
Department agreement will still permit the importation of too much
low-priced steel. Bethlehem Steel Corp. said the industry might
seek relief in federal court if the administration implements the
Russian accord. But the bigger threat to the administration's plans
is a bill now circulating in the House that would cap the amount of
foreign steel permitted into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's accord is exactly the kind of agreement that, in other
contexts, the administration has denounced as an interference with
market forces. For example, it sets an annual quota for hot-rolled
steel _ 750,000 metric tons, or slightly more than 20 percent of
the amount imported last year _ and sets minimum prices for the
steel. It also imposes a six-month moratorium on all imports of
hot-rolled steel, to work through a glut in the market.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Commerce said it would not impose penalty tariffs on
hot-rolled steel. Those could have ranged up to 218 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
