   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, Feb. 23. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) It's not only bricks and mortar we leave
behind when we move from one house to another, not if it's a home.
It's more like walking from a sunny spot and having your shadow
remain, unwilling or unable to follow you. I'm learning again
(though I've always known) that it's not enough for us simply to
have a place we can go to when it gets dark outside. It must also
be a place in which we can find our way when the lights go off. By
E.J. MONTINI Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
AMWESMAIN - (Tempe, Ariz.) Main news of America West rejecting
suitors, reaction from travelers, travel agents. Background on
what's happened in the last month and what exactly did CEO Bill
Franke say? By DAWN GILBERTSON and PETER CORBETT. Story will move
in the ``A'' cattegory. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RANCH (Phoenix) The Arizona Boys Ranch says a lengthy consultant's
report will be its roadmap to recovery. The Ranch plans to ask for
its license later this week. By PAT FLANNERY. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FEDS (Phoenix) When a Black man in Texas was dragged to his death
last year behind a pickup truck, the call went out for a federal
law against such vicious hate crimes even though state prosecutors
had already charged three White men with capital murder. Last week
a task force of the American Bar Association cited that case as an
example of a ``misguided, unnecessary and even harmful'' trend in
Congress to federalize crimes that have long been handled by state
and local authorities. By JERRY KAMMER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DIGNITY (Phoenix) At first, it was exciting. It was a lot of
attention for a girl with low self-esteem - cars honked when she
walked by, men whistled at the sight of her and ``boyfriends''
promised her anything and everything. And, of course, there was the
money and the drugs. But the glamorous life quickly faded as
Vicki's crack addition grew. She was beaten, robbed, raped. And at
six-months pregnant, she made a decision. Vicki, who asked her last
name not be used, was orderded to attend a diversion program for
one of many prostition arrests. A year later Vicki was off the
streets. The Dignity Diversion Program is a pilot program sponsored
by City Prosecutor's Office contracted with Catholic Social Service
aimed at providing support and services to help prostitutes get off
the streets. There are only a few other cities across the nation
that have similar programs, and none are as extensive as Dignity.
By CHRISTINA LEONARD. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
