A5107 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      02-22 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SUSPECT, 20, HAS ALIBI IN WIG SHOP SLAYING, ATTORNEY SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Filed in ``a'' and ``i'' categories) 
 
By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The attorney for a 20-year-old Texas man indicted in
the death of a wig shop employee claims his client is a victim of
mistaken identity and was playing football with friends when the
fatal stabbing occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Dror Haim Goldberg was indicted Wednesday in the Nov. 27 death
of Manuela Silverio, 54, at Wigs by Andre in Houston. The shop's
owners _ Roland Ingrando, 67, and his wife, Roberta, 55 _ were also
stabbed but survived.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Dick DeGuerin said Monday that he believes his
client may not know he is wanted in the slaying. He said family
members indicated Goldberg had been planning a backpacking trip to
the Middle East, perhaps in the Sinai Desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Goldberg) was very upset, at first, that he was arrested and
accused of what is apparently a case of misidentification,''
DeGuerin said. ``He was so upset that he didn't want to go to
school this semester and I assume he wanted to continue with his
plans to go backpacking.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg was studying hotel management at the University of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg's divorced parents issued a statement Monday asserting
they are not hiding their son and that he has not fled to Israel,
where his Israeli citizenship can protect him from extradition.
Goldberg's father is an obstetrician/gynecologist, and his mother,
Michele Goldberg, is an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   DeGuerin said Goldberg's parents are attempting to locate their
son because they want him to surrender to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   DeGuerin, who was hired by the Goldberg family the day after the
slaying, said Goldberg became a suspect after a license plate
number taken at the scene led investigators to a Lincoln Navigator
sports utility vehicle registered to a woman living with Goldberg's
father.
</P>
<P>
   DeGuerin said he believes the witness may have been mistaken in
taking down the license plate number. He said Goldberg was playing
football with friends at the time of the killing and that his
friends told this to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County Assistant District Attorney Chuck Rosenthal,
however, dismissed the alibi claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not true,'' Rosenthal said. ``He's got an alibi for later
but not for the relevant time when the murder occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said DeGuerin refused to let Goldberg testify before
the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Since Goldberg's indictment, his parents have declined to
discuss their son's case. In a one-page statement Monday,
Goldberg's parents answered allegations raised by Silverio's
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Silverio family has asked if we are hiding Dror Goldberg
from the authorities. We are not. Two months ago the police
questioned Dror for over six hours and then released him. They
never asked to see him again. They never asked him to remain in
Houston,'' the statement read.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Silverio Family has asked if Dror is in Israel. He is not.
The Israeli authorities have already told the police that Dror is
not in Israel. The police have chosen to keep this fact a secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Yvonne Palmer and Yvette Menendez, Silverio's
daughters, distributed leaflets asking the Goldbergs why their son
was in Israel and offered a $10,000 reward to anyone with
information that will lead to his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like the Police Department has dropped the ball
or that the District Attorney's office hadn't done something they
should have. It's just unfortunate how our system is run,'' said
Brendan Gowing, the Silverio family attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg was detained by police the night of the slaying,
questioned, gave a statement and was placed in a lineup before
eventually being released.
</P>
<P>
   Though Goldberg remained a suspect in the slaying, he was not
questioned again by police, who maintain they kept him under
surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Vice Consul Modi Ephraim released a statement Monday
confirming that Goldberg holds an Israeli citizenship, as does his
father. Under Israeli law, Israeli citizens are not extradited if
wanted on criminal charges elsewhere. Instead, they are tried for
the crime in an Israeli court.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to our police representative at the Embassy of
Israel in Washington, D.C., Dror Goldberg is not presently in
Israel,'' Ephraim said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Goldberg's family claims their son is not in Israel,
Goldberg was known to have returned from Israel shortly before the
slaying and returned to Israel about a week after the killing with
his grandparents, who live in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   DeGuerin said Goldberg spent about three weeks with his
grandfather, who has a heart condition, in Israel. Authorities
believe Goldberg returned to Israel in late January. DeGuerin said
Goldberg's grandparents do not know where their grandson went.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know his current whereabouts,'' said Homicide Capt.
R.W. Holland. ``We're basically throwing a wide net and looking for
him anywhere that the evidence leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that he skipped the country. We really don't know
where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
