<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5109 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS &LR;      02-22 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURER TAKES STEPS AMID `HEIR FINDER' SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY AND BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Moving to contain a growing financial scandal uncovered
in her office just weeks after assuming her new post, Treasurer
Shannon P. O'Brien ordered Monday a major overhaul of
Massachusetts' multimillion-dollar cash accounts.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day that a New Hampshire ``heir finder,'' Martin
Robbins, pleaded not guilty to bilking $6.5 million from the
Treasury's Unclaimed Check Fund, O'Brien said she was taking action
to prevent check forging and was filing legislation capping at 10
percent the unlimited finder fees bounty hunters can now charge for
uniting rightful owners with their money.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a three-person task force comprised of O'Brien, State
Auditor Joseph DeNucci and Comptroller Martin Benison will look for
other ways to ensure that the alleged embezzlement, aided by
20-year Treasury worker John Trischitta, never happens again.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office has assigned nearly a dozen State
Police troopers and office investigators attached to the criminal
division to work on the growing scandal. Officials said they are
making a thorough search of the circumstances under which millions
of dollars worth of checks had been issued from the Unclaimed
Checks Fund during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators are poring over the documents to determine if
Trischitta may have engaged in schemes with other heir finders.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, who was arraigned Monday, allegedly conspired with
Trischitta to divert the unclaimed funds into an escrow account at
BankBoston in November. A bank employee reportedly grew suspicious
about Robbins when he tried to withdraw the money on Feb. 10 and
tipped off Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, as O'Brien reiterated her criticisms of lax controls she
inherited at the Treasury, her predecessor, Joseph D. Malone,
defended his eight-year management of the office during a news
conference in his Waltham home.
</P>
<P>
   Malone called the alleged scam a failure of ``people, not
policy,'' and said that public and private auditors repeatedly had
given the department a clean bill of fiscal health.
</P>
<P>
   While the investigation is far from over, O'Brien did say that
the only person who may be fired at this point is Trischitta, 47,
who is on paid leave after being released on $10,000 cash bail
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta has worked in the Unclaimed Check Fund for much of
his 20-year career at the Treasurer's office. The Fund is
responsible for finding individuals or companies that are due
checks or reimbursement from the Commonwealth of Massachusetts for
services rendered to the state. Generally the fund holds the money
for a year before it is turned over to the Abandoned Property
division, which is also within the Treasurer's office, and is
responsible for finding the rightful heirs of bank accounts, stock
funds and other assets held by banks, brokerage firms, and
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   According to former officials of the Treasurer's office, the
Unclaimed Checks Fund has not been supervised to the same extent as
the Abandoned Property division. Trischittta, in fact, was the sole
full-time management employee of the Unclaimed Checks Fund office,
while the Abandoned Property division had about 20 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said that increasing pressure from heir finders, who were
seeking access to the unclaimed check list through Freedom of
Information requests, prompted the department to revise its
policies last summer. In exchange for access to the list, Malone
said, the heir hunters were required to provide a notarized power
of attorney from the person or company seeking the unclaimed money.
</P>
<P>
   Although Malone described this change as a tightening of the
restrictions, O'Brien Monday said that ``the impact may have been
to weaken the regulations.'' Among other things, the heir finders
would not be bound by a 10 percent cap on commissions they could
receive for finding owners of property listed in the state's
Abandoned Property Division.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, some of the heir finders turned their attention to
the Unclaimed Checks Fund, which operated far more loosely and was
far more lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe reported Monday that a small group of heir finders met
with top Malone officials including Deputy Treasurer Thomas
Trimarco last May and persuaded the Treasurer's office to make a
fundamental change on behalf of the heir finders. Trimarco denied
Monday that he attended the meeting but said that other Malone
officials had met with one heir finder and her attorney to help
streamline the fund's procedures for issuing checks. Trimarco said
that one change required that heir finders show that they represent
potential beneficiaries through a formal power of attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say Robbins apparently forged the name of a former
officer of the Cambridge Economic Development Corp. last year on a
power of attorney document that he submitted to Trischittta to
facilitate the issuance of the fraudulent checks.
</P>
<P>
   However, investigators, who intend to bring this case to a grand
jury, are now scrutinizing the process of how money was released
from the fund and say they are not focusing on any one individual.
</P>
<P>
   At his arraignment Monday, a scruffy Robbins pleaded not guilty
in Boston Municipal Court to charges of uttering and larceny. Judge
Herbert H. Hershfang, citing the seriousness of the charges that
could send Robbins to prison for 25 years, set bail at $50,000
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Carol Starkey told Hershfang
investigators found Robbins had a total of $7 million in his
BankBoston account when it was frozen earlier this month, the bulk
of which was the $6.5 million Robbins and his co-defendant,
Trischitta, are accused of stealing from the state.
</P>
<P>
   Starkey said Robbins, a frequent traveller with real estate
holdings and a time share condominium in Aruba, was in the process
of setting up ``heir finder'' businesses in New York and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Starkey said Robbins, of Lincoln, N.H., worked with Trischitta
to divert $6.5 million from the state's Unclaimed Checks Fund into
the escrow account that Robbins controlled. Trischitta was paid
$50,000 and promised a third of any other money Robbins recovered.
Starkey said Robbins submitted a forged power of attorney on behalf
of the Cambridge Economic Development Corp. to get the $6.5 million
released to him.
</P>
<P>
   But Robbins' attorney, Albert F. Cullen 3d, said his client
tried to return the money to the state on Feb. 11 when he became
concerned about the validity of his claim to it. Cullen said
Robbins had obtained the power of attorney from a man he identified
only as DeGregorio whom Cullen said ``purported to be the treasurer
of this organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Commonwealth now says that Mr. DeGregorio did not sign''
the power of attorney, Cullen said. ``We'll just have to wait for
the facts'' to come out during the criminal process.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Treasurer Michael Travaglini said investigators still do
not know who the $6.5 million rightfully belongs to, although the
check was believed to be for the Economic Development Industrial
Corp., an agency now controlled by the Boston Redevelopment
Authority. A BRA spokeswoman says they do not believe they are owed
any state money.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said that two officials -- Trischitta and a supervisor --
would have been needed to authorize the $5.3 million and $1.2
million checks sent to Robbins' escrow account. However, Malone
acknowledged, Trischitta might have simply told Robert Foley, his
department head, or Foley's deputy Amelia Viscomi, that he had the
necessary assurances to authorize the payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policy was two sets of eyeballs, two people agreeing on
it,'' Malone said. ``And whether it's Ms. Viscomi or Mr. Foley,
they should have said, when they saw that, `Before we hand this $5
million check over, let's make sure this is a valid claim.' ''
</P>
<P>
   One telephone call to the Cambridge Economic Development Corp.,
which has been defunct since 1986, would have blocked the alleged
scam, Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Travaglini said Monday that capping finders fees will help make
the fund less attractive to unscrupulous individuals who try to
manipulate the system.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci, in Washington attending the National
Governor's Conference, said he was ``stunned'' to hear about the
problems in the Treasurer's office and said he supports efforts to
institute tighter controls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff writers Stephen Kurkjian and John Ellement and States
New Service reporter Mark D. Preston contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
