u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GOVS-NYT &LR;      02-22 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GOVS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNORS ASK CLINTON TO STAY AWAY FROM TOBACCO SETTLEMENT MONEY
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican and Democratic governors told President
Clinton on Monday that they would work with him to improve
education and make politics more civil, but they also asked him to
keep his hands off the settlement money they have wrested from
tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply don't want the federal government telling us how to
use our money'' or itself spending that money, Gov. Thomas Carper,
D-Del., who is chairman of the National Governors' Association,
told the president at the White House on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration argues that the federal government is
entitled to some of the settlement as reimbursement for its share
of Medicaid costs attributable to smokers' illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton assured the governors, gathered here for their winter
meeting, that he would not insist on a cut for the federal
government provided they spent, in four related areas, the amount
on which Washington would otherwise insist: improving public
health, reducing teen-age smoking, benefiting children in
additional ways, and assisting tobacco farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But in his budget proposal, Clinton assumes that the federal
government will get $18.9 billion from the tobacco settlement to
spend for its own purposes from 2001 to 2004. That money is not
dedicated to any specific programs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, reached in November, 46 states are to
receive $206 billion from the tobacco industry over 25 years as
compensation for their share of Medicaid costs due to
tobacco-related illnesses. That money is in addition to settlements
of $40 billion or so reached earlier by the four other states:
Texas, Florida, Minnesota and Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is state money,'' Michael Leavitt, the Republican
governor of Utah, told Clinton. ``The federal government was
invited to participate'' in the suits that led to the settlements,
``but declined. We sought as states only costs related to state
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, said that by law
the federal government was required to recoup a share of the money.
``We can work toward waiving that requirement if the money is put
toward the appropriate uses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Carper, Leavitt struck a cooperative tone, over all. Many
of the governors here have bemoaned as lost time the lengthy
impeachment investigation and trial of Clinton. ``We as governors
join with you and others to call for a return of civility to
Washington,'' Leavitt said. ``We believe it's time to move forward
with an agenda that will move not only the capital but also our
states forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The two governors made their remarks in speeches in the East
Room of the White House on Monday morning, before they and their
peers sat down for more than an hour of private round-table
discussion with Clinton and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In politely differing on Monday over the federal role in
education, the president and the governors demonstrated how
different Washington can look from the White House and a
statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   In his own public remarks before the discussion, Clinton urged
the governors to support his bill to attach strings to the $15
billion the federal government spends yearly on public education.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for that money, Clinton would demand that school
districts turn around or shut failing schools, enforce discipline
codes, produce report cards on schools, check teacher competence
and end the practice known as ``social promotion,'' passing
children to the next grade regardless of achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The president was careful to note that many governors, including
Republicans, had made such changes. ``We did not dream up these
ideas in Washington,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that some people might feel the federal
government should be giving states more flexibility rather than
demanding more accountability. But he said he was doing both.
</P>
<P>
   Some governors, however, suggested that Clinton was talking more
about accountability than flexibility. ``We believe that linking
federal investment to specific local programs is unhelpful,''
Leavitt said. He said the federal government should invest ``as a
limited partner, not as the managing partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Carper said the governors were forming a bipartisan task force
to consider Clinton's education proposal. He said that they hoped
to find a consensus ``between those who simply want to be more
prescriptive with federal aid and those who simply want to turn
federal aid over to block grants directly to school districts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think we can find some middle ground,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
