<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EVERGLADES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL WILL MONITOR PLAN FOR THE EVERGLADES
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After meeting with scientists who have criticized a projected
$8-billion plan to restore the Florida Everglades to ecological
health, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt on Monday in Washington
announced the establishment of an independent scientific panel to
evaluate the plan as it evolves.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's members, yet to be appointed, will be expected to
serve for three or four years and ``will be individuals who are not
personally involved in South Florida research and monitoring
activities,'' Babbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists who met with Babbitt said the action satisfied
their basic aim, to insure that the plan was subjected to scrutiny
by experts not involved in formulating it.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stuart L. Pimm, an ecologist at the University of Tennessee,
has criticized the plan, which is to be submitted to Congress for
approval in July, on the ground that it does not go far enough
toward re-establishing the natural, north-to-south flow of shallow
water that historically controlled the character and ecological
health of the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Pimm and other ecologists wanted an
independent review to determine the degree to which the Everglades
might realistically be restored, given all the alterations to the
South Florida landscape in the last century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
