<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-LABELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THURMOND SEEKS TO BLOCK LABELS HINTING AT WINE'S BENEFITS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a move that may foreshadow a bitter struggle
over government policies on alcohol, Sen. Strom Thurmond introduced
legislation on Monday that would bar ``health messages'' on wine
bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond, a South Carolina Republican, said he wanted to reverse
the ``erroneous and irresponsible'' action of the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, which on Feb. 5 approved two new
bottle labels requested by the wine industry that encourage
consumers to learn about the benefits of drinking wine.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation proposed by Thurmond would also transfer
authority over labeling to the Department of Health and Human
Services from the Treasury Department, and would raise taxes on
wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, I do not favor increased taxes,'' Thurmond said,
``but in this era of shrinking budgets, the only way in which we
will be able to finance adequate, impartial and trustworthy
research into alcohol-induced diseases such as hypertension, breast
cancer and birth defects is to generate a new revenue flow that
will be used specifically for investigating such killers.''
</P>
<P>
   John De Luca, the president and chief executive of the Wine
Institute, a trade association, said the wine industry would fight
Thurmond's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can argue the merits if it comes to that,'' De Luca said,
asserting that an objective reading of the dietary guidelines
published by the Departments of Agriculture and Health and Human
Services would show that there were health benefits as well as
drawbacks to drinking wine.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond's proposals are sure to face big hurdles because the
wine industry is well financed and capable of mounting a formidable
campaign against legislation it does not like. On the other hand,
Thurmond, as the senator with the most seniority, has considerable
influence. Another powerful senator, Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., also
spoke unsuccessfully against allowing the kind of labels approved
on Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Although the wine industry had long sought permission to attach
promotional labels to bottles, the label texts approved by the
alcohol bureau, a division of the Treasury Department, are neutral
in tone.
</P>
<P>
   They invite people to consult the dietary guidelines, which warn
of the dangers of alcohol but also cite evidence that moderate
drinking may lower the risk of heart disease. The guidelines also
note that alcohol has been used ``to enhance the enjoyment of
meals'' throughout history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 2102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
