<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-GREECE-NYT &LR;      02-22 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-GREECE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY AND GREECE TRADE WORDS OVER KURD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Turkey and Greece traded harsh words Monday
as the crisis over a captured Kurdish guerrilla commander further
soured already tense relations between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurdish commander, Abdullah Ocalan, whose fighters have been
waging war against the Turkish army for 14 years, was seized by
Turkish commandos last Monday night in Kenya, where he had been
living clandestinely under the protection of Greek diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   President Suleyman Demirel of Turkey said Greek leaders ``must
be made to explain to the international community how they came to
support a terrorist murderer who has killed thousands of people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Greece should be added to the list of countries that support
terrorism and harbor terrorists,'' Demirel said in a television
interview Monday on a visit to the Philippines. ``A country like
that can only be described as an outlaw state. If Greece continues
its illegal behavior, we reserve the right given to us by
international law to take the necessary measures for legitimate
self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Demirel made his statement a day after Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem said his government would ask the European Union to review
Greece's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the European Union to seriously examine the case of
one of its members, which has violently opposed the organization's
charter, commitments and obligations,'' Cem said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Turkey was also considering issuing a complaint against
Greece at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Foreign Minister George Papandreou of Greece
asserted that Turkey was trying to turn Greece into a scapegoat for
its Kurdish problem and urged Turkey to solve the problem quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not, I fear spiraling into further destabilization, further
problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Greek Foreign Ministry, Dimitris Reppas,
asserted that Turkey was ``trying to plot against Greece with
imprecise statements and tall tales.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkey is inventing an external enemy to distract the
international community from the fundamental problem of
acknowledging and respecting the human rights of the Kurdish
people,'' Reppas said. ``It is presumptuous of Turkey to make
accusations when it illegally occupies half of Cyprus and
systematically violates legal and human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting in Luxembourg Monday, European Union foreign
ministers issued a statement saying that the union took ``note of
the assurances of the Turkish government that Abdullah Ocalan will
have a fair trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It expects this to mean fair and correct treatment and an open
trial according to the rule of law before an independent court,
with access to legal counsel of his choice and with international
observers admitted to his trial,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish officials have said they will not permit observers from
foreign organizations to attend Ocalan's trial. They have also
indicated that he is most likely to be tried by a ``state security
court,'' a special tribunal presided over by a panel of judges that
includes a military officer.
</P>
<P>
   The European Court of Human Rights has described those courts as
neither fair nor independent.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish Bar Association urged Monday that Parliament be
called into session from a recess to amend the law that governs
such tribunals by eliminating the military judges. The lawyers'
group said such a change was necessary ``to prevent the verdict
from being subject to any disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   A Turkish newspaper with close ties to the military, Hurriyet,
published what it said were statements that Ocalan has given to
interrogators. The newspaper reported that Ocalan had said had
Greece supported his group for years, provided it with missiles and
other weapons and trained its fighters at camps on Greek soil.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Ocalan have not been allowed to visit him at his
island prison, and it was not possible to verify his reported
statements or to determine the conditions under which they were
made. Greek leaders have in the past denied allegations that their
government aided Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
   In Diyarbakir, center of the Kurdish region of Turkey, some
shopkeepers reportedly shut their doors in response to an appeal by
a group that supports Ocalan's rebels. The group called for a
three-day business strike in leaflets that warned, ``Those not
joining the protest will be punished.''
</P>
<P>
   News agencies reported that police officers with megaphones
ordered shopkeepers to open for business. Diyarbakir and the rest
of southeastern Turkey have been closed to foreign journalists.
Several have been turned away on landing at the Diyarbakir airport
in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said he hoped the effect of the
Ocalan affair in Greece, where it has cost three Cabinet ministers
their jobs, would sober Greek leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political turmoil that has recently erupted in Greece has
shown that involvement with terrorism against Turkey is bound to
have a boomerang effect,'' Ecevit said. ``I hope that Greek
politicians will come to realize that dialogue with Turkey would be
a much safer way of addressing common problems than supporting
terrorism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
