<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Tuesday, Feb. 23, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet at 206-448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   AIRREPAIR-TRAMCO (Everett, Wash.) _ Federal aviation safety
inspectors, warning of dangerously incompetent work on dozens of
jetliners, last summer tried to temporarily shut down Tramco, one
of North America's largest independent aircraft repair stations.
The chief FAA inspector assigned to the sprawling plant called the
facility, which worked on 421 aircraft last year, ``a disaster
waiting to happen.'' And in July, FAA inspectors wrote agency
lawyers that Tramco's ``violations raise significant concerns for
safety and clearly raise the potential of a catastrophic failure
leading to a crash.'' But their bosses ruled against pulling the
company's FAA license to operate.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider and Lisa Olsen. (Story will move in the
``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRREPAIR-ACCIDENTS (undated) _ Government investigators have
reported that the work performed in aircraft repair stations have
been identified as a factor in several aircraft accidents.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TRIBAL-FETAL-DEATHS (Tokeland, Wash.) _ Something is killing the
future of the tiny Shoalwater Bay Tribe. A generation is being
wiped out in the womb, and nobody knows why. Of 13 pregnancies in
1997 and 1998, only one baby is alive today. It is a statistic so
startling that last month, a team of investigators from the
national Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta
descended on this southwest Washington reservation.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Shukovsky. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FALL-FASHION (New York) _ Pale colors, sleek silhouettes, A-line
skirts, luxe sportswear for evening and knee-high boots (flat or
with heels) are key to fall '99 fashions. Those messages were sent
by designers to retailers and media gathered here to preview their
collections. But the best message of all is these are very wearable
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   By Susan Phinney. (Story has moved in the ``l'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   HAHN-COLUMN (Undated) _ As you are reading this, I am about to
do to my guts what your mechanic does when he boils out your
radiator and back-flushes your cooling system. They call it a
pre-surgical catharsis. You and I would call it a real pain in the
whatchamacallit. But my innards must be squeaky clean for
tomorrow's surgery to remove a couple of polyps from my colon.
</P>
<P>
   By Jon Hahn. (Story has moved in the ``l'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-WILLOW (Undated) _ Much has been made of the strong
independent women of The WB, women like Sarah Michelle Gellar
(Buffy the Vampire Slayer) and Keri Russell (Felicity). But lost in
the shuffle is Alyson Hannigan, who plays the bookish Willow on
``Buffy.''
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-THIEL-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Shaq, shut up and play. The NBA is
full of officiating injustices and Shaquille O'Neal, the Lakers
center claiming persecution, benefits as much as he suffers.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
