<HEADER>
A5127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-625&AMP;     02-22 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS REJECT OLIVETTI'S BID FOR TELECOM ITALIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The $60 billion bid by Olivetti SpA, the No. 2 Italian
phone company, for its big domestic rival, Telecom Italia SpA, met
a serious setback on Monday, when Italian stock market regulators
ruled the bid inadmissible.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the regulators said Olivetti's bid, which was
hastily approved by the Olivetti board Saturday, was contingent on
the sale of Olivetti assets and lacked clear deadlines, thus
failing to meet requirements set by Italian takeover law.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti contested the ruling on Monday night and announced that
it would move ahead with its bid for Telecom. In a statement,
Olivetti said its bid contained ``all the necessary characteristics
to produce the desired effects.'' Olivetti said it had been forced
to make an early decision because of market rumors. The company's
determination seemed to indicate that serious legal wrangling lay
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Olivetti's declaration, for the moment the ruling
appeared to allow Telecom time to take measures that would sharply
raise the price of Olivetti's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom's chairman, Franco Bernabe, was set to meet with union
leaders on Wednesday and with Telecom's board on Thursday to
propose sweeping plans to overhaul the former state phone monopoly,
plans that would include a buyout of shares in Telecom's mobile
phone unit that it does not now own, people close to the company
said. The unit, Telecom Italia Mobile, or TIM, now has a market
value of almost $50 billion. Telecom now holds a 60 percent share
in TIM, and by increasing that share, it would raise the market
value of the parent company, thus increasing the price Olivetti
would have to pay to take it over.
</P>
<P>
   Also under consideration would be Telecom's divestiture of such
noncore activities as phone equipment manufacturing, real estate
and an insurance subsidiary, the same people said.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom has moved quickly since Saturday, when it was confronted
with Olivetti's hostile bid, to engage investment bank advisers
that included Credit Suisse First Boston, Lazard Freres, J.P.
Morgan and the Italian investment bank Banca IMI SpA. The steps
planned by Bernabe are expected to include overtures to British
Telecom and AT&AMP;T to include Telecom Italia in strategic alliances,
with possible equity stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, stock market investors had given the
Olivetti bid a black eye, sending Olivetti's share price down more
than 7 percent, after the company announced its board would meet
Wednesday to approve a capital increase to finance the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti's bid also appeared to lose ground in Italian
government circles, as the negative market reaction and details of
the bid, involving cash, stocks and bonds, sank in.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema of Italy,
who appeared last week to favor the Olivetti bid, said the
government, which holds a decisive ``golden share'' in Telecom,
would remain neutral.
</P>
<P>
   But the most serious blow came from the stock market regulator,
CONSOB, which had been under pressure to decide on the validity of
the Olivetti bid.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom's board had rejected the bid on Saturday as ``full of
holes,'' and hence null, and demanded a ruling on its validity.
</P>
<P>
   In trading before the CONSOB decision Monday, Telecom's ordinary
share price soared 11 percent, then fell back in later trading,
buoyed by market perceptions that Telecom would fight back.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, CONSOB said Olivetti had made its takeover bid
contingent on the sale of its mobile and fixed-line phone units,
Omnitel Pronto Italia and Infostrada, to its phone business
partner, the German giant Mannesmann AG, and that it had failed to
provide exact deadlines for its bid _ both shortcomings, CONSOB
ruled, that rendered the bid invalid under Italian law.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For its part, Olivetti moved Monday to secure almost 98 percent
of Tecnost SpA, the gaming machine unit it said it would use to
start the bid, sending Tecnost shares soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti made its name as a nimble manufacturer of typewriters.
Acquired from the founding Olivetti family by the flamboyant
investor Carlo De Benedetti, it reinvented itself as a computer
company. Under its present chairman, Roberto Colaninno, who also
engineered the takeover bid for Telecom, the company transformed
itself again as a provider of mobile and fixed-line phone services.
</P>
<P>
   Even before CONSOB's decision, Olivetti appeared to be running
into serious market resistance to its proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said institutional investors shied from the Olivetti
bid, which involves raising about $50 billion through debt and
asset sales, because it would make Telecom cash-poor at a time when
phone companies need deep pockets to finance investment. One German
analyst said Monday that the price Mannesmann was offering for
Olivetti's mobile and fixed-line systems suggested that Olivetti
itself was overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that other objections to the Olivetti bid were
that the price Olivetti offered for Telecom ordinary shares, about
10 euros a share, or $11, was too low. ``They would be getting the
company on the cheap,'' said Douglas White, telecommunications
analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
