<SLUG> BC-BBA-JAYS-WELLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST WORD FROM WELLS, A YANKEE NO MORE, IS UNPRINTABLE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNEDIN, Fla. _ David Wells began a news conference to trumpet
his arrival with the Toronto Blue Jays by admonishing one newspaper
and two television stations with a forceful expletive for visiting
his house after he had been traded from the Yankees last Thursday.
Two officials from the Blue Jays cringed. It would have been more a
stunning display if the words spilled out of the mouth of someone
other than the wacky Wells.
</P>
<P>
   But Wells has always described himself as a rebel who does what
he wants to do, so Monday he basically did what he wanted to do.
Wells playfully acted as if he were about to lose control of the
steering wheel of his sport utility vehicle and almost clip
reporters when he eased into the Englebert Complex on Monday
morning. He laughed and lifted his middle finger at photographers
as he gave a blood sample a few hours later. Different team, same
Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting the brilliant red cap and bright blue pitching jacket
of the Jays, Wells, the man who adored the simple pinstripes of the
Yankees, looked garish sitting behind a table inside an interview
tent. Before Wells criticized members of the news media, he pulled
out the microphone jack from one of the stations that had offended
him. Then the pitcher who David Cone had called ``beyond
depressed'' tried to convince everyone the healing process has
started. Started, not ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a childhood dream for me wanting to be a Yankee,''
Wells said. ``Getting the opportunity, it's a tough situation to
leave. Trades are trades. I have no say so. I have to move on. I
can let things go. It was tough, but life goes. I think Toronto got
the better of the deal, to be honest with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical Wells. The Yankees grabbed a future Hall of Famer in
Roger Clemens for Wells, Graeme Lloyd and Homer Bush, and they are
happy. Wells, who scooted from Tampa to Miami to find solace and
play golf after the trade, tried to talk tough and appear happy.
But it was easy to see and hear the disappointment in his eyes and
in his voice and realize this is a player who will miss being a
Yankee and miss being a New Yorker. ``I could understand David
being upset,'' Lloyd said. ``He  &UR; was &LR;  New York last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Cone said that Wells' emotions had gravitated from
``shock to anger'' when the two spoke on Sunday night, Wells was
careful not to criticize anyone affiliated with the Yankees. Not
yet, anyway. Wells would never criticize George Steinbrenner, but
he said the owner had told him that General Manager Brian Cashman
made the trade. Wells has squabbled with Manager Joe Torre, so
either one of them could become verbal targets for the 35-year-old
pitcher in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the enemy,'' said Wells, speaking of the Yankees. ``My
feelings I had there, they're my heart, mind and soul. I had a
great time. It was fun while it lasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells said he hoped that the Jays and the Yankees battle for the
American League pennant and that he secured his third World Series
ring. He said he was not bothered that he did not have a no-trade
clause and reiterated that he wanted to face Clemens whenever
Toronto opposes New York so he can ``do my magic'' at Yankee
Stadium. That matchup could happen since Gord Ash, Toronto's
general manager, repeated that he has no plan to trade Wells
because the Jays believe they can reach the postseason. ``There's
been a lot of conversations, a lot of rumors about the Blue Jays
moving David along,'' said Ash, whose club released Wells in 1993.
``That's not something we're going to do. That's not something
we're contemplating.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, every time Wells, the new Jay, claimed to be over the
Yankees, he would slip and say something that proved he was not. It
was such an emotionally wrenching deal that it took Wells four days
to even discuss it. Monday, Wells praised the Yankees the way a fan
from the bleachers would.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to leave that group we had,'' Wells said. ``I
loved every one of those guys. They were my brothers. When you get
close and you feel comfortable and, all of a sudden, there's a
change, obviously, you need a few days to get over it. I can move
on. I can forgive and forget. Forgive and forget, I think will take
a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But Wells followed those slightly angry words by saying
of the Yankees: ``Everything over there was grand. It was awesome.
But I've got to move on and try to make things as comfortable and
as admirable as it was last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than Cone, Wells said he has not spoken to any other
Yankees since he was traded. Wells was definitely more popular with
the fans that he called ``very crazy'' than he was in the Yankee
clubhouse. With Clemens, a five-time Cy Young Award winner, taking
Wells' spot, Wells will miss the Yankees more than they miss him.
It was a splendid ride for Wells, but it ended abruptly and Wells
must digest that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I was very depressed,'' Wells said. ``I love New York.
They made me feel welcome. They made me proud to be there. I wanted
to be there. It's just something that's a shock when you've been
traded. I didn't expect to go anywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
