<HEADLINE>
PATTERNS: FALL SHOWS HANG ON IN NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fashion industry and New Yorkers may think that
with the shows ending last Friday, they have put the fall 1999
collections behind them. Not so fast. What was initially to have
been a few stragglers showing in April has turned into a full-blown
fashion event, organized for the most part by South of Seventh.
</P>
<P>
   South of Seventh, which began last season as a breakaway group
of small downtown design houses sponsored by the SoHo and TriBeCa
Partnerships, said it hopes that 31 designers will participate in
the event, from April 7 through 9. By Monday, 28 had been signed
up, said Vicki Ross, the organizer of South of Seventh.
</P>
<P>
   There will be three show sites, two at the Puck Building and one
nearby at St. Patrick's Old Cathedral. An exhibition area will also
be provided for accessories and beauty products.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Beene heads the list of designers showing, a king among
plebeians.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Blass will show in April, too, probably in his showroom or
at Le Cirque 2000, Yvonne Miller, his spokeswoman, said Monday. But
she said he had not finally chosen a place or date.
</P>
<P>
   Beene has always been supportive of young, up-and-coming talent.
Among the other designers expected to show over the three days are
Robert Danes, William Calvert and Todd Thomas and more experienced
hands like Joan Vass and Neil Bieff.
</P>
<P>
   Designers will pay $1,000 to $3,000 to participate, compared
with the $6,000 to $25,000 it takes to show under the Seventh on
Sixth tents in Bryant Park. ``These shows are so expensive,'' Ms.
Ross said. ``I see why Seventh on Sixth has to charge what they
do.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 9, the last day of South of Seventh, two group shows
will open to the public at $25 to $500 a ticket. Part of the
expense of South of Seventh is being defrayed by those shows, and
part by sponsors like New York magazine; Alu, an Italian display
company, and the SoHo and TriBeCa Partnerships. Any extra funds
that are raised will go to the two community partnerships, social
services organizations that help the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   A SHIRT MODELS A MODEL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russell Simmons has made his name as a businessman, but who knew
he was also a romantic? His latest venture combines both instincts.
He has turned the attractive image of his new wife, Kimora Lee
Simmons, a model who graced runways last week, into a print for a
new line of camp shirts at his Phat Farm fashion company.
</P>
<P>
   The oversize shirts, which arrived in his SoHo store this month
and cost $65, feature photo images of Mrs. Lee Simmons' face and
body in muted colors. Simmons was uncharacteristically speechless
when asked about the print. He's not sure why he did it, he said,
adding, after some thought, ``It's a conversational print.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does Mrs. Lee Simmons think of her husband's homage to
her _ or exploitation, if you're a cynic. ``I think it's sweet,''
she said. ``I'm glad it sells, and I'm waiting on a check, which
I'll never get, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't know that there's underwear, too,'' Simmons said.
That arrives in May.
</P>
<P>
   THE MUSEUM'S NEW CLOTHES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Costume Institute at the Metropolitan Museum of Art
wanted to step back and assess all it had collected in the last 10
years, it decided that the best way was to mount an exhibition
around that theme. The result, ``Our New Clothes: Acquisitions of
the 1990s,'' opens April 6 and runs through Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our New Clothes'' will include old ones, too. The emphasis is
on styles the museum has acquired in the last decade, not styles
designed in the last decade. There is room for some confusion. As
Richard Martin, the Costume Institute's curator, explained, a
creamy white frock from the rococo period in the 18th century will
stand side by side with a 20th-century white Gucci gown with steel
belt designed by Tom Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Designs by Martin Margiela, Ann Demeulemeester, Giorgio Armani,
Giorgio Sant'Angelo, Todd Oldham, Rei Kawakubo and several dozen
more will also be on display. An ``American Heroes'' theme will
focus on Geoffrey Beene, Calvin Klein and the late Sant'Angelo, who
was discovered and championed by Diana Vreeland, a predecessor of
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The museum came by its Kawakubo sample by way of Barneys New
York, which is sponsoring this show, its first major fashion
exhibition. Recalling an encounter with Jason Weisenfeld, vice
president for publicity at Barneys, Martin said: ``Two years ago at
a Barneys Warehouse sale, I had a bag of goodies including a Comme
des Garcons piece, and as I went to the checkout, Jason said:
`Don't go to the checkout. Let me take that from you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It arrived the next morning wrapped in a Barneys box as a gift
to the museum.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, more than 100 garments, will cover women's and
men's clothing with a couple of children's pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The institute has not had an exhibition of recent acquisitions
since the 1940's, Martin said. ``We have textbook examples of the
history of fashion,'' he said. ``We want to show that we are ready
to write about the history of fashion. It proves the value of a
museum collection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
