<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PEONY-$ADV28-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAVILION WHERE HARMONY LIVES: SELLARS' TAKE ON A CLASSIC  CROSSES
CULTURAL LINES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB GRAHAM  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. &LR;   &LR; _ Please don't call it ``a Chinese opera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Peony Pavilion,'' in the production that opens March 5 at
Zellerbach Hall in Berkeley, is ``an American avant-garde opera,''
in the words of its composer, Tan Dun.
</P>
<P>
   Director Peter Sellars picks up the thought and, being Sellars,
runs with it. ``You're watching the future of Chinese culture,
which is being made outside China.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Peony Pavilion'' is having its American premiere in Berkeley
after performances last year in Vienna and Paris. For many, the Cal
Performances presentation promises to be the music-theater event of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of ``Peony Pavilion'' is the intermingling dreams of
a pair of ``star-crossed'' young lovers _ the reference to
Shakespeare is deliberate. A privileged 16-year-old girl dreams of
her ideal lover and after her death by starvation _ starved for
love in the midst of plenty _ the lover, a poor scholar,
hallucinates her ghost and restores her to life. ``It's three
nights of making love to a ghost,'' Sellars says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This piece could not have been done in China,'' he says, and
by that he means created there today. ``This big question of
tradition/innovation, of generations looking for expression, is
very difficult to arrive at in China.''
</P>
<P>
   He does want, nonetheless, to take this production there for the
millennium, where he hopes it will be welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   Welcoming is a big thing with Sellars. He hugs complete
strangers upon meeting them. It is bright-eyed friendliness on his
part, but it also seems to be a matter of conviction. Sellars would
like to welcome everyone in the world into the tent of
intercultural collaboration _ but they have to want to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can no longer discuss culture in nationalistic terms,'' he
says. ``This goes way beyond a sense of national identity or
flag-waving. The world is so complicated and so interestingly
interdependent and interwoven that it's world culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Peony Pavilion'' is in Mandarin and English. It is spoken,
sung and danced by different performers representing the same
characters. It is in two parts. The first could loosely be called
traditional, the second anything but. It uses video but no
traditional Chinese costumes. It is also very erotic. Sellars calls
it ``just a luscious, beautiful, romantic evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on a classic Chinese text, this production was inspired
by, and is built around, Madame Hua Wenyi, a former Shanghai opera
star who now lives in Los Angeles, where she is a neighbor of
Sellars'. Small world.
</P>
<P>
   The music was written by Tan, who was born in Hunan and now
lives in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Hua's role is doubled by Lauren Tom, a Chicago-born actress
(``The Joy Luck Club'') of Chinese descent, and by Shanghai soprano
Ying Huang.
</P>
<P>
   Collaboration is a key to Sellars' work. While the Metropolitan
Opera is a cultural institution built by immigrants, he says, ``I'm
very interested in a generation of immigrants that now is changing
American culture. Here's Tan Dun living in the United States
writing music that has to be characterized as American music.
Here's Madame Hua no longer in China but having to find a language
with which to communicate across the generations with a Chinese
American actress who does not speak Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both Chinese and they're from completely different
universes. This performance is the story of them finding a way in
which both of their lives include each other in their future. And
so it becomes American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``In China, Tan Dun and Hua would never have met. They are
working different sides of the street _ Tan Dun in this avant-garde
direction, Hua representing the tradition. So the future of Chinese
culture becomes an urgent discussion for them to have in
performance _ but not in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Sellars calls this ``an extraordinary cultural crossroads.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In China, they would not meet because their worlds would not
touch. Whereas in America, everything's available, everything could
happen next.''
</P>
<P>
   Sellars, beaded and braceleted, has become a familiar figure on
the University of California at Berkeley campus. ``I Was Looking at
the Ceiling and Then I Saw the Sky,'' his collaboration with
composer John Adams and poet June Jordan, was seen there in 1995,
and he has been teaching a class this semester.
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident that Sellars, who is on the cusp of 40, lives
in Los Angeles. He went there originally to run the Los Angeles
Festival and stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Los Angeles. It's so important for my work. It's the
future of America being played out in the streets every day. I
admire New York. I lived there for years, but to me it's like
Paris. It's nostalgic, how things used to be. Los Angeles is the
edge. It's the city that erupted in flames a few years ago. It's
the city where what is happening is really happening.''
</P>
<P>
   He lives there by himself. ``You know, at the moment it's fine.
I'm a very social being, and every day I'm in the room with
extraordinary people at a level of very intense emotional
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also important to have a little space in my life. My life
is very intensely engaged with people all over the world. I'm on
the road half the year. I think that's part of my nature. Certain
people have a nomadic streak. That is the nature of the work and
always has been. It's not exactly about settling, but it comes from
something that is unsettled but looking for another way to
understand what home might be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
