<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5151 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-FASHION-I-ART-N     02-22 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-FASHION-I-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCHEDULED STOP AT UTILITARIANISM
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one is better than Calvin Klein at seizing the moment, which
in New York, at least, means a certain expensive simplicity, a
certain standard of grooming, and a certain fanatical eye for the
differences between, say, felted wool and plain old wool. It's all
very precise, like engraving the Manhattan skyline on the head of a
pin, and Klein, whose show effectively closed the New York fall
season last Friday, proved with sleek sportswear that he's still in
the groove.
</P>
<P>
   But so what? This is 1999, hardly a year to preserve the status
quo with conscientious minimalism _ black and white monochromes of
perfectly styled glamour, which, when considered next to the
looming vitality of the millennium, look like Oreo crumbs scattered
on a long white banquet table.
</P>
<P>
   Klein may have felt embarrassed by the millennium hype, and so
confined himself to a few choice words in his program notes, like
``uniforms'' and ``modern utility,'' to convey the future. But that
just means that Klein and Donna Karan, who also showed Friday,
arrived at utilitarianism on schedule _just when Rudi Gernreich,
the late fashion futurist from California, predicted it would
happen some 25 swinging years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, only a handful of designers last week stepped forward
to deal with the millennium, and the emotions associated with it,
in a bold, imaginative way. One thinks of Helmut Lang, mixing the
romantic militarism of Elgar's ``Pomp and Circumstance,'' written
at the turn of this century, with a ferocious montage of molded
leather trousers, shag fleece vests and coats the color of the
flaming orange space suits in ``Armageddon.'' A couple of people
actually said they got chills watching the show, although that
probably had more to do with the imperial strains of Elgar. Lang
said he got the idea for the music from ``A Clockwork Orange.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just pushed the presentation to another level, basically,''
he explained. ``But there's only one millennium, so you might as
well go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   One also thinks of Daryl Kerrigan, whose militant urbanism now
places her in fashion's vanguard, and, to a lesser extent, of Marc
Jacobs, John Bartlett and Stephen Sprouse, who went straight to
NASA for his futuristic, 3-D tableaux, as if to say: ``Mars? But of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the more fatalistic Y2K predictions _ chaos, months of
civil unrest, computers going berserk _ it's probably not
surprising that many American designers seemed to hunker down in a
survivalist's mode. Everywhere there were images of fashion ready
for a long siege: padded coats and fuzzy blanket wraps that could
be converted into sleeping rolls, Velcro-tab-front trousers and
jackets for quick convenience, jungle fatigues at Claude Sabbah,
fur trapper boots at Patrick Robinson, sleeves that could be
instantly left by the side of a road with a tug of a zipper.
</P>
<P>
   Even Michael Kors' homage to the western style of Slim Hawks and
Gary Cooper suggested, unwittingly, a case of misguided optimism.
Kors' stretch cashmere riding coats, wool jeans and sable pullovers
certainly looked very sporty and chic. But mention the American
West, and suddenly the mind fills with a thoroughly different image
of the prairie _ not the socialite's paradise at all. More like
Waco.
</P>
<P>
   NASA or Waco, Waco or NASA? Which way is the modern fashion
seeker to go?
</P>
<P>
   Klein, understandably perhaps, chose the path of least
resistance: through the safe middle. In a collection that was
predominantly black and cream, with touches of camel, henna and
almond, Klein expertly ticked off the themes of the season. There
were sleek, boot-legged trousers in felted stretch wool; tidy
trench coats and fencing jackets cut with military sharpness;
mock-turtleneck shells and jersey tops, some lacquered for shiny
contrast. A black jacket in waxed calf, for instance, zippered over
a wet-looking black jersey T-shirt, and came with a pair of black
felted trousers. For evening, Klein stayed the course with
side-draped skirts in papery black radzmire, layered chiffon slip
dresses and some black wool dresses with long, lacquered leather
strands that could be gathered into a nice whip.
</P>
<P>
   Klein is one designer who understands that while the pace of
fashion has accelerated, through globalization and slick marketing,
the changes themselves are actually marginal. It's the difference
between black nylon and black felt. Which is exactly why this sort
of fashion _ discreet, invisible, manicured to within an inch of a
smooth surface _ can rarely gather forward momentum.
</P>
<P>
   It is generally taken as a bad sign when editors in the front
row stop writing, although, in Ms. Karan's case, the idle Mont
Blancs didn't necessarily spell trouble. Her collection was a
mostly black-and-cream series of a blanket cashmere coat and a
sleeveless blanket dress in blanket double-faced cashmere, which
adds up to ditto. Her silhouette was similar to that of a jacket
tied around the waist and left to hang in asymmetric points.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes were obviously very comfortable, with woolen ponchos
and body jerseys, and the models, whose lips were painted a deeper
red in the center, as if they had just sucked on peppermints,
seemed to enjoy rolling around in Ms. Karan's plush new stretch
cashmere sweaters. But as a collection, it was too much a Zenlike
meditation on a single idea.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other shows that rounded out the week, Robinson's
collection of homespun-looking dresses in cherry jersey and royal
blue corduroy, as well as jackets with funnel sleeves stuffed with
fleece at the cuffs, had a heavy drop-out's quality. It didn't help
that the models wore furry slippers.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Nye's first runway collection was something of a
no-brainer: classic pea coats for men and women, gray flannel
suits, white military twill jeans and some standout woolen
sweaters. Nye, a former assistant to Calvin Klein, Ralph Lauren and
Carolina Herrera (who was in the front row with her husband,
Reinaldo) neatly finessed the gender issue, though one wonders
about his sailor jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who trooped around town last week, from high-rise
showrooms and fashion tents to arty dives on the Lower East Side,
knows that fashion's influence comes increasingly from the fringes.
It is obscure and often highly personal, like Bartlett's hardy
fleece coats and gently worn, almost dog-chewed felt skirts, which
owed their inspiration to the small-town portraits of the
photographer Mike Disfarmer.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn Smith's collection, entitled ``Angel's Gone Nuts,''
perfectly captured the helter-skelter bravura of fashion without
rules, while the design team of Sonja Rubin and Kip Chapelle caught
the downtown taste for plain skirts and sculptural handknit
sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most intriguing trends to come along is the new
bohemianism _ ``this whole generation of travelers,'' as Anna Sui
said. She picked up on the idea when she noticed two of the models,
Stella Tennant and Kirsten Owen, reading ``The Beach,'' the cult
novel by Alex Garland. Ms. Sui worked the theme into her
folk-music-inspired collection _ and knew she was onto something
when the models wanted to take home her fur trekker boots. ``We had
the hardest time holding onto the boots,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, though, one comes back to Helmut Lang _ to the way
the models darted out like dragonflies, to the creepy brilliance of
his vision, to the music (organized by Frederic Sanchez) that
somehow lifted the whole thing above the banality of fashion. After
the show, one editor said, ``I liked the clothes, but I don't know
the woman in them.'' Lang would probably regard that as a high
compliment. You can't see the future, only imagine it.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Lang doesn't go in for a lot of heavy analysis. What he
liked about his coats, which the models wore dangling down their
backs from shoulder straps, was that they were utilitarian, but
also a little fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It frames you,'' he said. ``It gives you a kind of wings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
