<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5155 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-PEONY-TAN-$ADV2     02-22 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PEONY-TAN-$ADV28-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPOSER TAN PUT NEW LIFE INTO `PAVILION'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (with MUSIC-PEONY-SFCHRON)  
 By BOB GRAHAM  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Tan Dun wrote the music for ``Peony
Pavilion'' in an amazing three weeks _ ``just like Rossini and
Mozart,'' says director Peter Sellars.
</P>
<P>
   For the two parts of Sellars' production, Tan ``adapted the
traditional music'' from the Kun opera _ and, interestingly, from
Monteverdi _ and composed two hours of new music, including a
ritual shaman ceremony. He describes the emotional content as
``deep longing and sorrowful beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no identifiable composer for traditional Chinese opera
in the sense that Verdi is the composer of ``Il Trovatore.'' Often
the music is based on standard or folk melodies from the different
regions _ Peking Opera and Cantonese Opera represent those regions,
and Kun Opera is from Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone says they are presenting the original `Peony
Pavilion,''' Tan said in a telephone interview from his home in New
York, ``there is no such thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most popular sections are still being performed today. The
complete opera does not exist, but the play does.''
</P>
<P>
   Tan composed a symphony for the celebration of the handover of
Hong Kong to China in 1997, but he says that piece was
``nonnational'' and not intended to promote the interests of either
the Chinese or the British. ``It was written for world culture, not
just for the handover,'' he says, ``and is the only piece written
for the 1997 festival that has had a life beyond it.'' There are
performances scheduled for Vienna, Jerusalem and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Tan, who is in his early 40s, will appear at the San Francisco
Symphony's ``Mavericks'' concert during the Stravinsky festival in
June. He said he wants to present himself there ``as a music
maker'' and not as ``an academic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be there working with the San Francisco Symphony either
as an improvisational soloist or maybe conducting something to
discover the fresh music-making way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
