<SLUG> BC-NYTIMES-INTERNET-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES TO INVEST $15 MILLION IN THESTREET.COM
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times Co. said on Monday that it had
agreed to invest $15 million in cash and services in TheStreet.com,
an online provider of investment news and financial information, in
exchange for a minority equity stake.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co. also said it was ``currently discussing
opportunities for strategic alliances with TheStreet.com.'' Michael
Golden, a vice chairman of the Times Co., has been nominated to
serve on TheStreet.com's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a year, TheStreet.com has raised $50 million in
financing, including the Times investment. It was founded in 1996
by James J. Cramer, the financial columnist, and Martin Peretz,
editor in chief and chairman of The New Republic magazine.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com, which offers a broad mix of news and commentary
on investment and trading-related topics, has about 37,000
subscribers. Cramer also manages a hedge fund, writes frequent
articles about his trading experiences and is the Web site's
marquee contributor _ he also writes for several publications,
including Time and GQ magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation has been growing on Wall Street that TheStreet.com,
which recently struck two deals to license its name for stock
indexes that track Internet companies, is preparing for a public
offering of its shares.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 6, Bloomberg Business News reported that Kevin W.
English, chairman and chief executive of TheStreet.com, said that a
1999 public offering ``is a strong possibility, depending on market
conditions and other variables.''
</P>
<P>
   The market for Internet stock offerings has been red hot, with
most new issues jumping sharply on their first day of trading. In
fact, TheStreet.com and Cramer held an investment roundtable on
Friday about the outlook for Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, English declined to comment on a possible public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Russell T. Lewis, chief executive and president of the Times
Co., said the deal held promise for the Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``In just two years, TheStreet.com has rapidly grown into one of
the most influential financial information sites on the Web,
attracting some of the country's most affluent and market-savvy
Internet users,'' Lewis said in a statement. ``As a result,
TheStreet.com is a good strategic fit with our own customer base,
which needs timely and quality information to make informed
investment decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Carparelli, a spokeswoman for the Times Co., said that the
type of services to be provided to TheStreet.com had not yet been
determined.
</P>
<P>
   One media consultant said advertising was the most likely
service. ``Any time one of the traditional media companies has
invested in one of the Internet companies, what the Internet guys
want is marketing support,'' said Bill Bass, a analyst at Forrester
Research Inc., a media research company. ``There may be some
editorial ties,'' he said, or some form of promotion in which The
Times urges readers to view TheStreet.com's Web site. The Times Co.
said the editorial relationship, if any, had not yet been defined.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com charges a fee for access to most of its Web site,
while access to The New York Times Web site is free.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Times deal brings together two longtime friends, Cramer and
Martin Nisenholtz, president of The New York Times Electronic Media
Co., the unit of the Times Co. that operates its Web site. The two
attended Springfield Township High School in Pennsylvania in the
early 1970s, and Cramer once told The Associated Press they were
close friends in school.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com has been aggressively raising money, an activity
that is frequently a prelude to an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   In January, it received $25 million from a group led by Oak
Investment Partners, a venture capital firm with $1.6 billion in
investments. Also participating in the group were Bowman Capital
Management of San Mateo, Calif.; Waller-Sutton Media Partners, a
New York private equity fund that invests in the media,
communications and entertainment industries; Henry R. Kravis, the
financier, and Optimix Private Equity Fund.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, TheStreet.com also received additional financing
from Flatiron Partners, Chase Capital Partners and Softbank
Technology Ventures, which combined had put $10 million into the
company back in May 1998. Other early investors, Constellation
Ventures, Pequot Capital Management, Cramer and Peretz, also bought
additional shares in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
