<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Second strong showing gives Wohlers optimism
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Mark Wohlers turned a good day into a
trend on Monday by pitching his second strong batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in three days, after a wobbly beginning in
spring training, Wohlers consistently was on target with his
fastball. He did not throw batting practice Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If today was any indication, he'd be ready for Opening Day,''
manager Bobby Cox said. ``That's the best I've seen Mark throw in a
year and a halfreally since the middle of the (1997) season. ... I
thought today was just excellent. He looked like any other pitcher
today. It was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers said he knows he's on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not where I want to be,'' he said, ``but from
where I've come from, I'm very pleased and quite optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers said he was glad the coaching staff decided to allow him
to pitch against live hitting from the start of spring training. It
has given him the chance to face his fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked off the mound and ran to the outfield to get my
shoes to run, I remember smiling when I ran out there,'' Wohlers
said. ``It felt good. It's been a while since I walked off the
mound and actually felt pretty good. But at the same time, I want
to have the same approach _ that's what I'm supposed to do. Let's
not jump for joy and do cartwheels because I threw some strikes in
batting practice.''
</P>
<P>
   HUBBARD STARTS OVER
</P>
<P>
   Back in the major leagues for the first time since he retired as
a player in 1989, Braves first base coach Glenn Hubbard has had
much more on his mind than his move from coaching in the minor
leagues. Hubbard's Stone Mountain house burned in December, and he
has spent the time since then trying to put his life back together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough deal waking up the next day and what you had on
the night before is what you have left,'' Hubbard said.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the fire, Hubbard's oldest son Jeremy, 19, had a
snowboarding accident and tore his spleen. Another son, Daniel, 14,
broke an arm while rollerblading.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the toughest spring I've ever had,'' Hubbard said.
``I felt bad about coming down here because (the settlement) wasn't
finished yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard, his wife and their three sons had to do inventories of
all their belongings, listing when and where they got all their
clothes, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The Hubbards are living in a rental house four miles from the
remains of their home. It will take at least seven months for
construction workers to destroy the remains of his house and
rebuild it.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard has learned that he was responsible for starting the
fire. He had discarded almost two-day-old ashes from his fireplace
into a container on his back deck, and that's where the fire
started. Luckily for the Hubbards, no one was home.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The fire investigator) told me, `I've never seen a house fire
that bad without loss of life,''' Hubbard said. ``You have to look
at it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the record, the fireplace in the new house will be a
little different.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting gas logs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   THEN THERE WERE EIGHT
</P>
<P>
   The Braves agreed to terms with minor-league second baseman
Marty Malloy on Monday, bringing the number of players signed on
the 40-man roster to 32. Those yet to be signed are Andruw Jones,
Kevin Millwood, Kerry Lightenberg, Bruce Chen, Odalis Perez, George
Lombard, Damian Moss and Randall Simon.
</P>
<P>
   ON DECK
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the day for the Braves position players to report to
camp. Those yet to show include Ryan Klesko, Andruw Jones, Gerald
Williams, Ozzie Guillen and Danny Bautista. The Braves will begin
their full-squad workouts today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
