</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARTIN-COURT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin's lawyers seek delay, own trial
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lawyers for Falcons wide receiver Tony Martin filed a
motion in federal court Monday asking to delay until next year his
trial on five charges of money laundering and one charge of
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 33, was indicted last month in connection with his
relationship with Ricky Brownlee, a twice-convicted drug trafficker
who is charged again. The trial tentatively is scheduled to begin
May 3.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed in U.S. District Court in Miami, attorneys
Howard Srebnick and Roy Black also asked judge Kevin Michael Moore
to ``sever Tony Martin from his co-defendant,'' so that the two
would be tried separately.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Martin) is not charged with any drug-trafficking activity,''
Srebnick said. ``It doesn't make sense for him to sit through a
trafficking trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Srebnick and Black also asked the court to postpone Martin's
trial, hoping for a ruling before Martin's March 8 arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have requested January of next year. That would permit
(Martin's) uninterrupted employment,'' Srebnick said. ``Also ... we
have other clients, obligations to other judges and other courts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons owe Martin a $400,000 roster bonus March 1 _ next
Monday _ and might seek to delay that deadline.
</P>
<P>
   FALCONS LOSE ANOTHER
</P>
<P>
   Reserve defensive end Antonio Edwards, who had 17 total tackles
in his only season as a Falcon, became the third unrestricted free
agent to depart Monday. He agreed to a two-year, $1.3 million
contract with Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The Moultrie native turned down a little more money from
Atlanta, which has now lost both reserve defensive ends.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, former defensive end John Burrough signed with
Minnesota, and reserve safety Devin Bush signed with St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have eight more unrestricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   PR CHIEF QUITS
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Taylor, the easy-going director of public relations for
the Falcons, resigned Monday after 12 years with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 49, did not say he was forced to leave, but he often
felt left out of the loop by the front office.
</P>
<P>
   It was not uncommon for reporters to approach him seeking
details on organizational moves before he knew of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we talked about for a few weeks,'' Taylor said.
``I'll try to stay in Atlanta. It's time to move on. These days,
the PR guys don't seem to move up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
