<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lehman rusty but ready in Match Play
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ Say this for Tom Lehman. He hasn't come to
the Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship overprepared or
golfed out. Following right shoulder surgery Nov. 30, Lehman hasn't
competed in an actual tournament since the Tour Championship at
East Lake in Atlanta Nov. 1. His last event of any kind was the
Skins Game Nov. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a first-round match in the $5 million event Wednesday
against Scott Verplank, Lehman admits to some rust on his game, but
desires no medical slack. He is swinging the golf club without pain
for the first time since July 15, when he injured the shoulder
while playing with his kids at an amusement park on the eve of the
British Open. The surgery repaired a separation in the shoulder and
chopped off three-fourths of an inch from his clavicle to improve
his range of motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoulder's completely healed,'' said Lehman. ``It's just a
matter of getting my strength back. I get a little tired out at the
end of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances Lehman, who has played on two Ryder
Cup and two Presidents Cup teams, would be among the top contenders
for this debut event of the World Golf Championships. But while a
question mark, there was never a question that he would attend the
inaugural WGC event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' he said, ``is the one that everyone wants to play.''
</P>
<P>
   COURSE MADE FOR WOODS
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price would agree with those who, for all practical
purposes, automatically place Tiger Woods into the quarterfinals.
``For somebody who hits the ball as long as he does, this course is
right up his street,'' said Price. ``He can reach all the par 5s.
Normal hitters can maybe reach two of them.'' . . . The 32
first-round matches begin Wednesday at 10:20 a.m. EST. . . . No. 64
Nick Faldo, who plays No. 1 Woods in a first-round match, got
typically testy with reporters Monday while waiting to hit off the
10th tee, citing the approaching ``vultures.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
