</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MITCHELL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mitchell tiring of turmoil
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ World-class sprinter Dennis Mitchell says some friends
and family have turned on him after he flunked a drug test, since
overturned by the U.S. track and field federation. His legal
defense alone cost in ``the six digits,'' and now he is unable to
earn even a dime from product endorsements and sponsors. Meet
promoters and competitors alike greet him with a wary eye.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the middle of a world summit on doping in sports
earlier this month, Mitchell's controversial case was held up for
ridicule, as everyone from Olympic drug czar Prince Alexandre de
Merode to Olympic gold medalist and British parliamentarian
Sebastian Coe ripped into what had been widely published as his
defense: engaging in sex and drinking beer the night before an
unannounced visit from a drug tester.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, 100-meter bronze medalist at the Barcelona Olympics,
said he is under his attorney's orders not to discuss his defense,
except to say it is more complicated than reports have indicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to really grow up. If it (the sex and alcohol
defense) was that easy to beat a doping case, then there would be
no deterrent for using drugs,'' he said. ``There is a lot more to
it, of course. When my case was heard by USA Track and Field, it
was obvious to everyone in that room that I did nothing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Masback, head of the U.S. track federation, refused to
discuss the evidence and expressed concern that details of
Mitchell's case had been leaked to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Having been cleared by USATF in December, Mitchell has competed
this indoor season. He ranks among the top names, along with
Maurice Greene and Jon Drummond, entered in the 60 meters this
weekend in the U.S. Indoor Track and Field Championships at the
Georgia Dome. But the legal wrangling has come at a heavy price,
and it's not over yet.
</P>
<P>
   The international track federation ultimately determines whether
athletes are cleared in drug cases. Officials met with Mitchell's
attorney two weeks ago, but the decision _ either accepting the
U.S. federation's innocent verdict or sending his case to
arbitration _ might not be made soon.
</P>
<P>
   A similar case involving American female distance running icon
Mary Slaney remains unresolved almost three years after a positive
test at the 1996 Olympic Trials in Atlanta. Like Slaney, Mitchell's
test was flagged because of elevated testosterone levels.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's level of testosterone to epitestosterone, two natural
hormones, was above the allowable 6-to-1 ratio. The controversial
test, designed to detect performance-enhancing substances, has been
constantly under challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a huge distraction,'' said Mitchell, a former
University of Florida star who still trains in Gainesville. ``You
go from being a very highly respected athlete to being accused of
something you had never thought would be a part of your life. It's
like being on death row and being innocent of something that's
almost impossible to prove you're innocent of. The moment this
thing made it into the press, I lost everything _ my income, my
endorsements. My entire life is track and field.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said the turmoil has hindered his training and his
confidence, which was apparent in his sixth-place finish Friday
night in the Adidas D.C. Invitational. As he walked off the track,
his mother, Lenora, came out of the stands to offer a consoling
hug. This week, he'll spend time with his sister Denise, an Atlanta
teacher. Those two relatives have supported him. Others have not,
he said without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has devastated him,'' Lenora Mitchell said. ``Dennis has
always prided himself on justice. He likes to be in control, and
here he's in a situation that is in someone else's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is assumed that track athletes dabble with drugs on
occasion, the news of Mitchell's alleged involvement came as a
surprise to the track community. He has been outspoken against drug
use and has served as president of the USATF athletes advisory
committee. He had not been, in his words, one of the ``bad guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell learned during a July 8 phone call from Masback that
his testosterone levels had shown to be high and that he would be
given a hearing to explain why. The news came just after he had
competed in the U.S. outdoor championships _ where he pulled up
with leg cramps _ and before the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was absolutely stunned,'' he said. ``At that time, it was
probably the worst news that I could ever have heard .''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said he is confident the international federation will
rule in his favor. If they don't, he is prepared to fight the case
through appeals. But he also said the case has tired him and left
him to ponder his future. He hasn't bothered commuting to North
Carolina to work with his coach, Trevor Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 32, and I only want two more years in the sport,''
Mitchell said. ``If I have to go through this arbitration process
(should the international body fail to accept the U.S. federation's
ruling), looking at past examples, it's going to take two years. I
might have to make a decision whether I want to compete or not.''
</P>
<P>
   USA INDOOR CHAMPIONSHIPS
</P>
<P>
   _ When: Preliminaries Friday, finals Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   _ Top athletes: Maurice Greene and Jon Drummond (60 meters),
Melissa Morrison (60 hurdles), Jeff Hartwig (pole vault), Tisha
Waller (high jump), Jearl Miles-Clark (400), Reggie Torian (60
hurdles).
</P>
<P>
   _ Tickets: $17 reserved seating, $12 general admission, $8
students for Saturday's finals. All Friday tickets $5. Available at
Ticketmaster and Dome box office.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: 5-6 p.m. Saturday, NBC (live); 12:30-1:30 a.m. and
4:30-5:30 p.m. Sunday, ESPN (taped).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
