<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5174 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINBUDGET-SFCHRON &LR;      02-22 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINBUDGET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Tuesday, Feb. 23, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Marcus Chan at 415-777-8443 or
Catherine Laidlaw at 415-777-6057.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SDGE  &LR; - With nearly all of its debts paid off, San Diego's electric
utility says it will cut electric rates by 15 percent in July _
nearly two years ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by San Diego Gas and Electric Co. may nudge
other big utilities, chiefly Pacific Gas and Electric Co. and
Southern California Edison, to get their debts retired more
quickly. By Rebecca Smith
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STREET &LR;  - Will investors go for a second cup of Diedrich
Coffee?
</P>
<P>
   The Irvine coffee house chain plans on holding a secondary stock
offering to help pay for its $35 million buyout of Castroville's
Coffee People, according to documents filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission. By columnist Mark Veverka
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MONEY PACKAGE &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; DAYTRADER -  &LR; They've been lampooned for their eccentricity in Garry
Trudeau's ``Doonesbury'' comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   They've been rebuked for their high-risk investment tactics by
the chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   They've been reviled by the Wall Street establishment for
roiling the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   They're the Internet day traders _ perhaps hundreds of thousands
of them nationwide _ stubborn individualists who have rejected
9-to-5 jobs, choosing instead to indulge in fast-paced, in-and-out
securities trading from their homes. By Arthur M. Louis
</P>
<P>
   &UR; With: PROFILE1 &LR;  _ In his previous incarnation, San Mateo day
trader Tom Weeden worked for a firm specializing in fancy,
multicolor printing for graphic artists.
</P>
<P>
   That's how he learned about a company that had come out with a
digital printing press.
</P>
<P>
   He bought 100 shares, made a profit and decided that the stock
market was much more interesting than his printing job. ``I decided
that trading stocks was something I would really like to do, and I
became quite a student of the market.'' By Arthur M. Louis
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PROFILE2 _  &LR; Avery Neal _ the alias of a publicity-shy,
40-year-old tile contractor _ went from assets in ``the middle five
figures'' to ``well into six figures'' in a few years by buying
stocks whose prices were battered to historic lows or those that
were making ``breakouts'' on the myriad charts that cover
practically every wall of his Alameda home. By Arthur M. Louis
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PROFILE3 &LR;  _ Shari Smith, 51, co-owner with her husband of a
tool-making company, started trading from her home in San Carlos
more than a year ago with $200,000 in savings. Now she has
$530,000, thanks largely to an uncanny ability to predict price
moves in Nasdaq stocks by staring at the ticker tape on CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEYBAG -  &LR; Question: I'm a 13-year-old girl who received a
$10,000 gift from my grandmother. I'm thinking of investing the
money in a combination of stock ($6,000), an IRA account consisting
of either Vanguard or Merrill Lynch stock mutual funds ($2,000) and
a bank certificate of deposit ($2,000). The stock I have in mind is
my father's company, which is not yet publicly traded, but he says
it has a great future. Does this sound like a good plan? Columnist
Arthur M. Louis has the answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
