</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE2-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 It's All in the Charts  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Avery Neal _ the alias of a publicity-shy, 40-year-old tile
contractor _ went from assets in ``the middle five figures'' to
``well into six figures'' in a few years by buying stocks whose
prices were battered to historic lows or those that were making
``breakouts'' on the myriad charts that cover practically every
wall of his Alameda home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look for stocks breaking out to new highs,'' says Neal, a
profane, excitable ex-New Yorker. ``Or reversals _ stocks that have
hit their lows and are starting to bounce back. I judge companies
strictly by their charts. I know nothing about business, but I can
detect reversals in psychology. My house is a f_ mess. Newspapers
and charts everywhere. You wouldn't think a 40-year-old guy would
live like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Neal prefers stocks with small capitalizations, mainly _ though
not exclusively _ ``cutting-edge'' high-technology companies, whose
prices tend to move faster than other stocks. ``You can get a 25
percent move in a day.''
</P>
<P>
   However, if the 25 percent move doesn't materialize, he often
will bail out of a stock after it has moved only a fraction of a
point. ``I consider myself like a mosquito on the ass of an
elephant,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of the big dudes who sways the markets. I bought
Shaman Pharmaceuticals at 30 cents and sold it at 46 cents. I don't
give a crap where it is now. You've gotta get out before everybody
else does. On Wall Street, bulls and bears are fed, but pigs are
slaughtered. If I make or lose 1,000 bucks on something, that's the
rent.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he moves in and out quickly, he makes ``only a few
trades a day.'' After buying a stock, he will enter a stop-loss
order (an order to sell if a stock falls to a certain price)
slightly below the purchase price _ ``so I don't lose too much if
the stock moves against me. I can never understand people I hear
moaning about how their AOL stock fell to 146 after they bought it
at 170. Why would they still own it?''
</P>
<P>
   He makes all his decisions on his own. ``If you listen to
anybody else _ and that includes brokers _ you're just gonna lose
money because they don't know s_.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
