<HEADLINE>
SENIOR APPOINTMENTS ANNOUNCED BY THE NEW YORK TIMES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two senior appointments in the Washington bureau of The New York
Times were announced on Monday by Michael Oreskes, the bureau
chief. Jill Abramson will become the Washington editor, taking over
in April from Adam Clymer, who becomes the Washington correspondent
of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In her new post, Ms. Abramson, who is 44, will help plan and
direct the work of the paper's 60-member bureau. She came to the
newspaper in 1997 as enterprise editor in the Washington bureau.
She had been a reporter and deputy Washington bureau chief of The
Wall Street Journal. She is the co-author of ``Strange Justice''
(Houghton Mifflin, 1994), a history of Clarence Thomas' nomination
to the Supreme Court, and author of ``Where They Are Now''
(Doubleday, 1986), the story of the women of the Harvard law school
class of 1974. From 1986 to 1988, she was the editor of Legal
Times, a weekly newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   She is a native of New York City and graduated from Harvard in
1976. She lives in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Clymer, 61, will write on major issues in government and
politics. He has been a reporter and an editor at The New York
Times since 1977, serving as political editor, director of polling
and senior editor for weekends before becoming the Washington
editor.
</P>
<P>
   Clymer graduated from Harvard in 1958 and lives in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
