</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SDGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 San Diego's Early Electric Rate Cut May Set Example  &HT;       
 By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
With nearly all of its debts paid off, San Diego's electric utility
says it will cut electric rates by 15 percent in July _ nearly two
years ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by San Diego Gas and Electric Co. may nudge
other big utilities, chiefly Pacific Gas and Electric Co. and
Southern California Edison, to get their debts retired more
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope this announcement by SDG&AMP;E puts pressure on others,''
said Kevin Smith, spokesman for the California Manufacturers
Association in Sacramento. ``We'd like to see an early retirement
of utility debts everywhere so rates can fall throughout the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of PG&AMP;E and Edison have said they will need much
more time to pay down their debts than the San Diego utility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not as far along in our cost recovery as SDG&AMP;E,'' said
Mark Huffman, a PG&AMP;E attorney. ``We don't have an exact forecast
but there's no way it'll happen this summer for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the state's deregulation law, utilities have been allowed
to keep rates high during a transition period and use surplus funds
to pay off debts that were shouldered under the old regulatory
regime. Utilities have until March 31, 2002, to collect the extra
money, unless they get debts paid down sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Once the collection period ends, rates must fall to a level
based on utility operating costs. For PG&AMP;E, that should mean at
least a 20 percent rate cut for customers.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Guiles, president of SDG&AMP;E, said his firm is ending the
freeze early because it's paid off $2 billion worth of debts,
thanks to high prices fetched, at auction, for electricity as well
as power plants.
</P>
<P>
   It auctioned its Encina Power Plant and 18 smaller generating
units for $356 million last year. At four times book value, it was
one of the highest prices obtained in any power plant divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   The utility also profited from being last in line to sell its
plants, giving it a very unusual opportunity to sell power from
unsold plants into an electricity auction last summer when prices
hit a high of $9,999 per megawatt as compared with normal prices of
a few dollars per megawatt.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E's situation is quite different from San Diego's. How soon
PG&AMP;E ends the freeze rests on two things: the wholesale price of
electricity that it procures for customers and the sum it fetches
for its huge hydroelectric generating system that's now for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The more it must pay for wholesale power bought from the
California Power Exchange, the less money it has left for debt
reduction.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if wholesale electricity prices run 1.5 cents per
kilowatt hour, PG&AMP;E figures it can pay off debts and end the freeze
in 2001. If it must pay 2.5 cents per kilowatt, it figures it will
need an extra nine months to pay down its debts.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of SDGE23 (13826 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  In 1998, PG&AMP;E paid an average of 3.3 cents per kilowatt for
wholesale electricity obtained from the state's new power auction.
</P>
<P>
   The best bet for an early end to the freeze is a high valuation
on the hydroelectric system it wants to divest.
</P>
<P>
   If PG&AMP;E can get a hefty profit from that deal, all those dollars
would be used to slash debt.
</P>
<P>
   So far, PG&AMP;E projections have assigned a value of $1.6 billion
to its hydro assets. That's straight book value and few outside the
utility expect the system to sell for so little.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E has said it hopes to transfer the system to a sister
company and credit the proceeds from that transaction against its
debts. Consumer advocates have said this means there's a huge
incentive for the utility to sell the system at a low-ball price.
</P>
<P>
   That would do two things. It would save the sister company money
and allow PG&AMP;E to perpetuate the freeze, presumably capturing more
dollars for the parent company, PG&AMP;E Corp.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E attorney Huffman said the utility did not submit
projections to the PUC showing different yields from the hydro
divestiture. ``We didn't want to prejudice the hydro proceeding,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in a similar situation, Edison submitted a matrix showing
the freeze for its customers could end six to nine months sooner if
its hydroelectric system sells for two times book value _ roughly
$800 million _ instead of book value.
</P>
<P>
   At three times book value or $1.2 billion, the freeze for Edison
customers would end a full 15 months sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the freeze ends is a function of the market price of
power and asset valuations,'' said Edison senior vice president
John Fielder. ``The end of next year is the earliest we could
envision it ending, though.''
</P>
<P>
   One thorny issue must be settled before San Diego's freeze ends.
</P>
<P>
   Although SDG&AMP;E wants to end the freeze this summer, it is
apprehensive about doing so just when power prices hit their peak.
It's possible that volatile prices could eat up the 15 percent
reduction.
</P>
<P>
   The utility is proposing a gradual end to the freeze, basically
by averaging power prices during a nine-month period.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates are skeptical. ``It sounds to me like
they don't want people to understand what deregulation was right
away,'' said Nettie Hoge, executive director of the consumer group
The Utility Reform Network in San Francisco. ``It can mean volatile
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   She thinks the PUC should make sure that, if there is rate
averaging, consumers aren't charged extra for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
