<HEADER>
A5181 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYTRADER-SFCHRON &LR;      02-22 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTRADER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Risky Business of Day Trading  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
They've been lampooned for their eccentricity in Garry Trudeau's
``Doonesbury'' comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   They've been rebuked for their high-risk investment tactics by
the chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   They've been reviled by the Wall Street establishment for
roiling the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   They're the Internet day traders _ perhaps hundreds of thousands
of them nationwide _ stubborn individualists who have rejected
9-to-5 jobs, choosing instead to indulge in fast-paced, in-and-out
securities trading from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Although day trading _ which now accounts for a phenomenal 25
percent of the volume on Nasdaq _ is a great source of commissions
for online brokers,  &LR;   &LR; it is causing other people in the investment
community a lot of headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Some warn that it could lead to the kind of speculative excesses
that often precede a calamitous stock-market crash.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Zarb, chief executive of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, Nasdaq's parent, recently deplored the
``extreme'' volatility on Nasdaq, fueled by day trading. He
complained that it has ``disrupted the ability of market-makers to
communicate with investors in a timely manner,'' and he warned that
Nasdaq's administrators might have to bust in from time to time and
suspend trading in exceptionally volatile issues.
</P>
<P>
   To most investors, weaned on the notion that stocks are bought
to be held _ not passed around like marbles or baseball cards _
what the day traders do seems almost un-American.
</P>
<P>
   SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt recently summed it up in a long,
cautionary statement about the perils of Internet trading:
``Investment should be for the long run, not for minutes or
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt may have a point.
</P>
<P>
   Most Internet day traders quickly fall by the wayside, experts
say. They don't have any special knack for picking stocks or other
securities, or they don't study the market hard enough. And because
they trade so heavily, their funds get eaten up by short-term
capital gains taxes, &UR;  &LR; commissions and market-makers' ``spreads'' _
the difference between the price at which a stock is bought and
sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very much a professional's game with a very painful
learning curve,'' says James Lee, president of the Electronic
Traders Association and co-owner of Momentum Trading, a brokerage
firm specializing in day trading. ``Most people can expect to lose
a lot of money, at least at first.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of DAYTRADE () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  But some Internet day traders have done quite well _ grinding out
a living by chasing short-term price moves. They seem to have an
almost supernatural feel for the market, or a lot of luck, or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I resent the stuff I see in the media about how all these
idiots just throw money at Internet stocks and get rich,'' says
James De Porre of Anna Maria Island, Fla., who claims to have made
millions in profits from day trading over the past four years and
serves as a guru to thousands of other traders through his Shark
Attack Web site on America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the long run,'' he says, ``you need a strategy and you
need to work at it.'' He himself makes 30 trades a day, but he
insists: ``This isn't gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Day trading used to be confined to a tiny segment of the
investment community _ probably no more than 5,000 people
nationwide _ who carried on their activities at the offices of a
dozen or so specialized brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   These day-trading firms, with a total of 80 offices nationwide,
provide their customers with work spaces, computers, software and
data links that allow them to trade on Nasdaq and other markets. In
return, the brokers receive a commission for each of the many
trades their customers transact each day.
</P>
<P>
   But the advent of extremely powerful personal computers, the
proliferation of bargain-rate online brokerage firms, and the
greatly increased volume and sophistication of research and data
available to PC users has shifted much of the day-trading activity
into the dens, bedrooms and living rooms of the investing public.
</P>
<P>
   With a good computer and an outlay of perhaps $250 per month, an
investor can obtain enough up-to-the-minute market information _
real-time price quotes, news alerts, charts and tables that
constantly update _ to make Internet day trading a plausible
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   That, plus the enticement of being your own boss and working
from home in bathrobe and slippers, is motivation enough for many
traders.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that day trading isn't hard work.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be your run-of-the-mill, 9-to-5 job, but it does
occupy every weekday, major holidays excepted, from 6:30 a.m.
Pacific time, when the markets open, until 1 p.m. or later, when
they shut down.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not necessarily all: The more-earnest day traders
spend the rest of their waking hours preparing for the next trading
session.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of DAYTRADE () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  During the time the market is open, the day trader must
concentrate on the action full time. Bathroom breaks and trips to
the refrigerator can be fraught with peril.
</P>
<P>
   In the time it takes to pour a can of soda, a heavily margined
futures position or a flyer on a wildly swinging Internet stock can
go to blazes, wiping out a big chunk of a trader's bankroll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
