A5183 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KARP-MALL-BOS &LR;      02-22 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KARP-MALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPER SEEKS BUYERS FOR NEW ENGLAND MALL EMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD KINDLEBERGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Developer Stephen R. Karp is moving to sell the
shopping mall empire he built into New England's largest over the
past 25 years, industry sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Karp, chairman of New England Development, is said to be in
separate discussions with the nation's two biggest publicly traded
mall owners, Simon Property Group Inc. of Indianapolis and General
Growth Properties Inc. of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   One industry observer estimated a sale would bring $1.6 billion
to $2 billion. ``There won't be a bigger transaction around here
that takes place this year,'' he said. Karp could not be reached.
Spokesmen for Simon and General Growth declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   The move to sell his properties comes as Karp explores new
development ventures in other arenas, including a proposed
hotel-retail complex on the South Boston waterfront and a possible
role as a partner with the Boston Red Sox in developing a
replacement for Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The attempted sale follows by 15 months the collapse of a bid to
merge Karp's mall with those of the Richard E. Jacobs Group of
Cleveland and then take the combined company public. An earlier
attempt at a three-way merger was broken up when 12 malls run by
the third would-be partner, the O'Connor Group of New York, were
bought for a higher price by Simon, a real estate investment trust,
or REIT.
</P>
<P>
   Karp has a reputation for developing high-quality shopping
centers. His portfolio has almost 20, including the CambridgeSide
Galleria and The Atrium at Chestnut Hill in Boston. Karp is said to
have developed more malls than anyone else in the Northeast, if not
the nation, during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Karp and Jeremiah O'Connor, chairman of the O'Connor
Group, combined their mall management businesses under the name
WellsPark Group. That business continued after their failed attempt
to merge the ownership of their malls with that of the Jacobs
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Fred S. Carr, whose Penobscot Group research firm follows REITs,
said this might be a good time for Karp to sell. He said mall
prices are fairly strong and there is concern about future growth.
``There's a lot of rumbling out in the world about Internet sales
chewing into most retail venues,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   But Carr, who had not heard of Karp's talks with Simon and
General Growth, questioned whether those companies would be good
candidates to purchase the Karp malls. ``Simon has too much debt,''
he said, while General Growth has been more interested in older
malls in need of work. ``Karp's reputation is that his assets are
very good and very professionally run,'' Carr said, adding he
thought that ``a fair observation.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the sources said the buyer would probably structure the
transaction as a joint venture with a pension fund. By raising
equity for the purchase at the property level, he said, it would
not show up on the balance sheet. As for Karp, the source said,
accepting payment in partnership shares in the acquiring REIT would
allow him to defer paying tax on the capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   Simon, with a market capitalization of $4.1 billion, is the
largest retail REIT. General Growth is second, at $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Jennifer Babson contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
