<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5191 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESTRIN-SFCHRON &LR;      02-22 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTRIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Cisco's CTO Is a Powerful Woman in a Field Dominated by Men  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
It was the early 1980s and Judy Estrin, a 27-year-old entrepreneur
who had recently started her own company, was called for jury duty.
</P>
<P>
   With two weeks to go before her networking company, Bridge
Communications, showed off its first product, Estrin was desperate
to avoid serving as a juror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the judge and said I have a company that's about to
demonstrate its first product, I'm the vice president of
engineering and I have to be there,'' Estrin said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge laughed, telling Estrin she was much too young to be
vice president of anything. But he liked the story, he said, and he
let her off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's laughing at Judy Estrin anymore.
</P>
<P>
   She sold Bridge to 3Com Corp. for $235 million in stock in 1987,
and Estrin, along with her husband and co-founder, went on to start
two other highly successful technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she is the chief technology officer of Cisco Systems, an
$8.5 billion company in San Jose whose networking equipment
dominates much of the Internet. She joined Cisco in March after
being heavily courted by chief executive John Chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me three years to convince Judy to join our board and
the Cisco team, and the reason I recruited her so diligently is
that I knew her personality and talent would be a great long-term
fit for us,'' Chambers said.
</P>
<P>
   Estrin is now a major player at a company whose equipment is as
crucial to today's PCs as Windows software and Intel chips. She
sits on the boards of several high-profile companies, including
Walt Disney Co., Sun Microsystems and Federal Express, and was
recently named one of the top 50 women in business by Fortune
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Her meteoric rise has taken place in an industry dominated by
men, where few women have powerful roles. While lots of women work
in high tech, they tend to be in marketing or public relations.
Estrin, 45, is one of the few female chief technology officers of a
major Silicon Valley company _ a role that combines management
expertise with engineering savvy.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tell Estrin that her achievements are anything other
than the norm. Her life has been driven by a desire to develop and
apply technology, and she has never let youth or gender stand in
her way.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents had three daughters,'' said Estrin, who was the
middle child. ``Growing up, there was never a question about
whether or not women had a career or could do something
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The only question was how successful they could be. Because
Estrin was surrounded by people who were blazing new trails, the
answer seemed predetermined.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Israel at a time when her parents were leading
the team to build the first computer in the Middle East. Her
father, an electrical engineer, started the computer science
program at UCLA, and her mother, a biomedical engineer, was among
the select few women to teach a scientific subject at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, as an undergraduate student at UCLA, Estrin watched
as the school installed the first Arpanet node _ the beginnings of
today's Internet. And she did her master's work at Stanford
University with Vint Cerf, considered the father of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   She took the lessons she learned from these groundbreaking
events and quickly applied them to her career.
</P>
<P>
   After selling Bridge to 3Com in 1987, she and her husband,
William Carrico, started Network Computing Devices, a Mountain View
company that made computer systems. The company went public four
years later, and in 1995, they founded Precept Software, a
multimedia networking software company in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of ESTRIN22 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Three years later, they sold Precept to Cisco for $84 million,
and both joined the networking giant as part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Estrin oversees a $1 billion research and development
budget, evaluates Cisco's acquisitions and drives the technology
vision and strategy of one of the top companies in the industry.
Her husband is senior vice president of small and medium business
at Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Estrin has taken the CTO reins at a time when the networking
industry is undergoing massive change. Cisco is attempting to
capitalize on the demand from service providers, such as telephone
companies, for a single, seamless network for voice, video and
data.
</P>
<P>
   The company is moving aggressively onto the turf of players like
Lucent Technologies and Northern Telecom, which have been selling
to the AT&AMP;Ts and Pacific Bells of the world for years. It also
faces competition from 3Com and a slew of foreign
telecommunications equipment providers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fierce battle, and Estrin admits there is only room for
two or three winners, but she's confident in her ability to drive
Cisco to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know and work with her say if anyone is prepared for
the battle, it's the energetic and focused Estrin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judy is simply an incredibly capable person who's pragmatic
and oriented toward results,'' says Cerf, her former professor, who
remains a friend and self-described admirer. ``She has grown
dramatically in the scope of what she's able to do. She's gone
beyond engineering to understand businesses and how businesses
work, which makes her a valuable commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerf, who studied engineering under Estrin's father at UCLA and
has known her since she was 12, said he often asks her for advice
about his own ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going to her with some ideas when she was at NCD
... her first reaction was to figure out what the cost impact would
be, something I had not been worrying about,'' Cerf said. ``She's
quick to comprehend the gestalt of the ideas and all the
ramifications and come back with conclusions and helpful
suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   Her ability to understand new concepts and flesh out solutions
is something that will prepare Estrin for battle. She's been CTO at
Cisco for less than a year and already faces massive challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the biggest hurdles, she said, are getting high-speed
Internet access to the home and improving the service quality of
Internet-based networks. Estrin wants phone calls placed over the
Internet to be as reliable as those made over traditional phone
lines.
</P>
<P>
   It's something the entire industry is focusing on, Estrin said,
and it's one reason she and her husband decided to sell Precept to
Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The networking industry has changed, and that's typical of a
maturing industry,'' Estrin said. ``Early on, you make the biggest
impact in a startup. But in a mature industry, critical mass is
important. Small companies without critical mass cannot solve the
challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   She is excited about the changes underfoot and the part that
Cisco will play in the new world of networking. But her favorite
aspect, she said, is seeing how technology affects people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like technology for technology's sake. I love applying
technology to solve problems,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude and outlook is what prompted Chambers to recruit
Estrin.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Silicon Valley, people value results, experience and the
ability to make a difference,'' Chambers said. ``Judy has always
been involved with leading-edge technology and has clearly
established herself as one of the Valley's key leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrin said she's gotten to this point in her career by not
making a big deal out of herself. As the mother of an 8-year-old
son, Estrin doesn't have much time for self-aggrandizing, but
still, she said she doesn't spend her days trying to prove herself
to the world.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of ESTRIN22 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Estrin said that attitude has also helped her succeed in a
male-dominated industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just assume I'm as good as they are and that I don't have
anything to prove,'' Estrin said. ``I think that's made it
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband has also helped her get to this point, she said.
Carrico, who was CEO of Precept for two years, moved to the
chairman role after Estrin said she wanted to try running the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always just worked together as a team,'' Estrin said.
``I've mellowed him out and he's made me tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   The circuitous path that's led Estrin to where she is today is
something she could never have predicted, she said. So she doesn't
try to guess where she might be in two or 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those people who needs to be doing what I love
doing,'' she said. ``When I look out on the horizon, I know
whatever I'm doing in five years, I'll need to be making an impact,
enjoying it and learning.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of ESTRIN22 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
