<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5192 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETFILES-SFCHRON &LR;      02-22 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 THE NET FILES (column)  &HT;     The Stars of Technology Sweeps Month 
 &HT;     By Jon Swartz  c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   February is sweeps month in the television industry, when the
major networks scramble to come up with the most sensational and
titillating programs to increase ratings and, consequently, improve
their advertising rates.
</P>
<P>
   The same principle applies to the Internet in late January and
early February, when scores of startups trot out their wares at a
string of computer trade shows, with names like Internet Showcase
and Demo 99 in hopes of gaining the attention of investors and the
press.
</P>
<P>
   A few stand out, however, because of the impact they are likely
to have on the average surfer. They include:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Qubit Technology  &LR; (www.qubit.net).  &LR; This two-pound information
appliance for Web browsing and e-mail is the size of a small
laptop. And it's wireless. Company officials are in the process of
looking for manufacturing and content partners. No price has been
set.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; AtBackup &LR;  ( &LR; www.atbackup.com &LR; ). Software allows traveling
business users to retrieve information from their personal
computers from anywhere on the Internet. &UR;  &LR; For $99 a year, the
service can be invaluable in the event of a computer crash.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Hypercosm &LR;  ( &LR; www.hypercosm3d.com &LR; ). Eye-popping software lets
Web developers and graphics artists create and display lush 3-D
images on the Internet. Pricing has yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Jump Networks &LR;  ( &LR; www.jump.com &LR; ). This free Web-based calendar,
address book and e-mail service allows users to store schedules and
contact information on their personal-digital assistants and
personal-information management software programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; ActiveTouch &LR;  ( &LR; www.activetouch.com &LR; ). Software enables
employees scattered around the world to easily meet and share
documents over the Web. The WebEx Meeting Center requires only a
browser and a telephone. It starts at $4.95 per meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Maybe one of these products will strike it rich, and
we'll have our next Yahoo or Inktomi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early year conferences are an invaluable environment for
investors and young companies to strike up relationships. They set
the tone for the rest of the year,'' said Chris Shipley, editor of
DemoLetter, the San Mateo computer newsletter that organized Demo
99 this month in Indian Wells (Riverside County).
</P>
<P>
   DEPARTMENT OF WEIRDNESS: High tech and fast food aren't a
contradiction in terms as you might think. Taco Bell Corp. last
week named Kenneth Kraemer, a computer-science professor at the
University of California at Irvine's Graduate School of Management,
to a $500,000 endowed chair in information technology.
</P>
<P>
   Before you scoff at the notion of mixing computer chips with
tortilla chips, Kraemer calls Taco Bell ``an early innovator'' that
has automated its operations for drive-through orders and its
internal companywide Internet.
</P>
<P>
   If true, is a cross-promotional deal between McDonald's Big Mac
and Apple Computer's Macintosh far behind?
</P>
<P>
   AN EXPENSIVE HAM SANDWICH: Speaking of computers and food,
Tabloid News ( &LR; www.tabloid.net &LR; ), an Oakland Internet news service,
has sued the Richards Group, a Dallas advertising agency, for
copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   Flabbergasted Tabloid.net officials say an animated talking ham
sandwich logo that first appeared on their news site in 1997 was
pilfered and reused in a $20 million marketing campaign for the
Florida Department of Citrus last fall. You may remember the
Florida orange growers as the folks who previously paid Anita
Bryant to be their spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed February 8 in U.S. District Court in San
Francisco, alleges that the leftover sandwich _ featured in a
Tabloid.net news series _ reappeared in the orange juice ads.
Tabloid.net officials, who say they have computer records proving
that ad agency employees repeatedly visited its Web site, are
seeking a share of any profits made from the use of the ham
sandwich, as well as licensing fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a strange thing the Internet is when a potentially
precedent-setting copyright case involves a dispute over a talking
ham sandwich that gives advice,'' noted Ken Layne, Tabloid.net
co-founder and editor.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of NETFILES () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Dick Murray, a principal at the Richards Group, said the company
has not been served with the suit and denied it stole the sandwich
idea.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Call this a hunch (or just a bad pun), but it sounds as if
someone is going to have their lunch eaten in the pursuit of bread.
</P>
<P>
   NOTHING IN LIFE IS FREE: It seems too good to be true _ and it
probably is.
</P>
<P>
   One Stop Communications ( &LR; www.shopss.com &LR; ), a New York online
shopping mall, says it is giving away Apple Computer's popular iMac
_ valued at $1,200 _ for free.
</P>
<P>
   But be sure to read the fine print: By the time you have
fulfilled your obligations to get one of the space-age Internet
computers, you'll have spent at least $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   That's how much One Stop wants in assorted charges to qualify
for a free iMac. For instance, you must agree to spend at least
$100 per month for three years on merchandise offered by a handful
of virtual stores, including auctioneer eBay's antiques page and an
FTD online floral shop, listed under One Stop's site. As of last
Friday, however, the site was experiencing technical glitches and
none of the mall's participants were accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers also must use One Stop as their Internet service
provider, at $19.95 a month &UR;  &LR; indefinitely. The charge is waived in
any month when a subscriber spends more than $200 at the online
mall.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this as well: According to Wired Digital, One Stop CEO
Israel Rosenfeld pitched a similar offer last summer through a
different company. Consumers were obligated to buy at least $100 of
online goods each month to receive free ISDN access. But that firm,
AcTVnet, quickly filed for bankruptcy, leaving customers out at
least $100.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer beware? How about buyer retreat!
</P>
<P>
   DOH!: A pair of astute readers point out that we've overlooked
the ideal actor to portray Oracle chief Larry Ellison in our
suggested movie about a deadly sailboat race in Australia last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Silver _ the Tony Award-winning thespian who recently joined
the cast of the NBC sitcom ``Veronica's Closet'' _ is the ideal
choice for the roguish software billionaire. The bearded New York
native looks and acts like Larry. If you need further proof, catch
his role as attorney Alan Dershowitz in the film ``Reversal of
Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   SITE OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's distinctly alternative bookstore, City Lights,
has gone digital at  &LR; www.citylights.com &LR; . Brush up on Dada,
surrealism and Beat Generation scions Jack Kerouac and Lawrence
Ferlinghetti.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Got any interesting or quirky Web sites you'd like to share? If
so, drop me an e-mail at  &LR; jswartz &LR; (AT-SIGN) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of NETFILES () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
