<HEADLINE>
DOMINION'S $6.3-BILLION DEAL FOR GAS UTILITY MARKS TREND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., Pa., Calif., Colo., Texas, Okla., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dominion Resources Inc. announced on Monday that it would
acquire the Consolidated Natural Gas Co. in a stock transaction
valued at $6.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Dominion Resources, a major electric utility based
in Richmond, Va. and Consolidated Natural Gas, a large natural gas
company based in Pittsburgh, Pa., said combining the companies
would allow them to serve smaller customers.
</P>
<P>
   And in another example of the trend toward combining utilities
and natural gas companies, the Sempra Energy Co., a large utility
in Southern California, announced Monday that it had agreed to
acquire KN Energy Inc., a large natural gas pipeline and storage
company based in Lakewood, Colo., for $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In another deal, the Southern Union Co., a natural gas utility
in Texas, said that it had offered $1.84 billion in cash and
assumed debt for the Southwest Gas Corp., which sells natural gas
to 1.2 million customers in Arizona, Nevada and California. The
offer tops a $1.73 billion bid made in December by Oneok Inc., a
gas company based in Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest said that its board had told its management to begin
negotiating with Southern Union, which is based in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Southwest closed at $28.375, up $1.75, while shares of
Southern Union closed at $19.75, up $1.8125. Shares of Oneok closed
at $27.375, up 43.75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   As the utility industry is deregulated, companies have sought to
strengthen their competitive positions by taking over natural gas
companies so that they can offer a package of electricity and
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Sempra Energy, which is based in San Diego, was formed last year
through the merger of the Enova Corp., an electric utility in San
Diego, and the gas company Pacific Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Since the deregulation of the natural gas industry took place
earlier than that of the electric utility industry in many states,
gas companies have developed the experience and the staff to
survive in a more competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Capps, the president, chairman and chief executive of
Dominion, said that was a major reason for the acquisition of
Consolidated.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania has allowed its customers to choose their natural
gas supplier for several years and recently gave them a choice of
suppliers for electricity.
</P>
<P>
   George A. Davidson Jr., the chairman of Consolidated, said in an
interview Monday that the utility had 310,000 customers for natural
gas in Pennsylvania's deregulated market, but had attracted only
22,000 customers for electricity. He said Consolidated would have
new sources of electricity and a larger customer base by combining
with Dominion.
</P>
<P>
   Capps said that there were 10.3 million customers for natural
gas and 17.5 million customers for electricity in Ohio,
Pennsylvania, Virginia, Maryland and West Virginia and that the
combined company would concentrate marketing in that area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a lot more residential customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a departure from the strategy of most utilities,
which have gone after large industrial customers where the returns
are expected to be greater. Even though many states on the East
Coast are deregulating and allowing customers to choose their
supplier of power, few marketers have made a major effort to sell
electricity to residential and small commercial customers because
it has been difficult to earn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller customers have seen their rates decrease mostly through
savings mandated by legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has really been successful with small customers,'' said
Robert Rubin, a utility analyst with Bear, Stearns. ``It will take
time and a lot of persistence.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Consolidated shareholders will each get
1.52 shares of Dominion Resources stock, valuing the transaction at
$64.22 a share, based on Friday's closing price. Dominion Resources
is also assuming Consolidated's debt of $2.15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of Dominion Resources closed at $40, down $2.25, and
shares of Consolidated closed at $55.1875, down $1.0625, in trading
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement with Sempra, shareholders of KN
Energy will get $25 a share in cash for each share, or 1.115 share
of Sempra's stock. Based on the close of Sempra's stock on Friday,
the stock offer translates to $24.88 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sempra closed at $21.5625, down 75 cents, and shares
of KN Energy closed at $21.625, 12.5 cents higher, in trading on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
