<SLUG> BC-MA-LOTTERY-AUDIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURER TO SEEK LOTTERY TICKET AUDIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Already faced with a $6.5 million theft in her office,
Massachusetts Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien is also grappling with
evidence of wrongdoing at the State Lottery, where investigators
have found evidence of a potential black market in tickets and a
$13 million debt owed by ticket vendors, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the sources familiar with the investigation,
O'Brien plans to contact a major auditing firm to review the
Lottery's books and operations following initial findings by
investigators working for State Auditor Joseph DeNucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believes there's a big problem down there,'' said one
source close to O'Brien, who just completed her first month in
office and is facing, with the missing $6.5 million, one of the
biggest thefts in state history.
</P>
<P>
   One of O'Brien's first acts as treasurer was to remove Beth
Lindstrom, former treasurer Joseph Malone's lottery executive
director, and hire Edward Lashman as an interim director. Lashman
is a former top state official in the Dukakis administration and
has a reputation as a tough trouble-shooter.
</P>
<P>
   The problems at the lottery, which generates $3.2 billion in
sales each year, came to light during O'Brien's transition into the
office when DeNucci's auditors briefed her on some initial findings
of an ongoing investigation. Since then, a source said, O'Brien has
focused intently on the agency and its problems.
</P>
<P>
   The suspicions of wrongdoing are occuring just as Attorney
General Thomas F. Reilly, tipped off by BankBoston over a
suspicious transaction, last week began prosecuting the theft of
$6.5 million from the treasurer's cash management division.
</P>
<P>
   ``This operation like any other multibillion industry should be
reviewed annually with an independent audit,'' O'Brien said in a
statement released by her office. ``With that money at stake, we
need to be absolutely certain that appropriate financial controls
are in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Robson, O'Brien's spokesman, said the lottery will be
contracting shortly with a major auditing firm to review the
lottery's books. The results of that audit, along with DeNucci's
report, will determine what course O'Brien will take.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said the state treasurer has yet to go public with the
initial findings for fear that it would shake the public's
confidence in the state lottery, an enormous cash cow for the state
and a major source of local aid to municipalities. The lottery
generates $750 million in funds that the state sends to cities and
towns.
</P>
<P>
   The sources familar with the investigation said Monday that
DeNucci is preparing a report that shows that the 8,000 private
vendors that sell lottery tickets owe the agency about $13 million,
a debt that has nearly doubled in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The question has been raised as to why the lottery has not
pressed those vendors for the money. Some lottery officials have
told O'Brien's aides that the agency had wanted to give a break to
the vendors, many of whom are operating small businesses on a tight
budget.
</P>
<P>
   However, investigators are concerned that, in fact, not all the
tickets that were billed to the vendors were sent out.
Investigators are trying to determine if lottery employees may have
used the tickets for private gain.
</P>
<P>
   One source said that some of the attempts to collect the $13
million stopped short when the vendors were able to demonstrate
that they never received the tickets that were recorded as having
been printed and sent to them.
</P>
<P>
   Lashman said he is not aware of any reports of a black market
for lottery tickets. ``This is the first I have heard of it, but I
am happy to look into it,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lashman also said he is reviewing the $13 million that vendors
owe the lottery to determine whether it is a serious problem facing
the agency. He said the lottery is also owed another $2 million
from vendors that is not collectable because they have gone out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be sure we will have the type of controls that
prevents any losses of funds that in the end go to prize winners
and to cities and town,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
