<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Diedrich Coffee Hopes Investors Are Thirsty for Second Serving  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Will investors go for a second cup of Diedrich Coffee?
</P>
<P>
   The Irvine coffee house chain plans on holding a secondary stock
offering to help pay for its $35 million buyout of Castroville's
Coffee People, according to documents filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Diedrich's plan to buy Coffee People hinges directly
upon the success of such a stock offering. Without it, Diedrich
won't have the money to do the deal, and any buyout agreement will
evaporate like the foam atop a double cappuccino.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks ago, Street Smarts spotlighted little-known
Diedrich's bid for Coffee People, citing it as a reason to talk
about the company's strong potential as a turnaround candidate. The
acquisition announcement was one of the first bold strokes by
Diedrich Chairman John Martin, the former head of Taco Bell, since
he had taken the helm of Diedrich more than a year ago. Martin,
incidentally, has invested about $1 million of his own cash in the
once-beleaguered coffee chain.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed takeover, Coffee People shareholders would
get $10.8 million in cash, proceeds from a bank loan, and 1.7
million shares of Diedrich stock.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, they would get another $14.3 million in cash from the net
proceeds of the stock offering, which Diedrich plans to hold before
the buyout closes.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how events are expected to unfold. Diedrich and Coffee
People hope to nail down their definitive acquisition agreement
(they currently have just a letter of intent) by March 5. About
three weeks after the agreement is reached, Diedrich will file its
prospectus for the secondary offering. And if the offering flies,
both companies hope to close the buyout before the end of summer.
Thus far, Diedrich has yet to choose an underwriter for the
offering. However, San Francisco's First Securities Van Kasper is
presumably in the running. It is the only investment bank with a
financial analyst that provides research on Diedrich. The analyst,
Eric Wold, who has a buy on the stock, would not comment on an
offering.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET23 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  According to a registration statement filed with the SEC,
Diedrich hopes to sell about 1.5 million shares at about $6 a
share. The current float, or number of shares that are publicly
traded, is 4.1 million. The stock has risen about $1.50 on the
buyout news and has been trading above $6 a share since then.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Diedrich, whose stock trades over the counter, isn't
for the faint of heart. While Chairman John Martin and Chief
Executive Officer Tim Ryan have demonstrated the ability to build a
national fast-food chain, there are no guarantees that they can
duplicate that magic.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, after some diligent observations by readers of
Street Smarts, it was discovered that some of the explosive growth
of Taco Bell under Martin and Ryan wasn't clearly represented. The
two men saw the number of full-scale restaurants at Taco Bell grow
from 1,500 to about 7,000 during their 13-year tenure. An earlier
press release cited that they grew the concept to ``25,000
outlets.''
</P>
<P>
   While not inaccurate, that total included joint ventures with
gasoline stations and reduced-scale ``express'' outlets on college
campuses. The number also included point-of-sale displays in
grocery stores where Taco Bell packaged products are sold, says
Diedrich Chief Financial Officer Ann Wride.
</P>
<P>
   Still, judging by the high interest in Diedrich stock by Street
Smarts readers, it is prudent to remind investors that Diedrich is
a turnaround play. Remember: This company has posted losses in
three of its past five fiscal years.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of STREET23 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  However, as mentioned in the earlier column, Diedrich shows
promise. It's worth watching Martin and Co. over the next several
months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
