<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5197 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON &LR;      02-22 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 What to Do If You're 13 And Have $10,000  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I'm a 13-year-old girl who received a $10,000 gift from
my grandmother. I'm thinking of investing the money in a
combination of stock ($6,000), an IRA account consisting of either
Vanguard or Merrill Lynch stock mutual funds ($2,000) and a bank
certificate of deposit ($2,000). The stock I have in mind is my
father's company, which is not yet publicly traded, but he says it
has a great future. Does this sound like a good plan?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Answer: &LR;  I can't say for sure because I don't know anything
about your father's company. It's not surprising that he speaks
well of it, but it's my understanding (and experience) that
adolescent girls aren't shy about challenging their parents. Make
him prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, maybe I'm being too skeptical. Nowadays, any privately
held company seems to be a good investment _ provided it plans to
go public. If you can get in at a bargain price before the initial
public offering, you might be able to retire before age 20.
</P>
<P>
   The investment in stock mutual funds seems appropriate for a
young person. In the long run, a diversified portfolio of stocks is
likely to outperform most other types of investment. However, bear
in mind that you must have some earned income to contribute to an
IRA. Your maximum contribution each year is $2,000 or the amount
you earn, whichever is less.
</P>
<P>
   As for the certificate of deposit, it certainly is safe enough.
But the current 4 percent or 5 percent annual return from CDs is
piddling. I don't know why you would want to limit yourself this
way unless you think you will need to spend that portion of your
money in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   IRA Withdrawals
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have an Individual Retirement Account with about $14,000 in
it. I am not yet 59-1/2 years old, but I would like to withdraw all
the money. My situation is complicated by the fact that I am living
and working outside the United States and will not have any
reportable income this year except for investment income. Will I be
allowed to offset the tax on my IRA withdrawal with deductions and
exemptions? (I am married, filing jointly with my wife.) Also, will
I incur the 10 percent penalty for early withdrawal from my IRA?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Last question first: Yes, you will have to pay the 10
percent penalty _ $1,400 in your case _ because you haven't yet
reached age 59-1/2. That is unless you are withdrawing the money to
pay for education expenses, in which case there is no penalty. The
same holds true for the first $10,000 you withdraw to purchase a
first home.
</P>
<P>
   You also will have to pay regular income tax on whichever
portion of the $14,000 in your IRA constitutes taxable income. If
this is a deductible IRA, then all the money in the account is
taxable. If it is a nondeductible IRA, then only your investment
gains are taxable.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MONEYBAG () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  However, you should be able to offset most or all of the taxable
amount with deductions and exemptions. You and your wife are
entitled to a total of $5,500 in exemptions for 1999, and an
additional $2,750 for each dependent child. You also can take a
joint standard deduction of $7,200 _ or you may be able to top that
if you itemize deductions.
</P>
<P>
   Your question breezes past the interesting fact that income you
may be earning abroad is exempt from income tax. This wasn't always
true, but it is now _ provided you have been abroad for at least a
year. The foreign earned-income exclusion for 1999 is $74,000 _
meaning that up to that amount of salary and self-employment income
is exempt from U.S. income taxes. You do have to report the income
_ on Form 2555 _ but that is just a formality (or nuisance,
depending on your point of view). Your investment income remains
taxable.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Options vs. Restricted
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you please explain the difference between restricted
stock and stock options, and also the difference between vested and
unvested stock options?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Although you don't say so, your question seems to imply
that you are in a position to profit if your employer's stock
performs well. Perhaps you have a choice between options and
restricted stock?
</P>
<P>
   Restricted stock is a gift from your employer of a specified
number of shares. However, you can't take possession and sell the
stock until you satisfy certain conditions. Normally, you only have
to remain with your employer for a stated number of years. This
type of compensation most often is used to retain valuable
employees who might otherwise jump to the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Stock options give you the right to buy a stated number of
shares at a fixed price before a fixed date _ usually 10 years
after the options are granted. They can become valuable if the
stock shoots up, but they also can expire worthless if they fall
below the grant price and stay there.
</P>
<P>
   Your employer may require you to wait a certain period of time
before the options become vested _ that is, before you are entitled
to buy the stock and pocket any profits.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a choice between restricted stock and options, you
should ask yourself how high (or low) you expect your company's
stock to go in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   If you expect the stock to go down, then it's no contest: Take
the restricted stock because, unlike the options, it will be worth
something when you finally get your mitts on it.
</P>
<P>
   If you think the stock will go up, that will be favorable
whether your take restricted stock or options. There is no pat
answer as to which will be better.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MONEYBAG () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  You will have to do the arithmetic, taking into account just how
far you think the stock can rise over various periods of time. You
also must consider the number of restricted shares involved and the
number of options. Make the choice that will leave you holding the
most money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
