<HEADLINE>
FEDERALIZING LOCAL CRIMES BAD POLICY, BAR TASK FORCE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ When a Black man in Texas was dragged to his death
last year behind a pickup truck, the call went out for a federal
law against such vicious hate crimes even though state prosecutors
had already charged three White men with capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a task force of the American Bar Association cited
that case as an example of a ``misguided, unnecessary and even
harmful'' trend in Congress to federalize crimes that have long
been handled by state and local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's member on the 17-person task force said broadened
federal criminal jurisdiction ``is an unfortunate usurpation of the
traditional authority of states in our federal system.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Susan Ehrlich of the state Court of Appeals said the
problem ``could undermine the state courts and lead to a sense of
local impotence in the face of federal authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlich, a former federal prosecutor, cited President Clinton's
call for a federal law against drunken driving as an example of a
politically expedient get-tough mentality in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federalization trend has far-reaching consequences,'' said
the panel, headed by former U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese.
</P>
<P>
   ``It strains the constitutional view that local crime is, with
rare exception, a matter for the states to attack,'' the task force
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a phenomenon capable of altering the careful
decentralization of criminal law authority that has worked well in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force cited political grandstanding as a principal
source of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not considered politically wise to vote against crime
legislation,'' even if it is not necessary, the panel concluded.
They quoted a legal scholar's contention that such efforts are
``symbolic gestures to appease the public rather than actual
attempts to reduce crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force report noted that Congress has weighed in over
the past several years by making such crimes as carjacking and
drive-by shootings federal offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The recent congressional effort continued a trend that began in
the 1970s. The task force reported that more than 40 percent of the
federal criminal laws enacted since the Civil War were adopted
after 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The surge is continuing. Over the past two years, senators and
representatives sponsored nearly a thousand bills dealing with
criminal statutes.
</P>
<P>
   The spate of federal legislation has produced little federal
prosecution. There were no drive-by shooting or domestic violence
cases in federal courts, for example, despite the public outcry
that included such crimes in the 1994 crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   That inactivity led the task force to conclude: ``Increased
federalization is rarely, if ever, likely to have any appreciable
effect on the categories of violent crime that most concern
Americans, because in practice federal criminal law enforcement can
only reach a small percent of such activity.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
