r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE3-SFCHRON &LR;      02-22 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE3-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Using Women's Intuition  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Shari Smith, 51, co-owner with her husband of a tool-making
company, started trading from her home in San Carlos more than a
year ago with $200,000 in savings. Now she has $530,000, thanks
largely to an uncanny ability to predict price moves in Nasdaq
stocks by staring at the ticker tape on CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   She got hooked on Internet trading after talking to some women
friends who already were doing it. Women, she says, are
particularly suited for this kind of investing because they are
``intuitive and visual.''
</P>
<P>
   She used to work full time in the family business, but her
trading has proved more lucrative. Her only previous investment
experience was with mutual funds, ``but I made very little money.''
</P>
<P>
   Her market day actually starts in the evening. ``It's the best
time to place your trades, when the market isn't open and you
aren't emotionally involved.''
</P>
<P>
   She bases her choices on the previous session's price action.
She follows 20 or 30 stocks at a time _ ``primarily technology,
they're more volatile; AOL and AtHome are good trading stocks'' _
watching the prices scroll across the bottom of the TV screen on
CNBC. Then her intuition takes over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a feel for the direction of a stock, whether I can get
it at a low price in the opening hour the next day. After that,
there is generally a bounce up in the morning. I often buy and sell
a stock before the end of the first hour of trading. A long-term
hold for me is three or four days.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is as intense as Tom Weeden, the San Mateo day trader, is
easygoing. She bristled at a suggestion that luck could have
contributed to her success.
</P>
<P>
   ``My trading rules are very strict,'' she says. ``Hold your
winners; cut your losses. There's no exception. You have to be
unemotional about it. I used stop-loss orders a lot last year, when
the market was going down in the summer. (A stop-loss orders a
broker to sell a stock if it falls to a specified price. It is
designed to protect a profit or limit a loss.)
</P>
<P>
   She concludes: ``There's a lot of opportunity out there if
people are willing to study and learn the rules.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
