<SLUG> BC-PINKERTON-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITAS OF SWEDEN TO ACQUIRE PINKERTON'S IN $384-MILLION DEAL
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pinkerton's Inc., the detective and security company that has
struggled to keep up as the security problems of its big
multinational clients have become global, said on Monday that it
had agreed to be acquired by Securitas AB of Sweden for $384
million.
</P>
<P>
   The rich premium _ at $29 a share, the offer was 72 percent
above Pinkerton's closing price of $16.88 last Friday _ underscored
the value of a famous name in the low-margin security business.
Pinkerton's, which is based in Westlake Village, Calif., was
founded in 1850 by Allan Pinkerton, a Scottish immigrant who had
become Chicago's first detective.
</P>
<P>
   Securitas, which has built itself into a European powerhouse in
the highly fragmented industry through acquisitions, expects to use
Pinkerton's to leap to prominence in the United States, too, and to
pursue more business from huge multinational companies.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will have sales of about $3.5 billion, 114,000
employees in Europe, the Americas and Asia, and about 5 percent of
the global security market.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas W. Wathen, Pinkerton's chairman and its largest
shareholder with a 30.6 percent stake, has already agreed to sell
his shares to Securitas.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Pinkerton's jumped $11.6875, or 69.3 percent, to
$28.5625 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange. An even
stronger indication of investor enthusiasm was apparent in Sweden,
where Securitas' shares jumped 15 percent, or 18.5 kronor ($2.31),
to 139.5 kronor, in trading on the Stockholm Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkerton's derives just under 90 percent of its revenue from
guard services these days, although it also sells alarms and
provides security consulting.
</P>
<P>
   The company initially specialized in investigating train
robberies, but it quickly gained renown for uncovering a plot to
assassinate Abraham Lincoln in 1861 when he was president-elect.
Its ``We Never Sleep'' slogan and its trademark, an open left eye
that gave birth to the term private eye, have been fixtures on the
business landscape ever since.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 2208EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
