<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5207 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMWESMAIN-AZR &LR;      02-22 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMWESMAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA WEST-UNITED DEAL WON'T FLY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT AND DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ America West Airlines answered the billion-dollar
question about its future Monday by saying no to a merger with
another airline.
</P>
<P>
   Citing ``antitrust, regulatory and employee issues,'' America
West Chairman Bill Franke ended weeks of speculation, saying the
airline's board of directors had unanimously concluded it should
remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   UAL Corp.'s United Airlines, the world's largest carrier, had
expressed interest in buying the airline to bolster United's West
Coast operations and add planes to its growing hub at Dulles
International Airport in Washington. UAL reportedly made a bid for
America West last week.
</P>
<P>
   Franke said America West is no longer considering bids by United
or any other airline.
</P>
<P>
   His comments drew cheers from a crowd of employees gathered
Monday outside the company's downtown Tempe offices.
</P>
<P>
   United had little to say about America West's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we're disappointed at this announcement by America West,
we will continue to run our company in the best interest of
employees, shareholders and the communities we serve,'' the
Chicago-based carrier said in a memo to employees late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   United spokesman Andy Plews declined to comment on whether
United would raise the cash offer it reportedly made for America
West last week.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its initial announcement a month ago that it was
interested in America West, United has not commented on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had pegged America West's takeover value at between $23
and $30 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about a deal surfaced Jan. 20 when America West and
United disclosed that merger talks were underway. No dollar figure
was ever revealed, but analysts said it could have been as high as
$1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions from reporters, Franke bristled at
suggestions that America West had hung a for sale sign on the
company. He called that speculation ``total B.S. promoted by the
local press and others.''
</P>
<P>
   As a public company, America West had a responsibility to
shareholders to consider the ``expressions of interest'' from other
carriers, Franke said, adding that there were no formal offers made
by United or any other carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't comment on who did or who didn't or what the
circumstances were,'' Franke said, citing confidentiality
agreements between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the news conference he said: ``There was no deal
that we were entertaining. There were no negotiations we were
having.''
</P>
<P>
   Had a formal offer been made, America West would have been
required by law to disclose it.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Pressnell of Chandler, who was traveling on an America West
flight Monday, said he's glad the merger talks are off because it
would have meant higher air fares for Phoenix-area travelers.
Observers feared United would cut Phoenix routes and move some of
America West's planes to other hubs.
</P>
<P>
   With the merger talks now scuttled, Franke said America West
will continue to expand with its hubs in Phoenix, Las Vegas and
Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have significant strategic opportunities,''
Franke said. ``We have positioned the airline with a low-cost
structure, a flexible fleet plan, a strong balance sheet, growing
hubs and committed employees. We are confident about the company's
future as an independent airline.''
</P>
<P>
   Franke has said that the airline has 28 new planes coming into
its fleet over the next three years and will add 100 flights per
day out of Sky Harbor International Airport. It currently has 214
daily departures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this airline has a very strong future in front of it
and you'll continue to see us grow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While some employees cheered the announcement, others were
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Bill McGlashen, president of the Association of Flight
Attendants Council 66, said the employees and flying public would
be better off if United took over America West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope United Airlines isn't scared off that easily in its
attempt to purchase America West,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An end to the current merger speculation comes as America West
is embroiled in a labor dispute with flight attendants. Contract
talks have broken off and a 30-day cooling off period expires at
midnight March 20 EST. After that, the flight attendants are free
to strike and they plan to engage in intermittent unannounced
strikes if a settlement isn't reached.
</P>
<P>
   America West has said it will consider shutting down operations
entirely in the event of a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots union Chairman Donald Steinman encouraged America West to
``focus on reaching a fair and equitable resolution in the flight
attendants' contract negotiations'' now that merger talks are over.
</P>
<P>
   Two flight attendants at Sky Harbor International Airport who
declined to be identified said they had hoped for a merger because
it might have improved pay and morale, which are at rock bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``If United came in, it might improve the way management feels
about employees,'' one said. ``They just think we're here to push
peanuts.''
</P>
<P>
   An America West pilot, who also spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said he thinks that eventually America West will be
swallowed up by another carrier because it can't compete against
the major carriers at its present size.
</P>
<P>
   Airline policy prohibits employees from speaking with the media.
</P>
<P>
   Airline observers suggested that United's interest in America
West was a response to American Airlines' acquisition of Reno Air
and an alliance with Alaska Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. Justice Department scrutiny of an America West deal was
seen as a major hurdle because United, the nation's largest
carrier, would have solidified its domination of the Western market
by acquiring No. 9 America West.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines' right of first refusal also was viewed as
a major stumbling block to an alliance. Continental was interested
in protecting its alliance with America West.
</P>
<P>
   America West made the announcement that merger talks were over
after the stock market closed Monday, but some investors obviously
got wind of the company's plans to stay independent. On a day when
airline stocks and the market in general were up, America West's
stock fell $1.38, to $21.38 in extremely heavy trading. United's
stock rose $2.50, to $62.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect America West's stock to fall again today as
investors who bought the stock on speculation of a sale bail out.
The stock was trading in the $16 to $18 range before merger
speculation drove up the price a month ago. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. Dawn Gilbertson may be reached
at 444-8617 or dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
