<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS WANT PIECE OF OLIVETTI-TELECOM ITALIA DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: With OLIVETTI-TELECOM) 
(mk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it Wall Street's version of ``piling on'' in a football
game.
</P>
<P>
   But almost every investment bank was scrambling to get a piece
of the action in Olivetti SpA's hostile offer for the
telecommunications giant Telecom Italia SpA last weekend. Eleven
European and U.S. banks have lined up to represent various parties
in the transaction, which suffered a setback Monday when Italian
regulators said Olivetti's bid was not admissible.
</P>
<P>
   The tussle over Telecom Italia is reminiscent of Kohlberg Kravis
&AMP; Roberts' bid for RJR Nabisco in 1988, the decade's defining
hostile takeover. But this time, the investment banks representing
Olivetti have a personal stake in seeing the bid succeed because
the deal represents their shot at breaking into the European market
and attracting attention. ``These things are a lot like casting a
Broadway play,'' said one investment banker who asked not be
identified. ``There are lead actors, supporting players, the chorus
and bit parts. Right now there is a mighty struggle for every
banker to find a role.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the list of banks involved is so confusing that a chart
is needed to track the dealmakers. Olivetti has been working with
bankers since last November _ including Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette and Lehman Brothers, both of which have been vying for a
place as the mastermind behind the bid, said people close to the
companies. ``This looks like a feeding frenzy,'' said Samuel Hayes,
a professor of finance at the Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   But that strategy could backfire. One concern, said people close
to the companies, is that the high profile of the bankers in this
deal could attract the attention of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, something Olivetti does not want. The commission has no
jurisdiction over the offer because it is not open to U.S.
investors, but it could try to get involved because the bulk of the
bond buyers would most likely be U.S. institutions.
</P>
<P>
   That would slow the takeover process by as much as six months.
Olivetti is also being advised by Mediobanco SpA and Chase
Manhattan Bank; Germany's Mannesmann AG, Olivetti's phone business
partner, has retained Merrill Lynch and Deutsche Bank AG.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia is believed to have a team of four banks in
place. Most of those bankers _ Credit Suisse First Boston, IMI
Banca SpA, Lazard Brothers &AMP; Co. and J.P. Morgan _ have long-term
relationships with Italia and more of a presence in Europe than the
Olivetti team. That, said one analyst, could give them an edge over
their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be left out, a team of bankers from Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter's London and Italian offices was in Rome Monday meeting with
government officials. That would leave Goldman, Sachs; Salomon
Smith Barney, and Bear, Stearns to represent other companies that
are interested in Telecom Italia, such as British Telecom or a U.S.
concern, like Bell Atlantic, said people close to the companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
