r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     02-22 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN CIRCUS COMES TO TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In addition to the usual nose and ear rings, goofy hat, weird
clothes, bizarre necklace, toadying entourage and fawning female
admirer this time it was actually his wife, Carmen Electra Dennis
Rodman Monday pulled a new trick from his freak show repertoire of
sleaze.
</P>
<P>
   Tears.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, Rodman, reacting to being accused of selfishness by
the media at a late morning press conference at the Planet
Hollywood in Beverly Hills, actually began to weep in what was
either a sincere display of emotion or a contrived bit of
play-acting calculated to boost his cinematic career.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what the reaction of Jerry West was several hundred
miles away in Las Vegas he was there on a scouting expedition but
it wouldn't have surprised me if West, too, began crying when
Rodman announced it was a certainty he would be signing with the
Lakers Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The executive vice president of basketball operations for the
Lakers wants Rodman to join his team about as much as he wants
Shaquille O'Neal to miss free throws, but he has no choice in the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Del Harris, who probably also broke out in tears
when it became painfully clear that he soon will be coaching the
tattoo-covered, kaleidoscopic-hairstyled, party-crazed,
gambling-addicted, rebounding-obsessed oddity who's sort of a
hybrid between Howard Stern and Hulk Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only person I know rejoicing in the Laker
organization at the thought of Dennis Rodman actually becoming a
part of it is none other than Jerry Buss, the only person who
really counts.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Mr. Buss happens to own the team.
</P>
<P>
   He has been the driving inspiration being the signing of Rodman,
a seven-time NBA rebounding champion who's been on five
title-winning teams, including the past three seasons with the
Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Buss, a drinker, gambler and notorious skirt chaser in his own
right, admits part of the reason he's so enamored with Rodman is
that he relates so well to him.
</P>
<P>
   And anyone who saw the two fun-loving men downing kamikazes last
Friday evening after the Laker-San Antonio match at the Forum could
understand Buss' sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the second time in two years, Buss has chosen to
ignore the advice of West, who understandably views the 37-year-old
Rodman as an annoying nuisance capable of disrupting a young Laker
team with his well-chronicled shenanigans that are a part of his
persona.
</P>
<P>
   You may recall that early last season West had a trade worked
out with the Sacramento Kings, wherein the Lakers would have
received the All-Star guard, Mitch Richmond, for Eddie Jones only
for Buss to nix the transaction in what, in retrospect, was a
terrible miscalculation by Buss.
</P>
<P>
   There is also speculation among Laker insiders that West would
have liked to have made a coaching change in the off-season, but
once again Buss disagreed with West and prevented him from dumping
Del Harris.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time in their 20-year working relationship when
Jerry Buss always ultimately deferred to West's opinion, as he did
in 1986 when Buss was set to trade James Worthy to the Dallas
Mavericks for Mark Aguirre and the drafting rights to Roy Tarpley
only to pull the deal off the table when West threatened to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West won't threaten to resign over Buss' latest personnel
brainstorm West just last summer signed a four year, $16-million
contract extension but it's not a coincidence that he's been
keeping discreetly out of view during Buss' passionate pursuit of
Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   He's not happy about it, and even Dennis Rodman himself admits
he's not sure he will be warmly welcomed by the Laker players when
he starts performing for the team, which might be as soon as
Thursday against the Los Angeles Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I discover I'm not wanted, I'll leave,'' said Rodman. ``I
think I can help this team. I have the experience of playing on
winning teams. This team needs a guy who can get rebounds, and I'm
that guy. But if I'm not wanted, I'll leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman was quintessential Dennis Rodman during the
30-minute session, in which there were almost as many members of
the tabloid press present as there were of the mainstream press.
</P>
<P>
   He told of a sexual act performed on him by his pint-sized wife,
much to the laughter of the crowd, as cameras whirred and sound
bites faced FCC monitoring. Not to be out-done, Carmen Electra
stepped up to the podium and said Rodman had performed the same act
on her, which also drew guffaws.
</P>
<P>
   Ha, ha, ha.
</P>
<P>
   Real funny.
</P>
<P>
   Real, nice, role model stuff, more fodder for the deviancy down
of modern society.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman argued with sportswriters who had the temerity to ask why
he would call a press conference if he hadn't yet signed his name
on a Laker contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to make a big spectacle out of all this,'' he
said with a straight face, at least as straight as a guy can keep
it with rings sticking out of both nostrils. ``Can you imagine what
kind of zoo it would be if we held a press conference before a
Laker game?''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman kept insisting he wasn't playing for the salary-cap
restricted money that Jerry Buss plans to pay him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be making only $495,000,'' he said. ``And after
taxes, it'll be about $200,000. I'm playing for the people. I'm
playing because I'm bored and need something to do. I'm playing
because I feel I can help the Lakers win a world title.''
</P>
<P>
   The tears began streaming down Rodman's eyes that were covered
by sunglasses after a lady newscaster accused him of being selfish
for dragging out the negotiations with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you say I've been selfish?'' he asked rhetorically, as
he was being consoled by his sister and his newest Hollywood agent
stooge. ``I'm giving $150,000 of my salary this year to charity.
I've given more than $4 million to charity.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on for a few more emotional moments and then, as if on
cue, his tears suddenly disappeared and he and his hangers-on made
a briskly theatrical exit.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea if Dennis Rodman was honestly upset, or if he was
auditioning to play Madonna's boyfriend in a remake of ``Love
Story.''
</P>
<P>
   All I know is that Dennis Rodman is one whacked-out character
who's going to create a lot of chaos with the Lakers, and perhaps
grab a few rebounds, too.
</P>
<P>
   And I also know that Jerry Buss and Jerry West, once so in tune
with each other when the Lakers were the most envied franchise in
the NBA, no longer are on the same wave length as the Lakers move
into dangerous terrain with the coming of Dennis Rodman.
</P>
</TEXT>
