<SLUG> BC-CANCER-STUDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCES TREAT CANCER OF THE CERVIX 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Patients with advanced cervical cancer who are treated
with a combination of radiation and chemotherapy may increase their
chances of survival by as much as 50 percent, according to studies
by a local hospital and four others around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are considered so significant that the National
Cancer Institute, which sponsored the studies, on Monday issued a
``clinical announcement'' urging cancer specialists to consider
adding chemotherapy to radiation in the treatment of advanced
cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first fundamental advance in the treatment of
cervical cancer in more than 40 years,'' said Dr. Mitchell Morris,
the oncologist who directed the Houston study at the University of
Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have the data, it is vital to make chemotherapy a
part of standard care for women with advanced cervical cancer.
Every day that we wait to make it a part of treatment fewer women
have the opportunity to benefit,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   About 14,000 women in the United States are diagnosed with
cervical cancer annually, one-third of whom die because present
treatments have been ineffective against advanced forms of the
disease, Morris told reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When diagnosed early, the prognosis is generally good for women
with cervical cancer. But the outlook for patients with advanced
cervical cancer _ normally treated with radical surgery or
radiation alone _ has been less hopeful if the cancer spreads,
Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time a patient experiences symptoms _ abnormal bleeding,
a discharge or pelvic pain _ the tumor may be quite large.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year survival rate for women with advanced cervical
cancer is 58 percent for those who receive the traditional
radiation-only therapy, compared with 73 percent for women who
receive radiation and chemotherapy simultaneously, according to the
Houston study.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston study followed patients from two to eight years _
195 women were given chemotherapy and radiation therapy, and 193
women were given radiation alone.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the women on the combination therapy received
radiation five days a week, chemotherapy with the drugs cisplatin
and 5-flourouracil and radioactive implants that remain within the
body for 48 hours at a time. The therapy regimen lasted about eight
to 8 1/2 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The study revealed that the disease-free survival rates were 66
percent &UR;  &LR; for patients who were given both chemotherapy and
radiation and 40 percent for those receiving only radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said the chemo-radiation combination may work because the
chemotherapy drugs are ``sensitizers'' that increase the
sensitivity of cancer cells to radiation, making them easier to
kill.
</P>
<P>
   The chemotherapy drugs also might wipe out cancer deposits too
small to detect at the time of treatment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Williams was a 47-year-old mother with three children at
home when she became the second patient to enter the study in 1990.
She said she was scared to undergo chemotherapy because of the side
effects, but experienced little nausea and minimal hair loss.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer-free for eight years, Williams now believes that the
combination therapy was a miracle cure.
</P>
<P>
   But while she and fellow patient Lizzet Escoto hope others will
follow their treatment, they warned against skipping annual Pap
smears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let other things get in the way,'' Williams advised.
</P>
<P>
   Escoto, 39, said she had not had a Pap smear in years and
experienced heavy bleeding for five months before visiting a
doctor. ``I thought I was going through menopause,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of widespread screening, the incidence of cervical
cancer has dropped in the United States by half since the 1970s.
The Pap smear test is 90 percent effective in detecting the
disease, even before symptoms appear.
</P>
<P>
   But in countries where screening is inadequate, the death rate
is high. Morris said most of the cancer deaths among Mexican women
are attributed to cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the National Cancer Institute funded five studies aimed
at studying the treatment of advanced cervical cancer. The studies
were conducted primarily at M.D. Anderson, Washington University
School of Medicine in St. Louis, New York University and the State
University of New York Health Science Center.
</P>
<P>
   Reports on three of the studies will be published in the April
15 issue of the New England Journal of Medicine; they also have
been posted on the Journal's Web site (www.nejm.org).
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Patricia Eifel, who also worked on the Houston study, said
researchers are testing similar combinations on cancers of the head
and neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major milestone in the treatment of this disease,''
Morris said. ``The use of chemo-radiation for women with cervical
cancer will have a tremendous impact and save thousands of lives
every year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
