<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPERDEATH-TRIAL23-C     02-22 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPERDEATH-TRIAL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Words of Jasper killing suspect speak loudly, despite refusal to
testify
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The white supremacist accused of dragging a
black man to death chose not to testify in his trial, but jurors
heard his words anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made history and shall die proudly remembered if need
be,'' John William ``Bill'' King boasted in a jailhouse letter
after his arrest for the shocking death of James Byrd Jr. last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter read in court Monday, King said his sandals
probably were stained with the black man's blood. But, he wrote,
``We'll know how to handle those things by the time we go to
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   King's lawyers handled things by putting on a defense that
lasted just under an hour and included only three witnesses _ one
foul-mouthed convict and two acquaintances who acknowledged King
has a strong disliking for black people.
</P>
<P>
   The jury will begin deliberations today in a murder that has
jolted America. King, 24, faces the death penalty if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Even though King did not take the witness stand, his words
reverberated through the Jasper County courtroom during the
weeklong trial. King spoke loud and clear through his prolific
writings _ letters to friends and newspapers, dogma about white
supremacy, poetry, and, even, graffiti found scratched on the metal
door of his jail cell.
</P>
<P>
   King's writings, introduced as evidence by prosecutors, espouse
survival of the Aryan race, white pride, death to race traitors,
and Ku Klux Klan principles.
</P>
<P>
   After King's self-incriminating jailhouse letter was given to
the jury Monday, Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray
called the document ``pretty close to a confession.''
</P>
<P>
   The last horrifying moments of Byrd's life were reviewed in
graphic detail Monday, prompting the murder victim's eldest
daughter to leave the courtroom. Other family members wiped their
eyes, and the murder defendant's father left the courtroom
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   For 11 silent minutes, the jury and 17 rows of courtroom
spectators were transported via movie screen to the long, winding
road where Byrd was dragged behind a pickup truck until he was
beheaded. Prosecutors played a videotape shot from a police car
that drove down the rural Jasper road marked with dozens of orange
circles where Byrd's personal items and body parts were found. The
last scene showed the stained spot in the road where Byrd's
shredded torso was dumped.
</P>
<P>
   One woman on the jury removed her glasses and wiped her eyes
with a tissue during the video. The somber mood was enhanced by the
darkened courtroom; the wood shutters had been drawn and cardboard
had been placed over some of the stained-glass windows for the
screening.
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment today,'' said Clara Taylor, one of Byrd's sisters,
who sat with a stunned look on her face for several minutes after
the film was over and the judge declared a 20-minute recess.
</P>
<P>
   Before watching the video, the jury of 11 whites and one
African-American was told by a forensic pathologist that Byrd was
alive when he was dragged down the rural blacktop. The timing of
Byrd's death is crucial for prosecutors because they must prove
Byrd was kidnapped before he was killed in order to win a capital
murder conviction against King.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my opinion that, while being dragged, Mr. Byrd was
conscious and attempting to relieve the pain and injuries that he
was receiving,'' said Dr. Tommy Brown of Port Arthur, who performed
the autopsy on Byrd last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd struggled to stay on his elbows and shift from side to side
until his body slammed into a concrete drain pipe opening, Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was alive when the head, the right arm and shoulder were
separated'' from the torso by the collision with the culvert, Brown
said. ``He had blood pressure and had a heartbeat at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pathologist testified, each member of the jury followed
along with a notebook of 14 color photographs of Byrd's battered
body.
</P>
<P>
   King showed no emotion Monday except for a brief smile exchanged
with the first defense witness, a tattoo artist in state prison who
winked at King as he sat down in the witness box.
</P>
<P>
   John ``Big Moe'' Mosley, who is serving time for burglary and
sexual assault, gave King some of the tattoos that cover much of
his body. He said King got tattooed to send a message that he would
fight to protect himself from black inmates who preyed on white
prisoners of small stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't fight, you got to give them your momma's money
and give them sexual favors,'' Mosley said.
</P>
<P>
   The other defense witnesses, a friend and a former employer,
said King did not use racial slurs in public, display racial
animosity on the job or try to recruit them into a gang. But the
friend, Gilbert Cunningham, told the FBI earlier that King was a
proud white supremacist. The former employer, Dennis Symmack, who
hired King for construction work, acknowledged under
cross-examination that King was intensely bitter toward blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys have tried to portray King as a young man
whose attitudes toward blacks changed dramatically in prison, where
he felt vulnerable as a 5-foot 7-inch, 140-pound white man.
</P>
<P>
   King turned to the Knights of the White Confederacy gang in
prison as a defense, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors contend King is a hate-filled racist and planned
an attack on a black person as a high-profile feat to gain
credibility for a white supremacy gang he was forming in Jasper
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Even after his arrest in Byrd's killing, King did not stop
promoting racism, evidence introduced Monday showed.
</P>
<P>
   Law officers found that King had scratched some graffiti in his
Jasper jail cell: a KKK symbol, the words ``White Pride,'' and a
message for his friend whose pickup allegedly was used in Byrd's
dragging death: ``Shawn Berry is a ... traitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry initially cooperated with law enforcement officials. He
told them he stood by in fear while King and Brewer beat Byrd and
chained him to the pickup and began dragging him. Authorities say
Berry lied, however, and allege he was an active participant in
Byrd's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
