<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITED-SUNDSTRAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED TECHNOLOGIES ACQUIRES SUNDSTRAND
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United Technologies Corp., makers of Pratt &AMP; Whitney jet
engines, announced the $4 billion acquistion Monday of the
Sundstrand Corp., a maker of internal systems for airplanes, in a
deal that would enable United Technologies to provide airplane
makers with a broader array of aeronautics wares to buy. The deal
continues a consolidation wave sweeping the aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
   The half-cash, half-stock deal would give Sundstrand
shareholders a minimum of $70 a share, or a 21 percent premium
above Sundstrand's closing price of $58 a share on Friday. Monday,
Sundstand's shares rose $10.25 to close at $68.25. The deal would
give Sundstrand shareholders $35 in cash and a 0.279 share of
United Technologies stock.
</P>
<P>
   United Technologies, based in Hartford, Conn., would also assume
around $400 million in Sundstrand debt. Under terms of the deal,
Sundstrand, located in Rockville, Ill., would be folded into United
Technologies' Hamilton Standard division and renamed Hamilton
Sundstrand. United Technologies, with $25.7 billion in sales, makes
everything from Otis elevators to Carrier air conditioners to
Sikorsky helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Sundstrand, with $2 billion in sales, is also a diversified
manufacturer, but derives about 60 percent of its business from
supplying a variety of equipment to airplane makers like the Boeing
Co. and Airbus Industrie.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal makes a lot of sense and means that there will be
few planes that go off the ground that United Technologies won't be
able to supply with engineers and component parts,'' said David
Leibowitz, an analyst with Burnham &AMP; Co. ``And this isn't just
Boeing, but private aircraft on up. It means they will be able to
sell equipment and engines to virtually anything that takes off
into the skies.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Nisbet, an analyst with JSA Research in Newport, R.I., said
the Sundstrand acquisition would help improve the operation of
United Technologies' Hamilton Standard subsidiary, which he
described as a ``poor performer.'' That subsidiary makes such
things as propellers and environmental systems for aircraft. ``The
combination with similar types of products will enable United
Technologies to give a more systematic approach to customers, it
should help eliminate about 3 to 5 percent of costs between the two
companies and improve margins,'' said Mr. Nisbet. In making jet
engines, United Technology's competes directly with Rolls Royce and
General Electric. ``This will bring a lot more products in the
aerospace and industrial area for United Technologies to get
into,'' said Nisbet.
</P>
<P>
   George David , the chief executive of United Technologies, said,
``This acquisition reinforces our long-stated strategy of
augmenting UTC's world class aerospace and commercial franchises.''
Robert Jenkins, Sundstrand's chief executive, will become the chief
executive of the Hamilton Sundstrand Aerospace division.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the rapidly changing nature of our industry, we firmly
believe that United Technologies is an excellent strategic fit for
Sundstrand,'' said Jenkins. ``We have a highly similar culture and
operating philosophy.'' Sundstrand makes electrical, mechanical and
power systems for commercial aircraft including the Boeing 737, the
Airbus A320 and A340 and such general aircraft as the Gulfstream V.
United Technologies rose $1.0625 Monday to $126.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
