<SLUG> BC-AMERICA-WEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA WEST CALLS OFF TALKS WITH OTHER AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ending four weeks of speculation that it might be bought by
United Airlines or a larger rival, America West Airlines said
Monday that it had called off talks with other airlines and was
committed to going it alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board of directors unanimously concluded that America
West's shareholders, employees and the communities we operate in
will be better served by a growing, profitable and independent
company,'' William Franke, chairman and chief executive of America
West Holdings, the airline's parent, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at the airline's headquarters in Tempe, Ariz., cheered
when they heard the news.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came as America West, the country's
ninth-largest airline, was considering an offer from United, the
world's largest carrier. That turned out to be the only credible
bid after Delta Air Lines and American Airlines backed away from
buying it, according to several executives at the airlines who
spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But a United deal had numerous stumbling blocks. It hinged on
the approval of the unions representing United's pilots and
mechanics, each of which owns substantial stakes in the parent UAL
Corp. No deal could have been consummated unless at least one of
the unions' two representatives on UAL's board of directors
approved.
</P>
<P>
   United and America West would have also faced strong opposition
in Washington, where the Justice Department's antitrust division
has taken a hard line on airline consolidation, as have several
influential lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Continental Airlines, which has a lucrative partnership
with America West and a right of first refusal to buy stock
representing 49 percent of shareholders' voting rights, would have
also tried to derail a deal with United.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business it is extremely difficult to find a
transaction that isn't highly conditioned,'' Franke said in an
interview Monday. ``At least for the foreseeable future, the odds
are overwhelming that the company will pursue an independent
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   With about $2 billion in revenue, America West serves 100 cities
from hubs in Phoenix, Las Vegas and Columbus, Ohio. Though it was
profitable last year, it has not enjoyed the same financial success
as other airlines and it has been plagued by operational mishaps
and poor relations with its labor unions. The company and its
flight attendants are currently in a 30-day cooling-off period
mandated by federal mediators before the flight attendants are
permitted to strike.
</P>
<P>
   Franke said that with its low cost structure and strong balance
sheet, America West had a bright future. Now that the airline was
off the block he was eager to negotiate a contract with the flight
attendants.
</P>
<P>
   America West made its announcement after the close of the stock
market Monday. Its stock was down $1.375 a share, closing at
$21.375, while UAL shares rose $2.50 to close at $62.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
