<HEADLINE>
8 ARE ARRESTED IN CITY HALL PROTEST ON POLICE SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eight protesters were arrested near City Hall Monday
when they chained themselves together to block traffic on lower
Broadway during an angry demonstration over the police shooting of
Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters were the first to be arrested at a demonstration
over the shooting, which has made rallies against police brutality
nearly a daily rite. Four officers killed Diallo, an unarmed
22-year-old street peddler from Guinea, in a barrage of 41 bullets
on Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting ``stop killer cops,'' the demonstrators separated from
a larger rally of several hundred people and lay down on Broadway,
just outside the City Hall fences, their bodies chained together at
the arms.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic on Broadway was blocked for about 15 minutes until
police officers stepped forward to move the demonstrators. The
crowd chanted, ``We're watching you,'' as officers carried the
demonstrators to a nearby police van.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators _ six women and two men _ were later charged
with disorderly conduct and resisting arrest, police officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many speakers who addressed the crowd from a flatbed truck
parked on the sidewalk denounced Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who they
said had set a tone that tolerates police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has consistently defended his record on police
misconduct and has presented statistics that show fatal shootings
by the police last year were the lowest in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for the eight people who chained themselves together,''
said Colleen Roche, a spokeswoman for the mayor, ``it was a
peaceful, relatively uneventful and small event, so there is
nothing for the mayor to comment on.''
</P>
<P>
   As the demonstrators gathered, a Bronx grand jury began its
second week of hearing evidence in the shooting, which occurred in
the vestibule of Diallo's Bronx apartment building. The officers
involved, who were searching for a rapist, have told lawyers that
they mistakenly believed Diallo was reaching for a gun when they
opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   The case has been complicated by the fact that although many in
the neighborhood heard the shots and witnessed their aftermath, no
one so far has come forward who says he or she saw the original
encounter between the police officers and Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   The large number of shots and Diallo's unblemished record have
combined to make the shooting a central event for people who
believe that the police routinely disregard the civil rights of
black and Hispanic residents. Diallo was black, and the four
officers are white.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Applewhite, a 58-year-old hospital worker who attended
the City Hall rally, said she had never been to a demonstration
before but felt it was important to add her voice to the protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this guy put his hand in his pocket to get his keys and he
got killed, what does that mean for the rest of us?'' she asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
