<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-LIGHTNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTNING IS PERFECT FOR WHAT AILS DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ In a slump? Need a lift? For the New Jersey
Devils, the Tampa Bay Lightning showed up on their schedule just in
time.
</P>
<P>
   With left wing Brian Rolston scoring two goals, the Devils broke
a two-game losing streak Monday night and improved the National
Hockey League's best road record with a 3-2 victory over hapless
Tampa Bay in the half-empty Ice Palace.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, just the Devils' fifth in the last 11 games, left
them at 32-20-7 over all and 19-8-1 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had to work much harder for this victory than they
did in last Wednesday's 7-1 demoralization of Tampa Bay, but the
result was the same. The Lightning dropped to 12-41-5, the league's
worst record.
</P>
<P>
   The losers have one victory and one tie to show for their last
13 games, and are now 1-74-7 when trailing after two periods, which
they did Mon night.
</P>
<P>
   A banner commemorating the Lightning's one-game NHL
regular-season attendance record _ 27,227 in 1993 _ hangs from the
Ice Palace rafters, reflecting what used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Barely 3,000 were on hand when Monday night's game started, and
attendance eventually was announced at 8,802 _ the team's
fourth-lowest crowd of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, the Devils took a workmanlike approach
and kept enough pressure on to create cracks in Tampa Bay's
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Martin Brodeur salvaged what looked for a while like a
game he would rather forget. He allowed two cheap goals, but played
like the all-star he is in the third period, when Tampa Bay
answered the crowd's pleas with spots of impassioned play.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur stopped 26 shots in raising his season's record to
26-17-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils opened the scoring 17 minutes 10 seconds into the
game with their 40th power-play goal of the season. Rolston took a
pass from Bobby Holik on the right side, promptly took the puck to
the middle as if looking to pass, then suddenly whirled and shot.
It was his 16th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning tied the score just 1:44 later on an embarrassing
moment for Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Andrei Skopintsev shot into a crowd from 35 feet, and
center Vincent Lecavalier was given credit for redirecting it,
though video replays seemed inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   The slow-moving puck squibbed between Brodeur's legs as he
flailed at it.
</P>
<P>
   Lecavalier further frustrated Brodeur and the Devils 2:20 into
the second period. Devils defenseman Kevin Dean went behind the net
to retrieve a loose puck and shovel it to Brodeur, who swung and
missed on a clearing attempt. Lecavalier was there gleefully to
seize a rare shot at a vacant net.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils drew even at 14:29 of the period and needed just 37
seconds more to recapture the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Lyle Odelein managed to tie the score after receiving
a pass to the middle from left wing Patrick Elias. Odelein quickly
lifted a 12-footer over a pile of fallen players that were blocking
goalie Derek Wilkinson's vision.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, the Devils were applying pressure again, and
Rolston gained control of the puck on the right side near the
crease. Wilkinson hadn't moved to shut off Rolston's angle.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston made him pay with a rising shot in the net's right
corner.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for the Devils to hang on, and to be able to
savor Tuesday, when most of the players are planning to play golf
and bask in the sun. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
