<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA FREE THROWS ARE COSTLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Bruins aren't bad free-throw shooters.
</P>
<P>
   They are historically bad free-throw shooters.
</P>
<P>
   If their current pace holds _ 58.8 percent, last in the
Pacific-10 _ they'll become the first UCLA team in 50 years to
shoot worse than 60 percent from the line.
</P>
<P>
   They miss short, they miss long, they miss right and they miss
left. They shoot rim-rattlers, backboard breakers and air balls.
</P>
<P>
   They're shooting 56.5 percent in conference play and haven't
shot better than 65 percent in a game since Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Their best player, guard Baron Davis, has attempted 39 more free
throws than anyone else and is shooting 59.7 percent _ the only
weakness in his string of stellar performances.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's greatest fear is that poor foul shooting will cost it an
NCAA Tournament game.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Bruins lost to Oregon State and Stanford in part
because they made a combined 19 of 37 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   It nearly cost them last week against USC, when they made 12 of
26.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime we went to shoot a free throw, there was a murmur or a
buzz in the crowd,'' assistant coach Steve Spencer said. ``There
isn't a great free throw shooter on this team. We tell them they
need to tinker and adjust because what they're doing isn't
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, who coordinates UCLA's individual workouts, is
frustrated by the foul shooting but has no answer. Some players
have concentration problems, perhaps the result of inexperience.
Others have flaws in their technique. Each situation is different,
and there's only one remedy: practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins shoot 200-250 free throws per day, but so far it
hasn't helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good free-throw shooters practice a lot,'' Spencer said.
``They find a rhythm they're comfortable with and replicate until
it becomes muscle memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are repeating some bad habits. (To correct them),
they have to take themselves out of their comfort zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Where they stand: Based on recent power ratings _ 22nd in
Sagarin, 19th in the RPI _ the Bruins probably are dangling between
a No. 4 and 5 seed.
</P>
<P>
   They have four games left, against the Washington and Arizona
schools. Four wins likely would vault them into the third-seed
territory. Three wins, and they hold ground. But two losses _ to
Washington and at Arizona, for instance _ may bump them to a No. 6
seed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
