<SLUG> BC-DOG-AUDITIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR HOUNDS HIT HIGH NOTES FOR SHOT AT COMMERCIAL FAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was a lot like ``Star Search,'' except some of
the contestants tried to eat the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   And all of the contestants were naked.
</P>
<P>
   And the winner got a chance to appear in a flea commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the 1999 Search for North America's Best Singing Pet,
which started its 10-stop tour Monday with a preliminary round in
Pershing Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give us so much love and attention, it's nice to give
them some attention back,'' said Heide Karp-Briggs, a professional
clown who sang along with her dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Karp-Briggs' chorale, Moondoggie and Noe, bounded on stage with
all the pent-up energy of a shaken-up can of Pepsi. Her third dog,
Phoebe, had an ``attitude problem'' Monday and sulked off-stage
while the others performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the Shannen Doherty of our dog pack,'' Karp-Briggs said.
</P>
<P>
   Moondoggie, Noe and eight other canine crooners from Southern
California sang their little hearts out, while their owners made
punny comments about ``pawditions'' and ``fleanominal
purrformances.''
</P>
<P>
   Finalists will be flown to New York in September to compete for
a recording studio session and a chance to appear in an Advantage
flea control advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   Take away the 25-foot inflatable flea at one end of the stage
(plus the two guys in brown flea costumes roaming through the
crowd), and Monday's event had all the class of a Hollywood awards
show.
</P>
<P>
   Red carpets. Spotlights. Complimentary food (doggie treats) and
water at a sprawling catering table.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll sing along to anything,'' said Steve Kirchner, whose dog
Bijou yelped enthusiastically as Ted Nugent's ``Cat-Scratch Fever''
played. ``As long as I turn it up loud, he'll start going.''
</P>
<P>
   While several dogs opted to embarrass their masters with silence
once they reached the spotlight, others produced sounds that
resembled everything from a 747 airplane lifting off to a humpback
whale.
</P>
<P>
   And this is one contest where size clearly doesn't matter. Last
year's winner, Pumpkin, is a 2-pound, 10-ounce ``opera-singing''
poodle.
</P>
<P>
   While the search has left Los Angeles, cat and dog owners have
until Aug. 6 to send a VHS tape and entry form to contest
organizers at 200 East Randolph Drive, 63rd Floor, Chicago, IL
60601.
</P>
<P>
   Entry forms can be picked up at selected veterinary clinics and
animal hospitals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
