<HEADLINE>
ON BAR STOOLS, GIULIANI PLAN IS SCORNED
</HEADLINE>
   (With BC-DRUNK-DRIVERS, BC-DRUNK-POLICY) 
(nk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The regulars at Montero Bar in Brooklyn Heights say
they do not usually drive before or after they take their drinks.
Joseph and Tony call a car service, while the bartenders, Carol and
Linda, always walk home. They all condemn drunken driving, but
Monday they reserved their fiercest condemnation for Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm walking, they can't give me a ticket if I'm drunk, can
they?'' asked Carol, who like everyone else would provide only her
first name.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing a 5 p.m. Budweiser and dragging on a Marlboro, Tony
sarcastically answered: ``Walking after drinking. It's the next
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Montero to more upscale pubs on Manhattan's Upper East
Side and watering holes in Queens, the mayor's new policy of
seizing vehicles from people arrested for drunken driving was
greeted with scorn and contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani calls the plan a tough measure to reduce traffic
fatalities, but people on bar stools across the city called it a
punishment exceeding the crime and portrayed it as an erosion of
civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid of them profiling and targeting people in minority
neighborhoods,'' said Lyne Mosby, 55, a painter from Queens. Mosby,
who is black, had driven to Don Romeo's in Kew Gardens, though he
was not drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``People work too hard to get their cars to have them taken
away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bartender at Don Romeo's, Chyna Reynoso, 24, spoke for many
when she said: ``I don't believe they should be taking someone's
property away. If they feel like someone is intoxicated, let them
spend 30 days in jail. If they were caught a second time, then I
would understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has described the campaign as a tough, unambiguous
plan, but several people predicted unforeseen complexities and
inequities.
</P>
<P>
   At Last Exit Bar and Lounge, a trendy nightspot in the Cobble
Hill section of Brooklyn, John Waters and Arthur Ballard sipped
French martinis and noted that a person who owned a Jaguar would
suffer a greater financial loss than someone who owned a Ford
Escort.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd Bennington, 41, a financial manager who lives in Manhattan,
said he had become more cautious about drinking and driving since
he was arrested for drunken driving eight years ago in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But, as he sipped on a beer at O'Flanagan's Ale House on
Manhattan's East Side. he he criticized the Giuliani plan on legal
and practical grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seizing property without a trial, that sounds
unconstitutional,'' he said. ``A lot of people's cars are used to
earn a living. I think it will be detrimental for business in the
city as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, at Mo's Caribbean Bar and Grill, Chuck Frissora,
48, a road builder visiting from Sudbury, Mass., conceded that he
did occasionally drive after a drink or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous,'' he said of the city's crackdown. ``It's
certainly not a democratic punishment. I think you need to be
responsible, but the government taking away your car is
unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Frissora decried the confiscation measure as ``another bit of
erosion in our foundation of personal freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm convicted of a crime, I'll pay the penalty. But taking
my possessions on the spot is an abuse of power. If they put up
roadblocks, I would never come to Manhattan again and would take my
tourist dollars elsewhere,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
