<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PERROT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERROT VOWS TO CONQUER CANCER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By W.H. STICKNEY JR. 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Kim Perrot, a 5-foot-5-inch pillar of strength on the
basketball court during the Houston Comets' two WNBA championship
seasons, cried frequently Monday as she talked of being diagnosed
with lung and brain cancer and discussed the difficult fight now
confronting her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a tough moment for me,'' Perrot said. ``But I've
always had to battle. And this is just another battle.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the past month, Perrot has been subjected to
numerous tests at M.D. Anderson Hospital in Houston to determine
the cause of periodic headaches and weakness in her arms. On
Friday, she was informed of the results: Cancer that began in her
lungs had spread to her brain.
</P>
<P>
   As she talked of her ordeal Monday, Perrot sat with two of the
Comets' team doctors, two of the three cancer specialists in whose
hands her future rests and Comets coach Van Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the news conference at the Westside Tennis Club,
Perrot clutched the hand of Chancellor, who over the past two years
has gone from a coach she once despised to a father figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe with all my heart and faith in God that I will
overcome this,'' she said. ``And my goal is to be back on the
basketball court at 110 percent, doing what I've been doing for the
last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have said it's too early to offer a complete prognosis.
But Dr. Raymond Sawaya, chief of neurosurgery at M.D. Anderson
Cancer Center, said the lung cancer, alveolar adenocarcinoma that
was classified as advanced, is the biggest long-term worry.
</P>
<P>
   The brain tumors _ one golf-ball-size tumor and a few smaller
ones _ offer the most immediate threat, however.
</P>
<P>
   Sawaya said the smaller tumors ``are of no immediate concern
right now ... The larger one is best treated if removed.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the golf-ball-size tumor did not originate in the brain,
Sawaya said there is a high probability it can be removed and not
grow back. It is on the left side, immediately beneath the brain's
surface and near the motor cortex that controls power to the
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   During surgery expected to last about four hours Wednesday,
doctors will use critical mapping, which measures function on the
surface of the brain, to determine which part of the brain to cut
through to remove the tumor without causing paralysis. Two weeks of
radiation will follow the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer in the lungs is more of an unknown. But doctors said
there is no reason to think Perrot won't respond to treatment _
about six months of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Sawaya said it is hard to imagine Perrot playing competitively
this season. But he admitted he was hesitant to say that, because
chemotherapy treatment is hard to predict.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Taylor Wharton, special assistant to the president of M.D.
Anderson and an oncologist, said Perrot probably began to
experience symptoms associated with the lung cancer last fall.
Although lung cancer is most often associated with heavy smokers,
Wharton said Perrot ``is a nonsmoker and a nondrinker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lifestyle has nothing to do with it,'' Wharton said. ``It's
just a low-frequency, random event. And unfortunately, it caught up
with one of our star athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot said she gains comfort from living in Houston, where
facilities and personnel such as those at M.D. Anderson are readily
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock to me to even think this would happen to me,''
she said. ``But I've accepted it. I've dealt with it, and the last
weeks that I have been meeting with the doctors at M.D. Anderson
have really made me feel confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust that they are the best and will take real good care of
me. So it is an asset to be in a city where they have the best
doctors in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor said he has no doubt Perrot will overcome her
illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of how tough she is,'' he said, ``she's going to
fight this, and she'll be back playing one day. I just don't see
this as being a battle she can't win. She's small; she's overcome
that on the basketball court. She's just won every battle you can
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lamb, starting center for the Comets during their repeat
season as champions of the Women's National Basketball Association,
said Perrot's teammates were all shocked upon hearing of her
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so ironic and so tragic,'' said Lamb. ``She is the most
health-conscious on this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I like to say that this disease has just barked upon the
wrong tree. Kim is relentless against her foes. I have no doubt she
will attack this in the same manner, the same fashion, all the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Perrot, ``I just want to thank all my fans, my family and
friends for their support. And just know that I'm going to get
through this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
