bear,'' said Ms. Maughan, who can lumber about in pretty convincing
fashion. ``When I come in the door, they're thinking that way.
They'll take a swat at me. They'll grab my shirt sleeve like it's
the scruff of another bear.'' And that is the whole point, for Ms.
Maughan is doing all she can to get these bears back into the wild
this spring. Idaho wildlife officials call her ``the bear lady,''
and for the last 10 years she has been the volunteer in charge of
an unusual program intended to return orphaned cubs to the
wilderness. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
