known as synesthesia _ in which the customary boundaries between
the senses appear to break down, sight mingling with sound, or
taste with touch _ received little attention. But in the past 10
years, the arrival of imaging techniques and other new technologies
for studying the brain at work has revived interest in synesthesia
by a core of researchers who hope that the condition will give a
greater understanding of all kinds of perception or even shed light
on the nature of consciousness itself. By Erica Goode.
