<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5379 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNOLOGY-EXPORTS-2N     02-22 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOLOGY-EXPORTS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION REJECTS SALE OF AMERICAN SATELLITE TO CHINESE-LED
GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS grafs 2-3 to recast, specify that future satellite sales
are in doubt, expand on why administration supported
transactions.) 
 (sw) 
 By JEFF GERTH and DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Swayed by criticisms that commercial satellite
deals with China could threaten national security, the Clinton
administration decided on Monday to reject the sale of a $450
million satellite to a consortium with close ties to the Chinese
government, senior officials here said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision casts considerable doubt on the future of satellite
sales to the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's decision reverses the policy in effect for
several years of promoting commercial satellite deals with China.
The United States championed the transactions to help American
business and exports and to help China make technological advances.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last several months, the administration has faced a
barrage of investigations and a growing stack of official reports
that have called the commercial satellite sales and associated
expertise a threat to American security and a great boon to China's
military capability. The findings have indicated that the program
of satellite sales might have given the Chinese the scientific
expertise to improve their missile-launching capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Disapproval of the satellite deal is likely to be another
sensitive issue raised next week when Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright visits China. With Chinese-American relations eroding over
other issues like human rights and trade, Beijing could interpret
the disapproval as a fundamental retreat from Washington's
commitment to expanded economic relations. At the moment, though,
no further sales are pending.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after the Defense and State Departments
objected to allowing China to launch the satellite. The Commerce
Department favored the sale, but the State and Defense departments
overruled it, concluding that the technology to place the satellite
in orbit would help the Chinese military make its intercontinental
ballistic missile fleet more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts also feared that that Chinese military would
benefit, both commercially and technologically, by controlling the
satellite once it was in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   The deal involves a Hughes Space and Communications satellite
designed to set up a mobile telephone network over much of Asia,
reaching from China to Indonesia, and then across the Indian Ocean
as far as Pakistan. The Commerce Department is expected to formally
notify Hughes of its ``intent to deny'' in the next few days,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The company issued a statement on Monday night that made no
reference to a decision, but reiterated that the satellite deal
``can be used as a model for how we can protect national security
while launching satellites overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision effectively revokes President Clinton's quiet
approval of the sale two and a half years ago. At the time,
Clinton's aides assured him it would not contribute to Chinese
military capabilities. The State Department and the Defense
Department concurred with the decision, but had not thoroughly
vetted the military links of the Singapore-based consortium, which
was the official buyer of the satellite. Top officials of the
consortium included top military officers of the People's
Liberation Army, who also served in posts with the China Satellite
Launch and Tracking Control Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes officials had sought an expedited review, and pressured
the administration to approve the deal, according to government
documents provided later to congressional investigators. A change
in the satellite's design forced the company to apply for a revised
license, and a raft of subsequent investigations into China's
efforts to obtain American technology helped prompt the
administration to reverse its position.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes at a time that relations between the United
States and China are eroding on many fronts, from human rights to
economic interchanges. A senior administration official, speaking
on the condition that he not be identified, said on Monday that
``we are heading into a very rough patch,'' and speculated that the
decision Monday could make it ``very difficult'' to approve other
satellite sales to China in the near future, though none are
pending.
</P>
<P>
   The official also speculated that the Chinese would likely move
quickly to obtain a similar satellite from Europe, in part to drive
home their ability to circumvent American restrictions and reward
non-American competitors. However, it appears unlikely that China
could acquire technology as sophisticated as that offered by
Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is scheduled to visit Beijing next week in connection
with a visit to Washington in April by China's prime minister, Zhou
Rongji. Zhou is widely regarded as China's economic czar, and
administration officials believed until recently that his visit
would be preceded by intense negotiations to secure China's entry
into the World Trade Organization, a move Beijing and Washington
have long sought.
</P>
<P>
   But with China's economy slowing, and unemployment unrest around
the country, Zhou appears less eager to strike a deal that would
require him to open China's markets rapidly. The cancellation of
the satellite deal could easily be interpreted in Beijing as a
fundamental retreat from Washington's commitment to expanded
economic relations with China, and could also diminish the chances
of any broad trade agreement. Such an agreement would ultimately
require approval by Congress, and administration officials say that
in the current atmosphere, that would be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect that the satellite deal would be approved has
diminished for months. On Monday morning, The Financial Times of
London reported that the deal was close to being rejected. By later
Monday, the Commerce Department had received the last of the votes
from four other agencies with a voice in the deal, and concluded
that it had been overruled.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes Electronics or the Commerce Department could
theoretically ask for a reconsideration of the decision of the four
export licenses involved in the deal, but administration officials
said that as a practical matter they thought it was unlikely any
reconsideration would change the outcome.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At a high level interagency meeting on Feb. 11, the Pentagon
said it was troubled by the involvement of the Chinese military in
the regional satellite system, called Asia-Pacific Mobile
Telecommunications, an official said.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's concerns at the meeting included
questions about Hughes' dealings in recent years with China, the
official added. One troubling episode involved a 1995 tutorial on
rocket launching given by Hughes engineers to Chinese scientists,
now the subject of a criminal inquiry. Another involved the
company's hiring of the son of the Chinese general who oversees his
country's military satellite programs, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The recent findings of a select House committee also figured in
the decision to deny the Hughes deal, officials said. The panel
criticized Hughes' dealings with China and recommended that the
administration strengthen export controls. The administration
supports most committee findings.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Intelligence Committee is completing a similar
report, which officials said is likely to also harshly criticize
Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Hughes told the government that it faced
potentially large losses if the license was denied, including $100
million in unrecoverable costs and a possible penalty if the
government did not approve a license by Feb. 15, according to an
administration official.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the company's questioned deals with China, its
chairman was C. Michael Armstrong, who also served as head of
Clinton's export advisory council, a group of private-sector
executives and labor leaders who advice the administration on trade
policy. Armstrong now heads AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   His successor at Hughes, Michael T. Smith, wrote Albright last
December that Hughes ``will adopt new policies and procedures for
the export of technology and equipment,'' including a ``new
internal export compliance program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hughes of today is a very different company than it was
even a year ago,'' Smith said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   The license for the satellite deal was handled by the Commerce
Department, which must consult and win the consent of other
government departments involved in satellite exports. Next month,
as a result of legislation passed by Congress last year and
opposed, but signed, by Clinton, the State Department will once
again take on the lead role for a wider range of satellite exports.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Deparment will no longer have a vote in licensing
reviews for many of the most sophisticated products, which will be
considered part of the State Department's ``munitions list,'' a
list of the nation's most sensitive military-related technologies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
