<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5383 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DRUNK-POLICY-NYT &LR;      02-22 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUNK-POLICY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW POLICY REMAINS A WORK IN PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-DRUNK-DRIVERS, NY-DRUNK-REACT) 
 (nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As New York City began seizing the cars of people
arrested on drunken-driving charges, police officials and lawyers
studied the new policy Monday to figure out exactly how it would
work and whose cars could be kept for resale.
</P>
<P>
   The most clear-cut of cases, officials said, is when the driver
charged with drunken driving is the registered owner of the
vehicle. In those cases the car will definitely be seized.
</P>
<P>
   But other situations are murkier.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of a teen-ager arrested for drunken driving in a
car registered to his mother. If the teen-ager can establish that
he borrowed the family car and that his mother had no idea he would
be drinking, officials said, the car will eventually be returned.
But if it appears that the teen-ager was the primary user of the
car, it might well be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Leased cars will also be seized and kept, though Robert Messner,
the executive managing attorney of the Police Department's Civil
Enforcement Unit, said the city would return most leased cars to
the leasing companies. But he said that the drivers of seized
leased cars would probably still be required to pay off the terms
of their leases.
</P>
<P>
   Rental cars will not be seized. Messner said that they might be
held briefly in case they are needed as evidence, but that they
would eventually be returned to the rental companies.
</P>
<P>
   Taxis and livery cabs will be seized when the owner is charged
with drunken driving or if the owner was aware that the car would
be driven by someone drunk.
</P>
<P>
   The police will also seize private automobiles if they can show
that the owner knowingly allowed the driver to operate the vehicle
while drunk. Those cases are easiest to prove, police officials
said, when the owner is a passenger _ and such seizures would also
eliminate the possibility that when two companions are drunk, the
owner can circumvent the law by having the other person drive.
</P>
<P>
   Only people arrested for driving while intoxicated _ and found
to have a blood alcohol level of .10 or higher _ will have their
cars seized. People arrested on the lesser charge of driving while
impaired _ meaning their blood alcohol level was between .06 and
.09 _ will have their cars returned.
</P>
<P>
   Once an arrest for drunken driving is made and a car is seized,
two processes begin: the criminal case against the driver and the
city's civil case to take ownership of the car.
</P>
<P>
   For the criminal case, the suspect is brought back to the
station house and given a Breathalyzer test on videotape. If a
driver refuses to be tested, that refusal is videotaped and the
driver's license will be suspended. His car can still be seized,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The civil case is separate. The Civil Enforcement Unit must
begin proceedings to have a car legally forfeited within 25 days of
the time a driver asks for his car back from the Police
Department's Property Clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Hessner said that a civil action could take anywhere from days
to years.
</P>
<P>
   The city may agree to give back cars to people who can make a
good case in court for their return, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said that someone acquitted of driving
drunk in a criminal case still might not get his car back, because
the standard of proof the city must meet in a civil case is lower
then the standard in a criminal one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-99 2348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990222.0470 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-TRUCE23-CO     02-22 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-TRUCE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feds, foes reach truce on restoration plan
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The federal government reached a truce
Monday with scientists whose widely publicized criticisms could
have jeopardized Congress' approval of a $7.8 billion Everglades
restoration plan.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, federal leaders agreed
to appoint an independent panel of researchers from outside South
Florida to review the restoration throughout the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The plan still will go to Congress on July 1, as the U.S. Army
Corps of Engineers had intended. But the panel will have the
authority to review the science underlying the restoration and make
recommendations directly to Babbitt and his successors.
</P>
<P>
   And Babbitt will choose the experts with help from the National
Academy of Sciences, the not-for-profit society Congress created
during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   That could satisfy demands by the Sierra Club and other groups
that the academy, or some similarly renowned body, play a role in
the review.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement reached Monday is a more detailed version of a
review proposal that federal advisers had announced Feb. 3. But
that announcement received nothing like the widespread approval
that emerged from Monday's hourlong meeting in Washington between
three of the scientists and Babbitt. ``I'm delighted,'' said
University of Tennessee ecologist Stuart Pimm, one of the
restoration plan's most vocal critics. Pimm embarrassed the
government last month by recruiting criticism from five other
nationally known scientists, including leading ecologists from
Harvard and Stanford universities.
</P>
<P>
   While his doubts about the plan remain, Pimm said the experts'
panel will have two crucial ingredients to ensure the government
makes the needed improvements: ``It's ongoing and it's an
independent advisory board. . . . That's what we wanted at the
outset.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, which wasn't involved in the meeting, also
expressed optimism afterward. But Frank Jackalone, the club's
senior Florida representative, said he hopes the experts will have
enough clout to insist on changes if they find serious flaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the country will settle for nothing less than a plan
that begins to restore the Everglades,'' Jackalone said.
</P>
<P>
   The peer review proposal also won written endorsement last week
from Everglades National Park Superintendent Richard Ring, whose
scientists have called the restoration plan inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration, perhaps the largest ever attempted, would be
the first major overhaul of the federally created drainage system
that made South Florida safe for expanded farming and development
after World War II. The plan calls for creating 251,000 acres of
reservoirs, marshes, quarries and well fields to store hundreds of
billions of gallons of water each year for farms, cities and the
Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the plan would rely too much on pricey engineering
experiments and provide too much water for suburban sprawl. They
say it would do too little to restore the Everglades' broad-flowing
sheets of water _ and even those improvements would not occur until
after 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The corps still had the support of many environmental groups,
including the National Audubon Society, which said the plan had
undergone exhaustive review during the past two years. Even so,
Monday's agreement ``will be very helpful'' when the plan goes to
Congress, Assistant Interior Secretary Patricia Beneke said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Beneke said the government had always intended to have an
ongoing scientific review, but ``perhaps we hadn't communicated
what the plan will be, how serious we are about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
