<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GRAMMY-PROFESSOER-     02-22 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GRAMMY-PROFESSOER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH `JAZZ SINGERS,' PROFESSOR IS SPOTLIGHTED
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert G. O'Meally, the Columbia University professor
and jazz writer who will be attending his first Grammy Awards
ceremony Wednesday night (he's been nominated), in his first tuxedo
(hey, he's not going to lie to you, he's excited), is one of those
guys who likes to put together music tapes, at least one a week.
</P>
<P>
   The family is driving to Queens, O'Meally makes a tape. He makes
tapes for his wife's exercise class. It was a tape, for his own
pleasure, that led to the Grammy contender. O'Meally had been
invited by Henry Louis Gates Jr. to a study group on black
intellectuals held in a villa in Bellagio, Italy. ``Kind of a
boondoggle _ I shouldn't call it that,'' O'Meally says. There was
great food, there was wine, there was no music.
</P>
<P>
   Out come some of O'Meally's tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's ``The Jazz Singers,'' a five-CD collection of more
than 100 artists, which was the last collection produced by the
Smithsonian Collection of Recordings. O'Meally co-produced the
collection with Bruce Talbot, then the executive producer at the
Smithsonian. The set also includes a 127-page booklet by O'Meally,
who, after all, has a Ph.D. from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to say here are the indispensable progenitors of the
traditions,'' O'Meally says of the project. ``I wanted some
historical sweep. I wanted to show that jazz singing is quite
various and diffuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Can we see the tux?
</P>
<P>
   Pleased as a kid stepping out for the prom, O'Meally brings it
out and, as requested, puts it on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got it in a store called Rue St. Denis on 11th Street,''
O'Meally says. ``I'm not going to pay $1,000 for a suit I'm going
to wear one day a year. They said it was from the 40s. It was
$150.''
</P>
<P>
   The jacket is double-breasted, with lapels sharp enough to cut
out your heart. Pretty slick. He looks like one of the guys he
writes about.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meally, a boyish 50, smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jazz musicians always liked to get dressed up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meally, a professor of American literature, is the first
Columbia professor nominated for a Grammy, as far as anyone knows.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a teacher of the best sort, excited about his field.
Talking about jazz in the expansive, prewar apartment he shares
with his wife and two teen-age sons, he illustrates his stories
with music. O'Meally's wife, Jacqui Malone, a professor of theater
and dance at Queens College who is working on a book about tap
dancing, gets up from her computer in the adjoining room and firmly
shuts the French doors without saying hello _ a signal, perhaps,
that there is more than one significant artist in this house.
O'Meally, meanwhile, is lost in the music.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the photos you might see on a visit to
O'Meally's place: His younger son on a fishing trip, so delighted
with the big, fat fish he has caught that he is giving it a kiss. A
photo of O'Meally's parents, his dad the map maker, his mother the
schoolteacher, at a costume party, talking with Count Basie.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a photo, on the living room wall, of a middle-aged
man with a Panama hat and a flashy shirt, impatient and restless,
listening to another man _ possibly his producer _ whose face is
only partly visible. Is race important here? The artist is black,
the authority figure white. ``My hero, Johnny Hodges,'' O'Meally
says. ``He was a star soloist with Duke Ellington. Sax.''
</P>
<P>
   He gets out an old album, plays a few cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feigned this indifferent attitude, but you can't miss the
passion in his playing,'' O'Meally says. ``As a boy, I reacted to
the melody. He was also the essence of coolness, pretending to look
the other way while squeezing all this beauty out of the horn.''
</P>
<P>
   Most little boys choose other heroes: sports figures, John
Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the risk of being too analytic about it, I grew up in
segregated Washington,'' O'Meally says. ``I had to go cope with the
fact that I couldn't go to certain theaters or restaurants. You had
to know what the limits were and operate within them. Hodges could
live within a partition and still have a full sense of life, still
test the limits. He traveled to the Far East, all over Europe. He
stood for the possibilities of exploding those boundaries, just as
Louis did. Great Ambassador Satch. For me, he was more than a John
Wayne. Wayne was a tough hero who would confront you at every turn.
You couldn't do that in Washington. You had to learn how to stop
around an aggressive police officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that his was an unhappy childhood, O'Meally stresses. Quite
the opposite. For all of his talk of segregated Washington, his
best friend _ out comes another picture _ was a white kid. There
was always music in his house. His mother, at the piano, playing
Beethoven and Chopin. His father, taking over, doing a
boogie-woogie variation or listening to Duke Ellington or
Cannonball Adderley, closing his eyes, sometimes, so you knew
something special was happening in the music.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meally, inspired by Hodges, played tenor sax.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't he become a musician?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just never was that good,'' O'Meally says.
</P>
<P>
   Out comes another CD, ``One Hour With Duke Ellington'' and
Hodges, again, making the saxophone sing of love and longing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've Got It Bad and That Ain't Good'' _ just the song with
which to leave O'Meally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
